<SLUG> BC-CALM-TRAFFIC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIES SEEK END TO SPEEDING, TRAFFIC IN RESIDENTIAL AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Not too long ago, residents who complained
about drivers speeding through their neighborhoods probably would
have seen a stop sign pop up or police stake out the street for a
couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't happen so much anymore. It is not because city
officials stopped caring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop signs get ignored,'' said Bonnie Johnson, planner for
Liberty. ``If drivers do slow down, they just speed up quickly
between the next stop sign and end up going faster.''
</P>
<P>
   And police enforcement only temporarily solves the problem.
After the police leave, speeds increase.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Kansas City area, officials are looking into
other ways to make neighborhood traffic calmer. So you can expect
to see more speed humps, speed tables, chicanes, slow points and
even roundabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Wallwork, president of Alternate Street Design in Orange
Park, Fla., said the increased interest in such devices stems from
a change of attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to build skinny streets and rely on a grid network
when it came to planning,'' Wallwork said. ``No one went too fast
and no one street carried a lot of traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   But since the 1950s, the main focus in street design was how to
get people from Point A to Point B the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, streets became wider and straighter. Cities removed
obstructions. Trips became quicker and travel became easier.
</P>
<P>
   This has led to increases in traffic volumes and speeds, and
ultimately an increase in crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are not too happy with that,'' Wallwork said. ``They
have been crying out for such things as stop signs, traffic signals
and speed humps. But none of them are truly effective slowing
traffic down.''
</P>
<P>
   Now people are willing to forgo high-speed travel to improve the
quality of neighborhood life.
</P>
<P>
   Wallwork said traffic calming began in the early 1970s in
Australia and Holland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is finding a balance between those who want to
speed and people who don't want them to speed in the
neighborhood,'' he said. ``That is often a big challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Independence, Mo., recently adopted new design standards in new
development.
</P>
<P>
   But because of budgetary constraints, Independence is limited on
what it can do for its older areas. If traffic speed is a problem,
the city first will try signs, including stop signs at
intersections.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a cost-to-benefit ratio, it sure looks a lot better,''said
Rob Richardson, senior planner for the Independence.
</P>
<P>
   In older areas that have few curbs, gutters and storm water
drainage, Richardson said, the costs increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``You basically have to redo the street, including acquiring
more right of way, which is not practical for a lot of cities,''
Richardson said. ``When it comes right down to it, a lot of
neighborhoods would probably have to be asked to participate in the
cost. A lot of times they determine it is not justified if they
have to put their own money into it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, Jere Meredith, division engineer of Streets and
Traffic, said the city has a reactive program that is triggered
after neighborhood complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally we wait until a neighborhood group comes forward and
says it has a problem,'' he said. ``At that time we explain to them
what the possibilities are, including the benefits and drawbacks of
each device, and let them decide if we should pursue the measure.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it is up to the neighborhood to convince its residents
that something should be done. The city, however, does not consider
stop signs an effective measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been pressured into putting in stop signs for speed
control before,'' he said. ``When we do that, we do
before-and-after studies and invariably the speeds go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all traffic calming projects receive the public's
acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Olathe, Kan., officials installed chicanes _ bulges of
the curb into the street that force drivers to slow _ but removed
them two weeks later after 45 persons complained.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Linan, traffic engineer for Olathe, said the city failed
to convince residents that stop signs don't really control speeds
and volume.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those problems, Olathe has adopted guidelines for
using speed humps. Neighborhoods now are required to appoint a
representative to request the city to take action. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the city will do speed studies, traffic counts
and accident reviews. If a problem is found, residents must submit
a petition showing at least 80 percent approval for speed humps.
The only exception is in extreme conditions. In that case, the city
will install speed humps without approval of the residents.
</P>
<P>
   Linan said that some people might blame poor design for traffic
problems, but he thinks not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over last 30 years, the goal of the traffic engineer was how
to get from here to there faster and how to make it easier to get
from here to there,'' Linan said. ``The least impedance you had,
the better it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently they did a good job because now, decades later, we
are retrofitting them. Now the priority is to make sure people get
there safely.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
