<SLUG> BC-FUEL-FORUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUEL FORUM BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Today, the ``Fuel Summit'' begins.
</P>
<P>
   The summit could result in slightly higher prices at the pump.
And it may lead to a healthful reduction in the Kansas City, Mo.,
area's summertime smog.
</P>
<P>
   More immediately, it could return the area to compliance with
federal clean-air regulations so that highway expansion projects
can resume.
</P>
<P>
   The summit begins at 10 a.m. today at the Jack Reardon Civic
Center in Kansas City, Kan., and ends Thursday. Regulators, local
officials and oil industry representatives will discuss whether
reformulated gasoline, a new kind of less-polluting fuel, should be
brought to area pumps. The fuel is sold in the St. Louis area.
</P>
<P>
   The forum is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan and Kansas Gov. Bill Graves have
hesitated to ask for federal permission to bring the new fuel here.
Proponents of the fuel hope the summit will lay to rest any
questions the governors still have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope we will see all the issues aired, and it will put the
governors in a position to take action,'' said Eileen Hiney of the
Mid-America Regional Council.
</P>
<P>
   Recently federal regulators ruled that area highway projects to
expand a road's capacity had to be shelved until both governors
officially requested reformulated gas.
</P>
<P>
   The governors have said they would wait until the fuel summit to
decide whether to do so.
</P>
<P>
   There are several variations of reformulated gas, but the most
popular blend has included MTBE, methyl tertiary-butyl ether.
</P>
<P>
   In California the governor has called for a ban on the use of
MTBE fuel because the chemical is prone to pollute groundwater
supplies and lakes used for drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of reformulated gas in Kansas City has been brewing
for nearly three years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the regional council's Air Quality Forum proposed
bringing reformulated gas to Kansas City. In February 1998 the
Missouri Air Conservation Commission approved the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In much of those discussions, representatives of the oil
industry objected to bringing the new fuel here. The fuel costs
more to manufacture, and industry representatives also questioned
whether it was legal to bring it here.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues still remain, said Ken Peterson, director of the
Kansas Petroleum Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there are other actions that Kansas City should
look at before taking this rather severe step,'' Peterson said
Tuesday. ``This is more expensive fuel. It'll cost more at the
pump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
