<SLUG> BC-BBN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS EVEN SERIES WITH 88-86 VICTORY OVER KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It was him again. After the New York Knicks had
put themselves in divine position to steal the soul of Indiana and
command of the series, Reggie Miller hit two free throws with two
seconds left to give the Pacers Game 2 of the Eastern Conference
finals on Tuesday night at Market Square Arena, 88-86.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, limping as badly as he had been since Game 5 of
the Knicks first-round series in Miami, had a golden look at a
game-tying, 14-foot jumper at the buzzer, but missed. In a frantic
finish, the Pacers evened this four-of-seven-game series after a
heart-stopping ending and sent it to New York for games Saturday
and next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   With 17 seconds left and the score tied, Allan Houston lost the
ball for New York and gave Miller his chance; it was the Knicks'
20th turnover. Miller held the ball in front of Chris Childs. With
the clock winding down, he darted to his left to the baseline,
leaped and drew contact for a foul.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who finished with 16 points, coolly made both free
throws to finally stop the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But this game showed that there is something in the Knicks that
won't allow them to stop coming no matter how dire the situation.
Down by 14 points in the third period, they rode the energy of
Childs, Houston, Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby, along with
Larry Johnson and Chris Dudley. This alternating unit just kept
circling the Pacers like vultures, ready to swoop down on their
every mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Each Miller missed jumper, each errant free throw by any number
of Pacers, and each turnover put air under the Knicks' hopes. With
an aching Ewing on the bench and in foul trouble, the Knicks went
on a 17-4 tear to end the third period and begin the fourth. They
took a 73-71 lead two minutes into the fourth period on a putback
by Dudley. But Dudley fouled out with 6 minutes 26 seconds left in
the game and the Knicks ahead, 78-74, and Ewing trudged back onto
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Over a minute later, Johnson, who had 22 points, fouled out. It
looked as if attrition was going to get the best of the Knicks as
the Pacers went on a 9-0 run to take 84-80 lead after a 3-point
play from Derrick McKey with 3:04 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   But on his wobbly legs, Ewing delivered a jumper and Camby
soared in off a shot that was blocked by Antonio Davis and hit the
putback with 1:22 remaining to tie the game. Ewing's next shot
almost tied it again at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing finished with 10 points, making 2 of 7 from the field.
Mark Jackson led the Pacers with 17 points, and added 8 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout this game, Ewing was limping, sarcastically goading
on the crowd as it booed his moves and cheered his foul trouble.
Ewing's counterpart, Rik Smits, was hobbling through yet another
game when he had foul difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   With the marquee big men down and out for much of the game, the
Knicks were leaning on Camby to find some rebounds, Sprewell to
turn a couple of fast-break points and Johnson to deliver some
offense as they weathered an early onslaught by the Jackson-led
Pacers to turn a 14-point third-quarter deficit into a 73-71 lead
with 10:50 left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The turnabout was stunning. A tense and bizarre first half
unfolded as a result of a flurry of fouls committed by Childs and
Charlie Ward, who were trying in vain to stop a determined Jackson
on his way to punishing the Knicks in the post. Their foul woes
left Coach Jeff Van Gundy to opt to put a team on the floor without
a point guard for an eight-minute stretch, from the first quarter
to the early minutes of the second. The Knicks also went without a
point guard in the final three minutes of the half.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the mismatches worked to the Knicks' favor, with
Sprewell bringing the ball up. Other times, it failed miserably as
the Pacers took a 53-38 lead with 2:21 left in the half. At that
moment, Ewing picked up his third foul. Exiting with a limp in the
middle of a cascade of boos, Ewing flapped his arms to the crowd,
as if to say, ``Bring it on.''
</P>
<P>
   It was on, all right. The Pacers were playing intense
basketball, taking their cue from Jackson, who was finding his
teammates inside the 3-point arc. The Pacers took just three shots
from 3-point range in the half in an effort to eliminated the
fast-break points and cool the transition-happy Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Knicks scored just 6 points off the break, Sprewell
got his shots, though, hitting 5 of 10 in the first half. He and
Johnson, who had 17 first-half points by obliterating Chris Mullin
inside, were seizing the chance when they had a mismatch. With both
teams shooting just over 50 percent, neither team was exactly
stopping the other in a first half pierced by whistles.
</P>
<P>
   As the aggressors, the Pacers got the calls and went to the
free-throw line 27 times in the first half, compared to the Knicks'
16 attempts. The good news for the Knicks was that the Pacers hit
just 19 of their free throws.
</P>
<P>
   Only when the Pacers got careless by turning the ball over twice
in the last 1:37 of the first half did the Knicks scramble to make
up ground and pull within 57-46 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers then turned very un-Pacer like and began to unravel
in the third quarter. With the Knicks turning occasionally to
double-team Jackson in the post, Miller and Mullin missed open
3-point chances. The Knicks were able to capitalize and pull within
61-53 with 7:30 left in the third on a jumper from Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was unflustered, though. He continued to post-up Ward,
and then Childs and put the Pacers back up, 68-57, with 4:09 left
in the third. The Knicks clinged to the game by getting to the foul
line and making their free throws while the Pacers were missing
badly on their end. That helped the Knicks to pull within 70-64
with a minute left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   After being bludgeoned by Jackson, Childs then lost Jackson's
replacement, Travis Best, and delivered a 3-pointer with 28 seconds
left in the third. After another botched offensive possession by
the Pacers, Sprewell found his way to the free-throw line and hit
both free throws with 2.7 seconds left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   What had the makings of a blowout, ended with the Knicks on a
12-3 run that allowed them to cut the Pacers' lead to 71-68
entering the fourth quarter. After losing their poise in the first
quarter, the Knicks had calmed down and worked themselves right
back into the game courtesy of some poor free-throw shooting by
Indiana, which made just 2 of 8 in the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
