<SLUG> BC-CARGO-SETTLEMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY SETTLES LAWSUIT OVER DEATH OF PILOT AT KCI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT BOCZKIEWICZ  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The widow and children of a pilot killed in the 1995
crash of a cargo jet at Kansas City International Airport recently
settled their lawsuit against McDonnell Douglas Corp. and UAL Corp.
for $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   The family of Mark N. Ulmer, first officer of the Air Transport
International jet, sued in federal court in Denver, where the
settlement was disclosed in documents filed last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ulmer, 38, and the two other crew members were killed Feb. 16,
1995, in a fiery nighttime crash along a KCI runway. The plane had
unloaded freight and was being flown to Massachusetts for
servicing.
</P>
<P>
   The plane crashed after the crew aborted the first take-off. The
crew was trying to take off with one of the plane's four engines
not working, something officials said was not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell Douglas built the DC-8-63, and UAL Corp. trained the
crew at its United Airlines Flight Training Center in Denver in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Ulmer and her three sons claimed in their 1997 lawsuit
that the companies were responsible for the crash through
negligence by providing unsafe instructions and training for
three-engine take-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies denied responsibility. According to court
filings, they blamed the crash on errors and negligence by the crew
and by Little Rock-based Air Transport International. McDonnell
Douglas also blamed the Federal Aviation Administration for
allegedly failing to adequately monitor the crew.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulmer family will receive $122,607 of the $300,000,
according to court filings. The remainder will cover attorney fees
and other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The families of the plane's captain, Walter Miga, and its flight
engineer, Kerry Hardy, earlier this year settled their lawsuit
against UAL and McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney for those families said the terms of their
settlements were confidential.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
