<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COMMENTARY: WITH THE PACERS IDLING, BIRD CALLS ON RESERVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ They were down and nearly out, struggling for
points and defense and anything to get them back in this dogfight
of a game. The building was electric, the Knicks bench became
flammable and nothing Larry Bird tried seemed to rectify the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers were within minutes of falling into an 0-2
hole, the kind of crevice that good teams never recover from.
Latrell Sprewell was taking flight in transition, Marcus Camby's
elongated arms were reaching over two and three players for the
basketball _ and securing it. Chris Dudley put back a missed shot
with less than 11 minutes, giving the Knicks their first lead of
the game and hushing the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing his starters had lost momentum, Bird fought fire with
fire and summoned his reserves. In came Jalen Rose, leading a 9-0
run in a span of 2 minutes 21 seconds. In came Antonio Davis,
rebounding the basketball with desire.
</P>
<P>
   And when they had done their duty, Reggie Miller, Mark Jackson
and Dale Davis came back to finish the job.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 may have been the best theater this season, an heirloom
won by the resilient Pacers, 88-86, and lost by the
just-as-resilient Knicks. It did not end until Patrick Ewing missed
a fallaway 18-footer at the buzzer _ on a three-quarters-court pass
from quarterback Charlie Ward, nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the Knick assassin who finished only 3 of 11 from the
field and could not get an open shot if his career depended upon
it, drew the cheapest of fouls from Chris Childs with 2 seconds
left and made the deciding two free throws.
</P>
<P>
   There may been 15 fouls not called on Tuesday night, but some of
the ones that were whistled were unnecessary and momentum
deflating. Every time Mark Jackson began to back another player
into the post, the slightest bit of contact would result in a foul.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 is at Madison Square Garden Saturday, which is nearly too
long a wait for these two rivals
</P>
<P>
   So contentious was the battle in the middle, so crucial each
possession, you half-expected a riot to break out after it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson backed Chris Childs and Ward into the post like a beer
truck with a broken parking brake. Sprewell grabbed Miller's
jersey, refusing to let the Pacer guard break free for a
3-pointers. Ewing was taunting the crowd more than they were
taunting him.
</P>
<P>
   Did you catch the elbows Antonio Davis and Kurt Thomas were
generously doling out on each screen they set? No one gave ground
in the most physical game of the National Basketball Association
season, a flat-out scrap that had people rising out of their seat
with either venom, euphoria or both.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in the stands was almost as heated and maniacal
as it was on the court. Two overzealous Knick fans were escorted
out of the building after offending everyone they sat next to.
High-fived on the way out by Herb Williams and the Knick bench, the
scene typified the lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   Two young children sat a few rows in back of the Madison Square
Garden president Dave Checketts, holding a sign up with an arrow
pointing toward Checketts: ``Phil Jackson's Next Boss,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a lot of second-guessing going on Wednesday,
especially when it comes to Jeff Van Gundy not going to his bench
earlier in the second half or the Knicks having any timeouts at the
end of the game. Camby, though, had an open wound on his leg that
had to treated, costing the Knicks a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, Childs and Camby were instrumental in bringing the
Knicks back, but their abysmal first half were responsible for
putting their team in a double-digit halftime hole.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson kept the Knicks in this game, scoring 22 points
over three quarters and hitting 9 of his first 12 shots. He did not
finish strong, but he was the thread in their comeback and his
defense was brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Where this series goes from here, no one can say. The Pacers are
the best road team in the post-season, winning every game they have
played away from home. They are poised, they will be rested and
there is no reason to think they cannot steal one of two games at
the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have to feel good about their resolve, even if did
fall 2 points short in a game they had every chance to win. As Bird
said before Game 2, ``It's going to be a long series, that's what
I'm telling all my players.''
</P>
<P>
   A war took place here on Tuesday night, one of the best
post-season games in recent memory. And as good as it was, you
still get the sense that the battle has only begun. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
