<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' `THUG' HELD OWN AGAINST FORSBERG
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA AND WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Richard Matvichuk has been called ``thug'' in the
Denver media. He has been labeled a cheapshot artist who has
inspired Avalanche center Peter Forsberg to a new level in the
playoffs because of his dirty play.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, however, the Stars defenseman was simply called
``good.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk and defensive mate Derian Hatcher won their battle
against Forsberg _ or at least tied it _ and that's all the Stars
can ask. Forsberg has been the catalyst for the Avalanche and he
had another outstanding game Tuesday night. However, not so
outstanding that it dragged his teammates to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a great player, one of the greatest in the world,''
Matvichuk said. ``So any time you get a chance to challenge
yourself against one of the greatest in the world, you take it
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk, the Stars' leader in hits per game (three) for the
past two seasons, didn't have one Tuesday night. He blocked three
shots and took three shots. Mostly, though, he held Forsberg to one
assist with solid positional play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what our job is and we knew we did a horrible job (in
Game 5),'' Matvichuk said. ``Tonight, we went back and worked hard
and did our job.''
</P>
<P>
   And that job included the Stars' defenseman scoring his third
career playoff goal in his 50th postseason game. So, did he take
any satisfaction in outscoring Forsberg?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even see it go in,'' Matvichuk said. ``I was heading
back to play defense, that's what my job is all about.'' EVENLY
MATCHED
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with the altitude and everything to do with
the hockey. Sighs of relief are rarely breathed in this Western
Conference finals series.
</P>
<P>
   When the Stars scored two goals in a 14-second span to take a
4-1 lead, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I let out my sigh of relief,'' he said. ``I took
my hands out of my pockets then and relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   While just two of the first six games have been decided by a
single goal, the teams have split the first six games by playing
evenly matched hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two wonderful hockey teams that are giving
everything they've got in order to get to the dance,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Every game goes down to the last 10 minutes and every game
is up for grabs. It doesn't matter what happens
</P>
<P>
   the first 50 minutes. Both teams are confident they can play
their best right now.'' SIDES DON'T MATTER
</P>
<P>
   The left-to-right move of winger Jamie Langenbrunner has paid
big benefits for the Stars during their playoff run.
</P>
<P>
   He spent much of the season playing on the left side and scored
only a dozen goals. Moved back to the right side for the playoffs,
Langenbrunner, a natural right-handed shot, scored twice in the
Stars' 4-1 Game 6 victory Tuesday night and has eight playoff
goals, only one behind team-leader Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving him back to the right side has been huge,'' coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``He's just been much more comfortable there and
you can see it in the way he's been playing.'' STATIC LINEUP
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive game, the Stars used the same lineup.
Since Grant Marshall returned from a sore groin and Shawn Chambers
returned from a knee injury, the Stars have been virtually
injury-free.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hrkac continues to nurse sore ribs, but is close to being
cleared to return.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the healthy scratches for the Stars were Derek
Plante, Brad Lukowich, Aaron Gavey, Jon Sim, Marty Turco, Doug
Lidster, Brent Severyn and Alan Letang. HART FAN
</P>
<P>
   On the back of Brett Hull's skates are written the initials,
``O.H.'' It's Hull's tribute to Owen Hart, the wrestler who died
last week after falliing from a support wire as he was being
lowered into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Hull is a huge fan of pro wrestling and has appeared as a
celebrity in a match.
</P>
<P>
   Hull said the league has honored NHL player Steve Chiasson and
Columbine High School with stickers on the players' helmets, and he
has been remembering Doug Wickenheiser, an old friend and St. Louis
Blues player who died of cancer. So he thought honoring Hart was
natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got stickers all over our helmets and I've been wearing
the Wick sticker all year,'' Hull said. ``(Hart) was a good
Canadian and it was such a tragic loss. I just wanted to remember
him.'' FIRST GOAL
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has scored first in the past four games, but has
won only two of those four games.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Stars are 5-3 when scoring first in the playoffs
and 6-2 when giving up the first goal. TRIPLE THREAT
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have not lost three consecutive games since April 1-4,
1998. That's a span of 121 games _ including the playoffs the past
two seasons. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
