<HEADLINE>
KING IS TALKING TO KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dave King might not become the Los Angeles Kings'
next coach, but at least he has the right name.
</P>
<P>
   King, an assistant coach with the Montreal Canadiens, Tuesday
became the third candidate to interview with general manager Dave
Taylor for the Kings' vacant coaching job. On King's resume are
stints as coach of the Calgary Flames and the Canadian national
team.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor _ who also signed three players Tuesday _ previously
interviewed former Buffalo coach Ted Nolan and Long Beach Ice Dogs
coach and general manager John Van Boxmeer. Taylor is expected to
interview Detroit assistant Dave Lewis and possibly another
candidate this week. He is expected to conduct second interviews in
mid-June, with a decision likely before the June 26 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor signed junior defenseman Richard Seeley, Finnish right
wing Marko Tuomainen and free-agent left wing David Hymovitz, who
scored 46 goals this season for Indianapolis in the IHL.
</P>
<P>
   Of immediate interest is Tuomainen, whose one-year contract is a
one-way deal, meaning he gets paid the same amount whether in the
NHL or in the minors _ a sign the Kings expect Tuomainen to
contribute this season. The 6-foot-3, 205-pound Tuomainen, 27, was
drafted by Edmonton in the ninth round in 1992 and spent the past
two seasons in the Finnish league, collecting 50 points in 94
games.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-11, 185-pound Hymovitz, 25, signed a two-way,
two-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Seeley, a sixth-round choice in 1997, signed a two-way,
three-year deal. The Kings had to sign him by Tuesday's deadline or
he would have gone back into the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
