u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-1ST     06-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE WAR IS ON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ At one point near the end of the first half on
Tuesday night, Patrick Ewing drew his third foul and went to the
bench to the accompaniment of some 16,000 fans in Market Square
Arena chanting an obscenity at him. Ewing raised his great wingspan
as if to encourage them, and wiggled his lengthy fingers as if to
say, sticks and stones can hurt your bones but _ well, you ain't
hurtin' us.
</P>
<P>
   A shrink in the stands might have wondered if Patrick was losing
it, especially since his Knicks had fallen behind to the Pacers at
this juncture in this second game of the Eastern Conference finals
by 15 points. In fact, Ewing, who has in his basketball dotage
become the emotional linchpin for this team, was just expressing
the determination, the tenacity, the implausible impetuosity of
this team.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the fourth quarter was little more than 30 seconds
old they had tied the game at 71 and shortly after took the lead,
and even went ahead by 6 at 78-72. The Pacers fought back, however,
to go ahead again. And it was close until the finish when Reggie
Miller hit two free throws with two seconds remaining to give
Indiana a 88-86 victory in Game 2 to forge a tie in their Eastern
Conference final.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Knicks had vanquished the favored and home-team Pacers
in the first game of the four-of-seven-game series, Mark Jackson,
the Pacer point guard, was asked before the second game if his team
felt a sense of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same desperation as Game 1,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly all games in the playoffs are significant. But staring
the Pacers in their collective, determined faces was the distinct
and rather ugly possibility that if they lost again on Tuesday
night they would go into Madison Square Garden to resume the
series, down 2 games to 0, and play the next two games before that
wild and crazy Gotham crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Of course an athlete must feel loose and confident if he is to
perform at his apex. And Larry Bird, the Pacers' head coach, and a
former player of some note, understands this fully. He acknowledged
that the Pacers would have to get back quicker on defense to stop
the Knick fast break, that Rik Smits, his 7-foot-4-inch center had
to be more aggressive on offense and perhaps a little less
aggressive on defense _ no silly fouls!
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, too, that his estimable star sub, Jalen Rose,
couldn't take his Knick counterpart, Latrell Sprewell, as a
personal insult, but had to remain in the flow of the team game,
and he acknowledged that it is important for Jackson to not only
post-up Chris Childs, but had to make those jump hooks from close
range that he missed.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers indeed made adjustments, but so did the Knicks _
including having Larry Johnson crash to the hoop for 17 points in
the first half, and Childs hitting two big long shots as the Knicks
caught up and passed the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Given all that and more, Bird also laid the underpinnings for a
potential loss in Game 2. ``We're a good road team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. And the success included no road losses Milwaukee and
Philadelphia, since the Pacers swept the Hawks and 76ers in the
first two rounds of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who played for the Knicks for five seasons, starting in
1987, is hardly a stranger to the Garden. Nor are Chris Mullin or
Sam Perkins, both of whom, like Jackson, are from New York City.
And when Jackson was asked about a New York tabloids headline that
called this series The ``Knicks versus Hicks,'' he said he found it
curious. ``We have three guys from New York City,'' he said, ``I
don't know where the Knick guys are from, but I'd bet none of them
have ever been to downtown Brooklyn.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing is from Jamaica (not Queens) and Boston; Allan
Houston is from Louisville, Larry Johnson's from Tyler, Texas.
Sprewell is from Milwaukee, Childs from Bakersfield, Calif.,
Charlie Ward from Tallahassee. Only Marcus Camby and Chris Dudley
are even neighbors, from Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   And to Reggie Miller, the Great Knick Villain, the Garden is
like a second home. Tensions with the Knicks are generally a happy
sop to him _ though his 3-point shot with his team down by a point
with 12 seconds to to in Game 1 ended by the ball hitting the front
rim. But he hit the winning free throws on Tuesday night, and now
Knick fans will remember how he burned them for 39 points in Game 5
of the 1994 conference finals, his 8 points in 8.9 seconds to
co-opt Game 1 of the 1995 second-round series and his 3-pointer in
last year's second-round series, which forced overtime, won by the
Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought Knicks-Pacers would be a war,'' Rose said.
``And now we have one.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or, to paraphrase Jackson, same ol', same ol' desperation. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
