<SLUG> BC-BBA-HELLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING KEEPS IT CLOSE IN RANGERS' WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MILLER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Early in Tuesday night's game, Texas Rangers
starting pitcher Rick Helling felt similar to his Opening Day start
when he allowed seven runs, five earned, in only three innings of
work of an 11-5 loss.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he never lost his focus.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did not get the win, Helling kept Texas within
striking range with seven strong innings of work, allowing one run
on three hits and three walks, in the Rangers 3-1 come-from-behind
victory against the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let that one get to me and I pitched poorly,'' Helling said
of his Opening Day performance. ``Tonight, I battled through it and
I did a good job of keeping the team in it. I didn't have my best
stuff, but those are the nights you have to find a way to get
through it and battle. Tonight, I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the first five innings of the game, Helling fell behind
in the count to most of the batters he faced. He started off 12 of
the first 18 batters he faced with balls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he seldom found himself in any real trouble. He allowed one
hit and two walks in the first four innings with only one runner
advancing as far as second base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to throw mostly zeros up on the board and keep the
team in it and give us a chance to score some runs and win the ball
game,'' Helling said.
</P>
<P>
   The only time he allowed two base runners on base in one inning
came in the fifth when he walked catcher Chad Kreuter, who later
came home on a two-out, full-count double by second baseman Steve
Scarsone.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed one base runner in his final two innings of work,
leaving the game after the seventh with the Rangers trailing 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' second baseman Mark McLemore said. ``You can't
ask for anything more out of your starter. I just wish he would
have been able to get the win.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling lowered his earned-run average to 4.99, the first time
last year's 20-game winner has had it below 5.00. He is the only
member of the Rangers' starting rotation allowing fewer than five
runs a game.
</P>
<P>
   It is only the second time in 12 starts Helling (5-5) has not
figured in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rick has pitched a whole lot better than his basic
numbers indicate,'' Texas manager Johnny Oates said. ``What was
this? His 12th start? I believe he could have won nine of those
very easily.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
