<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     06-02 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STARS, BORING CAN BE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DENVER _ For what it's worth, and that may be plenty, the Stars
backed off the muscle here Tuesday night. While not exactly turning
a cheek, they did turn a page. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This, of course, had been a bruising Western Conference finals
of one crunching blow after another. Unlike Stone Cold Austin and
his ilk, none of it was fake either. The last guy left standing got
to score the game-winning goal. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Game 6 statistical sheet will show the Stars with 16
``hits.'' You will see more than that on a ``Jerry Springer
Show.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had been over 35 hits in three of the previous five
games, two of them losses. The low for the series had been 23,
which was a Game 3 shutout victory for Dallas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We got carried away with the physical stuff, and that
benefited \RColorado\S,'' admitted Guy Carbonneau, who has been
around the NHL long enough to know the difference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So staying alive for the Stars last night meant going back to
plain ol' basics, which brought many changes, including combat
restrictions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And while these ``basics'' have been described in Denver circles
as boring to watch, the yawns aren't necessarily restricted to the
Mountain time zone. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Stars' locker room, players are sometimes heard
plotting an occasional escape from Ken Hitchcock's button-downed
defensive system. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But last night, when survival was all about now-or-never on road
ice, the Stars willingly returned to those foundation roots of
``positional hockey.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The racehorse _ meaning the Colorado Avalanche _ never left the
barn. Whatever that 12-goal thing was Sunday afternoon, this time
it was the Stars that dictated ice space and tempo. And this time
the frustration slowly but surely overwhelmed the Avalanche. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Game 6 was up for grabs in the third period. The Stars did the
grabbing, and wouldn't let go, piling up three goals in the final
13 minutes en route to a 4-1 victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, we got our organizational feet back under us,'' said
Hitchcock. ``The emphasis was on positional play. What happened was
not unexpected. We always perform well in adverse situations.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With one of those adverse situations successfully overcome, now
there's Game 7 on Friday night at Reunion Arena. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is that good or bad? The Stars have more road victories in this
series. Could they possibly lose three out of four games to one
team at Reunion? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many questions still to come, but first, there had to be the
Game 6 answer. Or many answers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among those was Eddie Belfour returning from the Game 5 dead. He
was brilliant again in goal. And when the offense had to get going
after an early 1-0 deficit, Jamie Lagenbrunner led the way with his
third-period outburst. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why then, did Hitchcock's first praise in his postgame comments
center on the ``\RBrian\S Skrudland line, with \RGrant\S Marshall
and \RBlake\S Sloan?'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because those grinders established an energy tempo, not to
mention a game-plan tempo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``If we play good, they can't beat us,'' sniffed Avalanche
defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh afterward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ozo, however, sounded more bored than defiant. Which is the way
the Stars want to keep the Avalanche for Game 7. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How can anyone say it's boring?'' asked Hitchcock, knowing the
Denver media has, more than once in this series. ``This is the way
we have to play to win. It's a system that suits our personnel. Our
players are proud of that. It takes discipline, but we play well
this way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Opposed, of course, to the Game 5 monster. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``As a series is in progress, sometimes both teams get caught up
in a certain style of play,'' Hitchcock said. ``And sometimes, like
in Game 5, the schedule takes its toll, creating fatigue. That
happened Sunday at home.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In regrouping the troops for last night's most important game
ever for a Dallas hockey team, Hitchcock said he never attempted to
calm nerves. ``Actually, you'd better be nervous at this time of
year,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there was also no detailed game plan to stop a Colorado team
that had hung up seven goals two days earlier. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we spent 15 seconds talking about Colorado at
our team meeting today,'' added Hitchcock. ``The only discussion
was about us. About who we are and what we are all about as a team.
And what it takes for us to be the kind of team we know we are.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other words, boring was beautiful last night. And more
boredom is needed for Friday night. &QL; 
 &LR; tagtop:Randy Galloway's ``Sports at Six'' can be heard weeknights,
6-8 p.m., on WBAP NewsTalk 820.
 &LR; tagbottom:rgalloway\Nstar-telegram.comnn
</P>
</TEXT>
