<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL JUST CAN'T SEEM TO GET IT RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Major league baseball has always abhorred spontaneous
bursts of creative intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the owners are so comfortable with Bud Selig as
commissioner; that's why the umpires' union, instead of the rules,
is allowed to run the game on the field; that's why baseball's
marketing slogan has been (brace yourself) ``What A Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Put all the good ideas that have improved baseball for fans and
players into a book, and it reads faster than ``The Peruvian Guide
to World Dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   So when umpire Frank Pulli Sunday relied on instant replay to
correct an erroneous call on a home run by his crew in the
Florida-St. Louis game, he found himself predictably upbraided
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use of video replay is not an acceptable practice,'' National
League president Len Coleman said. He was backed by his American
League counterpart, Gene Budig, who said, ``Major league baseball
games are determined between the lines, and electronic assistance
is not permitted.''
</P>
<P>
   No word on whether Pulli was sentenced to watch the WB network,
or similar hideous punishment that fits the crime.
</P>
<P>
   But it's plain that baseball has a larger priority on doing
things the standard way instead of pursuing fairness. Which once
again proves the point that there is little difference between
baseball and most of the rest of corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   No, there was no expectation that, based on one episode,
baseball should suddenly adopt instant replay in the middle of a
season. But the summary dismissal of instant replay by most of
baseball showed its standard lack of enlightenment.
</P>
<P>
   Even Pulli had backed away from his act so fast he was near a
reverse whiplash.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things went through my mind,'' he said. ``I hope I
don't have to go to the replay again. I don't want it to become
like football.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohmigawd, no. Let's not be like the NFL, a sport that at least
is attempting to get things right this fall by re-introducing a
limited use of instant replay.
</P>
<P>
   Given the hundreds of episodes of umpire judgment that are a
part of every major league game, baseball traditionalists assume
that replays would render the already languid game inert.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that logic, Ben &AMP; Jerry's should be labeled a hazardous
substance, because eating it too fast will create fatal ice cream
headaches.
</P>
<P>
   It's all in how the item is used.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL this season will confine replay's use to out-of-bounds,
goal-line and possession calls, limiting the number of challenges
as well. It's a better, faster system than the unwieldy method used
from 1986 to 1991 that alienated even replay advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Replay is a partial answer to a chronic, once-insoluble problem
in football and many sports: Too many things happen too quickly or
too distantly for the eye to see and the mind to interpret.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that TV often can provide the home audience with better
information than any available to officials only serves to
aggravate a skeptical fan base already primed to believe the worst
about the source of judgment calls.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest results of the NFL's original experiment with
replay was to confirm that officials were right most of the time.
When they weren't, calls were reversed and the sport's credibility
increased. Changes to the method this time around figure to reduce
the delays and inconclusiveness that compromised the NFL's first
try.
</P>
<P>
   Replay's use in baseball should be even more limited than
football: No balls and strikes, no plays at a base, no continuation
plays (in which a reversed call would have an undetermined effect
on subsequent play).
</P>
<P>
   Replay's primary use would be for what Pulli encountered Sunday:
Potential dead-ball situations that determine a home run or a fair
ball at points far from the nearest umpire.
</P>
<P>
   If stadium fences were uniformly distinct, there would be far
fewer ground rules. But fences, including the Kingdome's right
field, often are not clear, festooned as they are with scoreboards,
railings and other gewgaws.
</P>
<P>
   No Kingdome season has passed without several arguments about
whether a long ball hit a fence, a rail or a fan before bounding
back onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   A fat umpire lumbering into the outfield can only guess about a
small, fast-moving object 150 feet away. But of course, if that
shortcoming were eliminated, we would also forego the privilege of
witnessing spittle exchanges between the cherubic arbiter and Lou
Piniella, which is hell on hygiene but always a highlight.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine what kind of threat will be posed to
baseball's integrity in which well-placed, unmanned cameras provide
key information about fair or foul, home run or double.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm sure a demon will be discovered and seized upon by
umpires, players and owners and beaten senseless, in order to
restrain baseball's entry into the 20th century, just in time for
the 21st.
</P>
<P>
   Why spend a few thousand bucks on the game's credibility when
many millions can be given to old, broken-down pitchers?
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
