<HEADLINE>
ROSE STEALS THE SHOW BY BEING HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ After two years, Jalen Rose was finally the
player Larry Bird wanted. Or so the Pacers' coach thought. Gone
were the games when Rose would attempt to steal the spotlight with
dazzling one-on-one moves, with flashy cross-over dribbles in the
paint. Or so Bird thought.
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who had slowly turned himself into a structured team
player under Bird, reverted to his old ways in Game 1 of the
Knicks-Pacers playoff series, lured there by the showy Latrell
Sprewell. Rose tried to mirror Sprewell's performance, and it got
him benched for the final nine minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just his way of telling me he loves me,'' a smiling
Rose said, referring to the benching. ``Everyone wants to be in
there during crunch time. You don't make it to this level by
settling for anything less.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose was in the right frame of mind before Game 2 on Tuesday
night. Having taken criticism for his selfish play, he said he had
learned his lesson. For 14 minutes in the first half, Rose played
within himself, scoring 5 points on 2-for-6 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the spotlight fell on Rose, but not because he
forced it upon himself. He was front-and-center late in the fourth
quarter because he made several crucial shots down the stretch to
bring the Pacers back in a game they won, 88-86.
</P>
<P>
   With the Knicks leading by 78-72 with a little more than seven
minutes to play, Rose nailed a 10-foot jump shot to pull the Pacers
within 4 points, 78-74. The capacity crowd at Market Square Arena
jumped to its feet. On the next Pacer possession, Rose was fouled
by Chris Dudley as the two chased a loose ball. Rose went to foul
line and sank both shots to pull the Pacers to 78-76.
</P>
<P>
   Then after Reggie Miller, who had been coasting through a quiet
game, sank a 15-footer to bring the Pacers even with the Knicks at
78-78, Rose hit his biggest shot thus far in the series with 5
minutes 13 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pacers in serious jeopardy of traveling to Madison
Square Garden down by 0-2, Rose popped out at the far right corner
and fearlessly nailed a 3-point shot that gave the Pacers a 81-78
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Rose finished the game with 13 points on 4-of-10 shooting,
including 2 of 3 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game Bird said: ``We'll see. I think Jalen will have
a good game. He usually backs up a performance like he had the
other day. Just as long as he understands what the problems were.
And the problems were that he was breaking a lot of plays where he
was trying to go one-on-one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a better player when he comes off a pick and gets the
ball and penetrates and makes plays. Jalen is a fine basketball
player, and we need him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Rose proved his coach right. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
