<HEADLINE>
BELFOUR'S PERFORMANCE QUIETS RUMORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Ed Belfour was one game away from possibly his last
game in a Dallas Stars uniform _ or so it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   Lose in Game 6 Tuesday night and the rumors about Belfour's
future in Texas would have taken on the combined force of
discussions currently surrounding Cowboys players Michael Irvin and
Deion Sanders. It was that important.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have to choose between Belfour and Roman Turek this
summer _ they have to make a choice not unlike when the San
Francisco 49ers had to choose between Joe Montana and Steve Young.
With the expansion Atlanta Thrashers ready to take one of the two
goalies in the expansion draft, the Stars have a tricky decision.
</P>
<P>
   And if Belfour would have gone out in Game 6 with a loss after
allowing six goals in Game 5, the jury would have been out on
Belfour and the push to keep Turek would have grown wings.
</P>
<P>
   But Belfour made that point moot Tuesday night _ at least for a
few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he thinks about that stuff at all,'' Stars
defenseman Craig Ludwig said. ``I just think Eddie has been
tremendous and he continues to be great. He was there when we
needed him tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   So was there an easy explanation for Belfour's meltdown in Game
5 on Sunday afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a night game, and Eddie's always ready for night
games,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but Game 7 is a night game, not that Belfour is
concerned. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
