<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANGENBRUNNER GIVES STARS A LITTLE EXTRA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
DENVER _ Ken Hitchcock closed his eyes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No, silly, not for the whole game, but for those few seconds
late in the third period, when Jamie Langenbrunner was racing down
the ice with the puck all alone, just him and Colorado goalie
Patrick Roy and a full house at McNichols Sports Arena holding its
breath.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner had already given the Stars a 2-1 lead _ it would
prove to be his fourth game-winner in the playoffs _ but everybody
knows a one-goal lead isn't enough against these guys. With just
under four minutes to play, this was his chance to put Roy and the
Avalanche in their Rocky Mountain graves for good.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least for Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't watch,'' Hitchcock admitted.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Langenbrunner never got a shot off _ Roy, coming out
of his crease, poked the puck away as Langenbrunner tried one deke
too many _ but the Stars and their sometimes star-crossed
left-to-right winger would not be denied.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-five seconds later Langenbrunner one-timed a pass from
Dave Reid into the net, helping the Stars to a pulsating 4-1
victory that ties this best-of-seven series at three games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   If ever a series deserved a Game 7, this one does, and now it's
on for Friday night at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got two great hockey teams, two wonderful hockey teams,
who are giving everything they've got to get to the dance,''
Hitchcock said. ``It never seems to matter what happens in the
first 50 minutes. It always boils down to the last 10 minutes of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Didn't think you could hold your breath for 10 minutes, did you?
</P>
<P>
   Get ready to try it for 60 minutes Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars rediscovered their game last night after Sunday's 7-5
debacle at Reunion Arena. Their second and third periods, in
particular, were brilliant, maybe their best of the season, and
came from desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could feel they had a good sense of urgency,'' Avalanche
coach Bob Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Eddie Belfour was back to his old self, stopping 26 shots
as the Stars played excellent positional hockey and still outshot
the Avalanche 40-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a night game,'' Hitchcock shrugged, referring to
Belfour's penchant for taking afternoon naps, even during games.
``No problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps most importantly for the Stars, their so-called
second line of Joe Nieuwendyk, Dave Reid and Langenbrunner, who has
found a spark since being moved back to right wing from the left
side, continued its premier playoff performance.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner's two goals were his seventh and eighth of the
playoffs, one behind Nieuwendyk's team-leading nine. Throw in
Reid's pair, and the line leads the team with 19 goals and 37
points, outperforming the more highly touted No. 1 threesome of
Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen, who scored his first
goal of this series to tie the score at 1 early in the second
period last night.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's the Modano line which has to spend its time
bumping heads and matching rushes with the Avs' No. 1 line of Peter
Forsberg, Valeri Kamensky and Claude Lemieux. But Nieuwendyk and
company have dominated the Avs' second line of Joe Sakic, Theo
Fleury and Chris Drury, nine goals to four.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nieuwendyk has just been a good player all playoffs, but
Langenbrunner's really picked it up in the last two series,''
Hitchcock said. ``We were a little down when \RBenoit\s Hogue went
out, because he played so well, but Reid's really filled in
admirably.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RReid\S is being very effective. He's had the benefit of not
playing very many minutes so he has a lot of energy, and it's just
a good line, good chemistry.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner's game-winner with 13:11 to play was another case
of his being in the right place at the right time. Nieuwendyk fired
a point-blank shot that Roy blocked, but it handcuffed him and he
couldn't control the rebound. Langenbrunner poked it past him and
into the net before Roy could recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a first great save,'' said Roy, never missing a chance
to pat himself on the back, ``and I think it hit Ozo's \RSandish
Ozoliinsh\S stick and bounced back under me. And then I think
Langenbrunner's stick was under me and I could not put my pad on
the ice and he just pushed it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Langenbrunner played a super game. I think they made
their breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche was putting incredible pressure on the Stars and
the seconds ticked away, however, and it was Langenbrunner's second
goal which gave them some breathing room and demonstrated the
resiliency and determination of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Reid, using his strength to keep control of the puck, fed
Langenbrunner in front of the net for a 3-1 Stars' lead.
</P>
<P>
   It was the foiled breakaway that lingered on Langenbrunner's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You dream about scoring goals in the Stanley Cup playoffs when
you're a kid in your basement,'' said Langenbrunner, who scored
once in 17 playoff games last year. ``It would have been nice to
put us up 3-1 with that breakaway ,but he just poked it away from
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, I got another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   So now, do the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Don't close your eyes. You don't want to miss
anything on this ride.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
