<HEADER>
A9347 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ROYALS-RANGERS-TE     06-02 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ROYALS-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS RALLY FOR EIGHTH CONSECUTIVE VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Don't mistake Kansas City's Matt Whisenant for
the Rangers' Jeff Zimmerman. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whisenant appears to compare favorably to Zimmerman
statistically, but go beyond their earned-run averages and
opponents' batting averages. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The similarities between the two relievers end there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman will not beat himself through lack of control. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whisenant did in the Rangers' 3-1 victory Tuesday night at The
Ballpark in Arlington. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Royals' left-handed reliever ignited the Rangers'
eighth-inning rally with a seven-pitch walk to first baseman Lee
Stevens, and the American League's hottest team capitalized on it
for their eighth consecutive victory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore delivered the game-winning hit with
his two-run single off right-hander Terry Mathews, and Zimmerman
(5-0) earned the victory with a scoreless inning of perfect
relief. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what one little walk can do,'' said manager
Johnny Oates, whose Rangers won their fourth consecutive game in
their final at-bat. ``It seems so innocent at first, but it led to
their run and started our three-run inning in the eighth.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stevens drew the walk, and Whisenant responded by hitting the
next two batters _ shortstop Jon Shave and pinch hitter/center
fielder Roberto Kelly _ with first-pitch deliveries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surprising? No. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whisenant (1-1) entered this appearance with a 1.69 ERA and
opponents hitting only .118 against him, but the left-hander had
issued 10 walks and hit three batters in 16 innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing worse than letting down your team,''
Whisenant said. ``I felt good. I just took a little too long to
find the strike zone out there. You can't do that in situations
like that. Anytime you walk someone in a one-run game, that's
asking for trouble.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royals manager Tony Muser summoned right-hander Mathews from the
bullpen after Whisenant failed to retire any of the three batters
he faced, and McLemore greeted him with the game-winning hit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McLemore swung at a 2-2 fastball that appeared up in the strike
zone and lined it into center field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too close to take,'' McLemore said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Rusty Greer, who twice failed to deliver a clutch
hit with a runner in scoring position in the first and sixth
innings off Kansas City starter Jay Witasick, followed with a
run-scoring single for the final run. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland followed Zimmerman's one-inning,
two-strikeout appearance and pitched a 1-2-3 ninth inning for his
league-leading 17th save, although a save opportunity appeared to
be out of the question for most of the evening despite another
strong performance from right-hander Rick Helling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling entered the fifth inning with a one-hit shutout intact,
but Witasick proved to be worthy to the task by pitching six
scoreless innings. The Royals produced only three base runners
during the game's first four innings, and the Rangers' defense
retired two of those. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling induced a one-out, second-inning ground ball from Kansas
City's Larry Sutton that McLemore and shortstop Jon Shave converted
into a 4-6-3 double play, and right fielder Juan Gonzalez retired
shortstop Rey Sanchez with an accurate throw to second base after
the latter attempted to stretch a third-inning single into a
double. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helling, though, issued a one-out, fifth-inning walk to catcher
Chad Kreuter, who later scored the game's first run. Second baseman
Steve Scarsone, the Royals' No. 8 hitter, worked the count full
before delivering a two-out double. Kreuter scored easily from
first base by getting a running start on the two-out, 3-2 pitch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that run would stand until Whisenant unraveled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't give up,'' McLemore said. &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
