<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEHTINEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEHTINEN'S GOAL BRINGS STARS BACK FROM RINK OF DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Colorado Avalanche followed the script perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   A high-spirited, high-energy first period was winding down with
a scoreless tie when Claude Lemieux deflected a shot past Ed
Belfour with just 35 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche already had a 3-2 series lead on the Dallas Stars
going into Tuesday night's game. Now surely they had them out, with
the lead, the momentum and the backing of a raucous, sellout crowd
at McNichols Sports Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Surely money-goalie Patrick Roy would pitch a shutout, and the
Stars' season would be over.
</P>
<P>
   But then Jere Lehtinen sent the script to rewrite.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars forward lifted a shot over Roy less than two minutes
into the second period and washed away the bad taste of the late
first-period goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big for us,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``That
was a great goal. From then on we picked it up and got better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars went on to a 4-1 victory, tying the series and forcing
a deciding seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was important to get that first goal just to tie it up,''
veteran forward Guy Carbonneau said. ``We came back in the room and
talked about it. We knew we could come back. It was a matter of
keep playing disciplined and look for the opening.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal was Lehtinen's sixth of the playoffs, but the first of
this series. While the other marquee players on both sides had
their moments of brilliance, Lehtinen was silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was pressing a little,'' he said. ``I have had chances
almost every game. I just had to keep playing hard, and hope it was
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   It came because Lehtinen has a nose for the puck, and knows what
to do when he gets it.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had the puck in the Colorado end, and the line of Mike
Modano, Brett Hull and Lehtinen worked hard to keep it there.
Modano dug it off the boards, and passed it to defenseman Sergei
Zubov at the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov unleashed a slap shot that was stopped in front by Hull,
who was going for the deflection. Then, the puck landed on
Lehtinen's stick.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen had just enough time to mentally review the scouting
report. He knew that Roy's butterfly style makes it hard to beat
him low because he drops down so quickly, so he didn't want to just
slide it across the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got it, I said I have to shoot upstairs,'' Lehtinen
said. ``We have seen that work, when you shoot up.''
</P>
<P>
   He went top shelf, hitting the narrow gap between Roy's left
shoulder and the cross bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a little bit of time to look,'' he said. ``I was glad it
went into the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal provided redemption for the first line, which was on
the ice when the Avalanche scored late in the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our line made some mistakes on their first goal, and we wanted
to get that back,'' Modano said. ``It was a great play by everybody
to keep the puck in the zone, and then by Zubie to get it on net.
It gave us new life and got us back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen's goal was the only one by the trio, but it wasn't
their only scoring chance. The first line combined for 13 of the
Stars' 40 shots, with Hull getting five and Modano and Lehtinen
four each. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
