<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-1STLD-W     06-02 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAY HAVE DIFFICULTY RENEWING CHINA'S TRADE TIES WITH U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Fixes in 9th and 10th grafs)  (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the seventh time since he took office,
President Clinton will ask Congress on Thursday to renew China's
trading privileges with the United States. It has always been a
dicey proposition, though one that Clinton _ with aggressive
lobbying help from companies with interests in China _ has always
won.
</P>
<P>
   But this year the battle over what is now called ``normal trade
relations'' with China promises to be more confused, more emotional
and far trickier than at any time since the military crackdown in
Tiananmen Square, exactly 10 years ago. Just a few months ago
Clinton and the Chinese had hoped to be asking Congress for far
more _ for permanent trade privileges, as part of a deal that would
usher China into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides say that on Thursday the president will hold
open the possibility that the bigger and more permanent deal will
be struck soon _ presumably after the furor dies down here over
accusations of Chinese spying and in Beijing over the mistaken
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. But some of Clinton's
advisers say privately they fear the chances of getting a trade
deal signed with the Chinese and through an angry Congress are
increasingly remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are watching,'' one of his advisers said last week,
``is a seven-year initiative with China crumble in our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the White House called that initiative the development of a
``strategic partnership'' with China, a phrase that has now been
stricken from all official references to that country. So has the
term ``commercial diplomacy,'' once used to describe how increased
economic engagement with China would strengthen ties in other
arenas. Now the White House, and the business community, are
arguing the opposite, why national security issues should be
divorced from trade.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's seeming ambivalence about how to tackle this
vote _ which usually becomes a congressional referendum on the
state of Chinese-U.S. relations _ is mirrored by the ambivalence of
the Republicans. Roughly half the hopefuls for the Republican
presidential nomination _ including Pat Buchanan, Steve Forbes and
Gary Bauer _ argue that the spy case underscores why the United
States should suspend negotiations with China over WTO admission.
</P>
<P>
   The other half, including Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen.
John McCain, have carefully separated the issues, with McCain, the
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, arguing that ``we should
make judgments on the basis of our trade interests. The scandal is
not that they spied on us, but that we let them.''
</P>
<P>
   For many business executives, this year's debate over how to
respond to the spying accusations has echoes of the debate that
played out in the first two years of the Clinton administration,
over tying China's human rights record to its trade privileges.
Clinton himself started out that way and reversed course,
separating human rights issues from arguments over the annual
renewal.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Intel Corp., Andrew Grove, said he saw the
relationship in terms of parallel universes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is the political and geopolitical universe, where
nations have problems and collaborations,'' he said. ``There is the
trade universe and then there is a universe of technology issues.
And what we have to deal with _ whether we want to tie those three
together, so that if it hits a brick wall they all stop making
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Grove's concern, one that he and other technology executives
plan to voice in Washington next week, is that Congress will link
the trade vote to new restrictions on technology transfers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entirely possible that higher-end Pentium III's will not
be salable in China,'' said Grove, referring to Intel's
top-of-the-line microprocessors. ``Imagine that: A personal
computer you will be able to buy for $1,200 at CompUSA by the end
of the year could not be shipped to China.''
</P>
<P>
   Grove and other technology executives argue that such
restrictions would not deny technology to China; they would only
force China to make its own. ``And then you have to ask: Are we
better off in any of those universes _ the political one, or the
trade one, or the technological one _ if we force them to build up
their technological base on their own?''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, though, such subtleties have not yet been debated.
After Tiananmen, Congress imposed a series of trade and technology
restrictions, many of which have since been lifted. There may be
the same reaction this time.
</P>
<P>
   But some on Capitol Hill say they believe that when passions
cool, there will once again be momentum for a trade deal that opens
China's markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end,'' said Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., who is pushing
for permanent trade privileges, ``people will come to realize that
all the concessions in this trade agreement are on China's side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
