<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS     06-02 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ It was time for a Reggie Miller moment.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or perhaps we should say it was about time for a Miller moment.
</P>
<P>
   With two seconds left in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference finals
at Market Square Arena on Tuesday night, Miller strode to the foul
line and buried two free throws to give the Indiana Pacers a
dramatic 88-86 victory over the New York Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   In true theatrical fashion, though, the victory wasn't wrapped
up until Patrick Ewing's last-second jumper clanged off the rim,
giving the Pacers a split in the first two games of the
best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   And New Yorkers thought the best shows were found on Broadway.
It was Miller _ again _ playing the villain to New Yorkers in this
act, which was performed before 16,586 at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who made a living by killing the Knicks, had yet another
opportunity Tuesday. He wasn't at his best in this game, scoring 16
points on 3-of-11 shooting, but he was there when the Pacers needed
him at the end.
</P>
<P>
   That's all the Pacers could have wanted. And it's all the Knicks
feared.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who had not scored a field goal since popping in a
3-pointer with 8:03 to play in the first quarter, pump-faked Allan
Houston to draw the two-shot foul, and he wasn't about to miss
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to get the ball on the last play,'' Miller
said. ``They really don't count stats on how many (shots) you make
or miss. It's who wins the ballgames. As long as you make the last
one, that's all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   And New Yorkers are familiar enough with Miller's history
against the Knicks to know he was going to drain those last two
foul shots.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Miller is the same guy who scored 25 points in the
fourth quarter to personally win Game 5 of the 1994 conference
finals, the same guy who scored eight points in a span of 8.9
seconds of the fourth quarter to beat the Knicks in Game 1 of the
1995 conference semifinals. And it was Miller who rifled in the
game-tying 3-point shot with 5.9 seconds left to force overtime in
Game 4 of last season's conference semifinals, a game the Pacers
won 118-107.
</P>
<P>
   Knicks fans can now add Tuesday's game to the list.
</P>
<P>
   But they're probably busy blaming the referees to give Miller
too much credit for pulling out the win for the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials Dick Bavetta, Hue Hollins and Joe Forte established
early how this game was going to be played, and neither team was
happy about the tempo. The teams were whistled for 68 fouls _ 40 on
the Knicks _ and they combined to shoot 84 free throws, turning the
game into a marathon-like procession to the respective foul lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your best players are sitting over there with you (at the
end of the game), it's not a great feeling,'' said New York coach
Jeff Van Gundy, referring to Larry Johnson, who fouled out with
4:58 to play after scoring a game-high 22 points. ``I guess there
was a statement to be made about whatever I don't really know what
the statement was supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Indiana coach Larry Bird wanted to hear none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They shouldn't be disgruntled over any calls that were made
out there,'' Bird said. ``I thought the officiating was going
haywire out there for a while, so they should be very happy with
calls they got.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's foul shots capped a frantic final minute that saw both
teams take short-lived leads.
</P>
<P>
   Despite trailing by 17 points in the first half, the Knicks
rallied to take a 78-72 lead on Houston's baseline hook shot with
8:24 left in the game. But the Pacers weren't about to fold,
outscoring the Knicks 12-2 over the next five minutes _ a run that
was capped by a three-point play by Dale Davis (15 points and 12
rebounds) that gave Indiana an 84-80 lead with just over three
minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks scored the next six points, four by Ewing, to retake
the lead at 86-84 with 45.5 seconds to play, but Antonio Davis
scored underneath to tie the game with 31.1 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks brought the ball downcourt, attempting to get one
good look at the basket, but Houston committed a crucial turnover
with 20.4 seconds remaining that gave the Pacers time to work the
ball to Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove to the basket, but I probably should have pulled up
for a shot,'' said Houston, who finished with 15 points on 3-of-12
shooting. ``I didn't get a shot up, and in that situation you have
to get a shot up.''
</P>
<P>
   But after Miller's foul shots, the Knicks got one last look at
the basket, throwing the ball nearly the length of the court to
Ewing, who missed a wide-open jumper from the left of the
free-throw line at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a desperation play,'' said Ewing with a shrug. ``I got
a good look and a good shot. I thought it was going to drop, but it
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing like some good drama to enliven an already entertaining
show. But as riveting as the show has been so far, the series now
goes on hiatus, resuming Saturday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   And about the only problem the Knicks face as they head back to
New York is dwelling on what could have been.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, the only eighth seed to ever make it this far in the
playoffs, could have been going back to New York with a sweep of
the first two games in the Eastern Conference finals but instead go
home with a split.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of disappointed,'' said Ewing, who was limited to 10
points in 25 minutes. ``This is a game that we could've won,
should've won. We had our opportunities, but for whatever reason _
and I'm not even going to dwell on it _ we didn't. Now we have to
come back, regroup and get ready for Saturday.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
