<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For WEDNESDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Wednesday, June 2.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ANTHRAX-ISLAND (Vozrozhdeniye Island, Uzbekistan) _ In the
spring of 1988, Soviet germ scientists secretly transferred
hundreds of tons of anthrax bacteria to this remote island in the
heart of the inland Aral Sea. Russian soldiers buried the germs
and, Moscow hoped, a grave political threat. Today, Vozrozhdeniye
Island _ or Renaissance Island, as it translates from the Russian _
is the world's largest anthrax burial ground. But scientists who
have secretly traveled here have discovered that some of the
anthrax spores are still alive. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.
Photos have bee sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Final
curtain-raiser on the South African election on Wednesday: how race
has defined the election. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO (Washington) _ The U.S. government's dissatisfaction
with how Mexico investigated accusations of drug corruption
involving President Ernesto Zedillo's closest aide reflects the
mistrust that continues to shape the two governments' dealings on
matters of criminal justice. Officials say it also reflects the
difficulty that Washington continues to have in handling reports of
corruption that involve high-level Mexican officials. By Tim
Golden.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-ELECTION (Serpang, Indonesia) _ One year after a
paroxysm of rioting in which ethnic Chinese were the targets of
widespread vandalism, arson and rape, Chinese all across the
country have been preparing for new attacks before next Monday's
general election. But something utterly unexpected has happened.
The election campaign, in most parts of the country, has so far
been mainly peaceful. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-OCALAN (Istanbul) _ When the Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan finished his extraordinary testimony on the opening
day of his treason trial Monday, he left many Turks and Kurds dazed
and surprised. His abject apology for years of war and avowed
determination to re-invent himself as a democrat seemed dubious but
also tantalizing. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-BABY-SMUGGLING (Agua Prieta, Mexico) _ When Martina
Toscano Quiroz gave three of her seven children up for adoption,
her main goal, she said, was to give the girls a chance to have a
better life. The lawyer who took her children to New York, she
said, ``told me he would build me two rooms with new tin for the
roof.'' Ms. Toscano never got her new house. Last week, the lawyer
and two women on Long Island were arrested and charged with running
a baby-smuggling ring. Some of the adoptive parents have complained
that the women lured them into illegal agreements by preying on
their desperation to have children. But, worlds away, in this
isolated patch of the U.S.-Mexico border, the view of these
adoption agreements gets even more complicated and tragic. By
Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-TORT-REFORM _ Alabama, where a family who sued over
$1,200 in satellite dish payments won a startling $581 million, is
taking steps to curb the big jury verdicts that have given the
state a reputation for dispensing ``jackpot justice.'' By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   SUPPLEMENT-STUDY (Undated) _ Androstenedione, the supplement
taken to boost athletic performance, did not enhance
muscle-building or increase testosterone in the blood but appeared
to produce adverse health effects in a small study of young men,
published in the latest issue of The Journal of the American
Medical Association. By Kenneth B. Noble.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON-JEWS (Princeton, N.J.) _ Jewish enrollment at
Princeton University has fallen 40 percent since the high-water
mark of the early 1980s, and Jewish students and faculty members
are asking why. Campus life for Jews, they say, has never been
better. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-SAFETY _ An ambitious Energy Department environmental
project, turning radioactive liquid wastes into a solid to prevent
leaks, is unable to surmount complicated chemical challenges after
years of work. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BARNES&AMP;NOBLE-AMAZON (Undated) _ With its planned acquisition of
the nation's largest book wholesaler in jeopardy, Barnes and Noble
is poised to carry out what its top executive calls an alternative
``plan B'' if its $600 million deal to buy Ingram Book Group
collapses. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLCAP-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Small-cap stocks are on a tear.
They even held up well the past three weeks, while the broad market
dropped about 5 percent. But can they make up all the lost ground
of the last few years? By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   VINIK-HEDGEFUND (Undated) _ Jeffrey Vinik made a famous market
call in November 1995 while still manager of Fidelity Magellan, the
world's largest mutual fund: He bailed out of $10 billion worth of
technology stocks. Now Vinik, whose Vinik Asset Management LP
manages about $2.5 billion, has slashed his technology holdings
once again, according to federal securities filings. By Richard A.
Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   IMPALA-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ It may not be your father's Impala,
but the advertising promoting the latest model of the Chevrolet car
may take him back a few years. That's because Chevy has revived it
popular 1950s song ``See the USA in your Chevrolet'' in a new
campaign for the 2000 Impala. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ Maureen Dowd comments on Tipper
Gore's efforts on behalf of husband's lackluster presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN (Indianapolis) _ The Knicks can take a
monumental 2-0 lead home to the Garden by winning their seventh
consecutive playoff game. By Ira Berkow.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RAMIREZ-BAT (New York) _ Did Manny Ramirez use a corked bat
in hitting a first-inning home run to dead center field on Monday,
as the Yankees suspect? And what happened to that bat, since
Ramirez didn't use it for the remainder of the game? By Murray
Chass.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF-PAK (Undated) _ Se Ri Pak, who will defend her U.S. Women's
Open title, is not exactly the same person, or player, she was a
year ago. She has split with a coach, dismissed a business manager
and learned that fame and fortune always come with a price. By
Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING (Moved in ``d'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HALAL-BUTCHERS (New York) _ In almost any neighborhood in
America where Muslims make their home, halal meat shops are the new
butchers in an old-fashioned way. To non-Muslims the shops can be
mysterious, even intimidating. But to others they are a happy
addition to the checkerboard of tiny, specialty food shops _ places
with impeccable meat and intensely personal service. Even as the
production of meat nationwide becomes increasingly industrialized,
analysts say that Halal meat is nevertheless the fastest growing
style of specialty butchering in the country. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-CAKES (New York) _ When a woman walked into Magnificent
Confections a few weeks ago, she wanted a simple cake for her son's
30th birthday. But by the end of her visit, she had ordered a white
sculpted elephant, with it's trunk turned up, dressed with jewelry.
``She got obsessed,'' said Lege Sulit, a co-owner of Magnificent
Confections, a tiny bakery on the Upper East Side. But in New York
today, she isn't alone in her obsession. The party cake has become
an over-the-top symbol of creativity and, some would say,
competitive excess. By Monique Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUE-SAUCE (Undated) _ Beyond the basic barbecue sauce. By
Steven Raichlen. With recipes.
</P>
