<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT     06-02 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CRUSH INDIANS, 11-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ More than a year has passed since Roger Clemens was
charged with a loss, but he is not kidding himself. Clemens
embraces the responsibility inherent in being the ace of a staff,
and his legs are not as strong as he wants them to be, he is not
pitching as well as he expects, or as long.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a time this season, presumably, when Clemens takes
off and carries the Yankees, but for now, he continues to win with
a lot of support from his teammates, who bludgeoned the Cleveland
Indians on Tuesday night in an imperfectly played 11-5 victory
before 32,759 at Yankee Stadium. Since last June, Clemens has won
20 consecutive decisions, an American League record that is four
short of the major league mark set by Carl Hubbell of the New York
Giants in 1936-37.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens grinded through a slow start and tired in the seventh
inning, and as he waited on the mound for Manager Joe Torre to
relieve him, Clemens turned and thanked the teammates around him
for playing well, again. Appropriately, Derek Jeter was among
those; he had two hits and drove in three runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on the sun right now, and the rest of us, we're playing
here on Earth,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter has reached base in all 50 Yankee games this season, which
may explain why Cleveland's Steve Reed drilled Jeter in the left
thigh with a fastball in the eighth inning, apparently retaliating
for the two Indian batters hit by pitches earlier in the game.
Jeter cursed Reed on the way to first base, and after the umpires
made sure both teams remained on their respective benches, Paul
O'Neill hammered a two-run home run _ his first homer since April
27 _ and Jeter trotted deliberately and smirked his way around the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Yankees suspected that Manny Ramirez had used a
corked bat to hit a monstrous home run in Monday's game, but as
expected, the controversy didn't spiral beyond the Yankees' quiet
accusations and the adamant denials by Cleveland Manager Mike
Hargrove. Ramirez went 0 for 5 with two strikeouts, both in at-bats
against Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled to pitch against the Mets on Sunday, Clemens said he
has not resumed his usual workouts. He likes long-distance running,
to build his legs, and while with Boston and Toronto, he developed
regular routes in the neighborhoods around the stadium. He hasn't
done this in the Bronx yet, chiefly because he strained his left
hamstring in April and is still rehabilitating.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Clemens is lacking his best stuff, his best
command. Early in Tuesday night's game, Clemens did not establish a
consistent breaking ball, or his split-fingered pitch, and his
fastball was not overpowering. He had trouble finishing off
batters. Without having to contend with Clemens's full variety or
his explosive high fastball, the Indians fought off a lot of his
best stuff: In Clemens' first two turns through the Cleveland
lineup, the Indians swung and missed only five times, and fouled
off 17 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   But he just kept grinding and grinding, catcher Jorge Posada
said, never giving in, constantly searching for a pitch that would
get him past a crucial hitter and allow him to escape a jam. ``You
see it in his eyes,'' Posada said.
</P>
<P>
   Torre said Clemens is pulled through those situations by his
toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows he pitches once every five days, and he's going to do
everything he can on that day he pitches,'' Torre said. ``He just
wants to prove he's the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens surrendered a first-inning run, but then the Yankees
came back with two, and a pattern developed: Cleveland tied the
score, 2-2, the Yankees scored the go-ahead run in the third, and
in the next half-inning, the Indians tied it, 3-3. Finally, Jeter
punched a two-run single off Dave Burba (5-2) in the fourth to give
the Yankees breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens finally fought through his mound malaise, his fastball
getting better from inning to inning, his split-fingered fastball
emerging in the fourth inning. Ramirez led off the sixth inning;
with two strikes, Clemens drew back and fired, and Ramirez swung
through. That fastball, teammates agreed later, was the best
Clemens threw all night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens tired in the next inning, telling the pitching coach,
Mel Stottlemyre, that he had some stuff left _ in Clemens code,
that means he was just about finished _ and one out later, Torre
pulled him.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander walked off to cheers and waved his glove, but
later, it was apparent in his face and his tone that Clemens wants
more. He is sure he can pitch better. He is sure he will pitch
better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
