<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9360 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     06-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MILWAUKEE _ Hitting home runs in each of his first two starts
wasn't enough to make Sean Bergman an honorary Killer B, but he
might have earned his stinger Tuesday night.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there's one thing the Killer B's needed as badly as a timely
hit or two, it was a shutout pitching performance to take some of
the heat off their frigid bats.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman delivered in timely fashion, blanking the Milwaukee
Brewers 3-0 in a rain-shortened game at County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Astros first baseman Jeff Bagwell said of
Bergman's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman's second career shutout was his first since he logged
one for Detroit on Aug. 2, 1995, against Boston. Tuesday's effort
was two innings shy of a traditional blanking because the game was
halted by rain with one out in the top of the eighth inning. But it
still counts.
</P>
<P>
   Astros manager Larry Dierker was planning to bring Scott Elarton
in from the bullpen in the bottom of the eighth inning, but Mother
Nature was on Bergman's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really didn't want to come out of the game,'' Dierker said
of Bergman. ``He came to me a couple of times trying to get me to
let him stay in. But with the conditions the way they were (cold as
well as wet), I just didn't want to push it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman's strongest showing of the year helped the Astros snap a
season-high four-game losing streak, and it took the focus off
their struggling offense, at least for a day.
</P>
<P>
   The offense wasn't much more impressive than it has been during
a much-publicized funk, but it was just enough to get past the
Brewers, who are mired in last place in the National League
Central.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros accounted for just five hits, and three of them came
in the decisive three-run seventh inning. They had gone 68 innings
without collecting more than two hits or scoring more than two runs
in the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   Russ Johnson's sacrifice fly was the only run the Astros needed,
but Tim Bogar added a little insurance with a two-out, two-run
double.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, the Astros had the bases loaded with one out and
Carl Everett due to hit when home-plate umpire Mark Hirschbeck
waved the players off the field.
</P>
<P>
   The rain delay lasted 1 hour and 12 minutes, and fewer than 100
of the 15,266 fans who attended the game were still around when it
officially was called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever a game gets rained out, I've always believed we
should come back and play it the next day,'' Astros second baseman
Craig Biggio said. ``But that's the way the rules are, and I'm glad
we benefited this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewers starter Scott Karl, who had allowed 14 runs in his last
8 innings, found the perfect tonic for his pitching woes. The
Astros have been more soothing to opposing pitchers than a hot
toddy on a cold night.
</P>
<P>
   The first nine Astros went down in order, with only Biggio, Tony
Eusebio and Johnson managing to hit a ball out of the infield.
Derek Bell ended any premature thoughts of a no-hitter with a
one-out double in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl was really sharp,'' Dierker said. ``He was throwing more
hard stuff than we had seen him throw. I felt like we were lucky to
get to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Karl retired 18 of the first 20 batters he faced, but he ran
into trouble when Bagwell led off the seventh with a single to
left. Everett singled, and Eusebio drew a walk to load the bases
with one out. Bagwell scored on Johnson's sacrifice fly to right.
Bogar, back in the lineup after missing six games because of a
hamstring injury, hit a blast to left field that looked as if it
might be a homer when it left the bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was a home run,'' Bogar said. ``I don't hit
enough of them to know when they're gone. I was just glad that I
felt good and that I was seeing the ball well after being out for
six days.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you really have to give Bergy all of the credit. Our
offense has been struggling, and he went out there and threw up
zeros for seven innings. That's the kind of thing that can really
pick you up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, who also pitched a complete game at Florida on April
30, retired 10 of the last 13 batters he faced and stranded five
runners in scoring position. He allowed six hits and two walks.
Bergman had gone six starts without issuing more than one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of guys on base in the first couple of innings,
but the defense made some great plays behind me, and we were able
to have a big inning with the bats,'' Bergman said. ``I wasn't
thinking about being the guy to stop the losing streak or anything
like that. I was just trying to stay focused on the job at hand.
This was a big win for us, and hopefully this will get us rolling
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
