<HEADER>
A9361 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS &LR;      06-02 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOX GO LONG WAY AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-RED SOX-TIGERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody wants to get into the act. If it's not the veterans
who are spurring the Red Sox to new heights, it's the new kids on
the block who are getting it done.
</P>
<P>
   No better example can be found than Tuesday night's 5-4 victory
over the Detroit Tigers at Fenway Park. What started out as a
triumphant return by pitcher Bret Saberhagen wound up as a
celebration featuring rookies Trot Nixon and Brian Daubach, who
tied and won the game with homers in the seventh and eighth
innings. The winning pitcher was John Wasdin, who would you believe
has a 5-0 record. Who's writing these scripts?
</P>
<P>
   The first-place Red Sox have a five-game winning streak,
matching their season's best so far. They aren't supposed to be a
power-hitting team, but they belted four homers Tuesday night,
getting contributions up and down the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it has been every night,'' said Daubach, whose
leadoff homer in the eighth was his second game-winner of the
season and second blast in as many days. ``I don't know how I came
through. I guess I'm just lucky in the clutch.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck? This team has had a ton of it lately. Take the ninth
inning, when the Tigers put a man on first base with two outs and
had fleet outfielder Karim Garcia pinch run for Bill Haselman. When
the next batter, Brad Ausmus, hit a double into the gap, Garcia
took off like a deer. But he rounded second like Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, stumbling across the bag. By the time he got up, he
could get only as far as third.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Lowe then struck out Damion Easley to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team is doing well right now and I want it to continue,''
said manager Jimy Williams. ``Saberhagen pitched good. All our
pitchers, overall. Our relievers have been asked to do a lot of
things lately. Fortunately, it worked for us tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for Nixon and Daubach, you have to say they're more than
just two kids on the team. They go out and compete. They're not
playing like they are rookies. But maybe it's because they're
getting some help from those veteran guys out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen used up his pitch limit at 77 and had to be relieved
after five innings, but he left with a 3-2 lead, built in part on
homers by Troy O'Leary (No. 10) and Jason Varitek. Jim Corsi held
the fort until he gave up a two-out single to Luis Polonia in the
seventh. Wasdin came in and Ausmus socked his first pitch into the
screen for a two-run homer and a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the bottom of the seventh, Nixon hit a fastball
into the Red Sox bullpen, his first home run at Fenway Park.
Daubach couldn't wait for his turn and teed off against reliever
Doug Brocail in the eighth. Not bad for a couple of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see them whack one, it doesn't surprise me,'' said
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   While the frantic finish pleased most of the 26,457 in
attendance, it was the return of Saberhagen that seemed to delight
the Red Sox most. Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan pointed out that the
righty threw 13 first-strike pitches (he faced 21 batters). His
velocity was in the low 90s, and through three innings he had
thrown just 38 pitches. But he needed 27 in the fourth inning, and
there was no way the Sox were going to let him go over 80 pitches
after five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a lot of things right,'' said Kerrigan. ``I'd like to
see him go throw six innings, but 77 was enough. Next time we'll go
for 90.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Williams, ``He did a nice job. After all the rehab, he came
back and was ready to throw. He got 15 outs and came out when we
were ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, predictably, had mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy the way I threw,'' he said. ``I'm disappointed that
I only went five innings. I've always gotten the ball to the
bullpen later in the game. I understood the pitch count tonight. I
just hope I can do a little bit better next time. I was able to
throw all my pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year it's a matter of me staying healthy and being able
to do what I think I can do. I want to pitch a couple of complete
games before it's over. That's my goal right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
