<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
PORTUGAL: NO DECISION 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-PORTUGAL-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He came to Fenway Park. But he didn't hang around.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox righthander Mark Portugal cleaned out much of his
clubhouse stall after pitching three innings in Monday's win over
Detroit and left the park in a bit of a huff.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, he was back to meet with Red Sox brass and talked with
some teammates in the clubhouse before the game, but he was not in
the dugout when it started.
</P>
<P>
   He got together with manager Jimy Williams and then general
manager Dan Duquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have a resolution to his status with the
team,'' Duquette told reporters during the game. ``He's still on
the roster. He's considering a couple of different options and he's
got a couple of personal issues he needs to get resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette declined to detail the options or the issues or how the
team might resolve his situation. But he did point out that
Portugal _ who suffered an incomplete dislocation of his left
shoulder while fielding a ball early in Monday's game _ was
healthy. And, Sox officials emphasized, he did not have a problem
with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not hurt, so we're not considering the disabled list as
an option,'' Duquette said. ``He's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he did not expect Portugal to be available to the
media in the next couple of days, nor did he expect him around the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met (Tuesday) and we're going to meet again later in the
week,'' Duquette said. ``He's not in uniform (Tuesday night), but
he's on the roster. We've discussed a number of different things,
but we haven't done anything yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he hoped to have Portugal's situation resolved by
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Portugal had brought up the subject of retirement,
Duquette responded, ``Not directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Pat Rapp would take Portugal's place in the
rotation for Sunday's game against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take care of things in-house,'' Williams said. ``It's a
personal matter and we'll deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, 36, had run into a few rough outings of late. He won
his first two games of the year but had just one victory in his
last eight starts.
</P>
<P>
   That stretch started with maybe his best performance of the
year, a three-hit, no-walk job at Detroit that he lost, 1-0. He had
two straight no-decisions, then a win, another no-decision, and two
losses before Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It was against Detroit again Monday that he suffered his
toughest game of the year, leaving after three innings and having
given up six runs on six hits. He hurt his left shoulder in the
second inning but convinced Williams he could continue to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Duquette became aware of Portugal's personal
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had some things on his mind other than pitching,''
Duquette said.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal is 3-3 with a 5.33 earned run average.
</P>
<P>
   While Rapp, who pitched three strong innings in relief Monday,
gets the start Sunday, Saberhagen's return couldn't have come at a
much better time with Portugal out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess so,'' said Saberhagen. ``A few days ago, everyone was
asking who, where, what, and why, and with Mark going down and
having some problems, Pat steps back into his spot almost like he
didn't miss a whole lot because of the way he pitched (Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen saw Portugal both Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's got some things to go over,'' Saberhagen said. ``I know
his knee's been bothering him. His shoulder (Monday) was bothering
him. He needs to kind of sit down and think exactly how he's going
to approach the rest of this. All we can do is offer him support.
We'd like to have him pitching for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Whiteside of the Globe staff contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 0141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
