<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9365 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-H     06-02 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ They were saying all the right things, but no one knew
quite what to expect. Two days earlier, he had been so awful that
his coach wouldn't even comment on his play, and there was little
in Eddie Belfour's history to suggest this was the ideal spot to
bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened between a wretched Sunday afternoon at Reunion
Arena and a remarkable Tuesday night in the Rockies?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a night game,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said with a
smile. ``Eddie is always ready for a night game.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, he was ready for this one. With game, season and
perhaps even career on the line, Belfour stopped 26 of 27 Colorado
shots as the Stars stunned the Avalanche 4-1 to extend the NHL
Western Conference finals to a Game 7 Friday night in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie came up big,'' said Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner,
whose two third-period goals broke open a tight game. ``He had a
rough outing, as did the team, in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came out and played a great game just when we needed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Dallas dodged elimination after flirting with
disaster in an ugly 7-5 loss just two days earlier. Now, at the end
of a series in which the home team has won just two of six games,
neither the Stars nor the Avalanche will be taking anything for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only an advantage if you make it one,'' Dallas' Brett
Hull said of heading back to Texas. ``So far, it hasn't meant
much.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be an issue for another night. There will be at least
one more for the Stars because a fellow who looked so awful in
giving up six goals his last time out _ dredging up memories of
big-game meltdowns past _ was able to rebound from one of the worst
big-game performances of his career.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up a goal to Claude Lemieux to account for the
game's first score with just 34.9 seconds left in the opening
period, Belfour stared down Colorado's three-time Stanley Cup
winner Patrick Roy the rest of the way. In doing so, he gave Dallas
time to establish control of the style and pace, subtly turning the
game the Stars' way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made some big saves for us when we needed him,'' Stars
winger Mike Keane said. ``Eddie's a very emotional goaltender, but
he knows we need him to stop pucks for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he doesn't make the saves, who knows where we'd be?''
</P>
<P>
   Playing golf today, most likely. The challenge of delaying those
tee times would not be without its anxious moments, though, made
all the more so by Belfour's awful experience in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected him to come back, just like the rest of us,''
center Mike Modano said. ``We needed a big game, and Eddie gave us
one.''
</P>
<P>
   After Jere Lehtinen's roofer beat Roy 1:55 into the second
period, the teams stayed tied into the third. As Dallas clung to
postseason life, the Avalanche tried to close the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 1-1 after two periods, and whoever got that next goal
was a big difference,'' Colorado's Joe Sakic said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Langenbrunner got it, picking up a rebound of a Joe
Nieuwendyk shot and poking it past an off-balance Roy at 6:49. The
Stars nursed the one-goal edge for the next 10 minutes before
cashing in twice in 14 seconds _ the first on a power-play goal by
Langenbrunner, the second on a shot off a faceoff by Richard
Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, a series of strange plot twists was going the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's be honest: We played a very solid first period, but the
second and third (Dallas) played extremely well,'' said Roy, who
has been beaten nine times in the last two games. ``Give them
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, in particular, seemed due for some. His rocky moments
were a big part of Dallas' demise in last year's conference finals,
and he was the focus of much of the attention heading into this
make-or-break Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Would Eddie ``The Eagle'' lay another egg? The McNichols crowd
did its best to goad him with the standard derisive chants, but
Belfour was not to be had.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to stay as calm as you can,'' he said. ``But there
were a few butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   To win it, Belfour did his best to tap into happier thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since you are little kids, you're always playing for the
Stanley Cup and pretend it's Game 7,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he did in those games, Belfour allowed a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we always won,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the real thing, it hasn't been quite so simple, as Belfour
has yet to see his name etched on the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Dallas moved a step closer. The fellow at the
center of the storm did all but assure it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
