<HEADLINE>
HILL LIFTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Yes, the Texas Rangers have won eight in a row
and are threatening to run away with the American League West. Yes,
the Anaheim Angels are in last place, 6{ games out, their biggest
deficit of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels have something positive to focus on: June.
</P>
<P>
   With Angels starter Ken Hill coming within one strike of
throwing the club's first complete-game shutout of the season, the
Angels began June much like they finished June of last season. By
winning _ this time 5-1 over the Minnesota Twins before 17,003 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Last June the Angels went 22-6, their best month in club
history. Ever the optimist, Angels manager Terry Collins pointed
out that their record of 25-27 is not much different than last
year's mark at this point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through 52 games last year we were 26-26, just a couple games
off the pace,'' he said. ``Are we happy? No, of course not. But you
look at the whole situation and you have to be optimistic. The most
important thing is to keep the confidence up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill did his part, coming so close to throwing the first shutout
by an Angels pitcher since Chuck Finley blanked the Devil Rays on
April 17, 1998. But the Twins' Corey Koskie homered with two out in
the ninth on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Hill threw a season-high 123 pitches at that point, so Collins
replaced him with Mark Petkovsek, who needed only one pitch to get
the final out and end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's only other trouble came in the fifth inning, when he
walked the first two batters. But he got Todd Walker to hit into a
4-6-3 double play, then got Denny Hocking on a comebacker,
stranding the only Twins baserunner to reach third.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Angels' offense came from Randy Velarde and Troy
Glaus. Velarde went 2 for 4, including his fifth home run of the
season; Glaus went 2 for 3, including his seventh homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was an especially good sign for Glaus, who was benched May 27
after his average had dipped to .226. In the five games since,
Glaus is 5 for 12 with two homers.
</P>
<P>
   This night, however, belonged to Hill (2-4), who won for the
first time in six starts. He gave up five hits, struck out six and
walked three.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
