<HEADLINE>
HOMESTORE.COM APPLIES FOR IPO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- HomeStore.com Inc., a collection of three real
estate Web sites, registered Tuesday with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to hold a $100 million initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which had revenues of $5.5 million for the quarter
ended March 31 and $19.1 million for all of 1998, said it hopes to
raise money with the IPO to make its sites the premier real estate
destinations on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents filed with the SEC, HomeStore's three
sites are already the most heavily trafficked collection of real
estate Web sites on the Internet. David Rosenblatt, the group's
vice president of marketing, said that data compiled by Media
Metrix, an Internet traffic monitor, found the company's sites are
receiving about 1.8 million unique visitors each month.
</P>
<P>
   The HomeStore sites include Realtor.com, the official Internet
site of the National Association of Realtors; HomeBuilder.com, the
home site of the National Association of Home Builders; and
CommercialSource.com, a site targeting commercial real estate
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced plans last month to buy SpringStreet.com,
a San Jose-based site that provides renters with apartment
listings.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore's various sites generate revenue from advertising and
by renting out Web space to other Realtors. The company said,
however, that it has consistently lost money and expects to operate
at a loss for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   HomeStore's planned IPO will be underwritten by Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter, with Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette; Merrill Lynch &AMP;
Co.; and BancBoston Robertson Stephens acting as co-managers.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
