<HEADLINE>
HILL LIFTS ANGELS OVER TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Yes, the Texas Rangers have won eight in a row
and are threatening to run away with the American League West. Yes,
the Anaheim Angels are in last place, 6{ games out, their biggest
deficit of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels have something to positive to focus on: June.
</P>
<P>
   With starter Ken Hill coming within one strike of throwing the
club's first complete-game shutout of the season, the Angels
defeated the Minnesota Twins 5-1 on Tuesday before 17,003 at Edison
Field, and the Angels began June much as they finished June of last
season: by winning.
</P>
<P>
   Last June the Angels went 22-6, their best month in club
history. Ever the optimist, Angels manager Terry Collins pointed
out their record of 25-27 is not much different than last year's
mark at this point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through 52 games last year we were 26-26, just a couple games
off the pace,'' he said. ``Are we happy? No, of course not. But you
look at the whole situation and you have to be optimistic. The most
important thing is to keep the confidence up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill did his part, coming close to throwing the first shutout by
an Angels pitcher since Chuck Finley blanked the Devil Rays on
April 17, 1998. But with two outs, the Twins' Corey Koskie homered
in the ninth on a 3-2 pitch to center field.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had made a season-high 123 pitches at that point, so
Collins replaced him with Mark Petkovsek, who needed only one pitch
to get the final out and end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's only other trouble came in the fifth inning when he
walked the first two batters. But he got Todd Walker to hit into a
4-6-3 double play, then got Denny Hocking on a comebacker,
stranding the only Twins baserunner to reach third until Koskie's
homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got out of sync a little bit,'' Hill said of the walks in
the fifth. ``I started to think about my mechanics, and that's the
last thing I need to do. But I gathered myself and made a pitch to
Todd Walker and got out of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Angels' offense came from Randy Velarde and Troy
Glaus. Velarde went 2 for 4, including his fifth homer of the
season; Glaus went 2 for 3, including his seventh homer.
</P>
<P>
   It was an especially good sign for Glaus, who was benched May 27
after his average had dipped to .226. In the four games since,
Glaus is 5 for 12 with two homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not trying to muscle the ball, and he's putting a good
swing on it,'' Collins said. ``He's shortened his swing a little
and he's seeing the ball good. He's taking balls down and away that
he wasn't 10 days ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This night, however, belonged to Hill (2-4), who won for the
first time in six starts, his previous win coming April 29. He gave
up five hits, struck out six and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great. I felt as good in the ninth as I did in the
first,'' Hill said, adding that losing the shutout was not a
disappointment. ``The biggest thing is getting a win, no matter how
you get it. We needed a win. I needed a win. It's been rough.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like all pitchers, he lives with command,'' Collins said.
``When he throws good, he spots his fastball. Tonight he was doing
that. He was also throwing other pitches. He threw splits when he
was behind in the count, and when you do that, it keeps people off
your fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a 1-0 lead in the third inning after Glaus
doubled, went to third on a grounder to second by Matt Walbeck and
scored on Andy Sheets' sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels knocked Twins starter Mike Lincoln (1-8) out of the
game in the fourth after Garret Anderson (double) and Todd Greene
(single) each drove in a run with basehits, giving the Angels a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus and Velarde homered in the seventh and eighth innings,
respectively, to give the Angels and Hill a 5-0 lead entering the
ninth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
