<HEADER>
A9382 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-02 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES SOLVE GARCIA IN RUNAWAY WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It wasn't the inning from Hell, but the Mariners still
felt flames lapping at the feet of their yearling pitchers for
nearly a half-hour Tuesday night at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   When all the ashes were pushed aside, as well as rookie starter
Freddy Garcia and first-year reliever Jordan Zimmerman, the
Baltimore Orioles had sent six runs across in the sixth inning to
break a 4-4 tie and punish the M's with an eventual 14-11 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The home club made things interesting in the ninth inning with
five runs _ including home runs by Russ Davis and Dan Wilson _ all
off former teammate Mike Timlin. Davis, in fact, had two homers for
the evening, his 13th and 14th. But the damage had long been done.
</P>
<P>
   This 28-hit, 11-pitcher epic was familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, the Mariners were bruised for a 14-batter,
eight-run fourth inning by the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, suffering
through 44 minutes of despair en route to a 15-7 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve Orioles marched to the plate this time. Half faced
Zimmerman, and none of them went away unhappy. Five got hits, the
other got hit.
</P>
<P>
   Making just his seventh big-league appearance, Zimmerman was
called on to rescue Garcia from a two-on, one-out situation with
the game deadlocked at 4. Zimmerman didn't come up for air. Most of
the 21,597 fans went out for some.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have my stuff tonight,'' said Zimmerman, who had
given up just two harmless hits in his previous outings. ``It
seemed like everything I threw up there, they hit. It's just one
bad game. I'm sure there are going to be plenty.''
</P>
<P>
   As this one quickly got away from the Mariners, the crowd turned
their loud invective on manager Lou Piniella, obviously displeased
with Garcia's departure time.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the move, Piniella said Garcia was struggling and
Zimmerman had been virtually unhittable. Five of the upcoming
Baltimore hitters were lefties; it was a natural move. Plus, Garcia
had exceeded a 100-pitch limit, one strictly enforced with the
Mariners using a four-man rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jordan just didn't get it done tonight, but he'll be all
right,'' the manager said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia wasn't at his best, but he wasn't exactly throwing
batting practice either. Through four innings, the righthander had
a 4-1 lead and a clear shot at picking up his seventh victory in
eight decisions. Ken Griffey Jr. helped put him out front, doubling
in a run in the first and singling home two in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia (6-2) couldn't stay out of trouble, giving up three
runs in the fifth. His big mistake was plunking Brady Anderson with
an 0-2 pitch with one out and the bases clear. Delino Deshields and
B.J. Surhoff followed with run-scoring doubles and Harold Baines
knotted the game with an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Garcia gave up a leadoff single to Cal Ripken Jr.
He had a chance to avoid major damage when the next hitter, Mike
Bordick, skipped a grounder up the middle. M's shortstop Alex
Rodriguez dove and gloved the ball, but couldn't make the flip to
second for the force and a possible double play.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia came back to strike out the next batter, Charles Johnson.
But his evening was over. The Venezuelan was yanked in favor of
Zimmerman, having exceeded the all-important pitch count. A couple
more might have prevented considerable discomfort. When the inning
ended, Baltimore was up 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   Outwardly, the Mariner rookie pitchers emerged from this mess
wearing brave faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't at all frustrated,'' Zimmerman said. ``A couple guys
hit good pitches. A couple guys hit bad pitches, which really
surprised me. You make mistakes up here, they're going to jump on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Garcia, ``I have no excuses. I felt pretty good tonight. I
felt strong. It happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
