<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 03:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9390 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-BENEFACTOR-SFCHR     06-02 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-BENEFACTOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISS BROWN'S `BABIES' BOUND FOR COLLEGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By THAAI WALKER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  OAKLAND, Calif. _ Some call her Miss Brown. To others, she's
Mama.
<P>
   Twelve years ago, Oral Lee Brown stood before a class of 23
first-graders at Brookfield Elementary in Oakland, looked into
their small brown faces and told them: I am not here to take the
place of your parents. I am here to try to help you be the best
person you can be.
</P>
<P>
   This month, 19 of those youngsters will receive their high
school diplomas. Miss Brown will be at each ceremony _ nine
graduations in all. And in the fall she will send them all to
college.
</P>
<P>
   It is the promise she made all those years ago _ to shepherd
them through elementary, middle and high schools, to help them get
into college and to pay their way once there.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, the Oakland Realtor has put $10,000 into a trust
fund. The money has come out of her own pocket; set aside from
commissions made selling working-class homes in East Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The money will help pay for tuition and housing at schools such
as San Francisco State University, Georgia Tech, Clark University
and Merritt College.
</P>
<P>
   But the promise Miss Brown made to ``the babies'' as she calls
them, was about more than just money and schooling. She promised to
be hard on them when they deserved it; to put her arms around them
when they needed a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's like a second mother,'' Teisha Beverly, 17, says of Miss
Brown, who has been on her case lately because her grades have
slipped. Teisha, who wants to be a nurse, plans to attend Oakland's
Merritt College in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go to her with any problems you have _ things you
can't tell your parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Now high school seniors, the youths are scattered throughout
schools in Oakland and other parts of the East Bay _ one lives as
far away as St. Louis. But Miss Brown has kept her eye on all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brown is not the first one to go into a community where
poverty is abundant and hope is scarce, and promise to give a group
of children a shot at a future they might not otherwise have.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best known of such benefactors is Eugene Lang, who
18 years ago promised 61 Harlem sixth-graders that if they stayed
in school, he would pay their college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Lang and other philanthropists who have followed
suit, Miss Brown, 54, is not rich. She lives in the same struggling
community her children do. Reared in rural Mississippi, she, too,
grew up in a place where dreams were hard to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where Miss Brown grew up, she had a hard life, just like
ours,'' says Michael Tatmon, a Castlemont High School student who
plans to attend Louisiana's Southern University in the fall and who
knows without a doubt that he will be famous someday.
</P>
<P>
   It would not feel the same, Michael says, if Miss Brown had come
from a world different than his.
</P>
<P>
   When she was a child, Miss Brown would sit on the long front
porch of the small wooden house she shared with 12 brothers and
sisters, her parents and a grandmother. She would look into the sky
and watch crop-dusting planes flying overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, she would say aloud to a sister, I'm going to fly high
in the sky just like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did lots of dreaming,'' she says from inside her small
windowless office in the East Oakland realty company she has run
for the past 20 years, a smile touching her face.
</P>
<P>
   Reality had a way of doing things to dreams if you were black
and living in Mississippi in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Reality was a young black boy named Emmitt Till; lynched for the
transgression of whistling at a white woman. Reality was knowing
from an early age that you stepped off the sidewalk into the road
if a white person was headed your way.
</P>
<P>
   She got two pairs of shoes a year _ one for church, the other
for school. In the summer she went barefoot. Her dresses were made
out of 50-pound flour sacks.
</P>
<P>
   She was 18 when she came to Oakland on a Greyhound bus to live
with an older brother. Over the next few years she went to college,
raised three daughters (one died in 1977), got married, then
divorced and worked a variety of jobs: a hairdresser, a dispatcher
and a file clerk. She opened the realty company in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   ``God had gotten me out of Mississippi,'' she remembers thinking
in 1987. ``I figured I'd work another four or five years and then
retire.''
</P>
<P>
   But one afternoon, while heading to a corner store for a snack,
she was stopped on the street by a little girl who asked her for a
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brown took the child with her to the store. She thought the
girl, who looked about 9, would simply buy some potato chips, but
the child picked up a loaf of bread, some cheese and bologna.
</P>
<P>
   As they left the store, Miss Brown asked her: Where is your
mother? Don't you go to school?
</P>
<P>
   ``At home'' and ``sometimes'' were the answers. They went
separate ways at the corner. Miss Brown never saw her again.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to work bothered, and the troubled feeling would
not leave her. Three weeks later she phoned the principal at
Brookfield Elementary, a school where most students are black and
poor and college is often not even a dream, much less an
expectation.
</P>
<P>
   She told Principal Yolanda Peeks: I want to adopt a class. I
want the kids no one expects to go anywhere in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her I wanted to be able to go to the school every week
to see about my babies,'' Miss Brown recalls, ``that I wanted to
tutor them, talk to them and that when 1999 rolled around _ which
seemed like a long time to me _ the kids would go to college.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 years, there have been nights, at the end of long
demanding days divided between running her business and tending to
the children, that she has gone home bone weary, climbed into bed
and cried. It was all much harder than she had ever envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   And now, as the days whittle down to when the children will don
caps and gowns, she is both elated and sad _ sad that four of the
original 23 children will not graduate because of their grades.
</P>
<P>
   It sits heavy on her mind and heart. She has gone over it again
and again in her head, ``What could I have done differently?''
``Did I do enough?'' Once she even asked the four: ``Where did I go
wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   They told her she had done everything right.
</P>
<P>
   She has bought some of them shoes when they had none. She has
fed them when their was no food in their homes. Every year there
are Christmas presents.
</P>
<P>
   She has taken them on outings to show them the world that exists
beyond East Oakland. Once she took them to a farm in Manteca so she
could teach them how to milk a cow.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, she took them on a tour of colleges. They went to
out-of-state schools such as Morehouse, Spelman and Georgia Tech.
Most of the youngsters had never been on an airplane before.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Brown got the biggest thrill watching the looks on their
faces as the plane rose high into the sky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
