<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9391 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-BOOM-SFCHRON &LR;      06-02 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-BOOM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   MORTGAGE DOOR OPENS WIDE FOR MANY BUYERSBy RAMON G. MCLEOD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Getting a home loan used to be a pretty big deal, something you
sweated out as you prayed that the banker would overlook that old
late payment on your gas card.
<P>
   But now we live in an easy-credit world, a time when
unsolicited, preapproved, $75,000 equity lines come in the mail and
the 20 percent down payment for a house is ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   The shift started in the early '90s with a confluence of events
_ the newly elected Clinton administration's desire to curb
redlining, industry innovation that allowed for more home loans and
new technology for determining whether borrowers are likely to pay
their bills.
</P>
<P>
   Without those changes, it would be hard to comprehend the kind
of price increases and bidding wars that have characterized the Bay
Area housing boom. Even with the robust economy, very few people
could pony up the $60,000-plus it would take for a down payment on
a $300,000 home under the traditional mortgage lending system. But
now, much smaller down payments _ often less than 5 percent _ are
commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   And while the credit revolution of the '90s has made home loans
easier to get for everyone, it has dramatically boosted home
ownership rates for minorities, who are now the fastest-growing
group of homeowners in the nation. Data are sketchy for single
women, but mortgage brokers say that this group, too, has greatly
benefited from new credit practices and rules.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993 to 1998, home ownership for white households increased
by 3.4 percent. But it increased by 8.6 percent for African
Americans and by 13.5 percent for Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were programs for us in 1993 that just weren't there
before,'' said Reg Moore, an African American meter reader who
bought a home in Antioch that year with his wife, DiShon, and their
four children.
</P>
<P>
   The home, an attractive, modern, 2,000-square-foot home with
five bedrooms on a quiet street, was priced at $163,000 in 1993,
which would have been out of reach for the Moores if they had been
required to put down 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to put relatively little down on the house,
though it was a lot of money to us ($12,000),'' he said, ``and we
got an adjustable loan that really made it possible to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the biggest downside connected to changes in lending
practices has been a troubling rise in personal bankruptcy rates,
usually blamed on credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, mortgage default rates have stayed low and
steady, meaning that the ``nontraditional'' homebuyers are good
about paying their mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people get themselves overencumbered, it happens after they
buy their house,'' said Ginny Ferguson, co-owner of Heritage Valley
Mortgage in Pleasanton. ``Credit cards are far too available to
people, and some people mistake all the offers they get as some
kind of validation that they can run up their bills. That's where
the trouble usually comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Today in the Bay Area, more than 52 percent of homebuyers are
buying their first home, according to 1998 data from the Mortgage
Bankers Association of America. This is a major shift from the
1980s, when the overwhelming majority of buyers were existing
homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   What is even more remarkable is that this is happening in the
costliest housing market in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question in my mind that if things had not
changed, there would be very few first-timers buying houses in the
Bay Area,'' said Hannah Goody, owner of Goody Mortgage and
Investments in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people come in with a minimum down payment because it is
too hard to save up $40,000 or $50,000,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what helped first-time buyers like Elena Pushnova.
</P>
<P>
   A single Russian immigrant, she has a limited credit history and
minimal personal savings. She has a good job as a molecular
biologist, earning about $56,000 annually, but a decade ago, a
person with her background would have been sneered out of most
banks.
</P>
<P>
   However, with a little help from her friends, a good credit
record and a willingness to live frugally, she was able to buy a
1,100-square-foot A-frame home last year in Oakland's Montclair
district. The home cost $209,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, I had to start from scratch. I needed
clothes, furniture, everything. I came here with a suitcase and
$50,'' she said. ``By '96 I was starting to save, but it looked
like many years before I would have enough to put a down payment on
a house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I started hearing that I could do it without a lot of
down payment. So I borrowed $8,000 from friends and I was able to
get a mortgage that had a special program for new buyers. ... I got
$2,500 cash back in closing costs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s and early 1990s, people like Pushnova and the
Moores would probably have been excluded from the housing market.
</P>
<P>
   However, three things happened in the 1990s that dramatically
altered the home-buying landscape:
</P>
<P>
   --Political pressure. Reports of denying credit _ called
``redlining'' _ to people living in minority neighborhoods led the
newly elected Clinton administration to pressure the industry for
easier credit.
</P>
<P>
   --Industry innovation. The so-called ``secondary market'' has
grown, providing the industry with a steady flow of cash to lend
from the sale of mortgages to the Federal National Mortgage
Association (Fannie Mae) and the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
(Freddie Mac), two federally chartered, but private organizations.
</P>
<P>
   --Credit scoring. Technology was developed that accurately
predicts whether a person will pay bills on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is interesting history, one that most people outside the
industry don't know. But it was one of those rare times when you've
got a real win-win situation,'' said Brian Carey, a spokesman for
the mortgage bankers association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1993, after a major refinancing wave, there was excess
capacity in the market. There was more money to lend than there
were customers. At the same time, there was a big push on by the
Clinton administration to reach out to nontraditional and minority
home buyers. There was real acknowledgment that there are these
markets that were underserved and that helped push along new
programs with no down payments and low down payments,'' Carey said.
</P>
<P>
   The emergence of that ``secondary market'' for mortgages has
made a substantial difference in the availability of money for home
loans, said Michael Carney, executive director of the Northern
California Real Estate Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system that was typical through the early 1980s, home
loans were made by savings and loan associations, which, with their
limited reserves, eventually would find themselves without any
cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically it worked this way: I give you money and you give me
the note and trust deed. But eventually I have no more money to
lend and my primary asset becomes the IOUs, the notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This created liquidity problems for the S&AMP;Ls,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, President Richard Nixon signed a law that authorized
Fannie Mae, a quasi-federal agency, to purchase conventional loans
from lenders. That same year, Congress also created Freddie Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Both these entities are private, stockholder-owned corporations,
with very similar purposes: They buy mortgages from lenders,
package the mortgages into securities and then sell the securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took some time, but this brought a great deal of liquidity
to the market,'' Carney said. ``Instead of just holding the loan
paper as an asset, the S&AMP;L sells them to Fannie Mae, which gives
them cash so that they can in turn loan out more money.''
</P>
<P>
   The last piece of the equation that has revolutionized lending
has been credit scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit scoring is a method of projecting who is likely to pay
or not pay,'' said Sally Taylor Shoff, director of credit bureau
products for Fair, Isaac of San Rafael, the national leader in
developing the software used by banks and credit bureaus to
generate credit scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this has really done is to allow credit granters to be
precise in the kind and amount of credit they are willing to issue
to an individual,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Practically speaking, what this means is that even people with
poor scores won't be turned down as much as they will get
alternative credit offers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even a bad credit risk can get a loan, although
it will have a higher interest rate than that given a person with a
good history.
</P>
<P>
   The way it basically works is that an individual's credit
history is matched with a computer model that is based on patterns
of repayment of people with similar histories to the credit
applicant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A score won't tell you that this particular person won't
pay,'' she said. ``It will tell you that this person is part of a
group, 90 percent of whom will pay their loan. It is up to the
lender to then decide whether they want to assume this risk and to
price their loan accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, because scoring can accurately predict default risk,
individuals are allowed to carry a much higher amount of debt than
once was thought safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit scoring really revolutionized the whole industry,''
said Karen Christie, an analyst with Bank Rate Monitor, a lending
industry watchdog group. ``There really were points at which people
would be cut off from credit because of some pretty unscientific
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the not-so-distant past, a lender would be
reluctant to give a mortgage to people who would be spending more
than 36 percent of their gross income on mortgage, credit cards and
all other debt repayment. Lenders today routinely go beyond that
old standard.
</P>
<P>
   This makes it possible for someone like Pushnova, whose
obligations total about 40 percent of her gross income, to get her
mortgage, Christie said.
</P>
<P>
   Pushnova said the $1,900 she has to pay each month for her
insurance, taxes and mortgage do require her to be smarter about
her money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I've had to tighten my belt, but I'm not starving. I
go out with friends to restaurants and to the jazz clubs,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I have my house.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
