<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9392 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSING-LOANS-SFCHRON     06-02 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-LOANS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL PROGRAM OFFERS $16 BILLION FOR S.F. BAY AREA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By REBECCA SMITH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ Fannie Mae will pump $16 billion into Bay Area
home lending during the next five years and will make it easier for
immigrants and public-transit commuters to buy houses under a major
initiative announced in San Francisco Tuesday.
<P>
   This is the largest commitment to a single region in the housing
corporation's 61-year history. The $16 billion will be spread among
nine counties, with at least $2 billion earmarked for San
Francisco, where the median price for a home is well over $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae, the nickname of the Federal National Mortgage
Association, will not lend the money directly to homebuyers.
Instead, it promises to buy $16 billion worth of loans from
mortgage lenders, thus encouraging financial institutions to make
home loans.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae announced the initiative at San Francisco's City Hall
Tuesday. It said the program should help 100,000 Bay Area residents
buy homes during the next five years. In addition to the overall
$16 billion loan commitment, Fannie Mae introduced two new loan
programs:
</P>
<P>
   -- The New Immigrants Initiative will let those who have applied
for permanent resident status (``green cards'') pool money for a
down payment and share the monthly mortgage expense.
</P>
<P>
   For example, an extended family wanting to buy a $200,000 home
could qualify for a 97 percent loan, as long as all adult members _
who may be parents, children, aunts and uncles _ have been living
together at least 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   All they would have to do is come up with a $6,000 down payment
(3 percent of the loan amount) and combine their incomes to come up
with the minimum $55,400 income required to qualify for a $194,000
loan.
</P>
<P>
   The ``boarders'' who, technically are not borrowers, would be
allowed to contribute up to 30 percent of the qualifying household
income, or $16,600, in this example.
</P>
<P>
   The program breaks many traditional rules of lending by allowing
people without citizenship or green cards to take out a mortgage.
In addition, the pooling eliminates the usual requirement that
borrowers come up with a down payment without using funds from
friends or family.
</P>
<P>
   Although the program is directed at immigrants, it is also open
to American families living under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   -- A Location Efficient Mortgage program lets people who ride
public transit to work qualify for a loan with less income than
people who drive. The rationale is that public-transit riders spend
less on car upkeep and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   This program is being tested in the Bay Area, Seattle and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae says it will buy at least $25 million worth of these
commuter loans, and will work with lenders, local transit officials
and the Natural Resources Defense Council, a nonprofit
environmental organization, to develop software that will determine
income requirements.
</P>
<P>
   A third program focuses on existing homeowners in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae said it will provide assistance for seismic upgrades,
such as installation of foundation bolts or cripple walls. The
Disaster Prevention Loan Program will provide financing for loans
of up to $20,000 with repayment terms of up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   There are no income limitations for the earthquake program. The
interest rate has not yet been set, though Fannie Mae pledged to
make it ``a competitive interest rate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenders said the programs seem well suited to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't for everyone, but for certain segments of the
community, they will make the difference between qualifying for a
home loan and not qualifying,'' said Dottie Sheppick, a mortgage
lender with Countrywide Home Loans in Calabasas (Los Angeles
County), one of the largest lenders to minorities in America.
</P>
<P>
   Following criticism a decade ago that its lending criteria were
too rigid, Fannie Mae has been trying to come up with more flexible
loan programs.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it received a healthy dose of inspiration from
California public officials, including San Francisco Mayor Willie
Brown and U.S. Senator Dianne Feinstein, who were both at Tuesday's
press conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only wish Fannie Mae came up with this in the 1980s when I
was mayor,'' joked Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he began pushing Fannie Mae to ``get realistic''
about the housing crisis when he became chairman of the housing
committee for the U.S. Conference of Mayors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coup to get this kind of a commitment for Bay Area
affordable housing,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fannie Mae executives said they realize that traditional
underwriting standards do not work in places with extremely high
housing costs. Though most lenders want to cap mortgage costs at no
more than 28 percent of household income, many renters pay
substantially more and could devote more of their income to a
mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an obligation to see that we're doing everything we
can to broaden the scope of what we do in the Bay Area,'' said Ted
Chandler, vice president of housing and community development for
Fannie Mae's western region in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   The programs will be promoted by lenders for residents
throughout the nine-county Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fannie Mae purchased $300 million worth of San
Francisco mortgage loans. Nationally, it purchased $400 billion
worth of purchase loans and refinance loans, providing capital to
lenders that they can recycle into new loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 0350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
