<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     06-02 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING VENT TO DUST MITE FRIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
I used to be concerned. Now I'm scared.
<P>
   An ad that runs regularly in this paper for a home
air-duct-cleaning outfit used to feature a drawing of a dust mite,
about the size of a dime, with the caption ``Not life-size.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the ad has a new drawing, much more graphic and scary, and
the mite has grown to the size of a silver dollar, and there's no
more ``Not life-size'' disclaimer.
</P>
<P>
   If one of these megamites were to crawl out of a vent, small
children could ride it. Puff the Magic Dust Mite.
</P>
<P>
   The duct-cleaning operation, screams the ad, ``helps eliminate
DUST MITES BREEDING in your vents!''
</P>
<P>
   So that's what all that noise is.
</P>
<P>
   The mite in the drawing looks like a plucked, headless, mutated
turkey. It would give George Lucas the creeps.
</P>
<P>
   Clean my ducts, hell. I'm going to spray my ducts with
automatic-weapons fire, then weld closed the vent openings.
</P>
<P>
   CASA JOE: Marilyn Monroe slept there. So did the Yankee Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   If you're into celebrity ghosts, the late Joe DiMaggio's house
at 2150 Beach St. in the Marina is a steal at $1.4 mil.
</P>
<P>
   Joe bought the place for his parents for $14,600 after he signed
with the Yankees in '37 for $15,000. Who knows how he squandered
the other $400?
</P>
<P>
   So far, no prospective buyer, says broker Joan Smith. The price
might be a little above the going rate, but consider that Joe's '91
Mercedes, Blue-Booked at $18,000, just sold for $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy the house, you'll have to BYO Joltin' Joe
memorabilia. The only trace of the Clipper is the rusty nails Joe
pounded into the knotty pine walls of the rec room (converted
garage) to hang pictures and plaques on.
</P>
<P>
   One day, plumbers working in that trophy room broke a pipe.
DiMaggio heard the commotion, ran downstairs, grabbed one of his
old No. 5 New York jerseys and began mopping up the floor with it.
</P>
<P>
   Mama mia! That's like Da Vinci using the Mona Lisa to bash out a
brushfire.
</P>
<P>
   STILL GRAPPLING with the Y2K problem, the Rite Aid pharmacy in
Oakland's Rockridge district filled Allen Matthews' prescription
and gave the expiration date as May of 2200.
</P>
<P>
   The computerized printout also listed Matthews' birth date as
1897.
</P>
<P>
   So the medicine will be fresh for two more centuries, while
Matthews, who doesn't look a day over 40, is due to expire at any
moment.
</P>
<P>
   WARM MEMORIES of Candlestick Park: That's today's oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   I take a back seat to no one in my disdain for the blah and
blustery ball barn. But as Bruce Adams points out, the 'Stick had
(and has) one thing that the new ballpark won't have _ seats.
</P>
<P>
   Available and affordable seats for average fans, that is. I miss
the old meat locker already, and it's not even gone.
</P>
<P>
   FORGET LOTTO: The Super Lotto jackpot is up around $30 mil, but
don't waste your money.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Sanfilippo has it in the bag. He won a $33 mil jackpot
seven years ago and immediately predicted he'd win another $30
mil-plus seven years hence.
</P>
<P>
   That would be now. Dennis' lucky numbers are 7 and 11. It's been
seven years, so Tuesday he bought seven quick-pick tix at exactly
11 a.m., maybe at a 7-Eleven mart.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, a former roofer who lives in San Andreas, parlayed his
Lotto fortune into a bigger fortune in real estate.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Sanfilippo is throwing a party Saturday, a
fund-raising concert for the local Women's Crisis Center, $10 for
noon-to-midnight top-name bands at the Metropolitan Theatre in San
Andreas.
</P>
<P>
   He sounds like a good guy, but it's going to be hard to root for
Dennis when the ping-pong balls start poppin'.
</P>
<P>
   YOU BITCH ABOUT the spare-change panhandlers because they might
blow your money on drugs or booze.
</P>
<P>
   But in Contra Costa County, a civil grand jury found that, among
other shortcomings of the homeless program there, ``homeless
officials were unable to provide a mission statement or written
report on how money and time were spent.''
</P>
<P>
   So would you rather donate to the homeless or to the clueless?
</P>
<P>
   And Brother, can you spare a budget spreadsheet?
</P>
<P>
   BUS, HO! The first of Muni's new NextBus computerized bulletin
boards spring to life Wednesday, around noon in a few locations.
The readouts tell you when your bus is expected to arrive, so you
can adjust your anger and frustration levels up or down, as
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   No, the board will not give Vegas odds on whether your bus will
be too full to stop for you.
</P>
<P>
   BOB BUGG is an entomologist at UC Davis, duly noted here
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Among Bugg's current writing projects: ``Nitrogen dynamics in a
non-tillage cover-cropped organic almond orchard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds fascinating, but I'm waiting for Bob's megachiller,
``Revenge of the Lust-Crazed Dust Mite.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
