<HEADER>
A9596 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KISSIMMEE03-COX     06-02 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KISSIMMEE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The destruction _ and restoration _ of a river
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Halfway across Central Florida's grassy
midsection in the late 1960s, a college student heading for Boca
Raton came upon a curious divide.
</P>
<P>
   Looking north from his French-made 1959 Simca, Richard Coleman
saw a curving waterway, its natural color a shade of dark cola.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, the water sliced south in a straight gash. It was
cloudy with clay and silt, ``like coffee with milk in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't know it then, but Coleman was witnessing one of
Florida's most notorious environmental fiascoes, still in progress.
The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers was dredging the Kissimmee River
into a straight line, destroying the snakelike curves that
sheltered game fish, wading birds, ducks and alligators amid
overhanging oaks and a 3-mile-wide marshy flood plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how much destruction was taking place,'' said
Coleman, of Winter Haven, now a 55-year-old Sierra Club leader and
boat captain.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next three decades, he would find out. Fishing would
collapse in the former river that the corps labeled Canal 38.
Oxygen levels in the water would plunge. Wading bird populations
would plummet 90 percent. And when downpours struck, the canal
would dump huge surges of water into Lake Okeechobee downstream.
</P>
<P>
   The drained land created by the canal also aided an influx of
ranches, dairies, citrus farms and homesteads into the Kissimmee
valley, worsening the lake's pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, meanwhile, would join a cadre of activists demanding
that the corps undo what it had created.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're getting their wish. Crews hired by the corps are set
to begin filling 22 miles of the canal, a project meant to restore
the curves and marshy floodplain along a little less than half of
the old river. More than 40 square miles of former flood plain will
flood again.
</P>
<P>
   But even after acknowledging its mistake, the corps says it
can't restore the entire river. That would risk creating floods
around lakes to the north _ some less than 10 miles from Walt
Disney World _ and around the town of Okeechobee to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the $495 million project is a milestone in the broad
restoration of the Everglades-Lake Okeechobee region, for which the
Kissimmee serves as the headwaters.
</P>
<P>
   For environmentalists, the Kissimmee fight also served as a
trial run for the Everglades struggle _ with the same early
skepticism from decision-makers, squabbles over money, and
hostility from property owners who objected to losing their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said we were crazy,'' said West Palm Beach
environmentalist Johnny Jones, another leader in the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   By some accounts, Kissimmee is an ancient Calusa or Ais Indian
word for ``long water.'' But today's Kissimmee is a lot shorter
than it used to be: just 56 miles long, compared to the old river's
103-mile-long meander.
</P>
<P>
   The straightened river greets boaters like a broad highway,
lined by mounds of dredged soil instead of billboards. But modest
restoration attempts have revived a few traces of the old river
along scattered detours, called oxbows. Navigating them is like
leaving Florida's Turnpike for a rutted cow trail.
</P>
<P>
   The waterway turns narrow and twisting, curving in one direction
and then another, splitting off into forks, some of them dead ends.
Oaks, maples and Carolina willows line the banks, with expanses of
prairie visible between the trees. Sand bars are reappearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to look a lot like the Kissimmee used to be,''
Coleman said. It's the river seen in photos from the 19th century,
when steamboats plied the water.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration project under way will go much further. While
crews fill in the canal, South Florida water managers plan to raise
the elevations of the lakes upstream to increase the flow
southward.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent flooding nearby landowners, the South Florida Water
Management District has spent $89 million to buy 81,187 acres
bordering the lakes and the river. The district is also paying half
the costs for the whole restoration project.
</P>
<P>
   Many landowners didn't want to leave. Others insisted that the
corps had done enough damage and should just let the river alone.
And much of the land was caught in a legal tug of war, as state
officials insisted it was former river bottom that the state
already legally owned.
</P>
<P>
   The Kissimmee restoration by itself won't solve Lake
Okeechobee's pollution problems, said Kent Loftin, the water
district's chief engineer. That will probably have to wait for a
separate $7.8 billion Everglades restoration plan from the corps.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kissimmee project should help slow the river down.
</P>
<P>
   In the rainy summer and fall, the old river used to overflow and
spread across the surrounding plain. Instead of shooting
downstream, it would lazily flow, spread and seep, filtering
through the marsh.
</P>
<P>
   When dry times returned, the receding waters would leave
isolated ponds, allowing gators and wading birds to feast on the
trapped fish.
</P>
<P>
   Okeechobee rancher Frank ``Sonny'' Williamson said he remembers
hearing ``millions of frogs'' on the river in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roar of those frogs at night when you shut off an airboat
was amazing,'' said Williamson, also a former South Florida water
manager.
</P>
<P>
   But to ranchers and other landowners, the flooding was also the
problem. A 1947 flood inundated 600,000 acres. The state demanded
action.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, the corps moved in to straighten what it called a
``crooked river.'' The new channel was 30 feet deep, more than
triple the depth of old river, draining not only the riverbed but
43,000 acres of surrounding marsh.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Loftin said, it would have been cheaper just
to buy out the ranchers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the corps finished in 1971, opponents were already
demanding that the river be restored.
</P>
<P>
   The state changed its mind first, passing a law in 1976 aimed at
devising solutions to the river's problems. In 1983, then-Gov. Bob
Graham made the Kissimmee's restoration a prime goal of his Save
Our Everglades plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the corps at first refused to issue a permit for the work,
and then contended that filling the canal wouldn't create enough
economic benefit to qualify for federal money. The corps later came
around after some changes in federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The environmentalists had one ally: Much of the land surrounding
the river is still undeveloped and without roads..
</P>
<P>
   ``If development moved in, we would have lost all of it,''
Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert P. King writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
