 Wednesday, June 2, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Thursday. If
you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SMUGGLERS-BORDER (Brownsville, Texas) _ Immigrant smugglers and
their desperate clients are now using rented infants to get into
the country, say Border Patrol officials who have documented the
practice for the first time. The unusual case of Baby Doe, a
6-month-old girl rented three times to immigrants who then posed as
a family and avoided jail because there are no detention facilities
for children, has shocked even veteran agents. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   EXTINCT-INDIANS (Refugio, Texas) _ The mystery surrounding the
Karankawa Indians of the Gulf Coast may never be answered. The
tribe disappeared from Texas by the mid-1800s. But archeologists
now have another piece of the puzzle to study: Last week, in the
middle of a major highway construction zone in the town of Refugio,
they started digging up the graves of what are believed to be the
last of the Karankawa. By PATTY REINERT. (Photos available on NYT
database.)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-ATHEIST (Austin, Texas) _ It has all the elements of a
B-movie: body parts, revenge and double-cross. But the document
that became public here last week was not created as a work of pulp
fiction. It was the result of the federal government's
investigation into the disappearance in September 1995 of famed
atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   ILLEGAL-IMMIGRANTS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ A taxpayer group is
suing California Gov. Gray Davis to stop secret negotiations over
the fate of Proposition 187, the 1994 initiative designed to cut
off government services to illegal immigrants. Davis sent a lawsuit
on the ballot measure to the 9th Circuit Mediation Office in San
Francisco. The court-run office works in secret to settle civil and
criminal lawsuits, but has never handled the fate of a ballot
initiative. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
