<HEADER>
A9599 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CERABINO-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take hurricane season kickoff as act of faith
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's that time of year again when we in
the media duly report that another hurricane season has begun.
</P>
<P>
   The opening day of hurricane season is a very artificial news
story. There's never a real hurricane in the works. It's pretty
much like any other day in late May. Except it's June.
</P>
<P>
   It's not at all like the opening of baseball season, which
involves a real event along with all the trappings of a fresh
start, including the pomp and circumstance of a presidential visit.
</P>
<P>
   The president never shows up at the National Hurricane Center to
toss out the first ceremonial weather balloon.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Nature plays dumb too, refraining from showing her hand
early by putting a weather disturbance off the West Coast of Africa
at the beginning of June.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was pretty much like every other opening day of the new
hurricane season. Uneventful.
</P>
<P>
   We did manage to get a little rain here, but it was certainly
not the kind that would send people scurrying to Home Depot for
chain saws. No, you've just got to accept the beginning of
hurricane season on faith. You've got to believe it's there, even
though you can't see it or feel it.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's like tourist season. Nobody can say for sure when
tourist season begins. It's just that one day you're driving to
work on I-95, and you realize that every other car on the road is
caked with salt and outfitted with a rack of clothes strung across
the back seat. Then you know it's tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between the hurricane and tourist seasons,
though, is that you can count on the tourists showing up every
year.
</P>
<P>
   Unreliable storms easy to ignore
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes are far less reliable. They're so unreliable that
many people around here have just blown them off.
</P>
<P>
   I know because I'm one of those people. Here's my typical
preparation for hurricane season.
</P>
<P>
   1. Read Palm Beach Post hurricane guide, paying close attention
to checklist of recommended supplies.
</P>
<P>
   2. Realize I only have tuna.
</P>
<P>
   3. Think about buying everything else.
</P>
<P>
   4. Think about something else.
</P>
<P>
   I realize this is horribly irresponsible of me. I should already
be stockpiling water, batteries, cash, insect repellent, duct tape,
and SPAM.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just for Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is, my hurricane plan for the past 15 years could
be summarized in a single word: Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   It got me thinking what it would take for people like me to take
hurricane season more seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Need tougher sounding names
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the storms need to be renamed. This year we have
storms with such ferocious names as Cindy, Bret and Tammy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, my name is Bret. I'll be your hurricane this evening.
Can I start you off with an appetizer of feeder bands?''
</P>
<P>
   How about giving them names that inspire fear? How about
Hurricane Diablo, Hurricane Sayonara, or Hurricane Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   How about Hurricane Doom, Hurricane Halitosis of Hell, or
Hurricane Slobodan?
</P>
<P>
   And we should come up with some activity to kick off the
hurricane season, something to give this phantom season more of a
presence in our lives.
</P>
<P>
   I have a parade in mind, one like the Mardi Gras, except that
people on the floats would throw batteries, instead of trinkets,
into the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   And we'll invite the president to ride on a float, and we'll
serenade him with Golf-Ball-Sized Hail to the Chief.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he might not show, choosing to distance himself from
the 12th storm of the year _ Hurricane Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
