<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Tuesday was pretty
much like every other opening day of the new hurricane season.
Uneventful. My hurricane plan for the past 15 years could be
summarized in a single word: Orlando. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ WASHINGTON _ As he stops by the men's room to
and from his office, a journalist friend of mine drops a bit of
change into the urinal. Why? Some Washington secrets are best left
unexposed. (Murray, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Kalman Gabriel started
this little project that has since landed him an agent, a book and
a 1998 Youth News Writers award. He liked to collect autographs,
but it got to be too expensive. So, he wrote to people, famous
people, and asked them a simple question: ``Dear So and So, I am a
12-year-old boy from Oyster Bay, New York. If you could give me
advice for life, what would it be?'' And for the next three years,
young Kalman kept his mailman on Long Island very, very busy.
(Minor, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Uh-oh. This could be the
beginning of the end of this Williamson County city's rock-solid
conservative, family-oriented image. Hooters is planning to open a
restaurant in Round Rock on Wednesday, June 16. Mothers, lock up
your husbands. Fathers, lock up your sons. Fathers, lock up your
daughters so they won't get jobs at Hooters running around
half-nekkid. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-COLUMN _ Though women today can aspire to the highest
office, events of the past few months convince me that if Elizabeth
Dole runs, she will have to do so while carrying gender baggage.
(Jefferson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
