<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gender will color Dole campaign
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ I remember her wearing a yellow suit at
the 1996 Republican National Convention. With microphone in hand,
Elizabeth Dole moved through the audience toward the stage as she
told America why husband Bob, the party's nominee, would make a
great president.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe ``Liddy'' wore bright blue that night. Still, whether
filtered through yellow or blue, the memory lingers of Ms. Dole, a
poised, articulate woman speaking convincingly about her man and
her party. Her performance so impressed many on the convention
floor and others _ like me _ in the television audience that we
came to believe she would make the better presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the former Red Cross director has decided to go after
the Y2K Republican nomination, I'm a tad ticked at myself for
trying to remember what she was wearing. Annoyance turns to anger
when I find myself wondering if she will be so bold as to wear red
to accept the nomination, should she win her party's mandate.
</P>
<P>
   Why annoyance? Because I'm obviously caught up in the ``woman
thing.'' Why anger? Because while I, a would-be liberated woman,
have extricated myself from the tangle of traditional gender
judgments on a conscious level, my subconscious remains actively
engaged. I become aware of this affliction whenever I catch myself
focusing on trivial details while assessing a female politician,
applying standards I would never apply to a male. I find little
comfort in discovering I'm not alone in this practice.
</P>
<P>
   Though women today can aspire to the highest office, events of
the past few months convince me that if Ms. Dole runs, she will
have to do so while carrying gender baggage. Some will be light,
such as the interest in what color she wears. Some will be heavier,
such as the speculation that her positions on abortion, gun control
and other issues are designed to prove a feminist independence.
</P>
<P>
   Inconveniently bulky baggage also will include the remarks of
her spouse, the would-be first ``First Gent'' who seems to be
bristling at the prospect. Mr. Dole's remarks that he is thinking
about donating to another Republican candidate's campaign because
he doubts his wife can raise enough money for a credible campaign
are, at best, insensitive. At worst, he has betrayed their
marriage, a private relationship that in public requires mutual
support of each other's goals.
</P>
<P>
   When contrasted with his wife's earnest appeals on his behalf
three years ago, Mr. Dole's gaffe suggests that the former senator
experienced a sexist moment, the kind of gender bias too frequently
buried deep inside men _ and women _ who thought themselves free of
the affliction.
</P>
<P>
   In her marriage and professional life, Ms. Dole faces the same
unsettling reality that has confronted others who dare to knock at
the door of an exclusive club. Those who want to share power
probably won't get in. If the club has to accept her, she will face
attempts to undermine her status.
</P>
<P>
   They will come from writers who, consciously or subconsciously,
try to reduce her to a stereotypical woman. Tongue in cheek, they
will portray her as a hysteric who may roar to be entrusted with
power but obsessed with matters only a woman would consider
important. Calvin Trillin's essay in the May 24 issue of Time,
satirizing the first 100 days of an Elizabeth Dole presidency, is
an example. Once the ``candidate-as-shrew'' image sets in,
everything Ms. Dole does likely will be viewed through a prism of
ridicule. So, perhaps she will rethink her goal and go for the
vice-presidential slot. Democrat Geraldine Ferraro already bloodied
her head loosening the hinges on that door.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if Ms. Dole remains at the door to the
presidency, hammering away, she will have the consolation of
knowing that she jolted the lock sufficiently for some future
female candidate to break in. Somebody's got to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Stebbins Jefferson writes for The Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
