<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hooters is hot news in Round Rock
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the beginning of the end of this Williamson County
city's rock-solid conservative, family-oriented image.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters is planning to open a restaurant in Round Rock on
Wednesday, June 16. Mothers, lock up your husbands. Fathers, lock
up your sons. Fathers, lock up your daughters so they won't get
jobs at Hooters running around half-nekkid.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters, the restaurant chain that features statuesque young
waitresses dressed in teeny, shiny orange short-shorts and snug,
revealing tank-top T-shirts, is coming to Round Rock. This is not
necessarily bad. Hooters and the Grand Canyon have one thing in
common _ great scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters in Round Rock. My gawd. What's next? A head shop with
casino gambling? The town is becoming downright licentious.
</P>
<P>
   You know what's causing this? Free-wheeling, hippie-dippy Austin
is starting to rub off on stodgy ol' Williamson County. The place
is turning into Sodom, and soon Hutto will be Gomorrah. Next thing
you know, Leslie and his thong will be moving up from Austin to
Round Rock to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I'm all for a Hooters opening in Round Rock. For one
thing, the location is perfect. It's on the southbound feeder road
of Interstate 35, just north of FM 1325, near Garden Ridge pottery.
</P>
<P>
   Ever notice when you go to Hooters that the customers are almost
exclusively guys? It's only fair that Round Rock guys are getting a
Hooters at this spot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being dragged for hours through Garden Ridge pottery
to look at all that Martha Stewart trash _ the dried flowers,
kitchen linens and candle accessories _ the old man can stay behind
at Hooters and look at Melanie, Bambi and Dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Hooters really is marching forward on this.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday I went by the place, which is still under
construction. Hooters is hiring waitresses and kitchen workers at
the location out of a trailer.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 200 people have applied for work, said Meagan Lee, the
assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten them from Round Rock, San Marcos, Austin,
Georgetown,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the place has already hired about half of its staff of
70 Hooters girls.
</P>
<P>
   The Polaroid snapshots of those who have been hired to wear the
Hooters colors are displayed in the trailer. Let's put it this way.
The ones I looked at all had nice teeth.
</P>
<P>
   What they ought to do is call this Round Rock Hooters Cyber
Hooters. I say this because it'll be right across I-35 from the
enormous Dell Computer campus, which employs about 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Dell has the campus, and thanks to Hooters it's about to get the
cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   Don't you just know that at lunch great numbers of that prolific
high-tech species Floppius discerooni will make the trip across the
road to check out the, uh, chicken wings at Hooters?
</P>
<P>
   If the Round Rock Hooters has any snap, Friday nights will be
Geek Night, with wings half off.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
