<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDLIFE-JOURNEY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sunny days in the Yukon (even at 3 a.m.!)
 &HT;    (EDS: This is Installment 15 in a series of columns by Ron
Wiggins, ``Midlife journey to Mount McKinley.'' If you are
interested in previous columns, please call CoxNet at
404-526-5456.)
 &HT;    By Ron Wiggins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There are strange things done under the midnight sun by the
men who moil for gold . . .'' _ from ``The Cremation of Sam McGee''
by Robert Service.
</P>
<P>
   DAWSON CITY, YUKON TERRITORY _ They weren't kidding about this
midnight sun business. An hour before midnight, the sun hangs just
above the mountain, flooding my camper, and if I'm to get any
sleep, I may have to climb the mountain with a bat and beat the sun
beneath the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 a.m. the sun subsides just low enough to provide some
darkness and with it, blessed sleep. And the next morning, when the
sun blazes out of a cloudless horizon, warming my face, I bound out
of bed and see by my watch that it is 3:17 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   There are no roosters in the Yukon. They are all in therapy.
</P>
<P>
   After more ``rest'' I drive into this legendary gold rush town
of 2,500 to find out what kind of people thrive in 50-below zero
winters punctuated by 10 weeks of ceiling-staring insomnia. The
town itself consists of old houses and stores set in a tight grid
on the banks of the mighty Yukon River.
</P>
<P>
   The roads are graveled and oiled to hold down dust, and if this
is meant to be quaint or faithful to its boomtown past, the effect
is more shabby than nostalgic. But if there is madness here, it
begins with neglected buildings that lean dangerously toward their
upright neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the permafrost,'' explains Guy Chan, 35, owner of Dawson
Donuts. ``Five or six feet down the ground is permanently frozen.
When the ground above thaws, the buildings tilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Frame houses and businesses are elevated on blocks so that they
do not melt the ground before spring and sink into a bog of their
own making. When spring comes, the ground under the house thaws
unevenly and tilting results.
</P>
<P>
   You know an adjustment is needed when a meatball falls off the
table and rolls to the wall. Then you get out the shims and the
sledgehammer and true up the house the way you stick a matchbook
under a table leg.
</P>
<P>
   The graveled roads, according to Chan, are another concession to
permafrost sag. No use repaving every spring when there are
mountains of gold mine tailings for the gravel. Where else are
roads impregnated with gold and the hope of finding an overlooked
nugget on the streets?
</P>
<P>
   There is gold still being taken out of the river, but it wasn't
the lure of gold that brought the native of Vancouver within a
three-day mush of the Arctic Circle. It was an assistant chef's
job. He stayed as he grew to love the town. And ``the girl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim,'' he smiled. ``She works at the refinery. She's the one
who pours the gold into bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan came to know Kim from the hotel where both worked. ``One
day she's all dolled up and looking really hot, and I ask her where
she's going and she says to break up with her boyfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   She did, and they started dating and bought the doughnut shop
and the Victorian house next door and to this day, Chan still
doesn't get it. ``Why get all dolled up to break up with somebody?
It doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it has something to do with the Northern Lights or the
warped diurnal cycle or Dawson City's undisputed bipolarism: The
town is by the pole and it's still deciding whether it's a tourist
town or a gold town.
</P>
<P>
   Bona fide miners and bonanza seekers comb the stream beds for
gold even as hundreds of thousands of vacationers throng the town
to drink at Diamond Tooth Gerties, attend the Robert Service
Theater and even try their hand at gold-panning. All Chan asks is
that the nostalgia revelers stop by for a doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was new here,'' Chan said, ``I assumed that the gold
was played out and that these miners were dreaming. I said that a
couple of times in bars, and suddenly it got real quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   Are there people getting rich in the creeks? Chan shrugs. ``Some
of these guys work their claims when it thaws, and in October, a
lot of them go to South America and Mexico. Somebody's finding
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Most newcomers to Dawson City, Chan says, are like himself,
young and entrepreneurial. ``We know a half dozen people our age
who had babies last year.'' He and Kim intend to rear a family.
``Cuba will be opening up soon. Maybe we'll go there when we
retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chan says, in Dawson City not much goes on that
doesn't get repeated at Dawson Donuts. Winters are cold, he
concedes, but not as brutal as Toronto winters with the wind
blowing off the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   And to prove his point, he told me about a prospector named
Cory, who lives year around in a 12-by-12-foot tent heated by a
wood stove. ``When it's too cold to prospect, he works in town as a
machinist.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can survive a Klondike winter in a tent, I say flatly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the old pictures of Dawson City in winter,'' Chan
replies. ``Nothing but tents.''
</P>
<P>
   As I board the ferry to cross the Yukon River and connect with
the Top of the World Highway to Alaska, I am sorry I didn't get to
meet the man who winters the Klondike in a tent, but I am sorrier
that I didn't get to meet Kim and ask her if this is a normal thing
for women to get all dolled up to break up with somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Shouldn't she let her hair go for a few days, throw on her
rattiest bathrobe and smudge a little soot under her eyes? This
continues to trouble me as I drive north and the days become longer
and the nights shorter.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT: Alaska's bounty: salmon-studded rivers, virgin forests,
the pristine droppings of a bull moose.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Wiggins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
