<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen finds fortune in the stars
 &HT;    By Emily J. Minor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Folks, we've been outsmarted by a
12-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually, he's 16 and he'll be 17 soon. He's taking
driver's ed and he's looking for a girlfriend, if anyone's
interested.
</P>
<P>
   But Kalman Gabriel used to be 12. And when he was, he started
this little project that has since landed him an agent, a book and
a 1998 Youth News Writers award.
</P>
<P>
   Kalman liked to collect autographs, mostly from sports figures.
But it got to be too expensive. So, the handsome kid with the
little sister and the mom and dad who are both accountants started
a project.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote to people, famous people, and asked them a simple
question:
</P>
<P>
   Dear So and So,
</P>
<P>
   I am a 12-year-old boy from Oyster Bay, New York. If you could
give me advice for life, what would it be?
</P>
<P>
   Sincerely,
</P>
<P>
   Kalman Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   And for the next three years, young Kalman kept his mailman on
Long Island very, very busy.
</P>
<P>
   His first response, and, thus, still his favorite today, was
from actor Alec Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   July 18, 1994
</P>
<P>
   Dear Kalman
</P>
<P>
   1). Show thanks and pray to God every day.
</P>
<P>
   2). Live a vegetarian lifestyle. (No beef, no pork, no poultry.)
</P>
<P>
   3). Work hard in school.
</P>
<P>
   4). Honor your mother and father.
</P>
<P>
   With all best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Alec.
</P>
<P>
   His weirdest letter? The one from Sydney Biddle Barrows, the
Mayflower Madam. She told him to practice safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was kind of a weird thing to tell a
12-year-old,'' Kalman says.
</P>
<P>
   Regis Philbin: Obey the commandments.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Cash: Look to the light.
</P>
<P>
   Art Garfunkel: Always try to show up.
</P>
<P>
   George Carlin: Question everything you are told by governments,
corporations and religions. Question and resist!
</P>
<P>
   As time went on and the project grew, Kalman switched from
handwritten notes to letters printed on the computer. He turned 13,
then 14, then 15. His cursive signature got a little more fancy.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, Kalman ran out of names. There are only so many
people like Michael Jordan and Mother Teresa. That's when Kalman,
with the help of his dad, started writing to people he'd never
heard of before in his life. Nobel laureates. Scientists. College
presidents. Politicians. He's heard from more than 300 in all.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kemp: Never give in!
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan: Don't go along with the crowd. Be your own man.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Polanski: Read a lot. Good books inspire.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Turner: LEAD, FOLLOW OR GET OUT OF THE WAY!
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, it probably cost a lot because of all the stamps
and everything,'' he says. That's when he found himself an agent
and got himself a deal for a book (Dear Kalman, William Morrow and
Co., Inc., $14).
</P>
<P>
   Some people wrote several pages. Some people wrote a few words.
A lot of people told Kalman to do well in school, love his parents
and be nice to other people.
</P>
<P>
   And some people were too stuck on themselves to write back.
People such as Michael Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Mr. Gabriel, wrote Eisner's assistant, Thomas J. Deegan.
</P>
<P>
   As you may expect, Michael's Disney duties fully occupy his
schedule. He simply has no free time to pursue the dozens of
requests he receives every week, especially those requiring his
personal attention such as expressions of opinion, ``words of
wisdom,'' or personal advice.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like a certain gazillionaire could use some advice. Advice
like, Hey Michael: Lighten up. Make time for kids like Kalman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
