<P>
   COXNET FOOD BETTER BURGERS _ Summer's here and the lazy months
ahead are sure to afford many opportunities for showing off your
grilling finesse, so why not start with the basics: burgers.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes three color
photos of three sandwiches: Turkey Burger filled with Brie,
Open-Faced Seared Tuna Burger with Wasabi Mayonnaise and
Greek-Style Hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GRILLING TIPS: How to enhance your grilling experience.
(Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color
photo of hamburger resting on a spatula.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES _ Turkey Burger filled with Brie, Open-Faced
Seared Tuna Burger with Wasabi Mayonnaise and Greek-Style
Hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE _ Finding free stuff on the Internet can be a
fun and very rewarding experience. (Parham, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) With recipe; Stuffed Artichokes.
</P>
<P>
   DIET-COLUMN _ In February 1997, my 5-foot-4 wife had ballooned
to 185 pounds. If there was a diet she didn't try, it was only
because it wasn't printed in English. Packaged stuff from a
strip-mall weight-loss place. Weight Watchers. Starvation.
Everything in between. Nothing worked long-term. In February 1998,
Margaret, who hates to cook, settled on a low-fat diet and our
kitchen became a fat-free zone. She also ran 3 or 4 miles a day and
played for an indoor soccer team. She began to see results. And
then the fighting began. (Lomartire, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FANNIEFARMER _ Marion Cunningham, the author of the Fannie
Farmer cookbooks, is one of the country's most respected food
authorities. She's not a bit ashamed to tell you she'd rather have
an iceberg lettuce salad than trendy micro-greens any day. In her
latest book, ``Learning to Cook with Marion Cunningham'', she
revels in the simplicity of plain but well-made fare _ and shares
secrets for getting the most from them. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH COLOR PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-FANNIEFARMER-RECIPES _ Recipe page to go with Fannie Farmer
story centerpieced on AJC weekly food section. (Kessler, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-RECIPESWAP _ A weekly recipe exchange column. This week:
``Special Icing''. (Langhenry, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-SKUBE-BEERCOLUMN _ Michael Skube's beercolumn is not
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-CYBERSPICE _ A weekly column looking at the plethora of
recipes on the Internet. (Parham, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NEWLYWEDS _ Food and kitchen advice from those married a
year or so for those tying the knot this summer. (Crider, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WINE-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ What's the hardest thing you've
ever had to do? Wayne Flynn can answer that question. ``The hardest
thing I've ever had to do was to price the first bottle of wine
that I produced,'' said the proprietor of Flynn Winery in Oregon.
The bottle was a 1984 pinot noir. ``I decided to be as close to
under $10 as I could be.'' The wine came out at $9.95. That was
nearly 15 years ago. You know what has happened to wine prices in
the past decade and a half. They've risen faster than a Champagne
cork exits a warm, shaken bottle. Kapow. Through the roof. Flynn
produces two pinot noirs now. So what do you suppose they cost? Um,
$8.99 and $12.99. (The $12.99 wine is the one that used to cost
$9.95, by the way.) And the wines are delicious. (Fisher, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
