 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 2)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Years ago, I read that Jacqueline Kennedy put something into
President Kennedy's casket before he was buried. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Arlington National Cemetery reports that the president's
widow, and his brother, Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy, placed
several items in the casket. They included three letters, a pair of
gold cuff links, a piece of scrimshaw engraved with the
presidential seal, a silver rosary, and a PT-109 tie clasp.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can you tell us about White Oak Plantation in Florida,
where the Clintons spent their recent short vacation?
</P>
<P>
   A: The plantation, a 7,500-acre spread on the St. Mary's River
dividing Florida and Georgia, and about 20 miles north of
Jacksonville, isn't your average resort. For starters, it isn't
open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   White Oak was established in 1938 as a family residence by
Charles Gilman. His son, Howard Gilman, who died last year at age
73, developed the plantation as a corporate meeting place. The son
was chairman and CEO of Gilman Paper Co. in St. Mary's, Ga., the
largest privately held paper and building products company in the
United States. The plantation, accessible by an unmarked dirt road,
has a swimming pool, nine-hole golf course, political research
center and a studio for dancers and other artists. Guests have
included Al Gore, Colin Powell, Mikhail Baryshnikov, John F.
Kennedy Jr., Julia Roberts and Jessica Lange. The Clintons are
guests of the Howard Gilman Foundation, which lets groups and
individuals use its facilities for free.
</P>
<P>
   The grounds are home to about 400 animals, such as giraffes,
cheetahs, black rhinos and white rhinos, and Big Guy, an endangered
Florida panther injured by a car. They're under the care of more
than 40 zoologists at the White Oak Conservation Center,
established in 1982 by Howard Gilman to breed and preserve
wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   White Oak has 14 houses, including log cabins, lodges and modern
stucco dwellings. The Clintons stayed at Roseland, a two-story,
five-bedroom cedar-paneled house.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In all the articles I've read about the Vietnam Veterans
Memorial in Washington, I've never seen whether new names can be
added. Is it possible? If so, who can I contact to see about adding
someone's name?
</P>
<P>
   A: The names on the Wall _ numbering more than 58,200 _ were
obtained initially by the Defense Department, which compiled a list
of combat zone casualties according to an executive order handed
down by President Johnson on April 24, 1965. The Vietnam Veterans
Memorial Fund says it continues to receive numerous requests each
year from people who want to have names placed on the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   While the fund finances the addition of names to the Wall, it
says the decision on determining which names are inscribed is made
by the Defense Department. Only those people who died of a combat
injury suffered in Vietnam can be added. For more information on
the parameters involved in the consideration of adding a name,
contact the relevant service branch: Army, 703-325-5304; Air Force,
1-800-531-5501; Marine Corps, 703-696-1177; and Navy, 703-687-3979.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement addressing the question of adding names, the fund
adds that the memorial ``stands to honor all who served in Vietnam,
not just those whose individual names it bears.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any information about a lawsuit involving Gerber
baby food? I received an e-mail saying that children born between
1986 and 1997 would be issued a $500 savings bond if the parent
writes to a settlement office in Minneapolis .
</P>
<P>
   A: This story, which makes the rounds from time to time, is
``completely inaccurate and false,'' says Gerber Products Co. This
misinformation appears to have started circulating after a 1996
settlement involving infant formula and pricing issues, but Gerber
wasn't connected with that litigation. In any case, Gerber says,
the deadline for filing claims in that settlement expired Jan. 31,
1997. The company also says a Minneapolis post office box linked to
Gerber for the processing of claims has been closed by Minneapolis
postal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate that consumers are being misled by this
information,'' Gerber says in a statement posted on its Web site.
``Consumers are cautioned not to send birth records or other
information in conenction with this rumor.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do I write to Vice President Al Gore, and how should I
address him?
</P>
<P>
   A: A spokeswoman in Gore's press office said most people who
write him use the title The Honorable Al Gore, Vice President of
the United States, followed by this address: The White House, 1600
Pennsylvania Ave., Washington, DC 20500.
</P>
<P>
   If you're online, call up the White House Web site _
www.whitehouse.gov _ and click on The President &AMP; Vice President
and follow the steps. You'll be able to leave a message with a
maximum of 10,000 characters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After seeing a TV series about Gen. Douglas MacArthur, I'm
reminded of his widow, Jean. Is she still living? What about their
son, Arthur?
</P>
<P>
   A: Jean Faircloth MacArthur, who turned 100 last Dec. 28, lives
quietly at her home in New York's Waldorf-Astoria, where she has
been a resident since 1951. She has shunned the limelight for
years, never appearing on talk shows and rarely turning up in
celebrity columns, said Col. Bill Davis of the MacArthur Library
Archives and Memorial in Norfolk, Va. Davis said she's in good
health, but other than that he chose not to describe her
activities, saying only that she is ``very much'' a private person.
</P>
<P>
   One of Jean MacArthur's few public forays came in 1990 when,
accompanied by her friend Barbara Bush, she cut a ribbon to open a
research center at the Norfolk facility named for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur MacArthur lives in New York, Davis said, but he declined
to provide any details. It has been reported variously that the son
was either a music arranger, a Wall Street businessman or ballet
dancer, but there never has been any confirmation. Since his
father's death in 1964, he has chosen to stay out of public view.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas MacArthur is entombed at the Norfolk museum, which is
part of the library and archives. When his widow dies, she will be
entombed with him.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about the lightning tracking system used by some
television weather reporters. Can you explain how it works?
</P>
<P>
   A: Meteorologist Glenn Burns of WSB in Atlanta likens the
technology to what happens when you're listening to AM radio and
hear a static discharge from a distant thunderstorm. A network of
sensors detects the presence of positive and negative lightning
strokes, Burns said, and enables TV stations to show their location
on display maps ``in real time'' almost instantly as they occur.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The newspaper has reported frequently about the new quarters
honoring the 50 states. What about the District of Columbia?
</P>
<P>
   A: The authorizing law calls for quarters to honor only the 50
states, according to the Treasury Department, so the District of
Columbia is out of the question, at least for now. But there's a
provision in the law regarding the possibility of additional
honorees. A bill introduced in Congress by Del. Eleanor Holmes
Norton (D-D.C.) seeks to extend the program to include the District
of Columbia, American Samoa, Guam, Puerto Rico and the Virgin
Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that Los Angeles police and the FBI are
closing in on two fugitives from the 1970s, Kathleen Soliah, former
associate of Patty Hearst and her Symbionese Liberation Army
colleagues, and James Kilgore, suspected member of the New World
Liberation Front, which was blamed for various bombings in
California in the mid-1970s. Is there no statute of limitations
involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no statute of limitations because the charges involve
a capital offense, said FBI spokeswoman Celestine Armstead.
</P>
<P>
   The Symbionese Liberation Army was a group of ex-convicts and
radical college students that claimed responsibility for the
assassination of Marcus Foster, superintendent of schools in
Oakland, Calif. The SLA kidnapped Hearst from her Berkeley
apartment in 1974 and demanded, among other things, that her
father, Randolph Hearst, then president and editor of the San
Francisco Examiner, feed the poor for her release. Patty Heast
joined the radical group during the next 18 months, and she was
videotaped holding a gun during an April 1974 bank robbery in San
Francisco. Hearst eventually told authorities, and wrote in her
book, ``Every Secret Thing,'' that Kilgore and Soliah had
participated in another SLA bank robbery a year later in
Carmichael, Calif., in which a woman customer was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard on the radio that Earl Spencer, Princess Diana's
brother, bought the original sheet music to ``Candle in the Wind.''
What will he do with it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Spencer paid about $40,500 at an auction in London last week
for the original manuscript for the tribute song, which became the
biggest-selling single of all time after Elton John _ now Sir Elton
John _ performed it at Westminster Abbey during Diana's funeral in
September 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer plans to display the manuscript, which was signed by
John and Beatles producer Sir George Martin, at a museum devoted to
Diana's life which Spencer has created at Althorp, the family's
ancestral home. ``It will be on display this year, and we are very
happy to have it,'' said Shelley-Anne Claircourt, Spencer's
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the auction, which was held at Sotheby's in London,
will be donated to music-related charities, according to the
auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is this mysterious pin money given to Hillary Rodham
Clinton, which I'm told she has reported on her income tax return?
</P>
<P>
   A: No mystery. You're referring to the Henry G. Freeman Jr. Pin
Money Fund, which isn't new to Clinton. It was established in
Freeman's 1912 will for whoever, at a given time, is the spouse of
the president. The income tax return of the Clintons included
$12,000 from the pin money fund. As she has done in past years, the
first lady said she will contribute this income to charitable
entities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A told us about Hillary Rodham Clinton's pin money. I've
always been curious: Where does that expression come from?
</P>
<P>
   A: It goes way back, as the Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase
Origins explains. Metal pins, invented perhaps as early as the 14th
century and later manufactured in England by a monopoly under
grants from the crown, were so costly and scarce at first that
there was a law forbidding their sale except on the first two days
of January each year. About that time of year, husbands customarily
gave their wives money to buy all the pins they would need for the
months ahead _ hence, pin money. When pins became less expensive,
the expression still was used for this annual stipend. It came to
mean a personal allowance given to a wife, generally, by her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   End take 2 of 2.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
