<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A taste of wine: Producer a breath of fresh air in outrageous
pricing world
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Quick, what's the hardest thing you've ever had
to do? Ever?
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Flynn can answer that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing I've ever had to do was to price the first
bottle of wine that I produced,'' said the proprietor of Flynn
Winery in Oregon. The bottle was a 1984 pinot noir. ``I decided to
be as close to under $10 as I could be.'' The wine came out at
$9.95.
</P>
<P>
   That was nearly 15 years ago. You know what has happened to wine
prices in the past decade and a half. They've risen faster than a
Champagne cork exits a warm, shaken bottle. Kapow. Through the
roof.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn produces two pinot noirs now. So what do you suppose they
cost?
</P>
<P>
   Um, $8.99 and $12.99. (The $12.99 wine is the one that used to
cost $9.95, by the way.)
</P>
<P>
   And the wines are delicious. They could easily fetch more, if
Flynn was so inclined. He's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate raising prices,'' he said, shrugging. ``I don't mind
being known as a producer of less expensive wines.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, my. Can we speed up that human cloning technology, please?
</P>
<P>
   Flynn is a breath of fresh air in a wine price world run amok.
And his down-to-earth sensibilities extend beyond pricing. He's one
of the few winemakers who will casually admit to using oak chips _
a quick shortcut to obtaining the flavors and aromas of oak-barrel
aging _ in his wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been honest so far, and it's served me well. No sense in
changing now,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Some other winemakers, especially in Flynn's price category,
would have you believe each of their bottles picks up that toasty,
vanilla-like note from the hand-crafted new-oak barrels they've
lined up in the cellar. It just doesn't seem as romantic to picture
a cellar worker tossing chunks of wood into a steel tank filled
with wine. But it's a touch of technology that Flynn doesn't mind
acknowledging using for his under-$10 ``Clos d'Or'' pinot noir and
chardonnay. Besides, those new French oak barrels are nastily
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Flynn uses 15 pounds of toasted oak chips per 1,000 gallons, in
case you're wondering. ``Not to give oak flavors, but to soften the
wines a bit and bring out the fruit . . . I want to drink my wines,
not chew them.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn produces a solid lineup of wines. They're worth seeking
out for their value, and heck, for the refreshing integrity of the
guy who's making them.
</P>
<P>
   The wines:
</P>
<P>
   _ Flynn Cellar Select 1997 Oregon Pinot Noir ``Clos d'Or,''
$8.99: Fruity, delicate, just a bit smoky. Pinot doesn't get any
better than this for the price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flynn 1996 Estate Bottled Pinot Noir, Willamette Valley,
$12.99: This wine has been aged 12 months in oak barrels and has a
bit more richness and a vanilla note that the less expensive pinot
doesn't have.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flynn 1997 Pinot Noir Blanc, $7.99: This salmon-pink wine
makes a delicious alternative to white zinfandel. Great
concentration of fruit flavors balanced by just the right amount of
acidity.
</P>
<P>
   _ Flynn Cellar Select 1997 Chardonnay ``Clos d'Or,'' $8.99:
Fruity, straightforward, great summertime white.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
