<HEADER>
A9612 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIET-COLUMN03-COX     06-02 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIET-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How I lost 60 pounds and finally won a fight with my wife
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Fighting over food _ low fat vs. low
carb _ got real ugly at my house.
</P>
<P>
   And it all started with a photo.
</P>
<P>
   In almost 30 years together, Margaret has rarely seen me as
stunned as the day that photo arrived in the mail from my pal Greg
in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   It was taken two months earlier, at an NBA Trailblazers game.
Greg had gotten my son, Nick, and I courtside seats _ and that
high-profile placement came with a price.
</P>
<P>
   During the game, there I was _ 5-feet, 7-inches, 246 pounds _ on
the arena's aptly named JumboTron scoreboard. A big gut, no neck,
poured into the seat.
</P>
<P>
   From a skybox, Greg snapped the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret leaned over to take a look. ``Wha'd you expect? You're
a fat pig.''
</P>
<P>
   To say Margaret, the oldest of 11 kids, was raised with wolves
is not a gross exaggeration. She favors a quick-strike, bludgeon
offense.
</P>
<P>
   This time she was right.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret didn't grow up fat and wasn't going to settle for XL in
middle age.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, my 5-foot-4 wife had ballooned to 185 pounds.
If there was a diet she didn't try, it was only because it wasn't
printed in English. Packaged stuff from a strip-mall weight-loss
place. Weight Watchers. Starvation. Everything in between.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked long-term.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, Margaret, who hates to cook, settled on a
low-fat diet and our kitchen became a fat-free zone. She also ran 3
or 4 miles a day and played for an indoor soccer team. She began to
see results.
</P>
<P>
   And then the fighting began.
</P>
<P>
   We live in Tampa, but I'm in West Palm Beach four days a week.
When I came home on weekends, the food wars started.
</P>
<P>
   I'd buy orange juice, and she'd go into a frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing but sugar!'' she'd yell. (She was right. There's
more sugar in OJ than Coke.)
</P>
<P>
   I'd bring home a couple of doughnuts and you'd think it was
crack cocaine. We couldn't eat in restaurants. She searched any bag
I brought home as though she worked for U.S. Customs and I was
arriving from Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't about my health. Margaret doesn't worry about when I
drop dead but where I drop dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' she often says, ``the paper's life insurance pays
double if you die working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do my best.''
</P>
<P>
   No, food fights were about our 12-year-old son. Nick doesn't
have a weight problem. Yet, says Margaret. ``If you think for one
minute that I'm going to let him eat like you ... ''
</P>
<P>
   You've got no shot when Margaret begins any argument with ``If
you think for one minute.'' You can actually feel the little army
men in your brain dropping their weapons and beating a fast
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   A prisoner of war, I joined her fat-free march when my Portland
photo arrived in March '98. With low fat, I was miserable. Always
hungry. I lost and gained. I finally gave up after five months.
</P>
<P>
   Motorized Margaret stuck with it.
</P>
<P>
   Then low carb called to me.
</P>
<P>
   I listened to an audiobook of The Zone diet. I read more. I
understood the first two chapters of Protein Power. I couldn't stay
at 30 grams of carbs a day, so I invented my own diet, 50 to 75
grams of carbs daily, balanced with fat and protein.
</P>
<P>
   I quit eating bagels, fried food, pasta and all the obvious
sugar snacks. I ran/walked 2 miles, five days a week. I drank eight
glasses of water daily.
</P>
<P>
   In West Palm Beach, I don't cook, I eat at Howley's. I found low
carb to be restaurant friendly. I'd have a large Greek or Julienne
salad. Tuna sandwich. Chicken breasts. I had bacon, eggs, butter,
olives, cheese, nuts. At night I might have an apple or half of a
cantaloupe with Cool Whip.
</P>
<P>
   I bought low-carb. She bought low-fat.
</P>
<P>
   As I lost weight, it drove Margaret crazy. She couldn't get
enough low-fat microwave dinners, pasta, rice, bagels, cereal. The
fight was on. I'd ambush her worthless low-fat diet at night when
she'd be waiting for her usual bag of microwave popcorn or bowl of
low-fat ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Nick would wander into the kitchen. ``Can I have some ice
cream?''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret would say yes, it was low-fat.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say no, the fat was replaced by sugar that makes you
hungrier.
</P>
<P>
   She spent more than a year on low fat, lost 55 pounds and
stalled 10 pounds short of her goal.
</P>
<P>
   I spent six months on low carb and lost 60 pounds _ to within 10
pounds of what I weighed in high school 30 years ago. And I felt
better.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a truce arrived two weeks ago. Just in time. Margaret
was locked into low fat and taking some goofy appetite suppressant
pills she got from another soccer mom.
</P>
<P>
   I gave her Suzanne Somers' new diet book and told her to read
Dr. Diana Schwarzbein's foreward that explained low carb as clearly
as I'd seen it. Then I got her the clearly explained The
Schwarzbein Principle to read.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret read the nine low-fat side effects _ from cravings to
insomnia _ and admitted, ``I had them all.''
</P>
<P>
   She did low carb for a week and pronounced it a winner. Gone
were her cravings. She had more energy. ``I feel like a speed
freak!'' (For those of us from the late '60s, this is a good
feeling.)
</P>
<P>
   Nick wandered into the kitchen the other Saturday morning. He
smelled something foreign, something good. Margaret was microwaving
bacon to go with his scrambled eggs, a piece of peanut butter toast
and milk.
</P>
<P>
   His low-carb mother and father smiled as he devoured his
breakfast. He didn't ask for orange juice. Smart boy.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
