<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9613 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOONDOCKS03-COX     06-02 1343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOONDOCKS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boon or bane? A new comic courts controversy in its portrayal of
black life
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Cartoonist Aaron McGruder has discovered that there
are some things that some people don't want to joke about, here at
the far end of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Racial prejudice is one of them. Also plastic ``Star Wars''
light sabers.
</P>
<P>
   As far as race is concerned, McGruder knew that his strip ``The
Boondocks,'' featuring cub black nationalist Huey P. Freeman and
his gangsta-wannabe little brother, Riley, would ruffle some
feathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a small miracle that this strip ever saw the light of
day,'' says McGruder, 24, speaking from his ``office,'' which also
happens to be in his bedroom at his parents' house in suburban
Columbia, Md.
</P>
<P>
   That's because McGruder makes punch lines out of, well, touchy
subjects. He pokes fun at white people who get nervous seeing a
black face in the neighborhood. And he pokes fun at black people
who consider straight hair to be ``good hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Huey and Riley are two Chicago boys who have just moved to the
suburbs _ i.e., ``The Boondocks'' _ and become strangers in a
strange hood. In one leafy, bucolic panel, Riley complains to Huey,
``We've been walking for 10 minutes and haven't passed one subway
stop, ball court, Chinese carryout place or rib shack!'' Replies
Huey, ``Riley, we are pilgrims in an unholy land.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor Riley must practice his ``thug mug'' because, though he
wants to be bad, he's ``cursed with cuteness.'' And Huey's attempts
to raise his grandfather's Afrocentric consciousness generally
prompt an offer to whoop his behind.
</P>
<P>
   Marketed as a strip to appeal to the ``hip-hop generation,''
McGruder's dramatic, anime-influenced artwork and his puckish
sensibility have gone over big nationally. Universal Press
Syndicate reports that since its debut April 19 the strip has been
picked up by 180 newspapers, including the daily Constitution and
the weekend Journal-Constitution. It's one of the biggest launches
of any syndicated comic strip.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly equals the launches of `Calvin and Hobbes' and
`For Better or for Worse,''' said Lee Salem, Universal's editorial
director.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike those strips, ``The Boondocks'' has also raised some
tempers. Newspapers around the country have received scores of
complaints, along with a smattering of positive notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are going to give the author of `Boondocks' space to
spew race hatred, I think you should offer David Dukes equal room
to express his views on the subject,'' Dunwoody resident Walter
Mitchell wrote to the AJC.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted by telephone, Mitchell, 70, says that the strip has
``toned down a little bit'' since the episode that annoyed him. In
that sequence Riley is called ``cute'' by an elderly woman and
rails that he won't become her ``house negro.'' (The lady, hard of
hearing, misses the little tyke's tirade.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got enough trouble without stirring things up like
that,'' says Mitchell, who is the former publisher of Southern
Accents magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Salem expected some white readers to be put off by the strip,
but some African-Americans have also failed to find it amusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society already makes us look stupid anyway; why can't we have
a comic strip that is positive?'' says Travia Jones, 29, a resident
of Duluth. Jones was perplexed by a strip that showed a biracial
character, Jazmine, denying that she has an Afro, while her black
father ponders whether lye will straighten out his daughter's hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my job to make black people look good,'' says the
self-possessed McGruder. If processed hair is silly, he says, then
he should make fun of it. ``In 1999 I still have people coming up
to me, black people, saying 'Oh you've got good hair.' The hair
thing has never gone away.''
</P>
<P>
   McGruder owes his ``good hair'' to his part-Indian heritage.
Otherwise, his background is not unlike Huey's. McGruder was born
in Chicago, but was moved shortly thereafter to suburbs in
Illinois, Kentucky and Maryland. ``Virtually all my life I've been
the only black face in class,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That could also describe his presence on the comics page. By
some estimates there are only a half-dozen syndicated black comic
strips. McGruder failed repeatedly to break into that small circle
until he attended a panel discussion at a 1997 meeting of the
National Association of Black Journalists, and passed his panels to
Harriet Choice of Universal Press.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the small world of black strips, opinion on McGruder's
work is divided. Barbara Brandon-Croft, who draws the weekly
feature ``Where I'm Coming From,'' which appears Mondays in the
AJC, says: ``I applaud Aaron. We haven't been able to talk about
things like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandon-Croft, 40, adds that the stodgy world of the funny
papers needs shaking up. ``You can't please everybody, and if you
did please everybody, you'd be 'Family Circus.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Ray Billingsley, author of ``Curtis,'' which runs in the
daily Journal and the weekend Journal-Constitution, suggests that
McGruder should be ``careful.'' The role of the comics is to
entertain, he maintains, not to provide political or social
commentary. ``We want the situation to get better,'' says
Billingsley, 41, ``we don't want to dwell on it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGruder's answer is characteristically blunt. ``That's a
crock,'' he says. ``Doonesbury'' and ``Bloom County'' regularly
skewered sacred cows, says McGruder, which is what he intends to do
as well. He ascribes some of the uneasiness surrounding ``The
Boondocks'' to an American double-standard. Compare his strip to
``Calvin and Hobbes,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all love Calvin, but he was a cynical, obnoxious little
kid. And not only that but extremely violent,'' says McGruder.
Indeed, Calvin fantasized about destroying his elementary school
with air-to-ground missiles. ``But when somebody like Riley looks
at somebody sideways, he's a menace.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: This week's sequence has Riley disappointed
with a plastic lightsaber because it won't actually chop any of his
enemies in half. He demonstrates the toy's ineffectiveness by
whacking two fellow characters.
</P>
<P>
   In this post-Columbine era some editors were skittish about
running the strip. ``We winced when we saw that one episode,'' says
Diane Bacha of the Milwaukee Journal Sentinel.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee paper will run the strip and continue carrying
``Boondocks,'' but at least one paper, the Aiken (S.C.) Standard,
has canceled it due to reader complaints.
</P>
<P>
   It's a plastic toy, for Pete's sake, says McGruder. ``I don't
see the connection between a kid going into a school armed to the
teeth, and a plastic lightsaber, which is obviously designed to
whack other kids with.''
</P>
<P>
   The strip will run in Thursday's Constitution, whose editors are
high on ``The Boondocks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that it has more edge than other things on the
comics page, but it particularly speaks to younger readers,'' says
Susan Soper, assistant managing editor/features.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the paper is moving the strip. Next week, ``The
Boondocks'' will shift from the comics page to the second page of
the Living section, where the newspaper also runs the similarly
topical ``Doonesbury.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McGruder's career is on fast-forward. The cartoonist
was featured in the Washington Post and the Chicago Tribune; the
Today Show plans a feature; he's chatted with filmmaker Reginald
Hudlin about TV and movie projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went into this unafraid because I had such low
expectations,'' he says. ``The irony is that at end of the day the
same reason why the strip sold to 160 papers will be the same
reason the strip may get canceled out of some of those papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taking a lot of people out of their comfort zones,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't care. You shouldn't have been there to begin
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
