A9649 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     06-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH BEGINS _ BUT IN HIS OWN FASHION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And now it begins.
</P>
<P>
   With the Texas Legislature officially adjourned, Gov. George W.
Bush can turn his attention to the business of running for
president. Although his candidacy is not yet official, the
possibility that Bush might decide against making the race is
virtually inconceivable.
</P>
<P>
   He has come too far to turn back. The bandwagon has gained too
much momentum to suddenly slam on the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can call his upcoming campaign trips ``exploratory'' until
the cows come home, but everybody knows what he's doing: He's
launching his campaign for the Republican Party's 2000 presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, he'll just say it and be done with it: ``I am a
candidate for president.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Bush is sticking to his plan, which is to
explore the viability of his presidential ambitions before making
them official.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to test the waters,'' Bush said Tuesday during an
Austin news conference that generated nationwide news coverage.
``I'm going to start traveling the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody wanted to know what he meant by the phrase ``test the
waters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you fully committed to a run for the presidency?'' Bush
was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fully committed to start traveling the country,'' Bush
replied.
</P>
<P>
   This was a typical Bush-media exchange. Reporters try to bait
him into saying something he doesn't want to say, into going
farther than he wants to go in committing himself to future actions
or positions on likely campaign issues.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, for example, a reporter wanted Bush to take a position
on a local issue in Iowa _ one of the early and crucial states in
the nominating process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't you wait until I get up there so I can make news up
there?'' Bush said, adding that he will ``have a strong statement
on that subject when I get up to Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's detractors often accuse him of being short-tempered, but
he never seems to lose his composure with reporters, no matter how
much they try to annoy him. He even has a little fun with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I don't want to do is preempt your
colleagues in Iowa,'' Bush told the reporter who sought his views
on that issue in the Hawkeye State.
</P>
<P>
   As he wrapped up the news conference, Bush managed to squeeze a
laugh out of his tormentors:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure you're gonna get tired of me, but I will never get
tired of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Bush's insistence on refusing to commit himself
before he's ready has been identified by his critics in the media
and elsewhere as a chink in his armor when in fact it is one of his
greatest strengths. By taking his time and making sure of the
direction he wants to go, Bush almost always avoids the unfortunate
process of backpedaling and ``clarifying'' that defines the public
pronouncements of so many politicians.
</P>
<P>
   After enduring nearly eight years of Bill Clinton's habitual
mind-changing, chronic about-facing and pathological
promise-breaking, the American people will be more than ready in
2000 for a presidential candidate who thinks things through before
staking out a position.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when candidates and officeholders react in knee-jerk
fashion to the slightest shift in the political winds _ when
politicians trip over themselves and each other trying to sprint to
the front of any parade that passes by _ voters will surely be
intrigued by a candidate who carefully considers the ramifications
of important issues before lining up on one side or the other.
</P>
<P>
   If it's waffling to spend some time contemplating an issue and
then taking a position you are comfortable with, well, we could use
more wafflers in public office.
</P>
<P>
   Such cautious consideration is not waffling, of course. Waffling
is what Clinton does: Impulsively jumping into the fray in the hope
of gaining some short-term political advantage and then
flip-flopping later on.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of time for Bush to articulate his positions on
the important issues of the 2000 campaign. And when he does, there
will be no doubt where he stands.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
