<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Thursday,
June 3. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   DWB: A Blue Springs, Mo., woman complains that her sons were the
subject of police harassment after being pulled over for
``suspicious behavior.'' She says what was suspicious was their
skin color _ black _ in a predominantly white neighborhood. Many
people call it ``driving while black,'' or DWB. It's a nationwide
controversy that has been the subject of university studies and
Supreme Court rulings. Mary Sanchez. 35. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   DEXEC (with DWB): Three of Kansas City's most respected
African-American executives tell their stories of being stopped for
DWB. Photos. Mary Sanchez. 20.
</P>
<P>
   DSTOP (graphic only, with DWB): ``The Law and You'' is a how-to
pamphlet aimed at law-abiding young minorities, advising them on
how to respond to traffic stops; it's produced by the NAACP,
Allstate Insurance and the National Organization of Black Law
Enforcement Executives.
</P>
<P>
   INDY: Harry Truman's hometown, Independence Mo., celebrates its
sesquicentennial June 4-6. We look at Independence's role in
shaping the region as the jumping off point for the Westward
pioneers and how some of that history is being revised. File art.
Brian Burnes. 30-35.
</P>
<P>
   INOW (with INDY): What's Independence today? An older city
fighting creeping budgets blight and meth houses? Yes, it's that.
But it's also a booming suburban area in the east, with more
upscale homes and a shopping district. The city is hoping to mine
the promise of the booming area to try to rehab the older part.
Map, photos. Trisha L. Howard. 25.
</P>
<P>
   CHASE: Tuesday night's lukewarm vote of confidence for interim
Superintendent Phyllis Chase revealed a racial divide may persist
on the Kansas City school board. What does that portend for the
selection of the new superintendent? And do the black board
members, in fact, not support Phyllis or are they taking a stand
because they think the white board members are trying to ram
something down their throats? Tanika White. 15.
</P>
<P>
   AIR: First day of the ``fuel summit'' begins Wednesday in KC
discussing reformulated gasoline, smog and other air pollution
issues. Michael Mansur. 15.
</P>
<P>
   CAB: A cab driver who had been a recent victim of a robbery
heard a suspicious call for another cabbie. He staked it out and
helped catch a man accused of robbing other cabbies. Christine
Vendel. 10.
</P>
<P>
   STAFFORD (business) _ Minority professionals are leaving their
organizations at rates two and three times higher than Caucasian
men and women. Sometimes they're leaving for more money, but mostly
they're leaving because organizations talk a diversity game but
don't play it. At Work column. By Diane Stafford.
</P>
