<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9724 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FANNIEFARMER-REC     06-02 2291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FANNIEFARMER-RECIPES03-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marion Cunningham shares recipes from her new book `Learning to
Cook with Marion Cunningham'
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some of Marion Cunningham's recipes are stylish and
contemporary, others homey and old fashioned. But all have her
imprint: simple, fresh ingredients combine in ways that make sense.
Even experienced cooks can learn some lessons from this book.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   The Best Oatmeal Cookies
</P>
<P>
   Makes 48 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: 10 minutes per batch
</P>
<P>
   What makes this oatmeal cookie the ``best,'' writes Cunningham,
is that it has ``all the virtues of a true oatmeal cookie without
the usual `klutzy' coarseness.''
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) butter, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups quick-cooking (1-minute) oats
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Place one oven rack in center of oven. Preheat oven to 350
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place softened butter in a large bowl. Add sugar. Using back of
a spoon, vigorously mash and scrape butter against sides and bottom
of bowl, gradually mixing into sugar until it becomes smooth and
pale yellow. (Can also be done with electric mixer.)
</P>
<P>
   Add flour, oats, baking soda, salt, nutmeg and vanilla extract
to bowl. Using hands (or a sturdy spoon or electric mixer), blend
dry ingredients into the butter by pressing and squeezing dough
between fingers until it becomes a solid mass with no loose flour
or oats in bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Grease 2 cookie sheets with butter or nonstick cooking spray.
Using a small spoon, scoop up 1 rounded teaspoon of dough and
gently roll it between palms of your hands to form a small ball.
Place dough ball on a corner of greased cookie sheet, about 1 inch
from sides. Form another ball of dough and put on cookie sheet
about 2 inches from first one. Continue until 2 sheets are filled,
with 12 evenly spaced balls of dough on each. Using palm of your
hand, press lightly on each to flatten into a 1/4-inch-thick round.
</P>
<P>
   Put one cookie sheet in oven at a time and bake 10 minutes, or
until edges are golden brown. If not ready after 10 minutes, bake
another 2 minutes and check again.
</P>
<P>
   Place second sheet in oven and repeat baking instructions. Place
cookie sheets on heatproof counter or stovetop and let cool about
10 minutes. Remove cookies with spatula to a flat surface.
</P>
<P>
   Grease cookie sheets again and continue to make cookies until
all dough is used.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 72 calories, 1 gram protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 51), 8 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 81 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Smothered Chicken With Mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those dishes that everyone seems to like,''
writes Cunningham. ``The flavors are captured in the simple sauce
that brings together the delicate chicken flavor and the earthy
mushrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken breast halves (with ribs and skin)
</P>
<P>
   2 medium yellow onions
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups chicken broth, canned or homemade, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch parsley
</P>
<P>
   4 slices bread
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse chicken pieces under cold running water and pat dry with
paper towels. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and chop onions. Set aside. Salt and pepper chicken to
taste. Put oil in large skillet and place over medium-high heat.
Hold your hand about an inch above the bottom of the pan; if it
feels hot, it's ready. Place chicken, skin side down, in hot oil.
Cook 1 to 2 minutes; spear a piece with a fork to check underside
for brownness. If not brown, cook another minute or 2. If brown,
turn over and cook on other side for another 2 minutes. When all
the pieces are browned, put them into a 2-quart casserole with lid.
Cover and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put onions in same skillet and saute until just brown, about 2
to 3 minutes. Put 1/2 cup chicken broth and flour in a jar with a
lid. Tighten the lid and shake jar vigorously for 1 minute, until
well-mixed and without flour lumps. Pour into skillet with heat
still at medium-high, continuing to stir for about 1 minute as the
sauce thickens. Slowly add remaining broth and constantly stir
around sides and bottom of skillet about 1 minute. Remove from
stove when smooth and thick-soup consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Pour sauce over chicken. Cover casserole, place in oven and bake
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As chicken cooks, wipe mushrooms clean with paper towel and cut
into quarters.
</P>
<P>
   When chicken has cooked 20 minutes, add mushrooms, cover, and
cook another 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   As chicken cooks, finely chop enough parsley to make 1/2 cup.
Just before chicken is done, toast bread and butter generously.
</P>
<P>
   Remove casserole from oven and add salt and pepper to taste, if
desired. Place a slice of toast on each plate and top with chicken,
mushrooms and sauce. Sprinkle each generously with parsley. Serve
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 546 calories, 48 grams protein, 27 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 26 grams carbohydrates, 121
milligrams cholesterol, 447 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Parsley Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: about 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here, Cunningham raises the stature of the most mundane of herbs
by transforming it into a palate-cleansing salad. ``Don't think of
this as a typical salad,'' she notes. ``It should be served in
portions of 1/2 to 3/4 cup per serving. Try it with steak, or James
Beard's Roasted Spareribs (see recipe) or add it to spaghetti.The
salad will keep refrigerated for about a week.''
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing:
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 bunches curly-leaf parsley (4 cups, chopped)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   To make dressing: Remove the papery skin from the garlic cloves.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using a food processor or blender, put the oil and
the peeled garlic cloves into the bowl of the processor and blend
until the garlic is smoothly incorporated into the oil. Add the
vinegar, salt and pepper and blend.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not using a food processor, crush garlic cloves by
setting them on a cutting board and smashing them under the
broadest flat surface of a large knife _ the part nearest the
handle. Sprinkle the salt over the smashed garlic and use the same
knife to chop the cloves finely. The garlic juices melt the salt
and help spread the garlic flavor through the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Using the flat side of your knife, scrape up the garlic-and-salt
mash and put it into a small jar with a lid. Add olive oil, vinegar
and pepper. Screw on lid and shake well.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare parsley: Rinse under cold water and shake off excess
water. Pat dry with paper towels or spin dry in salad spinner.
Remove stems and discard. Separate clusters of leaves to make
fluffy pile of green.
</P>
<P>
   Put parsley in a bowl, pour dressing over it and sprinkle on
Parmesan cheese. Using hands or large spoon, mix well so dressing
and cheese coat parsley evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 201 calories, 4 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 87), 4 grams carbohydrates, 5
milligrams cholesterol, 441 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Crushed Macaroni
</P>
<P>
   and Vegetables
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham isn't averse to odd ideas if they work. Crushing the
pasta, she writes, transforms it ``into a wonderful new texture,
and with the tomatoes and eggplant it becomes a complete meal in
one dish.''
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 cup small elbow macaroni
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh spinach (2 cups chopped)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 small eggplant
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 large cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 medium tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon salt, divided
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon pepper, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups canned stewed tomatoes, undrained
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Pour 2 teaspoons oil into an 8-by-8-by-2-inch baking dish and
smear around bottom and sides, using fingers or paper towel. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Put macaroni in plastic bag and seal. Using rolling pin or
glass, crush macaroni, rolling it back and forth until each piece
is crushed into small pieces but not a powder. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Wash spinach and chop into large pieces. Press firmly into
measuring cup, and measure about 2 cups. Set aside in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Wash parsley and pat dry. Remove and discard stems. Finely chop
leaves. Place in bowl with spinach and toss. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Slice about 1/4 inch off stem end of eggplant and discard.
Leaving skin on eggplant, cut crosswise into 1/4-inch rounds. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Place remaining olive oil and water into small lidded jar.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and finely chop garlic and add to jar. Cover and shake a
few seconds until well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Cut fresh tomatoes into 1/4-inch-thick slices and
place in single layer in bottom of prepared baking dish. Add 1/2
teaspoon each salt and pepper. Spread half of spinach-parsley
mixture over tomatoes. Sprinkle crushed macaroni evenly over
spinach and parsley. Add remaining 1/4 teaspoon salt and pepper,
then another layer of spinach and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Spread stewed tomatoes and liquid over spinach and parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Place eggplant slices over stewed tomatoes. Shake water-oil
mixture again until well-blended. Drizzle over top. Cover dish
snugly with foil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 1 hour. To test for doneness, bite into a piece of
macaroni. If not tender, cook another 10 minutes and test again.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from oven and let stand a few minutes, or until bubbling
subsides. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 266 calories, 6 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 30 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 597 milligrams sodium, 3 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   James Beard's
</P>
<P>
   Roasted
</P>
<P>
   Spareribs
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Beard used to teach this recipe in his classes. Cunningham
writes that you can really taste the pork; after all, ``Who needs
all that BBQ sauce?''
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds meaty pork spareribs
</P>
<P>
   Generous salt (up to 2 tablespoons) and freshly ground black
pepper (up to 1 tablespoon) to taste
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the ribs with salt and pepper on both sides. Set a roasting
or broiler rack in a roasting pan. Arrange ribs on the rack, meaty
side facing up. Put the pan on the center rack of the oven and bake
for 30 minutes. Using a pair of tongs, turn the ribs over and cook
for another 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   When the second 30 minutes are up, the ribs should be nicely
browned and fairly crisp on the outside. If not, roast for another
10 minutes and check again.
</P>
<P>
   When you are serving the ribs, cut the rack into separate racks
of 3 or 4 ribs per person and place on a platter or plates. Serve
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (8 ounces edible meat): 744 calories, 53 grams
protein, 57 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 69), trace
carbohydrates, 209 milligrams cholesterol, 710 milligrams sodium,
trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Marietta's Spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Roasting the tomatoes beforehand intensifies the flavor.
Cunningham says, ``This recipe is just the thing when you can't
find perfect fresh tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   12 Roma or plum tomatoes (about 1 3/4 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch parsley, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   4 quarts water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt (for cooking the pasta)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound (12 ounces) dried spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh basil ( 1/2 cup chopped)
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the tomatoes in half lengthwise, and place them _ cut side
up _ in a large, shallow baking dish. Salt and pepper them lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Peel and finely chop garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Wash the parsley and pat dry; remove and discard the stems.
Finely chop the leaves (you want about 1/2 cup).
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the garlic, half the parsley and 2 tablespoons of
the olive oil in a small bowl. Using a spoon or your fingers, pat
the garlic mixture on the tomatoes and drizzle on 2 more
tablespoons of the olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 45 minutes, uncovered. The tomatoes should be mushy; if
not, bake for another 10 minutes and test again.
</P>
<P>
   After the tomatoes have baked for 30 minutes, fill a 6-quart pot
about 2/3 full of water, stir in the 1 tablespoon salt and set over
high heat, covered. When the water reaches a full boil, add the
spaghetti and stir. After about 10 minutes, start testing pieces of
pasta every minute or so.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the water and the spaghetti into a colander set in the
sink. Let the pasta drain.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a small pot over medium heat. Chop the basil
leaves into small pieces. In a large serving bowl, mix together the
remaining parsley and olive oil, melted butter and basil. Add the
drained spaghetti and the baked tomatoes. Using two forks, lift
small batches of spaghetti until it is all coated with the
oil-butter mixture and the tomatoes are well-distributed. Serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 599 calories, 13 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 72 grams carbohydrates, 16
milligrams cholesterol, 86 milligrams sodium, 4 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
