<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9725 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FANNIEFARMER03-C     06-02 1384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FANNIEFARMER03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-James Beard aide and prime advocate of home cooking aims to
bring families back to the table
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Marion Cunningham is excited about lunch at Watershed
in Decatur (Ga.). She's already a fan of executive chef Scott
Peacock and has heard something about the reputed fame of owner
Emily Saliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't she one of the Spice Girls? No? An Indigo Girl?'' She
lets out a hearty laugh. ``Well, at my age you don't know all these
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's age is 77, and her field of expertise is American
home cooking, so it's easy to see why she's more comfortable
talking gingersnaps than Ginger Spice. Tall, charismatic and full
of energy despite a 4 a.m. wake-up call, this striking woman in hip
jewelry makes senior citizenship seem like nothing more than a few
wrinkles. And even her wrinkles are elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Over lunch (potato gnocchi, which she loves) Cunningham speaks
about her years as personal assistant to father of American food
writing James Beard, her late-in-life career as a cookbook author
and cooking teacher, and her campaign to save the family meal from
extinction. Her persona is at once old-fashioned and California
contemporary. Even as she talks fondly of beef stew perfuming her
Bay area home, you suspect it's not a house filled with lace
doilies and crocheted samplers.
</P>
<P>
   At one point Cunningham stops herself in mid-
</P>
<P>
   sentence, folds her large hands on the table and laughs. ``My
God, I'm talking a lot about myself. What would my mother say?''
</P>
<P>
   But those expressive hands keep talking. You can imagine all the
pie dough and pot roasts that have passed through them. You can see
them, too, in her latest cookbook, ``Learning to Cook With Marion
Cunningham'' (Knopf, $29.95). The book is a mixture of homey
recipes spelled out in plain terms for beginners and a source of
gentle, nudging encouragement to get in the kitchen and cook.
Throughout, it features intimate portraits of Cunningham's hands
performing everyday kitchen tasks _ cutting a drumstick off a roast
chicken, stuffing garlic into slits in a leg of lamb _ that most
cookbooks don't illustrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm actually very clumsy,'' Cunningham admits, ``and I'm
left-handed so it looks awkward. But I'm able to do every job I
need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's longtime editor, Judith Jones, convinced her to
lend her hands to the project. ``They're long and gnarled and just
beautiful,'' said Jones by telephone. ``I wanted them almost as a
comfort for the readers, who could be in the kitchen with a
grandmother rather than witnessing the high jinks that a chef can
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The book grew out of a yearlong series of classes that
Cunningham held at her house with six adults who had never before
cooked. For this lifelong veteran of home-prepared meals, the
students' perspective was an eye-opener. They hated going to
supermarkets because they were overwhelmed by the rice selection.
They were mystified when asked to ``dot with butter.'' They were
intimidated by busy-looking cookbooks. They thought that if a
recipe called for green onions, you had to cut off the white part.
It took Cunningham little time to realize she was up against ``a
combination of fear and inexperience.''
</P>
<P>
   Her goal was not to transform these can't-boil-water wimps into
gourmet Pygmalions but to make them comfortable preparing meals at
home. ``Whether it's wonderful or just OK food doesn't matter. It's
the action in the kitchen and sitting down together _ that's what's
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham used the students' suggestions to determine the tone,
look and content of ``Learning to Cook.'' More than anything, she
worked on the language and wording of recipes, using vivid images
and steering clear of jargon. For stuffed cherry tomato appetizers,
she crumbles crisp bacon ``into small bits, about the size of Rice
Krispies''; or, in a recipe for basic risotto, she ingenuously
comments, ``when the rice is tender and ... has a creamy
consistency, almost like thick oatmeal, it is done.''
</P>
<P>
   No dish was too basic for these beginners or, Cunningham
suspects, millions of other Americans. So in addition to offering
contemporary dishes such as fish baked in parchment and pasta with
chile and cilantro, she hashes out detailed recipes for scrambled
eggs, baked potatoes and hamburgers. Does anyone really need a
recipe for hamburgers?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she says vehemently. ``There's an art to making a good
hamburger. If you've never made one, you want to pat and fiddle
around with that ground meat too much. Some of the most simple
things are harder than the harder things.''
</P>
<P>
   By year's end, Cunningham's students had developed ``enough
confidence to invite people over,'' she notes. ``It was interesting
to see what evolved. One of them is quite the food snob now!''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham knows firsthand that a mere cooking class can have a
profound impact. In 1972, when she was a 50-year-old California
housewife and mother of grown children, she ventured north to
Oregon to take a class with James Beard, her favorite cookbook
writer. (``He sort of talked to you through the pages.''). Beard
asked if she would become his assistant and for the next 11 years,
until Beard's death at age 83, she was his right hand at cooking
classes throughout the world. It was a change for a woman whose
only previous job had been in a service station during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Beard also hooked Cunningham up with Jones, who was looking for
a home cook to test and revise the 1,800 recipes in the ``Fannie
Farmer Cookbook,'' the classic text written by a Boston housewife
in 1896. ``I wanted someone who could take these old recipes and
change them, but still respect what Fannie did,'' said Jones.
Published in 1979, the book established Cunningham as a kind of
culinary missing link _ a gray-haired cookie baker who also travels
in the high-profile American food world. She's the mom with the
golden palate.
</P>
<P>
   She has cultivated this unique role in the intervening years.
Now settled in the Bay area, she is both a cooking teacher who
works with children and a regular dining companion of the San
Francisco Chronicle restaurant critic.
</P>
<P>
   Having shared an excellent meal with her at Watershed and a
mediocre one elsewhere, I can tell you the only thing Cunningham
doesn't mince is words. She is vocal about her likes and dislikes,
and praises upscale restaurant food as long is it honest and not
overly stylized, because ``pretty is as pretty tastes.'' But, when
she encounters a nouvelle carrot soup screaming with ginger, she
puts down her spoon after one bite and says, ``I think soup should
be soothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, she remains true to her love of simple American food
_ the meatloaf, head-lettuce salad and baking powder biscuits that
the other Marion Cunningham served to Richie and the gang on
``Happy Days.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many of us grew up on this food, Cunningham is really the
only major food personality speaking out for it. To her, it is
vital for a simple reason: The less Americans consider traditional
home cooking, the less they cook at home.
</P>
<P>
   In the preface to ``Learning to Cook,'' she addresses the
disappearing dinner hour. ``There are all kinds of reasons given _
lack of time, other demands at the family dinner hour, anxiety
about wasting ingredients not eaten up, the ease of eating in a
restaurant, the lure of takeout foods. But the main reason nobody's
in the kitchen, I began to suspect, was that people today are
uneasy about cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it roast beef hash therapy. Or chicken soup for the
stomach. Cunningham thinks that concise recipes for old-time
favorites might bring families back to the kitchen and back to the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds so preachy,'' she says over dessert, a chocolate
layer cake that gets high marks. ``Yet there's this mission I have
about trying to get people to share food together.''
</P>
<P>
   But aren't we looking at a future of supermarket sushi and
chicken wraps?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to stick to the idea that people might return to
more home cooking.'' She says it in a measured tone _ part realism,
part hope.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
