<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CHAMPAGNE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMPAGNE PRICES UP AS Y2K COUNTS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By KEVIN ROTHSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rumors that worldwide revelry this New Year's will
create a champagne shortage are greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   So says Don Atkinson, a wine salesman for the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give the Frenchman your money, he's going to give you
something,'' said Atkinson, a senior wine consultant at Manhattan's
Astor Wine &AMP; Spirits.
</P>
<P>
   True champagne comes exclusively from the Champagne region, a
province northeast of Paris encompassing only 85,000 acres. A rush
of New Year's parties to celebrate the year 2000, some fear, could
mean bubble trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson has seen prices rise a few dollars a bottle, but he
believes the increase is more hype than shortage. Still, Atkinson
said he already has a few bottles of choice libations stashed away,
to guard against future price increases if not shortages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have told all my regular customers to buy now, especially if
you're going to buy a lot of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The importers have already put retailers like Atkinson on a
ration of the finest champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts are predicting that shortages, if any develop at
all, will only affect the best champagnes, like Dom Perignon. Top
shelf champagnes start at about $100 and, depending on the vintage
and blend, can cost hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tell a lot of our customers is what will really be
depleted is prestige cuvees,'' said Michele Lawton, marketing
manager for Remy Amerique, which supplies Heidsick champagnes to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already seen our sales up 30 percent,'' Lawton said. ``We
plan on selling 80 percent of our volume by September.'' Forty-five
percent is normal every year, except this millenium year.
</P>
<P>
   Any bubbly not produced in the Champagne region is only
sparkling wine. Mass-produced brands like Korbel are in little
danger of running out of supply.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation that demand for champagne would surge for the
coming New Year comes as no surprise to the French vintners.
</P>
<P>
   The New York office of the Champagne Wines Information Bureau,
which represents champagne suppliers, says 300 million bottles are
on their way to America. Six years ago, only 11 million bottles
were exported to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our champagne sales were normal up until last November,'' said
Michael Aaron, chairman of Sherry-Lehman of Manhattan. ``That's
when everybody seems to have been bitten by the millennium bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices at Sherry-Lehman, which boasts the highest volume of any
single store in the country, have crept up as importers have made
it more difficult to buy top-quality champagne, Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   The liquor store executive attributed some of the increase in
Champagne sales to the publicity around rumored shortages. He said
volume this February was 55 percent higher than last February.
Sales were up 15 percent this March.
</P>
<P>
   At Flute, a tony champagne bar in midtown Manhattan, owner Herve
Rousseau is not worried about running out of the good stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Flute offers some 14 different champagnes by the glass, and more
than 100 bottles. Prices range from $30 for a bottle of California
sparkling wine to $1,200 for a magnum of 1973 Krug.
</P>
<P>
   Located just a few blocks from Times Square, Rousseau is
planning to throw a $500 fixed-price New Year's party, complete
with caviar and some of his better bubbly. Running out of the good
stuff is not a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they really have millions and millions of bottles,''
he said. ``So it should be OK.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Kevin Rothstein is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
