<HEADER>
A9738 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-MUSEUM-SHOPS &LR;      06-02 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MUSEUM-SHOPS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM THE THINKER TO THE NOODLE: MUSEUM SHOPS COMMODIFY ART 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By DESIREE ADIB
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tucked into a discrete corner near the entrance to
the Metropolitan Museum of Art there were once delicate postcards
and etchings for sale in a tiny shop. But that was in 1871. Nearly
125 years later, things are very different.
</P>
<P>
   Today that little shop has expanded to 18,760 square feet on two
and a half floors, with gold and mirrored walls. Discrete little
postcards are also a thing of the past. Today the store sells
thousands of different products _ everything from ties and scarves
to board games, stuffed animals and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the museum shop frenzy has spread across the
nation. Today, there are 1,855 museum shops registered with the
Museum Shop Association, a Denver-based trade group. The
``art-inspired'' merchandise for sale at these shops include
everything from pens with plastic eyeballs on top of them to
baseballs emblazoned with Cezanne's signature and pasta noodles
shaped like Rodin's ``Thinker.'' Prices range anywhere from 50
cents for a pencil with the museum's logo, to thousands of dollars
for limited edition prints.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that selling ``all-American'' merchandise such as
art-inspired baseballs democratizes the highbrow art world and
attracts the public to museums. But art purists believe that
turning works of art into menial objects like magnets and T-shirts
is demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's a manifestation of a deeper problem in our
society, which is that people aren't yet at the point of accepting
the experience of art as being the wonder of looking at something
and not taking it with you,'' said Nicholas Fox Weber, a
Connecticut art historian. ``I am not impressed with the idea of
taking a Picasso painting and putting it on an ashtray or a Jackson
Pollack and putting it on some underpants.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to retailers at museum shops, the merchandise for
sale only re-enforces the public's cultural education and allows
customers to bring a little art into their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very, very few people who can afford to have a Monet
in their house, but there are many, many people who can have a
print or a book or something representative of the artist,'' said
Judy Oldfield, the director of operations at the Museum Company
Store, a private retail operation that buys wholesale products from
250 museums across the nation. ``There are plenty of art movements
that have historically sought to democratize art and I personally
think that this is great.''
</P>
<P>
   For shoppers, the museum stores offer a chance to buy a token
related to a current exhibition or a favorite artist. The question
of taste is an important one for many shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a big fan of having a Picasso on a watch or a Klimt
impression on a scarf because I think that's just tacky,'' said a
German tourist, Eva Steiner, while browsing in the Metropolitan
Museum of Art Store in New York. ``But the fact is that not
everybody can buy a real Picasso, so I think that it's okay to have
a poster in your house.''
</P>
<P>
   For museums, the thriving retail industry has brought in
much-needed revenue to support programs and institutional costs.
According to the Washington-based American Association of Museums,
museums derive about 8 percent of their total operating income from
gift shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to raise taxes to support cultural
institutions and they are extremely critical of raising the price
of admissions, so how are we supposed to maintain them?'' said John
Curran, the vice president of merchandising at the Metropolitan
Museum of Art. ``Letting them help themselves is one way they can
do this.''
</P>
<P>
   The store at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, which sells
merchandise produced exclusively by the museum's in-house
reproduction studios, generates about $80 million a year. Nearly 10
percent of that is revenue that goes toward the operating budget of
the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really about survival,'' Curran said. ``It's about
helping to support institutions that people really love and feel
that it is important to maintain for educational purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   But would Rodin be rolling in his grave if he knew that his
famous ``Thinker'' statue had been reduced to a noodle? Would
Cezanne be mortified if he knew that his signature was being
slapped around by a baseball bat? According to merchandisers and
art retailers, it doesn't matter. The fact is that times have
changed and these products reflect an evolution of our culture.
Michelangelo might not be happy that his beloved ``David'' statue
is now a naked refrigerator magnet ready to be dressed in drag, but
good or bad, they say, that is the reality of culture today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are living in times when people's tastes and the
way they dress, the music they listen to, the shows they watch are
obviously not the same as in Michelangelo's time,'' Curran said.
``Even artwork produced today reflects that. So, therefore does the
merchandise that sells.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Desiree Adib is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
