<HEADER>
A9740 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-PREGNANCY-PREVENT     06-02 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-PREGNANCY-PREVENTION </SLUG>
  
 WHEN IT COMES TO TEENAGE SEX, IS IT BABY THINK IT OVER?
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By RAMONA JENKIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marguerita Rodriguez sat in the health clinic at St.
Columba School in Newark, N.J., filling out forms to help get
medical benefits for her 2-year-old daughter, Shailene, who was
fussing in her stroller.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, 18, became a high school drop-out three years ago
after she got pregnant with Shailene despite her participation in
an eighth grade health class at St. Columba that used an
infant-like doll called Baby Think It Over.
</P>
<P>
   The doll is intended to help teen-agers think twice about what
it is like to be a parent _ sleepless nights, never-ending feeding
schedules, lack of freedom _ before they engage in sexual activity
and find themselves on the fast track to responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   For a full week Rodriguez had to insert a special key into the
control box to quiet the doll, programmed to cry throughout the day
and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard,'' Rodriguez said. ``I had to take it everywhere
with me _ on the bus, to hang out with the girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the week I was saying, 'I'm never having a
baby,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her boyfriend, 24, did not go through the program, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later she became one of approximately 500,000
teen-agers who become pregnant each year in the United States,
according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   St. Columba's program is voluntary and requires parental
permission, said Betty Rosenbaum, a nurse who helps run the
program. Few boys choose to participate, she said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no pregnancies in eighth grade girls that she
knows of since the program started three years ago, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will only work if it's done with a very structured
program if it is accompanied by a larger program,'' Rosenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen-agers live for the moment,'' said Mary Jurmain, president
of Baby Think It Over.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to get teen-agers to stop and think what caring for
a baby really involves, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the company has been selling the dolls, now priced
at $295, to licensed professionals _ teachers, nurses, social
workers and doctors _ at schools, health centers and other
organizations that provide comprehensive health education for
teen-agers, Jurmain said.
</P>
<P>
   One of their printed advertisements states ``successful programs
are reporting reductions in pregnancy of over 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   But four years, 40,000 dolls, a million doll-educated teen-agers
and over $11 million in sales later it is unclear what role the
doll really plays in the prevention of pregnancy in teen-agers like
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   CDC data show there has been a 5 percent decrease in births to
teen-age mothers aged 15 to 19 between 1991 and 1995, said Michelle
O'Connell, a consultant for the Department of Health and Human
Services' Office of Population Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   OPA provides grants for 57 programs around the country to
develop pregnancy prevention strategies, she said. About 10 percent
use Baby Think It Over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregnancy rates and sexual activity have gone down,''
O'Connell said. ``That says that everything we're doing is
working.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that probably ``it's all AIDS and the fear are what's
doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Baby Think It Over program is an attractive idea,'' said
Dennis McBride, a program evaluator for OPA.
</P>
<P>
   But it is difficult and expensive to set up studies that look at
long-term outcomes, like pregnancy rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A study would have to randomize teen-agers getting different
interventions and follow them up over several years, McBride said.
That would mean some students would get the doll and others would
not.
</P>
<P>
   There is reluctance to withhold an intervention if there is any
possibility that it may have even a small impact on reducing
pregnancy rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doll is nothing more than a tool,'' said Brenda Lee Green
of Planned Parenthood of Pennsylvania. Almost 3,000 public school
teen-aged boys and girls have gone through their comprehensive
health curriculum around the doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our local pregnancy rates are in line with the national
rates,'' she said. She attributed the local decline in rates to
easier access to contraception and better education.
</P>
<P>
   But in a handful of teen-agers there were unexpected reactions
to the doll, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some of the kids it did the complete opposite,'' she said.
``It confirmed to them that they wanted a baby. They enjoyed it.
They liked the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our educators did some pretty serious processing around
that,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Baby Think It Over does not have any plans to do studies to
answer the question about preventing pregnancy outcomes, Jurmain
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to do it we'd have to hire an outside study to avoid
conflict of interest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have $40,000 to spend are we going to spend it on a
study?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a business,'' Jurmain said. ``We have to look at the
most efficient way for us to spend our money.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ramona Jenkin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
