<HEADLINE>
FOR BILLBOARD PAINTERS THE ROADSHOW NEARS THE END 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By GEORGINA GUSTIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They scale sheer vertical walls in every extreme of
temperature. They hang above speeding traffic and crowded
intersections at spectacular heights. They put themselves face to
face with tough cowboys and dangerous women daily.
</P>
<P>
   They are billboard painters _ the people who climb hundreds of
feet in the air with a few cans of paint and a brush to render
images that have become as much a part of this country's roadscape
as truck stops and budget motels. And they are a vanishing species.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the images on billboards, like the famous
Marlboro Man, have seeped into American lore, the people
responsible for creating them have remained anonymous. And now,
with changes in the billboard industry, these invisible artisans
may disappear altogether.
</P>
<P>
   To the average driver, the target of billboard ads, the
existence of these huge pictures is almost a mystery. Yet the
process of creating them requires agility and craftsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   To create a billboard, a painter stands on a platform that is
rigged on a pulley system enabling him to maneuver across the
billboard's surface. He carries a ruler so that he can measure a
grid onto the billboard and paint an image to scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billboards are quite noticeable, they're right in front of
you,'' said Jason Perline, a longtime billboard professional. ``It
amazes me that people still don't know about them. People think
they're there by divine right.''
</P>
<P>
   Perline knows better. The former owner of Van Wagner Outdoor
Advertising, he presided over some hugely successful billboard
campaigns, including the infamous Brooke Shields ad which featured
the then-adolescent model lying seductively above Times Square
wearing nothing but a half-open blouse and her Calvins.
</P>
<P>
   Perline respects the process of creating billboards. ``I was
once on a scaffold,'' he said. ``I said I'll never do it again. It
was scary as hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the many personal characteristics required of a billboard
painter, a fear of heights is not on the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a can-do attitude, the ability to think on your
feet,'' said Scott Charmichael, 43, of Scott Signs in New Jersey.
``You have to be intelligent because you're always being faced with
a new set of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, ``You don't want somebody who's always tripping
over their feet.''
</P>
<P>
   When potential painters come into his office seeking employment,
Charmichael instructs them to climb a ladder that he keeps in his
studio to test their confidence and comfort level up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want some kid who's got something to prove,''
Charmichael said. ``Guys come in here and say, `I'm not afraid to
die. I'm not afraid of anything.' Well, it's not worth dying for.
It's only advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   But to the painters, including Charmichael, a billboard is far
more than an appeal to drive-by consumers or a health risk. It's an
artistic challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Many billboard painters have formal art training.
</P>
<P>
   But Charmichael, who holds a bachelor's degree in fine arts from
Indiana University, said, ``I learned more about how to paint in
billboards than I did in art school. I spent my days up to my
elbows in paint.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, artistic skills and techniques are rarely employed.
The industry, once reliant on the abilities of artists who painted
billboards by hand, has come to rely on computer-generated images
that are printed on vinyl, called flex face, that is delivered to a
billboard site and stretched across the billboard's frame.
</P>
<P>
   Computer-generated billboards are quickly phasing out
hand-painted images that cost more and are labor intensive, often
taking several weeks to complete. New technology has enabled
advertisers to erect campaigns within a few hours and take them
down just as quickly, often moving one image to a different
location for maximum play.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has also enabled billboard companies to control
changing digital displays, like lottery jackpot numbers, via
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these advances, some advertisers insist on hand-painted
images.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no comparison to the artistry of hand painting,'' said
Jared Townsend of the Outdoor Media Group in Murietta, Calif. ``The
color, the depth, the contrast, the transition in color, are just
phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   One advertiser that has insisted on hand painting is the Philip
Morris Corporation, owner of Marlboro cigarettes. But as of April
this year, the company has had to seek other venues for the
enduring lonesome cowboy; because of a settlement reached between
the states and the tobacco corporations, cigarette billboards will
no longer be permissible in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically coming down to the end,'' Townsend said. ``The
Marlboro man is riding off into the sunset.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hole, a 16-year veteran of the billboard painting industry
and a former art teacher, has painted over 300 Marlboro men.
``That's a lot of cowboys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A short while ago, as if to defy fate, Hole had put the
finishing touches on a 60-foot-tall Marlboro Man _ the last he
expects he will ever paint. ``I did the hat yesterday,'' said Hole,
somewhat wistfully. ``All I have left is the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Hole said he will most likely return to teaching, but he is
sentimental about the career he is leaving behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more than just a job,'' he said. ``Thousands of people
see these things, and we're not going to be doing them anymore. You
feel a little nostalgic. It's sad to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hole's final rendition of the Marlboro Man _ it will be
dismantled and shipped in pieces to Venezuela where men of his ilk
are still legal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Georgina Gustin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9742 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-EX-CON &LR;      06-02 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-EX-CON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE INSIDE, LOOKING OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By TANYA WEINBERG  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His debt to society was paid. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   So wondered Charles Griffin upon his release from Coxsackie
state prison in upstate New York in the winter of 1996. He had $107
in his pocket and little to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 7, his mother died of a heart attack in his arms.
His abusive drug-addicted father blamed him, and Griffin became a
ward of the state for a decade. He struggled through high school
and joined the Army, which he loved. But, unable to keep up with
the discipline, he was kicked out and felt lost, he said in a
recent telephone interview from the Orleans Correctional Facility
in Albion, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two weeks after his release from Coxsackie, Griffin
grabbed a woman's pocketbook, down the street from where Mayor
Rudolph W. Giuliani was having lunch. He wanted to get out of the
filthy, drug-infested Brooklyn shelter where he had found a bed, he
said. He wanted to buy new clothes for a job interview, and things
for his estranged daughter. He landed back in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``My pride got in my way,'' said Griffin, who is 32 now and
serving his 16th year in his fourth robbery conviction. He now
regrets he wasn't more patient, and vows next time he will be. He
awaits his 2002 release and perhaps his final chance to go clean.
Another conviction would almost certainly win him a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat offenders like Griffin make up a significant portion of
the prison population across the country, although recidivism rates
vary between states. Of the 26,104 convicts released by New York
state prisons in 1994, 44 percent returned to prison within three
years, according to the state's Commission of Correction. Groups
like the Manhattan-based Fortune Society are working with
ex-offenders to increase their likelihood of going clean.
</P>
<P>
   As the city's largest nonprofit organization to assist
ex-offenders, the Fortune Society helps clients get their GED, look
for a job, fight drug abuse, and live with HIV. More than that, it
is a source of moral support for people who often lack job
experience, education and familial support.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a family to people,'' said Edmond Taylor, 40,
who works with clients in career development. Incarceration
isolates people, he explained, citing his own 12 years in state
prison. Like a majority of the society's 100 or so employees,
Taylor is an ex-offender who can relate to the frustrations
awaiting his clients upon their release.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say, 'If he can do it _ I can do it,' and that gives them
hope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The public foots 90 percent of the Fortune Society's $5.6
million budget. While state financing has grown for HIV and drug
treatment programs, the group constantly struggles to secure money
from the legislature, said Beth Finnerty, the society's financial
director.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics question whether taxpayers should dish out more
money to help people who got themselves in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be a balance,'' said Kevin Mica, spokesman for
the Law Enforcement Alliance of America, a conservative nonpartisan
advocacy group that supports victims' rights over criminals'
rights. ``Prisoners have so many perks and bonuses these days,'' he
said. Prisoners ought to serve their full sentences and not be
eligible for services, such as a free college education, when
plenty of innocent people do without, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Gov. George Pataki recently eliminated all college
classes in prison, but other prison-based programs remain. Some
rehabilitation programs may be worthwhile, but these should not be
financed predominantly by public money, Mica said.
</P>
<P>
   Others disagree. Rehabilitation works, without a doubt, said
Francis T. Cullen, professor of Criminal Justice at the University
of Cincinnati. Broad analyses of existing studies show that early
intervention, drug treatment, and other rehabilitation programs
prevent crime and reduce recidivism, he said. Get-tough approaches
such as boot camps and longer sentences do not. ``It's close to
indisputable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rehabilitation is cost effective, he said. Not only does it
reduce crime, it reduces the high costs of incarceration. ``It's an
absurd wasting of funds,'' Cullen said.
</P>
<P>
   New York state and city spend $28,000 a year to incarcerate each
of its more than 100,000 inmates. Nationwide, Americans spend close
to $31 billion a year on corrections.
</P>
<P>
   Although rehabilitation programs are effective, they are
imperfect, concedes Cullen. The work is often underpaid and
undervalued, and convicted criminals do not always want to take
advantage of these opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Griffin visited the Fortune Society between prison
terms, but he was among the 35 percent who regularly drop out.
Griffin said he might go there again, but thinks if he can just
land a job, he should be OK.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he is cutting vegetables in the prison kitchen for 38
cents an hour. Through eight-hour workdays, he hopes to amass close
to $2,000 by his release three years from now. He described the
prison environment as awash with negativity _ gangs, fights, ``lost
souls.'' Trying to avoid the bad and prepare for the best, he took
a 90-day ``personal enhancement'' seminar where prisoners role play
and discuss alternatives to drug use and crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that I can offer the world something,'' he said. ``I'm
a nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin wants to capitalize on his behind-bars food-preparation
experience to find work and vows to persevere this time. He hopes
to repair his relationships with his father, who has gotten off
drugs, and his daughter who is now 12. But the biggest test is yet
to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk is cheap,'' he said. ``I still gotta go home and prove
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Tanya Weinberg is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
