<SLUG> BC-CNS-KOSOVO-COPS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK POLICE OFFICERS PLAN KOSOVO TRAINING MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By DIANE HANDAL  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While Albanians were streaming out of Kosovo, a
unique group of police officers in New York wanted nothing more
than to get in.
</P>
<P>
   Secure in their adopted country and working in a career they
would have eschewed in their native land, these police officers are
repelled by the images of heavy-handed police who attack their
former countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   They hope one day to help replace Kosovo's militaristic police
force with a law-enforcement system based on civil liberty for all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly. I want to help people of my ethnic
background,'' said New York Officer Ylli Dauti. ``My family wants
me to go, too.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my moral duty to help. How can my conscience not let me
go?'' said one 27-year-old officer who asked that his name not be
divulged because of his undercover assignment in the New York
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers and 15 other New York police officers of
Albanian background were ready and trained for a special mission in
Kosovo even before the refugee crisis began in March. But Serbian
President Slobodan Milosevic's ethnic cleansing push and NATO's
subsequent bombing raids interrupted their plans to join a State
Department group organized to train a new police force in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Washington had recruited these police officers to oversee an
international peace agreement when it was still active earlier this
year. Officers were needed to help verify compliance with the
cease-fire and eventually to train a new local police force in
Kosovo. The State Department, which sent similar police missions to
Bosnia and Haiti, has found that American officers conversant in
the native tongue have a credibility with people in war-ravaged
countries, said a department coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disappointed I couldn't go,'' Dauti said. ``I want
to go as soon as possible to help with the refugees in Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   But the New York undercover officer, whose parents are from
Montenegro, said he was relieved that the mission was put off,
given the war that ensued. ``I'm still anxious to go but it's a
blessing in disguise,'' he said. In fact, one New York police
officer who did go early to Kosovo had to be evacuated when the war
started.
</P>
<P>
   The New York officers are strongly motivated by the policing
standards they have found in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the former Yugoslavia, police ``are an extension of the
government and there you would be told to beat somebody up if they
say something against the government,'' said Victor Preni, 30, a
beat officer in the Bronx who immigrated from Kosovo at age 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Police officers here fight against crime. There, it's
political thought,'' the undercover officer said. ``They are an
instrument of Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   On a 1991 visit to Yugoslavia, Dauti experienced police
repression. ``At every checkpoint from Belgrade to Kosovo,'' he
said softly, ``we were ordered out of the car, machine guns were
pointed in our faces and we were ordered to pay the police.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian-American police officers also believe their
immigrant status helps them with their police work in New York's
polyglot ethnic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather was in the Albanian army,'' said Dauti, a
patrol officer in Bedford-Stuyvesant, where gangs and violence are
synonymous. ``Because my family isn't wealthy and I come from a
different culture, I am more open and understanding to a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian contingency at the New York Police Department
seemed a natural fit, said Inspector Richard Martin, executive
officer of personnel. ``The diverse community and many cultures of
New York City add to their training and set them apart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the police mission to Kosovo was shelved indefinitely
pending outcome of the administration's broader effort with NATO.
``We have a moral and strategic interest in managing and solving
this crisis,'' said David Leavy, White House National Security
Council spokesman. ``All Serbian forces and para-military have to
withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   While they wait, the New York officers, like many Americans of
Albanian descent, have tried to contact family members still in the
former Yugoslavia and have closely monitored TV coverage of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day I saw my cousins on TV in the refuge camp,''
Dauti said. ``I thought they were dead.''
</P>
<P>
   His great uncle had opened the door to find a Serb policeman
brandishing a knife. ``The officer took out his knife and slit his
throat. There were two 11-year-old cousins in the house who jumped
out the window and escaped to Albania,'' Dauti was told by Albanian
family members.
</P>
<P>
   Preni heard from his uncle in Kosovo who witnessed the execution
of two neighbors, brothers who were dragged from their home by
three masked gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know these people,'' Preni said, weeping and clenching his
fists. ``I grew up next door to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Such sentiments far overtake the financial incentive that the
New York officers would have to join the training mission to
Kosovo. Their State Department stipend would be about $85,000,
which is more than double the average police salary in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would do it for the same salary I get now. The money doesn't
interest me. It's a matter of living with my conscience,'' said the
undercover officer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Diane Handal is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
