<SLUG> BC-CNS-PRIVACY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREATS TO MEDICAL PRIVACY SPARKS DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By WILLIAM MURRAY  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Computerized medical records are becoming standard in
hospitals and doctor's offices nationwide, with patients mostly
assuming those files remain as private as they have been in file
cabinets. But a growing debate is raising questions about just how
secure medical records are in the age of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing shelves full of manila folders with digital databases
seems like a great way to improve efficiency, diagnosis and patient
care. Today, however, consumers, the medical community and members
of Congress are fighting over whether computerized medical records
can ever be safe, especially when no national standard regulates
their protection.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been debating several bills to strengthen legal
protections against misuse of private health information. The issue
is particularly sensitive among those who seek to protect the most
sensitive data _ dealing with AIDS, psychiatric history and drug
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the United States has no consistent medical privacy
policy,'' said Ronald Weich, an American Civil Liberties Union
legislative consultant. ``There is a patchwork of state laws that
protect some citizens, but a national law is needed in an era of
electronic records and national insurance companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have protections pretty much along the lines of other
places around the country,'' said Kathy Stark, assistant director
at the Cabrini Medical Center in Manhattan. ``For those patients
with records of greater sensitivity, such as psychiatry and drug
addiction, there is a second step that must be taken. The patient
must be informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Within each state, medical institutions are on their own when
developing their own security systems, leaving questions about
whether the precautions can really thwart hackers, insurance
company investigators or private investigators.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Michigan Medical Center, a student in
February stumbled across thousands of pages of medical records
incorrectly placed on the Internet. The breach, which released
records including patients' Social Security numbers, employment
information and diagnoses, occurred as the hospital ironed out bugs
in new scheduling software. The university said the information was
not accessed by other third parties, but the incident highlighted
potential problems as more hospitals convert to digital record
keeping.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 the Clinton administration first proposed then backed
away from a Unique Health Identifier _ a Social Security number for
medical recorders _ after the ACLU and other privacy rights groups
vehemently opposed it claiming that electronic files could be
easily compromised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospitals are digitizing information. The large-scale
aggregating of data is causing the problem,'' because so much data
is available from a single entry point, said Alex Fowler, a
spokesman for the Electronic Frontier Foundation in San Francisco,
an Internet privacy organization.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressional bills aim to standardize federal
requirements and legal penalties for medical record protection.
Sen. James Jeffords, R-Vt., chairman of the Senate Health and
Education Committee, proposed civil penalties of up to a $100,000
against companies or individuals who violate medical privacy
guidelines. Others bills follow a similar vein.
</P>
<P>
   ``This battle is between American families who want some privacy
and big business buying access to their personal medical records,''
Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., said as he introduced legislation in
March allowing states to enforce higher protective standards than
the federal government. He cited instances where private firms
mined databases for medical records they could sell to insurance
companies for profit.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe that no degree of security measures can thwart
every invasion, particularly in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Nagel, a psychiatrist and spokesperson for the Electronic
Privacy Information Center in Washington, D.C., told the National
Committee on Vital and Health Statistics two years ago that 90
percent of security breaches with medical records involve insider
access.
</P>
<P>
   In a high profile case she cited, a convicted serial rapist
employed by a hospital in Massachusetts accessed the records of
nearly 1,000 girls and young women, one as young as 9.
</P>
<P>
   Even still, some medical records specialists believe electronic
storage of records actually improves security.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, there was no audit trail that could be traced
within the hospital,'' said Francoise Righini, medical records
director at St. Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center in New York.
``When the files were on paper, no one could know who had seen it.
Now with computers, every time a record check is made it must be
from a computer within the system and a password.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, privacy advocates also caution that health care
consumers themselves are too willing to part unnecessarily with
private medical information to insurance companies and courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients are not reluctant to give medical records to third
parties,'' said B.J. Armstrong, special counsel for the American
Medical Association in Chicago. ``People give up records that
contain things they don't want others to know.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: William Murray is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
