<HEADER>
A9745 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-RAT-KILLERS &LR;      06-02 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-RAT-KILLERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGET THE RAT RACE: THE ONLY GOOD RAT IS A DEAD RAT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ITAY HOD  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was almost midnight. James Valletti led his team
to the lower platform of Nassau-Broadway subway station, the most
infested area of New York City's 850-mile track. The three men
stepped onto the tracks, turned on warning lights and pulled out
their weapons _ plastic bags of rat poison covered with peanut
butter.
</P>
<P>
   They all knew what they had to do. Ted Dixon was in charge of
stopping the trains, Joe ``The Firm'' Nilsson posted signs and
James ``The Rat Killer'' Valletti spread the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like killing rats,'' said Valletti, a heavy set man in
his 30s. ``I always did. I like to see the numbers go down and I
like to see the carcasses on the tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   It's New York's other rat race, the never-ending quest to rid
the city of rodents. The Big Apple's get-tough mayor has made rats
a top priority, along with sex shops, jaywalkers, and other
undesirables.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1997, Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani spent $8
million on, what some have called, a re-election-inspired campaign
against vermin _ the Comprehensive Rodent Control Program. And
comprehensive it was. The three-part plan targeted 69 neighborhoods
in all five boroughs. All city departments joined forces to fight
what some consider New York's most serious health problem.
</P>
<P>
   Strategies have gotten ruthless. Exterminators are not only
cleaning up infested areas, but also targeting the areas around
them, making sure the rats have nowhere to run, nowhere to hide.
Almost two years later, the fight is still on.
</P>
<P>
   But is it working?
</P>
<P>
   According to Alan Yager, MTA manager at the division of track,
the crusade has been a success. ``There's no way of doing a rat
census, but in the past few years, I have seen a decline in rats,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department statistics support this claim. Complaints of
rat bites have declined by almost two thirds, from the upper 800s
in the 1980s to about 200 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the tracks, Valletti, wearing a helmet and an orange
reflective vest, sprinkles his deadly poison. From a nearby garbage
crevice, rats scamper around the tracks, squeaking and squealing.
Some sniff the bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not hungry tonight,'' he said. ``You have to think
like a rat in order to kill them. It's not just throwing poison.
You have to have the knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Rats are no easy prey. Although they have poor eyesight, they
hear extremely well and have a great sense of smell. They average a
pound in size, but can grow as big as four pounds. Not only can
they climb walls, they can swim for miles. They can also jump out
of a fifth floor window, without getting hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse, they are expert breeders. Sexually mature at two
months, they can have up to six litters a year, seven babies each.
In three years, one pair of Norway rats, the most common New York
City rodent, can yield 350 million. Fortunately, Norway rats only
live on average six months.
</P>
<P>
   More than just a nuisance, rats carry deadly diseases. During
the 14th century, 23 million people died from the bubonic plague _
almost half of Europe's population at the time. Last century, 12
million people died of rat-related illnesses _ rat-bite fever,
dysentery, salmonella, typhus, jaundice and more. These illnesses
are still a problem today.
</P>
<P>
   The MTA is pulling out all the stops. Twelve of its supervisors
have enrolled in higher education, a 30-hour course in the art of
the kill. This will ensure the system has exterminators on hand 24
hours a day, seven days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're nasty,'' said Tracy Bryant, an MTA maintenance
supervisor who is enrolled in the course. ``But it's good to know
how to kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   In one recent lecture, students gathered for a training video.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rats _ man's worst enemy,'' snarled the melodramatic narrator.
``It is now that the sickening force must be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a city where there are four rats for every person, it
seems unlikely the problem will ever completely go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an ongoing issue,'' said John Gadd, spokesperson for
the New York City Department of Health. ``There are numbers of
neighborhoods where the rodent situation had become unmanageable.''
</P>
<P>
   Valletti, who has killed close to 10,000 rats in the past six
years, agrees the epidemic can be controlled but not eradicated. As
he throws his peanut butter poison, Valletti tiptoes down the
soiled tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you're in their territory,'' Valletti said.
``Underground is their domain. They are not afraid of people. They
see them all the time, they are used to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Valletti recalled how some cable network crew brought their own
rats to film a documentary on vermin. They brought 15 rats with
them and left with 18. Three just went along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   After many years in the business, Yager has a story or two. He
recalls when a rat hopped onto a subway train to the amazement, and
horror, of the passengers. Everyone on board screamed and ran to
the opposite side of the car. ``They all got off on the next
stop,'' Yager said with amusement. ``Rats are not aggressive,
they'll only bite if they feel threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Williams, 33, a computer operator from Brooklyn has seen
more rats than he cares to remember. ``I'm so used to it by now,''
said Williams. ``It's kind of funny actually, you see so many of
them it makes you wonder why it's so difficult to get rid of rats
in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone takes the rat situation lightly. A concerned
citizen wrote the mayor asking permission to take action. Convinced
employees weren't doing enough, he wanted permission to throw some
poison of his own.
</P>
<P>
   His request was denied. Apparently, he could be sued for
littering.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Itay Hod is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
