r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-SURVIVAL-EATING &LR;      06-02 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-SURVIVAL-EATING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONIGHT, WE HAVE A LOVELY SLUG SOUFFLE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 BY JEANINE PREZIOSO  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Capt. James Sheehan, a Marine Corps reservist, knows
how to cut off a rattlesnake's head and throw it on fire for
dinner. He has learned which berries and roots are safe to eat and
how to build a rock dam to catch fish _ and then smoke the fish and
meat in a wood-and-rock shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan, 26, has been through both land and water survival
training.
</P>
<P>
   What Naval Air Force Sgt. Paul Laws, who teaches at the Air
Force Water Survival School, serves up may not tempt the palates of
most, but then who can be choosy when crash landing in the middle
of the Atlantic?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fluid around the eye sockets and spines of fish make good
water sources,'' Laws said matter-of-factly. ``If you don't have a
de-salinity kit, you can collect fresh rainwater. The most abundant
source of water is rainwater.''
</P>
<P>
   Most humans can go a few weeks without food but only five to
seven days without water, said Laws, so water is the priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the Arctic, you can use sea ice as a source,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Land survival techniques include which plants to eat, Sheehan
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taught how to get fresh water from leaves; wrap any
kind of plastic around the leaves, leave it in the sunlight and
over time water would condense around the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned how to make beef jerky,'' he said. ``The idea was
that we could smoke this stuff so that we could keep it and it
wouldn't go bad.''
</P>
<P>
   All Air Force crew members get both land and water training,
said Master Sgt. Buddy Gurnari of the Fairchild Air Force Base
Survival School in Spokane, Wash. Under a program called Survival
Evasion Resistance and Escape, or SERE, all members of the Armed
Forces receive some kind of survival training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Navy does it mostly with air crew members,'' he said. ``We
send the guys who fly planes with ejection seats to Pensacola for
water survival school. They go parasailing to simulate
parachuting.'' Aviators who fly cargo planes stay at Fairchild and
take a non-parachute course, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gurnari once trained cadets at Pensacola for water survival, now
he teaches land survival. Grasshoppers and a lot of plant-eating
insects taste like plants, he said. ``Grubs'' have a nutty flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grubs' are larvae,'' Gurnari said. ``And I've never gotten
sick from eating an insect.''
</P>
<P>
   One cadet just broke his class record for having eaten 27 banana
slugs, he said. ``He just got back from a tropical location, lots
of slimy things there,'' Gurnari added.
</P>
<P>
   Gurnari warned against eating ``puffer fish or fish that eat
directly off the reef. You can eat shell fish only if covered by a
high tide.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Water Survival Training'' manual given to all Air Force
cadets, gives survival pointers, some of which are just plain
common sense: ``Oceans and seas cover roughly 70.8 percent of the
earth's surface. The possibility of becoming a water survivor at
some point in a flying career is better than average ... nearly 3
out of every 4 feet of space on this planet is occupied by water.''
</P>
<P>
   Once enough water has been found or stored, survivors can begin
to think about food, available from ``the largest supermarket in
the world, located under the raft,'' says the booklet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to find something that doesn't have scales,'' Laws
advised. ``No brightly colored or ornamental fish either.''
</P>
<P>
   What he recommends: Fish that look like fish you see in the
supermarket. Don't eat anything that has a boxy shape. And eat it
raw and fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might shake up your system a little bit,'' he said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   If raw fish makes you sick, you can always turn to seaweed, a
good source of carbohydrates and vitamins. Only the leafy parts
should be eaten and only in small bites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turtles or birds are OK, too,'' Laws said, adding that it is
best to skin the bird and eat it raw or let it sit in the sun and
dry out, to get rid if that ``oily'' flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Insects are a good source of protein, said a senior official at
Fairchild Air Force base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ants are easy as long as they're not biting ants,'' he said.
``Just stick your hand in the nest, let them crawl all over and
lick them off.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Jeanine Prezioso is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
