<P>
   MUSEUM SHOPS _ Museum shops are full of refrigerator magnets and
pencils with copies of art on them. Is it culture or does it
diminish the art?
</P>
<P>
   BILLBOARDS _ The fine art of billboard painting is quickly
becoming displaced by computer graphics.
</P>
<P>
   CHAMPAGNE _ Fears of a champagne shortage for New Year's Eve
1999 are greatly exaggerated, wine merchants say.
</P>
<P>
   SURVIVAL EATING _ Insects and grubs make fine eating when you
are stranded in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   EX-CONS _ The Fortune Society is working with ex-offenders to
increase their likelihood of going clean. As the city's largest
nonprofit organization to assist ex-offenders, the Fortune Society
helps clients get their GED, look for a job, fight drug abuse, and
live with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   FORGERIES _ Forensic scientists analyze handwriting to reveal
fraud _ and in today's litigious society, they're increasingly in
demand.
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANCY PREVENTION _ A program tries to discourage teen-agers
from becoming pregnant by making them care for a demanding doll.
But does the program really work?
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO COPS _ Albanian-American police officers hope one day to
help replace Kosovo's militaristic police force with a
law-enforcement system based on civil liberty for all.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY _ With more and more medical records computerized, some
fear a reduction in privacy.
</P>
<P>
   RAT KILLERS _ In New York City the effort to keep the rat
population under control is a 24-hour-a-day job.
</P>
