<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-JAR-JAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAR JAR'S CHARACTER UNSETTLES SOME CRITICS AND `MENACE' VIEWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT L. JAMIESON JR.  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jar Jar Binks, the loopy, goofy, big-eared amphibian
alien from the hit flick ``The Phantom Menace'' must:
</P>
<P>
   a) move to a galaxy far, far away
</P>
<P>
   b) keepsa on workin' as yous humbule servant
</P>
<P>
   c) get a translator and a makeover
</P>
<P>
   d) DIE! DIE! DIE!
</P>
<P>
   e) all of the above
</P>
<P>
   Anyway you splice it, George Lucas' computer-generated movie
character is stirring powerful reactions on Planet Earth, from
radio talk shows (where shock jocks are calling for a Jar-B-Q) to
Internet Web sites (www.JarJarMustDie.com) to murmurings as people
exit theaters (``I thought he was racist,'' whispered a movie
critic from a metropolitan newspaper in the Midwest.)
</P>
<P>
   Though some adults think the alien goes too far far, kids mostly
love Jar Jar, who resembles a Rastafarian Joe Camel. But scholars
say his Caribbean-like speech _ ``when is yousa tinkin wesa in
trouble'' _ and shuffling klutziness smack of stereotypes of
African Americans straight out of Stepin Fetchit, the 1930s-era
actor who played lazy or easily frightened characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jar Jar is the science fiction version of a character in black
face,'' said Daniel Bernardi, an assistant professor of media
studies at the University of Arizona in Tucson, who studies race
and science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching him, I was reminded of the stereotype of colored
people as bumbling sidekicks. Big bulging eyes, big lips, can't
speak clearly and shuffling.''
</P>
<P>
   Even away from the ivory tower, Jar Jar sparks passions _
provided, that is, you can understand him. Many viewers complained
his speech was hard on their ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most annoying creature Lucas has ever created,''
said Rachael White, who spent $2,000 so she and her husband, Tim,
could see a special charity screening of the movie at Seattle's
Cinerama Theater. ``If I was 7 years old, I would have thought it
was the best thing ever. But I'm 27.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Mueller, an Auburn resident who is a clerk for Zanadu
Comics in downtown Seattle, became so jarred by Jar Jar he started
a Web site and club in dishonor of the bug-eyed, platypus-billed
character. It's called The International Society for the
Extermination of Jar Jar Binks.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller said the movie would have been ``vastly improved'' if
the alien was CTRL-ALT-DELETED. Others apparently agree. Mueller's
club and Web site have attracted several hundred members in recent
weeks, and he has become something of an international media
darling, drawing the interest of CNN and others.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas said Jar Jar was designed to bring comic relief to his
celluloid universe, much in the way the furry-faced Wookie,
Chewbacca, served up funny grunts in the original ``Star Wars''
trilogy. Speaking in New York recently, he said ``Phantom'' was
primarily a children's movie with humorous flourishes and was not
meant to be taken too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say children are precisely the people who will enjoy
the antics of Jar Jar and other Lucas characters but will fail to
see deeper stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of Jar Jar Binks, it is the dialogue that puts up the
red flag. There's a number of occasions where the character delves
off into some sort of ebonics,'' said Todd Boyd, a professor of
cinema studies at the University of Southern California School of
Cinema and Television.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd's phone has been ringing off the hook about Jar Jar. But he
was more offended by the presence of two aliens in ``Phantom
Menace'' who sported Asian-sounding accents. Those aliens lured the
Jedis into a trap at the beginning of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were speaking in this dialogue straight out of a Charlie
Chan movie,'' Boyd said. ``I thought it was much more overt than
Jar Jar.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Lucas company executives fired back at the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in `Star Wars' that is racially motivated,''
said Lucasfilm spokeswoman Lynne Hale. ```Star Wars' is a fantasy
movie set in a galaxy far, far away. It is populated with humans,
aliens, droids, robots and other fantastic creatures that have no
resemblance to the world we know today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hale added: ``To dissect this movie as if it has a direct
reference to the world that we know today is absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bernardi said Hale's way of thinking is precisely the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Lucas to suggest there isn't even a race issue is silly,''
he said. ``For aliens to reach us (the audience) emotionally, they
have to be tied to Earth in order to make it meaningful and
grounded in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernardi said Lucas' camp is engaging in ``plausible
deniability,'' or rationalizations _ Jar Jar's ``just an alien'' or
``it's just a movie'' _ while overlooking racial problems that have
been replete in the ``Star Wars'' saga.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said Billy Dee Williams' character, Lando
Calrissian, the baron administrator of Bespin's Cloud City in ``The
Empire Strikes Back,'' was a pimplike gambler with eyes for
Princess Leia. In ``Phantom Menace,'' he says, the winged junk
dealer and sand-planet alien, Watto, the slaveholder of Anakin
Skywalker, has an unmistakable Middle Eastern voice, suggestive of
an Arab or a Jew. But Jar Jar, he says, takes the cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the whitewashing of the future of the universe. You have
the main characters, the Jedis, trying to save the day. ... Then
there is Jar Jar _ the Stepin Fetchit loyal sidekick,'' said
Bernardi, who has written the book ``Star Trek and History:
Race-ing Toward a White Future.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some people say Bernardi has too much time on his hands.
(And his views have gotten him dozens of angry calls and e-mails.)
But he fancies himself a pop-culture guardian, pointing out
dangerous currents presented in mass media. ``People should see a
need for scholars to tear apart and challenge pop culture,'' said
Bernardi, who loved ``Phantom Menace'' but thought the racial
issues were strong drawbacks. ``It is important because it affects
the way children and adults see themselves in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Jar Jar is banished, or ends up with the popularity of a
fluegelhorn-playing Barney the dinosaur, will play out in the court
of public opinion. Juries are deliberating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, I wish people would stop attacking Jar Jar so
viciously,'' one Web entry reads. ``I wasn't thrilled by him the
first time around ... but I've grown to like Jar Jar.''
</P>
<P>
   But another site asks, ``How about replacing Jar Jar with Adam
Sandler? or Carrot Top?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
