<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIAN-DOCS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE DOCTORS MAKE HOUSE CALLS, TO THE NEEDY IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUZANNE HOHOLIK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ Aurrora Pulido hopes the American doctors
can help her daughter walk.
</P>
<P>
   Aurrora Ornelas, 3, cries softly when her mother flips the child
onto her abdomen to show a visiting Texas doctor the girl's
deformed spine.
</P>
<P>
   A large bump protrudes from the toddler's back. Aurrora was born
with spina bifida, a birth defect in which the spine fails to close
properly during pregnancy's first month. In severe cases, the
spinal cord bulges through the back and may be covered by skin or a
thin membrane.
</P>
<P>
   Pulido asked the doctor if surgery in San Antonio would help
Aurrora, who's as small as a 10-month-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to do it now so when she gets older she can walk. Even
then she will have crutches,'' said Pulido, 27. ``She moves on her
knees and butt. She doesn't like to be sitting down, she wants to
walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ken Long of San Marcos listens to Pulido in the small
cramped kitchen of a home here.
</P>
<P>
   On this spring day he'll see about 100 patients, most of whom
have never been to a doctor. His reason for donating his time and
making the trip is simple: ``For the love of God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them have relatively minor problems, malnutrition or a
common cold,'' he said. ``Once or twice a year we see these extreme
problems where we can fix it or at least improve it with surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Long sits on a wooden chair facing patients across from him. To
his left lined up on the kitchen counter are small bags of
medications, vitamins, decongestants, ointments and bandages.
</P>
<P>
   After patients are assessed, most take the small plastic bags
full of pills and stuff them into their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   A young girl's mother complains that her daughter isn't eating
well, and Long tells the mother the teen is malnourished and hands
her a bag of vitamins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind I like. I know what it is and I know how to treat
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio Area Christian Medical and Dental Society
sponsors eight of these trips a year to northern Mexico border
cities. Long was one of 36 caregivers on this trip to neighborhoods
in Nuevo Laredo, a city of more than 200,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Society Director Roger Matkin said the group has made 75 trips
to Nuevo Laredo, Piedras Negras and Ciudad Acuna since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend trips are a marathon of sorts, with participants
hustling to set up makeshift clinics with crude exam rooms where
they provide basic medical and dental care.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, dentists and students donate their time and often their
own vehicles to travel to the border cities. Each person pays about
$35 for lodging, insurance and a lunch. Other meals or expenses
also come out of participants' pockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the perfect opportunity for doctors and dentists to
use their profession in serving the Lord,'' Matkin said. ``They can
actually heal people in a little way. It's the kind of thing
Christians in general ought to be doing _ caring for the poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, dentists and clinics are readily available throughout
Nuevo Laredo _ dentists every few blocks, medical clinics and a few
hospitals. But Matkin said the people living in the poor sections
of the city lack the means to pay for such care.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies _ including medications, vitamins and medical
instruments _ are donated by member doctors, dentists,
pharmaceutical companies and the University of Texas Health Science
Center at San Antonio, Matkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Morina Rios hasn't been to a dentist in 10 years, but on this
day the 15-year-old is sitting in a chair of this second-story
concrete apartment overlooking a patio where other patients wait.
The dentist is about to pull a tooth that's forced the crowding of
her lower teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great because some people without money can come here and
have our teeth cleaned and extracted,'' Rios said seconds before a
dentist yanked out the tooth.
</P>
<P>
   John Wallace, a fourth-year dental student at the Texas Health
Science Center, said giving up a Saturday for people with nothing
is ``all about providing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't provide everyone with the dental care we give in the
States, but coming out here is a different world and helps get your
priorities straight,'' he said. ``It's so different going home
after this; you really rethink your priorities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
