<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLERS-BORDER-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN ARE LATEST TOOLS IN IMMIGRANT SMUGGLING SCAMS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ Immigrant smugglers and their desperate
clients are now using rented infants to get into the country, say
Border Patrol officials who have documented the practice for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   One unusual case involved ``Baby Doe,'' a 6-month-old girl
rented three times to immigrants who then posed as a family and
avoided jail because there are no detention facilities for
children. That case shocked even veteran Border Patrol agents who
thought they had encountered every callous tactic used by
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the lucrative criminal organizations that
smuggle people across the border have amassed a horrific legacy.
They have locked their clients in car trunks, left them to die by
the scores in unventilated truck trailers and freight cars,
abandoned them without water in blistering heat, hid them amid
shipments of hazardous waste and led them into raging surf, where
they drowned.
</P>
<P>
   But using infants as living ``props'' has increased as intensive
border-control campaigns from here to California have made it
harder to slip across the U.S.-Mexico border, said U.S. Border
Patrol officials.
</P>
<P>
   To get their clients through, smugglers are now pairing up
unrelated men and women and providing them with an infant so they
appear to be a family. And because there are no facilities where
families can be detained together while awaiting immigration
hearings, these ``family units'' are routinely released by the
Border Patrol and allowed to continue their northward journey,
officials explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're resorting to this, and it's unfortunate the babies are
suffering,'' said Border Patrol agent John L. Trevino, who heads
the anti-smuggling unit in Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ``Baby Doe,'' the infant was rented by smugglers
who provided her to three different sets of clients who swam or
waded across the Rio Grande River with the child. The infant's real
parents, undocumented Honduran citizens living in Houston, have
admitted renting their baby for $200 per trip, Trevino said. They
are now in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``What these smugglers have done is caught on to the fact we are
a humanitarian society,'' explained Border Patrol Assistant Chief
Harry Beall of the McAllen, Texas, sector. ``We do care for the
welfare of the people we detain, and they are using that compassion
to circumvent the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Beall said smugglers are aware that undocumented adults who are
detained by themselves on the border will languish in detention
until they get a hearing. But those who can convince agents that
they are a family are instead given a notice to appear before an
immigration judge at a later date and then are released with travel
documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've caught on to this, and what they're doing is
furnishing babies for them to carry,'' Beall said of the smugglers.
``We've seen an increase in it. But as far as being able to prove
it, it's hard because these kids are of such a tender age we can't
ask (the children) questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The case of ``Baby Doe'' began to unravel on the late afternoon
of March 30 at the Brownsville Border Patrol station, as agent
Griselda Vidrio was helping other agents process a young ``family''
from Honduras. The man and woman _ both in their early 30s and
carrying a 6-month-old _ had earlier flagged down Border Patrol
agents along the Rio Grande in Brownsville and surrendered,
confident they would be released shortly after processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at the baby, she smiled at me, and I said, `I've seen
this baby before,''' said Vidrio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I informed the agent who was processing the couple that I
recognized the baby,'' Vidrio said. ``So I started asking the lady
whose baby it was, and she said it was hers. But I don't know,
there was something strange about it that made me keep on asking.''
</P>
<P>
   Vidrio also noticed the ``mother'' seemed unpracticed at holding
a baby and had brought only two diapers, one bottle of formula and
no extra clothes. The agent also recalled seeing the red, beaded
bracelet, strung with turquoise stones, that the baby was wearing
on her right wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had seen this baby before with someone else. I
remember a man coming in (with the baby for processing by Border
Patrol agents) where he said his wife had died during the Hurricane
Mitch'' disaster in Central America, Vidrio said.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Vidrio, the young woman admitted the child was not
hers, but claimed the baby had been given to her by a man she met
in Mexico. Eventually she admitted the child was provided by
smugglers whom she had paid $1,000 to get her to Houston. The
smugglers had given her instructions on how to return the infant
after the ``couple'' reached Houston by bus.
</P>
<P>
   Agents began to search through the files they kept on families
who had been processed and released in Brownsville, and found the
baby in pictures taken of two other ``families'' released earlier
in March.
</P>
<P>
   The little girl was processed as part of one ``family'' March
18, and then with another March 19, according to anti-smuggling
agent Richard A. Serra.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's pretty cold. ... This is the first time I've seen
a baby used this way,'' he said, adding that doctors who examined
the infant found she was suffering from a slight cold and the
beginning of an ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of shocks you, even though you get kind of callous ...
,'' Serra said.
</P>
<P>
   Border Patrol agents handed the infant over to state child
welfare workers in Brownsville, and went after the smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration agents placed a southwest Houston apartment under
surveillance after identifying it from the telephone number the
smugglers gave the couple to call when they arrived in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Posing as the clients, the agents called the apartment from the
bus station and told a woman who answered that they had arrived
with the baby. The woman said someone would meet them at the
station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Agents arrested Sandra Patricia Orellana, 29, as she left the
apartment. Investigators say she is the one who answered the phone.
They later arrested Jose Antonio Guerrero Funez, 34, of Honduras,
at the bus station after he met with the agents, Serra said.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero was indicted April 28 on charges of encouraging or
inducing immigrants to enter or remain in the United States, a
felony punishable by 10 years in prison and a maximum $250,000
fine, said assistant U.S. attorney Doug Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Charges against Orellana have been dismissed, Davis said.
Immigration and Naturalization Service officials in Houston say
deportation proceedings are under way.
</P>
<P>
   The man and woman who posed as a family with the baby are being
held as material witnesses. Serra said they identified Guerrero in
a photo lineup as the smuggler who gave them ``Baby Doe'' and
instructed them to pose as a married couple.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two Hondurans claiming to be the infant's parents
went to the Houston Police Department and reported their child
missing after the infant and the smuggling couple failed to show up
as expected.
</P>
<P>
   The parents are being detained after admitting they rented their
child for use in the smuggling operation, according to federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While this case is the only time immigration agents say they
have been able to document the use of infants by a smuggling
organization, it is not the first time young children have been
caught up in this desperate trade.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 3, a young couple from the state of Veracruz in Mexico
walked up to the information booth at the INS office at the Gateway
Bridge in Brownsville to report their daughter missing.
</P>
<P>
   The distraught couple told Delia Gantt, an INS information
officer, that they had hired smugglers the month before to take
their 15-month-old daughter across the Rio Grande while they
attempted the crossing on their own. The couple had been arrested
on the Texas side of the river and returned to Mexico, but had not
been able to make contact with the smugglers who had their baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell they were two young kids looking for their lost
baby. You could tell by the look on their faces,'' said Gantt, who
said the mother was 17 and the father 24.
</P>
<P>
   Houston police had located the toddler in a motel room with
dozens of other undocumented immigrants, INS spokesman Art Moreno
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only luck that kept the toddler from being sold on the
black market or pressed into service by smugglers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the smuggler would have done with that child
... because smugglers have absolutely no moral ethics, nor do they
have any regard for human life,'' he said. ``I'm sorry to sound so
hard, but I've seen what they can do. I've seen the death they've
caused.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 8, state child welfare officials flew the child to
Brownsville and turned her over to her parents at the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked when they told me how old the little girl was
and that this had happened to her,'' Gantt recalled. ``Since she
was so little, we figured once she was lost, they would never be
able to find her. That's why we took action right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Last July, Esmeralda Ordonez, 24, a Houston woman from Honduras,
pleaded for help from federal officials after smugglers refused to
release her two children until she paid an additional $3,500 _ on
top of $7,000 she and her fiance had already paid _ to smuggle the
children from Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Her 2-year-old son, Juan Angel, and 6-year-old daughter,
Vanelisa Maradiaga, had been passed off as the children of other
adults in a group that was smuggled across the Rio Grande. The girl
was found after a raid on a downtown Brownsville hotel. The boy was
dropped off days later outside an apartment complex at 2 a.m. with
his mother's Houston phone number pinned to his shirt, said the
Border Patrol agents who found them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``Baby Doe'' case is far from being over. INS investigators
must prepare a criminal case against the alleged smugglers while
preparing to deport the infant's parents to Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Child Protective Services is trying to verify that the
couple claiming to be the baby's parents are, in fact, her parents.
They will have to produce birth records and submit to DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Once that's done, the agency has to decide what is best for the
child. &UR;  &LR; Lois Shull, director of community development for CPS in
Edinburg, said the agency has the authority to terminate the
parental rights of parents of an abused or neglected child,
regardless of immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still do have the child in foster care and, at this point,
we are not looking at terminating parental rights. It's too early
in the process to consider that,'' she said. Shull also confirmed
that ``Baby Doe'' has relatives in Texas who are here legally.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Border Patrol officials expect smugglers to
continue to come up with new techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can think of a way to smuggle drugs, parrots or people,
it's probably already in use somewhere because these are very
innovative people who are always looking for ways to beat the
system,'' Beall said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
