<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9788 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     06-02 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGHNUT LOVERS' DELIVERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Some people might wonder why more than 100 doughnut
nuts showed up at 5:30 a.m. Tuesday for the grand opening of a
Krispy Kreme shop at the Arizona Mills mall.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wonder are the ones who have never tasted a Krispy
Kreme doughnut.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep? You can do without sleep. You can't do without Krispy
Kreme doughnuts. Cold, they're little glazed and doughy wheels of
heaven. Hot, you may as well just lay down and die after you eat
one because your life is never going to get any better.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, they're Southern.
</P>
<P>
   If you've ever lived in the South _ make that the Great American
South, so that we can establish the point of view here _ you're
familiar with Krispy Kreme shops. They're as ubiquitous below the
Mason-Dixon line as Circle K stores in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   (Full disclosure: Not everyone who lives down South likes Krispy
Kreme. Two friends once debated the point _ the debate took place,
naturally, over pulled pork at a barbecue joint. One was a Dunkin'
Donuts man. Krispy Kremes are (begin ital) soooo (end ital) tasty,
the other guy said. ``Yeah,'' the first replied, ``if you like your
food dripping in hot fat.'' It should be noted that he was a
transplanted Yankee.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sign of greatness &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The spreading west of Krispy Kreme is a hopeful sign to those of
us of the Southern persuasion. For far too long we have been
derided as extras in ``Deliverance,'' ignorant sons of the soil who
marry their cousins and have bad teeth.
</P>
<P>
   What teeth we have.
</P>
<P>
   Enough. The South is no longer just bad grammar and gimme caps,
car races and corn squeezin's. There are plenty of great things
about the South, things as important as Krispy Kreme doughnuts _
things that, with any luck at all, will find their way west soon.
</P>
<P>
   Slaw on hot dogs, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   With so many transplanted Midwesterners here, the Chicago hot
dog is the dog of choice in the Valley of the Sun. And it is a
beautiful thing, especially when loaded down with sport peppers.
</P>
<P>
   But don't sell short the slaw dog until you've tried one. The
mayonnaisey flavor mixes with chili perfectly. Add onions, mustard
and ketchup, and you've got the makings of the best stomachache
you've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Or how about porches? (begin ital) Front (end ital) porches?
</P>
<P>
   True, it's so hot here from May to October that our only outside
activity is slathering on copious amounts of sunscreen for mad
dashes between the car and the office. Spend more than 10 minutes
napping in a porch hammock and you'd be drenched in sweat, your
skin the consistency of beef jerky.
</P>
<P>
   So what? It's worth it. A front porch is so relaxing, so
tranquil. And so perfect a place for storing old car seats and
washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry, the neighbors'll get used to it. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Acquired tastes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of acquired tastes, don't forget buttermilk. Your
classic Southerner drinks it like water. Like gloppy yellowish
water as thick as pancake batter, but that's part of its charm.
</P>
<P>
   It also goes well with vegetables that have been cooked with ham
hocks until they are as limp as soggy tissue, another Southern
staple. Probably has something to do with that bad teeth-thing.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of other worthy candidates for migration _ Moon
Pies, pork rinds, peanuts in Co-colas.
</P>
<P>
   But the best thing we could import from our Southern friends is
a big dose of hospitality.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Phoenix is a friendly place, especially for a big
city. People don't scream at each other in delis. Strangers nod on
the street and, occasionally, even say hello.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, they don't just say hello. They say, ``Hey, how
you? You look like you're hungry _ would you like to come on home
and get something to eat? You're skin and bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, if you're not used to this kind of treatment, it's a
little creepy at first. But don't worry. It'll grow on you.
</P>
<P>
   Like kudzu. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
