<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS (Washington) _ A special report: Miguel
Sanchez was just 1 day old when he was killed by a prescription
drug. In death, he joined a population that is causing increasing
anxiety among health care experts and federal regulators: the tens
of thousands of Americans who lose their lives each year not to
illness, but to medication intended to treat it. Food and Drug
Administration officials, as well as independent drug safety
experts, say a flood of new and ever more complicated medications
are overwhelming the nation's health care system, making it
increasingly difficult for pharmacists, doctors and hospitals to
protect patients from being killed or harmed by adverse reactions
or mistakes. By Cheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY (Berlin) _ Possible ledeall: Russian envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin and Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, the
European Union's envoy, head to Belgrade on Wednesday with a
proposal for Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Russian foreign minister meets top
Chinese officials who say bombing must stop, and talk about a
partnership for a multipolar world instead of the unipolar one that
they accuse the United States of trying to create. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-AHTISAARI (Undated) _ Man in the News on President Martti
Ahtisaari of Finland. By Warren Hoge.
