<P>
   MEDICARE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The head of a federal advisory
commission urges Congress to relax stringent limits on Medicare
payments for certain nursing home and hospital services _ saying,
in effect, that the '97 budget law cut too deep. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-SPARROW (Everglades National Park, Fla.) _ Scientists
say the plight of the threatened Cape Sable Seaside Sparrow
reflects the failing health of the Everglades ecosystem. Congress,
in July, takes up a $7.8 billion engineering plan to restore the
swamplands to ecological health, and some environmentalists and
wildlife officials say the sparrow is the test of whether the plan
can succeed. The controversy reflects how politically complicated
and interconnected the problems in the Everglades are, and how
difficult any solution will be. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-SWEARING (Standish, Mich.) _ If Timothy Boomer could
keep his balance better in a boat and Charles Fabry could keep his
temper, an obscure Michigan law against swearing in front of women
and children would not be tested now. But Boomer fell into a river
last August and Fabry got mad at a business customer in April, and
the legal fallout from both incidents has now produced a struggle
over free speech and communities' ability to limit offensive
language. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   PLANE-CRASH (Little Rock, Ark.) _ An American Airlines flight
with 145 people aboard skidded off a runway while landing during a
hail storm, broke apart and burst into flames. Sources familiar
with the investigation said nine people were known to have been
killed. (Summary from wires.) By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   ALABAMA-IMMIGRANTS (Huntsville, Ala.) _ In a sign of clashing
cultures in an area of the South that has seen an influx of
immigrants, the county tax assessor in Huntsville, Ala., is being
sued because he refused to give homestead exemption to people who
didn't speak English, even if they used an interpreter. The suit,
in state court, was filed by a Korean widow and a Dominican couple.
By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-CONNERLY (Miami) _ Ward Connerly, the man who campaigned
successfully to end affirmative action in government hiring and
school admissions in California and Washington state, has now aimed
his crusade at Florida, to the sound of slamming doors. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS-SETTLEMENT (Arlington, Va.) _ The Teamsters union and
companies that haul new cars to dealerships nationwide said
Wednesday that they have reached a tentative settlement in a labor
contract dispute. And the settlement says a lot about the
leadership of Teamsters President James Hoffa. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Closing statements in police
brutality case. By Joseph Fried.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (New York) _ The first lady delivers the
commencement address at City College. By Adam Nagourney.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   AUTOMAKERS-EXPANSION (St. Louis) _ Five years of strong sales
have led auto makers to announce plans to invest stunning amounts
of money in existing factories or to build new ones from the ground
up. While the investments are in large part a bet that the economy
_ and vehicle sales _ will continue to grow steadily, auto makers
are expanding for different reasons. By Robyn Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ General Motors, Ford Motor and
DaimlerChrysler are expected to report sales for May. By Robyn
Meredith.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN (Dateline to come) _ As Alan Greenspan speaks at a
conference sponsored by a think tank that promotes international
trade, investors will be listening intently for any signal that the
Fed may raise interest rates at its next meeting at the end of
June. By Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   EURO (Frankfurt) _ A look at the sluggish economies of Europe
and inaction by the European Central Bank as the euro falls to new
lows against the dollar and the pound. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-TAKEOVER-FIGHT (Tokyo) _ The tug-of-war between Cable and
Wireless of Britain and NTT over IDC, the first takeover fight
pitting a Japanese company against a foreign one, has been cast as
a test case of Japan's willingness to open one of the few
relatively strong sectors of its economy to foreigners. But it is
increasingly clear that accommodating Japanese corporate culture
will take precedence over price in determining the winner. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTLAND-ROBERTSON (London) _ Bank of Scotland says it is
reviewing its joint venture with Pat Robertson after Robertson
describes Scotland as a ``dark land'' and a stronghold of
homosexuality. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-ALTERNATIVES (Undated) _ A New England Journal of
Medicine study found that women diagnosed with breast cancer who
choose alternative medical therapies experienced more depression,
anxiety and intense physical symptoms than did those not using
alternative therapies.
</P>
