<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-ATHEIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY IN CASE OF MISSING ATHEIST READS LIKE THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ If it had been created by a Hollywood screen
writer, the creepy story might have ended up as drive-in fare, the
perfect double bill with ``The Texas Chainsaw Massacre.''
</P>
<P>
   It has all the B-movie elements, but the document that became
public here last week was not created as a work of pulp fiction.
Rather, it was the result of the federal government's investigation
into the disappearance in September 1995 of famed atheist Madalyn
Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-page affidavit of an Internal Revenue Service agent was
unsealed last week, leaving little room for optimism that O'Hair
and her two adult children will return.
</P>
<P>
   The document implicates O'Hair's former office manager, David R.
Waters, 52, of Austin; an ex-convict from the Detroit area named
Gary Karr, 50; and a heavy-drinking man from Florida named Danny
Fry, who was killed shortly after the O'Hairs vanished from San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waters, Karr and Fry planned and executed the scheme to
abduct, kidnap and murder Madalyn Murray O'Hair, Jon Garth Murray
and Robin Murray O'Hair for the purpose of stealing at least
$600,000,'' the affidavit states.
</P>
<P>
   Later it adds, ``Waters and Karr turned on Fry and killed him.
They then dumped the beheaded and handless body of Fry in Dallas
County, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   What began as an IRS money-laundering case two years ago has
become a multi-agency investigation of four homicides involving
</P>
<P>
   And according to the affidavit, revenge as well as greed led to
the abduction and apparent murder of O'Hair, John Garth Murray and
Robin Murray O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waters was open about his dislike of the O'Hairs and made
comments about harming Madalyn. Waters began obsessing about his
ability to take Madalyn's money without her knowledge,'' says a
confidential source quoted in the affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hair gained prominence in the 1960s for her successful court
battles to eliminate organized prayer in public schools. She went
on to lead a national atheist organization.
</P>
<P>
   According to O'Hair's surviving son Bill Murray, the violent,
ugly end that his mother apparently met was consistent with the
life she led.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her fate came as no surprise to me or anyone who actually
understood how bizarre and dysfunctional this family actually
was,'' said Murray, who renounced atheism for fundamentalist
Christianity nearly 20 years ago and lives in Fredericksburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``She led a very brutal life _ a life of constant aggression and
attempts to control,'' he said. ``It was the kind of life that
makes these kinds of enemies. She offended people to the point of
them wanting to kill her. My only surprise is that more people
didn't die with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fry is dead and Waters and Karr are behind bars on
federal weapons charges, no one has been charged with any crime
relating to the disappearance of the O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   The federal affidavit, however, advances a case made first in
newspaper stories over the past year that the three men were
responsible for the disappearance of America's most famous atheist
and her children.
</P>
<P>
   And the affidavit goes far beyond anything before made public to
fill in the many spaces in the story of the O'Hairs' last days.
</P>
<P>
   Using records from public storage facilities in Austin, van
rental companies, and hotel registers, federal investigators
produced an affidavit that tracks the movements of the O'Hair
family and the alleged abductors.
</P>
<P>
   Records there show Karr and Waters rented a room at the Warren
Inn in northwest San Antonio in late 1995, and a maintenance man
recalls seeing a woman who met Madalyn's description there at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit also makes good use of confidential sources to
report Waters' movements and thoughts before, during and after the
fateful month of September 1995.
</P>
<P>
   It shows a man who once worked for O'Hair who was consumed by
thoughts of revenge to the point of ``snipping off her toes.''
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit also offers clues to the two big unanswered
questions: What became of the $500,000 in gold coins that vanished
with the O'Hairs, and what became of the O'Hairs?
</P>
<P>
   According to one federal informant, Waters put the suitcase full
of coins in a storage unit in Austin but later claimed they
disappeared after a break-in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Waters said Fry stole the coins. Later Waters stated that
Fry's son stole the gold and still later, Waters stated that the
coin dealer stole the coins,'' the informant told federal officers.
</P>
<P>
   The other missing piece of the puzzle is what became of the
O'Hairs' bodies, assuming, as the government says, they were
murdered, possibly dismembered and stuffed into blue plastic
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   So far the FBI as been unable to find any remains, complicating
the case against Waters and Karr.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit offers only scant clues as to where the bodies
could be.
</P>
<P>
   According to another confidential source, Karr talked about the
O'Hair murders but claimed they were killed because of a card game.
According to this person, Karr said Waters killed the four people
and ``buried them in a field in Texas near a subdivision.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials, apparently acting on a tip from Karr, twice
searched a ranch in Real County, northwest of San Antonio, but they
came away empty-handed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
