<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LBJ-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LBJ HOME ALLOWS VISITORS TO EXPERIENCE WHAT SHAPED LIFE OF THE LATE
PRESIDENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSON CITY, Texas _ Driving across the Texas Hill Country, you
can sense the forces that shaped Lyndon Baines Johnson. Life
started and ended here for him, among the rock-strewn ranches and
sturdy German-heritage towns.
</P>
<P>
   LBJ's career thrived on Capitol Hill, but the 36th president of
the United States often returned to his ranch near Johnson City and
Stonewall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something different about this country from any other
part of the nation,'' he once said. ``The climate is generally
pleasant; the sun is generally bright; the air seems to be always
clean; and the water is pure. The moons are a little fuller here;
the stars are a little brighter.''
</P>
<P>
   LBJ has been gone for 26 years, but this native son left large,
lasting imprints for those who want to follow in his footsteps over
some of Texas' prettiest ranch land.
</P>
<P>
   Take the first step at the Lyndon B. Johnson National Historical
Park in Johnson City, located about 48 miles west of Austin. For
the record, the city was named not for LBJ, but for a cousin and
town builder, James Polk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 130,000 annual visitors start at the LBJ Boyhood
Home, one block north of the park's visitors center. Built in 1901,
this was Johnson's home until his marriage to Claudia Alta Taylor
(now known all over the world as Lady Bird) at age 26. The restored
house includes furnishings of the 1920s. Free daily tours are given
every 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors center features free exhibits and films about the
Johnsons' lives. If time permits, take a 10-minute stroll on a
nature trail to the Johnson Settlement, where programs focus on
Texas frontier life. Several historical structures include the
dog-trot cabin purchased by LBJ's grandfather, Samuel Ealy Johnson,
for his bride in 1867.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider the National Park Service's 75-minute bus tour of
Johnson's ranch along the crystal-clear Pedernales River.
</P>
<P>
   The journey begins with a quick look at the one-room Junction
School, where the former president learned to read at age 4. The
next stop is his reconstructed birthplace, and visitors can tour
the house he rebuilt as a guest cottage in 1964. Johnson delighted
in telling visitors that the only original piece of furniture in
the place was the beat-up-looking rawhide-bottom chair in the
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Across the road is the oak-flanked Johnson Family Cemetery where
LBJ was buried Jan. 25, 1973. Johnson died after suffering a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   The bus also visits his paternal grandparents' farmhouse, where
Johnson used to pick apples. It then makes a quick stop at the
century-old rock LBJ Ranch House, where Lady Bird still resides.
Also referred to as the Texas White House, it remains under Secret
Service protection. The final stop is the Show Barn, where visitors
can get a taste of life on a working ranch and see LBJ's
prize-winning Hereford cattle.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the former president's early years, trace
his rise to political power at the Lyndon B. Johnson Library on the
University of Texas campus in Austin. Operated by the National
Archives and Records Service of the General Services
Administration, this facility serves both as a center for scholarly
research and a historical museum.
</P>
<P>
   Three floors house LBJ-related exhibits, showcasing his tenure
as president. Other highlights include the First Lady's Gallery and
the 1968 Lincoln Continental presidential limousine. A must-see is
the animatronic display of LBJ, which spouts recordings of humorous
observations by the late president on politics, education and life
in general.
</P>
<P>
   The LBJ Library, 2313 Red River St., is open 9 a.m.-5 p.m.
daily, except Christmas Day. Admission is free. For information,
call 512-916-5137.
</P>
<P>
   Cost for the LBJ Ranch bus tour is $3 for ages 7 and older. For
information, call the LBJ National Historical Park at 830-868-7128.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
