<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV20-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 20, 1999. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: We have two overhead lights in the ceiling of our basement
stairway. Each has a bare bulb in the socket and while carry a
large box up the stairs I accidentally broke both these bulbs,
leaving only a few shards of glass and the base of the bulb still
in the socket. As a result I can't really get a grip on the bulb to
unscrew what is left. Is there anything you can suggest to solve
this problem, or must I have an electrician come in to replace the
sockets?
</P>
<P>
   A: One trick that usually works in such cases is to cut off the
end of a large raw potato. Shut off the power to the fixtures and
while wearing a heavy work glove push the cut end of the potato
into the shattered remains of the bulb. This will give you a grip
that will make it possible to turn the bulb's base out of its
socket safely. Incidentally, you can use a bar of soap instead of a
potato, but you can usually get a firmer grip on a potato.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About one year ago I attached a deflated balloon to my wall
with tape. I took the balloon off recently but found that ink from
the balloon had stained the paint on the wall. I tried painting
over this a couple of times, but the ink still shows through. How
can I get this ink off the wall?
</P>
<P>
   A: Since you have painted over it several times, removing the
ink stain would require removing all the paint on that area by
using a chemical paint remover. This will also remove the ink
stain. However, this may not be necessary. You can cover the stain
with a stain-killing sealer such as Kilz, B-I-N or similar product,
then paint over this in the usual manner. These sealers will keep
the stain from ``bleeding through'' any paint that is applied over
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of my basement windows is below ground level and there is
a well on the outside to keep the soil away. In a heavy rain water
accumulates in the bottom of this well and tends to seep under the
window and into the basement. Can I solve this problem by digging
out the bottom of the window well and filling it with gravel?
</P>
<P>
   A: It definitely would help, but you should dig down at least
10-12 inches before filling with gravel. However, if the soil
drainage below this depth is not good this may not completely solve
the problem. You may have to dig a deep ditch leading away from the
well and then lay underground drain tile (perforated plastic pipe)
to carry the water at least 10 feet away from the bottom of the
window well, preferably ending in a dry well (sump) that will
absorb or hold the water until is can seep into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The concrete basement floor of my new house is only 4 feet
below ground level and the walls consist of concrete blocks set on
the same footing as this slab. I have a problem with water leaking
into the basement. Do you think the water could be seeping in under
the footings?
</P>
<P>
   A: Without knowing where the water is actually coming in _
through the floor or through the walls _ it is impossible to
diagnose the source of your leak. The basement should not leak if
it was properly built and if the ground around the outside has been
properly graded so it slopes away from the house on all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``REMOVING BROKEN LIGHT BULB FROM
SOCKET'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: A raw potato pushed into remains of broken bulb makes
it easy to unscrew remainder of bulb. (Remember to shut off power
first.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Bernard Gladstone &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
