<HEADLINE>
COMFORT: A TOWN APPROPRIATELY NAMED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photo available on NYT database) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMFORT, Texas _ Everett Pauls' mind had drifted into the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking pretty comfortable there,'' a passer-by
commented.
</P>
<P>
   The words took a second to sink in. ``Well, sure, what do you
expect? I'm in Comfort,'' Pauls replied.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort, Texas, that is _ a town that seems frozen in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This road hasn't changed,'' Pauls murmured, almost to himself.
``This building hasn't changed, and the building next to it hasn't
changed. It looks pretty much the same. Yes, it does.''
</P>
<P>
   He should know. The 82-year-old Dickinson resident spent many
summers here with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time was when I was 2. We would come up here to swim
in the Guadalupe River when things got too hot in Galveston. They
didn't have air conditioning in those days,'' said Pauls, as he sat
in a rocking chair on the porch of the Comfort Common Bed and
Breakfast and Antiques.
</P>
<P>
   Change doesn't come easily in Comfort. But folks here like it
that way.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort is no bustling Fredericksburg, situated 30 minutes to
the north. There is still a quiet, quirky charm about this small
provincial town, settled in 1845 by radical German ``free
thinkers'' fleeing from political and religious persecution.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors often wonder how the town got its name. Nobody knows
for sure, but the unofficial version is that the early settlers
wanted to call it ``Gemutlichkeit,'' which connotes tranquility,
serenity, peace and happiness. It wasn't the easiest word to
pronounce, or to remember, for that matter, so folks opted instead
for the American equivalent: Comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Today, people come to leisurely browse through the antiques
shops and art galleries on High Street.
</P>
<P>
   Another lure is the 100 turn-of-the-century buildings within
walking distance of the town center. Listed on the National
Register of Historic Places, Comfort has one of Texas' most
complete 19th-century business districts. For those interested in
retracing area history, the Comfort Historical Museum at 838 High
St. houses considerable memorabilia from early German settlers. But
it's only open by appointment or when owner Roy Perkins Jr. is in
the mood.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, stroll over to the ``Treue der Union'' monument, a
Civil War memorial to townspeople who were killed by Confederate
soldiers for being Union sympathizers in the Battle of the Nueces
and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   Another landmark, the Ingenhuett Store, has been continuously
operated by the same family for more than 130 years. It's where
old-timers congregate to catch up on the news.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to the Chamber of Commerce at P.O.
Box 77, Comfort, Texas 78013, or call 830-995-3131.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
