<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAUNTING FACES OF DIPLOMACY'S VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Since I heard it on National Public Radio, I've
been unable to get the concept out of my mind.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on the debacle in Kosovo and Serbia, an international
correspondent said that diplomats on all sides of the conflict were
working behind the scenes ``to find a resolution that will allow
both Mr. Milosevic and Mr. Clinton to save face.''
</P>
<P>
   Save face. SAVE FACE?
</P>
<P>
   I have so many faces before me, I can't keep the faces of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and President Clinton in
focus, let alone grasp the value of saving them.
</P>
<P>
   What I can see are countless photographs and video segments of
ethnic Albanian Kosovars, weeping, keening or just staring into
space with a hopelessness and a desolation that belong in the
lowest ring of Hell.
</P>
<P>
   I see refugee children, filthy and sick from too many days and
nights on the run or trapped in inhumanely overcrowded camps.
</P>
<P>
   I see their mothers, physically and emotionally exhausted beyond
anything Milosevic and Clinton have ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs aren't necessary for me to see thousands of young
Kosovar women who were wrenched from their families ``because
they're pretty'' and imprisoned by Yugoslavian soldiers to be raped
and humiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Although Milosevic obviously does not care about them and
Clinton considers them but ``collateral damage,'' I see new-born
Serbian babies and women in delivery in a maternity ward at a
Belgrade hospital that was accidentally bombed by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   I see terrified mental patients in another facility that was hit
and dozens of people with kidney disease who can no longer receive
dialysis because so many Belgrade power stations have been
destroyed and electricity is scarce.
</P>
<P>
   I see 27 dead journalists, including a 60-year-old veteran
program director named Tomislav Mitrovic, at NATO-obliterated Radio
Television Serbia in Belgrade. I see a 52-year-old Kosovo-born
Chicago man named Muhamet Bajrahtar, shot dead near his second home
in Glogovce by the Serbian police; his pocket held U.S. immigration
permits for his wife and daughters.
</P>
<P>
   I can't count the number of terrified ethnic Albanians from
Kosovo I see marching over bridges and open roads for use as
``human shields.'' Nor can I estimate how many Serbian children I
see, now living without power, water and sufficient supplies of
fresh food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more than any face, I see that of a young mother described
by my friend Bernie Ward, a reporter at KGO radio in San Francisco
who spent several weeks in refugee camps on the Kosovo-Macedonia
border.
</P>
<P>
   One of thousands of fleeing ethnic Albanians, the woman was with
her new-born and toddler in the squalor of a camp nicknamed ``The
Valley of Death'' by refugees. The Macedonians, eager to get the
sea of humanity out of their country, began herding people onto
buses for transfer.
</P>
<P>
   As the young mother prepared to board a bus, an old woman in
front of her stumbled and fell. The younger woman reached down to
help, instinctively letting go of her toddler's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few seconds elapsed, but the little boy moved away from
the bus. The terrified mother screamed for him and tried to run to
him, but the Macedonian police shoved her up the stairs. The door
was slammed shut and the bus pulled away.
</P>
<P>
   Save FACE, Mr. Milosevic and Mr. Clinton? How, in God's name,
can either of you stand to look at your own in a mirror?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
