<HEADER>
A9833 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-TAKE     06-02 1553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS03-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDS: In two takes _ take 1)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at
</P>
<P>
   q&AMP;a(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article about Helen Suzman described her as a member of
Parliament in South Africa who for 36 years was the only one who
voted against apartheid and other repressive laws. How did she
manage to get re-elected over and over again?
</P>
<P>
   A: Suzman served as the liberal representative from Houghton, a
silk-stocking district in northern Johannesburg, from her first
election in 1953 until her retirement in 1989. For 13 of those
years, the South African-born daughter of Jewish immigrants from
Lithuania was the only opposition member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   She credited her ability to hold onto her seat for so long to
the people she represented, whom she called ``exceptional,
intelligent, traveled.'' Many of them were Jewish like herself,
with an ingrained aversion to racism.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers during her turbulent decades in South
African politics, however, said it was more than that, crediting
her uncompromising integrity and singleness of purpose. In 1989,
when she announced that she wouldn't run again, even her political
opponents joined the line of parliamentarians who paid tribute to
her.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Short-wave radio reports indicated that at least 21 Americans
have been killed in the fighting in Yugoslavia. Can you confirm? Of
that number, how many were military, and how many civilian?
</P>
<P>
   A: As of May 28, no U.S. or NATO forces have died in combat,
said Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col. Steve Campbell. Two U.S. pilots
were killed May 5 in an Apache helicopter training accident in
Albania, but they aren't considered combat casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said NATO has reported the ``possibility'' that
American civilians have been killed in its bombing campaign, but he
added that there has been no confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend told me she had heard about a lawsuit in the Claus
Von Bulow case that would force him to pay damages to the family of
his wife, Sunny. He had been accused of trying to kill her with
insulin some years back. Can you shed any light on this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It isn't something that happened recently. In 1985, after a
previous conviction on the attempted murder charge was overturned,
Von Bulow was acquitted of trying to kill Martha ``Sunny'' von
Bulow.
</P>
<P>
   Her adult children by a previous marriage then filed a $56
million civil lawsuit against him that was settled out of court in
1987 after Von Bulow agreed, among other things, to renounce his
claims to his wife's fortune and to divorce the heiress, who was
left comatose. Defense attorneys argued that the woman brought on
the comas herself by drug and alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Michael Armstrong, who represented the stepchildren,
said later: ``The purpose for the Von Bulow suit was to get Claus
out of the lives of the family. When he agreed to do that, there
was no longer any purpose in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is Ted Turner's military background?
</P>
<P>
   A: The CNN founder served six months of active duty in the Coast
Guard, according to Current Biography.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Many of us who are size-conscious find inspiration in Richard
Simmons. Can you give us some background information about him?
Where can fans write to him?
</P>
<P>
   A: The physical fitness specialist and TV personality was born
in New Orleans in 1948 as Milton Teagle Simmons. In his
introduction to the best-selling ``Richard Simmons'
Never-Say-Diet,'' he wrote that when he was a child he thought his
parents favored his older brother, Lenny. So he turned to food for
comfort and, in his own words, became addicted.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 or 11 he renamed himself Richard. By the time he was 15,
his love of food was evident as his weight approached 200 pounds.
He attended Southern Louisiana University and Florida State
University before heading to Italy, where he peaked at 268 pounds.
When someone left a note on his Fiat saying ``Fat people die
young,'' Simmons says he was was jolted into determination,
shedding 112 pounds in less than three months.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971 he returned to the United States, eventually opening a
restaurant and adjacent exercise studio in Beverly Hills, Calif. TV
producers attracted by his antics made him a staple on talk shows
and he eventually got his own program. Books, audiotapes,
videotapes and shopping center appearances furthered his celebrity
status.
</P>
<P>
   Write him in care of Anatomy Asylum, 9306 Santa Monica Blvd.,
Beverly Hills, CA 90210.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it possible for Americans to adopt orphans from Kosovo? If
so, what is the procedure?
</P>
<P>
   A: While the State Department says it shares humanitarian
concerns for the children of Kosovo, and applauds people's desire
to help them, it also says adoption isn't feasible. In a formal
statement on the issue, this is what the department says: ``In
general, adopts are private legal civil matters governed by the
laws of the nation where the child lives. The process involves
complex foreign and U.S. legal requirements. The laws in the former
Yugoslavia (Serbia/Montenegro) give priority to their own citizens
and make adoptions by foreigners very difficult. In a crisis
situation . . . it can be extremely difficult to determine if
children whose parents are missing are truly orphans. . . . Even
when children have been truly orphaned or abandoned by their
parents, they are often taken in by other relatives. Staying with
relatives in extended family units is generally a better solution
than uprooting the child completely.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: TV game show host Bob Barker was presented with a lifetime
achievement award at the recent Daytime Emmy Awards. Can you tell
us about his background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Robert William Barker was born Dec. 12, 1923, in Darrington,
Wash. He served in the Navy in 1943-45, and in 1947 graduated summa
cum laude from Drury College in Springfield, Mo., with a major in
economics. While at Drury, Barker worked for radio station KTTS in
Springfield. After a stint with a radio station in Palm Beach,
Fla., he moved to Los Angeles, where he hosted ``The Bob Barker
Show'' for radio station KWIK in Burbank.
</P>
<P>
   You know the rest: ``Truth or Consequences,'' ``The Family
Game,'' ``The Price Is Right,'' various beauty pageants, hosting
the Pillsbury Bake-Off and ``The Bob Barker Fun and Games Show,''
among many others. Before his recent recognition for lifetime
achievement, Barker had received at least a dozen Daytime Emmys,
starting in 1981-82. His wife, Dorothy Jo, whom he married in 1945,
died in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several articles about the Kosovo conflict have mentioned the
War Powers Act. What is that?
</P>
<P>
   A: The War Powers Act is a law passed by Congress in 1973 as a
result of actions taken by Presidents Lyndon Johnson and Richard
Nixon during the Vietnam War. It was designed to balance military
powers of the president, as commander in chief, and Congress, which
has the power to declare war.
</P>
<P>
   According to Section 4 (a) (1) of the resolution, the president
must inform Congress within 48 hours if U.S. forces are sent into a
hostile area without a declaration of war. In addition, those
forces may remain no longer than 90 days unless Congress approves
the president's action or declares war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what initially was considered a successful attempt to
involve Congress more meaningfully in war-making, the resolution
has been the subject of much criticism and debate. Some critics
argue that it attempts improperly to tie the president's hands,
while others view it as an invitation for the president to conduct
war freely within a specified period of time. Even if taken at face
value, the resolution contains loopholes. It states, for example,
that ``Nothing in this joint resolution . . . is intended to alter
the constitutional authority of the president.'' Also, there's no
mechanism to force the president to comply with the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does Evander Holyfield have a fan club? If so, what is the
address?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, the heavyweight boxing champion has a fan club. For
information, write: Holyfield Management, 794 Evander Holyfield
Highway, Fairburn, GA 30213.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A friend and I are debating the value of those popular green
and orange sports drinks. Are they really better than water?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unlike water, sports drinks provide sodium, which is lost in
perspiration, as well as carbohydrates. These ingredients also are
said to speed fluid absorption from the stomach into the
bloodstream, making dehydration less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some people think the drinks are no better than water
for most active people, who don't exercise long enough or hard
enough to reap the benefits of rapid hydration that the drinks
provide. People who consume water before, during and after exercise
don't come close to approaching dehydration, these experts contend.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor: Every quart of a sports drink contains 250
calories, so if you're exercising to lose weight, you need to burn
off well over 250 calories to create a caloric deficit.
</P>
<P>
   End Take 1
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
