<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9863 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-HILL-COUNTRY-A     06-02 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HILL-COUNTRY-ART-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM HOSPITALITY, COOL TEMPERATURES HELP VACATIONERS SAVOR TEXAS
HILL COUNTRY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Photos available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Also see: Travel LBJ and Travel-Comfort) 
 
By DAI HUYNH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREDERICKSBURG, Texas _ Peeking through the heavy morning mists,
the rolling hills seem like humpbacked dinosaurs rising from
slumber.
</P>
<P>
   As the sun washes over this land _ stitched together by green
valleys, glistening rivers, stately oak trees, limestone bluffs,
and pastoral villages and towns _ the enchantment of the Hill
Country takes hold.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, this region of Texas appears peaceful _ its
quiet beauty fashioned long ago by the elements.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the Hill Country is just a large, dissected
plateau, formed when thick layers of limestone and other
sedimentary rocks were deposited at the bottom of the ocean
millions of years ago. Many more millennia passed before a large
section was lifted to about 2,000 feet along the Balcones
Escarpment, a curving fault that stretches from Austin to San
Antonio to the Del Rio area. The rock layers were then raised,
forming relatively high, flat surfaces. Erosion did the rest,
carving the uplifted areas into the hilly, rocky terrain that makes
up the eastern and southern boundaries. The relatively undissected
Edwards Plateau defines the western region, and rolling plains and
prairies dominate the northern region.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rugged terrain and thin soil make the Hill Country
difficult to farm, more wildflowers bloom here in the spring than
in any other part of the state. And Mother Nature attracts droves
of vacationers _ even those with only a weekend to spare _ who seek
a romantic getaway against a technicolor backdrop. They congregate
in Fredericksburg, New Braunfels, Austin, Bandera, Georgetown,
Boerne, Kerrville, Wimberley, Blanco, Comfort, Mason or in more
secluded parts of the 25 Hill Country counties.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its scenic beauty and cooling temperatures, the Hill
Country is defined by the hospitality of its residents, a rich
German heritage and enough recreational pursuits to satisfy almost
any interest and age group, ranging from horseback riding and
golfing in Bandera to river-tubing and kayaking on the Guadalupe
River in New Braunfels.
</P>
<P>
   So where to begin? For now, point your travel compass westward
toward Fredericksburg in Gillespie County.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WELCOME TO FREDERICKSBURG &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Willkommen!
</P>
<P>
   This German salutation is posted all along roadways leading to
Fredericksburg. In a town driven by tourists, making people feel
welcome from start to finish is paramount. Once a secret hideaway
for Texans in the know, Fredericksburg now beckons travelers from
around the world; the Tourist Division of the Texas Department of
Economic Development estimates that visitors pump about $50 million
annually into Gillespie County.
</P>
<P>
   A weekend intruder quickly recognizes residents' pride in theirshedly Teutonic-flavored town, shaped by German culture and
history.
</P>
<P>
   Fredericksburg was settled a year after the first wave of German
immigrants erected New Braunfels, about 70 miles to the southeast,
in 1845. Led by John O. Meusebach, the 120 practical-minded,
God-fearing tradesmen, artisans, merchants, farmers and
professionals named the area near the Pedernales River after their
much-loved Prince Frederick of Prussia.
</P>
<P>
   The pioneers arrived in the spring when the landscape was
covered with acres of bluebonnets, belying the physical hardship
and danger to come. But despite attacks from Indians and breakouts
of cholera, Fredericksburg prospered. According to the U.S. Census,
there were 754 Fredericksburg residents by 1850. Today, the
population is about 8,600. But that number is on the rise as more
city-weary souls migrate to the area.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the old-timers grumble that Fredericksburg has changed,
become too crowded, too commercial. Still, this progressive town
has been able to retain its charm by keeping many of its German
customs and traditions intact.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors savor Fredericksburg's culture, history, food _ several
German restaurants included _ and shopping opportunities. But they
also come to stay in one of 300 bed-and-breakfast inns and guest
houses scattered about the area. Indeed, small family-owned
accommodations _ many of exceptional quality _ are a prime lure
throughout the Hill Country, and especially so in Fredericksburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the experience,'' says Carolyn Green of Austin.
``You want a place not only to sleep in, but also to dream in.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredericksburg is renowned both for traditional B&AMP;Bs and guest
houses, and although people often lump the two together, they are
distinctively different. Take, for example, the morning meal. B&AMP;Bs
provide guests with a full, family-style breakfast. Individuals
staying in guest houses make or find their own.
</P>
<P>
   Another distinction: B&AMP;Bs have an on-premises host or hostess to
answer questions. Guest houses don't, but there is always the
phone. Also, when you rent a guest house, you get the entire house
_ perhaps a 1920s cottage, a rustic log cabin or even a renovated
historical barn.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of guest houses exceeds that of B&AMP;Bs in
Fredericksburg, the occupancy rate remains higher for B&AMP;Bs, says
Donna Mittel, owner of Gastehaus Schmidt Reservation Service. ``For
people who really like the pampering, and sometimes we all do, B&AMP;Bs
are the way to go,'' Mittel suggests.
</P>
<P>
   But, she says, ``There are people who really value their
privacy. Some people feel like they have more privacy in guest
houses. There's nobody there to disturb them or for them to
disturb.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative of this kind of hospitality is the Schmidt Barn,
a charming little 1860s rock structure with an herb garden. Guests
are given a map and keys to the barn at the Gastehaus Schmidt
office downtown, and off they go, on their own, and not very likely
to bump into Loretta Schmidt, the barn owner who lives a few yards
away on the same hilltop.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1982, the Schmidt Barn was one of the first guest
houses in Fredericksburg. Schmidt got into the business simply
because the number of B&AMP;Bs fell short of the demand. At the time,
there were only a handful in town. Schmidt and a few other
homeowners were asked to help out by renting their spare rooms and
guest houses to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ladies immediately liked the idea because they liked the
company,'' Schmidt said ``But then they started liking the checks
that came along with that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As the number of guest houses grew, Schmidt founded Gastehaus
Schmidt in 1985. The reservation service, which she later sold to
Mittel, handles bookings for more than 100 guest houses.
</P>
<P>
   Like the owners, no two guest houses are alike. Aside from the
basics, each offers different amenities. Some, such as the Schmidt
Barn, provide cookies, juice and cold cuts; others nothing at all.
</P>
<P>
   Decor also differs. Some guest houses are sweetly draped in
floral designs and coordinating linens; among them is Oma Rosa's
Haus. Others take a more rustic approach; located off a country
dirt road on a 30-acre ranch, Das Jager Haus' enticements include
an outdoor shower.
</P>
<P>
   Many guest houses are built for romance: The Pappa John's
Bunkhouse and the Rosemary Cottage are among several that feature a
whirlpool tub for two.
</P>
<P>
   A few, including the Orange Street Cottage, Keepsake Cottage and
Up the Creek Guest House, are new. But most guest houses are
historical structures.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny one-room Sunday houses represent a style of architecture
unique to Fredericksburg. Between the late 1890s and early 1920s,
farmers erected Sunday houses for their families to use when they
came to town on weekends to worship, shop and socialize. Until
recently, the Sunday houses were being demolished to make way for
new shops and homes. Today, people are rediscovering and remodeling
them into guest houses; examples include the Yellow Sunday House
and Rode Sunday House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
