<HEADER>
A9869 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-HILL-COUNTRY-A     06-02 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HILL-COUNTRY-ART-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASING HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
FREDERICKSBURG, Texas: Rode Sunday House.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be tempting to spend all day relaxing within a guest
house. But take a last sip of fresh orange juice and discover the
other enticements that abound in the Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   Diverse museums celebrate toys and miniatures in Fredericksburg,
Hummel collectibles and handmade furnishings in New Braunfels,
antiques and sightseeing treks in Comfort, frontier days and rodeos
in Bandera and cowboy art in Kerrville.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown Fredericksburg, like many of its neighboring towns,
brims with a profusion of one-of-a-kind shops and old-time
atmosphere and history. And for now, it hasn't gotten too unwieldy
to tour on foot. So park the car and start pounding the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   For a glimpse of the past, start at the octagonal Vereins Kirche
(church society). Actually a 1935 replica of the first public
building, the structure is located at the center of Marktplatz
public park downtown. Built in 1847, the original building was used
for religious gatherings and community meetings. Today it houses
pictures and artifacts of life in the early days of Gillespie
County.
</P>
<P>
   Next, stroll over to the Gillespie County Historical Society's
Pioneer Museum Complex, 309 W. Main St. A must-see, it houses
several restored historical buildings, including a general store,
blacksmith shop, smokehouse, log cabin, wagon shed and schoolhouse.
Near the back of the grounds stand the one-room schoolhouse and the
1904 Weber Sunday House.
</P>
<P>
   Many fine buildings were designed by renowned architect Alfred
Giles, who lived here. Located at Adam and Main streets, the
Fredericksburg Public Library was built in 1882 from native
limestone from nearby quarries. Another of Giles' creations is the
old Bank of Fredericksburg, about a block down from the library on
Main Street. Although no longer a bank, the signage remains on the
building, noted for its impressive stone rampart and tower.
</P>
<P>
   One of Texas' most famous native sons was born in 1885 in a
pioneer home near the corner of Main and Lincoln streets. Indeed,
the ancestors of Chester W. Nimitz, the U.S. naval commander in
chief of the Pacific in World War II, were among the first German
pioneers to settle the area. To commemorate Nimitz' illustrious
career, his grandfather's Nimitz Steamboat Hotel at Main and
Washington streets was turned into the Admiral Nimitz Museum and
Historical Center, a state historical park managed by Texas Parks
and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Since the museum opened in 1983, Fredericksburg has become a
haven for retired military servicemen who come to trace Nimitz's
career and the events of World War II. Expect to spend a couple of
hours at the museum looking at picture murals and displays such as
the wheel and instruments of the SS Menhaden and a collection of
small and large relics from the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Components of the park are scattered over several blocks. Behind
the museum is a courtyard, with a walkway paralleling the Memorial
Wall with plaques placed by families and shipmates of naval
servicemen who died in the Pacific. At the far end is the serene
Japanese Garden of Peace, a gift from the people of Japan to
symbolize the friendship between Nimitz and their national hero
Adm. Heihachiro Togo.
</P>
<P>
   The latest addition to the park, the $3 million National Museum
of the Pacific War and George Bush Gallery, is scheduled to open to
the public June 12. Located directly behind the Nimitz Museum, the
new 23,000-square-foot gallery will include life-size exhibits such
as a B-25 bomber and Japanese midget submarine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOR NATURE LOVERS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of chasing history? Ready for fun in the great outdoors?
From canoeing and backpacking in Guadalupe River State Park to
water-skiing and golfing in Inks Lake State Park, the Hill Country
offers a wealth of opportunity to unwind in the sun and soak in the
rolling vistas.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the one place that draws more nature lovers to this part
of the Hill Country is Enchanted Rock State Park, 18 miles north of
Fredericksburg. The 1,643-acre park is home to the second-largest
granite rock in the United States (the biggest is Stone Mountain in
Georgia). Shrouded in legends and myths, it was christened
Enchanted Rock because of the reported strange lights and odd
sounds emanating from the granite structure. And despite its
semi-arid facade, a closer inspection reveals a thriving community,
including more than 500 species of vegetation and 150 or more
species of birds.
</P>
<P>
   A real eye-catcher, the solid pinkish-gray dome is also a haven
for hikers and climbers, providing both easy routes for the less
hardy and real challenges for the adventurers. Once these
nature-bound visitors reach the summit, many find themselves lying
on their backs on top of the smooth granite dome, watching the the
vultures and hawks circling and weaving through the white clouds
and clear blue skies. Later, they might set up a tent or lay out a
feast at one of the many primitive campsites and picnic areas.
</P>
<P>
   The Hill Country is famous for its tapestry of blooms. Aside
from the signature Texas bluebonnets, there are scarlet flax,
purple coneflowers, rocket larkspurs, baby blue eyes, yellow
cosmos, yarrows, Texas paintbrushes and Indian blankets.
</P>
<P>
   When in season, a place to visit with your camera is the
600-acre Wildseed Farms, seven miles eastward of Fredericksburg on
U.S. 290. It's hard to miss, especially when acres of bluebonnets
and red poppies are blooming. Visitors can take a leisurely stroll
on the walking trails and find more than 5,000 wildflower species,
including blue flax, winecups and lemon mint. For $4, you can also
pick some wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   For an unusual experience, about 12 miles from Fredericksburg
off the Old San Antonio Highway is the Old Tunnel Wildlife
Management Area (Bat Tunnel). Open nightly June through October, an
observation deck provides the chance to sit and wait for millions
of Mexican free-tail bats to come out, hunting their nightly meal.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, many bat colonies take up residence under the
bridges and caves throughout the Hill Country. Another bat
destination is Austin's Town Lake. Visitors from near and far
convene along its shores to watch the nightly flight of bats from
the Congress Avenue bridge, one of the nation's largest urban bat
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   The Hill Country also includes several wineries that offer tours
and tastings. One of the oldest is the Bell Mountain Vineyards at
463 Bell Mountain Road. Also here are the Grape Creek Vineyard,
Fredericksburg Winery and Becker Vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the wineries and other Fredericksburg
attractions, call the Convention and Visitors Bureau at
888-997-3600. Or access www.fredericksburg-texas.com on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on Fredericksburg-area guest houses or
B&AMP;Bs, call Gastehaus Schmidt Reservation Service at 830-997-5612 or
Hill Country Lodging &AMP; Reservation Service at 830-990-8455. Call
phone numbers listed elsewhere in this section for information
about B&AMP;Bs in other Hill Country locations. Many guest houses
require a minimum stay of two nights on weekends or during
holidays. Rates range from $65 to $140 per couple, plus $15-$25 for
each additional person.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
