<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLAME-YOURSELF-YANKS-COX-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEKING MUCK: HOW DID SO MANY PEOPLE LOOK THE WRONG WAY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...NOTE 250-word trim at 675)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 29 May 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
OFFERS A 250-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 675 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS
1,300.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ First, the comforting conclusion to be drawn from
the Cox report into Chinese spying: America does not find itself
suddenly facing a world-changing event, as it did in the Rosenberg
case (which revealed the secrets of the Manhattan Project to the
Soviet Union in the 1940s) or even during the missile crisis in the
Taiwan Strait in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The report, produced by a committee headed by Christopher Cox, a
mild Republican congressman from California, revealed that China's
spying has been a long-running campaign, not a sudden incident.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the report is disturbing for three reasons:
because of what it suggests about China's military capability;
because of its timing; and because of what it reveals about
American failures to safeguard nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   These go back many years, but have become considerably worse
during the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that China has stolen classified information on
seven nuclear weapons programs, including all the warheads deployed
in America's nuclear armory. It also claims that China has
obtained, by hook or by crook, information on satellite and
submarine guidance systems.
</P>
<P>
   The details of precisely which secrets it has got remain
unknown. All the same, at the very least, the range of options
available to Chinese military planners has increased.
</P>
<P>
   And the Cox report says the Chinese are about to test a missile
_ the Dong Feng 31 _ based partly on stolen American technology.
</P>
<P>
   When deployed (which the report says will be in 2002), the DF31
will be the first in a new family of mobile, solid-fuel missile
systems that will make China's nuclear force, which is now on the
level of the Soviet Union's in the 1960s, into something more like
America's in the 1970s: far from parity with the United States now,
but a step up.
</P>
<P>
   Given China's willingness to project force to get its way in
foreign policy, that could have big implications in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Neither that nor the revelations in the Cox report necessarily
requires a radical change in American policy towards China.
Nevertheless, the report has brought into question parts of
America's policy of ``engagement'' with China _ or at least the way
in which it has been implemented. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (250-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 375) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The policy has meant, for example, that when a Chinese company
has wanted to buy high-technology goods in the United States, the
presumption was that it would get an export license. That is likely
to change.
</P>
<P>
   Military cooperation is also a dead letter; China has suspended
it anyway in the wake of the Belgrade embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, the timing of the report _ just after that event _
will make improving American-Chinese relations even harder than it
would otherwise have been.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, opponents of China are a strange alliance
of right-wingers in search of a new Cold-War enemy and left-wingers
concerned about human-rights violations and Tibet.
</P>
<P>
   They have relatively little support at the political center.
Indignation about the theft of nuclear secrets is widespread and
might provide such support.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps surprisingly, that might not mean China's bid for
membership of the World Trade Organization (its top priority in
international trade) is doomed. Before the Cox report, the
administration had been taken aback by protests from companies at
Clinton's refusal to support China's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, any attempt to reopen the issue now will be awkward.
But even Cox supports China's bid _ on the right terms _ and, in
the past, trade issues have usually been separated from broader
political ones. Unfortunately, that means that even if China gets
into the WTO, relations with the United States may still not
improve. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cox report leaves both sides nursing grudges.
</P>
<P>
   But if America bears a grudge, it has only itself to blame. The
single most shocking fact revealed by the Cox report is not the
extent of China's spying, but America's failure to prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   The first cases of Chinese espionage in America's nuclear
laboratories date from the late 1970s. The broad details of the
operation were known as long ago as 1995, yet, on two occasions,
the Department of Energy refused to act on investigations by its
own counterintelligence officials.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until this April that a new energy secretary, Bill
Richardson, shut down the main computers to perform a thorough
check. By that time, the worst (and most recent) example of Chinese
spying had taken place _ after the completion of the Cox report.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the committee remarked that it was ``concerned that
no procedures are in place that would either prevent or detect the
movement of classified information to unclassified sections of the
computer systems.''
</P>
<P>
   It was right to worry. When officials at the Department of
Energy read that passage, they checked the computer of Wen Ho Lee,
a Chinese-American scientist employed at the Los Alamos Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   He had downloaded the so-called ``legacy codes'' on to an open
computer. These codes contain all the data the United States has
gathered in 50 years of nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Energy is finally slamming the stable door.
And if the Cox committee gets its way, security controls will get
tighter still.
</P>
<P>
   Its report lists 38 policy recommendations, from new binding
international controls on the transfers of sensitive technology, to
transferring authority over satellite licenses back to the State
Department. The day the report was released, the president said he
agreed with most of the recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the report's finer details raise three troubling
questions about America's response to China's recent spying.
</P>
<P>
   First, why did the Department of Energy demote the
counter-intelligence chief who originally raised the alarm?
</P>
<P>
   The man concerned, Notra Trulock, says he first knew of Chinese
spying in the mid-1990s and alerted the department, the secretary
of defense and so on at the time. He was demoted in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Second, why did the Federal Bureau of Investigation fail to act
against Lee and why did it and the Justice Department engage in
mutual recriminations about how to proceed?
</P>
<P>
   When the FBI in 1997 requested permission from Janet Reno, the
attorney-general, to monitor Lee's telephone conversations, she
denied the appeal, arguing that there was not enough evidence to
suspect him.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Robert Torricelli, a close ally of the Clinton
administration, called the attorney-general's failure to
investigate ``inexplicable,'' and questioned her fitness to remain
in office.
</P>
<P>
   Third, and most important, why did the chief of the National
Security Council, Sandy Berger, wait more than a year between
learning about the issue (in April 1996) and telling the president
in general terms (in July 1997)? And why did it take even longer
for the president to hear the details?
</P>
<P>
   In March of this year, Clinton claimed: ``To the best of my
knowledge, no one has said anything to me about any espionage which
occurred by the Chinese against the labs during my presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   his was three months after he had received the Cox report.
Either he did not read it, in which case he should have done. Or he
did read it and was lying.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the National Security Council says, he read the executive
summary it had prepared. This says there was proven Chinese nuclear
spying before his presidency; there was proven Chinese spying
during his presidency but against satellite tracking devices, not
nuclear weapons; and there was Chinese nuclear spying during his
presidency but it wasn't proven (the case of Lee, who is now in
retirement outside Los Alamos).
</P>
<P>
   To the White House, it seems, everything depends on the
definition of ``Chinese spying during my presidency.'' To the rest
of the world, such Clintonesque wordplay palls in the face of
massive nuclear theft. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent ECONOMIST article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer,
she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
