<SLUG> BC-GRIM-GROUNDWAR-SCENARIO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GROUND-WAR SCENARIO  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 800-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 29 May 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once a western force invaded Kosovo, it would, at least in
theory, have more than enough firepower to prevail over the Serb
forces. But getting NATO's armor inside a territory that is a
natural fortress ringed on all sides by mountains, and doing so
without great loss of life and equipment, would be much harder.
</P>
<P>
   There is simply no easy way for western forces to drive into
Kosovo. Of the neighboring countries, only Albania shows any
enthusiasm for being used as a launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   But the mountain road linking Albania to its embattled cousins
is a logistical nightmare. Without engineering on a huge scale, it
would simply crumble under the weight of a few tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Entering from Macedonia would be physically easier but
politically trickier, since that country is deeply reluctant to be
used as a staging post for war.
</P>
<P>
   The main road from Macedonia to Pristina, Kosovo's capital, is
in decent condition, though it passes through some high gorges and
tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   A flatter route connects Macedonia with southeastern Serbia. But
any invasion of Serbia proper, as distinct from Kosovo, would have
to face hostile locals.
</P>
<P>
   All the obvious entry points have been heavily mined, and the
Serb army has dug in as heavily as it can.
</P>
<P>
   How much resistance could the Serb forces actually put up? In
its most detailed report to date, NATO said on May 19 that it had
destroyed 556 pieces of military equipment in Kosovo, of which 312
were tanks, armored cars or big guns.
</P>
<P>
   That, if true, would mean that some 30 percent of the Serbs'
``heavy forces'' in the province had been knocked out.
</P>
<P>
   General Michael Short, the American commander of NATO's air war,
said the other 70 percent could be destroyed or chased out within
two months. But the exact pace of this destruction is impossible to
predict.
</P>
<P>
   NATO claimed exceptional success on May 21, saying it had
knocked out a dozen tanks and as many armored cars. But it was
hampered by bad weather for the next three days.
</P>
<P>
   If Serbia's goal is simply to ensure that NATO pays a high
military and human price for any invasion, then it has not yet
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the skepticism of those who doubt that a NATO ground
offensive this summer is feasible was bolstered by this week's
pledge from NATO that it would boost its forces in the region to
50,000 or so.
</P>
<P>
   A gradual buildup to those numbers looks much more like a
preparation for a peacekeeping force, to be deployed with Serbia's
consent, than a war-fighting plan.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, conventional wisdom holds that the moment for mounting
any sort of intervention in hostile conditions may already be
coming to an end, given that it would take many more weeks to get
the troops and their heavy weapons in place, and winter sets in as
early as October.
</P>
<P>
   But there is just a chance that conventional wisdom may be
wrong, particularly over timing. Some experts argue that it would
take only a couple of weeks for America's 101st Air Assault
Division to fly to Italy and then start ferrying mortars, artillery
and light vehicles to the edge of the war zone.
</P>
<P>
   They also argue that NATO could occupy two-thirds of Kosovo
quite rapidly, using American Marines and British and French
paratroopers to spearhead an operation in which western forces
might, with luck, lose only 200-500 men.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably true that once the political decision were taken
to make full use of America's support and attack helicopters, along
with the ``steel rain'' of multiple-launched rockets, the Serb
garrisons in Kosovo could be rapidly devastated.
</P>
<P>
   The long-range strike force of American tanks, gunships and
missiles that is building up in Albania, and could easily be
reinforced with units still in Germany, probably frightens Serb
commanders more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   So far, U.S. President Bill Clinton has explicitly forbidden the
use of Apache tank-busting helicopters; but he may be keeping that
option up his sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing in the Albania-based force would sharply raise the
stakes all around. Serb armor, now hidden or immobilized to avoid
