<HEADER>
A9881 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-EXERCISE-BOS &LR;      06-02 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-EXERCISE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO: DON'T READ TOO MUCH INTO THIS FICTIONAL WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK JERVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VYSKOV, Czech Republic _ Deployed on a weeklong military
exercise, soldiers from 20 NATO countries and allies are seeking to
end a hypothetical ethnic conflict and create a buffer zone to
resettle thousands of refugees forced from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Any resemblance between the exercise and the warfare taking
place two countries away is purely coincidental, insist officials
at the NATO camp in this eastern Czech town.
</P>
<P>
   Also coincidental, they maintain, is the exercise's possible
application for the broad peacekeeping mission envisioned by NATO
at the end of the Kosovo conflict, now more than 70 days old.
</P>
<P>
   On this Moravian hillside base, through Friday, 2,000 soldiers
are learning how to translate United Nations directives into
military operations, set up an international peacekeeping mission
in a hostile land, and meld 24 languages into one (English).
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has no relation whatsoever to the situation in Kosovo,''
NATO spokesman Andy Wallis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Exercise Cooperative Guard 1999, planned 18 months ago,
according to NATO, is centered on a fictional mission on a
peninsula called Gem, where the armies of the countries of Coral
and Topaz have bombed themselves into rubble. After four months, a
cease-fire was declared and UN observers sent in.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is up to NATO to create a buffer zone between the two
hostile nations and patrol the resettlement of ethnic Topazians
into an enclave within Coral.
</P>
<P>
   The public information officers are even instructed on dealings
with the Topazian and Coral journalists. One has a free press and
the other is state-run, Wallis said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Vyskov camp, men and women of all ranks dress in
similar green or brown camouflage fatigues. Stripes and medals
differ from country to country. The general rule is to only salute
anyone from your army that you recognize as high-ranking, Wallis
said. Otherwise it could get confusing.
</P>
<P>
   The combined joint task force headquarters, the heart of the
operation, is housed in a dormlike room with camouflage netting
overhead and NASA-style computers across the front wall. Romanian,
Belgian, British, and German officials confer over desktop PCs,
deciphering made-up tasks or the positions of troops in a fake
land.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would be asked to deploy anywhere, this would be the
setup we'd use,'' said US Army Lieutenant Colonel John Oliver, of
Killen, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Across campus, members of the Eurocorps wrestle with English
abbreviations in a NATO military order. Created in 1991, Eurocorps
began as a French and German initiative to launch peacekeeping
missions throughout Europe. Now composed of five countries (with
the addition of Spain, Belgium, and Luxembourg, Eurocorps is
participating for the first time in an English-language NATO
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no problem talking to someone in English,'' said Spanish
Major Jose Pardo de Santayana. ``But if you receive orders in
English, it's a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Air Operations Center, in an oversized white trailer,
about 70 men and women plan and track air missions and on
wall-sized computer screens. The center is a smaller version of the
air center in Vicenza, Italy, that directs the NATO air raids over
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing games here. We're assuming a challenging
situation, which could be done for real,'' said German Lieutenant
General Peter Vogler, the air center's commander.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly added: ``But this was planned a while ago. Not for
Kosovo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
