<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9892 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-GIFTS-COX     06-02 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GIFTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Payne's foundation reveals gifts given to IOC members
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Billy Payne's private Olympic foundation revealed for
the first time today that it gave dozens of International Olympic
Committee members expensive gifts and donated $25,000 to a South
African anti-apartheid organization.
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the U.S. House Commerce Committee, the foundation
provided a list of more than three dozen gifts that exceeded the
IOC's $200 limit, including a $948 carburetor kit for Bashir
Mohamed Attarabulsi from Libya and a live English bulldog for the
late Cuban member Manuel Gonzalez Guerra.
</P>
<P>
   The 38 gifts detailed by the foundation totaled $15,165 and
included many glass and crystal sculptures, clothing, a jewelry
box, a ruby pin, luggage and a set of surgical instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation provided extensive
documentation in the report that was requested by the House
committee, primarily dealing with cash payments, scholarships and
excessive gift exchanges during its bid for the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sincerely hope that our report will demonstrate that
Atlanta won the 1996 Olympic Games fairly,'' said Payne, who
created the foundation in 1987 to bid for the Games and remains its
chairman. ``Although we occasionally exceeded the IOC's guidelines,
our work was always done with honest intent.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Young, who served as co-chairman of the foundation during
the bid, said the anti-apartheid donation to an organization called
the South African Non-Racial Olympic Committee was important
because that country was preparing to rejoin the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many leaders of Atlanta's bid group were passionate about what
South Africa meant to the Olympic Games,'' he said, ``and our
financial support for its efforts was a small means by which we
could share our passion.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the donation, South Africa had no representation
on the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also acknowledged spending $14,099 for special
tennis training for two players from the Republic of Congo at
expelled IOC member Jean-Claude Ganga's request.
</P>
<P>
   They also funded tuition and housing for a swimmer from
Mauritius who came and trained at the Dynamo swim club in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus, Tiffany &AMP; Co. and Frabel Gallery appeared to be
the favorite shopping spots. A dozen sculptures alone came from
Frabel and ranged in price from $200 to $424.
</P>
<P>
   Pirjo Haggman, the IOC member from Finland who resigned when
allegations of bribery erupted over the Salt Lake City bid for the
2002 Winter Olympics last fall, was a big beneficiary of the
foundation's largesse. Haggman received clothing from Rich's and
British Passage totaling $937.66 in value.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Hodler, the Swiss IOC member who elevated the bribery
scandal to an international crisis when he accused other candidate
cities of influence peddling, was also on the gift list. He
received a Steuben crystal skier from Neiman Marcus that cost
$457.24.
</P>
<P>
   IOC executive board member Kim Un-Yong of South Korea, who
received a severe reprimand when it was revealed the Salt Lake
bidders funded a job for his son, took home a $616.25 Tiffany
jewelry box from Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Gifts weren't the only excess detailed by the foundation. The
group facilitated the donation of a used MARTA bus to the city of
Lima, Peru. Backed by an Atlanta City Council resolution, the
foundation worked with the Peruvian IOC delegate, Ivan Dibos, to
secure the bus. The Del Taco company reimbursed the foundation
$10,310 to finance the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the foundation said that it did not make any
direct cash payments or offer scholarships to IOC members or their
families. The group did pay some minor medical expenses for IOC
members while in Atlanta, including a $480 bill to fix IOC member
Guirandou N'Diaye's broken tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on our review to date, we are unaware of any action on
behalf of IOC members or on the part of GAAF that cast doubt on the
integrity of the bidding process for the 1996 Games,'' the
foundation wrote in its report.
</P>
<P>
   The report was sent to Rep. Thomas Bliley (R-Va.), chairman of
the House Committee on Commerce, and Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.),
chairman of the subcommittee on oversight and investigations, which
launched the inquiry into the Atlanta bid last month.
</P>
<P>
   Upton said he planned to send congressional investigators to
Atlanta to examine records related to the bid contained in the
1,400 boxes of documents housed at the Atlanta History Center.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
