<HEADER>
A9910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-RADIO-BOS &LR;      06-02 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-RADIO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VOICE THAT CARRIES THROUGHOUT SOUTH AFRICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ In Tim Modise's voice you can hear how he would
play the trumpet. It rises from deep within, where the bittersweet
memories of a ghetto youth churn, a scratchy scat tumbling along
its own improvised scale, unhurried and melodic.
</P>
<P>
   For all its character, though, his voice is not what captivates
about South Africa's most prominent radio talk-show host. In fact,
in a country where diverse races are still wary of strangers, some
find it jarring, too ``African'' for the sheltered ear of whites.
What gets the listener in the end is the laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Modise laughs and white women beg him to run for president.
He laughs and black men feel a warm vibe of brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
   When Modise laughs, light and disarmingly, he gets South
Africans _ voting Wednesday in their second election since
apartheid's end _ talking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim is that rare broadcaster who appeals across the board,''
said Tony Lancaster, who manages current affairs shows on SAfm, the
public radio station of South Africa where Modise hosts a morning
call-in show. ``Whites don't find him threatening. Blacks identify
with his sense of humor. And there is an intellectual element at
the base of his work. He is a pro to the hilt.''
</P>
<P>
   A pioneer in black radio, Modise (the last two syllables rhyme
with ``he say'') spent most of a decade breaking through the doors
of South Africa's white-run South African Broadcasting Corp. (SABC)
at the same time Nelson Mandela and others were tearing down the
political structures of the apartheid edifice. Now he is
ubiquitous, and represents the country's best hope for saving a
public network that for decades served as the mouthpiece for
minority rule and which is now struggling to compete for black
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic and unpretentious, Modise hosts two current affairs
television shows and writes a weekly newspaper column on politics
and the economy. In his free time _ and there isn't much of it _ he
travels on his own self-styled lecture circuit, sharing his
insights with communities and interest groups ``to keep the dream
alive,'' as he put it in a recent interview. Two weeks ago he flew
to London to urge business leaders not to lose faith as South
Africa continues its postapartheid transformation.
</P>
<P>
   But it is talk radio that Modise loves most and does best. Two
years ago the SABC put him behind the mike of a flagging two-hour
late-afternoon news program. He more than doubled its listenership.
Now the masters of public broadcasting hope he can turn the same
trick again, and recently bumped a white male host for Modise on a
coveted 90-minute morning call-in show.
</P>
<P>
   ``We inherited a station that was dominated by a particular
group of white South Africans,'' said Thoraya Pandy, producer of PM
Live, the afternoon show Modise hosted before moving to the
morning. ``The biggest problem at the SABC is making a significant
shift from the past. We have to overhaul the entire thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too soon to know for sure if Modise is changing the
complexion of the morning audience. Many of his callers are black,
but he's only been in the new time slot for two months and no
audience survey has been done.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no denying that, like a strong shot of espresso,
Modise has things hopping to an upbeat African tempo. The old show
started with a genteel signature tune of strings and brass. ``The
Tim Modise Show'' begins with street banter. Over the chaotic
sounds of an open-air market, a man shouts lyrically, ``Hey big
mama, what are you doing in the ghetto,'' his voice dissolving into
unabashed riffs of township jazz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted something that would create an atmosphere, set things
in motion,'' Modise said of the song, Hugh Masekela's ``The Boys
Are Doing It.''
</P>
<P>
   Modise thrives in the freewheeling format, which allows him to
spar with callers and studio guests for as long as he pleases. He
coaxes and prods _ sometimes serious, sometimes whimsical, always
in control and acutely informed. He seldom goes for the jugular but
never lets a politician off the hook. His whole manner seems to
say, ``Our time has come; let's make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a long way to go in this country,'' he said over
tea and muffins after a recent show. ``Decision makers speak to a
script; you know where they are coming from. But the general public
_ we're not one nation yet. By opening up the forum people can
learn from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Modise grew up in Ga-Rankuwa, a dilapidated township outside
Pretoria. Even as a boy he had a precocious instinct for the mike.
He once did a mock commentary of a rugby match in English class,
improvising and evoking the nuances of the game despite never
having seen it played. His schooling went as far as the first year
at Fort Hare, a black university, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   But those were turbulent days of antiapartheid action, and
student protests led to the institution being closed. Modise had
been studying communications, and when he returned home, a friend
found him a job as a production assistant with 702, a radio news
station operating at the time from inside Bophuthatswana, a black
homeland established by the apartheid government as nominally
independent and therefore free to hire nonwhites.
</P>
<P>
   He became a full-time journalist for the first time in 1985,
reporting from Bophuthatswana for the SABC. The notoriously
pro-apartheid station cracked open its doors, he said, ``because it
needed blacks to work the townships and homelands.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he left SABC to join Radio Metro, the first
commercial station managed by and aired for blacks. And that's
where his subversive attempts to transform South African
broadcasting began in earnest. The state forbid Metro from
discussing politics on the air, but now and then Modise would float
a question between songs. Next he started a talk show on consumer
rights with Bulelani Ngcuke, who would become the first national
director of public prosecutions under Mandela's government.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States went to war with Iraq in 1991, Modise and
his Metro colleagues took a chance and created a current-affairs
talk show to keep blacks informed. They called it ``Jungle Fever.''
The country's main black paper, The Sowetan, threw its editorial
backing behind the show, and by the time they turned their focus to
local events, such as the nascent talks between the apartheid
government and the African National Congress, there was little the
state could do to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   From then on, Modise's career has soared. He has won numerous
local and international awards, reported for the BBC in London, and
become South Africa's most celebrated broadcaster _ black or white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk shows were unknown to us, because whites had a view of
the world that didn't coincide with what blacks saw,'' said Aggrey
Klaaste, editor of The Sowetan. ``Then along came this bright young
black man who spoke our language, taking a lead in the direction of
self-expression. He would talk and then we'd give the issue space
in our next day's paper. It was all about nation building.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As easygoing as he is on air, Modise is surprisingly
businesslike in person. He reads avidly and has a keen interest in
economics. The big guns of South Africa's ruling class line up to
be on his show. It is evident, watching the way he relates to his
guests, and they to him, that Modise is a player _ a vital part of
the new discourse in his country.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 minutes before a show the other morning, Modise walked
in slower and heavier on his feet than usual. He'd been in a car
crash a few nights before and was still off balance. He looked
tired as he sat down behind the mike. When his signature song faded
out and he began flipping through the morning papers on air, as he
does to start every show, he suddenly perked up. He saw a story
about a group in the United States calling for American women to
refrain from crossing their legs for a day.
</P>
<P>
   He read part of the story aloud. He invited calls. ``This is not
really a tongue-in-cheek kind of discussion,'' he said, his sense
of irony and his laugh awakening. ``This is a sort of legs-crossed
type of discussion. Why do you suppose women in the States should
spend an entire day not crossing their legs? Let's talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Things started rolling. Modise hit his stride. When his guest
showed up, a leader from a minor political party contesting
Wednesday's elections, the discussion shifted to heavier topics:
abortion, the death penalty, the government's performance over the
past five years. The calls kept coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work keeps me going,'' he said after the show. ``It makes
me feel alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
