<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-FILM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY ON HOMOSEXUAL ISSUES IN SCHOOLS RAISES RUCKUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Debra Chasnoff cringed as she heard Pat Robertson launch into a
fiery speech at the 1992 Republican National Convention decrying
the damage homosexuals were doing to America's moral fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Something had to be done, Chasnoff thought, to counter the
strident anti-gay rhetoric being virulently promoted by Robertson
and his sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   Her weapon of choice was what she knew best _ film.
</P>
<P>
   What Chasnoff, an Academy Award winner, finally came up with was
``It's Elementary,'' and it has opened up a vicious new front in
the battle between gay advocates and conservative religious groups.
</P>
<P>
   While the film, which focuses on raising gay issues in school,
was controversial even before it was released in 1996 and became
widely used in school districts nationwide, the level of vitriol is
mounting now that it is scheduled to be broadcast this month on
nearly 100 public television stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say this is the Joe Camel of the homosexual movement,
but instead of teaching kids to smoke they are teaching kids to
enter into a behavior that could take 30 years off their life,''
said Janet Folger, national director of the Center for Reclaiming
America, an outreach of Coral Ridge Ministries, a conservative
group based in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to ask me how to put together a manipulative
campaign that indoctrinates children in the homosexual agenda,
`It's Elementary' would be it,'' added Folger, whose criticisms are
typical of those leveled by conservatives at the film as it edges
closer to gaining a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, which its makers say is aimed at educators,
takes cameras into six elementary and middle schools to show what
happens when teachers raise the subject of homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   It prominently features a discussion on gays at the private
Cambridge Friends School, including a schoolwide gay pride assembly
in which a gym teacher announces his homosexuality to the applause
and cheers of students.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors denounce the film as presenting a one-sided view of
homosexuality that takes a gratuitous slap at Christianity,
portraying Christians as violent oppressors of gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an issue of being open-minded,'' said Wendy Wright, a
spokeswoman for Concerned Women for America, a Washington
organization whose mission statement includes promoting ``biblical
values.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want our kids to be open-minded about alcohol, drugs,
or any other kind of unhealthy behavior,'' she said. ``It is not in
the best interest of children, families, or society to accept
homosexual activity as normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the film, which has been used in about 200 school
districts and 500 university teacher training programs, say ``It's
Elementary'' is a crucial resource to combat homophobia by
preventing stereotypes from taking hold among schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gay and lesbian people exist, and they have a right to the
same safety and respect all of us have,'' said Nancy DiMella,
health education coordinator for Newton public schools, which use
``It's Elementary'' to train teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The film's makers say the documentary's major opposition has
come from religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But the planned television broadcast of the film has raised the
stakes for conservative groups who view the film as part of a
campaign by gay activists to gain broader sympathy in society.
</P>
<P>
   WGBX &UR;  &LR; in Boston, one of at least 90 public television stations
planning to broadcast the documentary, has logged dozens of
telephone calls in recent weeks from detractors and supporters of
the film.
</P>
<P>
   That's rare, station officials, because the film does not even
air until June 18. ``It's not typical for there to be this kind of
controversy ahead of time,'' said Beth Potier, a WGBX spokeswoman.
``It's definitely on our radar screen as a show that brought with
it strong feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Several conservative Christian groups have mounted a massive
campaign attacking ``It's Elmentary'' and trying to prevent public
stations from airing the documentary. About 50 stations are still
weighing whether to broadcast the show, Chasnoff said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter urging members to mobilize against the airing of
``It's Elementary,'' Beverly LaHaye, chairwoman of Concerned Women
for America, describes the film as a ``major new effort to recruit
innocent children into the tragically destructive homosexual
lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Chasnoff, who won an Academy Award in 1991 for a documentary on
nuclear weapons production, bristles at the attacks, saying they
are led by conservative groups creating the same climate of
intolerance that ``It's Elementary'' seeks to counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as indoctrination when we inform kids that
saying `faggot' on the playground is being disrespectful to an
entire community,'' said Chasnoff, in a recent phone interview from
her San Francisco production office. ``I think everyone would like
their kids to have the tools to function in a multicultural society
that includes gay and lesbian people.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides letter-writing campaigns, opponents of ``It's
Elementary'' have produced and released their own videos rebutting
the documentary.
</P>
<P>
   One of the charges leveled in videos by the American Family
Association and Coral Ridge Ministries is that ``It's Elementary''
starts with the assumption that homosexuality is inborn. These
groups contend that plenty of gays have become heterosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific proof that one is born gay,'' said
Yvette Cantu, a policy analyst with the Family Research Council in
Washington who describes herself as a former lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   But Chasnoff said exploring the roots of homosexuality was not
the film's point. ``This was not intended to be a journalistic
piece of work,'' Chasnoff said. ``We wanted to make an uplifting,
inspiring film that showed people something maybe they had never
seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators, including Bob Chase, president of the National
Education Association, the country's largest teachers union, say
``It's Elementary'' has helped schools and teachers address a topic
that most schools have had a difficult time dealing with precisely
because it is so divisive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any issues we should back away from
when there are needs of students involved,'' Chase said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film takes on the issue of homophobia head-on and makes it
apparent that children are pretty receptive and pretty open to a
variety of ways of living,'' said Steven Luz-Alterman, assistant
professor of education at Tufts University, where ``It's
Elementary'' is used in several education classes.
</P>
<P>
   DiMella said she is not surprised the film has provoked such a
firestorm. ``From my view, homophobia is the one last form of
discrimination that is still endemic in our culture, and any time
an insitution _ in this case schools _ wants to rid itself of that
bias, you're going to come up against entrenched homophobia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
