<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-REICH-BOS &LR;      06-02 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-REICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GRADUATIONS; TWO APPROACHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Exemplifying the ideological chasm that separates them,
economic titans Alan Greenspan and Robert Reich next week will
deliver dueling commencement addresses on opposite sides of the
Charles River.
</P>
<P>
   On June 10, the chairman of the Federal Reserve Board will climb
the stairs of Memorial Church in Cambridge to face Harvard
University's class of 1999. That same day, the former labor
secretary will speak to graduates of the training program for the
homeless run by a shelter, the Pine Street Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one side of the river you have people beginning what are,
in the main, sort of fancy careers _ lives of privilege,'' said
Erik Butler, Pine Street Inn president. ``On this side of the river
you have people redeeming lost lives.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a supreme commencement matchup that contrasts the world's
richest university with a homeless shelter. It features a legendary
inflation-fighter who has helped steer the economy through the
longest period of peacetime growth in history against a a
self-described champion of working people and the poor.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second year that the Pine Street Inn has held its
commencement exercises on the same day as Harvard's, though last
year's occurrence was a coincidence. ``We decided, why not do it
again?'' Butler asked. He said the yin-yang aspects of the
simultaneous ceremonies appealed to him in a ``wry sort of way.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard, graduates clad in gowns or robes and traditional
mortarboard caps will march to music played by a live band. At Pine
Street, a microphone propped next to a boom box will provide
inspiration, and grads will be wearing suits and dresses donated
from the thrift shop _ no caps and gowns. ``We're a little lower on
the circumstance than Harvard,'' said Butler. ``But we do pretty
well on pomp.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pine Street Inn picked Reich as a speaker before Harvard
selected his ideological opposite.
</P>
<P>
   N. Gregory Mankiw, a Harvard professor of economics, said he
would be hard pressed to find two mainstream political figures from
the Clinton administration with such polar economic viewpoints.
``The big question in economics is what is the role of government:
should it be a large or small role? It's clear that Reich is a
believer in a much larger, activist government and that Greenspan
is a believer in a more modest government role.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich, who left the administration in 1997, frequently found
himself at odds with deficit-hawks, led by former treasury
secretary Robert Rubin and Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Locked in the Cabinet,'' Reich portrays Greenspan
as the real power in Washington, whose control over short-term
interest rates is the single most important governmental lever
affecting the US economy, with a crucial influence on whether
Americans have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Tongue in cheek, Reich describes the things he wishes he'd said
to Greenspan at a 1993 lunch meeting if he'd had the guts.
</P>
<P>
   Reich: ``What's your purpose in life?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: ``To stamp out inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich: ``Even if that means high unemployment?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: ``You bet.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich: ``Even if it means drastic cuts in federal programs that
help average working people and the poor?''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: ``Absolutely . . .''
</P>
<P>
   In Reich's imagination, the fanciful scene ends with the two men
exchanging epithets.
</P>
<P>
   Reich: ``Well you can take your crummy lunch and cram it, you
robber baron pimp.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan: ``Go suck a pickle, you Bolshevik dwarf.''
</P>
<P>
   In real life, both Greenspan and Reich are more restrained.
Indeed, few expect rhetorical fireworks when Greenspan gives his
afternoon address in front of the throngs in Tercentenary Theatre.
Nonetheless, when Greenspan talks, the financial reporters who
trail him at all his public appearances will parse each of his
utterances for significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty rare that he says anything dramatic,'' said
Manikiw. ``Usually his job is to sound serious and cautious. He
doesn't want to get people riled up. That's one of the reasons he
sounds opaque.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich, on the other hand, doesn't have to worry about upsetting
markets. He said he hadn't decided what he would say to the 77 Pine
Street Inn graduates of training programs in computers, culinary
arts, and commercial cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to preach to them,'' said Reich, a Brandeis
University professor. ``I don't want to take advantage of the fact
that Alan Greenspan is at Harvard.``
</P>
<P>
   But Reich said he might not be able to resist mentioning the Fed
chairman. ``The Fed at its last meeting decided to announce a bias
toward raising rates. If they do that, the people who are leaving
Pine Street, who have lost their jobs, are going to have a much
tougher time entering the job market. You can all but write them
off in terms of their getting a better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich said he isn't worried about the fates of Harvard graduates
if the Federal Reserve raises rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll do just fine in this new economy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
