A9933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW DAY FOR THE IRISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DINGLE, Ireland _ Some of the rotting trawlers lashed to the
town landing look so decrepit you'd think they'd sink if not for
the lines holding them prisoner to the shore.
</P>
<P>
   But the tourist has replaced the fish as the cash crop of the
new Ireland. Ireland is hot. On the same weekend that Bruce
Springsteen prepared for a Dublin stadium concert, a Japanese woman
drove into this old fishing town.
</P>
<P>
   An English language instructor for a Tokyo high-tech firm, she'd
taken a week's vacation to fly to Amsterdam, then Shannon, for five
days of bouncing around the hilly peninsula that pointed the way
west for hundreds of thousands of emigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Because Ireland is seen as clean, safe, and, if not cheap, at
least not as expensive as high-end touring in Paris or London,
foreign tourists and the hard currency they bring with them have
become an important component of the Celtic Tiger's staple diet.
</P>
<P>
   The overall European economy is gimpy, and the NATO war over
Kosovo is not helping, but Ireland, long the sick man of Europe, is
belting along like a Clancy Brothers tune.
</P>
<P>
   Housing costs in the republic are up 20 percent in a year, and
with mortgage rates down to 4 percent, real estate speculation is
in full flood. The peace process in Ulster is bogged down in the
kind of retrograde recriminations that made Northern Ireland for
decades the Balkans of the British Isles.
</P>
<P>
   But the Celtic Tiger has developed a taste for high living. The
Irish workforce is literate and well-educated; Ireland is easy to
get to, spotted between the European land mass and the United
States. The government is tax-friendly. So there has been a surge
in high-tech employment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Miami-based Bankers Insurance Group announced it
will expand its operations in a new round-the-clock Cork plant that
processes unemployment and disability claims for the United States
utilizing a high-speed data link.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland's push for large-scale manufacturing investments ran
afoul of the cyclical nature of big-ticket items. Ford, Dunlop, and
Sunbeam first created jobs, then cut back, which made things
difficult. Now the development schemes emphasize high-tech and
pharmaceuticals, and outfits like Apple Computer, Sandoz, and
Johnson &AMP; Johnson have filled the gap.
</P>
<P>
   The centralization and economies of scale anticipated with the
introductory phasing in five months ago of the new euro have yet to
materialize. The Bank of Ireland tried to elbow its way to the
front of the queue by merging with Alliance &AMP; Lester, a move that
would see Ireland's second-largest bank joined to a middle-sized
British institution.
</P>
<P>
   To the Irish Times, the announcement ``is the most significant
development in the financial sector (in Ireland) in recent years,''
one motivated by the Irish bank's fear of ``becoming one of the
smaller regional banks in the euro zone.''
</P>
<P>
   While it will be two years still before the new euro coins and
notes begin circulating, eventually to replace the coinage and
currency of 11 different European nations (including Germany,
France, and the Republic of Ireland, but excluding Britain, among
others), the euro began trading on the first day of business after
New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   It nudged up to $1.18 against the dollar, but last week sank to
a five-month low of $1.04, triggering louder murmurs and complaints
about the new fiscal ground rules that make it more complicated for
individual countries to manipulate the worth of their currencies.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar is still king, though some euro-fanciers continue to
maintain that the euro will one day, in the not so distant future,
threaten the mighty buck as the world's leading reserve currency,
the place to hide when economic cyclones strike.
</P>
<P>
   The destabilizing effect of the NATO campaign against the
marauding Serb forces of Slobodan Milosevic is difficult to
calibrate. The tensions exacerbated by the murders, shelling,
forced evictions and dislocation of a million Kosovar refugees
cannot be minimized.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, who take part in refugee resettlement and
international aid efforts in numbers far beyond their proportionate
share as a people, have mobilized in typical fashion. In every
village, in many shops and pubs, cash is solicited for Kosovo
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or 20 years back, Northern Ireland was the tinder box of
Europe, a sullen and fearful province wracked by sectarian murders,
military intervention, riots, and terror-bombing.
</P>
<P>
   There are still isolated episodes in the north, kneecappings or
sectarian murders, old scores being settled by violent men who see
no future for themselves and their limited talents and their work
ethic in the new high-tech Ireland of transistors, tubes, and
tourism. But in the republic, this is as good as it gets for a lot
of average folk.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperity has changed perspectives. The Irish are more worldly;
they travel now as middle-class tourists and not as mendicant
emigrants; they demand quality wines with their meals and shrewdly
consult their share prices in the financial columns.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
