<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELING GUILTY ABOUT FEELING GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a friendly building just outside Kansas City,
GuiltAmerica.com continues its research and development of new ways
to use guilt in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   GuiltAmerica's latest product for use by nonprofit organizations
is called ``Kids 'n' Pledges.'' For example, children who attend
private school knock on doors getting neighbors to sign pledges to
pay a certain amount of money to the school for each lap they run
in a track event.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if you already pay taxes to support the public
schools, and hate the idea of subsidizing a school where kids are
dropped off in Land Rovers and Jaguars. It's a kid at the door, a
neighbor's kid, and you can't say no.
</P>
<P>
   This is part of GuiltAmerica.com's motivational strategy. It's
not enough for people to give, buy or perform any action out of
generosity or desire. The basic formula for the company's Pledge
Division is, ``If you say no, you look like a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   That covers all those dance-a-thons and bike-a-thons in which
office workers go from cubicle to cubicle getting fellow workers to
sign pledges. In an ingenious new twist that recognizes the desire
of the end-used to say ``Just go away,'' GuiltAmerica invented the
option of paying an immediate $5 cash donation to avoid pledging
for each mile, thus ensuring the pledge collector won't return with
a bill.
</P>
<P>
   GuiltAmerica.com opened for business half a century ago as
Guiltco, selling the idea that kids should go door-to-door peddling
candies and cookies for their youth organizations, whose leaders
had the ability to guilt-trip the kids into doing it. The company
took its lead from mothers who always said, ``Finish your dinner.
Children are starving in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that didn't save any kids in China (or India or
Africa, as times changed and dinner table guilt stayed the same).
</P>
<P>
   But those kids darn well ate their spinach.
</P>
<P>
   No neighbors really bought all those cookies and candies. My Sea
Scout candy bars were bought by my mom because she felt guilty that
I was a lazy salesman. They should have called us See's scouts, but
the chocolate wasn't that good. The company that made the candies
raked in the bucks no matter who ate the chocolate or even if it
was thrown out.
</P>
<P>
   Who invented the idea of recycling bins, so neighbors could see
if you're recycling, and what kinds of bottles you're recycling?
Why, GuiltAmerica, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Who lobbied behind the scenes for warning labels on booze and
no-smoking bars and restaurants? Consultants for GuiltAmerica,
working soft hand in hard fist with lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Who marketed all those awards and bumper stickers, saying ``My
child is an honor student at Joe Blow Junior High''? GuiltAmerica,
and they did it with a complete horizontal and vertical integration
of the school guilt market.
</P>
<P>
   GuiltAmerica's Industrial Division has come up with a more
powerful motivator than ``If you say no, you look like a jerk.''
That principle, sold to human resources departments nationwide, is:
``If you say no, you look like an unemployed jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   GuiltAmerica set the goal of helping companies end paid overtime
by means of the use of a few simple questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're leaving awfully early today, aren't you Smedley? Are
you in a rush to watch Letterman?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you jog to work over the weekend? I didn't see your car in
the parking lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like to come to our motivational dinner and
team-building Tuesday night? No, spouses can't come, and I realize
it's your wife's birthday, but think of us as family.''
</P>
<P>
   If you say no, you look like an unemployed jerk. Works like a
charm. Poof, low overtime and the illusion of high productivity.
</P>
<P>
   GuiltAmerica.com is now doing some top-secret defense
contracting. The company is teaching the Pentagon brass and White
House national security advisers how to motivate the nation for
wars in unknown places.
</P>
<P>
   Patriotism doesn't rouse the nation anymore, because large
segments of the populace feel guilty about being patriotic. The
trick for guilt consultants is to relieve guilt in one area, while
applying it in another.
</P>
<P>
   People must be kept from feeling guilty about civilian
casualties inflicted by our pilots, while basically being told
``Finish the job. Children are starving in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Why the .com in the name GuiltAmerica.com? Well, my iMac just
told me ``This computer may not have been shut down properly the
last time it was used.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust me, guilt is going to be big on the Internet, and
GuiltAmerica.com is selling stock. You can't say no to that
offering, or you look like a jerk.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you can just give them $5 and hope they go away.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
