<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-EPSTEIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE ELEGANT, AFFECTING ESSAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT TAYLOR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NARCISSUS LEAVES THE POOL &QL; 
Familiar Essays &QL; 
By Joseph Epstein &QL; 
Houghton Mifflin, 321 pp., $25 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time's winged chariot glides through Joseph Epstein's latest
collection of personal essays. He has bypass surgery, turns 60,
feels mildly depressed. And yet the zest of his prose is
exhilarating. Cheerfulness _ as James Boswell says in his ``Life of
Samuel Johnson,'' citing the philosopher Oliver Edwards _ is always
breaking in.
</P>
<P>
   For 21 years Epstein edited The American Scholar and contributed
to its pages under the name Aristides. Lest this sound elitist and
chilly, Epstein is the kind of man who not only knows Aristides was
dubbed ``the Just'' in ancient Athens, but recognizes it as the
name of a famous racehorse. ``Narcissus Leaves the Pool'' is the
author's sixth collection of familiar essays; he's a master of the
form, and his range of allusion has few equals in contemporary
American letters.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Narcissus'' is darker than prior collections, it is also
equally effervescent. The personal essay demands strong opinions
and achieves its unique character when it has the quality of
intimate conversation. Epstein gets wonderful effects combining
this intimacy with an admixture of the erudite and a dollop of
self-deprecation. Here, for example, he recalls a long-playing disc
featuring June Christie, who sang with the Stan Kenton band in days
of yore:
</P>
<P>
   ``Her songs about loneliness, desertion, betrayal, and general
mistreatment at the hand of men made Ovid in the `Heroides' seem,
in the crying-the-blues department, strictly bush league. The
cumulative impression the album conveyed was of a beautiful woman
alone at a bar _ smoking a cigarette and two drinks ahead of
everyone else in the room _ who had gotten a very raw deal. . . .
(The questions of) why had so many men left her in the lurch, and
was there something fundamentally wrong with so habitually unhappy
a woman _ were, of course, best left unanswered. In musical
romance, only the unexamined life is worth living.''
</P>
<P>
   Epstein's subjects are, typically, more serious than they
appear, though the tone is always casual and confiding. ``Grow Up,
Why Dontcha?'' deals with changing perceptions of adulthood. One
sees people in their 50s whose sartorial ideal belongs to the
1960s; moreover, the movies of other decades preferred to imply a
maturity among leading men (Bogart, Cooper, Milland) that is no
longer visible. ``What's in It for the Talent?'' scrutinizes nearly
everyone's inclination to prefer talent to genius. ``A Nice Little
Knack for Name Dropping'' treats name-dropping as a minor art
requiring a gossamer touch.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the titles derive from S. J. Perelman (his ``Beat Me,
Post-Impressionist Daddy,'' for instance), and the essays adroitly
deal with what Chesterton called ``Tremendous Trifles,'' yet two
stand apart: ``My Friend Edward'' is a handsome, elegiac tribute to
the memory of a colleague, and ``Taking the Bypass'' is a somber
look, and no wonder, at Epstein's operation.
</P>
<P>
   As he points out, it is exceedingly difficult to get a clear
picture of all that such surgery entails. Hospitals do their best
to educate patients, but no institution can delineate the patient's
inner life as he or she experiences the panic and pain of what is
euphemistically called ``the procedure.'' Epstein pulls no punches
in describing the sensations of a patient and ``an abiding
vulnerability I hadn't felt before.''
</P>
<P>
   His sense of a loss of control over his destiny is partially
offset, however, by reading ``The Assault,'' by the Dutch novelist
Harry Mulisch. The principal character, an anesthesiologist, finds
his patients changed forever by their ordeal. Joseph Epstein too
feels changed in inexplicable ways. The surgery and its attendant
suffering have left him uncharacteristically off balance, conscious
of mortality; but one suspects, given his resources, cheerfulness
will sooner or later break in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
