<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, June 3:
</P>
<P>
   SAVANNAH-MERCER-HOUSE (Savannah, Ga.) _ Dorothy Williams Kingery
has just put Mercer House, the most famous _ some say infamous _
house in Savannah, on the market for $8.95 million. Kingery is the
sister of James Williams, who was tried four times for the shooting
death of a young man named Danny Hansford, which was the focus of
the bestseller ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil.'' If sold
at anywhere near that price, Mercer House would be the most
expensive private house _ by far _ ever sold in Savannah. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   CRANBROOK-RENOVATION (Bloomfield Hills, Mich.) _ Not long after
Eliel Saarinen's brand of kiln-fired, loom-woven, handcrafted
modernism was elbowed aside by the harder-edged International
style, development all but stopped on his architectural masterwork:
the ensemble of museums, schools and design academy now known as
the Cranbrook Educational Community. By David W. Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   LOFT-LIVING (Undated) _ Three decades into the loft age, the
box, a floor-to-near-ceiling structure, has become an important
design element _ an architectural treasure chest that made loft
living open and airy, yet intimate. By Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON'S-DIET (Undated) _ At this late date, the 200th
anniversary of his death, you might think that anything and
everything about George Washington had long been chewed over. But
wait: What was the connection between the beautiful, whoppingly
productive gardens of Mount Vernon and those famous false teeth?
And by the way, what could our first President eat? ``Not much!''
said Dr. John M. Hyson Jr., director of curatorial affairs at the
Dr. Samuel D. Harris National Museum of Dentistry in Baltimore.
``I'm sure he chewed with great difficulty.'' By Mac Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-ROOMS (Undated) _ Who's afraid of the dark? A bounty of
light-hearted accessories for children's rooms has just landed, and
among the cloud and moon shapes are brand new glow-in-the-dark
sheets and carpeting. By Marianne Rohrlich.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With how to drawing.
</P>
