<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MARVEL OF A MUSEUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ Just a few minutes into our tour of the
spanking-new Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, photographer
David Bruneau points to a clutch of ladders in front of a mammoth
James Rosenquist pop art triptych. ``Are the ladders part of the
art?'' Bruneau asks. His comment is not meant to be a joke, and no
one laughs.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA director Joseph Thompson has offered to escort me,
Bruneau, and Mat Gleason, editor of the subversive art monthly
Coagula (``Cruel, insensitive, unfair, and thoroughy readable from
cover to cover'' _ David Bowie), through his 250,000 square feet of
exhibition space. I had invited Gleason to join us mainly because
he is the coauthor of a book called ``Most Art Scks.'' As in fact,
most modern art does.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a genial art expert-cum-MBA, treats us with perhaps
more respect than we deserve. ``The least pretentious and
best-informed museum director I've ever met,'' Gleason says of
Thompson, outside his hearing. But it is hard to distinguish some
of MoCA's art from the construction materials littering the floor
before last weekend's opening. Later in our tour, Thompson directs
my attention to a work by Bruce Nauman, but I see only 20 feet of
studded drywall. Gleason instantly understands that the ``art'' _
some yellow neon lights _ is on the other side of the drywall.
Silly me.
</P>
<P>
   It's arguable that the art in MoCA's initial ``Test Site''
exhibition is beside the point. What is most impressive is that
MoCA exists at all. Fifteen years ago, these galleries were an
abandoned factory complex in an economically depressed Berkshire
mill town. Then, in 1988, a young Williams College-educated art
hustler named Thomas Krens convinced the Dukakis administration to
spend $35 million to transform the heart of North Adams into a
modern art gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Massachusetts Miracle ran out of gas, and the
state refused to fork over the museum's authorization. Krens bailed
out to take over New York's Guggenheim Museum. The incoming
governor, William Weld, thought MASS MoCA was a dumb idea. ``Weld
said to us, `Just go home,' '' Thompson recalls.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson didn't go home. Instead, he raised $11 million in
private donations to convince Weld that MoCA could fly. Working
with North Adams mayor John Barrett and then-state senator Jane
Swift, Thompson jawboned Weld's economic affairs aide Dan Gregory
to keep the project alive. When I asked Thompson why he spent six
long years in North Adams (think: Pittsfield without the glitz)
promoting a seemingly dead-end art project, he muttered some
platitudes about community involvement and the compelling nature of
the MoCA project. After a pause, he added: ``Besides, it was hard
to make a gracious exit.''
</P>
<P>
   So what about the art? Is MoCA just a ``dumping ground for
oversize works from big-name donors (read: the superannuated
Italian collector Count Giuseppe Panza di Buomo)'' whom the
Guggenheim ``couldn't afford to alienate,'' as I wrote in 1990? In
part, yes. Some of the lamer artists, like junkman John Chamberlain
and metal mucker Robert Morris, were slated to be exhibited here a
decade ago, when the funding collapsed. Even then, their work was
passe.
</P>
<P>
   My man Gleason calls Chamberlain, Morris, and yesterday's
minimalists like Robert Mangold and Carl Andre ``the equivalent of
the Rolling Stones. Just as the Stones have been releasing the same
album over and over again, these guys have been chugging away at
the same imagery since the late 1960s. Thompson isn't taking any
chances with this exhibit; I think he's playing it safe for the art
tourists. If you don't like the art, at least you won't be offended
by it. It's almost content-free.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what's good about MoCA? The galleries, some boasting
sightlines as long as two football fields, have been beautifully
restored by Cambridge architects Bruner/Cott &AMP; Associates. The vast
exhibition halls allow MoCA to display works like Robert
Rauschenberg's painted journal ``The 1/4 Mile or 2 Furlong Piece,''
which is in fact a quarter-mile long.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the same cavernous space accommodates Joseph Beuys's
``Blitzschlag'' (translation: ``Lightning/Whipped Cream''), a
20-foot-tall pyramid of darkened bronze surrounded by
submarine-sandwich-size pieces of dung. The good news is that all
MoCA exhibits are temporary, so a year from now ``Lightning/Whipped
Cream'' will have to find a new home.
</P>
<P>
   Will MoCA be here a year from now? Yes, although the economics
promise to be lean indeed. The museum has scaled down its
anticipated attendance from 150,000 to a minuscle 100,000 visitors
a year, with 65 percent of them expected during July, August, and
October. In the winter months, MoCA will cut its staff in half,
turn down the heat, and hope for the best.
</P>
<P>
   Happily, MoCA doesn't have to live by art alone. The museum has
a sound stage it can rent out, and some of the renovated mill
buildings already have paying tenants. The local newspaper rents
here, as do Kleiser-Walczak Construction Co., a special effects
outfit; HealthShare Technology, a health-care information provider;
and eZiba, yet another company that will ``completely reinvent the
concept of online retailing,'' according to its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   During the next few years, Thompson will use the $13 million
remaining in his state grant to rehab some space for art, and some
space for commercial leasing. ``That's how we'll survive,'' he
explains. Unbelievably, they will.
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9949 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      06-02 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST AND WORST; MEN IN DECLINE; PYTHON PLUS 30 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is nothing so satisfying as a good debunking.
</P>
<P>
   It does the heart good somehow to see an inflated reputation
reduced to a popped balloon by a few piercing words, or to see some
pillar of conventional wisdom given a boot in the old fundament. In
that spirit, American Heritage does solid service with its second
annual list of the most overrated and underrated people, things,
ideas, and events in US history.
</P>
<P>
   As with those Best-Worst lists, where your eye is drawn
irresistibly to the Worst, you may find yourself lingering upon the
``overrated'' list, especially given the scathing treatment some of
the subjects receive. Among those whose reputations are cut down to
size: Gloria Steinem, Al Capone, Ernest Hemingway, Isaac Asimov,
the '60s, Shel Silverstein, John Adams, Boss Tweed, atomic power,
Alfred Eisenstaedt, Hunter S. Thompson, Gary Cooper, the idea of
progress, Alexis de Tocqueville, Yalta, and the Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   You won't agree with all the choices (Stephen Sondheim
overrated? Rubbish!), but American Heritage has chosen its
debunkers well from a roster of opinionated scholars and writers
who argue, in general, that icon-hood is often just a matter of
good PR. But there's more than knee-jerk revisionism here. Allen
Barra is persuasive in arguing that Capone was a lightweight who
inherited a crime machine built by others and who owes his enduring
reputation to ``The Untouchables.'' Nicholas Lemann sheds new light
on the GI Bill. And it's hard to think of Hemingway in the same way
after Nancy Caldwell Sorel is done describing the shoddy journalism
he practiced as a war correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the food for thought, there are many deliciously
nasty lines. Camille Paglia brands Steinem the ``chief deb of her
own little sorority, which awards honorary memberships to pampered
men of power, such as glad-handing presidential adulterers.'' Woody
Hochswender dismisses Halston as ``probably a better hatmaker than
clothing designer.'' Nathan Ward notes that reading pieces from the
gonzo school of New Journalism ``can now make you feel as if you're
in an elevator with a counterculture salesman whose floor never
arrives.'' And Bruce McCall tees off on the '60s, calling the
decade ``one spontaneous, protracted narcissistic binge with all
the intellectual clarity of a spoiled brat's tantrum . . .. The one
profound thing about the period is the mystery of why a society so
advanced so willingly fell under the spell of this mush-headed
vision of life as children's holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: American Heritage belongs on any list of underrated
treasures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Except perhaps for a good debunking, there is nothing so bracing
as the sight of two first-rate minds engaged in mortal combat over
important ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The June Harper's generates some intellectual fireworks by
pitting essayist Barbara Ehrenreich against anthropologist Lionel
Tiger (coiner of the term ``male bonding'') to debate whether the
power of males is in decline and whether a ``fundamental shift'' in
the balance of power between men and women has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   At a New York restaurant, Ehrenreich and Tiger range across a
wide terrain, from the nature of sex roles 25,000 years ago to the
state of male-female relations, pausing to quarrel over such issues
as the Pill, the corporate glass ceiling, women in combat,
single-mother families, and changing male attitudes toward family
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   At times Tiger is pedantic (must he say ``emerging kinship
system'' when the word ``family'' is available?) and at times
Ehrenreich is snide (can't she rebut Tiger without accusing him of
nostalgia for ``feudalistic ways of life''?) But both are skilled
polemicists, and in general, this is a pretty high-minded exchange.
Tiger and Ehrenreich run out of time long before they run out of
words or ideas. I wouldn't want to get into an argument with either
of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denver TV stations took some lumps for their coverage of the
Columbine High School massacre, in particular for airing interviews
with students trapped inside the school and for broadcasting police
rescue maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one station, CBS affiliate KCNC-TV, displayed
professionalism and restraint under harrowing circumstances on
April 20, according to a chronicle of the station's 13 hours of
nonstop coverage in the Columbia Journalism Review.
</P>
<P>
   Former Wall Street Journal columnist Dean Rotbart, who spent
that day inside KCNC, reports that the station videotaped, but
chose not to broadcast, gory footage of a SWAT team dragging two
victims' bodies across the Columbine High lawn. Though KCNC learned
the identities of the two shooters early and could have scooped the
competition, the station held off on airing their names until
reporters got triple confirmation. All around the newsroom,
according to Rotbart, people rose to the occasion, including a news
director who had arrived at the station just two weeks earlier and
was still learning reporters' names.
</P>
<P>
   ``KCNC's news coverage . . . defies many of the most common
negative stereotypes concerning broadcast journalism in general and
local TV in particular,'' writes Rotbart.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And now for something completely brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, it's been 30 years since ``Monty Python's
Flying Circus'' debuted in England. In the years that followed, the
Pythons would take sketch comedy to heights it had not seen before
and has not seen since. In Python-world, silly walks had their own
ministry, purse-swinging old ladies terrorized the British
countryside, lumberjacks just wanted to feel pretty, and no one
expected the Spanish Inquisition.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Vanity Fair excerpts a good long chunk of David
Morgan's new oral history of the Pythons. It dwells overmuch on
Graham Chapman's drinking problem, and Morgan's stiff writing style
is strangely at odds with his subjects, but there are a few tidbits
in here for Python buffs. For instance, it turns out that the
famous dead parrot sketch originally had John Cleese trying to
return a faulty toaster to the store. But when Cleese performed it
for Chapman, the latter's only response was: ``Yes, it's boring,
why not make it a parrot instead?''
</P>
<P>
   The excerpt suggests why the Pythons worked together for such a
comparatively brief period: creative differences combined with
cranky temperaments (John Cleese and Terry Gilliam are portrayed as
the most prickly). ``Whether we will ever be able to agree on
anything ever again is moot,'' says Eric Idle. ``I think groups use
up all their agreements early and then all that is left is to
disagree. But I'm not sure whether I agree with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder some of us miss them so much?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9952 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-INTRI     06-02 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRIMAKOV-INTRIGUE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN RUSSIA, ENDLESS INTRIGUES and CLUELESS LEADERS, BUT LIMITED &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Mikhail Gorbachev's
monthly column on world affairs. To publish as a ``separate buy''
article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from
one of these New York Times Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By MIKHAIL GORBACHEV  
 c.1999 La Stampa  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Politics and power are inseparable; there is nothing new about
that. But it is policies that, in the final analysis, define the
nature of a government, the goals that it pursues and the interest
that it serves.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, the trend in many countries has been
to allow the prevalence of tactical, self-serving and even cynical
politics at the expense of responsible policy-making. This is
happening at a time when the world is changing rapidly and
fundamentally, when today's decisions could affect the future in
dramatic and defining ways. Hasty, thoughtless decisions have
already cost us dearly in a number of regions and even on a global
scale. The diagnosis of world politics today is very clear: The
patient is seriously ill.
</P>
<P>
   This disease has taken a particularly severe and acute form in
Russia. The political crisis here has become virtually permanent,
with reform its main victim. The attempt to solve overnight the
problems involved in the difficult transition from one system to
another has affected all aspects of Russia's life in the most
destructive ways.
</P>
<P>
   Politically bankrupt and clueless, Russia's rulers are flailing
about, rushing to extremes and changing ministers like gloves.
Endless intrigues serve to conceal continuous failure of policy.
Yevgeni Primakov and his cabinet are the latest victims of those
intrigues.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite clear from the start that President Yeltsin's
decision to dismiss the cabinet had nothing to do with his declared
intention of kick-starting the Russian economy. That was just a
pretext _ so much so that even Primakov's designated successor,
Sergei Stepashin, at first stated that he would continue the
economic policies of the previous cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, was the real reason behind the decision taken by the
small coterie of Yeltsin's close associates, whom many Russians
call the family politburo? One reason, which is clear at a glance,
was the Russian president's jealousy of Primakov's popularity and
well-deserved public support.
</P>
<P>
   Having taken over when Russia's economy was in ruins, Primakov
was able to keep the country from falling into the abyss and to
create an atmosphere of stability. And, although the life of the
average Russian has not yet improved, people were beginning to see
a ray of light, of hope that an end to chaos and some improvement
was in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, of course, resented the fact that while his own
approval ratings had plummeted to 2 percent or 3 percent, Primakov
had the support of about two-thirds of the populace, according to
opinion polls. Still, that reason, while obvious, was not the main
one.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov stood in the way of those in Russia who had illegally
accumulated tremendous wealth, who had grabbed vast amounts of
property through corruption and outright theft. It is those people,
fearful of losing what they had plundered, who orchestrated an
anti-Primakov campaign, declaring war on him in the media and in
the corridors of presidential power.
</P>
<P>
   By firing Primakov, Yeltsin forfeited Russia's real interests
and acted in the interests of himself and of a group concerned only
with its own future _ and with finding a successor who could make
that future secure and comfortable. A self-proclaimed ``guardian of
the constitution,'' Yeltsin is acting more like the guardian of the
property and safety of a corrupt group.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the president's actions have destabilized the
situation in the country. The fact that the State Duma, Russia's
parliament, approved the choice of new premier does not at all mean
that the government crisis is over.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it is continuing, now in the form of a fierce struggle
for seats in the cabinet, levers of influence and control over
major financial flows. Stepashin, who did not want to appear as a
puppet in the hands of the president's entourage and the group of
crony capitalists, is being cut off from decision-making on these
matters.
</P>
<P>
   We see emerging from the shadows and put in key positions people
who don't care one bit about economic reform and even less about
democracy. The anti-corruption drive begun under Primakov has for
all intents and purposes been stopped, and indicted officials and
businessmen are being allowed to get away from justice.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Russia's final stretch to parliamentary elections later
this year and then the presidential election in 2000 will be even
tougher than it had to be. The Duma's approval of the new prime
minister's appointment was primarily meant to deprive Yeltsin of
any pretext for dissolving Parliament and perpetuating the regime
of one-man rule. I think that in doing so, the Duma acted properly.
The important thing now is where the leading Russian politicians
will go from here. They, and the political groups now being formed
around them, must act with a sense of utmost responsibility and
balance.
</P>
<P>
   Of great importance will be what Primakov decides to do. It
would be unfortunate if his dismissal and the insulting way he was
treated caused him to leave the Russian political arena. My advice
to him would be to give the entire situation serious thought. He
could retain his broad-based support. Significantly, he continues
to lead all opinion polls. If the elections were held today, he
would most probably be elected president.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow's Mayor Yuri Luzhkov has already offered Primakov a
partnership within the political group he is now creating.
</P>
<P>
   It is my considered opinion that the ``optimal way'' scenario
for Russia would involve amending the present constitution. We must
get rid of its authoritarian straightjacket. Prudent changes in the
constitution would strike a proper balance between the presidency,
a more authoritative and responsible cabinet of ministers and a
reasonably strong parliament. I continue to believe that within
such a structure of government, Primakov would be the best choice
for president and Luzhkov for prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Russia is capable of leaving behind the overly long and painful
stage of its ``start-up development.'' Responsible policies and
policy makers must replace its current strain of politics. And,
though conditions differ, many Western countries too could set for
themselves a similar goal.
</P>
<P>
   Once it is achieved, we could begin to address together the
challenges of the coming century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __ Translated from the Russian by Pavel Palazchenko. &LR; __
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Mikhail Gorbachev, the last leader of the Soviet Union before
its collapse in 1991 and a Nobel Peace Prize winner, heads the
Gorbachev Foundation for International Peace and lectures
frequently around the world on subjects related to post-Cold War
trends and politics.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
