<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STADIUM-DESIGNER-BOS &LR;      06-02 1554
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STADIUM-DESIGNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BALLPARKS, COMPANY IS IN A LEAGUE OF ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Throughout the expansive, four-floor
headquarters of HOK Sport, dozens of employees are busy designing
the real fields of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   On one floor, two architects huddle over blueprints for the new
Pittsburgh Pirates stadium. Nearby, plans for The Ballpark at Union
Station, the new home of the Houston Astros, with its distinctive,
roll-out-of-sight roof, sit on a drafting table.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell Park for the San Francisco Giants, new ballparks
for the San Diego Padres and the Cincinnati Reds, PSI Net Stadium
for the Baltimore Ravens, Philips Arena in Atlanta, and minor
league ballparks and collegiate stadiums are in various stages of
design. HOK Sport's architects also planned Stadium Australia, the
Olympic stadium in Sydney, and they are working on the replacement
for the legendary Wembley Stadium in London.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, when the Boston Red Sox decided to replace
Fenway Park, they, too, came to HOK. So did the New England
Patriots, whose new stadium will be an HOK Sport design.
</P>
<P>
   Sprouting 16 years ago from a theory that an architectural firm
could thrive by planning only sports facilities, HOK Sport has
emerged as the preeminent designer of stadiums in the country. It
has competitors, but its annual revenues are now bigger than the
next eight ranked companies combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``HOK has done for sports architecture what McDonald's did for
hamburgers, except in a very upscale way,'' said John Moag Jr.,
chairman of the Maryland Stadium Authority, for which HOK produced
both the seminal design of Oriole Park at Camden Yards and the PSI
Net Stadium. ``They were first in many respects, they put a real
good product out there, and people like it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, HOK ignited the boom in retro-styled
baseball stadiums that has swept the country. Its position as the
leading architect for the National Football League is so well
established that last year NFL officials quietly encouraged owners
to solicit other designers to help drive down HOK's fees.
</P>
<P>
   While HOK clearly covets both the Red Sox and Patriots projects,
especially the challenge of replacing Fenway Park, in many ways the
projects are just two more jobs. The firm has designed more than
500 sports facilities, and it now has more than 30 stadiums in the
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stadium design is a relatively small niche in the field, but
they have a very high profile,'' said David Lee of the Boston
architectural firm of Stull &AMP; Lee Inc., designers of the South
Station renovation and the Roxbury Post Office on New Dudley
Street. ``And they carved out that niche early. There was a period
when there wasn't that many new stadiums being built, and they were
right there when things took off.''
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded in 1983 by a small group of architects,
most of whom had worked together at various times at companies that
are now HOK's competitors. By 1988, the firm's revenues had reached
$7 million. But business accelerated after HOK designed a minor
league ballpark in Buffalo that became a new standard for stadium
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, officials in Buffalo asked HOK Sport to design
a ballpark in an old section of the city, hoping it would help
revitalize part of downtown. Originally planned as a major league
park, HOK shifted course when Buffalo was denied an expansion
franchise by Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Field became the original retro-ballpark design in the
country. It demonstrates what observers say is another of HOK's
strengths _ the ability to match a stadium to its surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a way of walking into a town and spending time in a
town before they give you anything,'' said Bob DiBiasio, a senior
vice president of the Cleveland Indians, who have had more than 300
consecutive sellouts in their HOK-designed Jacobs Field. ``Rather
than handing you some boilerplate stadium that they want to build
you, they look at the architecture in a city and the landscape in a
city _ you know, the smokestacks, the bridges over the rivers _ and
they work of off it.''
</P>
<P>
   The result in Buffalo was a downtown stadium that looks old, but
that has all of the amenties for fans and the revenue-producing
premium seating for the owner. That formula is the essence of HOK's
success in Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our design became a kind of specific solution for that city,
and that solution happened to be a retro look,'' said Earl Santee,
a partner at HOK who presides over most of the firm's baseball
designs. ``But we just started with what was a strong urban
environment, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   If there were any doubts about HOK's approach, Oriole Park at
Camden Yards confirmed the popularity of the retro design.
Reminiscent of old parks like Fenway and Wrigley Field, it
institutionalized the Pilot Field look. None of the new stadiums
look much alike, but they are reflections of the eras of Ruth,
Williams and the young Mays and Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   ``These ballparks are stated in revivalist architectural
language,'' said Robert Benson, chairman of the School of
Architecture and Design at Miami University in Ohio, and former
architecture critic for The Detroit News. ``It is a popular sense
of tradition and place, and it provides the flavor of a specific
site married to a specific community.''
</P>
<P>
   When Camden Yards was complete, HOK Sport's annual revenue had
tripled to $23 million. By 1997, revenues reached $64 million.
According to Street &AMP; Smith's SportsBusiness Journal, that was more
revenue than the combined total of the next eight largest
competitors in stadium and arena design.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we hit Oriole Park, it was clear to us that each
ballclub and each community wanted to have their own brand of
baseball, which meant a clear identity, and a clear sense of how
poeple used the facility,'' Santee said. ``And in Baltimore, Eutaw
Street, and the big warehouse, and the ambience of the old
neighborhood there, just kind of set the stage for what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, HOK is even more dominant in the National Football
League. While the strength of its new designs have powered its
asendancy in baseball, its business strategy has led it to
leadership among designers in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years and years they were the only firm that ever showed
up at the big NFL owners meeting in March,'' said a sports
consultant who asked not to be identified. ``They were always
peeling one or two key owners off.''
</P>
<P>
   The consultant also said that HOK won the favor of owners by
completing large portions of preliminary design work without
charging for it. According to the consultant, the Patriots have
received such consideration, and it has gone a long way to solidify
HOK's relationship with Robert Kraft.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots officials declined comment on the choice of HOK Sport
as their architect, and officials at HOK declined to discuss plans
for the Patriots' new stadium. Privately, officials say that the
Patriots want to take many more steps, including garnering the
approval of officials in Foxborough, before they talk about the
preliminary design of the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   HOK has worked for more than four years on the Red Sox project,
having studied various sites, from the old Megaplex design, to the
South Boston waterfront, to at least four potential sites around
Fenway Park, as well as the potential for renovation schemes.
Santee can talk about the decisions made on each site in detail,
ticking of street names and the locations of residential properties
and artists lofts as if he lived in the neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge of the Boston project is really understanding
what all of the issues are up front, and to take the time to make
sure that you are thoughtful about what the possible solutions are,
and looking at every option,'' Santee said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Red Sox unveiled their plans for a new ballpark two
weeks ago, Santee spent six days in Boston to help pitch the
proposal. When he flew back to Kansas City, the seams in the
sleeves of his jacket were badly in need of repair from hauling the
hefty model of the proposed new Fenway Park from meeting to meeting
around Boston.
</P>
<P>
   HOK, Santee said, is at the top of the mountain _ for now. He
said that eventually the boom in stadium construction will decline,
if not go completely bust. But the firm's biggest, toughest
projects are now in the works, Santee said, including the
complicated quests for new stadiums for the Red Sox and the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most difficult projects are ahead of us _ and I would
definitely put Boston in that line, just because of the time it
takes to get it done and the difficult decisions that need to be
made on a project like that,'' Santee said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the difficulty of the new projects, Santee said, is the
public's increased awareness of stadium design. If it had been 10
years ago, he said, plans for the new Fenway Park could have been
rolled out with much less preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Santee said the firm accepts the public's growing interest in
stadium design as a challenge. ``The fans are really engaged,''
Santee said. ``The days of someone coming along and slam dunking a
project down the public's throat are long gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
