<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHARKS ARE CIRCLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to be a shark to survive in the ultracompetitive auto
insurance business in Massachusetts. Right now, the sharks are
circling Trust Insurance Co., hoping to take a bite out of a
company that has been bleeding red ink.
</P>
<P>
   Trust, which has 4 percent of the state's auto insurance market,
or about 175,000 policyholders, recently reported a $21 million
loss for 1998 _ a huge loss for a relatively modest-sized company.
The setback wiped out roughly 40 percent of the Taunton company's
surplus, the cushion it has for future rainy days. Trust insists
everything is fine and that it is close to a deal that will inject
new capital into the firm.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped rivals from approaching Trust's
insurance agents in a bid to get them to defect, according to
industry sources. Those same sources say that some of Trust's
agents, worried about their future, have put out the word that they
might be interested in defecting if the price is right.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, insurance agents are free agents. They can
move their business and their customers from one insurer to
another, which makes poaching a very serious matter. It also means
that rivals have an incentive to make it sound as if Trust is on
death's doorstep and Trust has an incentive to say everything is
just ducky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regrettably some people in this industry spend their time
fanning rumors, trying to make mountains out of molehills,'' says
William Ryan, Trust's vice president of government affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors may have been fueled by the skimpy details Trust made
public to explain its whopping loss. In a press release, the
company blamed investments in a new computer system and a
``software defect in a data processing system managed by an
outsider vendor.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders say some of Trust's computer work is performed
by CGI, a company based in Montreal. When CGI executives heard
about Trust's problems, they immediately put out the word that they
weren't at fault. ``CGI has nothing to do with the performance
shortfall referred to in a previous Trust Insurance press
release,'' says Ronald White, a CGI spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan declined to elaborate on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to insurance agents mailed last month, Trust
president Craig Bradley hinted at some other possible reasons for
the loss. Bradley told the agents that Trust's line of homeowner
insurance was priced ``way below the competition,'' a situation
that has since been rectified. Bradley also refers to the ``war of
attrition in auto insurance pricing'' that has been going on for
several years in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   That price war has made it difficult for anyone to make much
money in auto insurance here. The state insurance commissioner has
cut rates more than 20 percent over four years. On top of that, the
insurers have offered major discounts to safe drivers and to
members of groups such as the American Automobile Association.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically some of the insurers try to pull back on the
discounts, but the genie of competition has proved to be difficult
to put back in the bottle. Insurers blame insurance Commissioner
Linda Ruthardt for their problems, but the heavy discounting has
made it easy for Ruthardt to justify further rate cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt's office says it spotted a ``discrepancy'' in one of
Trust's quarterly statements, which led to the discovery of the $21
million loss. The Insurance Division is currently conducting a
routine examination of Trust's books, so it cannot comment further
on the situation. A department spokesman did point out that Trust
has yet to file its results for the first quarter, information that
should have been filed by May 15.
</P>
<P>
   Trust continues to say it has the situation well in hand and
that its only problem is industry rumor-mongering. ``Our
competitors continue with their heavy-handed marketing,'' Bradley
complained to agents in a letter mailed last week. In that same
letter, Bradley said that despite the disinformation campaign,
``agency defections are no greater this year than last and they are
minimal at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust says it plans to sell two parcels of real estate that
would translate into at least $10 million that can be added to its
surplus. The company also promises that new capital is on the way
from a ``close strategic investor.''
</P>
<P>
   Trust won't name that investor but industry speculation centers
around American Re, a Princeton, N.J., reinsurance company that has
had a long and close relationship with Trust.
</P>
<P>
   Over the coming months, Trust will have to file quarterly
statements that will make clear how much progress it is making. In
an industry in which competitors traffic in rumor and innuendo,
those numbers should make it clear who can be trusted and who
cannot.
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
