A9963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WEBB-OPEN-BOS &LR;      06-02 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WEBB-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GOLFER HITS HER STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ She has that unteachable golf skill, the
ability to visualize a shot, so it shouldn't be a surprise that
Karrie Webb can see a topic heading in the wrong direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is only my fourth US Open,'' she said. ``I answered these
sorts of questions at the Dinah Shore this year. This is my 14th
major that I have ever played in. I have a long career ahead of
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, don't start asking her how much a major
championship would mean to her.
</P>
<P>
   As the 54th US Women's Open at Old Waverly Golf Club begins
Thursday, Webb is the best player in women's golf, one who has put
up an All-Star season in just five months. In 11 starts this year,
Webb has four wins, two seconds, and two thirds. She has yet to
play an event over par and her cumulative red number for the year
is a mind-boggling 137. Stroke average? Try 68.49, nearly a full
shot better than the next best.
</P>
<P>
   All of which adds up to her being the overwhelming favorite
here, right? Webb grimaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my chances are just as good as they are any year,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking the LPGA Tour by storm with four wins in 1996, Webb
has been in the spotlight. She won three times in '97, twice more
the next year, and after her early-season rush in 1999, her win
total is up to 13. All this, and she's seven months shy of her 25th
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   That's something she wishes we would remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each year I am learning how to play US Open golf courses,''
said the native of Queensland, Australia. ``I am not in a hurry to
win a major. If I win one, that is going to be great. But I think
it may just take a little bit of time.''
</P>
<P>
   A rather cautionary approach, to be sure, like a safe shot to
the middle of a green. But even Webb concedes that the young can
win this event (Korean sensation Se Ri Pak prevailed in a playoff a
year ago at the tender age of 20), and if she thinks that she'll
learn the secret to winning the US Women's Open, there's another
player in the field of 156 who begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   ``You almost think there's a way to figure it out, and there's
not,'' said Nancy Lopez, who is winless in 22 of these national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   For all of her greatness (48 wins) and for all she has meant to
women's golf, it seems unimaginable that Lopez is without a US
Women's Open. She doesn't dodge the subject, however. At 42, Lopez
rejects sympathy and embraces the yearly challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep thinking that I can (win),'' said Lopez, four times a
runner-up in the Open. ``I know there were years when I put too
much pressure on myself and years when I didn't care. But after
Pumpkin Ridge (in 1997, when she finished a tearful second to
Alison Nicholas), I realized that I need to really set that as a
goal again, and it's happening this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb does not dream of emotional victory scenarios. She is
methodical and very serious about her golf, like David Duval a
superstar behind wraparound sunglasses who demonstrates very little
emotion. Great composure is a staple to her game, but there are
times when it leaves her. Such as at last year's US Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely lost my patience with nine holes to go,'' said
Webb. ``I still had a chance at a decent tournament, and I just
really lost my patience.''
</P>
<P>
   She had opened 76-73 at Blackwulf Run in Kohler, Wis., but moved
from 48th place to 18th after a third-round 73 on a course playing
so tough that 75 felt like 65. Webb had a chance entering the final
day but ballooned to 78 and finished tied for 31st.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who kept their patience were the ones that had a
chance to win,'' said Webb.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the learning process, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
