<HEADER>
A9965 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-BARNES-ART-BOS     06-02 1516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-BARNES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIT OF A GIGGLE AT ENGLISHNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo of Julian Barnes is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julian Barnes's new novel, ``England, England,'' imagines a
fantasyland of Anglophilia that crams into the ultimate theme park
a thousand years of Englishness: everything from Robin Hood and the
royal family to Magna Carta and marmalade.
</P>
<P>
   If such a place existed, the exhibits could include Barnes, too.
He's a bit of a dream version of Englishness himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with my Englishness in the banal sense that I
can't be anything else,'' he recently explained over lunch this
week during a stop in Boston on his book tour. It goes beyond that,
though. Barnes could more than suffice as an updated Oxbridge John
Bull.
</P>
<P>
   It's more than just a matter of their sharing initials. Barnes,
53, speaks in a satiny baritone that's at once refined and relaxed:
a voice for reciting lines from a drawing-room comedy written by
Monty Python (in one of their few restrained moments).
</P>
<P>
   Charmingly self-aware, he's a blend of reserve and merriment:
polished, polite, and very funny. Barnes's manner suits his face, a
calm, bashful rectangle. Bisecting that rectangle is a great, hawky
nose whose prominence emphasizes the amused squint of his deep-set
eyes. It's a face that wouldn't have looked out of place beneath a
helmet at Agincourt, nor does the resemblance end there: Barnes has
an archer's large shoulders and thick, long fingers.
</P>
<P>
   His digits are less likely to be gripping a longbow than a cue
stick or hoe. Barnes's echt-Englishness extends beyond appearance
to avocation. His North London house boasts a well-used snooker
table, and he's a passionate gardener. He handles the vegetables,
and his wife, Patricia Kavanagh, a prominent English literary
agent, tends to the flowers.
</P>
<P>
   ``England, England'' is nicely timed. These are heady days in
the United Kingdom. For one thing, it may not be united much
longer, with Wales and Scotland likely to achieve some measure of
political independence soon. For another, there's always the chance
it might stop being a kingdom: British republicans patiently wait
for the royal family to finally wear out its welcome. As for Prime
Minister Tony Blair, he's doing his best to turn the national
orientation from glorious past to well-hyped future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blair says, `We want you to admire us for what we are and not
for what we were,' '' Barnes noted. ``I think what we `are' has not
been very firmly decided. It's not something we're good at thinking
about, not the English, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``England, England,'' Barnes does his best to rectify that.
Set in 2005, it concerns the efforts of media mogul Sir Jack Pitman
_ imagine Rupert Murdoch on a bad day _ to honor his homeland and
turn a healthy profit. After surveying prospective theme-park
patrons on the ``Fifty Quintessences of Englishness,'' Sir Jack
proceeds to assemble them (either the actual item or a reasonable
facsimile) and moves them to the Isle of Wight, just off the
southern English coast.
</P>
<P>
   It's all quite ridiculous, of course, except that life has
already begun to imitate Barnes's art. The third item on the list
is the Manchester United Football Club, which is to soccer what the
New York Yankees are to baseball. Last summer, Murdoch tried to buy
the team. Unlike Sir Jack, he failed. The British edition of
``England, England'' was published a few weeks before Murdoch
announced his bid. ``Whenever I'd read that section of the book,''
Barnes said with a smile, ``I'd try to avoid all sort of
self-congratulation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, at least, Barnes is atypical. Since Blair's
election two years ago, Britain has been awash in
self-congratulation under the banner of ``Cool Britannia,'' which
sounds suspiciously like something Sir Jack had his marketing
people work up. Instead, Barnes assigns the blame elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all Newsweek's fault,'' he laughed. ``They sent (over)
some poor journalist who'd had it explained to him how horrible
London would be. . . . He had a nice meal. He went to a nice club.
He met a nice girl. He had a nice drink. And all of a sudden
Britain's swinging again! Whereupon the government dropped on to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's true. If you go to Paris, they say, `Paris is so
dull. London is where it's at.' I've been taking the Eurostar train
(to France), and at 11 o'clock in the morning it's full of
hung-over Dutch and German kids who've gone to London for a good
night's clubbing. The youth culture, the drug culture, the club
culture is maybe the best in Europe _ not my speciality _ but the
idea that all of a sudden you can get a good meal in London, all of
a sudden people have smiles on their faces there which they haven't
in 20 years, is preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists and even the general public might be living it up in
Britain, but things have clearly settled down at Buckingham Palace.
Oh, there's the occasional headline about the son of Prince
Charles's inamorata, Camilla Parker-Bowles, using cocaine, or a
tabloid photo capturing Prince Edward's fiancee bare-breasted.
Still, by recent standards, it's been all quiet on the royal front.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to hand it to them,'' Barnes agreed. ``They are
immensely resilient. I went to see Diana's funeral cortege pass by
with some friends. One said, `Well, this has made the royal family
safe for another hundred years.' I think it's true. They've behaved
quite cannily, as well. They've allowed her to be sort of canonized
while at the same time repositioning Prince Charles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the emotional bind that the Diana-philes are in is
they say, `Beastly royal family: They were frightful to St. Diana!
Now she's dead, let's get rid of the royal family!' They can't do
that because that would be disenfranchising Diana's children . . .
the elder of whom looks so much like Diana it's uncanny _ the shy
sulkiness, the underhung lip and jaw.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barnes grew up in suburban London, the son of schoolteachers. It
was a boyhood out of the poetry of Philip Larkin _ emotionally
tidy, culturally intent, resolutely understated _ English
middle-class life at its most middling. There were seaside family
holidays (the first overnight vacation Barnes remembers was to the
Isle of Wight) and the long train rides each weekday he took into
the city and back for school.
</P>
<P>
   The one incongruous element in an otherwise uncompromisingly
English upbringing derived from the subject Barnes's parents
taught: French. Growing up in a household abuzz with circumflexes
and cedillas helped foster in Barnes and his older brother,
Jonathan, now a philosophy professor at the University of Geneva, a
most un-English cosmopolitanism.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, only someone deeply in love with French culture could
have written Barnes's most celebrated novel, ``Flaubert's Parrot''
(1984). ``I go to France as often as I can,'' he said over lunch,
and just before starting his book tour he and his wife spent a week
in St.-Paul-de-Vence. Barnes makes light of his French, but to hear
the bouquet of vowel and consonant he makes of the words
``sauvignon'' and ``blanc'' when he orders a glass of wine is to
feel a breeze off the banks of the Loire.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Barnes, who went to Oxford, majored in French.
After graduation, he spent three years working as a lexicographer
for the Oxford English Dictionary. He once described his assignment
as the ``sports and dirty-word department.'' He briefly studied law
in London, then turned to literary journalism. It took him eight
years to write his first novel, ``Metroland,'' published in 1981.
He's since made up for lost time with seven more novels, a short
story collection, a gathering of his ``Letters From London'' for
The New Yorker, and four detective novels under the pen name Dan
Kavanagh.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at home and writing, it's a morning's work, and then
it's an afternoon of desk-clearing, bill-paying, servicing the
career _ `after-sales service,' as they call it in France _ maybe a
walk on (Hampstead) Heath, and then something social or out to a
concert in the evening. I like being alone through the day as long
as I know I'm getting society at the end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   That society tends to be literary. Barnes belongs to a circle
that includes his fellow novelists Salman Rushdie, Ian McEwan, and
Kazuo Ishiguro. It used to be a quintet of novelists, until Martin
Amis abruptly dumped Barnes's wife as his agent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lots of friends who are writers, and a lot of them are
very good. I like that. . . . I'm not one of those writers who
wants to be the only writer in their social group. There are two
ways of looking at it: Some people are threatened by it, and others
feel they've gotten their fill and want to spend time with real
people. I count writers as real people, despite some evidence to
the contrary.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
