<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-INVESTING-BOS &LR;      06-02 1536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-INVESTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFIT AND PRINCIPLE: INVESTING WITH SOCIAL CONSCIOUSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the New England Aquarium went shopping recently for a new
investment choice to add to its employee retirement plan, it joined
The Gap, Hewlett-Packard, and the American Medical Association in
choosing an alternative dedicated to principles as well as profits.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual fund that the Aquarium selected, Domini Social
Equity, marries the pursuit of riches with environmental and social
concerns by shunning stocks in companies that pollute,
discriminate, or make harmful products.
</P>
<P>
   Such do-good funds, whose ideological roots lie in the
18th-century Quakers' aversion to liquor and gambling outfits, have
quietly gained in popularity among some investors in recent years.
Now they are starting to show up in retirement plans, the principal
savings vehicles for millions of working Americans.
</P>
<P>
   So-called socially responsible funds generally avoid investing
in companies that make cigarettes, alcohol, or military weapons,
and employ elaborate screens to select firms based on their
environmental record or hiring policies.
</P>
<P>
   But as they exhort investors to make ethical choices and seek to
improve corporate America, principled portfolios raise a host of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that socially responsible funds hold most of the
same blue chips that other funds hold, and decry them as mostly a
clever sales pitch. What is so virtuous, they ask, about owning the
Wal-Marts and Intels everyone else has?
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think of the missionaries who went to Hawaii to do
good and wound up doing well by owning lots of land,'' said A.
Michael Lipper, chairman of Lipper Inc., the fund tracking firm.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, socially responsible stock funds _ there are around
50 of them _ are still only a fraction of the nation's $5.5
trillion fund business, which offers investors more than 8,000
different funds. Barely several hundred of the country's more than
700,000 retirement plans include a social fund.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons? Many such funds are viewed as underperformers that
swap returns for political correctness _ not a selling point in a
bull market. The average socially responsible growth fund gained
11.6 percent over the past 12 months, compared with 19 percent for
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, the broad market measure that has
produced most of Wall Street's gains in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many corporate retirement plan sponsors fear they could be
shirking their duties in offering a fund that may produce lower
returns by refusing to own certain stocks. Against that
conservative ethic, only well-known, mainstream funds tend to make
it into 401(k) retirement plans.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, improved returns by many social portfolios have
given them fresh appeal. Sales of such funds, a mere $70 million in
1995, were $520 million over the first four months of this year,
nearly as much as in all of 1998, according to Lipper. The rise
comes amid a slowdown in general equity fund sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Vanguard Group, a giant fund firm that is considering
creating a socially responsible fund, has seen ``a modest uptick''
in demand for such portfolios, according to spokesman John Woerth.
</P>
<P>
   David L. Wray, president of the Profit Sharing/401(k) Council of
America, a group for retirement-plan providers, said that state
associations, nonprofits, and university endowments are especially
keen on social funds, since they have fewer legal shackles than
companies in choosing retirement plan offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most traditional money managers are troubled by the
subjective criteria that social portfolios use to anoint one stock
but skewer another.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do see some interest for socially responsible funds from
retirement plan sponsors, primarily nonprofits,'' said Debra
McConnell, a spokeswoman for Fidelity Investments, the nation's
biggest fund firm and manager of one in four US retirement plans.
But while Fidelity sells Domini's fund, it has no plans to create a
similar fund of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue for us,'' McConnell said, ``is that it's difficult
to define what is socially responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those who fervently believe that investors can change the
world wrestle with that question.
</P>
<P>
   Take Amy L. Domini, the doyenne of social investing and manager
of Domini Social Equity.
</P>
<P>
   Domini won't buy shares in General Electric, whose operations
include defense contracting, or Texaco, the oil giant that had
problems with discrimination. And she doesn't own shoemaker Nike,
because of its alleged sweatshop operations in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   But she does hold Reebok _ a competitor accused of the same
offense. ``Nike was removed from the index because so many
activists called for it and it attracted so much attention,''
Domini explained. ``Until they do the same to Reebok, it stays on
the list.''
</P>
<P>
   And take Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Domini loves the retailer's ``Buy America'' stance and focus on
recycled packaging. But she admits to discomfort over Wal-Mart's
sales of guns, especially after the school shootings in Littleton,
Colo. ``Wal-Mart sells guns but doesn't make them, so they don't
flunk the gun screen,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Merck, a pharmaceutical stock that many social
funds shun. Domini owns it, despite Merck's 12 Superfund
environmental cleanup sites. The reason: the company also spends $1
million a year on a biodiversity project in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   ``The definitions can get a little squishy,'' said Domini,
adding that she did not see gray areas as a deterrent to cracking
the lucrative retirement plan market.
</P>
<P>
   ``But maybe investors don't need to define what's socially
responsible,'' she said. ``Maybe they just need to become better.''
</P>
<P>
   Investor habits are a window onto the Zeitgeist, and observers
posit various causes behind recent fresh interest in social
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Investing with a conscience first emerged in the 1980s as a way
for investors to avoid stocks in companies that did business in
apartheid-era South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   These days, according to Steve Scheuth, president of the
non-profit Social Investment Forum, concern over corporate
polluters and workplace diversity have replaced political worries.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that far from becoming more ethical, investors are
simply chasing returns that let them feel good _ the wealth effect
with a guilty conscience. Others observers, like Lipper, wonder if
images of Kosovo refugees aren't subconsciously spurring do-good
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Still others point to lawsuits that have demonized tobacco
makers, Hollywood's support of Tibet, and a rise in shareholder
activism. Marketers cite a growing willingness by consumers to ally
purchasing habits with personal ethics _ a philosophy behind niche
social funds like the Timothy Fund, which targets Christian
fundamentalists opposed to companies associated with abortion, and
the MFS Union Standard Equity fund, which is designed to appeal to
labor union supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, the interest is palpable. At Domini Social
Investments, the Boston and New York firm that launched modern
social investing, Domini Social Equity has tripled in assets in the
past 15 months _ in part to a rising stock market, but also due to
a flood of new cash. The fund, which has $966 million in assets and
is the best known of the genre, is taking in $2 million a day in
new money, four times 1997's level.
</P>
<P>
   More tellingly, one-quarter of its assets are now in retirement
plans, compared with 1 percent in 1998. At the Wisconsin Education
Association, a teachers' union, employees are putting nearly as
much retirement cash into Domini's fund as into Vanguard's popular
Index 500 fund.
</P>
<P>
   One appeal of Domini's portfolio is its index fund structure _
the flavor of the moment among investors. The portfolio holds 400
stocks that Domini and partners have screened for their Domini
Social Index, a barometer styled as an ``ethical'' version of the
S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   But Domini Social Equity's main draw may be its long-term
results. While up only 3.2 percent this year through last Thursday,
less than the average growth fund, it rose 33 percent in 1998 and
36 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With its Puritan overtones, it is no surprise to find social
investing's modern capital in New England and nearby. A dozen or so
outfits, led by Domini and including Citizens Trust in Portsmouth,
N.H.; Progessive Asset Management in Wellesley; the Calvert Group
in Bethesda, Md.; and Trillium Asset Management and Green Century
Funds, both of Boston, manage money and analyze companies' hiring
practices, community involvement, product safety, and employee
relations.
</P>
<P>
   Some firms file shareholder resolutions at companies whose
stocks they own. Those actions, Domini said, empower investors and
help corporations improve their practices.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lipper said social funds will never have more than a
niche appeal to investors.
</P>
<P>
   But others see a different future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that a company like Hewlett-Packard now has a social
fund,'' said Wray, the retirement forum head, ``will make the rest
of the business community sit up and take notice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
