<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9970 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGAZINE MARKS SERIOUS STRIDES, BUT WHAT OF KIDS? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Twenty years ago this month, a group of women writers and
editors came up with a novel idea: Why not create a magazine that
speaks to the concerns of working mothers?
</P>
<P>
   A test issue of ``Working Mother'' magazine, which was published
in 1978, included an article entitled, ``How Can I Leave That Baby?
Mothers Tell Why They Return To Work So Soon After Birth Of Their
Babies.'' Another explained how children rate babysitters. An
overwhelming response to that edition led to the magazine's birth
in 1979. Since then, circulation has grown from 200,000 to 925,000.
</P>
<P>
   Two decades later, it is clear that the influx of women into the
workplace, the growing reliance on technology, and a changing
economy have had a profound impact on how and where we work.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that had valued ``face time'' above all else now have
programs that include part-time work, job sharing and four-day work
weeks. Workers who were once tied to the office now work from home,
with the help of computers, faxes, e-mail and video conferencing.
Some firms now have day-care centers on their corporate campuses,
while others are erecting schools. Paternity leave, not as
widespread as maternity leave, offers a small cadre of fathers time
to bond with their children. And a push to expand the Families and
Medical Leave Act to include paid time off is expected to extend
the benefit to those who can ill afford any time off from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pioneers, women who went to work in the 1960s, faced
blatant sexism at work and at home,'' said Judsen Culbreth,
editor-in-chief of ``Working Mother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was common practice for a woman to hand in her resignation
at the same time that she announced her pregnancy. In contrast,
women starting their careers in the 1990s, the inheritors, are
likely to be given a tour of the lactation facility and on-site
day-care center,'' Judsen said.
</P>
<P>
   But while today's working mothers have far more options than the
women whom ``Working Mother'' first profiled, many have similar
concerns. New mothers still feel guilty about leaving their young
children, even when they know the children are being cared for
properly.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, sociologist Nancy Chodorow said that some of the
guilt working women were feeling had stemmed from the way they had
been socialized, and from the fact that men were not assuming full
parenting roles. Chodorow reasoned that if women did all the child
management and household chores, their daughters would acquire
attributes necessary for mothering.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Chodorow said, their boys would avoid the very
qualities the mothers were trying to teach. She maintained that
when raised in households where women always care for the young,
boys assume dominant, masculine roles to prove their masculinity.
To break the cycle, men and women must begin to share parenting,
Chodorow reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, men and women are still grappling with this
issue. One reason, said Francine M. Deutsch, author of ``Halving It
All: How Equally Shared Parenting Works,'' (Harvard University
Press 1999, $24.95) is that men's attempts at hands-on parenting
are often ignored or treated as aberrations, by outsiders, and
sometimes by wives. The wives, it was found, are afraid to
relinquish part of their role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers are often treated like invisible parents,'' Deutsch
said. ``Imagine this scenario: The mother of a child's friend calls
to arrange a play date. Dad answers the phone. The mother who has
called asks to speak to the child's mother. In this very normal and
everyday occurrence, the father, who is expected not to know
anything about playdates, has been told that he is superfluous.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsch says the expectation that women know more about child
care than men has become a reality because women have been given
more encouragement. Moreover, men have been forced to act like
invisible dads in the workplace, especially in traditional
corporate cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Powerful social expectations are conveyed even before the baby
is born,'' Deutsch wrote in her book. One father, identified only
as ``Larry,'' took paternity leave so that he could bond with his
newborn child and was surprised by the differences in questions
that were posed to him and his wife after the infant's birth.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that when his wife, Joyce, was pregnant, people said
to her, ``So, when are you quitting work?'' They turned to him and
asked whether he planned to take on more hours, or another job, not
realizing that the couple had decided that Joyce would work
full-time while Larry worked fewer hours to care for the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a working mother must still fight to retain her
standing in a corporate world that assumes she will be less engaged
in her job once her baby is born. Some mothers never mention their
children at work, or show their pictures, for fear that such
displays might be seen as unprofessional. Others become Super Moms,
a tendency that almost became the norm in the 1980s, when women
were first trying to climb the corporate ladder.
</P>
<P>
   In its anniversary issue, ``Working Mother,'' reported that
women have gained more than a toehold on that ladder. Armed with
undergraduate and advanced degrees, many are now primary
breadwinners. In fact, of 54 million households with married
couples, 5.5 percent now rely on the wife to bring home a
significant chunk of the family's total income. And, in some
dual-earner families, nearly 25 percent of the women earn more than
their husbands, up from 18 percent in 1987 and 4.4 percent in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The women's organization Catalyst reported that of 461 female
vice presidents surveyed in 1996, 75 percent were primary
breadwinners. In addition, 72 percent were married, and 64 percent
had children.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of these changes is that the issue of sharing
responsibility at home, for the first time, is being turned on its
head. Now the biggest challenge is whether working mothers and
fathers who share child care and housework can fully alter their
workplaces and social norms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are now seeing is that more and more parents, not just
women, are demanding flexibility and are bucking the whole issue of
face-time,'' Katherine Cartwright, senior editor of ``Working
Mother,'' said. ``Women have tried for years, but we also need dads
to buy into this in order to take it to the next level. Slowly, we
are getting there. But I think it will take another 20 years before
we can look back and say, `Look how far we've come.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Questions, comments, story ideas? Contact Diane E. Lewis at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
