<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PROFILE-SAYLES-H     06-02 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PROFILE-SAYLES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL WORK AND LITTLE PLAY FOR DIRECTOR OF `LIMBO' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ John Sayles doesn't look bad for a guy who has
just spent the past two weeks hawking his 12th movie to gaggles of
international reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He emerges from the bedroom of the San Francisco hotel suite
he's sharing with his longtime producer and equally dedicated
partner, Maggie Renzi, with a vague Cannes hangover. There, he'd
been practically asking to be drummed into numbness by giving 20 to
30 interviews a day because his film ``Limbo'' had been selected to
compete for the Palme D'Or, the festival's biggest prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to Cannes maybe five times and I think I've seen one
movie,'' he sighed. ``It's wall-to-wall work. It's nice to show the
film, but it's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Sayles' meeting the foreign press was as much a grassroots
public-relations blitz as it was a campaign to sway the haute
couture masses _ and on a smaller level the jury, which was led
this year by Canadian fleshmeister David Cronenberg.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work. The Palme D'Or went to a French film no one had
expected would win called ``Rosetta.'' But ultimately it was a nice
deal for team Sayles _ particularly for Renzi, whose neck is
temporarily locked in a brace thanks to bad yoga. Not only did she
and Sayles generate word of mouth for ``Limbo,'' but she got to see
her beloved saunter down that red carpet in an Armani tux.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something men should know about women,'' she beamed.
``It's a stupid formal uniform, but, golly, he looked good!''
</P>
<P>
   Today, dressed in a pair of faded deep gray khakis and a
shortsleeved pink button-down, Sayles looks like he's been
delivered from the Croisette to a less glamorous realm; he evokes
your favorite English professor or a good friend's dad. In middle
age, the 49-year-old writer-director's face has taken on the early
traces of the taut leathery lines and creases that have settled
into the rawhide skin of Clint Eastwood, who, also well over 6
feet, could be Sayles' more sinewy doppelganger. Sayles' mouth has
a similar pencil-thinness, but his lips curve up into a tiny,
permanent smile, where Eastwood's lie slightly askew in a more
intimidating scowl.
</P>
<P>
   But it's their eyes that actually separate them. Eastwood's
remain locked in an impenetrable squint that seems focused on an
object in his sightline that he appears to hold in contempt.
Sayles' are wide open, roving, probing, but not with X-ray-vision
presumption _ he would never suppose he could see through you.
Rather, he looks into you to allow you to reveal your strengths and
shortcomings yourself, without passing judgment on them, letting
the evidence speak for itself.
</P>
<P>
   That physical point of departure _ the eyes _ aptly characterize
what makes Sayles one of the sager figures making movies about
America in the increasingly dehumanized final moments of the 20th
century. Sayles' large vision has an attention to detail that is
uncanny, almost atavistic at a time when directors increasingly
rely on the visual details of storytelling: How much hellzapoppin'
and star-power can distract from the fact that nothing's happening?
</P>
<P>
   That would explain why Sayles abandoned the music video industry
after directing three Bruce Springsteen clips, most notably the
sweetly suggestive ``I'm on Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments in Sayles' movies are usually composed, then placed on a
large historical or geographical canvas: 1920s miner/union strife
(``Matewan''), the 1919 Chicago Black Sox scandal (``Eight Men
Out''), the revisionist West (``Lone Star''). Twice they've crossed
the border (``Men With Guns'') or have sailed overseas (the Irish
``Secret of Roan Inish''), but what unites the disparate themes of
his films is that eye, which is wholly devoted to the investment of
humanity to the characters living on the pages of his scripts.
</P>
<P>
   In a given film, Sayles' ambulatory Steadicam can follow up to
30 significant characters whose dialogue overlaps into a braided
assortment of regional patois. And his generosity as a writer and
his indifference to having stars in his films for the sake of
making a buck often has side characters endowed with large
monologues and lead actors who speak nary a word.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
