<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0018 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-     06-02 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEANING AND REPAIRING SCREENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the spring and summer months, homeowners keep their
windows open to allow fresh air to circulate through the house. It
is important to make sure the screens are clean before opening the
windows; otherwise, dirt on the screens will blow into the house.
Dirty screens can also obscure visibility and restrict air flow.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to clean the screens is by washing them on a flat
surface, like a picnic table. First, cover the table with an old
rug or towels. Wet the screens by spraying them with a garden hose,
then scrub them with a soft-bristle brush and detergent solution.
Rinse the screens with another spray, then stand them against a
wall so they can air-dry.
</P>
<P>
   You can also clean window screens with foaming bathroom cleaner,
although this can be expensive if you have a lot of screens to
clean. Spray the foam on the screens and let it set for a few
minutes, then rinse it off with the garden hose. Foaming cleaner
should not be used on plastic screens, only metal ones, because it
can erode the material.
</P>
<P>
   As you wash the screens, inspect them carefully for tears and
holes that could let insects inside. Small holes can sometimes be
filled with quick-drying waterproof glue. Place a drop or two of
glue on the screen and spread it over the hole with a toothpick.
Use acetone-based glue for fiberglass screens, but read the label
first (or test it on spare screen fabric) to make sure it will not
melt the material.
</P>
<P>
   Repair tears by temporarily holding the torn edges together with
masking tape. Place the tape on one side of the screen and spread
glue across the tear on the other side. Allow time for the glue to
dry, then gently pull off the tape.
</P>
<P>
   You can repair a larger hole with a patch. Most hardware stores
and home centers stock press-on patches for aluminum screens. These
patches have small hooks around the perimeter that grip the mesh
around the hole in the screen.
</P>
<P>
   You can also make your own repair from spare screening material.
Use scissors or tin snips to cut a patch larger than the hole.
Unravel the wire around the edges of the patch to create a fringe
about 1/2-inch wide on all four sides. Bend the free ends of the
patch and push them through the mesh around the hole in the screen.
For aluminum and metal screens, you can bend the ends back on the
other side to secure the patch in place. For plastic or fiberglass
screens, you will need glue to hold the patch in place.
</P>
<P>
   Patches made from new aluminum screening will be bright and
contrast with the old screening. Darken the patches by spraying
them with flat black enamel.
</P>
<P>
   Screens with extensive damage should be replaced. If the frame
is solid and in good shape, you only need a roll of new screening
material. Screening material is available in fiberglass and
aluminum. Aluminum is more durable, and more expensive. It is also
less forgiving if you make a mistake when you are installing it.
Once you press aluminum screening into the frame grooves, it forms
permanent crimps that cannot be flattened out.
</P>
<P>
   You will also need a package of spline -- the flexible strip
that locks the screening in the groove -- and a rolling tool to
install the spline. All of these items are available at home
centers and well-stocked hardware stores.
</P>
<P>
   Use a narrow-tipped screwdriver to pull out the old spline from
the screen frame. Remove the screening and discard it. Cut a new
piece of screening to the outside dimensions the frame. Center the
piece on the frame, then cut each corner at a 45-degree angle at
the point where the spline grooves meet. These cuts will keep the
screening from bunching up at the corners when the spline is
installed.
</P>
<P>
   With the rolling tool push the spline and screening into the
frame groove. Begin at one corner and work your way around the
frame. The screening material may wrinkle as you roll the spline in
place. A few small wrinkles are acceptable; they will flatten out
when the splining is complete. If the screening bunches up, pull
the spline out, smooth the screen, then replace the spline.
</P>
<P>
   At the corners push the spline ends into the groove with a dull
screwdriver. Trim any excess with a utility knife so the ends butt
together.
</P>
<P>
   After the spline is in place, use aviation snips, or a utility
knife with a sharp blade, to trim the excess screen material around
the spline. If you use a utility knife, hold it in a horizontal
position so the blade is parallel to the screen frame and points
toward the outside edge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
