<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Booting Up In `Safe Mode' &QL; 
Q. What's so safe about Safe Mode in Windows? What exactly does it
do when you restart in Safe Mode? A. If you are having system
problems that cause Windows to hang or freeze when you boot up your
computer normally, Safe Mode is an option you can pick from the
start-up menu. (To get to the menu with the start-up choices,
Windows 98 users should press the Control key as the computer
restarts. Windows 95 users should press F8.)
</P>
<P>
   Windows will also boot in Safe Mode automatically if it is
having a problem. When in Safe Mode, Windows will load only a
simple system configuration that temporarily disables the drivers
for your hardware devices (except for keyboard and mouse) and uses
only the standard video adapter for your monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason to start in Safe Mode is to get the system up
and running so that you can begin to figure out why it won't boot
normally. If the machine starts in Safe Mode without a problem,
then there might be a hardware conflict, incompatible programs or
device driver programs, or system configuration problems. If you
had recently installed a hardware device or new software before the
problems started, you should uninstall it and try to boot normally
to see if the problem goes away.
</P>
<P>
   Macintosh users who are experiencing unexplained crashes or
freezes as the machine starts up can also load a minimal system
configuration for troubleshooting. As the Mac reboots, hold down
the Shift key to temporarily disable the nonessential extensions
and control panels.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Q. Is it possible to send e-mail to more than one address
simultaneously without revealing each recipient's name and e-mail
address?  &QL; 
 &QL; 
A. Just about every e-mail program has an option in the header
field called ``Bcc.'' This stands for blind carbon copy, and it
lets you fill in addresses that you can see on your original
message, but your recipients cannot. Most programs will just show
the recipient's address in the header field, or display the line
``recipient list suppressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Blind carbon copy is used quite a bit for mailings to large
numbers of people _ the notorious junk mail from spammers, for
example _ and in corporate situations where e-mail memos are
discreetly sent to other recipients.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959 or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(AT)nytimes.com.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
