<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DORA GALITZKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Better Redder  &QL; 
Q. When I recently purchased a maroon-leaved form of Cimicifuga,
the nurseryman told me it needs a lot of sun. I have other,
green-leaved Cimicifugas that I know are shade plants. Where will
the maroon-leaved one do best?  &QL; 
A. Exactly why some plants have purple-red foliage is not
completely understood, but their appeal is clear, and plant
breeders have been offering more of them.
</P>
<P>
   The compounds in the leaves that cause the red color are
anthocyanins, which are composed of, among other things, sugars.
The more light the plant receives, the more sugars it makes, and
more sugars mean more anthocyanins. So, everything else being
equal, the purple colors will be more vivid when the plant gets
more light, and duller, with more green, when grown in shade.
</P>
<P>
   But remember, when there is more sun, the soil dries out faster
and the Cimicifuga (whose botanical name has recently been changed
to Actaea) will use water faster than its green relatives in the
shade. You want it to be red because it's happy, not because it's
stressed and hollering for water. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sour Grapes  &QL; 
Q. I planted a two-year-old grapevine about four years ago. Two
years later, I had plenty of tiny bunches of grapes on the vine,
but they grew only to the size of buckshot. Last year, I had many
more bunches. The grapes grew a little bigger, but then quit. Am I
going to taste a grape this year, or am I going to be buying my
grapes in the supermarket again? Please help.  &QL; 
A. There's a reason wine costs so much: grapes can be hard to grow
well. The period starting two or three weeks before flowering and
lasting until two or three weeks after the fruit sets is fraught
with danger. During that time, the plants are especially vulnerable
to several fungus diseases, including black rot, the disease that
is most likely causing your problems.
</P>
<P>
   Proper cultivation can help produce a better crop of grapes.
Don't overfertilize, which encourages the growth of leaves at the
expense of fruit. Don't ask more of your vines than they are
prepared to give: thin them to four to six fruit-bearing shoots for
each foot of vine. In the spring, before the buds swell, prune the
vine enough, so that when the grape clusters form, they will have
plenty of light and good air circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Wise, viticulture research specialist at Cornell
Cooperative Extension of Suffolk County in Riverhead, N.Y., said
that black rot did not respond well to most low-toxicity
fungicides, leaving homeowners with few choices. Copper- and
sulfur-based sprays, common treatments for fungus diseases, may not
be a good answer because many grape varieties are very sensitive to
them, and spraying may burn the leaves. If you do choose to use a
fungicide labeled for use on grapes, be sure to follow the
directions carefully, especially if you intend to eat or make wine
from the grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Since your trellises are already set up, why not switch to
morning glories? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Those Basils of Yesteryear  &QL; 
Q. I adore basil. A few years ago, it was a fabulous herb, aromatic
and delicious. It had small leaves, and one needed only to brush it
to be overwhelmed by its exquisite aroma. The taste of pesto sauce
was divine. Today, stores offer a basil that has huge, tasteless,
bitter leaves, aroma-less. Does anyone still sell basil seeds for
planting that hark back to what was?  &QL; 
A. In the beginning, there was basil, and it was good. And instead
of resting, breeders hybridized and selected and cross-pollinated
and experimented, and it was, perhaps, not so good for traditional
culinary use, but terrific for new ethnic dishes (think Thai) and
for ornamental use (think tiny, frilly or wrinkled, green splashed
with purple ).
</P>
<P>
   So now there are dozens of variations of Ocimum basilicum. The
straight species is usually called sweet basil, and is still widely
grown, but each cultivar has its own idiosyncrasies, fans and uses.
Trying to declare one basil to be the best is just asking for an
argument. Try several (seeds and seedlings are still some of the
best bargains around), and choose the one that suits you.
</P>
<P>
   Sources for basil include Shady Acres Herb Farm, 7815 Highway
212, Chaska, Minn. 55318, (612) 466-3391, catalog $3; and
Shepherd's Garden Seeds, 30 Irene Street, Torrington, Conn. 06790,
(860) 482-3638, free catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, all right. Genovese. There, I've said it. Genovese is the
best basil for tearing up onto sliced tomatoes or for pounding into
pesto. And I expect I'll hear a few contrary opinions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43d St., New York 10036, or by e-mail to gardening(AT)nytimes.com.
Those of general interest will be published. Unpublished questions
cannot be answered individually. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
