<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NINTENDO-GAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINTENDO CHARACTERS SHOW DARKER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nintendo has always been considered the kinder, gentler console.
When Sega's Mortal Kombat was splashing gore across the screen,
Nintendo had Mario. The Playstation is home to gun-slinging Lara
Croft and the industrial destruction zone of Metal Gear Solid.
Nintendo has the Legend of Zelda, a magical adventure set in the
verdant kingdom of Hyrule.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo characters are round. Nintendo characters are cute.
</P>
<P>
   Nintendo characters have gone ballistic.
</P>
<P>
   In Super Smash Bros., all of the sweet, cuddly characters we've
grown to love over the years have been thrown into the ring. That's
right: combat. No holds barred.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine all the puppets on ``Rogers' Neighborhood'' suddenly on
the rampage, and you'll have some idea of how darkly absurd and
thrilling Super Smash Bros. can be. This is a game that allows
Yoshi, Mario's endearing dinosaur sidekick, to beat his little
friend into submission. Link, the Legend of Zelda's knight errant,
can throw Donkey Kong over a cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Pokemon's adorable mascot, Pikachu, sneezes destruction. It's a
high-pitched baby sneeze _ ``Pika-CHOO!'' Then lightning bolts
shoot out of his dainty mouth, frying anything within range.
</P>
<P>
   Kirby, the most adorable creature in Nintendo's pantheon _ a
pink puffball with blinky eyes _ turns out to be hiding a machete
somewhere in that little round body, and if you hit the right
button combination, he wields it with a viciousness you wouldn't
expect from a plush animal.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small arsenal of shiny, happy weapons, if you're
quick enough to pick them up when they spontaneously appear. A
bowling ball with legs will explode if lobbed at the enemy, or just
waddle around until its timer reaches zero.
</P>
<P>
   A fire flower, once plucked, functions as a flame thrower. A
magic wand can be used to shoot stars at your opponents from a
distance or clobber them over the head at close range.
</P>
<P>
   All of this takes place in a series of environments that make
Disneyland look gothic. Mario's battle zone is in the upper reaches
of Princess Peach's castle. On Yoshi's home turf, a pink
heart-shaped sun smiles, showering sunbeams through orange and blue
clouds. In Kirby's Dreamland, the Teletubbies would not look out of
place among the friendly trees, crystalline water puddles and
pastel flowers dotting an emerald lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a combat game in this environment, with these
characters, is shocking and funny, and vaguely horrifying. It's
like seeing ``Das Boot'' staged aboard the Yellow Submarine _ a
dizzying cocktail of aggression and kitsch. David Lynch could not
have done it better.
</P>
<P>
   And you have to hand it to Nintendo for giving its candyland a
sharp elbow to the ribs. Because it's more fun to watch martial
arts performed by stuffed animals. It's exciting, because stuffed
animals are not supposed to be gladiators. They're meant to be
soft, harmless cuddling objects.
</P>
<P>
   Watching them clobber one another is a subversive thrill on the
order of ``South Park'' or ``Celebrity Death Match.'' Probably more
so, because it introduces an element of uncertainty into a universe
of plush merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   After you've seen Kirby whip a giant blade out of nowhere, it's
hard to trust your Kirby doll in the same unconditional way. Do you
really want it in your room while you're sleeping?
</P>
<P>
   It's mind-boggling that Nintendo would put Mario in the same
category as Chuckie. And it's equally surprising that the company
would allow its characters, who are all supposed to be friends, to
shake it up.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, kids do this all the time with their toys. Little
boys set G.I. Joe on fire and little girls hack Barbie's hair off,
but not with the blessings of Hasbro and Mattel. (I have yet to see
a commercial with Barbie and Skipper in a cat fight.)
</P>
<P>
   But this is the sort of play-acting that Nintendo has sanctioned
with Super Smash Bros. Forget the Super Friends. In the Smash Bros.
arena, it's every elf, dinosaur, plumber and gorilla for himself.
There are levels where Donkey Kong might fight with you against
Mario and Luigi. But in the next level, he's not going to show you
any mercy.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what makes a combat game different from an adventure
game or a shooter, or any of the other genres that feature Nintendo
characters. In a combat game, there are no good guys. There are no
bad guys. There are only winners and losers.
</P>
<P>
   In that way, it's much more like an athletic event than an
odyssey or quest, Nintendo's stock in trade. Every character has
the right to win, and you can root for any contender because of his
skill, or for purely personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mario: eye of the tiger, babe. Eye of the tiger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1555EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
