<HEADER>
A0034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GUNS03-COX     06-02 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GUNS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TO PRESS HOUSE FOR STRONGER GUN MEASURES, AIDE SAYS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration will press the House for
stricter gun controls than those contained in a bill approved by
the Senate, President Clinton's chief domestic policy adviser,
Bruce Reed, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast with reporters, Reed said the administration
would seek to raise the minimum age for purchasing a handgun from
18 to 21 and to require background checks on anyone who buys
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also will push to renew the federal law
requiring a three-day waiting period for obtaining guns. The law
expires this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``the only way to reduce the chances of more Littletons
is to attack on all fronts,'' Reed said, expanded gun control
measures would help prevent the kind of tragedy that occurred at
Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Littleton was a defining moment,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the deaths of 14 students and a teacher at Columbine
High led the Senate to pass legislation that would require
mandatory background checks on gun buyers at gun shows, require
trigger locks or similar safety devices to be sold with handguns,
and ban the importation of high-capacity ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP House leadership, which only four years ago vowed to
repeal a ban on assault weapons enacted at Clinton's behest, has
now agreed to vote on a version of the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those rare times when the national consensus
demands that we act,'' House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said
just before Congress recessed last week for the Memorial Day
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Reed's comments Wednesday are an indication that the
administration senses that after the Littleton tragedy, and last
month's wounding of students at a high school in Conyers, Ga., the
country is ready for stronger gun control concessions than the
House is prepared to offer.
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll last week indicated that 66 percent of Americans
believe gun ownership laws should be stricter, while only 7 percent
said such laws should be relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only 10 states prohibit the sale of handguns to
persons under 21: Connecticut, Georgia, Hawaii, Iowa, Maryland,
Missouri, Nebraska, Ohio, Rhode Island and South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association, the chief lobbying organization
for gun owners, is mounting a campaign to defeat the Senate-passed
measure and to stop any extension of the three-day background check
law.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA has issued an ``alert'' to its members this week calling
the Senate legislation ``unreasonable ... unworkable ...
unacceptable ... and to our Founders who gave us the Second
Amendment, unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members do a good job of contacting their representatives,
and they will be watching,'' Bill Powers, the NRA's chief
spokesman, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Reed's suggestion that the age for handgun
ownership to be raised to 21, Powers said, ``What's next _ that you
have to be 21 to vote? At some point, we have to recognize that if
we're going to send our young people to places like Kosovo to
fight, then they are probably old enough to be trusted at home.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
