<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0036 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-1930S-1000(3Take     06-02 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-1930S-1000(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGER PREVAILS DURING THE DEPRESSION, BUT THE FOOD INDUSTRY
MARCHES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like many American decades, the 1930s were a dichotomy of
despair and progress.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. stock market crashed in October 1929. As the next
decade opened, America imposed the Smoot-Hawley tariff, which
raised import taxes on goods from abroad. Our Depression became the
world's Depression.
</P>
<P>
   In Harlem, residents battled with dogs and cats for the contents
of garbage cans.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, the International Apple Shippers Association
gave its fruit on credit to jobless men to sell on street corners
to help the association dispose of its surplus. By November 1930,
6,000 men were selling apples on New York sidewalks. By spring
1931, the city declared the men a nuisance and ordered them off the
street.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of record wheat yields followed by a devastating
drought hit American farmers with a one-two punch. In 1931, some
Kansas counties waived taxes to help farmers. The wheat crop had
broken all records, driving down prices. Banks began to foreclose
on loans, forcing farmers off the land.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Wood painted ``American Gothic,'' a composition of a dour
woman and her equally dour husband, clad in overalls and holding a
pitchfork, expressing the outlook of a farm couple living in
depressed times.
</P>
<P>
   Women were encouraged to look for jobs to support unemployed
men. Because female workers were paid less than men, it was easier
for them to find jobs. Life Savers hired about 150 women to do
piecework and paid them $24 to $25 for a five-day week. Baby Ruth
bar manufacturer Curtiss Candy Co. advertised for women and girls
to wrap its products.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, ``Okies'' and ``Arkies'' devastated by the weather in
the Dust Bowl begin migrating to California. More than 350,000
farmers moved west over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet time also brought progress. Auguste Escoffier, creator of
the peach Melba and the father of modern cuisine, presided over a
dinner to celebrate the opening of the Hotel Pierre on Fifth Avenue
in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, Pan Am Clipper flights provide the first hot meals
served in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Production of home appliances escalated _ America was enchanted
with modernism. Design became streamlined; function followed form.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit London Chop House opened in 1939 with 75-cent steak
dinners and 25-cent scotch-and-sodas. The Pump Room opened in
Chicago the same year. Lawry's The Prime Rib premiered in Los
Angeles (later to pioneer valet parking).
</P>
<P>
   Women's clubs came into their own as ladies of leisure banded
together through charitable events, gardening and bridge. Light
club food (creamy, dainty and sweet) was the norm. The absence of
liquor and domestic help, to say nothing of the gloomy economy,
made entertaining more a family event.
</P>
<P>
   Americans found solace in simple things. Marshmallows were a
craze, as were candy and silly garnishes such as pineapple circles
and maraschino cherries. Waffles were the rage, much simpler to
make now that electric waffle irons were available. Waffles were
served for breakfast or lunch, and for Sunday night suppers.
</P>
<P>
   Americans were circling the hearth as a foreign war loomed.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1930: In 1930, the average household worked 91 days to buy a
year's worth of food and spent 25 percent of the household income
on food.
</P>
<P>
   1930: 4.5 million people are unemployed; the number rises to 8
million in 1931 and 12 million in 1932 (a total of 25 percent of
the work force).
</P>
<P>
   1930: Jiffy biscuit mix, sliced Wonder bread and Hostess
Twinkies are born.
</P>
<P>
   1930: The Brenham Creamery Co. changes its name to Blue Bell
Creameries. The company has been making ice cream since 1911 in a
wooden tub filled with ice, and has a production ceiling of 2
gallons a day. In 1936, the company buys its first refrigerated
truck and continuous freezer. In 1939, 1-pint ice-cream containers
are used for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   1930: The average distance between the field where fruits and
vegetables are grown and the markets in which they are sold is
1,500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   1930: Birdseye introduces frozen food; electric stoves appear.
</P>
<P>
   1930: Pat and Harry Olivieri of Pat's Restaurant in Philadelphia
claim to have created the Philadelphia cheese-steak, although they
say the cheese wasn't added to the beef sandwiches until 1948.
</P>
<P>
   1931: St. Louis widow Irma Rombauer publishes ``The Joy of
Cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   1932: The first Minyard Food Store opens in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   1932: Maytag advertises its washers as a boon for the
hard-working family. A farm family is pictured with its own laundry
workhorse.
</P>
<P>
   1932: Americans are more hungry or ill-fed than ever before. The
average weekly relief check for a family of five in New York City
is $6. Nearly 1 million Americans leave the cities to return to the
land, many of them on farms or land outside the money economy.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2-3
</P>
<P>
   2 cups diced chicken
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup stuffed olives
</P>
<P>
   1 cup celery, optional
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup lettuce, broken in small parts
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Place meat, olives and celery in mixing bowl, add mayonnaise and
salt, and mix well with a fork. Serve on crisp lettuce from the
``Frigidaire Hydrator,'' or use crisp endive; garnish the salad
with several stuffed olives.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving using full-fat mayonnaise: 524
calories, 42 grams fat, 3 grams carbohydrates, 34 grams protein,
123 milligrams cholesterol, 1,455 milligrams sodium, 72 percent of
calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Frigidaire Recipe Book,'' published 1932
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP LOUISIANE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon onion, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups peeled shrimp, fresh or canned, broken into pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons parsley, minced
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion in butter until soft; add shrimp and brown. Stir in
flour, salt, chili powder and then, gradually, the milk. Cook 5
minutes. Add tomato ketchup and parsley. Steam several minutes.
Serve over hot rice.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 314 calories, 17 grams fat, 17
grams carbohydrates, 23 grams protein, 177 milligrams cholesterol,
1,083 milligrams sodium, 50 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Gebhardt's Mexican Cookery for American Homes,'' published
1932
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE AMERICAN CHILI CON CARNE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons bacon drippings or vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound ground beef
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cups kidney beans, rinsed if canned
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon corn meal
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried crumbled oregano
</P>
<P>
   In deep, heavy pan, heat drippings, then add ground beef and
onions and cook over medium heat until beef is brown and onions are
soft. Pour off excess fat. Add garlic to pan and cook over low heat
for a few minutes. Stir in tomatoes and beans and cook 10-15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, mix together chili powder, corn meal and salt.
Stir in water to make a thick paste. Stir chili paste into beef
mixture. Stir in crumbled oregano. Cook over low heat, stirring
occasionally, for 1 hour. Correct seasonings, adding salt, oregano,
garlic or chili powder to taste. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   (If chili is held overnight, check seasonings at serving time,
because heat of chili powder seems to dissipate on standing.)
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 291 calories, 12 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 21 grams protein, 43 milligrams cholesterol,
463 milligrams sodium, 37 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Fashionable Food'' by Sylvia Lovegren (Macmillan, $34.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   SAUSAGE-STUFFED BAKED APPLES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 apples
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pork sausage
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   Peel apples and core. Stuff with sausage. Place in baking dish.
Sprinkle with sugar and dot with butter. Add 1 cup water, cover,
and bake in 350-degree oven.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 396 calories, 21 grams fat, 42
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 55 milligrams cholesterol,
763 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Tempting Meat Recipes 1935,'' by the National Live Stock and
Meat Board
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CREAMED CHIPPED BEEF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chipped (dried) beef, chopped a little
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   Pour boiling water over beef. Drain immediately. Melt butter in
large skillet over medium-high heat. When it foams, stir in beef,
letting edges frizzle a little. Stir in flour, reduce heat to low
and cook for about 5 minutes, stirring occasionally. Remove from
heat and slowly stir in half-and-half. Cook over low heat, stirring
occasionally, until mixture thickens. (Don't let it boil, or the
half-and-half will take on a scalded taste.) Cook another 5
minutes. Serve over toast, split baking-powder biscuits or waffles.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 241 calories, 15 grams fat, 6
grams carbohydrates, 19 grams protein, 64 milligrams cholesterol,
1,999 milligrams sodium, 57 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Fashionable Food''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CRIMSON CRYSTAL DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   4-serving size strawberry gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups boiling water
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup maraschino cherry juice
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   12 maraschino cherries, quartered
</P>
<P>
   Dissolve gelatin in boiling water. Add fruit juices. Turn into
10-by-5-inch pan. Chill until firm. Cut into cubes. Pile into
sherbet glasses with cherries.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 78 calories, 0 fat, 19 grams
carbohydrates, 1 gram protein, 0 cholesterol, 41 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _''Quick, Easy Jell-O Wonder Dishes,'' published 1930
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   1932: San Antonio candy-maker C. Elmer Doolin stops in a cafe
for a sandwich and is served a side dish of corn chips. He pays the
cafe owner $100 for his converted potato ricer and the recipe for
``tortillas fritas.'' Fritos are born, as Doolin and his family
begin producing 10 pounds per day. They eventually move their
operation to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   1932: Better Homes and Gardens publishes its first diet article.
</P>
<P>
   1932: Campbell's introduces its tomato soup.
</P>
<P>
   1932: Hotpoint introduces the single-slice toaster.
</P>
<P>
   1932: Sales of Ford automobiles to farmers fall to 55,000 down
from 650,000 in 1929.
</P>
<P>
   1932: The bagel is first mentioned in American print. The first
bagels sold in a supermarket were from Lender's Bagel Bakery in New
Haven, Conn., in 1955. The same company was the first to sell
frozen bagels, in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   1933: Prohibition is repealed when Utah becomes the 36th state
to ratify the 31st Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   1933: The E. and J. Gallo winery is founded at Modesto, Calif.,
by Ernest Gallo, 24, and his brother Julio, 23. The brothers sink
$5,900 into the operation, which will become the largest U.S.
winemaker.
</P>
<P>
   1934: Hard times lead to making do. Restaurants crop up in
unlikely locations, like this establishment housed in a tent.
</P>
<P>
   1934: Harper's Blue Bonnet Bakery opens in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   1934: Prohibition repeal takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   1935: The Social Security Act is signed into law.
</P>
<P>
   1936: Howard Johnson's first restaurant opens, on Cape Cod.
Through the next couple of decades, the restaurants begin appearing
on New England highways and spread through the rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   1936: Stuckey's gets it start when William and Ethel Stuckey
open a roadside stand in Georgia to sell pecans to motorists en
route to and from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   1936: Migrant farm worker Florence Owens Thompson becomes a
symbol of the Depression in Dorothea Lange's photograph.
</P>
<P>
   1937: The shopping cart is introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1937: The Waring Blendor is introduced as a bartender's tool.
Although band leader Fred Waring lent his name and financed the
appliance's development, the machine was invented by Fred Osius,
one of the founders of the Hamilton Beach Co.
</P>
<P>
   1937: Refrigerators are in more than 2 million U.S. households.
</P>
<P>
   1937: Kraft rolls out Kraft Dinner _ a boxed meal that sells for
19 cents with an advertising slogan of ``A Meal for Four in Nine
Minutes.'' Today, 1 million boxes a day of Kraft Macaroni &AMP; Cheese
are sold in the United States. In 1998, the company brings out a
microwave version.
</P>
<P>
   1937: Fortune magazine reports that hired domestics work in 70
percent of upper-income homes, 42 percent of upper middle-class
homes, 14 percent of lower middle-class homes and 6 percent of
homes of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   1938 _ Teflon is discovered.
</P>
<P>
   1938: Mrs Baird's expands by opening a bakery in Houston and a
new facility in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Nestle Tollhouse Morsels are introduced.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Despite the Depression, America continues its belief in
technology. Electric mixers, vacuum cleaners and irons are
manufactured with modern, streamlined designs.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Only 3 percent of Americans have enough income to pay any
taxes, and 670,000 taxpayers account for 90 percent of all income
taxes collected.
</P>
<P>
   1939: Nestle introduces the world's first instant coffee _
Nescafe.
</P>
<P>
   1939: The U.S. Department of Agriculture introduces the first
food-stamp program to feed the needy, in Rochester, N.Y. The stamps
moved surplus farm products into the homes of needy Americans.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields 3/4 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cold water
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon onion juice (extracted by grating onion)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Pepper
</P>
<P>
   8 drops Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Pour cold water in bowl and sprinkle gelatin on top of water;
add vinegar. Place bowl over boiling water and stir until gelatin
is dissolved. Add seasonings and cool (but don't allow it to
thicken). Pour into bottle, add oil, and shake until well-blended.
Use other seasonings as desired.
</P>
<P>
   This dressing will remain in emulsion, but don't place it in
refrigerator or it will acquire a jellylike consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 82 calories, 9 grams fat, 0
carbohydrates, 0 protein, 0 cholesterol, 202 milligrams sodium, 100
percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _''Knox Gelatin Desserts, Salads, Candies and Frozen Dishes,''
published 1933
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
