<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING RANCH CHICKEN RULES THE ROOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The image is clear.
</P>
<P>
   A tough old vaquero in the brush country of far South Texas
hovers over a smoky campfire. He slowly tears hand-made tortillas
and drops them into a pot, then adds a few peppers, some bruised
tomatoes (where he got them is a mystery), and finally some strong
Mexican cheese and either shredded chicken or beef.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, beef probably, since he's on the 800,000-acre King Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   I can't account for the cans of cream of mushroom and cream of
chicken soup that he uses. And, oh yeah, on those occasions he
doesn't have that tomato or the chiles, he uses a can of Ro-Tel
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it doesn't matter what he used. He wasn't even there
in the first place. As far as anyone can tell, King Ranch chicken _
or as it is sometimes known _ King Ranch casserole, doesn't have
one single thing to do with the King Ranch or a vaquero.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to know exactly where it started, but it has
clearly taken on a life of its own. There are rules in some
churches that say there can be no picnics, no socials, no circle
meetings without King Ranch chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Some marriages, christenings and divorces have been nullified
because no King Ranch chicken was served in celebration. Family
reunions use the same rule, probably because several members of the
family go to the same church.
</P>
<P>
   On those hard-to-take Mondays, downtown Fort Worth workers flock
to the Sundance Deli and Market for the King Ranch chicken
blue-plate special. Barry Harper said the casserole is one of his
more popular items. Theoretically, he serves it from 11 a.m.-2
p.m., but it's usually gone by 12:45 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   King Ranch chicken is a staple at many cafeterias, especially on
the days the buses come. It is clearly a comfort food that happens
to have a memorable name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lived here 31 years _ and you know how women like to
always collect recipes wherever they go?'' asked Kathy Henry of the
King Ranch visitors' center in Kingsville. ``Well, when I moved to
Kingsville, the first one I got was for King Ranch chicken. So I
know it has been here for at least 31 years.''
</P>
<P>
   But in all her time working for the sprawling King Ranch, Henry
has never found a link between the popular casserole and the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it was developed perhaps back in the 1950s,'' she
said. ``The word is, a lady in Robstown may have entered it in a
national cooking contest like the Pillsbury or Campbell Soup
contests. She didn't win the big prize but maybe a second or third.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just named it King Ranch chicken because Robstown is in
this area and she thought it would be a catchy name.''
</P>
<P>
   It was.
</P>
<P>
   Henry said she has never been able to research the story, but
whatever the case, she's certain the dish was developed between
1945 and 1965. ``That's the best I can come up with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   People have certainly adopted the dish. Henry said the visitors'
center gets hundreds of calls each year from people wanting the
recipe. For years, the ranch disavowed any connection, but now it
offers a standard recipe printed on small, wooden postcards.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the western motif, the recipe looks as if it has been
burned into the card like a brand. There are two choices: the
chicken version, which is the most popular, and the beef kind,
because King Ranch raises beef.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the official King Ranch recipe for the chicken
casserole:
</P>
<P>
   KING RANCH CHICKEN CASSEROLE
</P>
<P>
   Yields 6
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2-4 pound chicken
</P>
<P>
   1 chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 chopped green bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of mushroom soup
</P>
<P>
   1 can cream of chicken soup
</P>
<P>
   1 can diced tomatoes with green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 package (15) corn tortillas, quartered
</P>
<P>
   2 cups Cheddar cheese, grated
</P>
<P>
   Cook chicken in boiling water, covered, until tender. Strain,
reserve 3 cups broth. Cool chicken, then skin, bone and cut into
bite-sized pieces. Blend soups, chili powder, garlic salt and
tomatoes. Saute green pepper and onion; add to soup mixture. Thin
mixture to desired consistency with reserved broth. In 13-by-9-inch
pan, lightly greased, layer tortilla pieces along bottom, then
chicken, soup mixture, grated cheese. Repeat. Bake at 350 for 30-40
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 558 calories, 25 grams fat, 41
grams carbohydrates, 43 grams protein, 200 milligrams cholesterol,
1,570 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly food column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Write him at the Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, TX 76101, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web
Site: www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
