<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO (Washington) _ The U.S.-led bombing of Yugoslavia will
be temporarily reduced beginning Thursday to permit daily air drops
of humanitarian relief to besieged Kosovo refugees, in the first
major modification of the 71-day NATO onslaught. The move comes
amid peace efforts in Belgrade by European envoys and plans by the
Joint Chiefs of Staff to brief President Clinton on a possible land
invasion of Kosovo. By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-IOWA (Washington) _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush says he will
go to Iowa June 12 ``to look people in the eye, and shake their
hands and let them know what's on my heart.'' The unofficial
Republican front-runner will join former American Red Cross
President Elizabeth Dole, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and
Rep. John R. Kasich of Ohio in Iowa that same day. By GARY MARTIN.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-MOORE (Washington) _ Stacey Moore, 14, moves into the fourth
round of the 72nd National Spelling Bee. The student at Lee
Freshman School in Midland, Texas, easily overcame obstacles like
``monetary'' and ``interminable'' in the early rounds of the
competition. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-CIGARROA (Washington) _ Ricardo Cigarroa, 13, fails by one
letter to make it into the second round of the 72nd National
Spelling Bee. But the eighth-grader at United Middle School in
Laredo, Texas, says he hopes to return next year after incorrectly
spelling ``basmati,'' a type of rice. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BEE-BAROUH (Washington) _ Lena Barouh, 13, an eighth-grader at
Seattle's Washington Middle School, failed to clear the first round
of the 72nd National Spelling Bee after misspelling the word
``erubescent.'' By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-DeMAIORIBUS (Washington) _ Natalie DeMaioribus, 13, rides
``toboggan'' to the final rounds of the 72nd National Spelling Bee.
She just completed the seventh grade at Holy Spirit School in San
Antonio. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-SHAWHAN (Washington) _ Andrew Shawhan, 13, stumbles on
``piloncillo'' in the 72nd National Spelling Bee, vowing to give
the competition another shot next year. He's seventh-grader at
Bethlehem Central Middle School in Delmar, N.Y. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   BEE-CONLEY (Washington) _ Sean Conley, one of 13 children from
home schools competing in the 72nd National Spelling Bee, takes a
tour of the nation's capital as he awaits the competition. Conley,
11, is from Newark, Calif. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (Colorado Springs, Colo.) _ President Clinton
announces that the United States will provide 7,000 troops for a
peacekeeping force in Kosovo and he commits more aircraft to the
air campaign. By JOHN HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-AMERICAN (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Investigators poke through
the scorched hull of an American Airlines MD-80 that skidded off
the runway in bad weather and hit a light tower, breaking apart,
catching fire and killing at least nine people, including the
pilot. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA and LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   CRASH-SURVIVOR (Little Rock, Ark.) _ Moments after the American
Airlines plane crashed, a young woman traveling alone found herself
pushing her seatmate up the jagged incline of the plane's floor and
out a crack in the wall and into howling winds. Survivors lay flat
in a field for 30 minutes before help came because they thought
they were in a hurricane. By LISA TEACHEY.
</P>
<P>
   TAXES-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The headlines sounded simple
enough: Texas consumers will get sales tax exemptions for
back-to-school shopping, Internet connections and nonprescription
drugs. But leave it to lawmakers to require nearly 40 pages of
jargon to create those and other tax breaks. The provisions were
cobbled together in a compromise bill that was approved on Monday.
By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-DUNCAN (San Antonio) _ Heading into the NBA playoffs, Kobe
Bryant and Allen Iverson were the designated heirs to become the
next Michael Jordanesque megastar. But as the playoffs have
progressed, soft-spoken Tim Duncan of the San Antonio Spurs has
emerged as the player to watch. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-NEWCOMERS (Belmont, N.Y.) _ Several new horses will be
jumping into the Triple Crown picture this weekend in an effort to
derail Charismatic's bid for immortality in this weekend's Belmont
Stakes. An overview of what to expect from those horses as the
field is set for Saturday's final leg of the Triple Crown. By ALAN
TRUEX.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Milwaukee) _ Jose Lima seeks his league-leading
ninth victory of the season as the Houston Astros play the
Milwaukee Brewers in the second game of a three-game series. By
CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-DRAFT (Undated) _ High school players dominate the first
round of the major-league baseball draft, accounting for four of
the first five picks. Texas players also are very prominent in the
opening round, led by Spring High School pitcher Josh Beckett, who
is the No. 2 overall pick by the Florida Marlins. By NEAL FARMER.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN (Paris) _ A column from the French Open
advancing the women's semfinal matchup between Steffi Graf and
Monica Seles. By DALE ROBERTSON.
</P>
