<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXTINCT-INDIANS-ART-H     06-02 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXTINCT-INDIANS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF ARTIFACT AND FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  Archaeologists hoping to find more about extinct Karankawa Indians 
 
(Photos available on NYT database) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REFUGIO, Texas _ If the accounts of Texas explorers and settlers
are to be taken for gospel truth, and surely they are not, the
Karankawa Indians of the Gulf Coast were 7 feet tall. They were
naked and ugly and they smelled bad, too.
</P>
<P>
   And they were so mean, they'd start eating you while you were
still alive to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But historians of the day _ Spanish priests trying to
Christianize the nomadic Indians and settlers trying to drive them
off their land _ were hardly objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of spin going on and the Karankawa got some
bad PR that continues even today,'' said University of Texas
archaeologist Britt Bousman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the Karankawa were a group of giants, large and
mean,'' he said. ``And this whole cannibalism thing, I just don't
think there's anything to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many questions about the Karankawa, who disappeared from Texas
by the mid-1800s, will never be answered. But archaeologists now
have another piece of the puzzle to study: Last week, in the middle
of a major highway construction zone, they started digging up the
graves of what are believed to be the last of the Karankawa.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-year-old remains, first uncovered by Texas Department of
Transportation workers in early March, are among those of at least
127 Europeans and Indians buried in a cemetery on the grounds of
Nuestra Senora del Refugio, the last Spanish mission built in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery brought the $6.2 million expansion of U.S. 77, the
major north-south artery between Houston and Corpus Christi, to an
abrupt halt at the front steps of Our Lady of Refuge, a historic
Catholic church that eventually replaced the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as long lines of cars and 18-wheelers squeezed into
one lane and rounded a curve at the south end of this town of
3,100, archaeologists began sifting through the dirt. Later,
they'll tear up the other lane, and continue the excavation before
widening the highway in an effort to alleviate a weekend bottleneck
that sometimes backs up traffic in Refugio for three or four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The skeletal remains and any other artifacts found buried with
them will be taken to UT's San Antonio campus for identification
and study before they are reinterred, probably a couple of years
from now, at a new location.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Karankawa are extinct, several other Native American
tribes, including the Tonkawa, the Apache and the Caddo, are
working with state authorities to find an appropriate reburial site
and to identify any possible descendants of the mission Indians who
may have merged with another tribe along the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are 200-year-old remains, so it's a difficult thing,''
said Don Patterson, president of the Oklahoma-based Tonkawa. ``I
can't say with any certainty that they are part of us, but it's
possible that some straggler or remnant Karankawa may have joined
up with the Tonkawa.''
</P>
<P>
   Although burial records from the mission survived, it's unlikely
that any relatives will step forward to claim the remains. Still,
Bousman and his colleagues, under a $200,000 contract with the
transportation department, will try to distinguish the Spaniards
from the Indians and hope to determine the age, sex and cause of
death for as many as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Since only those graves falling in the highway right-of-way will
be disturbed, archaeologists estimate they will recover the remains
of about 60 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think this is going to be very easy,'' said Nancy
Kenmotsu, supervisor of the archaeology studies program at the
transportation department. ``We know the names of the 127, but we
don't know which name goes with which grave, and we won't have
every grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of what Texans have been taught in school about the
Karankawa comes from the journals of Alvar Nunez Cabeza de Vaca,
the 16th-century Spanish trader and medicine man who lived for
eight years among several South Texas Indian tribes. He described
the Karankawa as extremely tall and muscular, and said the men were
naked with their lower lips and nipples pierced with cane. Both men
and women tattooed their bodies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, though, archaeologists had little data to confirm the
trader's accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only skeletal evidence of the Karankawa is from
prehistoric sites, and most is too old to confidently say it was
Karankawa,'' said Robert A. Ricklis, a Corpus Christi archaeologist
who wrote a 1996 book on the Karankawa. ``This could be very
significant in terms of understanding the physical characteristics
and the health of the people. There's lots of potential here.''
</P>
<P>
   Research by Ricklis and others indicates that the Karankawa were
nomadic fishermen, hunters and gatherers who wandered from
Galveston Bay in the north to Corpus Christi Bay in the south. In
the fall and winter, they set up temporary villages along the Texas
Gulf Coast and on the offshore islands as base camps for fishing
expeditions in dugout canoes. In spring and summer, they split into
smaller family groups of 30 or 40 people and moved inland to hunt
deer and other animals, and to gather nuts and berries. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; After Cabeza de Vaca's years among the Indians, there was
little documented contact with the Karankawa until the French
explorer Rene Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle. Seriously lost in
his quest to locate the mouth of the Mississippi River, La Salle
landed in Matagorda Bay in 1685 and established Fort St. Louis in
the middle of Karankawa territory. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Many in La Salle's party drowned, starved or died of snake
bite; the Karankawa were said to have massacred most of the rest. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Later settlers, even when they were being kind, described the
Karankawa as ``cannibalistic,'' ``atrocious,'' ``bad-tempered'' and
``ungrateful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the most savage looking human beings I ever saw,''
wrote 19th-century blacksmith Noah Smithwick. ``Their ugly faces
were rendered hideous by the alligator grease and dirt with which
they were besmeared from head to foot as a defense against
mosquitoes.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But others noted the Indians' extreme fondness for children,
and described the women as affectionate and pretty, with their
bodies decorated with tattoos of animals, birds and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Cabeza de Vaca and his crew told how survivors of their
shipwreck, near death in the cold of November, were rescued and
nursed back to health by the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, there were a lot of derogatory things said by the
people who were trying to kick the Karankawas off of their land,
and what was recorded about the Karankawa depended on whether the
writers were at war with them at the time,'' Ricklis said. ``I've
read all the standard stories about them being scavengers and what
horrible people they were, but there is so much we don't know about
the Karankawa. &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In an effort to convert and ``civilize'' the Indians, Spanish
priests built the mission in 1795 on the north bank of what is now
called Mission River. The priests considered the mission a failure
because they were never very successful at keeping large numbers of
Indians on the grounds. They came for the free food, and when it
ran out, so did the Indians, they said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But Ricklis dismisses theories that the Karankawa came to the
mission only to eat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never did become a sedentary, Christian community, but
many did become Christians,'' he said. ``They had an arrangement
with the Spanish: `We're not going to be farmers and Christians in
your community, but we'll come and go and participate.' They even
took their newborn babies to be baptized there.''
</P>
<P>
   The mission closed in 1830, and the Karankawa, driven out by
settlers, dispersed and headed south of the Rio Grande. By 1850,
they no longer existed as an identifiable tribe. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; In addition to identifying the remains, Bousman and other
archaeologists are anxious to calculate definitively how tall the
Karankawa were, and to try to determine what their health was like,
what they ate, and how they buried their dead. They also might be
able to determine whether there was intermarriage between Europeans
and Karankawa at the mission or in the surrounding community.
</P>
<P>
   However, the study is unlikely to answer two burning questions
Ricklis and others have been pondering for years: Where did the
Karankawa come from and how long did they live here?
</P>
<P>
   ``The questions are endless,'' Ricklis said. ``There's so much
that we can learn from this, but there's also so much that we'll
never know.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
