<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0070 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TEAM-0603-COX     06-02 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TEAM-0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MULTI-TIERED WHITE HOUSE KOSOVO TEAM STAYS 'FLEXIBLE' IN CRISIS
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0603.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Like most effective managers, President Clinton
tends to think of problems in one of three ways: those that can be
ignored, those that can be solved and those that must be managed.
</P>
<P>
   Guess which box Kosovo fits into.
</P>
<P>
   Here, after all, is a foreign policy crisis with at least four
key dimensions -- military, humanitarian, diplomatic and political
-- each of which is affected daily, sometimes hourly, by
developments in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Each breaks down further into layer upon layer of sub-issues,
the fumbling of any of which could cost lives and spell disaster in
one of the biggest high-stakes gambits of Clinton's 6 1/2-year
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been closely engaged across the board, at times
surprising military commanders with questions that go quickly to
the heart of complex matters no one expects a president to master.
He will meet Thursday with his senior uniformed military advisors,
the Joint Chiefs of Staff, to discuss possible options for using
ground troops if NATO decides to invade Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He's avoided micro-management, however. Besides being contrary
to Clinton's style, that approach probably wouldn't work very well.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Clinton relies on a flexible, multi-tiered team with
diplomats, generals and lawyers at its core to manage U.S. policy,
objectives and long-term strategy in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The top-tier of the effort is Clinton and his national security
chiefs: Secretary of State Madeleine Albright; National Security
Adviser Samuel E. Berger; Defense Secretary William Cohen; Joint
Chiefs of Staff Chairman Gen. Hugh Shelton; CIA Director George
Tenet: White House Chief of Staff John Podesta and Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   This team, known inside the White House as the national security
principals, generally meets twice weekly in the ornate West Wing
Cabinet Room or the windowless Situation Room in the White House
basement. They discuss developments and options on the Kosovo
crisis, even as Berger keeps Clinton updated daily _ sometimes
hourly _ in person or by secure phone line.
</P>
<P>
   Berger generally meets twice a week with the other principals,
minus the president, to examine issues and make decisions not
requiring Clinton's input.
</P>
<P>
   By the time an issue reaches the principals level for a
decision, it has, in most cases, already been vetted, examined and
analyzed by a third tier called the deputies committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chaired by Berger's deputy, James Steinberg, the deputies
committee is in many ways the guts of the management operation,
what Steinberg describes as the ``senior operating committee,'' of
the Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies have met, with few exceptions, seven days a week
since the Kosovo crisis boiled over into a full-blown military
operation March 24.
</P>
<P>
   A bit more fluid than the principals, this committee generally
groups Shelton's vice chairman, U.S. Air Force Gen. Joseph Ralston,
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, the undersecretary of
defense Walter Slocombe, CIA Deputy Director John Gordon, the
undersecretary for political affairs, Thomas R. Pickering, and Vice
President Al Gore's security adviser, Leon Feurth.
</P>
<P>
   The deputies' role is to clarify priorities, lay out specific
policy options and try to assess the risks each alternative poses.
They then send their analysis up the management ladder to the
decision-makers. The idea is to keep the executive level from
getting bogged down with excessive detail or distracted by policy
sideshows so that they may stay focused on the big picture and the
broad goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to frame the issues for the principals,'' said Ralston,
``to make sure that all the views are represented. Nothing's
overlooked, and we eliminate as much of the underbrush as we can so
that the principals can deal with the core issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the principals, the deputies committee was active even
before the Kosovo crisis erupted. Part of its challenge, said
Steinberg, is to continue managing the broad panoply of national
security issues before it -- from nuclear nonproliferation to
international terrorism -- that don't touch directly on the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to not lose sight of the fact that you've
got multiple priorities here,'' said Steinberg. ``We have a lot of
other positions in play.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally there is something called the interagency working group,
charged chiefly with coordination efforts such as keeping the cable
traffic current between the White House and key U.S. embassies and
missions abroad. This group also helps to iron out interagency
conflicts and pool ideas and initiatives among the military,
diplomatic and political shops.
</P>
<P>
   Key players in the working group are Greg Shulte, the National
Security Council's Balkans point man; and diplomats Robert Gelbard
and James Dobbins, both of whom hold ambassadorial status and
Balkans portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
