<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0073 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTOR-PIAZZOLA-TEX     06-02 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTOR-PIAZZOLA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE OBSCURE, ARGENTINE COMPOSER IS NOW OMNIPRESENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ten years ago, most of us had never heard of Astor Piazzolla.
</P>
<P>
   Now, his music is everywhere. A classical guitar concert without
the music of Piazzolla is a rarity these days; Russian violinist
Gidon Kremer surprised Fort Worth audiences with a solo by
Piazzolla for his encore when he appeared with the St. Petersburg
Philharmonic at Bass Performance Hall in October. And on the
classical concert scene, Piazzolla's music has been recorded by
Kremer, Daniel Barenboim, Yo-Yo Ma, the Kronos Quartet and the
Orchestra of St. Luke's.
</P>
<P>
   But, like Schubert and J.S. Bach, Piazzolla had to wait until
after he was dead to be famous: After decades of, at best, regional
recognition in South America, the Argentine composer had just begun
to attract international recognition by the time he died at 71 in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Who was Astor Piazzolla?
</P>
<P>
   He was the composer who wanted to do for the tango what Chopin
did for the waltz: to turn a popular dance form into a classical
concert form.
</P>
<P>
   Piazzolla's obituary in ``The New York Times'' in July 1992 was
simple but explained his extraordinary cross current of musical
influences. Born in Mar del Plata, south of Buenos Aires, he spent
his early years in New York, where he absorbed the influence of
jazz, klezmer and classical music _ including piano lessons with
one of Rachmaninoff's pupils. There, he also met the ``King of
Tango,'' Carlos Gardel.
</P>
<P>
   When Piazzolla returned to Argentina as a teen-ager, he
continued his exploration in many directions, studying classical
composition with Alberto Ginastera while playing the bandoneon in
tango orchestras. His ``Sinfonia de Buenos Aires'' won him a
scholarship to study in Paris with Nadia Boulanger (teacher of
Aaron Copland and numerous other key figures in American
20th-century music); he returned to Buenos Aires in the 1950s ready
to create the ``new tango.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Argentina,'' Piazzolla later told interviewer Jon Pareles,
``you can change the government, you can change the literature, you
can change the architecture. But if you change the tango, there is
trouble. ... Traditional tango listeners hated me. I introduced
harmonies, fugues, counterpoint and other irreverences; people
thought I was going crazy. All the tango critics and the radio
stations of Buenos Aires started criticizing me; they called me a
clown, they said my music was `paranoiac.' And they made me
popular. The young people who had lost interest in tango started
listening to me. It was a war of one against all _ but in 10 years,
the war was won.''
</P>
<P>
   While revitalizing and reforming the tango, Piazzolla kept the
key underlying element: sex. Which explains the sometimes
irrationally repetitious segments and the predominance of mellow
melodies.
</P>
<P>
   Area audiences have been introduced to Piazzolla's music in
choreographed settings by Fort Worth-based modern dance
choreographer Bruce Wood and former Fort Worth Dallas Ballet
artistic director Paul Mejia; Gutierrez presented the Bandoneon
Concerto and the short ``Oblivion'' for bandoneon and strings in a
concert with the Fort Worth Chamber Orchestra in spring 1998.
</P>
<P>
   We're not likely to run out of new music by Piazzolla for some
time. He produced a body of 750 works _ enough concertos, operas,
and film and theatrical scores to keep performers busy for years.
</P>
<P>
   Why the relatively sudden increase in interest in Piazzolla?
</P>
<P>
   Piazzolla's music was written during an era, the 1960s and
1970s, when atonal music dominated and excluded other music, such
as his.
</P>
<P>
   But the current eclectic, neoromantic era has taken to
Piazzolla's music enthusiastically, embracing not only its
traditional values of immediate audience appeal and melody but its
unique sound. It's entirely unlike anything else in the classical
repertoire, thanks to its combination of tango, jazz and classical
strains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Schubert or Mozart,'' says pianist Emanuel Ax, who
has recorded and performed two-piano arrangements of Piazzolla's
music with Piazzolla protege Pablo Ziegler. ``But it's exciting,
beautiful, often fun. And that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
