<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH FRIENDS LIKE THIS, YOU NEED A BEER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON and ELLIOTT KNIGHT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people just don't have a sense of humor. Take my friend
Elliott. I wrote about him in a recent column, and now he's
irritated with me. ``Made me sound like a moron,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why _ all I did was call him a Philistine and imply
that he's a sot. ``I was just joshing,'' I replied. ``Too bad you
can't write your own column, ha-ha.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the swine did it. And to show what a nice guy I am, I
persuaded the editor to run it, and here it is:
</P>
<P>
   ``So my buddy the Beer Nut, Mister Big-Shot Column Writer, gives
me the pen _ actually, the keyboard _ and says through gritted
teeth, `Knock yourself out.' And I knew he meant it _ literally.
See, we go back a long way. I know all the dirt on the Beer Nut.
But since he knows all the dirt on me, too, I'll be fairly gentle
on him.
</P>
<P>
   I travel a lot for work nowadays, so we don't get together as
often as we'd like. But when we do, the Beer Nut and I head to the
Flying Saucer, a great Fort Worth joint that serves beers from
around the world. And while he professes to be a sophisticated
imbiber, I've seen him pound down his share of generic no-name
beers. His only requirement: cold, so he can't taste 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Because to the Beer Nut, image is everything. He drives fancy
cars and lives in a fancy house in a fancy, historic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   `(The Beer Nut notes: My car is nine stinkin' years old, and the
term ``historic'' must mean ``dilapidated,'' because the joint is
falling down around our ears. Where does he get this hoity-toity
stuff?)'
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet I always think about his bumper sticker, now long gone
from the tail-end of his old Toyota: `Decadence ... a Way of Life.'
To my mind, that says it all about the Beer Nut: He's a
beer-swiller in the land of high-rollers!
</P>
<P>
   `(The Beer Nut notes: What a great sticker that was.)'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm here to tell you about a recent late afternoon we
spent sampling beers with our kids at a local watering hole. With
our kids!!!?! We were both amazed at this turn of events, because
we've known each other since before the kids were born! This just
gives you a clue as to how old the Beer Nut actually is!
</P>
<P>
   Patrick (his son) and Kellie (my daughter) educated us geezers
as to the finer points of their beer selections. Their primary
decision points were: 1) `Hey! It's $2.50-a-pint day!' and 2) `If
you order a Bass, you get a free glass!'
</P>
<P>
   ``We love Bass, no question, but decided to let them enjoy their
brews while we moved on to Murphy's Irish Cream. It's the kind of
smooth, palatable stout that appeals to folks who like the idea of
a Guinness, but find the actual stuff too strong. Murphy's is soft
where Guinness is bitter, smooth as opposed to tart, and on the
whole, a very forgiving pint of joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which brings me back to my nearly three decades of friendship
with the Beer Nut: I like him despite his extremes, probably
because of them. He's a bit tart, a little bitter, but soft on the
inside _ pretty much like a Murphy's, when you get right down to
it. My suggestion: Take his advice and sample the beers he
recommends. All I know is that, after nearly 30 years, I have yet
to be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his choice of beers, that is.''
</P>
<P>
   `(The Beer Nut notes: Just remember, old pal, paybacks are
hell.)'
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBO/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
