<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0076 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAN-HAYES-TEX     06-02 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAN-HAYES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THERE'S A `WILL,' THERE'S A ZIPPY, QUIPPY SEAN HAYES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARRISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sean Hayes, master scene thief, got his star turn as a heartsick
gay photographer in the 1997 independent film ``Billy's Hollywood
Screen Kiss.'' An NBC casting executive saw the movie at a Sundance
Film Festival screening and faxed him the entire ``Will &AMP; Grace''
script.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, the 28-year-old Hayes, whose perpetual smile
occupies half his face, had the producers reaching for contracts.
``Timing, wit, execution, nerve, gumption _ he had what we wanted
and something a little more,'' ``Will &AMP; Grace'' producer and
co-creator Max Mutchnick said of Hayes, who grew up in suburban
Chicago glued to ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, his talent for making lame lines hilarious is
innate. As Jack McFarland, the wisecracking, unconditionally
self-possessed gay sidekick to Eric McCormack's strait-laced (read:
boring) gay lawyer Will, Hayes often amplifies the zing of a punch
line by throwing in an assortment of devices _ firing off a look of
distress, nausea or glee; striking a gaudy pose; flipping into a
headstand on a chair; spinning his legs as though on a bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hayes' Jack who gave the series a swift kickoff when,
during the second episode, he crossed verbal swords with the show's
other standout, the squeaky-voiced Karen (Megan Mullally), snippy
assistant to Grace (Debra Messing). The two ended up rubbing
bellies and trading fashion faux pas. If there was a funnier sitcom
scene this season, I'd like to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, a motor-mouth of train-wreck proportions, is easily the
best thing about this year's rookie hit, which ranked 40th in the
Nielsen rankings, pulling in a weekly viewership of 12.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace'' was written with NBC viewer sensibilities in
mind: Its pace, rhythm and snappy dialogue is right out of a
``Friends'' script. NBC even toyed with the idea of a
Thursday-night slot for the comedy, but when the fall schedule
arrived, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' was perched at ... 8:30 p.m. Tuesday,
sandwiched between ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``Dateline.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a no-brainer that Hayes plays the most outrageous character
introduced this season on any show, and that includes the disaster
that was Desmond Pfeiffer. His is also a character that has
shrewdly served a prime purpose: to be so flamboyantly gay that it
takes the pressure off Will. (To kiss or not to kiss finally came
to a head in the season finale, when NBC decided that a written
smooch ``didn't work creatively,'' which means they still feel it's
too early.)
</P>
<P>
   Having support characters show up the leads is hardly
jaw-dropping (see Michael Richards in Jerry Seinfeld's ``Seinfeld''
and everyone with a line in Kirstie Alley's ``Veronica's Closet,''
a show for which, ironically, Hayes was turned down). But it is
unusual for a network to zero in on a back-up player the way NBC
has by airing those 30-second ``Jack spots,'' complete with a
montage of Jack footage and a Jack theme song.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes, who is said to be mulling film scripts, only seems to
have come out of nowhere. He started in regional musicals,
eventually moving on to Chicago's famed Steppenwolf Theater. He
spent two years in an acclaimed original work called ``Role Play''
before rolling dice in Hollywood, where casting directors were
immediately taken with his disarming charm and choirboy good looks.
(He looks no more than 15.)
</P>
<P>
   Lots of commercial work followed. His big, high-profile moments:
as a henpecked husband thirsting for a Bud Light and as an
overeager Doritos fan. His three-headed partygoer in an ad for
Geico Insurance is a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   Now right in the high-profile mix on a weekly basis, Hayes has
earned such across-the-board kudos for his boundless energy and
spicy irreverence you wonder if ``Will &AMP; Grace'' would be the same
without him. (Pssst: It wouldn't.)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
