<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTARO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEALING WITH BIRD KARMA HAS ME POOPED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - I shuddered immediately.
</P>
<P>
   It was staring at me with cool, beady eyes that were the murky
color of an eight-ball. It didn't flinch, flutter or turn away.
From its perch at the top of one of the columns on my front porch,
its gaze was hard and direct, steady and unwavering.
</P>
<P>
   I had seen that same look before, some 11 years ago, and it
haunts me still.
</P>
<P>
   On that hot, wavy afternoon in 1988, I made contact with another
pair of those black-bubble pigeon eyes and I honked. I honked
again. Another pigeon, squatting next to it, flapped its wings and
split. The other one, however, turned to look me directly in the
eye as my car cast its shadow on the bird, eclipsed it, and then
spat out a thousand feathers falling in front of the sun in my
rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   It was my friends Jeff and Jamie who truly cast horror on the
episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``That lazy bird didn't even make an attempt to get up,'' I
assured them. ``How can that be my fault?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like the bird was deaf,'' Jamie said. ``You killed a
handicapped bird!''
</P>
<P>
   ``And apparently, the spouse witnessed the whole thing,'' Jeff
said. ``Pigeons mate for life, you know. What a sad little nest
that must be tonight!''
</P>
<P>
   ``How was I supposed to know it was a special-needs bird?'' I
said defensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``You owe that pigeon family a life,'' Jeff informed me. ``And
you know that karma returns tenfold, don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten fowl will darken your doorway until your debt is repaid,''
Jamie added.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't believe their words until exactly 24 hours later, when
I was walking with a very cute boy from my class at ASU. Suddenly,
a pinecone struck me on the head, and as I reached my hand up to
rub my scalp, a warm ooze of bird crap spread across my forehead.
The cute boy pointed and said, ``I think you're going to need shots
for that,'' before he handed me a dirty piece of newspaper from the
ground to clean myself up with.
</P>
<P>
   The prophecy was indeed proven true that day and has continued
to grow throughout the decade as I've been haunted by birds.
</P>
<P>
   A sparrow became trapped in my bathroom vent, worked its way
into the bathroom and refused to leave for four days, crashing into
the shower door and the mirror repeatedly. I had to start feeding
it because I was afraid that it would die, and I finally got rid of
it after it knocked itself unconscious and I captured it with a
large bath towel, but not before it pooped on my toothbrush.
</P>
<P>
   I was forced to chase a neighborhood child's pet, a diseased
pigeon with a broken wing, down the street and into various
neighbors' yards in my pajamas one morning when it escaped. After
delivering the bird safely into the hands of the child, the imp
looked me square in the face and said, ``When you were bent over
chasing Petey, we all saw your boobs.''
</P>
<P>
   One crafty bird hid in my car and staged an ambush the minute I
got on Loop 202 and was lighting a cigarette, which resulted in a
small but manageable fire that proved Twinkies really don't burn,
they just sort of liquify.
</P>
<P>
   While I was eating lunch with a friend on an outside patio,
another bird emptied its bowels on me, hitting me with its best
shot on the shoulder, and then, in a second attack, it turned my
half-eaten burrito into an enchilada-style one.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to save a baby bird that managed to fall out of its
nest, I took it to a lady who had turned her kitchen into a bird
sanctuary. When she asked me for a $35 donation for the 3-ounce
bird's room and board, I diverted her attention by saying, `Hey,
your cat sure is eating something big!` and then ran to my car.
</P>
<P>
   After watching me take her offspring away in a shoe box, the
mother of the baby bird began to target me for several months every
time I left my house, pecking me repeatedly in the head, arm and,
most predominately, the right _ and firmer of the two _ butt cheek.
One time it hit me behind the ear, and I looked up just in time to
see it fly away with a chunk of my hair.
</P>
<P>
   So when I recently saw the pigeon glaring at me from atop the
porch column, my blood naturally turned to ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead,'' I said as I stood beneath it, providing the bird
with a perfectly good target. ``Let's just get this over with.''
</P>
<P>
   But the bird made no move. Instead, it devised a devilish
torture that consisted of swooping down on me in a mad attack every
time I opened the front door, causing me to scream and bat my hands
wildly about.
</P>
<P>
   One day, when the bird was running errands, I took a broom and
knocked down the nest, and blocked the area with a large ceramic
pot. My strategy worked until the next day, when I saw the
beginnings of another nest on the next porch column.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't take it anymore,'' I complained to my husband as I sat
on the couch in our living room. ``One day that bird is going to
pluck my eyeballs out, you just wait and see!''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be lucky if that thing didn't affix itself to your face
and try to pull your brain out through your nose,'' my husband
said. ``You owe them a life, remember! That thing is probably just
trying to lay some eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   Just then _ and may God strike me dead if this isn't the truth _
I heard a rather loud FLAP, FLAP FLAP noise. As I turned to look, a
big, black raven swept toward me like I was a prairie dog. Due to
my bird battle experience, I rolled onto the floor, covered my nose
and screamed.
</P>
<P>
   My husband saw the assault, grabbed a towel and batted at the
raven until he had herded it into the bathroom, where he promptly
opened the bathroom window and shut the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did that come from?'' he asked, breathing heavily.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a warning! Don't you understand? That bird,'' I
shouted, getting up off the floor, ``was Number NINE!''
</P>
<P>
   My husband looked at me quizzically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number Ten,'' I explained, ``is waiting to be born up in that
nest on top of the column! It's the life I owe! My karma is DONE!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not yet,'' he said, pointing me toward the kitchen sink.
``Number Nine left a big Number Two on your head. And when you bent
down to hit the floor, I saw your boob.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Laurie Notaro is a freelance writer. Send comments about her column
to the Rep, P.O. Box 2245 NF-19, Phoenix, AZ 85002; or by e-mail to
laurienotaro(at)usa.net. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
