<SLUG> BC-TROUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARADISE FOUND: TROUT COOKED IN THE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photo available on the Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRED LeBRUN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ All that hiking and wading along treacherous
stream bottoms is great physical exercise. The solitude and
continual gurgling of the waters in the background soothe the most
frazzled nerves.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how you fish for trout, the game itself, the
pursuit, can be as challenging as the rules and equipment you
choose. Right at the top of grand advantages to trout fishing,
though, is that catching your own provides the precious luxury of
truly fresh fish for the skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Back when I was a wee lad of about 12 and knew everything there
was to know about trout fishing, my parents dropped me and a
like-minded friend off for a five-day camping adventure.
</P>
<P>
   I remember we had an old tent and sleeping bags, an ancient
pump-up Coleman stove and minimalist provisions. Milk, sugar,
flour, a couple of big cans of Dinty Moore stew, and Campbell
soups, and just enough loose change for one frosty Yoo-hoo a day
from the camp store at the campground entrance. I recall my
father's last words, in French, complete with Gallic wry smile as
he drove off in the sunset leaving us there: ``Dinner, gentlemen,
is still swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   No problem. We were already self-reliant little trout killers on
the streams back home and we knew what we had to do. Stun a few
black-nosed dace in the shallows, stick them on a bare size 10 hook
and let them drift free under big rocks. And it worked. We had all
the fresh trout we wanted, in the 10-inch range, which is prime
frying pan material. Never in my life were trout easier to catch
than when it never occurred to me we could fail.
</P>
<P>
   Failure came at a different place. Catching trout is one thing.
Cooking them so they are not just edible, but delicious is quite
something else. That little adventure, and several others like it
with the Boy Scouts and on our own, provided a lifetime of don'ts
when it comes to cooking freshly caught trout streamside.
</P>
<P>
   Don't use an open fire for cooking unless you have the patience
to wait for uniform hot coals. Don't try to fillet the little
suckers; clean and then cook them whole every time. Don't place
trout on a grill over an open fire and expect the fish to remain on
top of that grill when it's cooked, or cook evenly. Watch a day's
worth of catch slip through the grill into the fire as you
frantically try to save bits and pieces.
</P>
<P>
   I swear by _ rather than at _ a few key utensils. No to a
fireplace. Yes to a propane Coleman camp stove every time, the
sophisticated progeny of my childhood adventures. Gas gives good
control. The two-burner stove is light enough to maneuver anywhere
but sufficient for complicated preparations if necessary. A picnic
table, or just a pile of rocks, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   For trout in the wild, I strongly favor a seasoned cast-iron pan
with not too high a lip.
</P>
<P>
   But always remember the center piece is fresh, delicate trout.
Sweet fleshed and very dainty, a gentle flavor easily masked by too
strong batters or spicing, or even too much flame. Keep it simple,
that's always the best way.
</P>
<P>
   The best sizes are 8 to 10 inches, although let's face it, the
best fish are those you have. There's a neat, easy way to clean
them from front to back that takes away the gill plates along with
the vicera and just leaves the head attached by the back bone. If
that's a problem, just slit from anal opening to gills and the
insides come out easily. Don't forget to scrape away with the back
of your thumb the dark line at the inside center. This serves as
the fish's kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Swish the fish around briskly in the water you caught him from,
plucking away bits and strands that cling.
</P>
<P>
   In a paper bag mix half flour, half corn meal, salt, pepper and
maybe an inkling of paprika. Drop the freshly cleaned fish into the
bag, flip around, pull out and stuff heartily with either fresh
dill, tarragon or cress. The last is best. At the aforementioned
camp from my youth, there are patches of natural wild cress that we
used for salads and to stuff our little brookies. I like the
moisture the fresh herbs impart, and an unmistakable flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Cook over medium heat, with a little vegetable oil or butter in
the pan. No olive oil, please, unless you want to smoke up the
campsite. Don't overcook. A few minutes on each side, until the
flesh starts to pull away from the bone, and voila.
</P>
<P>
   With bigger fish, such as we had, separate the fillets in big
pieces after they're mostly cooked, pulling away the bones in
single strands, then finishing off those pieces with a little added
salt and pepper. But again, don't overcook. Remember, trout as
sushi is not out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   On a fishing trip one recent day, we finished our trout in the
wild with pretoasted almonds sizzled for a few moments, fresh lemon
wedges, and more rose. A good, dry rose is excellent with trout
because it doesn't overwhelm and our $27 bottle of Domaine Ott from
France was all of that.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, roses are not as popular as they ought to be in
this country and almost always are too sweet for serious work.
Otherwise, a chardonnay finished in the European style, that is,
non-oaky, is also fine for delicate trout as is a semi-dry light on
the acid riesling. Stay away from the big-bodied, bold whites, or
the acidic ones.
</P>
<P>
   On the side we cooked up a little store-bought polenta and some
little red potatoes with thyme.
</P>
<P>
   FREDDY'S TROUT MEUNIERE
</P>
<P>
   1 trout per person, head on or off (the trout, not the person)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Chopped herbs for stuffing
</P>
<P>
   Chopped parsley and chopped whatever herb used to stuff the fish
for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup toasted almonds
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, cornmeal, salt and pepper in a paper bag. Drop
the trout in a paper bag with the seasoned flour and toss about.
Stuff trout with fresh herbs, then brown in a cast-iron skillet
with the oil at a medium heat, about 3 minutes a side. Remove fish
to a serving platter and cover with foil. Brown the butter in the
skillet, add lemon juice and chopped herbs. Pour hot over the
trout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
