<HEADER>
A0109 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-TEX     06-02 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIBURN-AMATEURS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADULTS TAKE UP MUSIC FOR THE LOVE OF IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By day, Dr. Robert Kelly deals with disease and life-or-death
matters.
</P>
<P>
   But every night, for an hour or so before going to bed, Kelly's
mind turns to Chopin, Tchaikovsky and J.S. Bach, as he practices on
the restored antique Kohler upright piano that he inherited from
his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance to point your mind in a different direction,''
Kelly says. ``It's so different from what I do all day'' as an
internal medicine specialist.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, piano lessons were something kids took from a
grown-up teacher. Now, although no one keeps precise numbers, a
growing number of adults are taking piano lessons, often from a
teacher younger than themselves. Kelly, 44, studies with Igor
Resnianski, a 33-year-old Siberian-born graduate student at Texas
Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   Even the esteemed Cliburn Foundation has taken notice; next
week, it will sponsor the first International Piano Competition for
Outstanding Amateurs. Modeled on a similar competition in Paris _
and not to be confused with the ``real'' Van Cliburn International
Piano Competition, to be held again in Fort Worth in 2001 _ the
amateur competition will feature 97 devoted amateurs from 10
countries in solo competition.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the contestants are probably much like Kelly, who took
lessons as a youth but then became busy with school and career.
Kelly's three children had taken lessons from Resnianski for
several years. One week, when one of the youngsters was sick, Kelly
took a deep breath and asked if he could take the lesson.
</P>
<P>
   By last year, at the first amateur concerto concert at the
TCU/Cliburn Piano Institute, Kelly auditioned with a movement of
Mozart's Piano Concerto No. 21. Kelly didn't make the cut, but
he'll back this year with a movement from J.S. Bach's Concerto No.
5 in F minor, once again dreaming of the chance to play with a
professional orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   As a professional in a high-prestige and high-pressure field,
Kelly is certainly not alone in his devotion to amateur
music-making, says Amanda Byars, a Dallas teacher who specializes
in teaching adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority have been in scientific fields, or bankers, or
lawyers,'' she says. ``Surprisingly, very few have been
homemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Byars says that her oldest student is in his early 70s, though
the average age is 37-47.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not successful with my first adults,'' she says. ``I had
to learn and research why and how adults come for piano lessons.
They really want to be there, and have a genuine interest in
classical music.''
</P>
<P>
   Janie Brown, 43, of Fort Worth works as a training instructor at
Boeing Aircraft in Irving and is about to become a grandmother.
With her family grown, she decided to use her spare time to
concentrate on what she calls her ``heart's desire'' _ studying
music. She found Fort Worth teacher Patricia Brown in the telephone
book, began with voice lessons about four years ago and added piano
about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat tells me I'm further along than I should be,'' Brown says.
</P>
<P>
   But Janie Brown has more ambition than just having fun. She
wants to enter college as a music major, and more important, ``I
want to be able to show my grandchildren how to play the piano,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Brown teaches voice and piano to children and adults at
her traditional-style in-home studio in south Fort Worth, and
admits: ``Some teachers like teaching first- and second-graders,
but the adults are my favorites. I like relating to someone who's
doing it because he or she wants to _ not for any other incentive.
And I can relate to how they have to schedule it around family,
jobs and that kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The TCU/Cliburn Piano Institute had been around for decades as a
summer program for aspiring amateurs. Tamas Ungar, the
Hungarian-born pianist who heads the piano department at TCU, and
who founded and directs the Cliburn/TCU Piano Institute, added the
amateurs' program when he began to notice an increase in amateur
adult interest in the piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults have more time,'' he says. But he has also noticed the
particular interest among members of what he calls the
``intellectual professions. People like doctors and lawyers, who
need the creativity outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Ungar's guidance, Fort Worth has become a focal point for
many amateurs, who have arrived from all over the world at the
institute for three consecutive years to play in master classes
(essentially, lessons in front of an audience), take lessons,
participate in group discussions and share ideas. And, starting
last year, they could compete in the one-of-a-kind event in which
several are chosen to perform with the Fort Worth Chamber
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Rust, a California-based consultant in urban economics,
amateur oboist and publisher of ``Music for the Love of It,'' a
bimonthly newsletter for amateur musicians, also notes a definite
increase in adult amateur musical activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are living longer, retiring earlier and finding that
music is a wonderful thing to do with their time,'' he says. ``It's
a way of keeping the mind and spirit young, and a way of keeping in
touch with other people. It's a form of spiritual renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
