<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0110 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LESSONS-INLIFE-TEX     06-02 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LESSONS-INLIFE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY GOOD BOY DOES FINE: OUR CRITIC, THE STUDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of 1996, I watched the TCU/Cliburn Piano
Institute's newly instituted ``amateur weekend'' with pure envy.
</P>
<P>
   I was there as part of my job as Star-Telegram classical music
critic. But as often happens to reporters at events they cover, I
came away a changed person.
</P>
<P>
   After watching grandmothers and anesthesiologists struggle
through _ but thoroughly enjoy _ Mozart and Schubert, I was
determined to play the piano again. But I realized that, in spite
of years of piano lessons, I couldn't sit down and play a whole
piece.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about my job is the chance to hear the
greatest pianists in the world, live, almost weekly. But the piano
wasn't invented just to be listened to from afar. To play a prelude
of Chopin is the equivalent of owning a pencil sketch by Rembrandt;
with a few dollars' worth of music and a few minutes of daily
practice, one can ``own'' a masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   I was fortunate to grow up in a small town in Oklahoma that was
the home of one of the best independent studio teachers in America,
Jonetta Hinkle. That kind and vivacious lady introduced me not only
to Bach, Beethoven and romantic composers, but to the energy of my
favorite 20th-century music.
</P>
<P>
   One day, as I flailed with hopeless teen-age nonchalance through
the lean textures of a Mozart sonata, she very seriously told me
that it was time I started actually caring about the notes _ every
single note. That is a standard I have tried to hold myself to, and
it is the one absolute value I hold for all the musicians I review
and criticize.
</P>
<P>
   When I moved on to Baylor University in Waco to major in music
history, I was assigned to the studio of Jane Abbott, one of the
best college piano teachers in America. Fortunately, she had the
patience to work with my interest in piano music, which was
immense, rather than being discouraged by my minuscule talent.
</P>
<P>
   But, at 40, I had last taken lessons 13 years earlier from a
fellow graduate student at the University of Iowa. So, for my
renewed practice regime, I picked pieces that were lots easier than
those I used to play. Instead of a Bach fugue, I went for a
two-part Invention by Bach. I added some short, noisy pieces by
Bartok, and a sort-of-hard but not very long Etude of early
20th-century Russian Alexander Scriabin.
</P>
<P>
   I thoroughly enjoyed the first days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Other people at my house, both of whom play the piano, did not.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons were in order, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had hundreds of piano lessons from some of the finest
teachers in America, taught piano myself AND have two degrees in
music,'' I pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   I was outvoted, 2-to-1. So I called Tamas Ungar, head of the
piano department at Texas Christian University and founder and
director of the TCU summer institute _ and therefore the person
whose fault all of this was. He wisely and diplomatically declined
to give me a lesson but referred me to a graduate student, a young
fellow from Siberia named Igor Resnianski.
</P>
<P>
   Igor was about 30, a good decade behind me. Still green to the
ways of America _ his English at the time was charmingly halting _
he was years ahead of me not only musically but in the experience
of growing up. A former member of the Russian army, he had managed
to find a way out of a turbulent situation, making connections and
building friendships at competitions in Russia and China, until he
secured the attention and scholarship money of the TCU piano
department.
</P>
<P>
   I met him on a Sunday afternoon at TCU. He was late, as he would
always be. He had long, floppy pianist hair, smiled more often than
not, and wasn't at all intimidated _ if he even realized _ that I
was the much-feared local music critic.
</P>
<P>
   We found a vacant classroom with a piano. Being a Russian, he
zeroed in on the Scriabin. He showed proper horror at my
fingerings, then proceeded to dissect the piece _ which I had
regarded as mostly pretty romantic frill _ as if it were Bach or
Schoenberg.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he threw in bits of Russian romantic
pictorialism: ``These are church bells,'' he would say, adding life
and meaning to what had previously been a pair of lifeless chords.
Then, with his typical and irrepressible humor, he'd point at a
similar pattern a measure away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church bells in a different part of town,'' he'd say.
</P>
<P>
   He showed me how I had to practice. Not just play through, which
was more fun. I had to do it for Igor until it was as perfect as I
could get it, and it was still not half as good as when he shoved
me off the bench and showed me how it could really be done.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours, I had a headache and was more exhausted than if
I had run a mile.
</P>
<P>
   It's been three years now. I missed a whole year at one point,
then came back for more. Finally, I learned the Bach, dropped the
Bartok, added Mozart and Hindemith _ and, this winter, managed to
get in enough practice that I could come in every other week or so
and show progress.
</P>
<P>
   I'm proud that I taught him to respect Scott Joplin. Igor
sneered when I first brought in the lyrical Heliotrope Bouquet rag
but dived in with the same attention he had paid to Scriabin,
making my brain ache with implications. The second time, he
admitted that it was decent music; the third time, he allowed that
he might get some Joplin rags himself. Last time, he pondered the
possibility of a whole Joplin program.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also proud that I can once again play an entire Bach
Invention from memory (though Jonetta Hinkle and Jane Abbott, after
pulling me through countless sonatas, would be disappointed that
that's all I can do).
</P>
<P>
   But I'm sorry that, now that I'm finally practicing ``and''
learning music, Igor is moving away, lured by the chance to
complete a doctorate. I'll be looking for another teacher: one who
doesn't mind if I miss half a year or so now and then, one who
isn't shocked about how badly the music critic really plays.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Igor, good luck and thanks for making me practice
right, for shoving me off the bench and showing me how it's really
done, and for reminding the guy who writes about all the pianists
in the world about how hard it really is to do it right _ and that
writing about piano music is a mere shadow of playing it.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
