<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS (Washington) _ A special report: Miguel
Sanchez was just 1 day old when he was killed by a prescription
drug. In death, he joined a population that is causing increasing
anxiety among health care experts and federal regulators: the tens
of thousands of Americans who lose their lives each year not to
illness, but to medication intended to treat it. Food and Drug
Administration officials, as well as independent drug safety
experts, say a flood of new and ever more complicated medications
are overwhelming the nation's health care system, making it
increasingly difficult for pharmacists, doctors and hospitals to
protect patients from being killed or harmed by adverse reactions
or mistakes. By Cheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The head of a federal advisory
commission urges Congress to relax stringent limits on Medicare
payments for certain nursing home and hospital services _ saying,
in effect, that the '97 budget law cut too deep. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-SPARROW (Everglades National Park, Fla.) _ Scientists
say the plight of the threatened Cape Sable Seaside Sparrow
reflects the failing health of the Everglades ecosystem. Congress,
in July, takes up a $7.8 billion engineering plan to restore the
swamplands to ecological health, and some environmentalists and
wildlife officials say the sparrow is the test of whether the plan
can succeed. The controversy reflects how politically complicated
and interconnected the problems in the Everglades are, and how
difficult any solution will be. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   With a graphic.
</P>
