<HEADER>
A0129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVANNAH-MERCER-HOUSE     06-02 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVANNAH-MERCER-HOUSE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GARDEN-OF-GOOD-AND-EVIL HOUSE IS OFFERED FOR SALE AT $8.95
MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  ART ADV: Photos are being sent. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Dr. Dorothy Williams Kingery, owner of the most
famous _ some say infamous _ house in Savannah, walked down her
front steps and past a family of tourists who were clutching
guidebooks and wearing cameras like bandoliers. ``Excuse me,
ma'am,'' the man said, stepping forward and making an almost
imperceptible bow, ``but could we get a tour?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Dr. Kingery replied between clenched teeth. ``This is a
private house.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might disagree. Dr. Kingery, a retired sociology professor,
is well known, at least here, as the sister of Jim Williams, the
antiques dealer who was tried four times in the 1981 shooting death
of 21-year-old Danny Hansford. The killing occurred in the study of
this house and was the focus of the best-selling ``Midnight in the
Garden of Good and Evil.''
</P>
<P>
   She is about to be even better known.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kingery has put the house, which was given to her by her
mother, on the market for $8.95 million. (In his will, her brother
left her $10, his papers and the rights to ``Psycho Dice,'' a game
he invented.) If it brought anything near that price, the mansion,
known as Mercer House, would be the most expensive residence ever
sold in Savannah.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate prices have soared in this city of 143,000, but this
week townsfolk are wondering whether $8.95 million for Mercer
House, magnificent though it is, isn't a stretch. Celebrity has
little to do with real estate values, experts say. A house
connected with a killing? That might subtract value. After all, the
new owners of O.J. Simpson's house tore it down _ and it wasn't
even the scene of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert E. Jones, an agent with Cora Bett Thomas Realty, the
local company handling the property with Sotheby's International
Realty, said notoriety had ``very little to do with the price.''
Mercer House is ``a phenomenon,'' he said, but not because of the .
. . er . . . shooting. (``Please don't say `murder,' '' Jones said.
``If you have to mention it, call it a `killing.' '' Although
Williams was twice convicted of murder, both verdicts were
overturned; his third trial ended in a mistrial, and he was
acquitted in the fourth.)
</P>
<P>
   The Italianate mansion, built for a Confederate general _ the
great-grandfather of the songwriter Johnny Mercer _ sits with its
carriage house on an entire block facing one of the city's 22
squares. ``It's the only house left in private hands that fills an
entire trust lot,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The asking price was arrived at in consultation with Dr.
Kingery, Sotheby's and his own company, Jones said, adding that he
expects the sale to bring close to that amount. He warned against
using Mercer House as an example of Savannah's market, thereby
perhaps scaring off potential buyers. In the last year, only 15 or
16 houses have sold for more than $500,000, and only 3 for more
than $1 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a house sells for over a million, 20 people at a
cocktail party want to put their dogs on the market,'' he said.
``They don't understand that Mercer House is unique.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale has not been advertised in the local newspaper, but
some townspeople who know about it are amused at the price. Lee
Adler, who has been honored by the National Trust for Historic
Preservation for his work restoring houses in Savannah, lives next
door, in an equally imposing Italianate house. Adler, peering over
his tortoise-shell half-glasses, called both the house and the
price ``remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I don't even mind the mobs outside,'' he said wryly.
</P>
<P>
   John Duncan is a retired history professor who operates an
antique book and print shop across Monterey Square. ``From the time
it was built, Mercer House was a trophy house,'' he said. ``It was
one of 10 or 15 in town. It would have been just another trophy
house until Jim Williams shot Danny Hansford and John Berendt wrote
the book. Then it became `the premiere house in Savannah.' Dr.
Kingery should be grateful to John Berendt _ it should be called
the Mercer-Williams-Berendt House.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kingery refers to Berendt's book as ``the book.'' She calls
it inaccurate, saying that her brother died of ``a major
coronary,'' not pneumonia, as Berendt wrote. But Dr. James Metts
Jr., the coroner, said that the cause was pneumonia, complicated by
heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kingery also does not approve of artists' and entrepreneurs'
making money by using the image of Mercer House _ at least without
her permission. In 1997, she received a trademark for the facade,
and her lawyer has sent letters to local artists _ including the
Lady Chablis, a transvestite who was featured in the book and was
pictured on a postcard posing in front of Mercer House _ demanding
that they stop or give her 10 percent of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   ``A home is private property,'' Dr. Kingery said this week.
``When people use it indiscriminately, one questions what rights
one has. I did what I wanted to protect the house. But no, I don't
run out and stop people.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the crowds outside, ``I've adapted well,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kingery moved into Mercer House shortly after her brother
died in 1990. That year, she did not give the annual Christmas
party that he had been known for, only a small birthday party for
their mother, Blanche B. Williams, who had been left the house and
almost all of Williams' property. (In his will, Williams stipulated
that Dr. Kingery's two daughters should inherit the bulk of the
property if his mother died before him. Three people familiar with
the family said Williams and his sister did not get along and that
on one occasion he asked her to leave the house.)
</P>
<P>
   Other than saying that the house had been a gift from her mother
and that she was currently its sole owner, Dr. Kingery said that
she did not wish to discuss the will. But she graciously gave a
reporter a tour of her house, from the second-floor dome, with its
spectacular stained glass, all the way down to what she calls ``the
moat,'' a trough running around the basement. Only the three
bedrooms and the study where the shooting took place were off
limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most everything is original,'' she said, folding a set of
white shutters into their window pockets. ``Look at these arches.
Look at these pocket doors. They still slide as beautifully as when
the house was built.''
</P>
<P>
   The house was designed by John Norris, a New York architect who
came to Savannah to design the U.S. Custom House and stayed long
enough to design many of the town's finest houses. ``He designed
the house in 1859, and construction began in 1860,'' Dr. Kingery
said. ``But as a result of the hostilities, construction ceased, so
it wasn't finished until after the Civil War.''
</P>
<P>
   The library is still filled with Williams' mementos, a melange
of eccentric, striking objects that he still watches over in a
photograph, hung by his sister, in which he holds his favorite cat,
Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was quite a handsome man,'' Dr. Kingery said. ``With his
dark hair and eyes, he looked like our father.'' In the small
library, there are Audubon prints, pre-Columbian pots, a carved
eagle from the first tugboat that plied Savannah's harbor and, in a
frame, a wasps' nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim was fascinated by wasps' nests,'' Dr. Kingery said ``He
loved their structure.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   She apologized for the boxes of scrapbooks in the dining room,
with its chandelier and exquisite blue-and-white Canton china. She
is compiling a book: essays Williams wrote about the houses he
restored. She said she was publishing it herself, ``so I can get it
out quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kingery said she had decided to sell the house because
``we've reached a new stage of life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jim died nine years ago,'' she said, ``I had one daughter
still in college, and my mother was living in her hometown. Now
perhaps it's time for someone else to enjoy Mercer House.'' She
said she ``probably will stay in town.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   OPTIONAL TRIM FOLLOWS. STORY CAN END HERE.
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Later that afternoon, another family of tourists, this one from
Germany, were snapping photographs _ the father against the
backdrop of Mercer House, then the mother and fresh-faced teen-age
daughter. ``Why are we here?'' the father said. ``Is this not the
place in the book?''
</P>
<P>
   He checked his map. They were told the house was for sale for
almost $9 million. ``We have no intention of buying the house,' he
said nervously. ``We took pictures because it is in the book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0135 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOFT-LIVING-ART-NYT &LR;      06-02 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFT-LIVING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRIVACY? IN A LOFT? WIDE OPEN SPACES FACE SUBDIVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The loft, it has been changing.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1940s, when Abstract Expressionists like Barnett
Newman moved into lofts, they wanted their spaces big and empty,
the better to wield the paintbrush to make mammoth art. But by the
1970s, artists were no longer the sole habitants of lofts.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the '70s, loft living was far less transgressive, far less
pioneering,'' said Mayer Rus, the editor of Interior Design
magazine and author of ``Loft'' (Monacelli, 1998). ``It was an
option not just for artists but for families. Family is a major
catalyst for having privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter, then, the box.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades into the loft age, the box, a
floor-to-near-ceiling structure, became an important design element
_ an architectural treasure chest that made loft living open and
airy, yet intimate. Placed in the center of the loft, or
off-center, it can contain closets, drawers and cupboards, or
enclose bedrooms, bathrooms and offices. Doors can slip from hidden
pockets within the box, or discreetly materialize from a recessed
slot nearby, to provide what even the most committed loft dweller
usually requires: a modicum of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   The box has played a starring role in three new Manhattan lofts.
David Ling, a Manhattan architect, even tossed the box a curve.
When he was asked to transform two adjacent one-bedroom apartments
in Greenwich Village into a single loft with a home office, he
first drew a box _ the office _ within the rectangular loft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I loosened up,'' Ling said. He designed the office as an
asymmetrically curved cocoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like curves juxtaposed against the geometry of rectangles,''
he said. ``The outside is smooth and spare; inside, it's intimate
and nurturing.''
</P>
<P>
   For privacy, the architect designed doors that are recessed in
the outer walls at opposite ends of the office but close to create
a guest room. With the doors open, the office is a sculptural
divider between the living-dining area and the bedroom. The curving
wall keeps part of the loft hidden, slightly mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   Ling also used architecture as a source of reflected light. In
the office, a soft golden light (from fluorescent bulbs) glows from
beneath the soffits. In the bedroom area, reading lights are
recessed in the cantilevered canopy and are as narrowly focused as
seat lights in airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Ling, who likes minimalist architecture, is not blind to its
defects. ``Pure minimalism is too reductive, too devoid of life,''
he said. ``And you need storage to make minimalism work.'' (To that
end, he lined one wall of the bedroom with floor-to-ceiling
closets.) Call the loft, whose box, including doors and lighting,
cost $3,000, warm minimalism.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the office-guest room don't reach the ceiling, and
the couple who own the loft, a banker and an artist, feared that
they would be disturbed by sleep-over guests. But no. ``The street
noise masked the snores,'' the artist said.
</P>
<P>
   When Andrew Bernheimer and Jared Della Valle, designers in
Manhattan, met their clients, a married couple who work in finance,
they had just bought a 1,600-square-foot loft in Chelsea. The
clients gave the designers a wish list. ``They wanted a red
bedroom, an open kitchen and maximum storage, openness and views,''
Bernheimer said.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was a deep-red box of aniline-dyed birch, roughly 14
feet square and 8 feet high. The box has multiple functions. The
two walls facing the kitchen and the living room contain a laundry
closet, a pantry, a storage closet for bulky items like luggage and
skis, and a coat closet. A steel door slides out of the wall facing
the living room and provides privacy for the master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the box, invisible from the living room, are a bathroom
and a second bedroom. A series of pocket doors, recessed into the
box, divide one room from another, while natural light from windows
facing north and south streams over the box from one end of the
loft to the other.
</P>
<P>
   From the private rooms tucked behind the box, the owners look
north to the Empire State Building and the scalloped crown of the
Chrysler Building. From the wide-open living and dining areas, they
look south as far as the World Trade Center and the World Financial
Center. The cost of the transformation, including construction, new
appliances, new windows, lighting, central air-conditioning and
audio-visual equipment, was $300,000. The box, including shelves
and closet interiors, cost $27,000.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the red box, which has a dark solidity about it, the box
that Robert Young, a Manhattan architect, designed for the
Greenwich Village loft of a film producer is subtle, partly
translucent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the contemporary loft feeling, but I didn't want that
overdone industrial look, all gray and metal,'' said the loft
owner, who shares his home with his girlfriend, who works in
advertising, and her white cat. What they needed were a bedroom and
an office.
</P>
<P>
   Young obliged with a spare and serene design and a box that is
so unobtrusive that it seems at first to be an L-shaped wall, set
in the pale rectangle of a loft where only the living room has
windows.
</P>
<P>
   To take advantage of the light, the loft is painted in pale
colors. The ceiling, beams and columns are chalk white, the
perimeter walls are cream, the box is khaki. The woodwork is
equally understated _ all golden-tone woods. Against this neutral
background are occasional bolts of color. Cobalt glass tiles
sparkle on the kitchen back splash; the sofa is tangerine; a chair
is coral.
</P>
<P>
   The industrial look makes brief appearances in the 1910
building, which was once used by marble cutters. The front door is
the original stainless steel, and the window frames were stripped
down to their bare nickel alloy, then sealed with clear lacquer.
</P>
<P>
   But what orders the space is the box, 25{ by 9{ feet, which
hides the bedroom, closet and home office-guest room. Young
inserted elements that perform double duties of a small but useful
nature. Light passes through a fiberglass panel, which supports
bookshelves on the outside and forms the headboard of the bed on
the private side. A closet dividing the two small rooms opens on
both sides: a sleep-over guest can pluck his clothes from the
closet without disturbing anyone asleep in the adjacent room, and
vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   The loft, which cost $70,000 to build, excluding appliances and
furniture _ the box, including the bookcase, closet and doors, cost
$11,000 _ would be a peaceful oasis if not for the cat. ``She's
nice to my girlfriend, but not to me,'' the owner said. ``She
bites. She scratches.'' He looked at her, sitting docilely on the
coral chair. ``Is there kitty Prozac?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
