<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0137 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-SPANISH-INTERNET-     06-02 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SPANISH-INTERNET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SPANISH AND PORTUGUESE, WEB GROWTH SPURT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Calif., Fla., N.Y.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JAMES RYAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, Anna Spinello, a clothing designer in Buenos Aires,
set up a Web site to help boost sales of her spring line. By
clicking on a little flag, a viewer can see the site in English,
Spanish or Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Considering we haven't publicized it, we've had an amazing
response,'' said her son Francesco Spinello, 42, who manages the
small, family-run business (www.annaspinello.com) that sells to
boutiques in Argentina, Chile, Uruguay and Brazil. ``We've made a
lot of contacts that should pay off with the next collection.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spinellos are part of a wave of Latin Americans who have
recently discovered the Web. Lagging perhaps two years behind the
United States, Japan and Western Europe in its development, the
Spanish- and Portuguese-speaking Internet market is one of the
fastest-growing in the world and has emerged as the latest
battleground for viewers among such Internet titans as America
Online and Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year the scales are tipping,'' said Heather
Killen, the vice president of Yahoo International, who oversaw the
start-up of a Spanish version of the Yahoo portal
(espanol.yahoo.com) in June 1998. ``The shape of the Internet is no
longer a comet with the U.S. as the head and this thin trail
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Latin American governments, aware of the need to promote local
Internet access and business so that more precious dollars do not
flow overseas, are also beginning to look at ways to encourage more
people to get on line.
</P>
<P>
   The governments of Argentina and Chile, for example, have
mandated that privately held phone companies charge half price for
local Internet access phone calls. Recent privatization of the
state-run phone company in Brazil, which is the only
Portuguese-speaking country in Latin America, is expected to lead
to reduced phone charges and better infrastructure and service in
that country, the most populous in the region, accounting for
roughly half the Internet users.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't allow citizens on line, they realize their
country is going to be at a significant disadvantage in the
future,'' said Annika Alford, chief Latin American Internet analyst
for IDC, a market research company in Framingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Internet's contributions to Latin America will be
allowing the Spinellos and other merchants to expand their reach
across borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is an extraordinary medium to improve
communication and exchange among different cultures and
languages,'' Spinello said. ``In Brazil, for example, we have few
clients now but there is great potential for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies in the United States, faced with slowing
growth at home, are looking for expansion through service in
languages other than English. This year, for the first time, there
will be more people gaining access to the Web from outside the
United States than from within, many of them preferring to do so in
their native tongue.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish-speaking population in the United States also holds
growth potential for Internet companies. Luis Hernandez, 18, a
bilingual senior at Hollywood High School in Los Angeles, uses the
Internet to search for information about his favorite Latin bands
and to chat with childhood friends living in Mexico as well as
other Spanish speakers using one of America Online's Hispanic chat
rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish language ``is easier for me to write in _ I'm
faster,'' he said, adding: ``It's our culture. We understand
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As they rush to sign up Spanish-language consumers, Internet
giants in this country face stiff competition from both Latin
American media companies and existing Spanish-language portals _
the industry term for a site that is both a primary destination and
a gateway to the Internet at large _ based in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Of these portals, Starmedia Network (starmedia.com), which saw
its stock nearly double on the first day of trading in its initial
public offering last week, has grabbed much of the attention for
its Spanish-Portuguese site.
</P>
<P>
   But other ventures are vying for the same users, and the last
few weeks have seen a flurry of announcements of new sites in the
Spanish-language Internet sector. Among the competitors are Que
Pasa (quepasa.com), a Spanish-English site, and Yupi (yupi.com),
which recently acquired Ciudad Futura, a Spanish-language online
entertainment site (www.ciudadfutura.com), and says it is the
front-runner with more than 5.7 million users and 80 million page
views per month from both the Yupi and Ciudad Futura sites.
Starmedia lays claim to 60 million page views per month and 2.4
million users.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg recently announced that it would soon open a bilingual
personal finance site for Hispanics in the United States
(www.negociosbloomberg.com).
</P>
<P>
   Just how many Hispanic Internet users there are is the subject
of some debate. The number of users of the Internet at large _ or
of a specific site _ is hard to measure, in part because of
differences in the methods of measurement in the fast-changing
world of electronic media.
</P>
<P>
   While operators of Web sites typically keep detailed logs of
user traffic, there is no generally accepted industry auditing
process for that data. And outside companies that try to compile
Web usage data, a la television's Nielsen ratings, must extrapolate
from audience samples that are widely thought to undercount
Internet use from work and ignore or undercount Internet use from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Starmedia, lumping together Hispanics in this
country, Portuguese-speaking Brazil, the countries of
Spanish-speaking Latin America, Spain and Portugal, come up with a
figure of about 20 million users worldwide, two-thirds of them in
Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   IDC, which takes a slightly more conservative approach, based on
its figures showing that there is an installed PC base in Latin
America of nearly 16 million computers and an Internet penetration
rate of 20 percent, estimates that by the end of 1999 there will be
7 million Latin Americans on line. IDC predicts that number will
grow to 19 million on line by the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics in the United States are another large and growing
market for Spanish-language sites. Data from Nielsen Net Ratings,
which monitors Web traffic, indicates that about 5 million of the
30 million Hispanics in the United States are on line. A study by
Forrester Research, however, put the figure closer to 10 million.
</P>
<P>
   A focus group study by Yahoo indicated that 70 percent of
American Hispanics preferred to get at least some of their content
in Spanish. That would suggest that there might be as many as seven
million Hispanics in this country surfing Spanish-language sites.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Yupi, with headquarters in Miami Beach and offices in seven
Latin American countries, estimates that 20 percent of its traffic
comes from American users.
</P>
<P>
   While Hispanics in this country may be an important sector of
the Spanish-language audience, the big growth in the user base is
expected to come from Latin America, particularly Brazil, with a
population of 160 million.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Rosa, 33, a writer and translator in Rio de Janeiro, said
he downloaded software and regularly communicated via e-mail with
other writers in the United States and elsewhere. He also conducts
much of his research on line, sometimes using the Brazilian search
engine Cade (cade.com.br), sometimes an English or French one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives me access to a lot of dictionaries and translating
tools,'' said Rosa, who has also taken screen-writing courses over
the Web through a company called Online Learning, based in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Already the Web is breaking down national barriers. On
Starmedia's bulletin boards and classified pages, for example,
people from many Latin American countries post notices side by side
or banter in chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Winning over locals like Rosa may prove a challenge for United
States companies moving into an increasingly crowded market.
Already there are in the neighborhood of 450 Internet service
providers in Brazil, 240 in Mexico and 170 in Argentina, according
to numbers from America Online's Latin American unit, as well as
long-established major destinations, many of them sponsored by
Latin American media giants like TV Globo (globo.com.br) and Grupo
Folha (uol.com.br) in Brazil and Grupo Clarin (clarin.com.ar) in
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   A common strategy is to find local partners who can help pave
the way in a market where personal relationships are key to
business success.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't sit in a city on another continent and say, `Right,
I'm going to launch something in Chile,''' said Phil Ingram,
marketing manager of Orientation.com, which is based in New York
and is creating a network of country portals. ``You have to have
local contacts who can build bridges.''
</P>
<P>
   Orientation.com plans to carve a niche for itself by focusing on
some of the smaller, overlooked countries _ Colombia, Costa Rica,
Chile _ with a network appealing to business travelers, offering a
currency converter, weather forecasts and trade show information in
English and Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   America Online has formed a 50-50 partnership with the Cisneros
Group, a major entertainment and telecommunications force in Latin
America that is based in Venezuela. And last month, the two
partners hired Charles Herington as president and chief executive
of AOL Latin America, which will first tackle the Brazilian market
and later Argentina. Herington previously helped Taco Bell and
Pizza Hut spread their franchises in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing Internet services, however, will prove more
complicated than selling fast food. Sites must be locally tailored.
Jack Davies, president of AOL International, promised that
Brazilians will not find themselves force-fed a service planned for
North Americans, but will instead find a product reconceived for
their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be very bright, very alive, very colorful, more
so than corresponding AOL.com's because of the festive nature of
Brazil,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Though features like chat, e-mail and up-to-the-second news have
proved enormously popular in Latin America, as they have elsewhere
in the world, electronic commerce, including sales of books, CDs,
computer equipment and clothing, may catch on more slowly because
of cultural and logistical differences.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, for example, does not have the United States' extensive
tradition in mail-order catalog buying on which to build an
electronic commerce market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Brazilians like to see the thing, touch it, like to be sure
we're going to have something,'' said Rosa, who once ordered books
from Amazon.com but had to wait seven weeks for them to arrive and
vows never to buy on line again.
</P>
<P>
   Further slowing the expansion of the Internet user base in Latin
America has been the regional economic crisis. The number of
Internet users in the region more than doubled from 1997 to 1998;
the 1999 growth appears to be only half as fast, IDC said.
</P>
<P>
   Herington at AOL, among others, said that the Internet itself
might provide the solution by improving communication and
distribution channels.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the obstacles for Latin American Web surfers are
underdeveloped telephone systems, the relatively high cost of
Internet access and the fact that many phone companies in Latin
America charge by the minute for local calls.
</P>
<P>
   Rosa, who estimates he spends an average of 60 hours a month on
line, pays the equivalent of $20 a month to his Internet service
provider for unlimited access, but local toll charges add another
$40 to his monthly phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many people can afford this?'' Rosa said of his fellow
Brazilians. ``Most people don't have enough money to afford a
computer. The base isn't going to expand unless we do all sorts of
socioeconomic development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
