<HEADLINE>
MONDAVI AIMS TO RAISE THE IMAGE OF AMERICAN CULTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PEG MELNIK   
 Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPA, Calif. _ Wine icon Robert Mondavi wants to make the ugly
American a Renaissance man. The groundbreaking of The American
Center for Wine, Food and the Arts has set in motion Mondavi's
goal: to make American civilization more civilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looked upon as being as cultured as other
countries,'' says the 85-year-old Mondavi. ``As I traveled the
world over, I saw that no one else had attempted to put food, wine
and the arts in one location. I knew this would help raise our
image.''
</P>
<P>
   The center, expected to open by fall 2001, will be in the heart
of wine country on a 12-acre spread on riverfront land. The
centerpiece will be an 80,000-square-foot main building housing an
auditorium, a cafe, teaching kitchens and 13,000 square feet of
exhibition space. A 500-seat outdoor amphitheater will be built for
musical and theatrical performances, the focal point of the
center's 3.5 acres of gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The groundbreaking Tuesday began a weeklong celebration, ending
with a free, community picnic on the downtown Napa site Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The $70 million project was initiated with $20 million from
Mondavi. The board is hoping to raise another $10 million for the
building and another $20 million for an endowment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wine business, I was able to make more money than I
expected to,'' Mondavi says. ``I had the means to take care of my
family and I wanted to give something back to our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondavi says the museum's artifacts will date back to primitive
man, the Egyptians, the Greeks and the Romans, showing why food,
wine and the arts enhance the quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime supporter of food and wine, Mondavi helped create the
American Institute of Wine &AMP; Food nearly 18 years ago. His wife,
Margrit Biever Mondavi, inspired him to make art a part of the trio
after she had coordinated cultural events at the Robert Mondavi
Winery for years.
</P>
<P>
   The founders expect 300,000-plus visitors annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people will see is that it has been the same since the
beginning of civilization, that food, wine and the arts have
enhanced people's lives for 7,000 years,'' Mondavi says. ``People
will no doubt say, `Hey, there's something to this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
