<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-BUDGET </SLUG>
  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR JUNE
2, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT 202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   GEORGIA-SPELLER. Benjamin R. Locklair, a 14-year-old eighth
grader from Columbia Middle School, is competing in the National
Spelling Bee Wednesday. This is a wrap-up of how he did. (400
words.) By Ron Eckstein
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA-RADAR. After more than a year of testing, a digital
warning system designed to alert motorists of approaching roadside
hazards is being expanded in northwest Indiana. (500 words.) By
Sara Kugler
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-SPELLER. Maine's top speller, Greg Thaler, survived the
first round of the National Spelling Bee Wednesday. (600 words.) By
Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-SPELL. With three correct words Wednesday, Harry
Altman, a sixth grader at Glen Rock Middle School, continued his
own odyssey. He now moves into the final rounds of the bee after
spelling three words in the early portion of the tournament, which
brings together 249 of the nation's top spellers. Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA-BEE. Justin Balletta sat patiently on the stage
in the crowded Grand Hyatt ballroom as he watched words like
``trypanosomiasis'' and ``piloncillo'' trip up his fellow spellers
in the first round. But when the Weddington sixth-grader approached
the microphone, he spelled ``schnitzel'' with ease, setting the
pace for a successful first day at the 72nd Annual Scripps Howard
National Spelling Bee. (450 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-BEE. A few butterflies in the stomach weren't enough to
stop Dan Joslyn from making it to the second day of the Scripps
Howard National Spelling Bee. The North Olmstead Youth on Thursday
will enter the next round to compete for $10,000 cash, and other
prizes. (10-12 inches.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-SPELLING-BEE. Perryton eighth-grader Angela Arenivar
competed in the national spelling bee for the second year in a row
-- and made it one round further than last year, getting out on
``heleoplankton.'' (400 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-BEE. After successfully making it through the first
two rounds, Cedarburg speller Whitney B. Holcomb cautiously gave
the letters ``g-u-t-t-e-r-a-l-i-z-e.'' But then the fateful ding
sounded, telling her she had misspelled ``gutturalize'' --
eliminating her from the 72nd Annual Scripps Howard National
Spelling Bee. (450 words.) By Elizabeth Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-BEE. Wyoming whiz kid Clayton Thomas can still win the
National Spelling Bee after spelling his three words correctly.
(500 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
