</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0157 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRANBROOK-RENOVATION-     06-02 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRANBROOK-RENOVATION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDED BY THE SPIRIT OF ELIEL SAARINEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. _ Not long after Eliel Saarinen's brand
of kiln-fired, loom-woven, handcrafted modernism was elbowed aside
by the harder-edged International style, development all but
stopped on his architectural masterwork: the ensemble of museums,
schools and design academy now known as the Cranbrook Educational
Community.
</P>
<P>
   But today, a sinuous Y-shaped canopy of copper mesh and
stainless steel rises over a new entrance to the institution's
deeply wooded, 315-acre campus. It stands poised over the roadway
like sheltering wings or an echo of the rolling landscape beyond.
Or _ perfect for a Detroit suburb _ a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the iconology, the message is unmistakable. Cranbrook
is building again, on a campuswide scale, for the first time since
its flowering in the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Cranbrook offers a vibrant reminder that modernism
is not exclusively the realm of sharp right angles and cold, flat
surfaces, of glass and steel. In other words, that there is a place
for the tactile, the colorful and the irregular, for the handiwork
and sensuousness of rough masonry and glazed tile, even _ dare one
say it? _ for the picturesque.
</P>
<P>
   More than $100 million worth of construction and renovation has
been completed or is now contemplated at Cranbrook. This time,
there is no single designer. Instead, Steven Holl of New York, Jose
Rafael Moneo of Madrid, Peter Rose of Montreal, and Tod Williams
(Cranbrook '61) and Billie Tsien of New York are working almost
simultaneously on campus, exploring connections to the past while
forging Cranbrook's new architectural identity.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Dan Hoffman, the campus architect and a
professor at the University of Michigan, has broadened Cranbrook's
artisanal tradition to include skilled machinists at factories
around the Great Lakes, whose work he has incorporated in
small-scale projects like the entrance canopy.
</P>
<P>
   All of the designers are interested, as Saarinen was, in
architectural context, in the details of the building process and
in the relationship between structures and the natural environment.
They speak of weaving _ weaving rich materials into their
structures, and then weaving their structures into the landscape of
towering conifers and the legacy of Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   For in the end, the most important architect in the
revitalization of Cranbrook is Saarinen himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planning ideas, the buildings that make space, the
condition of perspective and termination and the secret axes
through the landscape are something very special and important,''
said Holl, who has designed an expansion and renovation of
Saarinen's Institute of Science. ``To be able to put a building
there as part of that network is an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Holl said one of his goals in architecture is to ``bring essence
back into experience'' _ smell, sound and touch _ and to give ``a
tactile and material dimension to everyday existence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a connection to Saarinen,'' Holl said. ``He believed
in the same things.''
</P>
<P>
   Saarinen's own work is being restored to luminous life following
decades of heavy use and inadequate care. He is emerging from the
shadow cast first by the Bauhaus and then by his own son, Eero, who
worked on Cranbrook as a young man but later soared to worldwide
renown for swooping abstract monuments like the TWA Flight Center
at Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Eliel Saarinen, whose roots were in the Romantic nationalistic
styles of his native Finland, came to America in 1923 at age 50,
using the second-place prize money he had won in the competition to
design the Tribune Tower in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   His losing entry, one of the more influential unbuilt buildings
of the 20th century, eliminated cornices and employed setbacks to
create an exceptionally vertical composition. But this was no
stripped-down building; Saarinen planned Romanesque arches at the
base, foreshadowing his work at Cranbrook.
</P>
<P>
   In 1924, he was invited by George Gough Booth, who published The
Detroit Evening News and had helped found the Detroit Society of
Arts and Crafts, to work on the design of a new kind of
educational, cultural and spiritual community that Booth and his
wife, Ellen, were planning at Cranbrook, their estate about 25
miles northwest of downtown Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the complex would include a graduate art academy and
art museum, a science museum, elementary and secondary schools and
a church, which was later separated from the group. Today, there
are 1,550 students from prekindergarten to the 12th grade and 150
graduate students in the Cranbrook Academy of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Saarinen was the resident architect for the campus from 1925 to
1950 and the president of the Academy of Art from 1932 to 1946,
during which time he attracted students and teachers like Harry
Bertoia, Charles and Ray Eames (who met and married there),
Florence Knoll, Jack Lenor Larsen and Harry Weese.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were few places in the world _ the vastly more
significant Bauhaus, of course, was one _ where every field of
design, from textiles and metalwork to architecture and city
planning, was encompassed in so comprehensive a curriculum,'' Allan
Temko wrote about Cranbrook in ``Eero Saarinen'' (George Braziller,
1962).
</P>
<P>
   Even though he did not attend the academy, Williams, who now
practices architecture in New York with Ms. Tsien, was exposed to
the academy's influence as a youngster in the boys' school. ``By
the age of 12, I was welding chairs,'' Williams recalled. ``You
don't get to do that in many high schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliel Saarinen's approach to architecture was as wide-ranging as
the academy's curriculum. The boys' school, called Cranbrook
(completed in 1929), feels like a Romanesque cloister. The girls'
school, Kingswood (1931), glides along the horizon, Prairie-style.
The Cranbrook Institute of Science (1938) stands as foursquare as a
1920s German factory by the likes of Peter Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   Saarinen's own house, which was completed in 1930 and lustrously
restored in 1994, is a cross between Finnish serenity and Art Deco
exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No architect, God forbid, who considered himself a modernist
would have used velvet portieres,'' said Gregory Wittkopp, the
director of the Cranbrook Art Museum, before drawing aside these
plush curtains to reveal Saarinen's jewel box of a dining room,
with its gold-leafed dome, hemispherical brass chandelier and
flute-backed side chairs of fir and maple.
</P>
<P>
   The new architects are neither replicating nor repudiating
Saarinen. ``They want to do something that reflects and enhances
what came before, rather than compete with it,'' said Dr. Robert
Gavin, the president of the Cranbrook Educational Community, as the
ensemble of institutions is now known. ``There's a strong feeling
about compatibility and integration, but not mimickry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavin inherited many of the projects from his predecessor,
Lillian Bauder, who in the mid-1980s began the much-needed process
of updating and expanding the campus.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The first significant new building to be completed, in 1996, was
a $9.5 million addition to and renovation of Brookside, the lower
school. Cranbrook chose Rose, the Montreal architect, for the job
in part because of his work within other historic contexts. One of
his best-known designs, in Montreal, involved a new building for
Phyllis Lambert's Canadian Centre for Architecture, which had to be
integrated with the historic Shaughnessy House of 1874.
</P>
<P>
   To Brookside's delightful 1929 jumble of storybook cottages,
Rose cobbled a two-story addition with its own lively tiled
roofscape and a facade of deliberately mottled concrete blocks in
varying hues and intensities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the block factory,'' Rose said. ``We did what
Saarinen did, which was we got involved in the construction
process. So what you get from this very base, ordinary, inexpensive
material is a richness of texture and color.''
</P>
<P>
   Holl, who has reversed the Saarinens' Finnish-and-American
cross-fertilization as the architect of the new Museum of
Contemporary Art in Helsinki, was chosen for the next significant
commission: a $29 million expansion and renovation of the Institute
of Science. He was picked, Cranbrook said in a statement, because
he ``shares Saarinen's interest in the theoretical issues of
science, the use of craft, and an interest in the integration of
art, architecture and nature.''
</P>
<P>
   As a museum of natural history and science that draws 250,000
visitors a year, the institute is by far the most public of
Cranbrook's buildings. And Holl's addition, clad in bright,
sand-colored Kasota stone and concrete block, loses no time in
performing its educational mission.
</P>
<P>
   The 42-foot-high entrance hall doubles as what Holl calls a
``light laboratory,'' where various characteristics of light are
demonstrated by a curtain-wall patchwork of seven different types
of glass, each of which transmits or diffuses or refracts daylight
in different ways. A thick speckled rainbow greeted museumgoers on
a recent afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Within, the plan is exceptionally open and draws visitors along
sloping pathways bathed in natural light, past bursts of
contrasting colors and playful displays. By attaching a new
structure to bridge Saarinen's U-shaped plan, Holl created a
courtyard and brought a sense of motion and circulation to a layout
that had previously ended in cul-de-sacs.
</P>
<P>
   Water in all of its forms _ liquid, vapor and solid _ is the
theme of the terraced outdoor courtyard that Holl created. The
centerpiece is a bulbous 15-foot ``ice house'': in warmer months it
looks like a giant steel woven basket, but come winter, sprayed
mist turns the frame into thick walls of ice.
</P>
<P>
   Water in another form _ an eight-lane, 25-yard swimming pool _
will be at the heart of the $10 million natatorium now under
construction, to designs by Williams and Ms. Tsien.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the Cranbrook spirit, Williams said, there will
be ``an inextricable relationship between inside and outside.''
Weather permitting, the pool can be opened to the sky through two
enormous oculi that have retractable roofs. And at all seasons, a
length of windows along one wall will allow swimmers to see trees
pass by.
</P>
<P>
   Because brick appears almost everywhere on campus, its use was a
``foregone conclusion'' for the natatorium, said Martin Finio, the
project architect at the Williams and Tsien firm.
</P>
<P>
   But at Cranbrook, brick is no simple matter. To help the
building recede into the landscape, Williams and Ms. Tsien chose an
extra-long, dark, plum-colored brick with iridescent spotting,
accented by panels of blue and green bricks that are meant to
recall sky, trees and Cranbrook's copper roofs. Getting just the
right translucent wash in those glazes involved much trial and
error for the brick makers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, Williams said, ``I intend for the trees to come
back and screen it so that it becomes more a part of the landscape
than an object.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy's new student art studios, workshops and gallery are
now being designed by Moneo, the recipient of the 1996 Pritzker
Architecture Prize. They will be joined to the building complex
that includes Cranbrook's signature structure, the Peristyle
(1942), an open-air columned pavilion that intersects a grand
north-south vista, framed by a fountain, pools and sculptures.
</P>
<P>
   The need for new work space is acute. It is not simply that the
existing studios are antiquated, but their small size inhibits the
production of large-scale contemporary art. ``If you have a library
with six-inch shelves,'' said Gary Griffin, the metal smith in
residence, ``you're probably going to have six-inch books.''
</P>
<P>
   On the facades facing the grounds, Moneo plans to follow the
early Cranbrook model of a strongly horizontal building of
interlocking masses, covered in dark brick and roofed in copper. On
the courtyard facades, he is proposing a more industrial look, with
a chorus of chimneys counterbalanced by the grid of a glass curtain
wall.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a struggle to keep the studio project within its
allotted budget. But financial squeezing is not a new exercise at
Cranbrook, which took almost 40 years to recover from the deaths,
one after the other, of Cranbrook's founders, Ellen Booth in 1948
and George Booth in 1949, and of Eliel Saarinen in 1950. To meet
expenses in the 1970's, Cranbrook sold off 60 percent of the
artwork from its Academy of Art collection.
</P>
<P>
   The physical plant was suffering, too. ``The dorms were
originally furnished in Stickley furniture,'' said Mark Coir, the
director of the Cranbrook archives. ``That wore out. Then it was
Aalto furniture. That wore out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he joked, ``it's Sears Best.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1985 with a $38.5 million windfall from the sale to
the Gannett Company of the Evening News Association, in which
Cranbrook was the largest stockholder, the institution recovered
its financial footing and began piecing its aging campus back
together.
</P>
<P>
   There was much to repair. For example, the cantilevered eaves of
the copper roofs of Saarinen's Kingswood buildings had been
extensively damaged because the gutters had deteriorated. And the
surface of the floor tiles had worn away.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration has now begun at Kingswood. The other day, when a
tile worker saw a visitor taking a photograph of the custom-made
floor tiles, in more than a dozen shades of green, he suggested a
better angle _ one that would show how exactingly he had laid the
courses.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again at Cranbrook, the craft tradition reasserts
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Trellis Bridge (1994), a 58-foot-long pedestrian crossing
over a branch of the River Rouge, was largely built by students in
the studio. The project architect, Ted Galante, was a student at
the time. (Hoffman, now the campus architect, was the designer.) It
is covered by an interlaced network of crisscrossed pine struts,
gently bowed into a wishbone shape, creating a dappled and
ever-changing profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ur-craft is weaving,'' Hoffman said, ``and weaving and
repetition produced all these wonderful qualities. And it was woven
into the education.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman has tried another kind of weaving, as well _ weaving the
work of skilled machinists into Cranbrook's architectural
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The mesh in the entry canopy was made by Phoenix Wire Cloth of
Detroit, whose products are ordinarily used for hydraulic
filtration or industrial waste treatment. The columns were made by
a Wisconsin company that supplies piping to nuclear power plants.
And a curving steel retaining wall along the roadway was made by a
shipbuilding yard on Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the thread between building construction and
high-quality fabrication practices has been lost in this country,''
Hoffman said. ``We have attempted to re-establish this
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Saarinen himself wrestled with the question of how the machine
would affect art and architecture. In ``Search for Form''
(Reinhold, 1948), he seemed to anticipate Hoffman's harnessing of
the craft potential in industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should it happen that the new disposition of mind may be
mechanized,'' Saarinen wrote, ``this will not be a lasting state of
things; for undoubtedly, mechanization of mind will turn _ when the
time is ripe _ into humanization of the mechanized mind. Form is
bound to follow the same metamorphosis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
