<HEADER>
A0167 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE-ART     06-02 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE-ART-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES BABY WANT A BROWSER? PERHAPS A CD-ROM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After his first grueling day as a software tester, Matthew Moore
went home, had a snack and an early bath, and was asleep by 7:30,
snuggled under his little quilted green blanket. At the time,
Matthew was 1 year old.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the software company called and said they had a program
for him, I said: `You must be mistaken _ you must want one of my
older children,''' recalled Matthew's mother, Megan Moore, a nurse
who lives in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But the software evaluators at Knowledge Adventure assured her
that it was Matthew and not one of his three older siblings _ all
experienced testers _ they were after. So a few days later, the
little boy sat on his mother's lap in the company's testing
laboratory in nearby Torrance, a comfortable carpeted room equipped
with a computer, a hidden camera and a big mirror covering one
wall. The evaluation team on the other side of the mirror could see
through a one-way window, observing as Matthew jabbered in
excitement when an animated teddy bear appeared on screen. Matthew
pounded on the keyboard. His mother moved it away. Matthew reached
for the mouse, then pounded it with a little fist. Repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Matthew became a computer user, Knowledge Adventure
introduced the teddy bear to the marketplace on a CD-ROM called
Jumpstart Baby, and Matthew, enamored of the program, begged
incessantly at home to play what he calls ``Star Baby.'' The title
became an immediate hit, climbing to No. 13 on a 1998 list of the
best-selling software for preschoolers compiled by PC Data of
Reston, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Both Jumpstart Baby and Matthew Moore are at the vanguard of a
trend in introducing younger and younger children to computers.
``We call it baby programming,'' said Idit Harel, the founder and
chief executive of Mamamedia, which operates a Web site
(www.mamamedia.com) where a baby can create an animated story by
clicking on icons. ``You take a character and attach it to a
behavior, and that is programming. You take the same creative tools
designed for older children, and often even a baby can learn from
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, that same motto _ even a baby can learn _
encouraged well-meaning parents to hang black-and-white mobiles
above cribs to stimulate newborns and to press headphones to their
pregnant bellies to expose the unborn to Mozart. These days, many
parents view the computer as a symbol of a technology-laden
tomorrow and want even the tiniest citizens of the future to be
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred on by eager parents who want to give their children a
head start, a growing number of companies have begun to develop and
release an avalanche of products aimed squarely at techno-toddlers.
America Online is developing a new content area to serve children
ages 2 to 5, encouraged by an online poll earlier this year of
10,000 parents; 25 percent said their children had begun using a
computer by age 2.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, diaper-dragging lap-sitters can choose from an array
of products, from software programs like Babywow! (published by
Bowwow House) to video console games like Elmo's Number Journey (by
Newkidco, for Sony Playstation) to Internet sites intended to lure
infants on line. The Children's Television Workshop is about to
release Baby and Me, the company's first software program for the
growing market of 1- to 3-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   But even as sales of the top 20 software titles for children 4
and younger increased 25.5 percent last year, to $45.8 million from
$36.5 million in 1997, skeptics raise a basic question: What can a
baby possibly get from a computer?
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine this: software for babies?'' said Ann
Stephens, president of PC Data. ``This category didn't even exist
five years ago. It's absurd. What next, womb ware?''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Armour Polly, author of ``The Internet Kids and Family
Yellow Pages'' (Osborne-McGraw-Hill, 1999), said: ``Little kids
should be down on the floor banging on pots and spoons, not banging
on the keyboard. I saw a Web site where you can drag a pine cone
over to a sink to see if it floats. Why not just turn off the
computer, go outside and pick up a pine cone so the toddler can
learn what a pine cone is?''
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of early introduction to computers say it will
make it easier for children to use the computers they will almost
assuredly confront as soon as they get to school. In addition, they
say, computer time creates one more activity that parents and
children can share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to help children learn in one way other
than the traditional ways of books and explanatory toys,'' said
Peter Doctorow, president of Knowledge Adventure, which this year
is greatly expanding its line of software for preschoolers. ``It's
wonderful when little kids become comfortable and excited about
what they can do with computers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, many of the programs don't require much from the children
_ a good thing, given that many of them would be just as happy
pouring a cup of orange juice into the keyboard as manipulating
objects on the screen. Some programs don't even make use of a
mouse; any key a baby bangs will prompt a response.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
