<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE-ART     06-02 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: a response.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As rudimentary as some of these programs are, some parents swear
by them. Peter Borish, a futures-fund manager who lives in
Manhattan, has three children, ages 8, 6 and 4. He said his
youngest child was introduced to computers earlier than the others,
sitting on his lap while he surfed with the older children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given a choice of using the computer or watching TV, my
oldest, a second grader, will want to sit down and watch an hour of
TV,'' he said. ``But my 4-year-old will always choose the computer,
and I think it's because it's been more a part of her life, from an
earlier age. Is it critical that at age 4 she's computer literate?
No, but I like the fact that she's doing something that's more
engaging and more intellectually stimulating than watching
television.''
</P>
<P>
   The Borishes' experience is typical of how computers insinuate
themselves into family life. There is a trickle-down effect. First,
parents buy a computer so their older children can use it for
educational purposes, like research and homework help. Inevitably,
younger siblings clamor for equal time at the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it becomes a shared experience with parents because you
just don't see many 2-year-olds sitting at the keyboard alone,
tapping away,'' said Anya Sacharow, an analyst at Jupiter
Communications in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What this generation will become when they get older is
something we're thinking of as post-modern kids, who will be more
prone to split their attention, to watch TV while they're on the
Internet and talking on the phone, all at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun maybe, but there is no evidence to suggest either a benefit
or drawback to introducing very young children to computers. ``With
older children, there's plenty of research that shows that good
software benefits them. But that's all research done in social
settings, such as schools, and with kids who are 3 and up,'' said
Daniel D. Shade, a professor of child development and early
childhood education at the University of Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   According to guidelines set by the International Society for
Technology in Education, a teachers' group in Eugene, Ore.,
children as young as 4 should learn to use a mouse and keyboard.
But since there's no evidence that it will speed a younger child's
physical development, ``I doubt seriously that a child who starts
at a young age of 2 or so will have an advantage,'' said Anita
Best, editor of Learning and Leading With Technology, the society's
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some toddlers just are not interested in computers.
Louisa Campbell, a writer and mother of two who lives in Brooklyn,
says her 5-year-old son likes the computer. But her 2{-year-old
daughter does not. ``My son, who is sort of technically oriented,
has been using CD-ROM's since he was 2,'' Ms. Campbell said. ``But
my daughter is much more physical and likes to run around a lot.
She doesn't like to sit at the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, researchers and manufacturers predict a steady increase
in products aimed at younger and younger children. ``We know there
are four million kids born in this country every year, and all of
them will need to know how to read and do math,'' said Jonathan
Harber, chairman of Newkidco, which this year released two
educational video console game titles for 2-year-olds. ``So what is
the right age to start a child on a computer? I'm not so sure there
might not be a place for a computerized rattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Moore is now well past the computerized rattle stage.
Now 2{, he has graduated to more sophisticated programs like ``The
Cat in the Hat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives him a great sense of accomplishment to be able to do
something that his older sisters and brother do,'' Ms. Moore said.
But he still hasn't learned to use the mouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
