<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASHINGTON'S-DIET-2TA     06-02 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASHINGTON'S-DIET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE WASHINGTON GARDENED HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   Mac Griswold is the author of ``Washington's Gardens at Mount
Vernon: Landscape of the Inner Man,'' which was just published by
Houghton Mifflin.  
 (bl)  
 By MAC GRISWOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At this late date, the 200th anniversary of his death, you might
think that anything and everything about George Washington had long
been chewed over. But wait: what was the connection between the
beautiful, whoppingly productive gardens of Mount Vernon and those
famous false teeth? And by the way, what could our first president
 &UR; eat &LR; ?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much!'' said Dr. John Hyson, director of curatorial
affairs at the Dr. Samuel D. Harris National Museum of Dentistry in
Baltimore. ``I'm sure he chewed with great difficulty, and since he
was a proud man, he must have felt great embarrassment about eating
in front of an audience. It was awkward to manipulate those things
the way the springs bounced around.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So when Washington sat down to dinner at 3 in the afternoon
after his daily ride (about five hours) overseeing Mount Vernon's
7,600-plus acres, he must have eyed the table warily to see what a
man with very few teeth could gracefully manage. (He lost his first
tooth at 22, and when he became president, at 57, he had only one
natural tooth left.)
</P>
<P>
   What grew in the garden would have been his first choice, said
Hyson, who noted that the great man especially liked fruit _
berries and baked apples.
</P>
<P>
   Peas and artichokes were also favorites, according to
Washington's own letters and diaries. When George and Martha headed
home after one of their many absences, Martha wrote ahead to say
she hoped the gardener would have ``every thing in his garden that
will be nessary in the House keeping way as vegetable is the best
part of our living in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1797, one Amariah Frost visited Mount Vernon. ``The dinner
was very good,'' he wrote, ``a small roasted pigg, boiled leg of
lamb, roasted fowls, beef, peas, lettuce, cucumbers, artichokes,
etc., pudding, tarts, etc. etc.'' Except for a few exotics like
ginger or tea, it was all homegrown.
</P>
<P>
   Before dinner, Frost had toured the two shield-shaped,
brick-walled gardens, the upper and the lower, each about an acre,
which he found ``very elegant, abounding with many curiosities, Fig
trees, raisins'' _ meaning table grapes _ ``limes, oranges, etc.,
large English mulberries, artichokes, etc.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, both gardens are again chockablock with rows of
vegetables, clumps of flowering herbs, and fruit trees, which stand
in beds or are espaliered to the brick walls. Some are dwarfed into
space-saving cordons around the edges of the beds. In the upper
garden is the conservatory, where the limes and oranges that Frost
saw were wintered over, as their descendants are today.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Mount Vernon's four-acre fruit garden was laid out
with berry patches and 25 varieties of apple, plum, peach, pear and
cherry. In the fall, field orchards produced as much as 120 gallons
of hard and sweet cider and homemade brandy a day. And besides the
gardens and orchards that fed Washington's family and guests, 316
slaves grew ``garden truck'' to supplement their daily ration of a
quart of cornmeal and 5 ounces of salt herring.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Head gardeners were often indentured. There was a lot of
turnover (10 between 1762 and 1797), and Washington had a hard time
finding good staff.
</P>
<P>
   In 1771, he wrote a grumpy letter to his English agent: ``I do
not desire any of your fine fellows who will content themselves
with Planning of Work, I want a Man that will labour hard, knowing
at the same time how to keep a Garden in good Order and Sow Seed in
their proper seasons in ground that he has prepard well for the
reception of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Dean Norton, Mount Vernon's 34th head gardener, scours
the globe for the heirloom fruits and vegetables that are now part
of the process of historic preservation. His job is easier than it
was when he started 22 years ago, thanks to the explosive interest
in old varieties among home gardeners. He prizes his collection of
beans, as decorative as they are edible, and the trimly espaliered
cherries _ May Duke, Morello and Montmorency.
</P>
<P>
   Washington would not be surprised at what Norton is putting in
at the beginning of June. He is still planting some of the same old
beans, like the bush bean Black Valentine, the lima bean called
Worcester Indian Red, and Blue Coco, an 18th-century pole bean.
Yellow crookneck squash and other squashes will thrive if planted
now, and so will sweet corn.
</P>
<P>
   Norton is most excited about 11 kinds of antique fruit trees due
to arrive in the fall, the gift of the Worshipful Company of
Fruiterers, in London, founded in the 13th century.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken many hands to get these old bloodlines back to
Mount Vernon _ gardening is still a hands-on business, just as it
was when Washington was grafting cherry scions given to him by a
friend. (Another myth dispelled: Instead of cutting down cherry
trees, Washington grafted hundreds himself.)
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Sam Benowitz of Braintree Nurseries in Morton,
Wash., the London fruiterers tracked down scions (small cut
branches) at Nick Botner's farm in Yoncalla, Ore. Botner has three
refrigerators full of plastic bags containing thousands of scions
of different varieties that he cut when the trees were dormant, and
he makes grafting a scion on a fruit tree you already own sound
easy.
</P>
<P>
   Grafting was the bio-engineering of centuries past: scions will
produce their own kind of fruit while deriving strength from the
host.
</P>
<P>
   So if you have a Bing cherry tree and you want May Duke cherries
like Washington's, you graft on a scion, and if it takes, you'll
soon have two kinds of cherries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some grafts will make fruit the following year,'' Botner said,
``because if you are grafting on an existing tree, you already have
established vigor.'' Plant a May Duke cherry tree from scratch, and
you'll wait several years for the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Like his Virginia planter contemporaries _ and like a lot of
gardeners today _ Washington enjoyed the status that comes with
growing produce no one else can grow. Those cherries and squashes
also embodied security; he knew where his next meal was coming
from.
</P>
<P>
   An ideal order in a chaotic world _ a balance of use and beauty
_ was part of Washington's vision, as it is for today's gardeners.
He hoped that the orderly agriculture and horticulture of his
plantation would be a model for the new nation.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the simple pleasures of observation and
anticipation, pleasures that frequently burst through our
gardener-President's usually measured demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cherries, Plumbs, Pears and Apples bloomed forth,'' he wrote
happily in his diary almost every spring over his 45 years of
vegetable and fruit gardening at Mount Vernon. By June, those
cherries would be in fruit and the fruit on the table _ stewed,
perhaps, for easy eating.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For anyone interested in growing historic varieties, Barbara J.
Barton's ``Gardening by Mail'' (Mariner Books, $24) is an
invaluable sourcebook. Among its listings for heirloom vegetables
and antique fruit trees is D. Landreth Seed Co., which furnished
seeds to both Washington and Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   The Cook's Garden, Londonderry, Vt. 05148 (800-457-9703) lists
more than 100 heirloom fruits and vegetables in its free catalog. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southmeadow Fruit Gardens, Baroda, Mich. 49101 (616-422-2411)
has more than 300 varieties of old fruit trees. Illustrated
112-page catalog, $9; illustrated pamphlet on grafting fruit trees,
$3; free price list. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southern Exposure Seed Exchange, Earlysville, Va. 22936
(804-973-4703) has many heirloom and open-pollinated vegetables.
Catalog, $2.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Botner, 4015 Eagle Valley Road, Yoncallo, Ore. 97499
(541-849-2781): a listing of his fruit tree scions, $2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The journal of North American Fruit Explorers, PO Box 29,
Lucernemines, Pa. 15754 covers all areas of fruit growing;
membership, $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heirloom Vegetable Gardening: A Master Gardener's Guide to
Planting, Seed Saving and Cultural History,'' by William Woys
Weaver (Henry Holt, $25), makes useful reading.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
