A0196 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-BEEP-COM-NYT &LR;      06-02 0525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-BEEP-COM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURN UP THE VOLUME FOR E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Colo.)   (af)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The best thing about e-mail: it's not a phone call. No jarring
rings jolting you out of a nap, no on-the-spot replies required,
and if you're not interested, the Delete button is just a few
inches away.
</P>
<P>
   But like it or not, the communications industry keeps trying to
find ways to merge the Internet with the telephone. A recent effort
is the introduction of Beep, which lets you send voice messages via
e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Offered by Vstream, a company specializing in Internet-based
teleconferencing, Beep works like this: you log onto the Vstream
Web site (vsnetcall.vstream.com/beep) and enter your e-mail address
along with the e-mail address of the recipient.
</P>
<P>
   You are then given a six-digit identification number and
instructed to call either a toll or toll-free phone number
(depending on what part of the country they live in). When a
Vstream recording answers the call, you enter your ID number on the
phone keypad and leave a message up to two minutes long, which is
recorded and converted using streaming technology.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, a message saying ``You've been beeped!''
lands in the recipient's e-mail In box, and the person is given a
link to a Vstream site to retrieve the message. Streaming enables
users to start receiving the contents of the audio file before it
has been completely transmitted, resulting in almost immediate
playback of the message.
</P>
<P>
   As with a lot of novelty items on the Web (think electronic
greeting cards), getting the final product can be a bit dicey.
Listening to the Beep message requires the receiver to have either
Windows Media Player or Real Networks' Real Player (for Macintosh
users), software that allows your computer to play the message.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 includes Media Player; for users of other operating
systems who must first download a player, the entire
message-retrieval process can take several minutes.
</P>
<P>
   David Latham, a rankled test recipient of Beep, said he spent
too much time trying to download the Windows Media Player without
success. ``A pox on your beep,'' he fired back to the sender.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Berberian, co-founder and chief executive of Vstream, which
is based in Boulder, Colo., said the company introduced Beep in May
to give ``recognition to the convergence of multiple
technologies.'' In April, Vstream introduced Netcall, its core
product.
</P>
<P>
   Netcall is a fee-based Internet software utility that lets you
send business presentations and other graphic information via
e-mail to a Vstream server. Vstream converts the content, again
using streaming technology, and makes the presentation available
for viewing by up to 1,200 people at a time.
</P>
<P>
   As for Beep, Berberian said it would remain a free service (with
the exception of the toll call required in some areas), and added
that the company was in discussions with electronic greeting card
companies, electronic photography companies and portal sites about
adding a voice layer to their products. Can telephone soliciting
over the Internet be far behind?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
