<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY CONVERSATION WITH LIDDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Wednesday, June 3)  
(DW) 
 By DAVID GRIMES Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I read where Elizabeth Dole, winner of the Ladies' Home Journal
``One Smart Lady'' award and also a candidate for some sort of
political office, has taken to making surprise 5-minute phone calls
to random journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when you'll be sitting at your desk and get a
call from Elizabeth Dole,'' said spokesman Ari Fleischer.
</P>
<P>
   Reporter Richard Berke of The New York Times is one of several
journalists who has been caught off guard by a Dole phone call.
Berke said he had no questions prepared, since he wasn't expecting
the call, and that it was so brief as to be of little use.
</P>
<P>
   I do not intend to let that happen to me. When Elizabeth Dole
calls - and I feel certain that she will - I will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to hem and haw when your wife calls you at work
to inquire about the $200 Visa bill you rang up at the Cheetah
Lounge and quite another thing when a candidate for president of
the United States calls to chat about the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Some cynics say that Dole is randomly phoning journalists to
dispel her image of being overly scripted. Last March, The New York
Times reported that Dole ``prepares so thoroughly for appearances
that she even requires aides to count the steps she must take to
the podium.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why Dole requires aides to count the number of
steps she must take to the podium _ perhaps her eyesight is bad and
she's afraid of walking too far and toppling off the stage and into
the audience _ but it's certainly something I'd like to discuss
with her when she rings me up &UR; . &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, for purposes of research, I have taken to
counting my steps to certain selected destinations to determine if
that is one of the secrets of Powerful People. For example, I now
know that it is 20 steps to the coffeemaker, 27 steps to the
bathroom and 107 paces to the front door and freedom. Perhaps it is
this attention to detail that allows people like Elizabeth Dole to
be named one of the Ten Most Fascinating People by Barbara Walters.
When she calls, I will ask.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole is, of course, married to Bob Dole who ran for
some sort of political office a few years back and now spends his
time doing Viagra commercials. It would be interesting to know what
Mrs. Dole's thoughts are on this matter, and whether she's worried
that a failed presidential bid on her part might lead to her
shilling for some prescription drug.
</P>
<P>
   (To be honest, I would be much too embarrassed to discuss this
with Mrs. Dole, who reminds me a lot of my mother, assuming my
mother was a Harvard-educated lawyer and former secretary of
Transportation and Labor. Plus, I don't want to be the guy who
causes Dole to change her mind about randomly calling journalists.)
</P>
<P>
   It would probably be safer to ask Dole a question pertaining to
foreign policy, inasmuch as there is a lot of that going around
lately. To get things rolling, and to make it clear to her that I
am a serious journalist who thinks deeply about things, I might ask
her something like, ``So, what kind of name is Slobodan, anyway?''
Say what you want about the situation in Kosovo, just about
everyone I've talked to thinks Slobodan is a terrible name and may
actually be making things worse in that part of the world than they
would otherwise be. I would ask Dole, if she were elected
president, if she would favor changing Slobodan's name to something
less belligerent-sounding such as ``Timmy'' or, perhaps, ``Bruce.''
</P>
<P>
   This would probably take care of my 5 minutes, but if there were
any time left over, I could ask about Mrs. Dole's pets, assuming
she has any, and perhaps share a story or two about my pug dog,
Buster, who is unique in that he is neither a candidate for
president nor a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean he wouldn't appreciate a call.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of The New York
Times Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
