<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0204 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-FOOTE-REVIEW-HNS     06-02 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-FOOTE-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYWRIGHT FOOTE REMEMBERS CHILDHOOD IN TEXAS TOWN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  ``Farewell: A Memoir of a Texas Childhood''; By Horton Foote;
Scribner, $24. 
 
By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The predominant question of Horton Foote's childhood in Wharton,
Texas, during the early decades of this century was, ``I wonder why
the Brooks boys are like they are?''
</P>
<P>
   The Brooks boys were Foote's three uncles on his mother's side:
Billy, Brother and Speed. Promising young men, sons of one of their
town's most respected citizens, all three wound up as
ne'er-do-wells, leading dissipated lives marked by varying
configurations of womanizing, alcoholism, drugs, prison and new
career paths hopefully begun and abruptly abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasted, tragic lives, I had by 12 observed, seemed nearly
always to occur to at least one male member of the families we knew
_ but to have the only three males of a family turn out so was most
unusual,'' Foote recalls in ``Farewell,'' his bittersweet memoir.
</P>
<P>
   By expressing his lifelong desire to understand the people
prominent in his early life, by depicting a family whose favorite
pastime was telling tales of their kin and the surrounding
community, Foote's memoir reveals the roots of his inspiration as a
dramatist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Farewell'' will be best appreciated by those who have enjoyed
Foote's plays and screenplays through the years, including the
Pulitzer Prize-winning ``The Young Man From Atlanta'' and the
Oscar-winning screenplays for ``Tender Mercies'' and ``To Kill a
Mockingbird.'' One meets the real-life models for many of his
characters, particularly those in his more recent, frankly
autobiographical ``The Orphan's Home'' cycle of plays chronicling
his parents' early lives.
</P>
<P>
   Foote's free-flowing reminiscences cover events from his
childhood, overheard bits of family history, stories of friends, of
hard times, of race relations and perseverance. Always there is the
picture of the inquisitive ``Little Horton'' _ his dad was ``Big
Horton,'' gentle proprietor of a men's clothing store _ questioning
his elders about family mysteries and secrets. Those white robes
found at the bottom of a trunk? And what is the Ku Klux Klan?
</P>
<P>
   As in his dramatic writing, the strengths of Foote's memoir are
simplicity and honesty. But this is no whitewashed, Norman Rockwell
vision of small-town life from Foote's birth in 1916 until his
departure in his late teens to pursue a career as an actor, an
ambition that would soon be redirected to playwriting. Amid the
colorful characters, Saturday-night dances and folksy banter, there
is a good deal of complexity, darkness and pain. Little Horton
hears of murder, lynching, floods, the 1918 influenza epidemic,
business reversals, betrayal, adultery, alcoholism and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a loving family, it's a tough life. Foote has an
almost Chekhovian knack for quietly revealing human frailty. His
people are just a bit hapless, bewildered by life _ including his
kindly, ineffectual father. They never quite understand why things
turn out as they do, good or bad, but they never stop wondering
why.
</P>
<P>
   The recollections sometimes ramble, a tad random and
scattershot. Yet overall the book is held together by the character
of curious Little Horton, particularly as he strives to comprehend
thornier matters, such as racism. By the later chapters, as his
seemingly arbitrary desire to become an actor gathers steam, the
book gains narrative motion as he bids a poignant farewell to
various relatives and sets out by train for the larger world.
</P>
<P>
   He gives us neat, often memorable character sketches, such as
the one of Lily Dale, his maternal aunt, who lives in Houston and
struggles to be artistic, composing piano pieces. There is Mrs.
Willford, who felt ``it was her duty before she died to teach the
men in Wharton to act like gentlemen, and so whenever she met a man
up in town who didn't tip his hat and say, `How are you today, Mrs.
Willford?' she would take her walking stick and hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gentle humor arises from the dialogue's sometimes odd mixture of
naivete and down-home wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``How am I going to get to be a movie star in Wharton, Texas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, don't stay in Wharton, Texas _ go on out to Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Foote did go to Hollywood and to New York, but eventually, in
his 70s, he moved back to Wharton. Given the prominent role those
early influences and preoccupations have played throughout his
quietly illustrious career, one might say he never left.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
