<SLUG> BC-CIR-EMAIL-ESSAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREETINGS AND SOLICITATIONS: THANKS, BUT NO THANKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JULIE HALLERAN BLISS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone gets spam for ``XXX hotpics!'' and get-rich-quick
schemes. Like most people, I usually send it straight to the trash,
unopened. But I must admit, sometimes I do read it, and sometimes
I'd like to reply. Of course I haven't, yet. That might encourage
them. It would be hard to imagine, but I might get even more, even
worse junk e-mail. So, although I can never send them, just writing
these replies did make me feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Here they are, unsent replies to actual e-mail solicitations I
have received. But all names and addresses have been changed to
ones that did not exist the last time I checked. If, for some
reason, you feel tempted to reach Kristi or Big, you will not
succeed. But don't worry, you can be sure the real snakes will find
you sooner or later.
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: kristi(AT)hottie.xxx
</P>
<P>
   Kristi,
</P>
<P>
   I am a 38-year-old mother of two small children, and though it
sounds like lots of fun, I no longer wish to receive updates on you
and your wet, wild and wicked 18-year-old college girlfriends. It
makes me feel old and grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: manemeister(AT)hairhairhair.man
</P>
<P>
   Dear Manemeister:
</P>
<P>
   Thank you for your recent inquiry as to whether or not I would
be happier, more confident and more sexually attractive to women if
only I had more hair.
</P>
<P>
   As a woman myself, I have spent years trying to reduce the
amount of hair I have on my body and so, you see, more hair is just
not for me.
</P>
<P>
   Should I ever feel like being sexually attractive to women
however, and come to believe that more hair is somehow the key
ingredient, I will contact you.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: wantsex(AT)pheromones4u.now
</P>
<P>
   Dear Sirs or Madams:
</P>
<P>
   Although I am not interested in purchasing your sex-attracting
pheromones at the present, thank you for thinking of me and for
your hopes that my sex life will awaken soon. I'm sure it is just
napping.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: headmaster(AT)diplomas.uni
</P>
<P>
   Now, this seems like a great idea! Instead of going to college,
I could have just sent you $300 or $400 and gotten a real diploma
from your ``eminent, nonaccredited university.'' Wow, I could have
saved my parents $59,700 or $59,600.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, since I already have a diploma, I will not be
needing your service, even though I'm sure a B.A. from diplomas.uni
would look much more impressive on my resume than Mt. Holyoke
College.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: mrbig(AT)dreamers.$$$
</P>
<P>
   Dear Big:
</P>
<P>
   I appreciate your job offer to sell dream vacations to thousands
of Internet users from the privacy of my own home. In the privacy
of my own home, I generally do not sell dream vacations, so I feel
I am not qualified.
</P>
<P>
   Do you mind if I ask how you got my name? If it was that pesky
headhunter who keeps sending me e-mail about working in the
modeling business (no experience necessary), don't take her word
for my qualifications. She seems to think anyone can do anything.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you will find the right person to fill this job, but
for now you can take me off your short list. Despite what you have
heard, I don't think I could dream-vacation-sell without it
sounding like a scam.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: slim(AT)poundadaydiet.lbs
</P>
<P>
   Dear Slim:
</P>
<P>
   As a petite woman tipping the scales at 110, I received the
invitation to join you and thousands of others in your
revolutionary diet plan with not a little surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the thought of losing four clothes sizes in two weeks
is a bit frightening. Your comment that people will really start to
notice me when they see that my clothes are so saggy is scary too.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose those closest to me might notice that under all those
saggy togs, I was dead.
</P>
<P>
   If I really wanted more people to notice me, perhaps I could
come up with a safer way.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to: credit(AT)badcreditfixer.crd
</P>
<P>
   Thank you for approving me for the unsecured Visa card I did not
order. It is truly empowering to know that I, despite my dozens of
low-paying jobs and chronic late payments, have finally earned an
unsecured Visa.
</P>
<P>
   You say I can use up to $2,500 in credit, right away, without
mention of interest rates. That would be great. What does unsecured
mean anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   Reply to : jehoover(AT)files.fbi
</P>
<P>
   Dear J.E.:
</P>
<P>
   I read with much interest your service that provides access to
the FBI files of anyone I know. I was always curious to know
whether my spouse was ever convicted of a major drug crime.
</P>
<P>
   My neighbors _ have they ever been institutionalized or ever
behaved in such a manner that resulted in the loss of life? They
are so quiet, always keep to themselves. It makes me wonder.
</P>
<P>
   I understand you can also run down info on children. I would be
quite keen to get the lowdown on my 7-year-old's recess friends.
Who are they, what do they do for a living, are they felons, pimps,
have they ever declared bankruptcy, etc. It would comfort a mother
to know these things.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks! Thanks! And Thanks! Again!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
