<SLUG> BC-GLF-SORENSTAM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUIETLY, SORENSTAM GEARS UP FOR RUN AT U.S. WOMEN'S OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID COOPER   
 The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Coming into the 54th U.S. Women's Open,
Annika Sorenstam has yet to win during the 1999 LPGA season.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly why the other 149 golfers are picking her as a
favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam comes to Old Waverly Golf Club in an eerily similar
fashion to 1995 and 1996. In both of those seasons, the Swedish
phenom came into the biggest major of the women's season without a
win.
</P>
<P>
   Both times she walked away with her name engraved on the cup.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old Sorenstam comes to her sixth U.S. Open having
competed in nine tournaments this year and with top 10 finishes in
six of them. She has finished alone or in a tie for second three
times, including her last two tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   And now she re-enters the arena of her two greatest
performances. The Open begins Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my game is better than it was two years ago,''
Sorenstam said Tuesday. ``I am hitting longer off the tee. I think
I am more consistent in general. It is just when you come to a
championship like this, it is not just how you have been hitting
it. It is more mental than anything.''
</P>
<P>
   To watch Sorenstam, on the course and off, is a technical study
in consistency. Through her photogenic schoolgirl smile, she
handles the glare of media attention with understatement and
simplicity. When it comes to golf she embraces the notion that the
safe play usually unwinds into a winning one.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I try to live my life,'' Sorenstam said. ``I've
never been a gambler. Some tournaments it pays off and others it
doesn't. I feel if I play the way that I'm comfortable with I'll
always get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Known for her durability with longer fairways and ability to
gauge her own abilities, even Sorenstam admits the technical
variance of U.S. Open courses brings out the best in her patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's one of my strengths in the Open. I always go
for the high percentage shot. I just do the shots that I know how
to hit. If I'm in trouble I try to get out as soon as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without a win, it's been hard to find anything wrong with
Sorenstam's game in '99. She currently stands fourth on the money
list with $360,026 of earnings in nine events. Her scoring average
of 69.50 is the best of her career and second to current LPGA
leader Karrie Webb.
</P>
<P>
   She is also third in greens in regulation with a percentage of
.783 and has hit 25 of her 32 rounds under par. In the last four
years, she was been the Player of the Year winner three times.
</P>
<P>
   Another proof of Sorenstam's consistency is the fact that her
nine appearances are the fewest of anyone in the top 15 of the
money list.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam says she rarely competes more than three weeks in a
row. Last week she laid off for the LPGA Corning Classic to prepare
for the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big event ... and I want to be as ready as I can. I
don't play in as many tournaments as some of the other girls. You
want to be fresh and it helps you a lot through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the week off, Sorenstam has a bit of a stealth cover
from the national media coming into this week's play at Old Waverly
in rural northeast Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-hole playoff between defending champ Se Ri Pak and
amateur Jenny Chuasiriporn from last year at Kohler, Wisc., still
has fans and broadcasters buzzing for an encore performance.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the magnifying glass on Webb, who has won four
times this season and finished in the top 10 in all 11 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Those stories, along with the sentimental favorite Nancy Lopez,
keep spectators asking all types of questions toward the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But the answer of the 54th U.S. Women's Open could well come
from the quiet voice of consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have got to have certain criteria to do well in the Open,
that is for sure,'' Sorenstam said. ``You need patience and you
really need the desire to win this week.
</P>
<P>
   (The Tuscaloosa (Ala.) News is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
