<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH PREPARES TO TEST POLITICAL WATERS IN IOWA, NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush will make the maiden trip
of his still-unofficial presidential campaign next week, heading to
two early-primary states as the leader in the polls and flush with
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is scheduled to go to Iowa on June 12 ``to look people in
the eye, and shake their hands and let them know what's on my heart
and hear what they have to say as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-term governor is regarded as the front-runner among
the Republican presidential hopefuls in early preference polls. And
he has eclipsed other Republicans in raising money without spending
any time on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   His exploratory committee raised some $8 million in the first
quarter of the year and is expected to raise at least that much in
the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Former American Red Cross President Elizabeth Dole, former
Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and Rep. John R. Kasich of Ohio also
are scheduled to be in Iowa on June 12. There are no plans for any
joint appearances, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, whose husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, was the GOP nominee
in 1996, comes the closest to Bush in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a two-man race. It's going to come down to
Elizabeth Dole and George W. Bush. That's a good contest,'' said
Ari Fleischer, Dole's campaign spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is focused on the four main themes of her campaign,'' said
Fleischer, who added that Dole welcomes Bush to the campaign trail.
``We are looking forward to a good contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole will address voters on the four main themes of her
campaign: cutting taxes, a stronger defense, education and making
the war on drugs a national priority.
</P>
<P>
   David Beckwith, a Bush spokesman in Austin, said: ``We are
preparing to present Governor Bush's ideas to the public, and we
will let other campaigns take care of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush won $1.8 billion in tax cuts from the
just-adjourned Texas Legislature, giving him an issue as he begins
to campaign, he has been criticized for failing to come out with
specific proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show the son of the former president leading the
GOP pack in Iowa, but his numbers are far off the mark posted by
Bob Dole during the last presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1995, Sen. Dole was supported by 52 percent of likely
Republican voters in Iowa. A May poll showed Bush with just 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Bob Dole was supported by 51 percent of voters
surveyed in a June 8, 1995, poll.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, two polls last month in that state showed Bush
with 28 and 30 percent of support from likely GOP voters. Those
same New Hampshire polls showed Elizabeth Dole with 17 and 15
percent of support from GOP voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of campaign trail to travel,'' Fleischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander and Kasich are bunched at the bottom of most public
opinion polls. Other GOP candidates _ including Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, television commentator Pat Buchanan, former Vice President
Dan Quayle, and magazine publisher Steve Forbes _ have
organizations established in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Bush formed a presidential exploratory committee earlier this
year and has all but announced his intent to seek the party's
nomination. The formal declaration is expected in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   He begins a month of campaigning next Wednesday, with a four-day
trip to the early primary states of Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to get out and start moving around some and make
sure the sentiment that I'm told is out there is out there,'' Bush
told reporters in Austin earlier this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
