<HEADER>
A0223 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-CITY-GUIDES-2TAKE     06-02 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CITY-GUIDES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME POINT-AND-CLICK GUIDES TO URBAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By TOM VANDERBILT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Leading the Blind,'' his study of nineteenth century
European guidebook travel, the writer Alan Sillitoe traces the
emergence of guidebooks like Baedeker's and Murray's to the
increasing popularity of travel among those outside of the strictly
leisured classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tourists,'' these newly itinerant classes would be derisively
called, were the first hardy souls the guidebooks, which Sillitoe
called ``educated dogs which led the blind.'' But they were
essential to understanding the character and mores of foreign
places for those travelers unprepared by their upbringing.
</P>
<P>
   The hazards were many. In France, Murray's guide warned, the
civilized traveler ought to eschew dining at the common table at
inns, for the company was less than desirable: ``Without denying
that there are exceptions among these gentry, it is impossible to
have sojourned in France for any time without the conviction that a
more selfish, depraved, and vulgar, if not brutal, set does not
exist, nd gentlemen will take good care not to encourage their
approaches, and to keep a distance from them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Switzerland, one guide counseled, buying a memento is a
challenge as imposing as the Matterhorn: ``There is hardly a
country in Europe which has so complicated a currency as
Switzerland; almost every canton has a coinage of its own, and
those coins that are current in one canton will not pass in the
next.'' In Italy, train travel made for a less arduous journey, but
one still had to be wary of brigands and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to this litany of risk, the concerns of today's
guidebooks seem petty. Tourism is now the world's number-one
industry and much of travel seems like an assembly-line process:
automated car rental, last-minute E-fares, global ATM card access.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of brigands, the most intimidating obstacle can be
something like getting frequent flier credit for that last leg of
the trip to Caracas on Avianca. Still, the increased frequency of
travel and the increased travel population make information all the
more important.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers on the Grand Tour of the Continent might have had time
to take in events as they discovered them, but today's weekend
continent-hoppers need up-to-the-minute information. With new
restaurants opening (and closing weekly), what hope does even an
annually updated guidebook have of charting New York?
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising then that city guides emerged as an early,
much-touted presence on the Internet. With a seemingly infinite
amount of space for listings, an ability to perform searches
targeted under any number of criteria, and, increasingly, the
option of purchasing tickets for events using the same site, the
Internet city guides seem to offer a guidebook, the Yellow Pages,
the daily newspaper, and even the rancor of public discourse all
rolled into one, a tribune for our time.
</P>
<P>
   There are limitations, however. For one, tracking all that
information still requires people to input it, and many online city
guides are less current than they suggest. Another limitation is
the guides' scope: not every guide covers every city. Citysearch,
for example, has a Danish version and is planning a Phoenix edition
but lacks Chicago in between. Even here, however, the Internet has
spawned myriad quirky, if low-budget, ocally produced guides.
</P>
<P>
   Yet whatever their weaknesses, they have become a sort of daily
guidebook to an increasingly complicated life. To test these
guides, I attempted to navigate each site in the hope of finding
one of the 53 Alfred Hitchcock films being shown this month at the
Museum of Modern Art and, for later in the day, a local video store
for something more current.
</P>
<P>
   In my estimation, the best way of experiencing a city is merely
wading into the human flow and letting the city's own rhythms and
contours carry one along, with stimulation of the senses the only
destination. But for those who favor the cultural equivalent of
global positioning systems, these latter-day educated dogs have
learned a few new tricks. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CITYSEARCH.COM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spanning a network of cities from Las Vegas to Copenhagen,
Citysearch, now owned by Ticketmaster, offers a wide range of
listings and original content. For visitors to the New York City
area, these include the gossip-magazine-style ``Insider's Guide to
the Hamptons,'' a thorough description of Hoboken and passable
music reviews.
</P>
<P>
   One of Citysearch's most useful features is personalization,
which allows one to, among other things, receive an e-mail alert
when a favorite performer is due in town (provided Citysearch knows
about it).
</P>
<P>
   Unique to Citysearch is its ``Virtual Tours'' function, which
presents a ``slide show,'' accompanied by text, of various city
attractions. The prose, as one might expect, is roughly on par with
a Circle Line spiel. Of the Brooklyn Bridge, the tour notes: ``A
symbol of American urbanization and industrialization, the Brooklyn
Bridge is an immediately recognizable milestone in New York City
history and culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding my Hitchcock film was a snap on Citysearch. I merely
clicked ``Movies,'' then a second heading titled ``Film
Festivals.'' I scrolled down a list to the ``Alfred Hitchcock''
listing, and was presented with a complete list of times and dates
for the 53 films the Museum of Modern Art is showing. Finding out
the time for ``The Trouble with Harry'' turned out to be no trouble
at all.
</P>
<P>
   When I queried Citysearch on video stores in my zip code,
however, I was informed that there were no video stores within a
quarter of a mile. Strange, I thought, given that there are at
least three within a few blocks of my home; perhaps not the highest
caliber, but with a copy of ``Vertigo'' nonetheless. I would have
been willing to walk more than a quarter mile, but apparently this
is the limit for an urban trek, and I saw no immediate way to
change the parameter. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SIDEWALK.COM  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This much-touted Microsoft site has a similar reach to the other
guides, but its online content, despite being localized, seems
almost entirely oriented towards consumer information. This is not
surprising, since the link to E-commerce is seen as the ultimate
way to make city guides financially viable online.
</P>
<P>
   No virtual tours here, simply features on ``shower heads that
know how to handle pressure'' and tips on buying a new lawn mower.
</P>
<P>
   One link that caught my eye _ shopping for ``mod furniture'' in
Brooklyn, turned out not to exist the first day I tried it (it did
the following day, but who wants to keep visiting?).
</P>
<P>
   Navigationally, Sidewalk is a bit confusing, often sending the
user to a national online retailer when a local one is desired,
which is odd since Sidewalk's main virtue is presenting shopping
and entertainment options in one's own neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Looking under ``book shops,'' I was made aware that within
blocks of my home I had at my disposal The Center for Thanatology
and the God Build Christian Book Store. Although Sidewalk tells you
the distance each store is located from your address, this
information is otherwise simply a Yellow Pages listing.
</P>
<P>
   My search for Hitchcock proved a bit more vexing on Sidewalk.
Entering ``Hitchcock'' under the entry for ``Find a Movie,'' I was
given a listing for ``Dial M for Murder'' (in 3-D), but none of the
Museum of Modern Art showings. Similarly, looking under
``Revivals,'' I was shown ``The Trouble With Harry,'' but none of
the other Hitchcock films. By the time my computer crashed, I was
already longing for a simple newspaper page.
</P>
<P>
   As for videos, there was no clearly apparent heading, so I
clicked ``Block by Block,'' hoping to get a rundown on my
neighborhood. After reading through a list of ``Cool
Neighborhoods,'' I selected Court St. between Union St. and First
Place, but this listing, which included the All Pets Go to Heaven
Funeral home and Helen's Restaurant, featured no video stores. My
usual video store, located on the corner of Henry and Sackett,
apparently suffers from an uncool address. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DIGITALCITIES.COM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America Online's foray into the city guide field has been fast
and furious, and it now boasts the most hits of any such site. The
New York version is something akin to the opening screen of America
Online itself, with news headlines, weather, and ticket offers.
</P>
<P>
   The local content is a bit sparse, with none of the newsy
features of Citysearch or Sidewalk, and a click on the ``book
shopping'' link brings up the Barnes and Noble site (no charmingly
bumbling used bookstore clerks here).
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a New Jersey ``bar cam'' that allows one to
view the action at Martell's in Point Pleasant; the picture is of
people sitting at plastic tables. I am not sure who would want to
watch this, or whether Martell's patrons knew they were being
filmed, but I had no intention of seeing how long the guy in the
plaid shirt would be on that bar stool.
</P>
<P>
   This site seems designed less for its own sake than for
packaging material available elsewhere on line. Looking for my
Hitchcock, I enter the director's name in a search field on the
movie page, which yields nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking video in the hopes of finding a video store, I was
given a Yellow Pages alphabetical listing of every video store in
the city. A subsequent search allowed me to ask for those stores
located only within a half mile of my house, but here I kept
getting the message, ``We've run into an error _ ours, not yours.''
Instead of Hitchcock, I decided to watch zoom-camera images of the
Jersey Shore, ``Rear Window'' style, and hoped that I didn't
witness a murder. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NYTODAY.COM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, many newspapers large and small have gotten
into the business of online city guides. So it is with New York
Today, owned by The New York Times. Readers of the newspaper will
find pretty thin gruel here _, articles simply reprinted from the
pages of the Times (albeit of a higher quality than most online
content) _ although nytoday does feature the listings,
personalization, and mapping services offered on other city sites.
</P>
<P>
   To search for Hitchcock, I called up the ``movies'' entry, which
allowed searches by type of film, location, and date. Luckily, I
guessed Hitchcock would be under Suspense/Thriller, and I was given
the time of ``The Birds.'' To find a video store, I clicked the
``Near My Home'' entry, and was then given a fairly intimidating
borough-wide video store listing, with no discernible way to narrow
the search. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CLUI.ORG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While not a city guide like the others, the ``land use
database'' maintained by the Center for Land Use Interpretation
offers a wonderful assortment of ``unusual and exemplary land use
sites'' in just about any locale in the country, revealing a layer
of the city far removed from the usual bistro openings.
</P>
<P>
   With its official-looking globe symbol and sober motto
(``Dedicated to the increase and diffusion of information about how
the world's lands are apportioned, utilized and perceived''), the
Center offers deadpan assessments of a variety of sites, which can
be searched by location or by categories such as ``waste sites''
and ``nuclear/radioactive sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Typing ``New York City,'' one is given a list of a dozen or so
sites, each containing a brief description and the simplest of
directions; highlights include the ``Meadowlands Trash Museum,''
which features a landfill cross-section (a ``veritable wall of
trash viewed through a glass wall'').
</P>
<P>
   At points, this site seems like a parody, but that might be
expected from a group that once put a sound-emitting device in a
remote desert area _ the noise was dripping water _ to see if
anyone would hear. On second thought, that does not seem much more
preposterous than training a webcam on a beachfront bar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
