<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-JAZZ03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jazzing up Bob Marley? Alexander makes it work
 &HT;    By Richard L. Eldredge
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The idea of blending a mostly straight-ahead jazz approach to
the work of reggae giant Bob Marley may seem ghastly. But pianist
Monty Alexander and his crack, handpicked Jamaican rhythm section
more than deliver. The anchor of the effort is Alexander, whose
fluid, melodic playing respectfully explores the music of his
Jamaican boyhood. What could have been a jarring train wreck of
musical ideas becomes an uninterrupted flow of reggae and jazz
themes. Both musical forms embrace improvisation, and drummer
Rolando Wilson, bassist Trevor McKenzie and guitarist Robert Angus
take full advantage of the freedoms. With a rhythm section this
formidable instead of a more conventional trio setting, Alexander
has to be on his toes. His solos are inspired; Alexander even finds
a way to drop a reference to the Beatles' ``Eleanor Rigby'' into
``Jammin.' '' It all works, even the energetic take on ``I Shot the
Sheriff,'' which sports both a trombone and conch-shell solo.
</P>
<P>
   JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``Stir it Up: The Music of Bob Marley''
</P>
<P>
   Monty Alexander. Telarc Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard L. Eldredge writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
