</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINI03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mainstream hasn't stopped Jamiroquia, a band on the move
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  R&AMP;B
</P>
<P>
   ``Synkronized''
</P>
<P>
   Jamiroquai. Work. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Just because the mainstream finally discovered one of London's
most soulful exports doesn't mean Jamiroquai has decided to simply
float along in it. This is a band on the move. Lead singer Jay
Kay's got ``Canned Heat'' in his heels on the first single, and the
strings and rhythm guitar can't help but spark any other sole
within earshot. Don't listen too closely, though, as Jamiroquai
often relies on the lyrical sensibility of a disco tune. Which
means almost every song is a different way of saying dancing will
make you feel better. An affable point punctuated with the salsa
break midway into ``Planet Home,'' the insistent bass on ``Soul
Education'' and the exclamation mark of this act's fourth album _
the taut, multirhythmic single with which it should have closed the
album, ``Where Do We Go From Here?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
