<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0227 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-POP03-COX     06-02 0273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-POP03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Loco for Lopez: Sweet sounds match good looks
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Come on, admit it. Before you even listen to Jennifer Lopez's
first album, you want to hate it. You want the screen star of
``Selena'' and last year's smoldering ``Out of Sight'' to do a Don
Johnson and fall flat on that sculptured face. After all, skeptics
say, it would only be fair. Someone with such good looks and
considerable acting talent couldn't possibly have vocal skills as
well. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, this debut is hardly a disappointment _ and not because
Lopez is a particularly remarkable singer. But with such skillful
pop success miners as Emilio Estefan (Gloria's husband), Rodney
Jerkins (Brandy's hit maker) and Sean ``Puffy'' Combs (Lopez's
rumored-to-be other half) involved, her serviceable abilities are
buffed to a remarkably likable glow.
</P>
<P>
   And as she should, the supermodel on seemingly every magazine
serves her varying backdrops well: sounding vulnerable against the
breezy flamenco guitars on ``Should've Never,'' then certain of
herself on the album's first single, ``If You Had My Love'' and
like she could start a party on the horn-powered ``Let's Get Loud''
and Combs' bouncy contribution, ``Feelin' So Good.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bloat on this streamlined package is the unnecessary
reworking of ``No Me Ames'' and the numbing plea, ``Promise Me
You'll Try.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the 6''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lopez. Work. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
