<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0228 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-ALIENS03-COX     06-02 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ALIENS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The ``Alien'' series re-released, digitally mastered and
THX-certified
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years after we learned an acoustical fact about screaming
in space, Fox is re-releasing the four ``Alien'' movies (packaged
as ``Alien Legacy''), digitally mastered and THX-certified,
available in three forms: VHS widescreen ($19.98 each), VHS
pan-and-scan ($14.98 each) and DVD ($29.98 each).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Aliens'' (R; 1986) _ Writer-director James Cameron is best
known as the daddy of the Terminator and the guy who re-sank the
Titanic. But his entry in the ``Alien'' franchise not only tops
Ridley Scott's original flick, it's one of the coolest (and
creepiest) action movies of the '80s. It stands up to repeat
viewing, especially now that it's available in crisp DVD.
</P>
<P>
   This director's cut, previously available on collector's-edition
VHS, reinstates 17 minutes of footage trimmed from the theatrical
release. This includes Ripley (Sigourney Weaver) receiving news
that her 10-year-old daughter has grown up and died during her
mom's 57-year hypersleep. It underscores the surrogate-mom bond
between Ripley and orphan Newt (Carrie Henn). We also see that
Newt's parents were responsible for accidentally introducing the
aliens into their settlement. And there's a nice, tense sequence
involving an alien assault and four motion-sensing machine guns.
</P>
<P>
   The extra footage extends Cameron's nail-biting buildup, as
Ripley and a squadron of Marines (including Michael Biehn and Bill
Paxton) journey to the planet of the crashed alien ship _ now
colonized by humans, who have mysteriously stopped contacting
Earth. It's a solid hour before any of the big action sequences
begin. Cameron saves his real ammo for the last 40 minutes,
culminating in the exhilarating fight-to-the-death between Ripley
and the alien queen. Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Alien'' (R; 1979) _ Ridley Scott's Space Age haunted-house
movie still holds up fine (except for those cheesy twinkling lights
meant to represent a computer). The film's balance between
excruciating suspense and bursts of violence remains startling.
Twenty years ago, when that nasty li'l alien popped out of John
Hurt's stomach, it was one of the most gruesome sights ever seen
onscreen. Things have changed, huh? Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Alien Resurrection'' (R; 1997) _ Like Ripley herself, this
latest film from Jean-Pierre Jeunet (``Delicatessen'') is an odd
hybrid. Half action film, half existential meditation, it casts
Weaver as a clone, part Ripley, part alien. While some of the
action scenes rock, the ``newborn'' monster and the finale are more
whimper than bang.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Alien 3'' (R; 1992) _ The third installment betrays the
faith of fans of ``Aliens,'' killing off two major characters in
the opening credits. But that's not all: Director David Fincher's
feature debut, stranding Ripley and one of those darned aliens in
an all-male penal colony, is loud and claustrophobic, with action
scenes so hectically staged you rarely know what the heck is going
on. Let's not even talk about the ending. Grade: D+
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
