<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-DIVINE03-COX     06-02 0201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-DIVINE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An odd Irish wake worth attending
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Waking Ned Devine'' (PG)
</P>
<P>
   Your twee alarm may go off at the very idea of this comedy: It's
the tale of a small Irish village where Ned, the new winner of a $7
million lottery ticket, has died of shock.
</P>
<P>
   The death inspires one old rogue named Jackie (Ian Bannen) to
try to convince all the townsfolk to pretend his pal Michael (David
Kelly) is actually Ned. The idea? If they can fool the lottery
officials, everyone in town gets to share the wealth.
</P>
<P>
   First-time writer-director Kirk Jones isn't in the same league
as Bill Forsyth, whose Scottish idyll ``Local Hero'' remains a
lyrical touchstone of 1980s filmmaking. But Jones elicits charming
performances from a mainly older cast that manages to steer clear
of cliched Irish blarney. Or at least most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Distributor Fox Searchlight Pictures obviously hoped ``Ned''
would be its ``Full Monty'' of '98. No such luck, but it's worth a
look on your VCR. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
