<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-LONGINO03-COX     06-02 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-LONGINO03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's all that: Teen-life flicks with real substance
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only one thing can come of Hollywood's recent teen movie glut: a
teen video glut.
</P>
<P>
   Several less-than-stellar depictions of American teen life are
headed for the video stores in coming weeks, including ``Varsity
Blues'' (June 29), the teachers-as-aliens ``The Faculty'' (June
15), the sinister ``Jawbreaker'' (June 22) and the ain't-all-that
``She's All That'' (July 13).
</P>
<P>
   The kids will be out of school soon, and if you don't want
multiple hours of their summer spent with ``Blues' '' James Van Der
Beek and his tin-eared Southern accent, you'll have to do
something.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a dozen, mostly older, videos depicting various aspects
of teen life. They may not all be great movies, but the truths they
more artfully present make for time better spent.
</P>
<P>
   You might even find yourself watching one of these with your kid
_ and maybe later even having a conversation about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Graffiti'' (PG; 1973) _ Before George Lucas lost
his mind with ``Star Wars,'' he made this funny, endearing homage
to 1962 cruising in California. Good performances, especially from
Charles Martin Smith and Candy Clark. At the time, many critics
didn't like this movie, either. They were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Breaking Away'' (PG; 1979) _ Dennis Christopher leads a band
of going-nowhere young men in a test of mettle in a college-town
bicycle race. Oscar for screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Crucible'' (PG-13; 1996) _ Yes, Daniel Day-Lewis gets a
little involved with young hellion Winona Ryder. But the glee with
which the 17th-century Salem, Mass., townsfolk absorb Ryder and her
girl gang's hysterical cries about devil worship reveals a lot
about how humanity never really changes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dead Poets Society'' (PG; 1989) _ The Australian director
Peter Weir's heartfelt drama of a free-spirited English teacher
(Robin Williams) using poetry to inspire kids in a taut prep
school. Your kid will spot Ethan Hawke in the talented cast. Oscar
for screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Fiddler on the Roof'' (G; 1971) _ One of the finest movie
musicals, it's a poignant look at Jewish life and racism that
includes a father's struggle to accept change brought about in part
by his daughters' emerging individualism. Oscars for
cinematography, sound and scoring adaptation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The 400 Blows'' (unrated; 1959) _ OK, so the kid in this
movie is 12. So what. Francois Truffaut's remarkable French film
(with English subtitles) about a child with nowhere to turn is one
of the must-see movies of all time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Great Santini'' (PG; 1980) _ Long before he married
Bonnie Raitt, Michael O'Keefe got an Oscar nomination for
portraying the eldest son of a big-as-life _ and abusive _ military
man (Robert Duvall). Often forgotten among all the fine
performances is Stan Shaw's delicate but effective work as
O'Keefe's African-American buddy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Last Picture Show'' (R; 1971) _ Growing up in Texas
isn't easy, either. Timothy Bottoms, Jeff Bridges and Cybill
Shepherd were young once. And here they're at their best in Peter
Bogdanovich's adult-themed masterpiece. Oscars for supporting actor
(Ben Johnson) and supporting actress (Cloris Leachman).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Native Son'' (R; 1986) _ Not entirely well-made, but it's
well worth watching this adaptation of Richard Wright's brilliant
novel of a 19-year-old black youth's experience of living in
America.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ordinary People'' (R; 1980) _ Before there was a Matt Damon,
a Ben Affleck and a ``Good Will Hunting,'' there was a Timothy
Hutton and this moving story of a high school kid and his therapist
coping with his family's tailspin following a death. Oscars for
best picture, director (Robert Redford), screenplay and supporting
actor (Hutton).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rebel Without a Cause'' (unrated; 1955) _ The real deal.
With James Dean, Natalie Wood and Sal Mineo.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Romeo and Juliet'' (PG; 1968) _ Who needs Leonardo DiCaprio
and Claire Danes? Leonard Whiting, 17, and Olivia Hussey, 15,
explode with youthful passion in Franco Zeffirelli's provocative _
and, unfortunately, mod-era dated _ adaptation of Shakespeare's
tragedy. Oscars for cinematography, costume design.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
