<P>
   AMERICAN AIRLINES CRASH
</P>
<P>
   CRASH _ LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ An American Airlines flight with 145
people aboard skidded off a rain-slickened runway during a storm,
broke apart and burst into flames. A source familiar with the
investigation said nine people were known to have been killed. At
least 80 people were injured and taken to hospitals. The deaths
were the first on a major U.S. airline in nearly 1 1/2 years.
Flight 1420, a Super MD-80, crashed just before midnight Tuesday.
It had 139 passengers and six crew members and was due to arrive at
9:41 p.m. The flight from Dallas was delayed for more than two
hours and arrived just as the storm was hitting Little Rock with
lightning, hail and winds gusting to nearly 90 mph.
(Manuel/Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is expected to
announce today the addition of 7,000 U.S. troops as peacekeepers
for Kosovo. (Deans, Cox News Service) Developing.
</P>
<P>
   w/KOSOVO-TEAM _ WASHINGTON _ Like most effective managers,
President Clinton tends to think of problems in one of three ways:
those that can be ignored, those that can be solved and those that
must be managed. Guess which box Kosovo fits into. Here, after all,
is a foreign policy crisis with at least four key dimensions _
military, humanitarian, diplomatic and political _ each of which is
affected daily, sometimes hourly, by developments in the other.
Clinton relies on a flexible, multi-tiered team with diplomats,
generals and lawyers at its core to manage U.S. policy, objectives
and long-term strategy in Kosovo. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-FORTDIX _ FORT DIX, N.J. _ Overseeing the arrival of
Kosovar refugees at Ft. Dix in New Jersey is a military mission
that requires more of a soft heart than a steady trigger finger.
Gen. Mitchell Zais, dispatched from Atlanta's Fort MacPherson on
May 1 to oversee Operation Provide Refuge, has a lot of heart for a
Vietnam veteran and the son of a four-star general. He has cried
many times looking into the faces of the families arriving here,
getting processed and then leaving to settle into apartments and
jobs across the country. With a PhD in psychology, a distaste for
mornings and cryptic military acronyms, General Zais is not very,
well, General-like. We spend a day following him as he goes about
his business tending to the needs of 3,700 refugees housed at Ft
Dix. (Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-GIFTS _ ATLANTA _ Billy Payne's private Olympic foundation
revealed for the first time today giving dozens of International
Olympic Committee members expensive gifts and donating $25,000 to a
South African anti-apartheid organization. In a report to the U.S.
House Commerce Committee, the foundation provided a list of some
three dozen gifts that exceeded the IOC's $200 limit, including a
$948 carburetor kit for Bashir Mohamed Attarabulsi from Libya and
the now famous live bulldog for the deceased Cuban member Manuel
Gonzalez Guerra. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   w/OLY-GIFTS-SAFRICA _ ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Olympic group says
its donation to a South African group involved in the
anti-apartheid movement was seed money to help bring the Games
there someday. But does the group's role make it a contribution to
a political organization? (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-GIFTS-Q&AMP;A _ ATLANTA _ Q&AMP;A with Billy Payne and Andrew Young
on the report. (Turner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GUNS _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will press for
stricter gun controls than those contained in a bill approved by
the Senate, his domestic policy adviser, Bruce Reed, said Wednesday
at a breakfast with reporters. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-WORKERS _ WASHINGTON _ Congress and the president have
joined in painting an illusion of a government that looks smaller
and more efficient, but which actually has a hidden number of
contract workers, says Brookings Institution scholar Paul Light.
His critical review finds that ``downsizing'' of the workforce has
been haphazard and could be disastrous. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON _ Medicare should devote more resources to
end-of-life care, a Medicare advisory board has recommended in a
report to Congress. (Lipman, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   SPELLING-BEE _ WASHINGTON _ How Cox-area spellers did on the
first day of the National Spelling Bee. (Hill, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM-ADVANCE _ He's been saving souls and setting spiritual
benchmarks for most of the century. At 81, the Rev. Billy Graham
may be making his last U.S. crusade. As Graham and his cast of
preachers, baptizers, singers and musicians comes to the RCA Dome
in Indianapolis, we take a look at the Graham legacy. (Jesse,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   BORDER-PATROL _ CHARLESTON, S.C. _ Last summer, the U.S. Border
Patrol Academy here was buzzing with activity as 700 chanting,
sweating, studying men and women honed their skills and prepared to
deploy to Texas and other Southwestern border states. Now the
academy, located on a former naval base, is quiet. The head count
has dropped to less than 150, all but two of the last eight
incoming classes have been canceled, and the remaining classes have
been pared down _ all because of a sudden shortage of recruits that
has put a crimp in the Border Patrol's expansion plans and brought
the wrath of Congress on the agency's tiny recruiting staff.
(Harmon, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE _ OKEECHOBEE, Fla. _ Preview to the start of the $600
million Kissimmee River restoration, which starts June 5. This is
the first major piece of Everglades restoration started by
then-Gov. Bob Graham in the 1980s. (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DUMPING-SENTENCES _ BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ Former employees and
officials of a now-closed Brunswick chemical plant are being
sentenced Tuesday, June 1, in federal court in Brunswick. They were
found guilty of deliberately polluting coastal marshes and
waterways around the LCP plant with dangerous chemicals. The
sentences are expected to be some of the stiffest ever handed down
for such violations. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOMBTHREAT-SURVEY _ DECATUR, Ga. _ Bomb threats have been a
hassle and a headache to schools this spring, so Decatur City
Schools Superintendent Ida Love has taken an approach that no other
district has taken: She has allowed parents to decide whether they
want their children to be evacuated. After seven bomb threats at
Decatur High in the past month, Love became frustrated at the
weekly evacuations. Because they all turned out to be pranks, she
decided to let parents decide whether they want their kids to miss
class if another bomb threat comes in. (Loupe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
