<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAPPY-THEATER-REVIEW-     06-02 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAPPY-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTING ONES BLESSINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Happiness, as we all know but usually forget, is a
state of mind. Take, for example, Winnie, Beckett's indomitable
spirit whose hymn to the minutiae of daily life forms the basis of
``Happy Days,'' his last full-length play. ``Not a day goes by that
there's not a blessing,'' Winnie muses, rummaging happily through
her handbag, then adds as anafterthought, ``in disguise.''
</P>
<P>
   Half buried in a mound of earth in a bleak landscape with only a
dubious parasol for protection, she observes, ``What a blessing
nothing grows.'' Sorrow, of course, keeps breaking in. And there is
all that time to fill between blessings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is one to do?'' she asks. ``All day long? Day after
day?'' After the morning prayers and ablutions, after the
toothbrush has been read, what is there to occupy oneself before
the earth completely swallows her up? There are always the handbag
and the music box and the gun and the hope that this will be the
day Willie will sing for her. That would be a really happy day.
</P>
<P>
   Beckett's existential Everywoman is one of his most brilliant
and evocative creations, and has always been a strong lure for
actresses. Angela Vitale, a former stalwart for the Jean Cocteau
Repertory, has returned to undertake the part, and she gives an
intelligent if sometimes uneven reading of Winnie.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vitale, who always brought a certain elegance and refinement
to her roles for the Cocteau, presents a Winnie who is almost
delicate and ladylike, with little of the earthiness one normally
associates with the character. A larger problem is the slow, almost
static pacing that Jonathan R. Polgar, the director, sets from the
opening. Ms. Vitale lingers over each line and each action _ for
example, in taking off her glasses, setting them down, putting them
back on, all with considered deliberation _ so that the performance
becomes self-conscious and mannered.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Ms. Vitale moves more comfortably into the character, and
some sections are more effective than others. But the tentativeness
in other passages also undermines much of the considerable humor in
the play. It almost seems as though Ms. Vitale is still working on
defining her character; in some scenes she has found it, but in
others she's still searching.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan Hazard delivers an admirable turn as Willie, whose grunts
and groans and mustache twirls provide most of this production's
laughs. Mary Myers' stark set looks like Arizona in August and
creates an appropriate sense of desolation.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPY DAYS'  &QL; 
By Samuel Beckett; directed by Jonathan R. Polgar; sets and
costumes by Mary Myers; lighting by Brian Aldous; production
manager, Evan Schlossberg; stage manager, Samone Weissman;
assistant director, Christopher D. Voss; technical director,
Heather Haley; sound engineer, Jason Crowl; production assistant,
Daylen Dalrymple. Presented by the Jean Cocteau Repertory, Scott
Shattuck, producing artistic director; Robert Hupp, artistic
director. At the Bouwerie Lane Theater.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
With: Angela Vitale (Winnie) and Duncan Hazard (Willie).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
