r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEER-NUT-TEX     06-02 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEER-NUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DUVEL MADE ME DO IT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN MELTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good Catholic boy that I am, I'd never advise anyone to consort
with the devil. On occasion, I've suggested that a few individuals
could pay him a visit _ that guy in the white Trans Am who cut me
off this morning comes to mind _ but I'd never recommend going over
to the dark side. Until now. And don't blame me for this sudden
conversion: It's all the Belgians' fault.
</P>
<P>
   You see, from this tiny, picture-pretty postcard of a country
comes a stunning variety of hearty brews that rival the wines of
the Belgians' French neighbors in complexity and style. Indeed,
many of Belgium's more substantial offerings come in sturdy
winelike bottles, capped with a cork and a wire cage.
</P>
<P>
   Duvel, Flemish for ``devil,'' is one such masterful brew. It
defies easy categorization: A top-fermented ale, it's pale like a
lager, probably thanks to the imported pale barley grown just north
of France's Champagne region. But the huge bouquet and enormous
head immediately put to rest any sense that this will be a treacly
batch of suds. The spicy Bohemian hops create a generous but
surprisingly subtle palate, whereas the long, yeasty finish gives a
final note of clarity with no cloying sweet aftertaste.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgium, Duvel is often served as an aperitif, but don't let
that limit your enjoyment of this fine beverage: I've found that it
works equally well as an accompaniment to spicy meats and heavy
cheeses.
</P>
<P>
   Brewed since 1871 at Moortgat Brewery near Malines, Duvel is
unfiltered and unpasteurized, with a fine layer of yeast at the
bottom, but otherwise surprisingly clear. Try to pour gently, so
that the goo remains undisturbed. (If you see ``Duvel'' lettered in
green on the label, you've come across the inferior pasteurized
version _ always ask for Duvel in red).
</P>
<P>
   ``But Beer Nut,'' you cry, ``whither the name, Duvel?''
Supposedly, one of the brewers tasted the as-yet unnamed brew and
remarked, ``This is a devil of a beer.'' Sounds apocryphal: The
name probably has more to do with the devilishly difficult brewing
process _ two to three months of fermentation and maturation at
both ale (warm) and lager (cold) temps, then a final dose of yeast
in each bottle.
</P>
<P>
   So if you'll excuse me, I'm off to confession now. ``Bless me,
Father, for I have sinned. I cavorted with the devil three times in
the past week.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
