<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME-TESTED AND CREATIVE WAYS TO SHOW KIDS HOW MUCH YOU LOVE THEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to parenting, advice on how to raise emotionally
secure children is as varied as the vast number of expert opinions
and self-help books.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of personality type, there is one piece of advice
that fits all children: unconditional love.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things every child needs is to feel loved,'' said
Will Glennon, author of ``200 Ways to Raise a Girl's Self-Esteem.''
``Often we think as parents that by providing for them, we're
showing our love, but we're just doing the job of parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   Glennon, who has two children, said a parent's ultimate job is
to discover what makes each child unique, be fascinated by it and
love it.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each kid it's going to be different,'' he said. ``Some
kids need the words. Some kids need hugs, to be touched a lot.
Other kids need you to do something that demonstrates they are
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Parsley, a former teacher and author of ``The Choice Is
Yours: A Teenager's Guide to Self-Discovery, Relationships, Values,
and Spiritual Growth,'' said parents need to emphasize the value of
uniqueness in their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of it starts with teaching the child how to build
self-respect, to value himself and look at himself as a unique
being; to not compare himself to others, but recognize his own
unique good qualities,'' Parsley said.
</P>
<P>
   Those basic principles lead to accepting self-responsibility,
because part of valuing yourself is being responsible for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you feel bad, don't blame it on someone else, but do
something constructive about it,'' she said. ``We have no choice
about what happens to us, but we do have a choice about how we
react to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Small gestures of caring also can make a big difference, Parsley
and Glennon agree. And not just for our own children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you love your children, you can't help but love other
children,'' said Glennon. ``One of the mistakes people make is they
build their world on a model of scarcity, where they think there
are not enough things to go around so they horde. But the more love
you give, the more compassion you show, the more kindness you have,
the more there is in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   When we asked Tarrant County residents how they make their
children feel loved, we were met with some age-old methods and some
creative new ideas. Here's a sampling of what they said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Randle, executive director of HOPE Farm, a nonprofit
ministry to inner-city boys ages 4 to 18: ``Children spell love
this way: TIME. It's hard to tell someone you love them if you
don't spend time with them. Another thing you can do to develop a
child is to speak and model the truth. When you are faced with
situations where not telling the truth is an option, always tell
the truth. Be a promise-keeper. That develops trust in children.
The last and most important thing is to give the children a
biblical foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bob Roberts, pastor of NorthWood Church, Keller: ``I do
not put ceilings on my children. If they have an idea that they can
do something, I try to affirm them and challenge them to explore
it. Expose them to different places and ideas and play with them;
let them know I'd rather be with them than anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Burks, father of two boys, ages 13 and 14, and field
service supervisor for the Tarrant County Juvenile Probation
Department: ``Involve them in athletics or the fine arts. Listen to
them. Acknowledge the things they do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Emerson, assistant dean for continuing education and work
force development at Tarrant County College: ``Teach children their
history and plan vacations around those things so that they can
associate places with things they've read about. Talk to them about
discrimination; it should never be a surprise. Introduce them to
individuals of color who are accomplished and have made
contributions to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Earla Golden, principal of Oakmont Elementary School: ``Greet
children with a smile. Show interest in what they are doing. Treat
every child with value and respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Minnies, director of marketing for the Festival
Marketplace mall in Arlington and mother of two children: ``Eat
together or go to a movie. Get to know their friends. Ask them what
was fun about their day.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Camarillo, father of one son, small-business owner in
Arlington, chairman of technology for the Arlington Hispanic
Chamber of Commerce: ``Give them access to the Internet in a
controlled environment. Take them to work and show them how it
really is. Involve them in church activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Gordon, Fort Worth mother, grandmother and administrative
secretary, University of Texas at Arlington: ``Tell them you
appreciate them when they help. Give a lot of hugs and kisses. Tell
them `I love you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nina Tan, Arlington business owner and mother of four children;
executive producer of Kids on Stage for a Better World, a group of
children who promote moral values in a nonreligious manner:
``Compliment them on their accomplishments. Give them extra time to
play on the computer after they finish their chores. Allow them to
solve their own problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Sampson, father of three and owner of an Allstate
Insurance franchise in Arlington, vice president of
operations/administrations for the Greater Dallas Chapter of 100
Black Men, a national mentoring organization: ``Entrust your
vehicle with a teen-ager. Give them an opportunity to help someone
else. Ask them about their day.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lisa Elliott, a psychologist at Cook Children's Medical
Center specialty clinic in Denton: ``Put love notes in their lunch
boxes every day. Schedule 10 to 20 minutes of one-on-one individual
time with them. Provide a special treat after school. Sing their
special song at bedtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hochberger, Fort Worth pediatrician: ``Concentrate on
their strengths and not their weaknesses and tell them how good
they are, how strong they are. Emphasize attitude over aptitude;
character principles like integrity, concern for others, honesty
and courage, curiosity and leadership. Foster leaders and not
followers by using these principles.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Sims, Grapevine, mother of two teen-agers and president
of the Arts Council of NorthEast Tarrant County: ``Attend their
competitions. Listen without forming preconceived ideas. Cook a
favorite meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Rice, coordinator of student support service at
Grapevine-Colleyville school district: ``Acknowledge their presence
with a pat or hug. Allow them to provide a service to an elderly
person. Talk to them about inappropriate choices and offer an
alternative. Follow through with consequences when rules are
broken.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
