<SLUG> BC-STORMPROOF-HOUSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT EVEN THE BIG BAD WOLF COULD BLOW THIS HOUSE DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It started, as so many school projects do, with an enthusiastic
child and a parent who wanted to help.
</P>
<P>
   Erica Stivison, 9, wanted to plan a house that was stormproof.
Her father, Ralph Stivison, who has a self-named architectural
practice, envisioned the big concept, ``a storm-resistant dwelling
primarily for the Texas-Oklahoma-Kansas tornado alley, but which
would also be appropriate for hurricane-prone regions of the Gulf
and Atlantic coasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph and Erica became so engrossed in their project, they were
invited to present their ideas to Erica's third-grade class at West
University Elementary School in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Her classmates volunteered suggestions. Ralph steered them
through the practical-thinking chores, their imaginations firing
off ideas both wild and reasonable. Ralph and Erica incorporated
the collective plan into a model _ earth-sheltered to counter the
uplift forces of winds and placed high on a grade to be above
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
   The house, with a long, light-filled atrium and rooms that open
off the center light well, was a hit with the class. The kids liked
the idea of playing on the roof, peeking through light wells down
into rooms. They also approved of the energy savings that earth
sheltering provides. ``The insulation value of the earth makes
heating and air-conditioning costs go way down,'' Ralph says.
</P>
<P>
   Through the eyes of adolescents, a house evolved that provides
shelter from the worst storms and the most frightening utility
bills. .MDBO/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
