<SLUG> BC-BEE-CIGARROA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAREDO SPELLING WHIZ GOES OUT IN BEE'S FIRST ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for those needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ricardo Cigarroa, 13, failed by one letter
Wednesday to make the second round of the 72nd National Spelling
Bee here.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarroa, who just completed the seventh grade at United Middle
School in Laredo, Texas, failed to correctly spell basmati, an
Asian long-grain rice. He used the letter ``z'' rather than ``s.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most contestants unfamiliar with a particular word,
Cigarroa asked the contest judge, or pronouncer, to define it.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarroa started spelling: B-A, then a pause, then Z-M-A-T-I.
</P>
<P>
   When the bell that signaled his error rang throughout the hushed
Grand Hyatt Hotel ballroom packed with 248 other contestants and
their relatives, Cigarroa knew he had been eliminated from the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed disappointed when he left the stage where the
contestants were sitting, but he soon emerged from a backstage room
with a smile. He said he was looking forward to touring the
Smithsonian Institution's National Air &AMP; Space Museum later
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He had been through a rough few days for Cigarroa. Sponsored by
the Laredo Morning News, Cigarroa caught a cold shortly after he
and his family arrived in Washington last Saturday. So he missed
touring the Washington, D.C., area with the other contestants and
their families.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarroa said that the night before the contest, which is run by
Scripps Howard newspapers, he hardly slept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept rolling around and looking at the clock,'' he said. At
one point he got up to study some of the words that are provided in
a 3,400-word handbook. But the contest words are not limited to the
handbook. The spellers can be given any word from the Webster's
Third New International Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarroa will take home $50 and a commemorative watch. He
defeated 50 other students in the Laredo Spelling Bee championship
in April to earn a place at the national contest.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarroa said he sometimes studies spelling for ``a couple of
hours a day.'' His mother, Melissa Cigarroa, said much of his study
time in the past few weeks went to studying for seventh-grade final
exams.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to continue teaching himself Latin and someday wants to
become a physician like his father, who also named Ricardo.
</P>
<P>
   Young Cigarroa said he plans to keep entering spelling contests
and hopes to be back here next year. The National Spelling Bee is
open to students under 16 who have not finished the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and on
e-mail at jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
