<SLUG> BC-COPLAND-2000-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING THE CENTENNIAL OF COPLAND, A NATIVE SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Plans for ``Copland 2000,'' a worldwide celebration
of Aaron Copland's music and contributions to American culture,
were announced this week. Copland, who was born in Brooklyn, would
have turned 100 on Nov. 14, 2000. He died in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The celebration of his centenary, which was announced at a joint
news conference at City Hall on Tuesday by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
and Linda Golding, president of the music publishing firm Boosey &AMP;
Hawkes, will involve more than 200 festivals, concerts and related
events over the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   It is being organized by Boosey &AMP; Hawkes, Copland's longtime
publisher. The events in New York City include ``Completely
Copland,'' a three-week festival to be presented this fall by the
New York Philharmonic in which virtually all of Copland's works are
to be performed. Philharmonic music director Kurt Masur took part
in the announcement, speaking of Copland's connection with the
orchestra and the city.
</P>
<P>
   Other local events include a survey of Copland's music for film
by the Museum of Modern Art, concerts featuring Copland's music by
the New York Pops, presentations of Copland's stage works by the
Kaye Playhouse and a four-day series called ``Celluloid Copland''
by the Eos Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Plans are under way for events and concerts in Minnesota,
Connecticut and other states as well as Argentina, Austria,
Belgium, Italy, Japan, Poland, South Africa, Britain and other
countries. There will be educational outreach programs, reissued
recordings and publications, and a nationwide tour by the Soldier's
Chorus and Concert Band of the U.S. Army Field Band featuring
Copland's music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Copland helped to build the reputation of New York City,''
said Giuliani. ``His music captured a quality of being grateful to
be an American. He closed the ceremony by proclaiming Tuesday to be
Aaron Copland Day in New York City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
