<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, June 3, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few thunderstorms will develop ahead of a cold front moving
through New England, but most sections will only notice a couple of
showers. It will be very warm and humid in the Middle Atlantic
region with partial sunshine. Widely separated thundershowers are
likely as the cold front approaches late in the day. Less humid air
will push eastward from the Ohio Valley into the western
Appalachians, but clouds will persist over the northern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Sunny skies and rather cool weather is expected over the Great
Lakes as high pressure builds across this area. Drier air will
circulate into the lower Ohio and middle Mississippi Valleys under
a mixture of sun and clouds.
</P>
<P>
   The South will be sultry with sunshine mixing with tall cumulus
clouds. The humidity will be uncomfortable and a few thunderstorms
are possible. Florida will notice several large thunderstorms as
sea breezes from the Atlantic and Gulf converge.
</P>
<P>
   A corridor of hot and humid air streaming northward into the
Plains will encounter a disturbance in the jet stream over eastern
Nebraska. A cluster of intense thunderstorms may form in the
eastern Dakotas this morning. Another batch of storms will initiate
over eastern Kansas Thursday afternoon and grow into Oklahoma and
Arkansas by evening.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air will make inroads to the Southwest. More showers
will dampen sections of California and a veil of clouds with some
rain will moisten the area from western Montana to central Nevada.
The deserts will stay warm and sunny, but much cooler air will
arrive Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Cape Cod Fog
</P>
<P>
   Dense fog shrouded Nantucket and Cape Cod early Wednesday. The
fog formed when warm, moist air from the south was blown or over
cool offshore waters. Fogs that form near bodies of water are
typically thicker, because of the large availability of moisture
for the myriad of tiny water drops that compose warm fogs. Fogs
that form near water also last longer because sunlight has more
difficulty penetrating thicjer fogs' outer edges. Moreover, water
under the fog does not warm fast, limiting currents of rising and
subsequently sinking air that might help to dissipate fog. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
