<HEADLINE>
STILL HOPING FOR DAD'S LOVE, EVEN IF YOU STRIKE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Remember this, Gil tells himself, knowing that he will not do
it again. Remember how it looks, with one inning to go, three outs,
to the win. Remember the people standing with their fingers hooked
through the metal fence, remember the milky blue of the stadium
paint and the similar color of the sky. . . . Remember your dry
mouth and constricted breath, the thump in your heart. Remember the
eerie silence. Remember the ache of being close.''
</P>
<P>
   So reads an important passage in Scott Lasser's affecting first
novel, ``Battle Creek,'' and while xou might doubt that a
middle-aged baseball manager would really talk to himself this way
(``Remember your dry mouth and constricted breath'') the passage
works in its context. You share Gil's breathless anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Gil is Gil Davison, manager of the Koch &AMP; Sons Dodgers, a
Detroit area amateur baseball team sponsored by a funeral home.
Beloved to fans for always getting to the finals of the national
elimination tournament at Battle Creek and for always losing, Gil's
teams are nevertheless of the highest quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``No other team has placed so many players in pro ball or has
had so many go all the way to the bigs,'' the narrative reports.
``Koch alumni have played in the World Series, are making big bucks
in Anaheim, Baltimore and Osaka. Last year one of the Battle Creek
papers called the team a dynasty.''
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Gil is determined to take his team all the way this
year, which he thinks may be his last. He will raise the bar of
competition even higher, harden his heart toward the mediocre
players on his roster. He will make his mind rule his heart when it
comes to yanking gutsy but tiring pitchers. He will face down all
obstacles that stand in the way of winning.
</P>
<P>
   These obstacles turn out to be legion. Ben Mercer, Gil's star
pitcher, has hurt his ankle climbing a fire escape in pursuit of a
woman he lusts after. The ankle interferes with his delivery, which
hurts his arm and forces him to fall back on illegally doctoring
the ball. Vince Paklos, Gil's old friend and coach, suffers from
severe emphysema, won't quit smoking and is literally counting the
days until his death. Luke James, Gil's young prodigy of a hitting
star, is having trouble adjusting to life after prison, where he
has done time for murdering a rival for his girlfriend's love.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the psychological barriers that Gil must
surmount. His 98-year-old father, who has always disapproved of
baseball, lies dying in a nearby hospital. Gil wants the suffering
to be over but also longs for recognition of his worth. At the same
time, Gil is torn by guilt over having driven his sons too hard.
One of them is dead of an accident for which Gil feels responsible.
The other is a lawyer in Chicago with little interest in baseball.
Have these stresses made Gil an object of Vince Lombardi's remark:
``Winning is a habit. Unfortunately, so is losing''? That is the
novel's epigraph.
</P>
<P>
   All of which may make ``Battle Creek'' sound like a cross
between a soap opera and a boys' sports adventure by John R. Tunis.
Yet the narrative is skillfully understated and elliptical. We get
to know the characters in their employment as stock brokers, United
Parcel Service deliverers and car manufacturing executives for whom
playing baseball is a release into a higher, more joyous calling.
Yet the games they play are described obliquely, with only the
relevant action set before the reader. Lasser, a Treasury bill
trader for Lehman Brothers who has published short stories in
literary reviews, sticks to the essentials of his story with little
wasted motion.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Battle Creek'' has a flaw, it is a slightly mechanical
emphasis on the theme of father love and its absence. As if Luke
James didn't have enough problems being an ex-convict haunted by
former inmates who have it in for him, he also suffers from Gil's
longing for paternal affection. ``Down the way the boy with droopy
pants got into his father's Cutlass. As they drove by, the boy
waved. James could see that the boy was drinking a Faygo red pop.
His father must have bought it for him. It occurred to James then _
in a startling, world-expandong way _ that other fathers loved
their sons whether they got hi4s or not.''
</P>
<P>
   But if such passages seem overly obvious, they contribute to the
novel's cumulative emotional power. The story's major developments
are stunning surprises.YIMU MMQ!Q5Y9QU11e!M  &QC; 5MQAI%
Q!Q5-Me &QC; UEUMQ% &QC; 9Q!] &QC; IQ! &QC;   &QC; 5AQ%99]%99%9%9Q!9Q! &QC; U! M 11%9
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
