<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      06-02 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JAGUAR LEAPS FORWARD  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY, JUNE 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - This was one of those perfect moments. I was soaring
along a back road in eastern Arizona, the shadows of tall pines
flashing across the car's hood and flickering on the brawny
shoulders of the Jaguar mascot leaping out in front.
</P>
<P>
   I was driving the new Jaguar S-Type sedan, quiet, refined and
substantial. Getting into the turns, the brakes prove to be strong,
the steering responsive, and handling incredible. The V-8 comes on
in a silky rush.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps best of all, I'm hot on the heels of a Jaguar XK-SS,
one of the most fabulous vintage sports cars. It's part of a
contingent of nine valuable, 1950s C- and D-type race cars and
XK-SS roadsters (derived from the D-types) taking part in an
Arizona car rally.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguar factory lent us a pair of new S-Type sedans, a
standard V-6 model and a sports-handling-tweaked V-8, for me and
the editor of ``British Car'' magazine to share as we tagged along
with the million-dollar hot rods.
</P>
<P>
   Among European car fanciers, particularly the Anglophilic ones,
the arrival of the 2000 Jaguar S-Type was a hotly anticipated event
ranking right up there with the release of ``The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaguar, flush with cash and access to a top-notch parts bin
after its acquisition by Ford, wanted to design a sedan to evoke
the style and heritage of its famous, sporting Mark II and S-type
sedans of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The British firm wanted to create a midsize car to compete with
the likes of BMW 5-series and Mercedes-Benz E-Class. And Jaguar
wanted to build a four-door car that would excite enthusiasts while
providing a calm luxury environment for friends and family.
</P>
<P>
   In most ways, the new S-Type delivers. The front aspect of the
body design is instantly recognizable as an update of the '60s
sedans. From the side, the size and proportions seem just about
right. The rear treatment is less successful, the trunk seeming too
high and the styling too generic.
</P>
<P>
   One clinker: The ovoid grille is made of chrome-plated plastic
that looks and feels chintzy.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Type is built on a platform developed with Lincoln for its
new LS sedan. Oddly, the Lincoln will be available with stick
shift, while the Jaguar won't, in opposition to Jag's sporting
heritage. Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   The lower end of the engines _ block, crankshaft, rods and
pistons _ comes directly from Ford Duratec design, the better to
reduce development cost, but the heads, fuel induction and other
bits are Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much discussion as to whether the S-Type would
turn out to be more Jaguar or Lincoln. I find its British accent to
be strong enough, and I had no trouble thinking of it as pure
Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   The S-Type's V-6 version has plenty of pull for all practical
purposes. Actually, it seems more akin to the old Mark II in sound
and performance than does the V-8.
</P>
<P>
   This test car was the standard setup, with 16-inch rims and
highway tires. Otherwise, it boasted just about every luxury-car
feature this side of Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   With the V-6 engine, stick shift would be very beneficial,
wringing out maximum power and control. Off the line, the V-6
accelerates quite leisurely until it gets up on the cam, and a
manual tranny with clutch would help a lot.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed automatic can be downshifted and upshifted
manually in Jaguar's familiar ``J'' automatic-shifter pattern. As
automatics go, this is a superb unit, with upshifts that are nearly
imperceptible and a readiness to downshift at the drop of a
throttle.
</P>
<P>
   The V-8 Jag is loaded with enough power to exceed the needs of
stick shift, though off-the-line torque is still rather tame with
this small-displacement engine. Passing power, and the power to
accelerate out of turns and up grades, is solid and impressive. The
engine roars swiftly up to its 6,800 rpm redline with an aggressive
snarl.
</P>
<P>
   With its nearly perfect 50-50 weight bias and well-engineered
geometry, the suspension is supple and allows the sedan to be
tossed into turns like a sports car.
</P>
<P>
   The V-8 test car was loaded with all the options, including
17-inch wheels with performance tires, a GPS navigation system,
even a voice-recognition system for the climate and stereo
controls. There was also CATS, Jaguar's clever acronym for Computer
Active Technology Suspension, which adjusts the suspension
according to how hard the driver is pushing it.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, all this exotic gear popped the price up into exotic
territory.
</P>
<P>
   The interior in either version is gorgeous and comfortable.
After driving about 500 miles over two days, I felt relaxed and
refreshed.
</P>
<P>
   The cabin is hip deep in leather, maple trim and wool carpeting,
nicely designed in traditional British fashion, and loaded with
nooks and cubbies. The dashboard is well-organized and
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   Although the BMW 5-series cars, especially the spectacular 540i,
and Mercedes' E-Class are the obvious targets, the Lexus GS300 and
GS400 are also in Jaguar's sights. These are all high-end sports
sedans that combine luxury with power and finesse, and the S-Type
easily joins their ranks. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaguar S-Type &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vehicle type: &QL; 
Five-passenger, four-door sedan, rear-wheel drive. &QL; 
Base price: &QL; 
$48,000 (V-8). &QL; 
$42,500 (V-6). &QL; 
Price as tested: &QL; 
$56,680 (V-8). &QL; 
$44,980 (V-6). &QL; 
Engine: &QL; 
4.0-liter V-8, 281 horsepower at 6,100 rpm, 287 pound-feet of
torque at 4,300 rpm. &QL; 
3.0-liter V-6, 240 horsepower at 6,800 rpm, 221 pound-feet of
torque at 4,500 rpm. &QL; 
Transmission: &QL; 
Five-speed automatic. &QL; 
Curb weight: &QL; 
3,770 pounds (V-8). &QL; 
3,650 pounds (V-6). &QL; 
Wheelbase: &QL; 
114.5 inches. &QL; 
