<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS ON TAPE, MINUS THE TAPE  
 MONITOR WITH GEEK APPEAL  
 SAVING MOUSE CLICKS AND MONEY  
 ROBOTIC FISH  
 THE BARBIE PRINTER  
 POPULAR PUP  
 WHY GORILLAS DON'T ANSWER E-MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 20 years ago Stevie Wonder produced a hit album called
``Talking Book.'' It hardly talked, but it did keep a mean beat.
Now, Audible Inc., an online distributor of audio content in Wayne,
N.J., has turne$ the tables by producing a portable audio player
that doesn't keep a beat so well but is, for all practical
purposes, a talking book.
</P>
<P>
   Shaped like a large thumb and studded with recessed control
buttons, the Audible Mobile Player-Plus stores audio content on its
16 megabytes of internal flash memory, the high-tech equivalent of
books on tape. But the Mobile Player-Plus, which weighs 3.5 ounces
and is small enough to slip into a pocket, uses no tape.
</P>
<P>
   And much like the Diamond Rio audio player, it receives its
recorded material, mostly books and newspapers, by way of a
personal computer. Unlike the Rio player, notes Jonathan Korzen, a
company spokesman, the Mobile Player-Plus does not use the MP3
format to store its material, but uses its own much-compressed
format that, unlike MP3, protects downloaded material from
unauthorized copying.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mobile player, which is sold only directly from
Audible's Web site (www.audible.com) for $299, is not made to be a
music player. It is intended for mobile professionals who spend a
lot of time traveling and feel they don't get enough time to read
as much as they want to or need to, Korzen said. The Mobile player
can also load more than seven hours of audio material and can even
be played through conventional cassette players and FM radio
receivers.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   More Than Just a Fashion Statement
</P>
<P>
   Now you see it, now no one else does.
</P>
<P>
   That is the killer application that lies just beneath the
filters of the new FT15 Exclusive View flat-panel computer monitor.
At first, the 14.5-inch LCD display by Sceptre Technologies in City
of Industry, Calif., looks very much like a slew of other
flat-panel monitors.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something that gives this monitor high geek appeal.
Unless users are wearing a pair of special polarized eyeglasses,
the Exclusive View screen appears blank no matter what is typed or
however a mouse is clicked. With the glasses, users can work,
browse and play in relative privacy and security.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,199 monitor is being aimed at groups for which ``it is
vital to keep trade secrets and other valuable information
secure,'' according to a company description. Primary users may be
found in government offices, law offices and banks, or among
hurried corporate travelers, said Li Ding, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The new monitors can be ordered only from the company's site at
www.sceptre.com and as complete packages or as an optional package
added to a standard flat screen made by the company.
</P>
<P>
   If someone else happens to have polarized glasses, however, the
screen will give up its secrets. But Ms. Ding said that was not
very likely.
</P>
<P>
   _ MICHEL MARRIOTT
</P>
<P>
   `Going Out Shopping' Takes On a New Meaning
</P>
<P>
   Tired of trudging around the Web trying to find the best price
on something? Power shopping just got easier, and you don't even
have to be in front of your computer anymore. If you have a Palm
VII, you might just be able to save money and mouse clicks from
wherever you are with Pocket Shopper, the new My Simon application
for 3Com's latest edition of its popular personal digital
assistant. My Simon is an e-commerce hub that specializes in online
comparison shopping with a constantly updated database of 10
million products from 1,300 merchants. The Pocket Shopper program
can be downloaded from www.mysimon.com or www.palm.net.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII, released last month, allows users to easily
connect to the Internet through wireless communications technology.
By firing up their Palm VIIs and remotely tapping into the online
database, users can have the Pocket Shopper instantly compare costs
and product availability on things like consumer electronics,
books, compact disks and golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Although not as extensive as its parent My Simon's list, the
Pocket Shopper patrols more than 15 product categories containing 5
million items from 500 different stores, with more added each
month. Future plans for the program include allowing users to
receive more detailed information about stores and merchandise, as
well as the ability to actually purchase the things found via the
Palm VII.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D. BIERSDORFER
</P>
<P>
   Fish That Won't Take the Bait
</P>
<P>
   Engineers in Japan appear to be getting into the robot business
these days: First, Sony announced the arrival of Aibo, the robotic
dog. Now Mitsubishi Heavy Industries is developing robotic fish.
</P>
<P>
   You might expect a robotic dog to fetch your slippers and
perform tricks. But the problem with robotic fish is they just
don't do anything.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mitsubishi has developed robotic fish that may have
several applications. One of the company's creations, swimming
around in a museum's fish tank in Yokohama, is a glassy-eyed sea
bream, about two feet long, that moves by wiggling its tail fin and
two pectoral fins. Battery-powered motors hidden within the fins
are remotely controlled by a desktop computer. The battery is
recharged automatically by a coil inside the fish that draws power
from an electromagnetic field that permeates the fish tank,
according to a report by New Scientist Magazine. Mitsubishi is
hoping to use the same technology to propel underwater vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   But the company's success with the sea bream has also led it to
consider building more robotic fish for exhibits, possibly replicas
of rare species like the coelacanth, an ancient fish with jointed
bones that was once thought to be extinct.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Printer With Pink Accents Lends a Barbie Touch
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that little girls would accessorize their Barbie
dolls with Barbie clothes, Barbie shoes or, if their parents
couldn't say no, Barbie's Dreamhouse. Now 7-year-olds with parents
who can't say no will have the chance to accessorize their
computers with Barbie peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel, which introduced the very popular Barbie digital camera
last year, and Apollo Consumer Products will soon be selling a $79
Barbie color printer in ``mist gray'' with ``glitter pink
accents.'' It also comes with Barbie stickers and the Barbie Magic
Hair Styler CD-ROM, one of Mattel's most popular pieces of
software. ``Every little girl that walks into the store and sees it
on a shelf will fall in love with it,'' said Mohan Garde, the
general manager for Apollo, a subsidiary of Hewlett Packard. His
own 7-year-old daughter, Garde said, keeps asking when he is going
to bring the printer home.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo (www.myapollo.com) was created in January to create and
market stylish, low-priced printers. The Barbie printer, Garde
said, is just one example of what he calls ``the next step in PCs
and printers as they transition from the technology market to the
appliance market,'' where color and style become major selling
points.
</P>
<P>
   Is a GI Joe printer next, maybe in camouflage colors or fatigue
gray? ``We don't want to play our hand yet,'' Garde said. But
creating something for the market for boys ages 7 to 12, he said,
is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   Dog in the Windows
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Sony has found an untapped market for robotic
dogs. Within 20 minutes of opening online sales on Tuesday, the
company sold out its 3,000 units of Aibo, a programmable pup, on
the Japanese market. Sales of the robot in the United States
weren't quite as brisk _ about 1,000 of 2,000 robots on the market
were sold by the end of the day. But Tod Freeman, a spokesman for
Sony, said that demand was high. ``For the first two and a half
hours, our server was so overloaded it was inaccessible,'' Freeman
said. Aibo, which is selling for $2,500, can be purchased only
online.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the Juggling Gene
</P>
<P>
   You sent an e-mail note to Koko the gorilla two weeks ago, but
she has been ``too busy'' to respond? She may have a good excuse.
Scientists believe they have located the part of the brain
responsible for the kind of multitasking called branching.
Branching involves temporarily shifting focus from one task to
others, then returning to the main task, a crucial skill in the era
of e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent issue of Nature, scientists from the National
Institute of Neurological Disorders and Strokes in Bethesda, Md.,
reported that branching activated the region of the brain called
the fronto-polar prefrontal cortex, which also controls complex
problem solving. Sadly for the other primates, the multitasking
part of the brain is well developed only in humans.
</P>
</TEXT>
