<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOFTUS-COLUMN-$ADV10-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEWARE OF LIBRARIANS BEARING HERMIT CRABS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release June 10)  
(rk) 
 By MARY J. LOFTUS   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know how it happened, really.
</P>
<P>
   One minute, I was a library volunteer at my son's elementary
school, helping move books into the gymnasium so the media center's
walls could be repainted, and the next, I was the HERMIT CRAB
SITTER for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   These things always start out with some offhand comment.
</P>
<P>
   As I siphoned water out of the fish aquarium so it could be
moved to the arts center, I remarked to the librarian that my son
wanted an aquarium, but I told him that having three dogs, three
cats and a cockatiel was more than enough animals for one
household.
</P>
<P>
   Being a skilled communicator, she hardly blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, fish,'' she said, pretending to be my ally. ``They
can be hard to care for.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, by nature, librarians are not manipulative schemers.
</P>
<P>
   The ones I know tend to be orderly, friendly, a bit daffy along
the lines of Mrs. Frizzle (who drives the Magic School Bus.) And
some are overly attached to the Dewey Decimal System.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when pressed, they can be downright Machiavellian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fish can indeed be a problem. But you know what's no problem
at ALL, what would be GREAT for your son to have in his room _ why,
I bet he would just love one _ is a hermit crab. Quiet, clean, they
only need to be fed about once a week. It's the ideal pet,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   I kept siphoning and nodding, still thinking we were just
whiling away the afternoon with some idle chatter. ``Sure, hermit
crabs, that's a thought. I'll have to look into it,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, it's good sometimes to try out a pet, you know,
before you actually buy it. Keep one for a few days, or even
months, while you see how it fits in to your family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I looked up, getting my first inkling that this conversation was
going somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take these hermit crabs right here,'' she said, pointing to
another aquarium in the opposite corner of the media center.
``These little guys are so popular with the children.''
</P>
<P>
   I blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they really need a home for the summer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at the cage, which appeared to be full of completely
harmless sea shells and a piece of driftwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's their pellets of food. You just fill it up right here,
and put water in this. That's all there is to it,'' she said. ``If
they die, don't worry about it. Can I help you carry it to your
car?''
</P>
<P>
   And, so, the aquarium is sitting on a shelf in my son's room,
out of direct sunlight. I fill the water dish each evening, and try
to keep my 2-year-old away from the timid creatures.
</P>
<P>
   There are three of the little guys, tucked into their separate
shells, and after careful observation, my son and I have gotten to
know which one likes to scoot around in the evening, which one
climbs the most, and which one likes to curl up and sleep in a
favorite corner most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is, we're going on vacation for a week. So I
called a friend who has a son about Adam's age, just to see how
things were going.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' I said, about midway through the conversation.
``Have you ever though about a hermit crab as a pet? It's always a
good idea to kind of have a trial run, you know, before buying one
...''
</P>
<P>
   (The Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
