<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0325 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      06-02 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR DROPS OF RELIEF SUPPLIES FORCE NATO TO REDUCE OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S.-led bombing of Yugoslavia will be
temporarily suspended over parts of Kosovo beginning Thursday to
permit daily air drops of humanitarian relief to besieged refugees,
military officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The first major reduction in bombing in Kosovo during the 71-day
allied air campaign comes as NATO war planes have halted bombing of
the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade to avoid disrupting diplomatic
efforts by European envoys meeting with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic there.
</P>
<P>
   Two Russian-built Antonov-26 cargo planes chartered by the
International Rescue Committee and flown by crews from the former
Soviet republic of Moldova will make daily humanitarian flights
over Kosovo to drop enough pre-packaged humanitarian meals to feed
about 8,000 refugees each day.
</P>
<P>
   The two planes will be over Kosovo for about two hours each day,
as part of the four-hour round trip from nearby Pescara, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, the Pentagon's head of
strategic planning, said Wednesday that the U.S.-led air campaign
will coordinate with the pilots of the supply planes.
</P>
<P>
   The relief pilots are advising NATO's Combined Air Operations
Center ``what time they'll be flying, where they're going to be
flying (and) what altitudes they'll be at,'' Wald said. The
humanitarian flights are being incorporated into NATO's daily ``air
tasking order''_ the minute-to-minute schedule of allied
combat-related flights that details the time and location of every
allied aircraft staging bombing runs and support missions.
</P>
<P>
   This will enable the allies' Airborne Warning and Control System
aircraft (AWACS) to track the relief flights and direct combat
operations away from the humanitarian operations.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the American Army four-star general
commanding the forces of the 19-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, said NATO war planes will allow civilian aircraft to
drop food supplies to ethnic Albanian Muslim refugees clustered in
various parts of Kosovo, a province of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to fly into the airspace at a time when we are
going to be sure we don't do anything to put them in jeopardy,''
Clark said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Smith, the International Rescue Committee's vice
president for overseas programs, said the supply planes will use
10-mile wide flight corridors over Kosovo each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO will allow us to use a corridor over Kosovo and they have
said that they will stay out of that corridor for the time that we
are in it,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots will vary their use of the designated corridors. Because
Kosovo is only about 100 miles wide, setting aside 10-mile wide
flight corridors will force NATO to temporarily suspend combat
operations over wide swathes of the province.
</P>
<P>
   To tighten coordination, NATO is allocating the two humanitarian
flights a radio monitoring frequency to listen in on certain NATO
communications.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said pilots of the civilian aircraft spied Yugoslav
anti-aircraft fire Wednesday when they dropped leaflets to alert
Kosovo refuges that airdrops would begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The air crews ``reported they did see some AAA (anti-aircraft
artillery) fired in their vicinity,'' Wald said. ``Whether it was
at them or not, we're not sure. But we assume it may have been.''
</P>
<P>
   Wald said the pilots were ``brave to take the risk'' to deliver
relief supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has resisted assigning slow-moving, low-flying
C-130 Hercules cargo planes to air dropping food to Kosovo refugees
because of the risk of Serbian anti-aircraft fire.
</P>
<P>
   Allied warplanes have carried out an average of 850 individual
flights or sorties over Yugoslavia during each 24-hour period. The
armada of 720 American aircraft and 325 allied aircraft has
conducted more than 31,000 sorties since the bombing campaign began
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The cutback in NATO combat operations over Kosovo gets underway
as an envoy from the 15-nation European Union, Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari, accompanied Russia's Balkan envoy, former Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, to meet with Milosevic. The envoys
met with Milosevic for two hours on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia have been at odds over the
structure of the planned post-war international security force
destined to enter Kosovo to provide security and encourage more
than 1.4 million displaced Kosovars to return to their homes in the
wake of a 13-month crackdown by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The United States insists that the multi-national force have
NATO troops ``at the core'' with a unified command structure
supervising all military operations across Kosovo, including
operations by cooperating Russian troops.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has suggested a divided force for Kosovo, with Russian
troops patrolling Serb-dominated areas adjacent to Serbia and NATO
troops patrolling southern Kosovo. Russia has long standing ethnic
and religious ties with the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the European and
Russian diplomats had reached ``sufficient agreement'' on the
composition and structure of the post-war security force to present
a united front to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, addressing graduating cadets at the U.S. Air
Force Academy in Colorado Springs, Colo., announced that the United
States will provide up to 7,000 of the 47,868 soldiers being
mustered by 30 nation to serve in the security force.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 percent U.S. share is substantially less than then 50
percent U.S. share of the 60,000-strong allied force that went into
Bosnia in 1995 to enforce a U.S.-brokered peace agreement ending
ethnic fighting there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a clear choice before the Serbian leader,'' Clinton
declared. ``He can cut his losses now and accept the basic
requirements of a just peace, or he can continue to force military
failure and economic ruin on his people. In the end, the outcome
will be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to meet with the Joint Chiefs of Staff on
Thursday to review allied military operations, including the
possibility of pouring allied forces into Yugoslavia for a ground
war.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen told reporters that the
nation's top six military officers will review all facets of the
military operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm that there will be a full range of discussions, questions
about whether or not there would be any kind of a ground option for
a non-permissive environment,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have ``a consensus for a strong air operation,''
Cohen said, adding: ``There is not a consensus for a ground
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
