<HEADER>
A0331 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ILLEGAL-IMMIGRANTS-HN     06-02 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILLEGAL-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYER GROUP SUES CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ A taxpayer group is suing Gov. Gray Davis
to stop secret negotiations over the fate of Proposition 187, the
1994 ballot initiative designed to cut off government services to
illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Davis caused a panic among supporters of both sides of the
Proposition 187 debate by sending a lawsuit on the ballot measure
to the 9th Circuit Mediation Office in San Francisco. The federal
court-run office works in secret to settle civil and criminal
lawsuits, but has never handled a ballot initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association, which did not take a
position on the measure, sued Tuesday arguing that Davis' decision
to jettison the normal legal process runs against nearly 200 years
of law.
</P>
<P>
   The association contends that the U.S. system of judicial review
requires the public courts to decide the fate of Proposition 187,
which was approved by nearly 60 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The group wants Davis to cancel the secret negotiations, which
are set to begin within a month, and move the debate over
Proposition 187 back into the open courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying that this is a public process,'' said Kris
Vosburgh, executive director of the association. ``This was put on
the ballot by the people, it was voted on by the people, and it
should be decided in public, by the courts.''
</P>
<P>
   The group also is distressed about just who will be involved in
secret discussions over the initiative, which has not been
implemented because of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   That lawsuit pits opponents to Proposition 187, namely the
League of United Latin American Citizens, against the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is continuing a defense of the initiative that started
under former Gov. Pete Wilson, arguing that he must respect the
will of voters who approved the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis, a Democrat, also worked strenuously against
Proposition 187 when it was on the ballot. And Davis said two weeks
ago he would not implement at least one portion of the measure _ a
provision that requires the state to remove illegal immigrant
children from the public school system.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' decision to send Proposition 187 to mediation opens up
the possibility of even more lawsuits down the road. The Pacific
Legal Foundation, which opposes the measure, has already complained
that no supporter of Proposition 187 would be at the mediation
conference.
</P>
<P>
   If it was dissatisfied after the mediation, then the Pacific
Legal Foundation could continue its lawsuit. The whole process
would be back in the public courts again, probably headed to the
U.S. Supreme Court for a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very concerned that all the participants in the
governor's mediation process are opponents to the measure,'' said
Sharon Browne, a lawyer with the Pacific Legal Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Davis said mediation was chosen because
litigation over Proposition 187 appeared to be on an endless path.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been debated, discussed, deliberated to death for the
last five years,'' spokesman Michael Bustamante said. ``It is time
to end this, to resolve this once and for all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
