<HEADLINE>
TRENDS: NIFTY STUFF TO BUY AND WEAR 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By KELLY DEGARMO 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ULTIMATE WATER BLASTER
</P>
<P>
   After last summer's awesome Torpedo, what can possibly make a
splash as the coolest water toy of 1999? Wild Planet's Paddle
Pumper will be a front-runner _ if you can find one. Many stores
already are sold out. The Pumper is a durable water blaster that
shoots a stream of water more than 20 feet and also can be used as
a paddle. Its great pump design makes it easy for small hands to
use. The Paddle Pumper comes packaged with an inflatable seat
called the Bumper Jumper and sells for under $20.
</P>
<P>
   Rites of Summer
</P>
<P>
   Memorial Day weekend has started off summer. Time to hit the
lake, water park or pool. To carry all your stuff, grab a bag. This
season's bags come in a variety of fun styles, from homespun
macrame to shiny patent. Anything goes. Just don't forget the
sunscreen.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Fashions
</P>
<P>
   Comfy terry cloth spins itself into fashion for another summer,
turning up in tank tops, shirts, dresses, headbands and even
sandals. A rainbow of colors spans from baby blue to sunshine
yellow. Airwalk's new Eva features a terry cloth-like texture in
the foot bed and straps for major comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Blown away
</P>
<P>
   Summer is bubble season. Blowers abound to create everything
from mammoth to teeny bubbles and every size in between. To create
your own bubble solution, follow this recipe from Camp Earth,
guaranteed to deliver the best bubbles ever. In a jug, gently mix:
1 cup Dawn liquid dish soap, 1 cup light Karo syrup, 4 to 5 cups
distilled water. Allow to sit for seven days at room temperature
before using.
</P>
<P>
