<HEADLINE>
BOOK MAY HELP BRING TEENS AND PARENTS CLOSER 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 By KELLY DEGARMO 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An endearing new book for teen-agers and their parents, ``Always
Accept Me for Who I Am'' (Three Rivers Press, $8) talks honestly
about support, communication, trust, acceptance, love and family.
</P>
<P>
   With viewpoints from 147 teen-agers, the book is compiled by
author J.S. Salt, author of ``Always Kiss Me Goodnight.'' It allows
youths, ages 13 to 18, to speak their minds and let their parents
know what's really important to them. Here are some of viewpoints
from the book:
</P>
<P>
   Support: ``Be open to new ideas ... If you're wrong, admit.'' _
Max, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Communication: ``Always listen to me, no matter how busy you
are. Having an open ear tells me you have an open heart.'' _
Jessica, 15.
</P>
<P>
   Trust and acceptance: ``Stop telling me what not to do and I
won't have to rebel. If you deprive me of my freedom, you will be
the one locked in the dungeon!'' _ Yvonne, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Love and family: ``Everyone has goodness inside of them. It just
takes another person to spark it. Sort of like a chain reaction. So
let me into your world and show you that I can do it.''_ Sean, 17.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
