<HEADLINE>
ADVICE ABOUT FRIENDS, STEALING 
 FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE 
 FROM THE FORT WORTH STAR-TELEGRAM
</HEADLINE>
  World rights. 
 Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I just stared middle school. In elementary, I
was a straight-A student. I played soccer and other sports. Now
that I am in middle school, I have lost some of my interest in
sports and my grades have fallen. My friends don't participate in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   My parents think I should still play sports and keep up my
grades. I have interests in other things, like guys, parties,
shopping and school activities. I make B's and C's. I'm passing all
my classes except one. I just want to do other things now that I
have other friends. How do I tell my p: It sounds like your
priorities have changed. When you are in elementary school, you
have the same friends and activities that you developed with your
family. When you change schools and meet new friends, your
interests change _ but your goals in life should not.
</P>
<P>
   If sports is important to you bch person is designed
differently, with different interests. You can play sports and do
your homework and get together on weekends to shop or have parties.
Success in sports and grades can open many opportunities for the
future. Don't drop the ball and forfeit the game.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR TeensTalk: I run around with a group of guys that I have
known since elementary school. We live in the same neighborhood and
go to the samchool. Last weekend, we went to a party and had a few
drinks. After we left the party, my friend decided to stop at a
store. When he came out, he told us he had stolen some stuff.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted him to go back and return the stolen items. The other
guys in the car thought we should all go in and steal stuff. I have
known these people for years. I never thought they'd steal
anything. I didn't take anything, and they gave me a real hard
time. How do I remain friends with them but let them know that
someday they're gonna get caught? _ Stealing.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR Stealing: Good choice. Your friends might have gotten away
with it this time, but next time they run the risk of getting
caught. The small items stolen hardly add up to the value of
getting caught. You set a good example for your old friends in
showing that you have values and don't intend to join them. If your
friends continue to steal, find new friends. Don't go down the
river with 'em.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Do you have a problem or concern that needs an answer? The Class
Acts TeensTalk panel _ headed by Kathy Pope, a counselor at a Texas
junior colle _ is comprised of teenage students who care about
other students. Write to: TeensTalk, c/o Class Acts, The New York
Times Syndicate, 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
