<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NEW JERSEY, AN OUTPOST OF BLACK THEATRICAL TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Ricardo Khan, the road to a Tony Award began with a matinee
performance of ``Hello, Dolly!'' in 1967. Khan, then a gawky
16-year-old theater buff, still remembers the awe he felt as the
curtain went up in the St. James Theater to reveal Cab Calloway and
Pearl Bailey in roles that had been radically recast by the
producer, David Merrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't inspired because it was on Broadway,'' Khan said,
``but because it was an all-black cast. It was a cast,'' he said
with a pause, ``that looked like  &UR; me. &LR; ''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, using a $225,000 federal jobs grant, Khan
established the Crossroads Theater Company in New Brunswick, N.J.,
and began making theater by, for and about black Americans. It is a
mission that, Khan admits, has had its share of financial pitfalls
and has had him spending more than a few afternoons sweeping
floors, tiling bathrooms and ``wondering why I got into this.''
</P>
<P>
   But any doubts were swept away this past season.
</P>
<P>
   On April 26, the company celebrated its Broadway debut when ``It
Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,'' a joint production with two other
nonprofit theaters, was picked up by a consortium of commercial
producers and reopened at the Vivian Beaumont Theater at Lincoln
Center.
</P>
<P>
   A week later Crossroads learned that it had won one of theater's
highest honors: the Tony for outstanding regional theater. On top
of that, ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues'' received four Tony
nominations, including one for best musical.
</P>
<P>
   The Crossroads story is one of individual and institutional
persistence. Inspired by the black theater scene of the 1960s, the
company survived cutbacks in federal financing by forging
relationships with New Jersey businesses and New Brunswick
officials who used the arts as a cornerstone for urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, its success has been bittersweet: the theater's growth
and prominence on a national stage coincides with a period of
crisis for many other black theaters, a point brought home during
the highly publicized debate in 1997 between playwright August
Wilson and artistic director Robert Brustein on issues of race and
cultural power.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Crossroads does not mean that black theater is in
the full bloom of health, though there are promising signs.
Crossroads is the first company devoted to works by black Americans
to win the Tony for regional theater since the award's creation in
1976. And it is one of only two black theater companies that belong
to the League of Resident Theaters, an association of 70 leading
nonprofit theaters; the Freedom Theater in Philadelphia, joined the
league this year.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there are about 50 full-time black theater
companies, said Woodie King Jr., who founded the New York-based New
Federal Theater, one of the country's oldest black troupes. He said
that major black companies include the New Federal, the Freedom
Theater, the National Black Theater in Harlem, the St. Louis Black
Repertory, the ETA Creative Arts Foundation in Chicago, Jomandi in
Atlanta, the Ensemble Theater Company in Houston, and the Penumbra
Theater in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   But as King points out, today's ranks bear little resemblance to
those that emerged in the wake of the civil rights movement. ``In
the late 1960s,'' he said, ``there were 45 black theaters in New
York alone.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the vibrant scene Khan leaped into when he founded
Crossroads. ``The Negro Ensemble Company was strong, the New
Federal was strong, the National Black Theater was strong,'' Khan
said. ``These were role models.'' The son of a Trinidadian doctor
and an American nurse, Khan attended Rutgers University in New
Brunswick, studying law but falling in love with theater. After
graduating, Khan and Lee Richardson, a classmate, set up a 60-seat
theater in an abandoned warehouse on an access road at the city's
edge.
</P>
<P>
   They used seed money from an unlikely source, the Comprehensive
Employment and Training Act, a federal jobs program. Not that there
wasn't ample labor involved. At first, Khan acted, directed and
cleaned the floors, a regimen that finally dulled his passion for
being onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided the acting could be done a lot better by someone not
thinking about whether the bathroom was leaking or why there
weren't people in the seats,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead Khan became an astute player as a director and producer,
raising money and connecting with local government leaders, talents
that served his company well when federal funds dried up in the
1980s. Richardson left the company in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   While many black theaters, including the acclaimed Negro
Ensemble, failed or lost steam, Crossroads grew into an institution
with a budget of more than $3 million. It has reduced its debt to
$600,000 from $1.7 million in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The company resides in a handsome 320-seat theater in the heart
of New Brunswick built in 1991 for $4 million by a partnership of
local government and private benefactors. About 65 percent of the
company's audience is African-American, Khan said, a substantial
increase since the theater's early days. The artistic roster is
also integrated; for example, works by the playwrights Romulus
Linney, who is white, and Migdalia Cruz, who is Puerto Rican, were
presented in the theater's new play series in March.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers prepare food and greet audience members nightly.
Kente cloth and African artifacts decorate the walls and music
fills the lobby. High-profile fans include Bill Cosby and Gen.
Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being outside a major media center has been to their benefit
because they haven't had to fight for attention,'' King said. ``And
being in a city where Johnson &AMP; Johnson is based doesn't hurt
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossroads gets support from Johnson &AMP; Johnson and other
pharmaceutical companies in New Jersey. Schering-Plough Corp. in
Madison, sponsored the theater's annual new play festival this
year. Other major corporate supporters include the AT&AMP;T Foundation
and Absolut Vodka.
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s, the theater has grown artistically, too,
attracting young talents like George C. Wolfe, who developed ``The
Colored Museum'' at Crossroads in 1986. Three years later, Wolfe
returned to work on ``Spunk.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
