<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0358 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-THEATER-ART-2ND     06-02 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-THEATER-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: on ``Spunk.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm sure I required a lot as an artist,'' Wolfe said, ``and
they provided it.''
</P>
<P>
   Productions in recent years have included new plays by Wilson
(``Jitney'') and Ruby Dee (``The Disappearance'').
</P>
<P>
   The company's breakthrough production came in 1989, when it
presented the world premiere of ``Sheila's Day,'' performed by a
collaboration of South African and American actresses. The play,
about the parallel journeys of a black woman in South Africa and a
black woman in the American South, traveled to Washington, the
Brooklyn Academy of Music and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sheila's Day'' piqued the interest of many theater
professionals, said Chris Jones, chairman of the regional theater
committee for the Tony Awards. ``That's when people began noticing
and talking about Crossroads,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His committee was also impressed by the company's ``specificity
of mission,'' he said, as well as its programs, like internships
that enroll students from traditionally black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   While the overt political meaning of ``Sheila's Day'' earned the
theater some acclaim, it was nothing compared with the publicity
generated by a fervent debate over its general role in black
theater.
</P>
<P>
   It began in 1996 during a national theater conference in
Princeton, N.J., where Wilson pointed out in a keynote address that
Crossroads was then the only black theater company in the League of
Resident Theaters. This, Wilson said, reflected a lack of support
for professional African-American theaters, and he argued that what
African-American artists needed most was not roles in plays
produced by predominantly white theater companies, but theater
companies and stages of their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The things Wilson said are things people wanted to say for
 &UR; so &LR;  long,'' Khan said. ``And people roared with enthusiasm because
he said it. They might not agree with all of it, but at least he
said it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some believed that Wilson's message smacked of separatism.
The most prominent critic was Brustein of the American Repertory
Theater in Boston. The debate culminated in a sold-out discussion
between the men at Town Hall in Manhattan, an event that many felt
clarified little.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Khan is typically sanguine: ``It was wild, it was
glorious. But it's not like we'd been thrust into the middle of
something. We were already in it. It's just someone pointed a light
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For black theater artists, Crossroads' status as a national
player was established long before the Brustein-Wilson debate.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Taylor, the creator of ``It Ain't Nothin' but the Blues,''
said that without Crossroads, the show could have easily died two
years ago. After three years of sporadic touring of high schools,
small town auditoriums and regional theaters, ``Blues'' had lost
its main financial backer, the Denver Theater Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on the telephone and started calling,'' Taylor said. One
of the people he called was Khan, whom he had never met, but knew
by reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick said, `I love this show,''' Taylor recalled, adding that
Khan hadn't actually seen it yet. ``He said, `If you can get it to
the East Coast, I think we can get it to New York.'''
</P>
<P>
   Working with the artistic directors of the Alabama Shakespeare
Festival and the San Diego Repertory Company, Khan helped arrange a
tour, with a three-week run at the New Victory Theater in Manhattan
in March. The New Victory sold out.
</P>
<P>
   One important factor leading to the Broadway run was Khan's long
friendship with Eric Krebs, a commercial producer who lives near
Crossroads and has been a longtime supporter. Krebs assembled a
group of other investors to move the show from the New Victory to
the Beaumont, where sales have been promising.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Khan said he had no intention or time to rest on his
laurels. He has a three-year plan to eliminate the theater's debt,
a mission he hopes the regional theater Tony will help. Khan would
also like to build an endowment for the theater.
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, too, Crossroads is looking to expand. Nurturing
new theater about African-American life continues to be the goal;
what that means, however, is changing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our existence is not defined anymore by what it is to be black
in America, but to be black in the world,'' Khan said. ``You spend
a lot of time on black and white and it starts to restrict you.
Black people are redefining who we are. Theater can do that, too.''
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
