A0359 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEDERAL-WORKERS03-COX     06-02 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-WORKERS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHADOW OF BIG GOVERNMENT STILL HOVERS, AUTHOR SAYS
 &HT;    430&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's now famous declaration that the
``era of big government is over'' is part of myth fostered by
presidents and lawmakers to hide the true size of the federal
bureaucracy, according to a new book.
</P>
<P>
   Critiquing the six-year effort to downsize government, author
Paul C. Light of the Brookings Institution writes that the
president gave only part of the picture when he announced three
years ago that the federal work force, at 1.9 million civilians,
was the smallest since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   That claim is part of a ``head count charade'' in the ``politics
of smallness,'' which is aimed at giving the illusion of a leaner
government, Light writes. He points to evidence that many agencies
have replaced permanent workers with contractors, largely because
they are not included in the official count.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the emphasis on payroll reduction has produced
``random cuts'' that make government less efficient, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``The True Size of Government,'' Light says that the
reduced civilian work force Clinton touted _ now at a level of 1.84
million _ was only a small portion of employees who depend on Uncle
Sam for their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Adding up what he terms the ``shadow of government,'' the author
calculates the actual total at nearly 17 million fulltime workers.
That includes 5.6 million hired through federal contracts, 4.6
million in state or local jobs that are federally mandated, 2.4
million paid through federal grants, plus 1.5 million uniformed
military and 850,000 postal service workers.
</P>
<P>
   Light argues that the six-year push to downsize, overseen by
Vice President Al Gore, has produced some efficiencies, especially
in purchasing. Moreover, he said it is logical for the government
to hire private contractors to do some work, such as in the space
program and in weapons manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   But over all, the pressure to hide the true reach of government
has led to a ``staggering'' lack of information that distorts
efforts to make reforms, according to the author, a longtime
authority on the federal bureaucracy. ``The state of the federal
work force in 1999 is anyone's guess, which is precisely not how to
run a government that works better, let alone one that costs
less.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds that both parties contribute to obscuring the truth.
``The fact is that the illusion of smallness benefits both branches
and both parties,'' he writes. ``Democrats and Republicans alike
understand the conceit. They know the true size of government is
not to be found in head counts, but they also appear to believe
that the American public just cannot be trusted with the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He argues that the effort has borne fruit, especially for
Clinton, who blunted traditional Republican attacks on waste in
federal spending by reducing the federal payroll, even though
almost all of the reductions came from the military.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Clinton claim of having the smallest government in
three decades was partly an illusion, says Light, who points out
that only the Defense Department was bigger in 1960. Non-defense
civilian workers have increased by 53 percent since 1960, he
writes.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the president successfully employed his
small-government theme, Light says. He cited campaign remarks
Clinton made in 1996 in Atlanta when he referred to ``how bad big
old federal government was, but it's our administration working
with our allies in Congress (that) has cut the size.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton had made bureaucracy lovable again by attacking it,
disparaging it, and ultimately, cutting it,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will almost certainly adopt the same theme in the 2000
presidential campaign, Light predicted, adding that Republicans
will probably counter that with promises to make even more cutbacks
in the federal payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
