A0360 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELVIS-AUCTION-NYT &LR;      06-02 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELVIS-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT AUCTION OF ELVIS MEMORABILIA, EVERYTHING BUT THE BLUE SUEDE
SHOES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For sale: One pair of used Army fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   Former owner: Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Also available: Ivory-colored wool cape with depiction of
American eagle and rhinestones, vintage yellow Cadillac station
wagon with wood-grain side panels, music publishing contract for
``Heartbreak Hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   These and 2,000 more of the king's most treasured possessions _
among them clothes, furniture and letters from Marilyn Monroe,
Frank Sinatra, Marlon Brando and President John F. Kennedy _ are to
go on the auction block in October in Las Vegas, Nev., in a sale of
memorabilia from the archives of Elvis' Graceland compound. None of
the items have been displayed at Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   The auction, to be held over three or four days at the MGM Grand
by Guernsey's, the Manhattan auction house, is to raise money for
housing in Memphis for homeless families.
</P>
<P>
   Any additional money is to be used to expand exhibition space at
Graceland, officials there said.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that the keepers of Graceland have turned cape-phobic,
they said. Rather, with a large number of holdings, they say, it is
time to groom their portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were certain priceless things that you can't line up in
endless hallways and frame,'' said Jack Soden, president and chief
executive of Elvis Presley Enterprises, which operates Graceland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we believe they're going to sit in a dark room for another
50 or 100 years and we can share them with the world so a homeless
family that was sleeping under a bridge can be part of a village,
we should do that.''
</P>
<P>
   A cluster of small homes to be called Presley Place will be
provided for families until they find permanent housing. The
building cost is projected at $1.2 million to $1.5 million, and it
is to be operated by the Metropolitan Interfaith Association in
Memphis, which will also provide counseling and job training for up
to a year.
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Presley lived with his parents for several years
in a federally sponsored Memphis housing project.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the items being auctioned are documents like record,
movie and performance contracts and letters. There will also be
such memorabilia as the saddle used on Rising Sun, one of Presley's
horses; personal 16-millimeter copies of some of his movies, and
artwork for his album covers.
</P>
<P>
   The items were selected by more than a dozen people from
Guernsey's and Graceland and others knowledgeable about popular
culture and Presley.
</P>
<P>
   The lots will be available for preview at the MGM Grand
beginning on Sept. 28. The expected auction dates are Oct. 8 to 10,
with a possible extension to Oct. 11. Buyers can bid online at
icollector.com or watch the auction live on the Internet at
Earthcam.com, said Ron Berkowitz, a spokesman for the auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are important documents, the likes of which have never
been offered before,'' said Arlan Ettinger, Guernsey's owner.
</P>
<P>
   The auction house sold Mark McGwire's 70th home run baseball in
January for a shade over $3 million. Last year it auctioned over
600 items from the Kennedy White House.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas was chosen for the auction because of Elvis'
identification with the city, Ettinger said. No minimum or upset
price has been set for the items, he said, adding that he expected
lot prices to range from ``extremely affordable'' to six figures.
The auction house says it is expecting buyers from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Guralnick, the author of an acclaimed two-volume Presley
biography, said the intense interest reflected the singer's
longtime loyalty to his fans as well as enthusiasm for his music
and what Presley represents historically and culturally.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents the triumph of American vernacular culture,''
Guralnick said.
</P>
</TEXT>
