<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGES-THEATER-REVIEW-N     06-02 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGES-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AGES OF MAN': MAN, DOWN THROUGH THE AGES (HIS OWN) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the stressed-out Manhattan mother in ``Infancy''
started reciting the alphabet, the multiplication tables and the
boroughs of New York to her infant son, all I could think of was
Diane Keaton's showing flash cards to her toddler in ``Baby Boom''
_ and of lots of competitive 1990s parents in real life. But this
play is set in Central Park in the 1920s, and the idea seemed to be
to calm the baby rather than prepare him early for the SATs.
</P>
<P>
   When Capt. Lemuel Gulliver landed on a remote island in
``Youth'' and learned that no one there was older than 29 because
citizens are put out to sea to die on their 30th birthdays, images
of Michael York and Jenny Agutter, young and doomed in the
futuristic science-fiction film ``Logan's Run,'' came to mind. That
70s movie had exactly the same premise (except that the leaders in
``Logan's Run'' had the populace convinced they'd be reincarnated).
</P>
<P>
   Odd associations like that are, unfortunately, the most
interesting aspects of the Willow Cabin Theater Company's
production of ``Thornton Wilder's `The Ages of Man.' '' These four
one-act plays are far from Wilder's best work and, for the most
part, neither the cast nor the director, Edward Berkeley, can make
them sparkle, but there are bright spots.
</P>
<P>
   John Bolger stands out as one of two man-size but
carriage-confined babies in ``Infancy,'' which includes a comic
suicide attempt on his part, and as Gulliver in ``Youth.''
``Infancy'' itself, the best of the four, is built on the theory
that babies understand adults and are trying so hard to learn that
they cry in frustration and grow suspicious of their caretakers
(``I think they don't want us to walk and to get good and get
better. They want us to stop.'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Youth,'' the 46-year-old protagonist marvels at the
shortcomings of an exclusively 20-something society (``To be young
and yet _ oh, ye immortal gods! _ to be without adventure of mind
or generosity of spirit!''). The other plays, ``Childhood,'' about
siblings who love to play games about funerals and orphans, and
``The Rivers Under the Earth,'' about a family at their beach house
reflecting on veiled memories and the past, have flashes of smart
Wilder observations (``I guess growing up is one long walk among
perils _ among yawning abysses,'' ``No one told me when I was a
bride that children are half crazy'') and whet the appetite for
something sustained.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ages of Man'' continues at the Blue Heron Arts Center
through June 13.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``THORTON WILDER'S `THE AGES OF MAN' ''
</P>
<P>
   Four one-act plays by Thornton Wilder; directed by Edward
Berkeley; sets by John Kasarda; costumes by Mary Nemecek Peterson;
lighting by Matthew McCarthy; assistant director, Cynthia Besteman;
production stage manager, Cynthia Tuohy; dialects by Leigh Dillon.
Presented by the Willow Cabin Theater Company, Berkeley, artistic
director; Fiona Davis, Maria Radman, Kenneth Favre, producing
directors. At the Blue Heron Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   `INFANCY' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With: Ken Forman (Patrolman Avonsino), Linda Powell (Miss Millie
Wilchick), Larry Gleason (Tommy), Angela Nevard (Mrs. Boker) and
John Bolger (Moe).
</P>
<P>
   `CHILDHOOD'
</P>
<P>
   With: Christine Radman (Caroline), Maria Radman (Dodie), Jed
Sexton (Billie), Ms. Nevard (Mother) and Gleason (Father).
</P>
<P>
   `YOUTH'
</P>
<P>
   With: Bolger (Lemuel Gulliver), Sarah Lively (Mistress Belinda
Jenkins), Ms. Powell (Lady Sibyl Ponsonby), Sexton (the Duke of
Cornwall) and Robert Harte (Simpson).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RIVERS UNDER THE EARTH'
</P>
<P>
   With: Ms. Maria Radman (Mrs. Carter), Harte (Tom), Ms. Lively
(Francesca) and Forman (Carter).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
