A0371 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-SPARROW-AR     06-02 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-SPARROW-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A TINY SPARROW, SOME SEE TEST OF EVERGLADES RESTORATION PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EVERGLADES NATIONAL PARK, Fla. _ Stuart Pimm stepped from a
helicopter in the middle of a saw-grass prairie, took off his heavy
white helmet and as the chopper pulled away began to sift the air
for the call of a sparrow, his educated ear sorting the feathery
whistles and clicks rising in the dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one there,'' he said, pointing, concentrating, raising
his clipboard to his ear. ``And a second there.'' The ecologist
paused, head down, eyes closed. ``Yes and a third in this
direction. A long way off.''
</P>
<P>
   The sparrows are hard to hear these days and even tougher to
spot. Because of human interference with the flow of water into the
Everglades, the object of Pimm's survey, the Cape Sable seaside
sparrow, is near extinction, along with other species, including
the American crocodile, the woodstork and the snail kite.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the plight of the sparrow reflects the failing
health of the Everglades ecosystem, a vast wetland wilderness
splintered by canals and dikes and threatened by urban development.
As Congress, in July, takes up a $7.8 billion engineering plan to
restore the swamplands to health, some environmentalists and
wildlife officials say the sparrow is the test of whether the plan
can succeed.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just that the breeding habits of the sparrow, a small
olive-drab bird that lives only in the national park, make it
vulnerable to even small disruptions to the Everglades' plumbing
system. The controversy surrounding the sparrow also reflects how
politically complicated and interconnected the problems in the
Everglades are, and how difficult any solution will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been described as the Everglades version of the canary in
the coal mine,'' said Steve Forsythe, the Fish and Wildlife
Service's supervisor in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Cape Sable seaside sparrow lives only in the Everglades in
the freshwater marl prairie on both sides of the Shark River
Slough, the ecosystem's critical artery. Its breeding cycle, like
that of many wetland birds, depends on the annual dry season, when
the shallow sheet of water that historically flowed south from Lake
Okeechobee through the wetlands retreats into the major sloughs.
</P>
<P>
   As the prairie dries, the sparrows build nests just four inches
above the ground between mid-March and mid-June. They need only 40
days to hatch eggs and fledge the young, but so few birds survive,
scientists say, they must breed twice each season to increase their
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But the bird's breeding habits have been severely disrupted by
the South Florida flood control system built since the 1940s,
combined with the Tamiami Trail, a highway across the northern
border of the national park.
</P>
<P>
   In the rainy season, dikes built along the edge of the
Everglades to keep Miami dry shift most of the water west, above
the Tamiami Trail. To relieve flooding there, state authorities
release water through gates in the highway miles west of the slough
where it once naturally flowed, flooding the sparrow's nests.
</P>
<P>
   During the dry seasons, when water is soaked up by irrigation
and urban use, the park drys out so much that the bird's habitat on
the east side of Shark River Slough burns up, scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1990s the sparrow's population had dropped sharply,
to 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The worst toll took place west of the slough, where flooding
reduced the population by 90 percent in the last 10 years,
scientists say. On the east side, the population has fallen nearly
60 percent since 1981, mostly because of fires. Only a third of the
population, near the Ingraham Highway, has remained viable.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build a nest four inches above the ground, and you
don't have a snorkel, you are in deep trouble,'' said Pimm, a
professor at the University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The problems occurred despite a plan Congress approved in 1989
to expand the park and improve its erratic flow of water, a plan
that many environmentalists consider the linchpin of the overall
program to save the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has been bogged down for 10 years in fights between
federal agencies, the Miccosukee Indian tribe, state water
authorities and homeowners near the park. That is not a good omen
for the larger project going to Congress now, which is intended to
restore the historic flow of water into the Everglades while
supplying South Florida's cities and farms with enough water for
the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 plan, known as the Modified Water Deliveries Project,
was to add 107,000 acres to the park and to relieve flooding and
improve wildlife habitats by sending more water into the Shark
River Slough, where it belonged.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to acquiring the additional acreage, a major
obstacle is a neighborhood of about 450 houses between the slough
and the dike that protects Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The area's homesteaders, many of them Cuban immigrants, bought
their land legally and have learned to put up with a fair amount of
seasonal flooding. But the shift of water back to the slough would
flood them out.
</P>
<P>
   The 1989 act directed the Corps of Engineers to build a
protective dike around the area, which covers 8.5 square miles. In
1992, the corps drew plans to do that.
</P>
<P>
   But the Parks Service objected, saying a better option would be
to buy out the homeowners and create a buffer zone between the
newly expanded park and Miami. Parks officials feared the
homeowners would eventually demand full flood protection and the
area would become a heavily developed suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, environmental groups have gained some protection for
the sparrow by threatening lawsuits under the Endangered Species
Act. State water managers have responded by keeping the excess
water above the Tamiami Trail, north of the bird's breeding
grounds, on lands controlled by the Miccosukee Indians. In
February, the Fish and Wildlife Service ruled that the sparrow was
in danger of extinction, legally forcing water managers to continue
keeping the breeding grounds dry.
</P>
<P>
   The Miccosukees complain that the government is killing the
wildlife on their land to save the sparrow. Floods in the last
three years have drowned more than 85 percent of the white tail
deer on islands in the reservation, a lawyer for the tribe, Dexter
Lehtinen, said.
</P>
<P>
   The Miccosukee accuse Pimm and others of exaggerating the
sparrow's situation, and the Department of the Interior of using
the sparrow's endangered status to gain legal leverage over the
Army Corps of Engineers and the South Florida Water Management
District.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The sparrow situation is a phony crisis,'' Lehtinen said.
``It's an abuse of the Endangered Species Act.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November after six years of studies and debate, the state
water authority agreed to buy out the homesteaders, voting to spend
$120 million. But many of the homeowners have refused to sell, and
some have sued the water authority. They have have won sympathy in
Dade County, where Cuban-Americans dominate the government, by
comparing the federal government's tactics to those of Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The county commission recently blocked the buyout, pending
resolution of the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The Miccosukees have jumped in on the side of the homeowners,
after deciding that building a dike around the settlement would be
the quickest way to resolve the dispute and get the floodwaters off
their lands.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The homeowners reject any notion that they are responsible for
the decline of the sparrow or the other endangered animals in the
park.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no connection between our living in our homes and the
health of the Cape Sable sparrow,'' said Madeleine Fortin, a
resident. ``They just use us as a whipping boy. When the Cape Sable
sparrow is flooded, we are flooded.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The federal government's program to add 107,000 acres has also
gone slowly. Most of the land, which is prone to flooding, is in
five-acre parcels that was sold to unsuspecting investors by
unscrupulous speculators in the 1950s and '60s. So far only half
the land has been acquired, and there are more than 1,000 private
owners who must still negotiate deals.
</P>
<P>
   For naturalists, the delays have been excruciating.
</P>
<P>
   Flying over the Shark River Slough in a helicopter recently,
Pimm and Sonny Bass, a Park Service ecologist, pointed out scarred
sections of earth where fires had burned what used to be wetlands.
Wading bird populations are less than 10 percent of what they were
50 years ago, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The sparrow, naturalists acknowledge, is not the most beautiful,
nor the most fascinating endangered species in the region. ``It is
sort of the rodent of the bird world,'' Bass joked.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most mornings in April and May, while the mist lays over the
swamps and the dawn lights up the cumulus clouds rolling over the
Florida Peninsula from the Gulf of Mexico, Pimm and Bass hopscotch
across the Everglades, counting sparrow calls. For each male bird's
song recorded, they count approximately 16 other birds. The data is
plotted on a map divided into square-kilometer sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a barometer of sorts,'' Bass said, as he jotted notes on
yet another spot with no sparrows. ``If the system's maintained,
then you maintain the sparrow.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pimm said the Endangered Species Act of 1973 is one of the few
levers that ecologists have to force government agencies to
preserve the wilderness. Naturalists used the spotted owl to save
old-growth forests in the Northwest, he said. The snail darter
became the standard-bearer for the entire ecosystem of the Little
Tennessee River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an issue about the species,'' he said. ``It's an
issue about the ecosystem on which it depends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
