<HEADLINE>
PALM VII PRICEY, LIMITED, BUT COOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY   c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The critics are right. The new ``Star Wars'' movie features
wooden acting and bad dialogue. I should know _ I've already seen
it twice.
</P>
<P>
   The critics are also right about 3Com Corp.'s new Palm VII
pocket data device. It's too expensive and offers a limited set of
features. But 3Com will sell heaps of them, regardless of the
critics.
</P>
<P>
   I won't shell out the necessary $600 _ 37 times the cost of my
two trips to the planet Naboo. I've a reputation for stinginess to
maintain, and I'd just as soon wait for the inevitable price drop.
Besides, the Palm VII is presently for sale only in the New York
area. Still, it's the first palm-sized machine that's actually
tempted me to spend some money.
</P>
<P>
   Regular readers know that I'm not a fan of personal digital
assistants. They have some value as electronic address books,
letting you store hundreds of phone numbers and a list of
appointments. But for this you don't need the pricey, heavy boxes
from 3Com or its rivals. The $99 credit-card-sized Franklin Rex is
quite good enough. Larger PDAs can also double as electronic
note-takers, but what's wrong with a pencil and paper?
</P>
<P>
   But the Palm VII transcends the limits of its predecessors by
adding a smidgen of interactivity. 3Com has crammed a radio
transceiver into a package almost exactly the same size as the
original Palm devices. With the cute plastic antenna extended, my
test unit worked perfectly, even inside the steel-and-concrete
walls of The Boston Globe. It snatched Internet data right out of
the air, and let me fire off brief messages to anybody with an
e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm VII uses a wireless data service that's available in
Boston and 259 other US cities. Users get access to a heap of
valuable on-line services _ news headlines from USA Today and the
Wall Street Journal, for instance. There's a nice applet from the
E-Trade on-line brokerage service that'll let you quickly check the
performance of your stock portfolio. The MapQuest driving
directions service, which can display the best route between point
A and point B, will delight newspaper photographers and others who
live on the road. And ``Star Wars'' buffs can use the Moviefone
applet to plan next weekend's viewings of ``The Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   The system also assigns you an address on Palm.net, 3Com's own
e-mail service, so you can send and receive messages. Writing on
any of the Palm PDAs is a tiresome business. You must either use a
special stylus to peck at the image of a keyboard, or you must
master Graffiti, a special writing method that enables the device
to recognize the human scrawl. I've never understood why anyone
would bother with all this just to jot down a phone number. But add
the ability to e-mail your notes, and it all makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's the unseemly price tag to consider _ and not just
for the device itself. You'll pay $10 a month for basic Palm.net
service, which limits you to a measly 50 kilobytes of data per
month. Extra kilobytes cost 30 cents each. A single downloaded
article from USA Today burns up one kilobyte, so heavy users will
burn through a small fortune in transmission costs. An ``extended''
service offering 150 kilobytes for $24.99 isn't much better.
</P>
<P>
   There are now hundreds of specialized programs that run on Palm
devices, but with a mere 2 megabytes of memory, the Palm VII won't
let you run too many of them. In this era of cheap memory chips, I
wonder why 3Com didn't squeeze in a few more.
</P>
<P>
   And why won't the Palm.net system let me check the contents of
my other e-mailboxes? There's a feature to gladden the heart of any
traveler. But it's not to be found here. You'll only get mail sent
to the Palm.net address. Maybe you can set up your office e-mail
system to forward your messages. If not, the Palm VII offers no
help.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the Palm VII is too expensive, too limited _ and too
cool. Its ability to send and receive data from almost anywhere
makes it the first such device that I'd consider a serious business
tool. The Palm VII's faults are like that floppy-eared alien in the
``Star Wars'' movie _ annoying, but not annoying enough to keep the
customers away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-27-99 1506EDT &QL;
</P>
