</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BLAME THE SOFTWARE
</HEADLINE>
 CPT- COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX 
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  DEAR DR.
BOMBAY: I think you should speak out against violent computer
games. My 13-year-old son is so absorbed in Doom I am afraid he may
suffer psychological harm.
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Concerned Mother
</P>
<P>
   DEAR CON: If you're really that worried, take away his computer
privileges or do a better job of overseeing what software he buys.
As I seem to recall, it's your job to help build his character, and
relinquishing that kind of power to the big shiny box on his desk
is no way to do that. Or are you afraid of not being a ``cool
mom''?
</P>
<P>
   And just because somebody plays Doom doesn't mean he's going to
go ballistic. First-person shooters can be fun if you're mature
enough to know they're about as much like real life as ``The Jerry
Springer Show.'' If you teach your kid that _ and get him to come
up for air once in a while _ he'll be OK.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I've got a Pentium 133 with about 400 megabytes
of available disk space, yet the thing is running a bit on the slow
side when you go from one program to another. I scan and defrag the
disk regularly and flush out all the temp files from the Internet
every day. I've also noticed that America Online 4.0 seems a lot
slower compared to 3.0.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slowpoke
</P>
<P>
   DEAR 'POKE: Available disk space doesn't have all that much to
do with how fast things run. You'll get the biggest bang for your
buck if you cram as much RAM as you can into the box.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the olden days, programs were a lot leaner and meaner.
Now, decreased speed is the penalty you pay for all that ease of
use and friendly graphics and singing icons. Microsoft Word seems
to get slower in each incarnation because they keep adding stuff to
it. The same is true of AOL. They're memory hogs.
</P>
<P>
   When Windows needs more memory than you have, it uses free hard
disk space to simulate RAM, but writing and reading all that data
to and from the disk is painfully slower than doing it to a chip.
And another thing: You say ``Pentium 133'' as if it's something to
be proud of. That's pretty marginal these days. See if you can
upgrade the processor.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I have an HP Vectra on which I have DOS and
Windows 3.11. I can't afford to do away with the DOS because I have
a 13-year-old database program with an enormous amount of records
that I don't want to redo in some newer program. Since you say that
Windows and Linux could be on one hard disk, could I do the same
with DOS and Windows?
</P>
<P>
   _Split Personality
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SPLIT: Forget what Microsoft tells you about Windows being
its own operating system. Windows is just a tarted-up DOS, and
there's really no reason to subdivide your drive to accommodate
both. Linux and Windows/DOS are radically different systems,
however, and they can't coexist in the same disk partition.
</P>
<P>
   You can get to DOS easily enough by clicking the MS-DOS Prompt
icon in the main program group. Assuming you have DOS 6 or so,
adding special commands into Config.sys and Autoexec.bat will allow
you to boot into either Windows or DOS, but that means you have to
get out the DOS manual. What, did you think I was going to do all
your work for you? They don't pay me enough for that. Go read the
manual.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay seems a bit cranky.
Maybe his editors should send him on an all-expenses-paid vacation
somewhere nice. Send your letters of support to
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com, via snail-mail to Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101, or fax: (817) 390-7257.
In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-99 1228EDT &QL;
</P>
