<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0603-C     06-02 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SENDING ADDED 7,000 U.S. TROOPS AS KOSOVO PEACEKEEPERS,
TO MEET ABOUT GROUND INVASION
 &HT;    900&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-TEAM-0603.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States would contribute 7,000 troops to
a NATO-led peacekeeping force in Kosovo, President Clinton said
Wednesday, raising by 75 percent the number of American soldiers
who would participate in such a mission.
</P>
<P>
   While moving forward with plans for peace, Clinton was also
preparing for a Thursday meeting with his top generals to discuss
the far riskier option of mounting a ground invasion of the
embattled Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear, though, whether an invasion of Kosovo sometime
later this summer was under serious consideration or whether the
option was being raised simply to increase the pressure on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic at a moment when both war and
diplomacy are intensifying.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Milosevic met for more than two hours to discuss a
peace plan proffered by Russia's envoy to the Balkans, Victor
Chernomyrdin, and Finland's president, Martti Ahtisaari. Ahtisaari
is the first Western leader to meet directly with Milosevic since
NATO launched air strikes against the Serb-dominated Yugoslav
government on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is a long way from announcing what sorts of
troops would be sent for a NATO peacekeeping force -- which would
total 47,868 troops from 30 NATO members and partner countries --
or which specific units might be part of any force that would be
deployed if peace can be brokered in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The boost in troop strength Clinton announced Wednesday,
however, reflected the increasingly difficult security environment
NATO planners envision in Kosovo since they prepared for a
peacekeeping force of just 28,000 troops before the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to discussions concerning the peacekeeping force,
the option of invading Kosovo will be on the table when Clinton
meets Thursday with the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the nation's top
military council.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that there will be a full range of discussions,
questions about whether or not there would be any kind of a ground
option for a non-permissive environment,'' said Defense Secretary
William Cohen, who will open Thursday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, as we have indicated on many occasions before, there is a
consensus for a strong air operation in the NATO countries,'' Cohen
said. ``There is not a consensus for a ground operation in a
non-permissive environment. So we intend to focus on the
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he is sending this week an additional 68 warplanes
and refueling tankers to further step up NATO's around-the-clock
air war against Serb military targets in Yugoslavia. The new
aircraft, part of a larger build-up announced last month, will
bring to 769 the number of U.S. planes involved in NATO attacks
that wound up their 10th inconclusive week on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have planes flying at all hours from every direction,
from bases in Italy, Germany, Hungary, Turkey, the United States
and from carriers at sea,'' Clinton said during commencement
remarks Wednesday at the Air Force Academy in Colorado Springs,
Colo. ``If we have the patience and determination to match the
courage and skill of our men and women in uniform, we will achieve
our goals.''
</P>
<P>
   With continued bombing as a backdrop, Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari
struggled with the difficult business of diplomacy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Finland is not a NATO member but is one of a group of countries
that cooperates with the alliance through its post-Cold War
``Partnership for Peace,'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari carried a peace proposal to Milosevic
calling for an end to a Serb military campaign targeting ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo, a withdrawal of Serb forces from the province
and the acceptance of an international security force to safeguard
the return of an estimated 1.5 million refugees forced to flee
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The envoys were scheduled to meet again on Thursday with
Milosevic. He has said he would accept a lightly armed United
Nations peacekeeping mission, but has so far rejected the U.S. and
NATO position that any peacekeeping force must have NATO at its
core.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said it was
``a significant step forward,'' that Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari
were able to agree on enough of the elements of a peace plan to
present a united front to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are going to be reading from the same script. I
think that that is important,'' Albright told reporters at the
State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question that remains to be answered is how Milosevic
will react,'' Albright said. ``The ball is in his court . . . we're
just going to have to see how he reacts to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism over the diplomatic track was tempered, though, by
continuing differences between NATO and Russia -- Yugoslavia's
closest ally -- over the composition and conduct of a Kosovo
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and its NATO allies have insisted that such a
force could include troops from Russia and other non-NATO countries
but it would be led by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will have a NATO command and control structure, it will
have robust NATO rules of engagement, and NATO certainly will be,
if you like, the central tent pole around which the force will be
built,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, however, told reporters that Russia was not
contemplating placing its troops under NATO control.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be two separate presences in Kosovo -- a NATO
presence and a Russian presence,'' Chernomyrdin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Shea rejected that formulation, however, suggesting that it
could lead to a partitioning of Kosovo into Serb areas, monitored
by Russian troops, and non-Serb areas overseen by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a single force, not a number of different
forces,'' Shea said. ``We are not going to do anything which could
increase the chances of some sort of partition, whether virtual or
real.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Without saying so specifically, U.S. and NATO officials also
alluded to the possibility that fighting could break out between
NATO and Russian forces under the formulation Chernomyrdin
described.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be unity of command for this to be really
effective, in order for it not to slip down a slippery slope into
partition, ineffectiveness or worse,'' Deputy Secretary of State
Strobe Talbott told reporters in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Against the background of diplomatic efforts, NATO pilots
reported their greatest success to date against fielded
Serb-dominated Yugoslav forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Under attack by the Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA, Serb troops
and police have been forced to mass near the Albanian border in
recent days to counterattack. As they have done so, Serb tanks,
artillery and military vehicles have been targeted by withering
aerial bombardments.
</P>
<P>
   In the area near Mount Pastrik, along Kosovo's southwestern
border with Albania, NATO planes flew nearly 150 bombing runs on
Tuesday alone, striking 15 armored vehicles, 40 artillery or mortar
pieces, four other military vehicles and a surface-to-air missile
site.
</P>
<P>
   The area around Mount Pastrik has become a shooting gallery for
NATO pilots, who have set up what's called a ``hog pen'' -- a sort
of aerial holding zone -- for A-10 ``Warthog'' attack jets along
the Albanian-Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO air commanders spot or otherwise learn where Serb forces
are located in the field, A-10s, built to destroy tanks, scream out
of the hog pen for a strike, often within minutes of a sighting,
Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, an alliance spokesman, told reporters in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current Serbian counter-offensive against the (KLA) around
Mount Pastrik
</P>
<P>
   offers NATO the best opportunity so far in the air campaign to
hit Serb forces hard,'' said Jertz. ``Because these forces have had
to come out of their camouflaged positions, they have become more
visible.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO pilots have flown some 32,000 sorties against Serb military
targets to counter a campaign of repression targeting ethnic
Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has described the repression as anti-terrorist
activities -- Belgrade regards the KLA as a terrorist organization
-- that got out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
