<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 SE CLEARS THINGS UP
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   In late 1996, Microsoft upgraded Windows 95 with a new version
that included, among other features, a new file system that gave
users more space on a hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that tantalizing option, Windows 95 OSR2 was not
available to most PC users.
</P>
<P>
   That's because it was only sold with a new machine or, in some
cases, a new hard drive. Microsoft argued that most of its new
features were only applicable to newer machines. Thus, if you
wanted a better Windows, you also had to buy a better computer.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows faithful were not amused. I suspect OSR2 became one
of the most-pirated operating systems of all times, as folks with
older machines discovered their neighbors brought home a new
computer _ complete with a Windows 95 install CD. ``Hey, Bill,
wanna come over for a beer? And say, bring your Win95 disk with ya.
How 'bout it?''
</P>
<P>
   Now Microsoft has updated Windows 98, and clearly has learned
from its past mistake. Windows 98 SE (Second Edition) will not only
replace the current boxes of Windows 98 now on store shelves, but
users of existing Windows 98 systems will be able to order a $20
upgrade CD via Microsoft's Web site in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MODEM-SHARING MADE EASY
</P>
<P>
   I've been using Windows 98 SE for several weeks. While it's
certainly not as compelling an upgrade as Windows 98 was from
Windows 95, it's definitely worth considering, particularly if you
currently have or plan to add a home network.
</P>
<P>
   The installation process is virtually identical to that for the
original Windows 98. In fact, I had to check to make sure I wasn't
reinstalling my old version.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you update an operating system, you run the risk of
breaking something else on the computer. Sure enough, installing
Windows 98 SE on my PC gave me problems with my Turtle Beach
Montego II sound card _ some games invoked the Blue Screen of Death
when I tried to run them. Reinstalling the sound card's drivers
fixed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   (Obligatory safety warning: Whenever you upgrade your operating
system, back up your key data files and make sure you have all the
latest drivers for your hardware at the ready.)
</P>
<P>
   If the FAT32 file system was the big deal with Windows 95 OSR2,
then Internet connection sharing is the main attraction for Windows
98 SE. If you have PCs connected via a network, this lets one
computer act as the conduit to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Those who promote home networks as the next wave in consumer
computing tout modem-sharing as the ``killer app'' for linking PCs
around the house. While I think higher-speed connections such as
cable modems will make modem-sharing obsolete, it's nice to have
this feature built into the Windows operating system while waiting
for the future to get here.
</P>
<P>
   When you install the modem-sharing feature, a simple wizard pops
up that asks a few questions about your computer and how you want
other machines to use its modem. At the end, you're asked to put a
blank disk in your floppy drive, and the wizard places a program on
the disk that's used to configure other PCs on the network.
</P>
<P>
   The sharing feature works well enough in most cases. However, if
you have an unusual setup in which your Internet provider has given
you a fixed numeric address (most dial-up connections assign a
random address upon log-on), you may run into problems. This is
because Windows changes the address of your machine so that the
others on the network know how to talk to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MAKING PEACE WITH USB PORTS
</P>
<P>
   Among the other features in Windows 98 SE is better support for
Universal Serial Bus, or USB, devices. Windows 95 OSR2 had support
for USB, but it was lousy. The original Windows 98's USB support
improved dramatically, but still choked occasionally. So far, I've
found the USB support in the SE version to be rock-solid.
</P>
<P>
   The new OS also comes with Internet Explorer 5, which I believe
currently to be the best Web browser available (See
www.chron.com/content/chronicle/tech/99/03/26/compute.html). If
you've been holding off getting IE5 because of the amount of time
it would take to download the browser via the Net, getting it along
with this operating system upgrade is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   There are other benefits _ a new version of NetMeeting,
Microsoft's Internet phone program; support for IEEE 1394, also
known as FireWire and iLink, a high-speed connection found on some
new computers; and, of course, numerous bug fixes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the fixes, by the way, already have been posted to the
Windows Update area of Microsoft's Web site. A Windows 98 Service
Pack will be posted soon that rounds all these up, and adds a few
more that are part of the Second Edition.
</P>
<P>
   One new feature that Microsoft has not touted but I think is
excellent is that some error messages are linked to help files. I
discovered this when my modem tried to connect and got no dial
tone. In previous versions of Windows, there's a cryptic message
that says ``No dial tone.'' With Windows 98 SE, however, I got a
button that took me to a modem trouble shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Is this new version of Windows 98 a must-have? Certainly, if you
still have Windows 95 or, heaven forbid, Windows 3.1, and have been
holding off making the move to 98, then yes, this OS is for you.
Ditto if you have a home network and don't have multiple phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you've already upgraded to Internet Explorer 5; have
kept up with the various patches Microsoft's released for Windows
98; don't have any USB problems; don't have a FireWire port on your
computer; and you don't have an in-home network and have no plans
for one, then probably not. Just grab the Windows 98 Service Pack
when it comes out and get on with life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-28-99 1510EDT &QL;
