<HEADLINE>
AOL CONNECTION LETS USERS BROWSE WITH REGULAR INTERNET SOFTWARE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I have a computer that has Netscape Communicator set up as
the browser for my Internet service provider. However, I have AOL
now, but I still want to use Netscape with it. How do I go about
changing from AOL's browser to Communicator?
</P>
<P>
   A: In most cases, this is much easier to do than most people
realize.
</P>
<P>
   When you connect to America Online, you are using the same kind
of connection you'd use with any other Internet provider. That
means you can use other software for accessing the Internet when
you log on to AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Simply launch Netscape Communicator _ or Microsoft's Internet
Explorer, if you prefer _ and use it. That's all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   There is one caveat, however. If you previously were using
another Internet provider, it's possible that you were required to
configure Communicator to go through a firewall _ a piece of
security software designed to keep hackers out of your provider's
system. If Communicator is set up to look for certain firewall
settings for your previous provider, then it won't work with AOL.
</P>
<P>
   To undo those settings, go to Edit, then Preferences, then
Advanced, then Proxies. Click on ``Direct connection to the
Internet.'' That will turn off the firewall settings.
</P>
<P>
   The settings will still be in place, in case you want to go back
to your old provider. Just recheck the item there that enables the
proxy connection.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am curious and confused. Is it a good idea to dump the
contents of the Windows temporary folder? It can get quite large
and I am not sure how often and at what intervals that Windows will
dump it automatically. I am a neat nut and I don't like unneeded
stuff on my hard drive _ but I don't want to do something that
might present a problem either. I seem to have enough without
provoking any more.
</P>
<P>
   A: Unlike the Recycle Bin, which is actually a folder with an
adjustable limit as to the number of items it can hold, the Windows
temporary folder (usually windowstemp) doesn't get ``dumped.'' This
is something you have to do yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The temporary folder is a kind of staging area where programs
place temporary files. For example, if you install new software,
the components of that program are often compressed, and must be
expanded before they can be installed. When you run the install
routine, the components are placed into this temporary folder
before they are moved or copied into their permanent folder.
</P>
<P>
   However, not all programs clean up after themselves like they
should, leaving digital detritus in the temporary folder. It's a
good idea to check in there about once a month and delete its
contents.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful, though, not to delete any temporary files that are
currently in use. But how can you tell what's being used?
</P>
<P>
   Right-click in the folder, choose View, then Details. Click on
the Modified bar that appears at the top of the list, and the files
will sort themselves by date and time. If you see any files that
were created in the past hour or so don't delete them. If you want
to be extra safe, don't delete anything created that day, unless it
happens to be the leftovers of a software installation.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else can go.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My computer's modem will sometimes connect in the middle of
the night. This bothers my sleeping wife. How can I turn off the
modem sound?
</P>
<P>
   A: Go to the Windows Control Panel, and click on Modems. Choose
your modem from the list that appears, then click Properties.
</P>
<P>
   You'll see a panel that includes a volume slider. Move it all
the way to the left, to the Off position.
</P>
<P>
   On some computers, the modem sound is controlled in the same way
that other sounds are _ via the speaker icon found in the system
tray. If the previous strategy doesn't work, double-click on the
speaker icon and look for a modem volume control there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
