<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-ART-NY     06-02 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHDRAWAL OF MILITIA WILL MARK TURNING POINT FOR ISRAEL AND
LEBANON
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEZZIN, Lebanon _ If all goes as planned, members of the
Israeli-backed militia that has long occupied this pretty
mountaintop town will head south in the next few days, completing
their withdrawal from an enclave that has served for 14 years, in
proxy, as Israel's deepest penetration into Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal is seen by many in Lebanon and Israel as a
test-run for the full-scale withdrawal from southern Lebanon that
has been promised by Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak. But
whether that proves to be the case may depend on whether the
withdrawal brings peace and security, or a new wave of killings.
</P>
<P>
   Among those waiting to see what happens next is Youssef, a
10-year veteran with the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army, who has
decided stay behind when his fellow soldiers leave. Youssef said he
has grown weary after years in which being on Israel's payroll has
meant seeing dozens of friends and relatives killed by Hezbollah
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   The persistence of Hezbollah, or Party of God, in fighting the
Israeli occupiers has made service here a worsening nightmare for
Israelis and their Lebanese allies alike. But under Lebanese law,
Youssef is a traitor who could face a death sentence, and to
Hezbollah, he is an enemy, a potential target for a settling of
scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be hiding in the bushes, waiting to see who comes to
Jezzin,'' said Youssef, 27, Wednesday at the entrance to the town,
which the militiamen had sealed off from reporters as they made
final preparations to leave. Their commander, Gen. Antoine Lahd,
has declared that the mounting toll of casualties being inflicted
by Hezbollah had made further occupation untenable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's the Lebanese government, I think that will be OK,''
said Youssef, who would give only his first name. ``But if it's
Hezbollah, that would be trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500-strong South Lebanon Army, mostly Christians, has been
a vital partner for Israel and 1,500 Israeli soldiers in
maintaining the nine-mile-wide strip that Israel has occupied since
1985 as a ``security zone'' against attack from guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Israeli forces in Jezzin, which lies in a
35-square-mile mountain salient that extends well north of the
occupied zone. But the withdrawal by the Lebanese militia _ armed,
paid and supplied by Israel, down to their dark green Israeli-style
uniforms _ is the first significant boundary change in southern
Lebanon in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   And because Israel has said any withdrawal by its own forces
must be preceded by security guarantees from Lebanon and from
Syria, the main power broker here, the withdrawal under way in
Jezzin is being described by many people in Israel, including those
close to Barak, as a kind of litmus test.
</P>
<P>
   Outgoing Defense Minister Moshe Arens said on the Israel radio
the other day: ``If the Lebanese enter Jezzin and prevent Hezbollah
from taking over the area, it's a good sign for the future. But if
Hezbollah seizes the enclave, it's a sign that the Syrians let this
happen, and that will tell us something of their intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Hezbollah's leader, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah, has
promised that his forces would not enter Jezzin once the Lebanese
militia leaves. But Hezbollah fighters have continued to harass the
militiamen even as they have pulled back from outlying villages,
and the guerrillas set off a roadside bomb in the center of Jezzin
on Tuesday that killed two South Lebanon Army fighters.
</P>
<P>
   That attack had clearly sharpened the anxiety among fighters who
stood guard Wednesday afternoon at the entrance to the town,
beneath a white religious statue labeled Our Lady of the Crossing
and a banner that identified Jezzin as ``The Bride of the
Waterfall.'' Approaching cars that were deemed to be suspicious
were greeted with warning shots that echoed loudly across a
plunging ravine.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 157 SLA militiamen have been killed while holding the
town and surrounding villages since Israel invaded in 1982. During
that time, more than half the fighters stationed here have
surrendered to the Lebanese government, and the population of the
town has dwindled to 5,000, from about 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government, wary of being seen as restraining
Hezbollah, which it regards as a legitimate resistance force, has
so far refused to say whether it intends to send its own forces to
Jezzin after the withdrawal. Nor has Lebanon said whether it
intends to grant any amnesty to soldiers like Youssef, who a local
priest said was among more than 200 militiamen who have made it
known that they intend to stay after their colleagues depart.
</P>
<P>
   That withdrawal could take place as early as tonight, one
militia commander said, with the militiamen climbing into their
tanks and armored personnel carriers and traveling south to Kafr
Hunah, a town at the edge of the occupation zone that is expected
to become the militia's new base.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of members of the militia, including Lahd, have been
tried and sentenced to death in absentia on charges of treason. But
several prominent residents of Jezzin said Wednesday that they
thought it important that the Lebanese government now adopt a more
forgiving stand, particularly toward young militiamen, who they
said had been essentially conscripted into service.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be a clear mechanism on how to deal with these
people,'' said Edmond Rizik, a former member of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   He and other suggested that punishing militiamen too harshly
might leave them with the conviction that they had no other option
but to continue their fight. The Rev. Adel Alam, a priest at a
Maronite Christian monastery in nearby Machmouch, said the
monastery would open its doors to militiamen and their families to
provide temporary sanctuary from reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   Lahd has said that the militia was withdrawing because his
troops in Jezzin ``could no longer endure more slow deaths.'' He
has promised that the pullout will be completed by mid-June; the
local commander, a major who would not give his name, said the
withdrawal, which began Sunday, was already ``halfway through.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the militiamen interviewed at the entrance to Jezzin
appeared downcast. Those who said they were planning to join in the
withdrawal said they had already sent their wives and children
south, to Marjayoun, in the Israeli-occupied zone.
</P>
<P>
   All said it would be wrong for the Lebanese government to charge
any of them with treason; with a long history of internecine
warfare, they said, Lebanon should have learned to be more
forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is calling us collaborators, but we're like any
Lebanese,'' said the militia commander, who was juggling both an
assault rifle and a mobile phone. ``We're the people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
