<HEADER>
A0421 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAPPINGS-     06-02 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-KIDNAPPINGS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVE OF KIDNAPPINGS SPREAD INTO COLOMBIA'S MIDDLE CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia _ The school Melba Martinez's daughter attends
doesn't go on field trips anymore. Alirio Lopez no longer returns
to the village where he was born to visit his parents on weekends.
Elber Espino leaves his new car at home and switches to his wife's
old compact anytime he has to drive out to the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Colombia's elite has lived in constant fear of being
kidnapped by guerrilla groups that are fighting the government of
this South American nation of 40 million people. But now a new kind
of mass and indiscriminate abduction is spreading that terror among
ordinary citizens who cannot afford the protection of bodyguards
and armored cars.
</P>
<P>
   The practice is known as ``miraculous fishing.'' A band of
guerrillas appears out of nowhere, sets up a roadblock on a main
highway, stops every car or bus that happens along, takes away all
the passengers who seem likely to have a healthy bank account, a
good job or a prominent name, and holds them captive until a hefty
ransom is paid.
</P>
<P>
   The term ``miraculous fishing,'' or ``pesca milagrosa'' in
Spanish, takes its name from a popular Colombian children's game
that is traditionally played at birthday parties and on holidays.
For generations here, excited youngsters have been reaching into
barrels with a hook or their bare hands to pull out gifts whose
identity is not known in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is terrible that something so frightening should be given
the name of something so pure and beautiful,'' said Luz Marlene
Sierra Mayorga, a 38-year-old engineer here. ``It is one more sign
that we Colombians have lost our innocence and joy in life.''
</P>
<P>
   In a new and alarming variation on the practice of mass
kidnappings of civilians, at least 30 guerrillas from the National
Liberation Army invaded a church service in an upper-class
neighborhood in Cali last Sunday and abducted more than 140
worshipers. About 60 people are still being held in the rugged
Andean mountains outside the city, where the government has
deployed more than 3,000 soldiers and police officers to locate
them.
</P>
<P>
   Precise statistics on the number of victims of fishing
expeditions are hard to come by, in part because many families and
businesses prefer to deal directly with kidnappers and not report
abductions to the police. But a report issued by the government's
anti-kidnapping office in May calculated that at least 4,925 people
have been abducted since January 1996, with the largest total
coming in 1998, after the advent of ``miraculous fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   The government report estimated that two-thirds of the
kidnappings were carried out by left-wing guerrilla groups,
principally the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC,
and the National Liberation Army, or ELN Ordinary criminal gangs
accounted for 20 percent of the abductions and right-wing
paramilitary groups for one percent, while the source of the rest
is listed as ``undetermined.''
</P>
<P>
   The hijacking of a propeller-driven passenger plane on a short
run from Bucaramanga to Bogota on April 12 heightened kidnapping
fears. The guerrillas that carried out the operation have not
demanded a monetary ransom for 25 passengers they continue to hold
at a jungle base, calling instead for the government to cede it
control of a safe haven zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the plane hijacking, people thought that they were at
least safe in the air,'' said Manuel Sanabria, a 46-year-old
advertising executive here. ``But now we know that is not true,
that you are in danger any time you travel anywhere in this
country, whether it is on the road or in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sierra, interviewed at a anti-kidnapping rally here early in
May, knows from bitter personal experience just how injurious an
abduction can be to a family. Her father was kidnapped and killed
by ordinary criminals 15 years ago, and her older brother Alvaro,
also an engineer, was among 41 passengers on the hijacked Avianca
Airlines prop flight; he was later freed.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Juan Carlos Mejia, a 38-year-old dentist, has
begun refusing to fly on any airplane that is not a jet. ``The
flight that the ELN fished was one of those prop planes, but it is
almost impossible for guerrillas to take over a big jet and make it
land at some little strip out in the jungle,'' he reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martinez, whose 7-year-old daughter no longer goes on field
trips, said: ``Really, you have to think twice before you go
anywhere these days. It makes life a lot more tense. It's like
living under siege, surrounded by an unknown, invisible enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During the week before Easter, a traditional vacation time
throughout Latin America, travel within Colombia was down 40
percent over last year, according to Camilo Gonzalez Pozo, director
of Citizen Mandate for Peace, a civic group. With increasing
regularity, the five million residents of this Andean capital are
canceling trips to towns that are barely a two-hour drive away,
while traffic on highways to the Caribbean coast has also dropped
significantly.
</P>
<P>
   A list of victims compiled by the Free Country Foundation, a
civic group dedicated to combat kidnapping, includes doctors,
accountants, surveyors, farmers, lawyers, pilots, engineers,
students and teachers. The oldest person kidnapped was 77, while
the youngest was just one day old.
</P>
<P>
   Even a 19-member mariachi orchestra, Grupo Garibaldi, was taken
captive at a roadblock in Santander Province last fall and held for
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon appears to have taken root as a result of the
successes that guerrilla groups, especially the Revolutionary Armed
Forces of Colombia, have enjoyed in the field in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   By most estimates, insurgent groups now either control or
operate openly in more than one-third of Colombia's territory,
giving them the capacity to strike almost at will and to evade the
Colombian army, but simultaneously increasing their need for money
to pay for their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mounting public disgust with and clamor against the
abductions, guerrilla leaders have made it clear that they do not
intend to abandon the practice. A government study released here on
May 10 estimates that the country's three main guerrilla groups
have obtained more than $1.2 billion in kidnapping ransoms in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``So long as it continues, the war must be financed,'' a FARC
commander who uses the pseudonym Raul Reyes said in an interview
with a television station here in May. After all, he continued,
``the state levies taxes on companies in the countryside, the
cities and even on international enterprises.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's anti-kidnapping czar, Jorge Alfredo Escobar,
did not respond to repeated calls to his office and cellular
telephones requesting an interview to discuss the phenomenon. But
in an interview here in early May, the minister of defense, Rodrigo
Lloreda Caicedo, said that President Andres Pastrana recognizes
that ``miracle fishing has become a fad,'' is ``very depressed
about this,'' and is intent on ``taking back the roads of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 26, Lloreda resigned, saying he opposed Pastrana's
decision to grant the FARC indefinite control of a
Switzerland-sized territory in order to induce them to engage in
peace talks. In remarks to reporters, Lloreda suggested the
guerrillas were taking advantage of their uncontested control of
the region to build up weapons caches, engage in drug trafficking
and house their kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
   The Free Country Foundation has published tips to avoid
kidnapping: ``Do not carry identification or emblems of the site or
company where you work. Arrange with your traveling companions and
fellow employees to adopt an identity that is `lower profile,'
since you quite possibly will be taken prisoner if your captors
realized that you hold a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miraculous fishing is intended not just to raise money, but to
generate fear and create an atmosphere of war, and that is what it
is doing,'' said Santos, the head of the organization. ``More and
more, people throughout the country are feeling that the
perpetrators of this have put all of us in jail.''
</P>
</TEXT>
