<P>
   TONY-AWARDS (New York) _ When did Broadway become the provinces?
The suspicion has been hovering for several decades, now that the
once-sophisticated mecca of American theater is really just a mall
in Squaresville: a forum for automated theme park shows, with doses
of high culture provided by visitors from more adventurous places.
All the same, when the Tony Award nominations were announced last
month, they seemed to offer especially disheartening confirmation
of the idea, giving off what Lorenz Hart once described as ``the
faint aroma of performing seals.'' It's not that there won't be
things to celebrate at the Gershwin Theater Sunday night, when the
awards are handed out. (The live telecast will begin at 8 p.m. on
PBS for one hour, followed by two hours on CBS.) By Ben
Brantley. &UR;  &LR; (Moved). Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   END-OF-AFFAIR-FILM (London) _ The remake of Graham Greene's
``End of the Affair'' by the screenwriter and director Neil Jordan
has recently finished its six-week shoot in various spots around
England, including London, where streets were turned back into
those of wartime and its aftermath. The movie, which is tentatively
scheduled for release at the end of the year, stars Ralph Fiennes
as Maurice Bendrix, the jealous novelist who falls passionately in
love with a married woman and whose tortured narration describes
the sad unraveling of the affair. Julianne Moore plays Bendrix's
lover, Sarah Miles, a woman who makes a devil's bargain with God
himself. And Stephen Rea, the melancholy staple of Jordan films,
plays Henry, Sarah's husband, whose asexual dullness conceals a
deep reservoir of emotion. By Sarah Lyall. (Moved).  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-CLUB-FILM (Undated) _ A sadness permeates Wim Wenders's
new film, ``Buena Vista Social Club.'' The documentary covers the
lives and recent unexpected success of a group of elderly Cuban
musicians _ nearly forgotten in their own country _ who banded
together under the direction of the American musician Ry Cooder and
did the improbable: recorded an international hit album. By Peter
Watrous. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COWARD-THEATER (New York) _ His name notwithstanding, he missed
being born on Christmas by more than a week. His name
notwithstanding, he was a brave man, brave enough to fire off
epigrams for the West End in London in the wake of Oscar Wilde. The
world has not forgotten Noel Coward (eventually Sir Noel),
playwright of ``Hay Fever'' and ``Private Lives,''
composer-lyricist of ``Mad About the Boy'' and ``Mad Dogs and
Englishmen,'' unmatched interpreter of his own mischief. Sheridan
Morley, the London theater critic for The Spectator and Playbill,
summed up Coward's genius in the title of his biography, the first:
``A Talent to Amuse.'' Coward died in 1973. Were he alive, he would
be celebrating his 100th birthday on Dec. 16. One of many
observances on either shore of the Atlantic this centennial year,
Morley's Off Broadway valentine, ``If Love Were All,'' opens on
Thursday at the Lucille Lortel Theater. By Matthew Gurewitsch.
(Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTE/BROWN-DANCE (New York) _ Ms. Elisa Monte, who left Martha
Graham's company in 1982 to run her own troupe, has taken an
unusual step by sharing artistic direction equally with her spouse,
the former Graham dancer David Brown. On Tuesday, when the company
long known as Elisa Monte Dance opens a two-week season at the
Joyce Theater, the marquee for the first time will read Monte/Brown
Dance. The dancers will perform three new works by Brown along with
two by Ms. Monte. The couple shares credit for a sixth new piece,
``Run to the Rock,'' a rhapsodic solo danced to Nina Simone's husky
rendition of ``Sinnerman.'' By Christopher Reardon. (Moved).
Photo. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SANFRAN-MUSIC (Berkeley, Calif.) _ They probably didn't plan it
that way, but San Francisco's leading classical-music organizations
will come into an interesting collision this week. At the War
Memorial Opera House, the San Francisco Opera will stir up pagan
ecstasy with several complete cycles of Richard Wagner's ``Ring of
the Nibelung,'' beginning on Wednesday. Meanwhile, beginning on
Thursday across the street at Davies Symphony Hall, and in a couple
of other spots around town (including a Roman Catholic church),
Michael Tilson Thomas and the San Francisco Symphony will celebrate
the life and times of Igor Stravinsky, who loved to bill himself as
Wagner's Antichrist, and for whom the ``Ring,'' with its ``miasmic
vapors'' and its labyrinth of leitmotifs, amounted to nothing more
than ``a sort of vast musical city directory.'' By Richard
Taruskin. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WAGNER-RING (Undated) _ Once again, the Wagnerites are
descending on San Francisco for the four-day spiritual adventure
that is the ``Ring of the Nibelung,'' offered in four overlapping
cycles, beginning on Wednesday. The production, unveiled in 1985,
last saw service in 1990. Of the original principals, the Wotan of
James Morris remains. Along with the new cast of other gods,
giants, dwarves and assorted demigods _ among them, the redoubtable
Jane Eaglen as Brunnhilde _ the current edition also introduces a
new director, Andrei Serban. By Matthew Gurewitsch. (Moved). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STRAVINSKY-MUSIC (Undated) _ Recordings of Igor Stravinsky
conducting his own music date from as early as 1928, when he was 46
and had few doubts about his own significance. The composer
continued to record his works until 1966, five years before his
death. He was especially active in the studio during the 1950s and
early 60s, when Columbia invited him to record virtually his
complete operatic, orchestral, choral and larger chamber works
under optimal conditions as a lasting legacy. The strengths and
weaknesses of Stravinsky's conducting, and consequently, the value
of these recordings as guides, have been variously debated. To me,
in terms of archival importance, this discography, especially the
Columbia recordings now reissued by Sony Classical, is the greatest
landmark in the history of recorded music from the classical
tradition. By Anthony Tommasini. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LUMUMBA-ART (New York) _ ``A Congo Chronicle: Patrice Lumumba in
Urban Art,'' is on view at the Museum for African Art in SoHo
through Aug. 15. It is a compact and moving show of paintings of
the young firebrand politician of the former Belgian Congo that
explores complex ways in which the image of a cultural hero is both
recorded and reinvented during his lifetime and after his death. By
Holland Cotter. (Moved).
</P>
