<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO SIGN $500 MILLION TAX RELIEF BILL  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush will visit Houston on
Thursday to sign into law a bill that will deliver more than $500
million in promised tax relief to consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The young men's section of the downtown Foley's department store
will be the backdrop for the 4 p.m. CST bill-signing ceremony,
which will give Texans a three-day reprieve each August from the
8.25 percent sales tax on clothes and shoes. The bill mandates a
permanent exemption from sales taxes on Internet connections and
nonprescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The tax breaks were embodied in Senate Bill 441 by Sen. Rodney
Ellis, D-Houston, who will accompany Bush at the bill-signing. The
legislation was a hard-fought compromise approved the day before
the 76th legislative session ended Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's, a regional retail store, was among the Texas businesses
whose representatives registered in favor of Ellis' bill at Senate
hearings. Merchants across the state expect to reap substantial
profits as a result of the bill, though Ellis said everyday
taxpayers should be the main beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan will provide tax relief to all Texans, but
particularly those most in need. It could mean a free pair of shoes
for a child. That's a real tax cut Texas families can feel and
understand,'' Ellis said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the bill is a key component to the $2.6 billion in
overall tax relief he promised during his 1998 re-election
campaign. He wound up getting just $1.85 billion of that from the
just-ended session.
</P>
<P>
   Tax experts are still deciphering the implications of the
40-page bill. But what's undisputed is that the first sales tax
holiday will be Aug. 6-8; the Internet tax break takes hold in
October, and savings on over-the-counter drugs won't be felt until
spring 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Some Texas merchants are already bracing for the commotion
likely to surround the three-day sales tax holiday on clothes and
shoes. After hearing how cash registers sang when other states
enacted similar laws, they're eager for the holiday to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a quick learning curve,'' said Texas Retailers
Association president Mickey Moore, whose group represents 1,500
companies, including giants such as Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from the experience we've seen in New York and Florida,
this is going to be a huge selling period _ particularly since
we've compressed it into three days,'' he said. Florida's lasted a
week, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers will promote very heavily for this and will reduce
prices on a good number of items,'' Moore predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a customer has $100 to spend on clothing, and that's all,
the merchant will sell $100 worth of merchandise, not $92.50 or
whatever it would be if you had to take the tax out. So in round
numbers, it's an immediate 8 percent increase in sales for the
retailer,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some answers about the various tax breaks:
</P>
<P>
   Q: When is the ``sales tax holiday''and what items are included
and excluded?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bill states that the exemptions on ``clothes and
footwear'' will apply from 12:01 a.m. on the first Friday in August
until 12 midnight the following Sunday. This year that means Aug.
6-8.
</P>
<P>
   For an item to be exempt under the legislation, it must sell for
less than $100. Retailers are likely to lower prices on some items
to below $100 in order to qualify them for exemption. Not included
in the tax exemption are athletic shoes and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Also not exempt are accessories such as jewelry, handbags and
umbrellas. Although lawmakers initially sought to limit the
exemptions to children's clothing and shoes, they were unable to
come up with a workable way of doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't define children's clothing. That was too big a
burden on the retailer to deal with,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Won't the state sales tax breaks lower revenues for cities
and other taxing entities?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes. And if they insist, local taxing jurisdictions can
repeal the tax breaks, but only their share. The tax bill allows
the governing body of a taxing authority, by a majority vote, to
repeal any of the sales tax exemptions beginning in fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The state sales tax rate is 6.25 percent, and local taxing
entities can add up to 2 percent more, making the maximum sales tax
8.25 percent. If a city, transit authority or other taxing entity
opts out, they can only collect up to 2 percent sales tax. Because
of the confusion such a move might cause, some lawmakers and
private groups are discouraging repeals.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is meant by ``nonprescription medicines,'' and when does
that exemption take effect?
</P>
<P>
   A: Beginning April 1, 2000 _ the effective date was delayed to
postpone the fiscal impact _ the sales tax exemption on
over-the-counter drugs will take effect.
</P>
<P>
   It will apply to any drug or medicine ``that is labeled with a
national drug code issued by the federal Food and Drug
Administration.'' Herbal and folk remedies not sanctioned by the
FDA are not included.
</P>
<P>
   A buyer should look for a National Drug Code, or NDC, number on
the label to be sure it qualifies. Also exempted were blood glucose
monitoring test strips, which are used by diabetics.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, an exemption on diapers was considered but not
included in the final legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will the Internet exemption work?
</P>
<P>
   A: After Oct. 1, the exemption applies to Internet access
service, in an amount not to exceed the first $25 of a monthly
charge. In other words if you are paying $25 a month for use of the
Internet, you would save $2 a month.
</P>
<P>
   It applies regardless of whether the billing cycle used by the
Internet service provider is monthly or annual; or whether the
service is bundled with another service; and regardless whether the
provider charges a lump sum amount or separately bills the
purchaser for each Internet user on the account.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What were some of the business tax breaks approved?
</P>
<P>
   A: After Jan. 1, small businesses _ those with gross annual
receipts of less than $150,000 _ will no longer be liable for any
franchise taxes. Savings will vary from business to business, but a
corporation that made $150,000 profit all within Texas and had no
deductible expenses would save $6,750, according the comptroller's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations of any size may apply for tax credits for research
and development or job creation; for providing day care services
for children of employees; and for underwriting before-school and
after-school programs for kids ages 5-13.
</P>
<P>
   Tax credits also will apply to capital investments in
``strategic investment areas'' if the outlays are to provide
agricultural processing, data processing, warehousing,
manufacturing, central administrative offices and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
