<HEADLINE>
MIDLAND, TEXAS, STUDENT BREEZES THROUGH DAY ONE OF SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stacey Moore, 14, of Midland, Texas, breezed
through the first day of the 72nd National Spelling Bee Wednesday
by quickly and confidently disposing of words in the contest's
initial three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   The first word she encountered was a doozy: ``cricetid.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many contestants, Stacey didn't ask that the word be
repeated or defined or used in a sentence. She just spelled it. The
word refers to a family of small rodents that includes muskrats and
gerbils.
</P>
<P>
   She gave a repeat performance during the second round with the
word ``monetary,'' which has to do with a country's currency or
coinage.
</P>
<P>
   During the third round, she did ask the pronouncer, one of the
contest judges, to repeat the word ``interminable,'' which means
endless, before she spelled it.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey, who completed the eighth grade last week at Alamo Junior
High School, will compete again Thursday. She is sponsored by the
Midland Reporter-Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just surprised to make it to the second day,'' Stacey said
after the contest, which is run by the Scripps Howard newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Pam Moore, an executive secretary in Midland, said
she gets nervous when Stacey ``just blurts words out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stacey said the longer she thinks about a word, ``the easier
it is to mess up.''
</P>
<P>
   She has competed in spelling bees since she was in the third
grade. ``I love it and have been doing it ever since,'' said
Stacey, who brought her stuffed monkey, Kizzy, with her to
Washington for good luck. Stacey has had Kizzy since she was a
baby.
</P>
<P>
   Her love of spelling at times conflicts with her other love,
tennis. Stacey will miss a tennis competition this weekend because
she and her family will be traveling back to Texas from Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   She said she will play tennis this summer before taking part in
a school spelling team when she enters Lee Freshman School later
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The spelling bee began with 249 spellers. By the end of the day,
TK were left. Round four will begin Thursday and subsequent rounds
will be held until only one contestant survives. That speller will
receive $10,000, a choice of encyclopedias and other prizes. Other
winners will receive commemorative watches and cash prizes based on
their ranking in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at 202-298-6920 and by
e-mail at jennifer &LR; hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
