<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0444 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      06-02 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PUBLIC OUTRAGE OVER BRUTAL, EXPENSIVE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - We're numb, desensitized, tuned out. The daily numbers
from Kosovo _ this many sorties flown, that many civilians killed _
carry the same emotional weight as the baseball scores or the stock
market, maybe less. We've talked more about ``Star Wars'' in recent
weeks than our destructive attacks in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Our bombs are killing and maiming innocent people we are seeking
to protect, and we write it off like a deductible expense in the
business of war.
</P>
<P>
   Our leaders say we are trying to degrade the Yugoslav military,
undercut Slobodan Milosevic's popular support and force him to the
peace table. In fact, we've struck dozens of civilian targets,
sharply increased animosity toward America and failed to harm
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Our aims were well-intended, but our approach has been foolishly
conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Before launching the attack, we gave the Serbs an ultimatum with
no room for negotiation, no space for diplomacy. Their refusal to
accept it was predictable.
</P>
<P>
   By relying entirely on air power in mountainous terrain, we
could not stop Serb paramilitary units from completing their grim
tasks. By using cluster bombs, which cause higher casualties, we
are looked on as indifferent to civilian life. By pledging not to
use ground troops, President Clinton gave the Serbs incentive to
accelerate their brutal expulsion of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Our multibillion-dollar bungling in the Balkans reminds me of
last December when our planes bombed Iraq after Saddam Hussein
refused to let weapons inspectors do their jobs. Net impact? Saddam
kept firm control of his country, and instead of some weapons
inspections, we have none.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's strategy against Serbia has been so misguided that a
strong ally, ex-President Jimmy Carter, felt moved to deliver a
scathing critique last week.
</P>
<P>
   Our bombs have hurt the oppressed, not the oppressor, he said.
With control of the news media, Milosevic manages to be seen as a
hero defending his homeland against foreign aggression.
</P>
<P>
   As a man long committed to freedom and human rights, Carter
appreciates our goals. But he noted that we have diminished the
United Nations by going around it, and the United States has
systematically ignored human suffering in conflicts across Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said the best way to make peace with abusive leaders is
to provide both the threat of consequences and the promise of a
reward. For a small fraction of the cost of this war, we could have
offered to help Yugoslavia economically. Instead, we are paying
billions to destroy the country and will pay billions more to
rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   We're now left with three options:
</P>
<P>
   Continue to flatten Yugoslavia and kill more civilians; work
more closely with Russia to find a diplomatic solution; or commit
ground forces, some of whom are almost certain to die.
</P>
<P>
   Carter favors diplomacy, concluding:
</P>
<P>
   ``Even for the world's only superpower, the ends don't always
justify the means.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 weeks we've been told there can't be a pause in
the bombing because Milosevic can't be trusted. But what exactly
could he do to us? A pause could give him a chance to save face and
put political pressure on him to settle. There are growing
indications this week that he may finally be interested in talking
peace. If clearing the skies for a few days could help, we should
do it.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Kissinger, who has a solid grasp of the difference between
realism and idealism in foreign policy, once said the ``most
fundamental problem of politics . . . is not the control of
wickedness but the limitation of righteousness.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to countries convinced of their moral
superiority, as we are today. He knew that a nation has to balance
what it sees as just with what is possible. Moral convictions, no
matter how well-founded, give no assurance of military success.
</P>
<P>
   Our bombing campaign misjudged Milosevic, miscalculated the
reaction of the Serbian people, claimed the lives of scores of
innocents and cost a fortune. Yet there's been remarkably little
public outrage.
</P>
<P>
   I wish the war could turn stock prices down. More people might
take it seriously. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at steve.wilson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
