<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-GOALIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAUSEY AFFECTS REVOLUTION'S STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY _ Revolution player/coach Walter Zenga knew what he
was doing when he removed himself from last Saturday's road game
against the MetroStars in the 90th minute in favor of backup
goalkeeper Jeff Causey.
</P>
<P>
   Causey, the former University of Virginia All-American, was
perfect the rest of the way, holding the fort to preserve a 3-3
regulation tie, then blanking the MetroStars in the shootout, 1-0,
enabling New England to end a two-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Signed by the Revolution to replace the injured Zenga two
seasons ago, Causey has experienced the best of both geographic
worlds since entering the league. As a rookie in 1996, Causey was
keeper for the MLS champion D.C. United, so he was close to his
hometown of Gainesville, Va. After being waived by D.C. and signed
by New England, Causey now finds himself in his wife's native state
(she's originally from Groton).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the couple met during Causey's first semester at
Virginia, where Jeff would go on to post an NCAA tournament-record
three shutouts in as many national championship games and Heather,
an All-American as well, would star in lacrosse and field hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were battling for a while to see who would win more
national championships,'' he said. ``She won two, I won three.''
</P>
<P>
   Causey said the physical part of Saturday's game was secondary
to being mentally prepared for the five shooters in the extra
session. He wound up stopping two balls, seeing two others miss the
net, and forcing the other shooter to run out of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to get myself into the right frame of mind, get
aggressive and do what I had to do, either get a piece of the ball
or force the shots to go wide.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time this season Causey has gone the extra
mile for Zenga and his teammates. On May 8 against Miami, he
replaced an injured Zenga in the second half, then backstopped the
Revolution to another shootout win, allowing just two goals on six
extra shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine out of 11,'' smiled Causey. ``That's a good average right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Causey has to be prepared to spell Zenga at a moment's notice.
Against the MetroStars, he was told with six minutes to play that
he would soon enter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a psychological thing that works both ways,'' he said.
``I'm going in cold and I don't even know what I'm going to able to
do, but I think it also changed their style. In a shootout, you
just hope their first one doesn't go in. You want to get off to a
good start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when it comes to a shootout, I tell my team that I'll
save at least three and that I hope they can get three and the
earlier the better for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case last weekend, but the way Causey came
through, the other two goals weren't needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of learning as much as I can from Walter and
taking that as far as I can,'' he said. ``I think I'm a more
confident and in-control player than when I first turned pro.''
</P>
<P>
   Causey said the win was ``something we needed to pick us up with
a huge game coming up against Chicago,'' a reference to Saturday's
matchup at Foxboro Stadium against the defending MLS champion
Chicago Fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were getting pretty low and frustrated because we've been
in all the games we've lost right to the very end. Our defense has
been playing strong and now our offense seems to be ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Striker Giovanni Savarese, who scored twice and assisted on
another goal against the MetroStars, was named MLS Player of the
Week. He now has four goals on the season and 45 all-time, third
best in MLS history &UR; . &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
