<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-BELMONT-BOS &LR;      06-02 1485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BELMONT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY ANTLEY IS RIDING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, N.Y. _ His eyes are lit with intensity, his voice firm
with certainty, and his spirit strong with life.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, for a reborn man, for a man back from the depths, what
Chris Antley did in Baltimore nearly three weeks ago still tickles
the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   No, not winning the Preakness Stakes aboard Charismatic. Not at
all, because the best jockeys are paid to give their best effort,
doing their utmost to win the biggest races. Antley was doing his
job and he did it very well aboard Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   It is what Antley did after the Preakness that still lingers in
the mind. The jockey did not tarry before the TV cameras and give
interview after interview, nor did he rush to the interview room to
tell the print media what it meant to him to be one ride from the
Triple Crown. Indeed, confidence oozed at that moment.
</P>
<P>
   That's because ``Charismatic's Preakness effort was kind of
breathtaking,'' said Antley. ``When I pulled him up after the race,
he raised his head up, cocked one ear, and he had no stress on his
face. He wasn't even blowing. And that's enough to send chills up
your spine, for a horse having been through so much to look that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Most, if not all, jockeys cancel any mounts they have later on
the card after winning a classic race. Instead, even in the
exultation of the moment and the rush he had that the Belmont
Stakes on Saturday might be even better, Antley rushed back to the
jockeys' quarters at Pimlico, changed his silks, rushed off to the
paddock, and was given a leg up on another horse.
</P>
<P>
   Antley, minutes after winning the Preakness, was back on the
track and riding in a mere allowance race. ``A few months ago,'' he
would say, ``if someone told me I could be riding a horse at
Pimlico on Preakness Day, any horse in any race Preakness Day, I
would have thought I was the luckiest man in the world.'' It was
only then, after riding a soon-forgotten horse in a forgettable
race, that Antley took his plaudits for winning the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   In his mind, Antley said Wednesday, ``I've already won the
Triple Crown.'' Just by being back on the race track. ``I mean, you
think about a gift,'' he said. ``Charismatic is a gift. I have a
very serene feeling. I am very content, yet I am very excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic, a colt nobody wanted, is ridden by Antley, a jockey
everybody doubted. That either could be a mere mile and a half from
winning the Triple Crown would be astounding; that the two of them
together are so close to racing immortality would be a figment, a
fantasy, a fantastic improbablity . . . except that it is real.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic's owner and trainer virtually wanted to give away
the colt. There were no takers. And when jockeys politicked and
switched and _ well, jockeyed _ for their mounts in the races
leading to the Kentucky Derby, all the top jockeys begged off.
Lafitt Pincay, one of California's best, had ridden Charismatic
seven times, but when Charismatic headed east for the Triple Crown
campaign, Pincay chose to stay home, opting instead to ride a more
promising horse at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Chris McCarron, another of California's best, also had ridden
Charismatic but McCarron had another commitments. Mike Smith, one
of New York's best jockeys, also saw promise elsewhere. All of
which left Chris Antley.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Kentucky Derby,'' Antley recalled, he returned to
California, entered the jockeys' room ``and one of the first
persons I saw was Lafitt and he gave me congratulations after the
Derby. Then, after the Preakness, I came in and saw Lafitt and I
said to him, `Lafitt, you were on him most of the time . . .' And
Lafitt looked me straight in the eye, I mean he had that spark in
his eyes, and he told me, `Congratulations.' He said, `Keep it up,'
and `One more.' As a younger rider, to see a Lafitt Pincay give you
that kind of support, it gives you chills.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Antley said, ``It gives you chills.'' From most jockeys,
such words would not be believable but they are so much so with
Antley. Chris Antley has been humbled and he is humble. There is a
wide-eyed innocence now to Antley that, once again, would not be
credible from others in this hard, hard world of horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   The tale has been well-told. Too many controlled substances and
too much weight had driven Antley from the winner's circle, then
from the limelight, and finally from the race track itself. He had
burst upon racing 14 years ago at Monmouth Park in New Jersey, the
hottest of hot apprentices, took the next step up and across the
Hudson River to New York's tracks _ one day winning a total of nine
races at Aqueduct in the afternoon and the Meadowlands in New
Jersey at night _ and was among America's top jockeys. But 18
months ago it seemed over.
</P>
<P>
   His weight ballooned to 148 pounds, more than 30 above his
riding weight. Even his father suggested he find another line of
work and, as far as racing was concerned, Antley's career was done.
But Antley, scraping bottom, was convinced he again could find the
top.
</P>
<P>
   But last November, after running 25 miles day after day at his
home in South Carolina, even Antley himself fell prey to doubts.
The last 10 pounds, the absolutely critical last 10 pounds, just
would not go away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for trainers working their horses now
based on what my legs went through,'' said Antley. ``I had to
change my training schedule because my legs kept breaking down. My
worst time was from Thanksgiving to last Christmas and when I broke
down then, I couldn't walk. I felt for sure then I was going to put
the weight back on.''
</P>
<P>
   The constant pounding of the road work broke down both his knees
(``I have no cartilage in my right knee'') and Antley was forced
from the roads to the gym. ``I had to use exercise equipment to try
and continue to burn myself off. I didn't have a whole lot of fat.
I was about 9 or 10 percent body fat at 125, so I had to go into
the muscle and into myself'' to shed more pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But Antley never melted down his core, because the core of
Antley just would not disappear. As he ran those 25 miles, as he
worked in the gym, as he willed footstep after footstep, he thought
mostly ``of putting one foot in front of the other'' but also of
the paramount goal, returning to the track. And when he finally
returned to Santa Anita early this year, ``when I entered the
jocks' room I got the same chill I got from winning the Derby''
which he did with Strike The Gold in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   And now that he is back, this serene man is also the hungriest
of jockeys, putting forth a top effort race after race, a trait
seldom seen in veteran riders. When asked to delve into his soul to
explain how he conquered his body, Antley said, ``I'm like
Charismatic, I guess, a $65,000 claimer. I had a lot of growing up
to do, a lot of learning to do, a lot of figuring out what was most
important to me in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there is such an innocence to this new Antley. For
instance, when it was mentioned that Belmont fans just might boo
him _ new Antley or no new Antley _ if he does not win Saturday,
the jockey said he didn't think that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer D. Wayne Lukas then leaned over and whispered to Antley,
``These are New York fans; they'll boo.' '' Antley slowly shook his
head and said, ``No, they won't boo.''
</P>
<P>
   Truly, a transformation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The post position draw of a 1 1/2-mile race is about as
important as counting the number of worms burrowing through the
dirt on the far turn. For the record, Charismatic drew post
position four, the filly Silverbulletday drew position three, and
Menifee drew outside in position 10. Bob Baffert, Silverbulletday's
trainer, half-joked that the only liability for post three is that
``Charismatic is just outside me and he's bumped my horses in both
the Derby and the Preakness and I hope he doesn't do it a third
time.'' . . . Of more interest, the morning line listed Charismatic
as the 2-to-1 favorite, Menifee the second choice at 7-2, and
Silverbulletday a somewhat-surprising third choice as 4-1 . . .
Lukas, who chastised the media in Louisville Monday and Tuesday,
had only one zinger Wednesday: ``I've grown more tolerable of you
guys.'' Meanwhile, Bob Lewis, Charismatic's owner, tried to douse
the latest flareups between training foes Baffert and Lukas.
Baffert had said last week that his filly was ``the best 3-year-old
in the country'' but Lewis said Baffert had been misquoted, that he
meant she was ``the best 3-year-old filly in the country.'' Lewis
also squelched talk of a possible $100,000 mano-a-mano bet with
Baffert over who would win the Belmont, Silverbulletday or
Charismatic. Lewis had proposed the bet last week after Baffert's
``best horse in the country'' comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
