<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICK-PANDA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANDA PERKS UP, BUT U.S.-CHINESE RELATIONS ARE STILL PEAKED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hsing-Hsing looked as cute as ever Wednesday,
perched against the back wall of his feeding room at the National
Zoo, munching on bamboo shoots. But the giant panda, the survivor
of two that China gave the United States in 1972, is suffering from
kidney failure, and zoo officials said at a news conference
Wednesday afternoon that they could not predict how much longer he
would live.
</P>
<P>
   ``His condition is irreversible but stabilizable,'' said Dr.
Lucy Spelman, a staff veterinarian at the zoo, who described
Hsing-Hsing's weakened condition as inevitable for a carnivore of
his advanced age. Giant pandas in the wild live about 20 years, and
Hsing-Hsing is 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately it's a debilitating illness,'' Dr. Spelman added.
``He'll get better, then he'll get worse. All we're doing is buying
time. But we really don't know how long he might live. There are no
models. He is the oldest panda being treated for this condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hsing-Hsing's female denmate, Ling-Ling, died of heart failure
at the age of 23 in 1992. At the time, she was the oldest giant
panda in captivity. The National Museum of Natural History, here in
Washington, obtained her skull and skin for its research
collection, and tissue samples were kept at the zoo's veterinary
hospital for study.
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials said Hsing-Hsing's death would leave 17 giant
pandas outside China, just 5 of them in North America _ 2 in San
Diego and 3 in Mexico City. Zoologists estimate that 1,000 giant
pandas live in the wild in China, the only country where they exist
outside captivity, and that 100 others are in Chinese zoos.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are among the rarest of animals, replacing
Hsing-Hsing (pronounced SHING-shing) would be difficult under any
circumstances. But National Zoo officials said the effort could be
made more difficult by the especially prickly relations between
China and the United States since NATO's accidental bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, and the finding of a
Congressional committee that Beijing had for years made a concerted
effort to steal American nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Yu Shu Ning, a spokesman for the Chinese Embassy in Washington,
said that he was ``very sad'' to hear of Hsing-Hsing's illness but
that he was not aware of ``any plans for the time being'' of
China's offering the United States another pair of pandas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing to us is have the result of the
investigation of the bombing of our embassy in Yugoslavia,'' he
said. ``Then we'll see what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Zoo officials said they became aware of Hsing-Hsing's condition
last month, when they noticed a decrease in activity, a loss of
appetite and a drop in weight from his usual 250 pounds or so. An
examination on May 15 found that he had severe kidney dysfunction,
a potentially fatal condition that zoo veterinarians began treating
with antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Stevens, the zoo's mammal curator, said more aggressive
treatments, including dialysis, which would have required daily
anesthesia, were not considered prudent because of Hsing-Hsing's
age. A kidney transplant was also ruled out, because no giant-panda
kidneys are available.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ling-Ling and Hsing-Hsing delighted visitors to the zoo
for decades, their lives there were not without troubles, some of
which reflected the severe difficulty of mating pandas in
captivity.
</P>
<P>
   From 1983 to 1989, Ling-Ling bore five cubs, all of which died
at birth or shortly thereafter. On six other occasions, she
experienced hormonal changes that resembled those of pregnancy but
produced no offspring.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Hsing-Hsing has suffered from medical problems over
the years, including an eye infection in 1993 and testicular cancer
four years later that was successfully treated with surgery. More
recently, zoo officials said, he has developed arthritis, which is
common for a mammal of his age.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevens, the mammal curator, said zoo officials were
heartened in the last few days to see Hsing-Hsing's appetite
return. But they continue to list his medical condition as serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
