A0455 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-CONTRACEPTIVES-     06-02 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-CONTRACEPTIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS LIFTING BAN ON `THE PILL' IN JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ In a major step toward ending Japan's ban on the birth
control pill, the nation's top medical advisory council suddenly
reversed itself Wednesday and recommended allowing the pill to be
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is the sole industrialized country that bans the pill, a
policy that has been the subject of debate for decades. Some
feminists argue that the ban reflects male domination of Japanese
society and politics.
</P>
<P>
   After the recommendation Wednesday by the advisory council to
Health and Welfare Minister Sohei Miyashita, Miyashita could add
his approval in a few weeks. If he approves, the pill could be
available by autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the widespread use of the pill around the world,
Japanese officials have said for years that additional research was
necessary before they could proclaim that the pill was safe for
Japanese women to use. Some officials have also warned that
permitting the pill would encourage promiscuity and reduce reliance
on condoms, leading to the spread of AIDS and sexually transmitted
diseases.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the government said it needed to delay adoption so
that it could better educate the public about such diseases. Then
last year, there was an environmental scare that the pill, through
human waste, might release certain chemicals into water that would
disrupt the human endocrine system.
</P>
<P>
   Some advocates of the pill say officials have been worried about
Japan's declining birth rate and the possibility that the pill
could quicken that decline. The health ministry does have strict
standards on introducing foreign medicines, and some products take
years to wind their way through all the regulatory hoops. Even
Tylenol is still not sold here.
</P>
<P>
   But the case for the pill received recent support from another
drug, Viagra. The blue pills, which treat impotence in men, sailed
through the predominantly male ministry and went on sale last
month, six months after the application. In contrast, the
birth-control pill has been under review for at least nine years.
The speedy Viagra approval provoked an uproar from women's groups,
which said the government was discriminating against women. When
the advisory council recommended approval of the pill, it also said
that packaging should include instructions on preventing the spread
of sexually transmitted diseases.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier version of instructions, some health officials had
recommended that women on the pill visit a doctor every three
months or so for checkups. Women's groups opposed that.
</P>
<P>
   Even with an approval, however, it may be an uphill battle to
persuade ordinary women to use the pill. The drug has suffered from
years of bad publicity over its side effects, leaving many women
reluctant to use it. Many women have images of the thalidomide
poisonings of the 1950s and '60s, in which women who took the
sedative to prevent morning sickness gave birth to babies with
severe defects. Other women fear that they could become sterile.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the high-dose pill has been sold here legally for
years, not for contraception, but mainly for women with menstrual
disorders. But many women persuade their doctors to prescribe it as
a contraceptive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
