</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA AND THE WEST MOVE CLOSER ON PRINCIPLES FOR ENDING WAR IN
KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-PLANE) 
(rm) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Russia and the West on Wednesday narrowed their
differences over the concrete measures required to end the war in
Kosovo, limiting the room for maneuvering by Slobodan Milosevic,
the Yugoslav president, and increasing the pressure on him to reach
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found a common approach,'' said Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy to the Balkans, after a marathon
negotiating session in Bonn with American and European officials
that went on through much of Tuesday night and only ended
mid-afternoon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said ``common approach'' was a
bit of an overstatement. But, the official said, the unity of
purpose was now sufficient to justify a visit to Belgrade late
Wednesday by Chernomyrdin and the Finnish president, Martti
Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said that Russia had agreed for the first
time that all Yugoslav forces _ army, police and paramilitary _
should withdraw from Kosovo and that the withdrawal be
substantially under way before any pause in NATO bombing. Perhaps a
few hundred Yugoslav soldiers could return, but only after the
deployment of a 50,000-strong international peacekeeping force,
which would include 7,000 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The West and Russia remain apart, however, on the composition
and the command structure of the peacekeeping forces. Russia is
holding out for a United Nations-controlled force; the West insists
that the force be effectively commanded by NATO. One possible
compromise would give a Russian contingent in Kosovo considerable
independence in day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Steiner, the top diplomatic adviser to Gerhard Shroeder,
the German chancellor, said diplomacy would now follow two main
tracks over the coming week: an attempt to secure Milosevic's
agreement to the terms reached by the West and Russia and an effort
to pass a United Nations Security Council resolution that reflects
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained far from clear that Milosevic would agree to
terms that appear closer to NATO demands than to the vague
statement by the Group of Seven richest nations and Russia on May 6
that the Yugoslav government has formally accepted. That gap will
be the subject of Ahtisaari's discussions in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made reasonable progress, particularly on the scope and the
timing of the Serbian withdrawal,'' said one U.S. official. ``The
Russians have understood that, for us, all means all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bonn talks were unexpectedly difficult and marked by
brinksmanship that saw Russia threatening to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said that Chernomyrdin argued for a pause in
the 71-day-old NATO bombing as a gesture of goodwill, but was
finally swayed by Western arguments that such a break would not
make Milosevic more pliant or more ready to negotiate in good
faith.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Russia agreed that the Serbian leader must start a
verifiable and substantial withdrawal of his forces before a halt
in the NATO bombardment could be declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at the moment there is a realistic chance that the war
will end,'' Chernomyrdin said. Strobe Talbott, the deputy secretary
of state, who has been shuttling between Washington, Moscow,
Helsinki, Bonn and Brussels, said, ``Increasingly the international
community is speaking with one voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Russia and the West have shifted their area of
agreement from broad principles that were vague on crucial issues
to the outline of a concrete program to which Milosevic must now
respond.
</P>
<P>
   The principles adopted on May 6 did not stipulate that all
Yugoslav forces must withdraw and alluded only to the deployment of
``effective international civil and security presences'' in Kosovo,
rather than to a NATO-led peacekeeping force on which the Clinton
administration has insisted.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was on the question of the make-up of the peacekeeping force
that differences with Russia proved most difficult, American
officials said. ``The Russians are still pushing for a United
Nations-controlled operation, but after Bosnia we learned the
lessons of watered-down command structures,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, between 1992 and 1995, a so-called ``dual-key''
system under which both NATO commanders and senior U.N. officials
had to approve any military action proved unwieldy, ineffective and
sometimes disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Belgrade, Chernomyrdin said that, under a
compromise reached in Bonn for the peacekeeping force in Kosovo,
``NATO will command NATO forces, Russia the Russian forces.
Relations between the two contingents will be governed by separate
agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steiner said this statement should not be taken at face
value. ``Obviously, each politician has his constituency that has
to be satisfied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   European and American officials said that a command structure
similar to the one now governing relations between Russian and
Western forces in Bosnia is being considered. This system involves
a NATO chain of command, although it gives the Russian contingent
there considerable latitude.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a Russian proposal that it take charge of a zone
in the northern part of Kosovo while NATO countries control the
southern part of the province had been rejected because it might
appear to lay the basis for partition.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said it was now crucial to involve the United Nations.
``If what we have now is the basis for a solution, then we must get
it legalized in the Security Council as quickly as possible,''
Steiner said. ``That in turn will give us the political leverage we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   If a Security Council resolution could now be passed calling for
a complete Serbian withdrawal and the deployment of a large
international force with a central NATO presence, as well as the
return of all ethnic Albanian refugees, then the pressure on
Milosevic would clearly increase still further.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said that with such a resolution, a full and
formal agreement from Belgrade might not be necessary. ``All we
would need is the absence of a rejection from Milosevic and the
withdrawal of his troops from Kosovo,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains unclear whether China, whose relations with the
United States were soured by the bombing last month of its Belgrade
embassy by NATO, would agree to the resolution and whether wording
could be found that would circumvent Russian objections about the
nature of the peackeeping force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the German foreign minister, said, ``We have
some good news, but I do not want to overrate it. We have to remain
skeptical until the last moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the West have come a long way since the first days of
the NATO bombing, when anger in Moscow was at fever pitch and
rumors were circulating that Russian missiles had been redirected
at European targets.
</P>
<P>
   However the diplomacy now progresses, immense difficulties
appear to remain, not the least being how to convince the divided
Albanian leadership and the Kosovo Liberation Army that any accord
with Milosevic is even remotely credible. The Serbs must also be
convinced that the rebel army can be disarmed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the West would apparently be committing itself to a
massive deployment of forces and huge investment of resources in a
state headed by a man indicted on charges of war crimes last week
by the international criminal tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari was expected to report on the results of his talks
with Milosevic to a summit meeting of European leaders in Cologne
on Thursday and Friday. The Finnish president is the highest-level
Western representative to meet with the Yugoslav leader since the
bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Chirac, the French president, said Wednesday that the
rapprochement between Russia and the West ``undoubtedly opens the
door to a significant chance for a political settlement. In this
situation, I cannot really see how the Serbian authorities could
refuse the solution demanded of them by the whole international
community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
