<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad execution causes CEO failures, Forbes says
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What do the following ex-corporate chief executives
have in common: Ronald Allen of Delta Air Lines, Robert Stempel of
General Motors, Robert Allen of AT&AMP;T and John Akers of IBM?
</P>
<P>
   According to Fortune (June 21), they failed in their jobs at the
top of some of the nation's biggest corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``These men all had what it takes to get to the top. One
weakness brought them down,'' says the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness? ``It's bad execution. As simple as that _ not
getting things done, being indecisive, not delivering on
commitments,'' Fortune says.
</P>
<P>
   In today's competitive global economy, chief executives who fail
to master the art of execution ``cannot effectively navigate their
company through ... changes and are being pushed out faster than
ever,'' the magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   In stocks, women beat men
</P>
<P>
   Men may be more active in the stock market, but women make more
money at it, Forbes (June 14) says in its 1999 investment guide.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of brokerage accounts by the University of
California at Davis found that single men traded 67 percent more
than single women, but the women's risk-adjusted annual returns
were 2.3 percent higher. Married men traded 45 percent more, but
married women had 1.4 percent better returns.
</P>
<P>
   Men, it seems, are impatient for quick profits, prompting them
to gamble. Women are more cautious, more long-term oriented and
more willing to match their own research with expert opinion,
Forbes says.
</P>
<P>
   Downloaded any books?
</P>
<P>
   A book is portable. But a library? In the Internet age, even a
library is portable, Business Week (June 7) points out in unveiling
its industrial-design award winners for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Three different hand-held digital readers won honors in this
year's competition for the best-designed new consumer products. Two
of them are for books and one for an ``electronic newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Information Age devices generally dominated the year's
breakthrough products, ranging from laptop computers to a laser
copier that can sub as a scanner. At a more practical level were
low-cost snowshoes and a disposable Polaroid camera.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine co-sponsors the competition with the Industrial
Designers Society of America.
</P>
<P>
   If traffic is bad now...
</P>
<P>
   The Futurist (June/July) taps Atlanta to be one of 10 ``future
supercities.'' Denver is the other U.S. city on the list.
</P>
<P>
   A supercity has ``a sustainable capability'' to meet its
residents' physical and social needs and a dynamic economy that
attracts and nurtures investment.
</P>
<P>
   Others are Madrid, Spain; Istanbul, Turkey; Bangkok, Thailand;
Vancouver, British Columbia; Wuhan and Shanghai, China; Bangalore,
India; and Cancun-Tulum, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
