<SLUG> BC-COKE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.K. approves Coke-Cadbury deal
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola's $1.1 billion deal to buy Cadbury
Schweppes' brands in 106 nations won approval Wednesday in the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The approval gives Coca-Cola an important regulatory win,
following opposition in other countries that forced it to scale
back the brand buyout in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.K. is a key market,'' said Manny Goldman, global
beverage analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``It's good news. I think they
would like good news in Australia and Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   But several analysts predict another defeat when Australian
antitrust regulators announce their decision, possibly within the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have asked for reconsideration in Mexico, where
regulators initially rejected the deal.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Greece, a much smaller market, is expected to
approve the deal shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Coca-Cola will buy such Cadbury brands as Dr
Pepper, Canada Dry, Crush and Schweppes. But regulators in some
countries object to the deal as anti-competitive.
</P>
<P>
   On May 24, Coca-Cola revised the deal, eliminating 20 European
nations from the agreement, which has never included the United
States, France or South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury's annual sales volume in the United Kingdom represents
about 60 million cases of the 470 million cases covered by the deal
globally, said John Sicher, editor and publisher of Beverage
Digest. Australia represents about 50 million cases, he said, while
Mexico accounts for 90 million cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're delighted the British government has approved the
transaction,'' said Coca-Cola spokesman Randal Donaldson.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said the deal is expected to close in most nations in
July. Other nations will follow in stages after that.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola's shares fell 50 cents Wednesday to close at $68.62
1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
