A0494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHWEST03-COX     06-02 0351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New union upheld at Northwest
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal labor board has upheld a tiny union's
successful bid to represent jet mechanics at Northwest Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The National Mediation Board ruled that the Aircraft Mechanics
Fraternal Association's upset election by Northwest mechanics last
fall will stand, despite claims of rule violations by the losing
International Association of Machinists union.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling clears AMFA to renegotiate the mechanics' contract,
which has been in effect since 1996. The union is in the process of
establishing locals and electing officers.
</P>
<P>
   AMFA ousted the powerful Machinists as the mechanics' legal
bargaining agent in November by a vote of 5,160 to 3,905.
</P>
<P>
   But the Machinists appealed, claiming AMFA had violated ballot
secrecy rules and that Northwest had meddled in the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling this week, the mediation board concluded ballot
secrecy was compromised through an Internet site that encouraged
AMFA supporters to submit signed copies of their ballots. The site
wasn't run by AMFA, but the board said union officials knew it
existed.
</P>
<P>
   The board found the violation wasn't serious enough to void the
election. As a penalty, it said rival unions can mount new
organizing drives to challenge AMFA after six months, rather than
the customary two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Machinists union said it intends to keep about $400,000 in
dues collected while the election was being contested, citing the
costs of grievances and arbitrations.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest election came only months after mechanics had
soundly rejected a tentative new contract negotiated by the
Machinists.
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge win for AMFA, which had been on the fringes of the
airline labor scene for years without much to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   The union claims it can represent highly skilled and in-demand
mechanics better than umbrella unions such as the Machinists, which
also represents about 17,000 other Northwest workers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
