<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ELECTION-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA VOTES FOR PRESIDENT TO REPLACE MANDELA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEDOM PARK, South Africa _ Wrapped in blankets against the
cold, South Africans began lining up even before the sun came up
Wednesday, many of them giddy with the excitement of voting for
only the second time in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lines outside voting booths sometimes stretched for nearly a
mile. Though the polls were supposed to close by 9 p.m., many
remained open late into the night to accommodate those who had
stood for hours but had not yet had a chance to mark their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   While some had predicted that South Africa's second
post-apartheid elections would be marked by voter apathy, it was
not evident Wednesday. At the polling stations _ some in schools
and community halls, others in simple tents set up near squatter
camps _ there was a mood of pride and celebration.
</P>
<P>
   First in line outside the voting station here was Beauty Hlela,
42, a mother of five who lives in a shack just yards away. Ms.
Hlela waited for three hours before the polls opened. She accepted
her ballot papers with trembling hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about this country today,'' she said, after
voting. ``I wanted to vote for such a long time. That's why I came
early.''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of black support, President Nelson Mandela's
African National Congress is virtually assured a victory. The only
real question is by how much. With the 80-year-old Mandela set to
retire, his deputy, Thabo Mbeki, 56 is expected to replace him, on
June 16.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, who spent 27 years in jail for his belief that all
South Africans were entitled to vote, cast his ballot early
Wednesday morning near his Johannesburg home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very wonderful occasion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By evening the most report of serious violence had come from the
volatile Richmond area of the KwaZulu-Natal province, where two
people were killed just hours before polling stations opened.
</P>
<P>
   The area has been plagued by political violence in recent years
caused by a turf war between the ANC and a new party, the United
Democratic Movement, started by a former ANC official, Bantu
Holomisa.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, peace reigned as voters waited patiently, sometimes
building fires to warm themselves. In many areas, enterprising
merchants set up stands and sold tea, coffee, fruit and bread to
the voters and a carnival-like atmosphere prevailed. Fears that a
flood of unregistered citizens might arrive at polling stations,
demanding to vote, did not materialize.
</P>
<P>
   In the affluent northern suburbs of Johannesburg, some voters
were still in line late in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, the vibe is much better this time,'' said Martie
Ramsey. There were bomb scares last time and a certain fear was in
the air. But this is very nice, very calm.''
</P>
<P>
   But others said that 1994 was a bit more special. ``Last time it
was a real worldly occasion,'' said Michel Stefansky, who runs a
computer business and waited three hours to vote. ``This time it's
just a schlep.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's polling operation is far more sophisticated than in
1994, when anyone with an identification document could vote. This
year, the country produced a registration list and demanded that
its citizens get new bar-coded identification documents.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were glitches. Some voting stations opened late,
others did not have voting materials on time and officials reported
problems with their bar-code scanning equipment.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the day, officials said they were unable to reach
dozens of polling stations in the rural area of Eastern Cape
because phones and two-way radios were not working. Some of the
nonworking phones were in public schools that were being used as
polling stations. Unbeknownst to election officials, the schools
had not paid their phone bills and service had been cut off.
</P>
<P>
   The country's election commission began counting votes after 9
p.m. but significant results were not expected until Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   There has been little suspense about which party would win the
elections. The African National Congress has always been out front
in the polls. But its campaign has focused on getting at least
two-thirds of the country's parliamentary seats, a few percentage
points more than the 62.5 percent it won in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Such a gain would give it the power to change some aspects of
the constitution, although Mbeki has said in recent weeks that the
party has no plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Still, political analysts say that that goal, as much as
anything else, would provide the party with a psychological boost
and a moral authority as it goes forward.
</P>
<P>
   The country's opposition parties have seized on this goal in
hopes of mobilizing voters against the ANC, saying that it has too
much power and a strong opposition is needed. But they appear to
have made few inroads into ANC support.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign season, which ended in a barrage of nasty insults
between the parties, has served to highlight South Africa's
continuing racial divisions. Polls indicate that the ANC has
managed to attract very few nonblack voters.
</P>
<P>
   Two white-led parties, the liberal Democratic Party and the New
National Party, which ruled during apartheid, have been locked in a
fierce battle over the rest of the population: whites, mixed race
and Indians.
</P>
<P>
   As many voters went to the polls they expressed concern over the
two issues that dominate conversation here: rising crime and a
jobless rate estimated as high as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such problems, many black voters said that the ANC had
earned another five years in office. Many say that Mandela, though
beloved, was perhaps too old for the job. They are counting on
Mbeki to have a harder edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have to give the ANC another chance,'' said Tommy
Mpolokng, a 44-year-old dispatcher in a carpet factory. ``We need
someone who is maybe tougher than Mr. Mandela.''
</P>
<P>
   But whites, mixed-race and Indian voters often said they felt
the ANC did not have their interests at heart. At a last-minute
rally for Tony Leon, the Democratic Party leader, Margaret Jones,
59, said she liked Leon's ``Fight Back'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ANC doesn't care about us,'' said Mrs. Jones, who lives in
the mixed-race neighborhood of Eldorado Park near Johannesburg.
``You never see them doing anything here. We have nothing for the
youth here. They do not pay any attention to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the ANC is expected to sweep the national vote, it
could lose in the Western Cape province, which includes Cape Town
and nearby farming and fishing towns.
</P>
<P>
   The province was the only one that the New National Party held
on to in the 1994 elections. Parts of it are relatively wealthy, it
is the country's prime tourist destination, and it produces most of
the fruit and wine the country exports. One of the National Party's
strongest campaign points was its claim that the province was
better-governed over the last five years than any other in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   As he cast his vote at 7 a.m. Wednesday in the Pinelands section
of Cape Town, Ebrahim Rasool, the ANC's leader in the province,
said the outcome would be ``a test of logistics.'' The race was so
close, he predicted, that it would depend on which party was best
at reminding its members to vote or driving them to the polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
