<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Thursday, June
3, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Veronica
Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON-TREATY (Seattle) _ The long-awaited Pacific salmon treaty
with Canada has been succesfully negotiated and apparently will be
announced by Washington Gov. Locke Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   TIANANMEN-ANNIVERSARY (Seattle) _ For a decade, stories of the
idealism, courage and portentous (for the world's future) defeat of
China's fledgling democracy movement at Tiananmen Square in June
1989 have been told and retold so many times they have become part
of the collective unconscious of the '90s. One Tiananmen story that
has not been told, however, is that of a British Hong Kong
businessman and fourth-generation China Hand named Robin Dale, who
found himself in a strange moral dilemma during China's days of
destiny, and exonerated himself with a unique act of conscience.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``a'' and ``i''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   SHIPS-Y2K (Seattle) _ Commercial vessels entering the Strait of
Juan de Fuca and Puget Sound will have to prove they meet Year 2000
computer requirements under new Coast Guard procedures expected to
be put into effect later this month.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Gorlick. (Story will move in the ``f'' and ``a''
categories.)
</P>
<P>
   BEARS-RELEASE _ Five black bears, scrubbed and nourished after a
winter in a Lynnwood, Wash., rehabilitation facility, will be sent
out into the world to fend for themselves Thursday in Eastern
Washington. They're the last five to be released of 16 that were
taken in by the PAWS Wildlife Center between March and December
last year.
</P>
<P>
   By Jane Hadley. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-INSTINCT (Seattle) _ On Friday, Disney studios will unveil
``Instinct,'' with Anthony Hopkins as a primatologist who turns
killer after studying a colony of mountain gorillas in Rwanda; and
June 18 is the release date for its animated-musical version of
``Tarzan,'' with the emphasis on the hero's upbringing by great
apes. To get an edge on the competition, Disney has also dispatched
representatives of both films _ including ``Instinct'' director Jon
Turteltaub and co-star Cuba Gooding Jr. _ on a lengthy press tour
of major American cities: a practice that's still common for indie
films but relatively rare these days for big Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-JAR JAR (Undated) _ Anyway you splice it, Jar Jar Binks,
George Lucas' computer-generated movie character is stirring
powerful reactions on Planet Earth, from radio talk shows (where
shock jocks are calling for a Jar-B-Q) to Internet Web sites
(www.JarJarMustDie.com) to murmurings as people exit theaters (``I
thought he was racist,'' whispered a movie critic from a
metropolitan newspaper in the Midwest.)
</P>
<P>
   By Robert L. Jamieson Jr. (Story has moved in the ``e''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-MANHEIM (Undated) _ Camryn Manheim is one of my new favorite
people. And not because of what she says about reporters. OK, maybe
a little bit. ``I love the press,'' Manheim says on page 258 of her
autobiography, which cracked The New York Times best-seller list
last week. ``Niney-nine percent of the reporters I've met have been
really cool people that I'd like to hang out with.''
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
