<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Dutiful attendance at the knee of privilege presupposes the
capacity to endure long bouts of stupefying boredom. ... Practice
with inanimate objects. Look at a balloon for 90 minutes with an
expression of close attention and profound respect; talk to a box
of Cheerios about Martha's Vineyard and Monica Lewinsky; ask a fern
for its view of the Mexican debt. The exercises will prepare you
for an evening at the Council of Foreign Relations or an afternoon
around the pool with Norman Mailer.''
</P>
<P>
   _ From Lewis Lapham's ``Lapham's Rules of Influence, a
Careerist's Guide to Success, Status and Self-Congratulation''
(Random House; $19.95) &LR;  cq &LR; .
</P>
