<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON LAWYER IN TOBACCO FEE FIGHT WAIVES CLAIM TO $1 MILLION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Marc Murr, a Houston lawyer whose role in the
state's tobacco case is being investigated by federal authorities,
has waived any claim to $1 million in legal fees he was awarded in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Murr also has returned $81,875 that cigarette makers already had
paid him under an award set late last year by a national
arbitration panel.
</P>
<P>
   The fees were waived in a letter that Murr and his lawyer, Roy
Minton of Austin, wrote to tobacco lawyer Meyer G. Koplow of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The letter offered no explanation, and Minton declined to
discuss it Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was dated May 25, five days after federal prosecutors
subpoenaed records of Texas Attorney General John Cornyn's
investigation of Murr. Cornyn's records are to be turned over to a
federal grand jury meeting June 15 in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has accused former Attorney General Dan Morales and Murr,
a longtime Morales friend, of doctoring contracts to try to
fraudulently secure $260 million in legal fees for Murr.
</P>
<P>
   Murr dropped his $260 million claim May 6, one day after Cornyn
made his allegations in a document filed in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has denied Cornyn's allegations and has insisted that
Murr played a crucial role in the tobacco case, which Texas settled
last year for $17.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But other lawyers have said that Murr did little work on the
case, and his name didn't publicly surface until about the time the
lawsuit was settled in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Morales hasn't been subpoenaed, one of his attorneys, Sam
Millsap of San Antonio, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Millsap said the subpoena for Cornyn's records was an
``appropriate step.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the FBI and the U.S. attorney's office, we'll have an
even-handed, unbiased review. When that is through, we're confident
there will be a determination of no wrongdoing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Millsap said Cornyn, a Republican, was trying to
politically damage Morales, a Democrat, so that the former attorney
general could never run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   Minton said he wasn't surprised that federal authorities had
demanded the state's records. He said Murr hadn't been subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
