<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMUNE-DRUG-BOS &LR;      06-02 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMUNE-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DRUG OPENS UP OPTIONS IN MARROW TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Using a new drug, scientists at Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute have shown they can safely perform transplants for cancer
patients from genetically mismatched bone marrow donors _ a
procedure that up to now has been virtually doomed to failure.
</P>
<P>
   Scientifically, the feat is being hailed because the researchers
proved, for the first time, that they can neutralize a tiny,
specific cadre of immune system cells in the donor marrow _ while
leaving the vast majority intact _ to prevent the marrow cells from
attacking the patient's tissues.
</P>
<P>
   This complication, known as graft-versus-host disease, is common
in mismatched transplants and can be lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Medically, the Dana-Farber researchers called the results ``a
glimpse into the future'' of transplantation, when the use of
donated bone marrow or other organs and tissues won't require the
patient to take lifelong regimens of punishing, toxic,
anti-rejection drugs. Because these drugs suppress the entire
immune system, they leave patients vulnerable to infections and
other cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the advance suggests that not too far in the future
cancer patients needing transplants may not have to spend the
$25,000 or more often required, and an uncertain wait, to find a
genetically compatible donor through a transplant registry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``parents, siblings and children may soon be eligible
to serve as donors for each other, regardless of how well they
match, without the complications that are so often associated with
transplantation today,'' said Dr. David G. Nathan, president of
Dana-Farber and professor of medicine at Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exciting and important research finding,'' said Dr.
Anthony S. Fauci, director of the National Institute of Allergy and
Infectious Disease, which funded the study. It is another step, he
added, toward the goal ``of not having to chronically
immunosuppress people'' who receive transplants.
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; today &LR; 's issue of the New England Journal of Medicine, the
scientists report that they used the new technique in carrying out
bone marrow transplants in 12 young patients with leukemia that had
reoccurred despite standard therapies. In the transplants, the
patients received massive doses of chemotherapy and radiation to
kill all the leukemia cells. Afterward, they received transplants
of bone marrow cells to rebuild their blood and immune systems that
were destroyed by the drastic treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The patients had been unlucky in that transplants were their
only hope, genetically matched donors were not available, and time
was running out. In the experiment, they received marrow from
donors who were only 50 percent genetically matched _ a situation
in which few medical centers will even try a transplant because the
risk of complications is so high.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people took a big risk'' on the experimental treatment,
``but it came out better than we had hoped,'' said Dr. Lee Nadler,
in whose DFCI lab much of the work was done.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Drs. Eva Guinan and John G. Gribben, the DFCI team
exploited a recently discovered ``on-off switch'' in immune cells,
enabling them to switch off only the T-cells (advance scouts in the
immune defenses) in the donor bone marrow that recognize the
recipient's tissues as ``foreign.'' That conflict between bone
marrow cells and a mismatched recipient often leads to severe
graft-versus-host disease that is a major cause of complications
and deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The key step in the experimental transplants took place in a $1
million laboratory, built at DFCI with National Institutes of
Health funds. While the startup cost for the new technique is high,
the Dana-Farber researchers said that ultimately it may save money
by dramatically reducing complications.
</P>
<P>
   Before the recipients got their big blast of chemo and
radiation, the researchers removed from them the white blood cells
that signal whether a tissue is that of the patient (or ``self'')
or is a foreign tissue that may be dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   After irradiating these ``antigen-presenting cells'' to erase
any leukemia cells, the researchers mixed them with all the immune
cells in the bone marrow sample taken from the donor. While
incubating for 36 hours, the T-cells in the bone marrow recognized,
and bound to, the antigen-presenting cells that carried a
distinctive marker identifying them as ``self'' _ from the
patient's point of view _ but ``foreign,'' and therefore a target
to attack _ to the donor's T-cells.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the scientists added a drug made from a
natural immune on-off switch in human T-cells discovered within the
last 10 years. Normally, the T-cells that had recognized the
recipient's tissues would have received a second ``costimulatory''
signal verifying that the tissues were foreign.
</P>
<P>
   But the drug, known as CTLA-4, blocked this second signal. The
result: the T-cells, lacking the second signal, went into a dormant
state, and from then on were unable to recognize the recipient's
``self'' markers or antigens. Put another way, the strategy made
the incoming donor bone marrow ``tolerant'' to the recipient's
biological environment.
</P>
<P>
   The CTLA-4 drug was developed by Repligen Corp. of Needham,
which sponsored the study.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 12 patients receiving the transplants in the experiment,
seven died of infections, organ failure, or other causes; the five
survivors have remained in complete remission from their leukemia.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 12 developed graft-versus-host disease, and it
was mild. Without the new treatment, at least 80 percent probably
would have developed it, said Dr. Paul Martin, a transplant
specialist at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get it down to this low level'' of graft-versus-host
disease ``is a spectacular result,'' said Martin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
