<HEADER>
A0539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICHIGAN-SWEARING-NYT     06-02 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-SWEARING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN TRIAL PITS FREE-SPEECH AGAINST LAWS PROTECTING TENDER EARS
OF WOMEN AND CHILDREN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANDISH, Mich. _ If Timothy J. Boomer could keep his balance
better in a canoe, an obscure Michigan law against swearing in
front of women and children might not be tested now.
</P>
<P>
   But Boomer fell into a river when his rented canoe hit a rock
near here last August. What he said then will be the subject of a
criminal trial, which will pit free-speech advocates against local
prosecutors who want to limit public use of offensive language. The
trial is scheduled to start next week.
</P>
<P>
   The heavily publicized prosecution already seems to be prompting
the police in other northern Michigan cities to enforce the
statute, which carries a maximum penalty of 90 days in jail and a
$100 fine. Daniel J. Hartman, a lawyer in Petoskey said that one of
his clients had been ticketed in April in Sault Ste. Marie, nearly
300 miles north of Detroit, in connection with cursing at a
customer at his boat-repair business and police officers in front
of the customer's 2-year-old son. Another client in Petoskey, 230
miles northwest of Detroit, was warned recently by the police that
he might be ticketed, accused of swearing at the driver of a school
bus full of children, Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boomer case has been featured on national television and
radio talk shows, stirring excitement in Standish, a town of 1,300
people, 125 miles northwest of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anybody in the United States who hasn't
heard of this case,'' said Jack L. Stoner, the town's part-time
mayor, as he smoked a cigar in his laundromat here.
</P>
<P>
   Richard E. Vollbach Jr., the 35-year-old, crew-cut assistant
county prosecutor who charged Boomer and who recently took a free
trip to Los Angeles to appear on a television talk show to discuss
the case, said the trial would raise broad issues of civility and
free speech in modern American society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of case the U.S. Supreme Court might end up
looking at, in that there are some genuinely interesting First
Amendment issues,'' Vollbach said, crossing forearms across his
dark blue T-shirt as he rocked in a leather chair in his small,
sparsely furnished office.
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union has given the case national
prominence by providing free legal advice to Boomer, making him
available to news organizations for interviews and promising to
keep appealing rulings against him to as high a court as necessary
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``If successful, the state will effectively criminalize speech
which is heard every day on television and the streets _ it's
trying to legislate morality,'' said Kary L. Moss, the executive
director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Michigan. The
police should use disorderly conduct statutes instead, Ms. Moss
said.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer's jury trial will be the first involving the 102-year-old
law, said Vollbach and William T. Street, a longtime ACLU member
who has volunteered to represent Boomer. In allowing the trial to
proceed, District Court Judge Allen Yenior ruled in February that
though the part of the law regarding use of expletives in front of
women may not be constitutional, the law's provisions regarding use
of obscenities in front of children are justifiable because they
protect minors.
</P>
<P>
   Judges in at least two other Michigan counties have dismissed
cases involving the law after deciding that it was
unconstitutional, but those decisions have not set binding
precedents. A handful of other people accused over the years of
breaking the law here and in Sault Ste. Marie have paid small
fines, typically about $25, without contesting the misdemeanor
charge, said Vollbach and Farrell E. Elliott, the county prosecutor
in Sault Ste. Marie.
</P>
<P>
   Boomer is accused of using strong obscenities after falling into
the Rifle River while canoeing for the first time. A local
resident, Tammy Smith, was paddling by with her husband, her
5-year-old son and her 3-year-old daughter. ``I covered her ears,''
Mrs. Smith said in an interview. ``I didn't want her to repeat what
he was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sheriff's deputies who happened to be nearby ticketed
Boomer. They were part of a law-enforcement crackdown prompted by
complaints from home owners farther down the river that canoe tours
were disturbing the peace.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Boomer, a 25-year-old computer programmer who
lives in Warren, north of Detroit, denied that he used the strong
obscenities the police accused him of using, but would not discuss
in detail what he had said. Boomer, who said he never saw the Smith
family, said he has an 8-year-old son, and that his parents
``didn't raise me this way, I don't walk around swearing.''
</P>
<P>
   While city leaders here agree that most residents are on the
prosecutors' side, a few are not, like Janice Syers, 47, a former
truck driver with a 28-year-old daughter and an 18-year-old son.
Mrs. Syers said that her disagreement was not based on any
tolerance for profanity. She said that she used to wash her own
children's mouths with soap after they used obscenities.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Syers said that people in the woods should be allowed
to say what they want, if no one else is nearby. ``They're making a
big case out of a little mole hill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in a conservative town where the biggest employer is a
maximum-security state prison, most people seemed to share the
views of Stoner, the part-time mayor. ``I understand about free
speech, but there should be some common sense about what you say
around other people,'' the mayor said at his laundromat. ``I don't
allow dirty songs on my juke box.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoner, 68, said that people should always speak as if in
church, but later acknowledged that his own conduct did not always
meet that test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear, but I kind of watch where I do it,'' he said. ``If
you're around a bunch of guys, that's different from when you're in
mixed company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
