<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN HITS GROWING PROTECTIONIST BENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The chairman of the Federal Reserve Board on Wednesday
denounced barriers to free trade being erected by US policy makers
and warned they would do ``great harm'' to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But Alan Greenspan steered clear of any comments on the future
course of interest rates for financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   He chose instead to criticize a rising protectionist sentiment
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end it is clear that all economic progress rests on
competition,'' Greenspan said in a speech to members of the
Alliance for the Commonwealth, a Massachusetts export group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we endeavor to freeze competitive progress in place, we
will almost certainly slow economic growth overall, and impart
substantial harm to those workers who would otherwise seek more
effective longer term job opportunities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan is already on record as favoring free trade _ he
delivered a similar speech in Dallas in April _ to boost
productivity worldwide and promote growth.
</P>
<P>
   But his comments came on the same day leading US steel producers
asked the federal government to impose punitive tariffs on a
high-grade product, cold-rolled flat carbon steel, from being
imported from Japan, Russia and 10 other countries to a US economy
with strong demand.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department has already ruled that Japan illegally
sold the industry's leading product, hot-rolled carbon steel, at
unfair prices.
</P>
<P>
   And the House of Representatives in March passed one of the most
protectionist pieces of legislation in recent memory. The bill,
which would strictly limit the amount of steel imported into the
United States, is expected to face a Senate vote this month.
</P>
<P>
   While Greenspan did not specifically mention the bill, Fred
Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Corp., said he belives
Greenspan wants to ``send a message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a position out there that people should spend their
time thinking about it before they cast their votes,'' Breimyer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the antitrade atmosphere in this country is a record
trade deficit, which widened to $19.7 billion in March. And
pressure to enact trade barriers are only expected to worsen if the
economy begins to slow.
</P>
<P>
   US exporters suffered last year as the economies of the world's
trading partners, from Moscow to Jakarta, went into a nose dive.
Exports by Massachusetts companies, after rising every year since
1990, slumped in 1998, according to the state's export index,
issued quarterly by the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a surge in Massachusetts exports in the fourth quarter,
especially to China, the state exported $16.6 billion in goods last
year, 4 percent less than was exported in 1997. But the state may
be seeing ``the beginning of a recovery in exports,'' said Charles
McChesney, the alliance's director.
</P>
<P>
   US steel makers are stepping up the fight to reduce competition
from imports. In federal filings, the nation's biggest steel maker,
USX-U.S. Steel Group, and several other companies Wednesday accused
overseas producers of the metal, used in automobiles and
appliances, of ``dumping,'' or selling in the United States below
cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antidumping initiatives should be reserved, in the view of
many economists, for those cases where anticompetitive behavior is
involved,'' Greenspan said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the nation's central bank explained his position on
trade in economic terms, saying, ``economic progress rests on
competition. It would be a great tragedy were we to stop the wheels
of progress because of an incapacity to assist the victims of
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the House approved trade tariffs in March,
Representative J. Joseph Moakley, the South Boston Democrat, noted,
``Not every American is sharing in the good times. . . . While the
stock market is flirting with the 10,000 mark, ten thousand steel
workers lost their jobs last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Casting trade in terms of employment is a mistake for both
sides, Greenspan said. More important to the United States _ and
the world _ is trade's boost for standards of living, as
competition raises productivity, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
