<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTERY ENERGIZES USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When USC plays at Stanford in the first game of
the super regional college baseball playoffs Friday night, the
Trojans will have a first-round pick catching _ Eric Munson _ and a
first-rounder pitching _ Barry Zito.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just proves what we already know,'' Stanford head coach
Mark Marquess said. ``They are great players. Zito has been just
phenomenal all season. They are both real special players.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquess is in his 23rd season as the Cardinal's head coach. He
said he's never faced a team in the playoffs with first-rounders
who are also battery mates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unusual for a team to even have two first-rounders,'' he
said. ``And a battery... darn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson was picked No.3 by Detroit and Zito was taken ninth by
Oakland in Major League Baseball's annual draft Wednesday. It
marked the first time the Trojans had two players selected in the
regular phase of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Zito's selection was somewhat of a surprise. He was expected to
go lower in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``For (Zito) to go No.9 overall, that was just awesome,'' Munson
said. ``It's really great to see him go that high and finally
achieve his dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling it: USC senior pitcher Justin Lehr, who was the fourth
Trojans player picked, by the A's in the eighth round, shut out
Virginia Commonwealth last weekend in his first career playoff
start.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr, a three-year starter at catcher for UC Santa Barbara who
transferred to USC for his senior season to concentrate on
pitching, played in the playoffs as a freshman at UCSB. He said he
has a different feeling this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, getting to Omaha isn't that far away,'' Lehr said,
referring to the site of the College World Series. ``When I was at
UCSB, we didn't think we could win the regional. It picks up your
game knowing you can go to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehr (7-2) struck out 10 and walked one against VCU and was
named to the all-regional team.
</P>
<P>
   Killer instinct: USC, which lost 11 of its first 15 games this
year, has been a different offensive team since the its series
against Washington to end the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   USC scored 37 runs in the three games and pounded Huskies ace
Jeff Heaverlo in the series finale, won by USC 17-6. Heaverlo, a
right-hander who was a preseason All-American, was charged with 11
runs in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier in the year, we would have been happy with eight
runs,'' Munson said. ``We were trying to get as many as we could
(against Heaverlo), we were looking for that knockout punch.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing man: The most important pitching performance of the
first-round regional for USC wasn't by Lehr or Zito, who beat
Pepperdine on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was by sophomore right-hander Rik Currier, who was cruising
against the Waves on Sunday before he was betrayed by his defense;
USC committed two errors in the seventh to allow Pepperdine to
score three runs and go on to win 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Currier gave up just one earned run in 61/3 innings. He pitched
well enough to win, which should be kept in mind if the Trojans'
series against the Cardinal this weekend goes three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Currier) was outstanding,'' USC head coach Mike Gillespie
said. ``It's the best performance he's given us this year. This was
the Rik Currier we thought he would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Currier slumped to 5-7 this season after going 6-1 and earning
freshman All-American honors in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
