<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW SLIPS AS CONCERN ABOUT INTEREST RATES DOMINATES TRADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks slumped in early trading Wednesday but
rebounded somewhat after bargain hunters stepped in to scoop up
shares of Internet and other high-technology issues.
</P>
<P>
   By the close, the Nasdaq composite index had reversed course and
posted a solid gain, but the other main gauges were flat.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, concern about higher interest rates dominated
trading, analysts said. A report showing that sales of new homes
surged unexpectedly in April was the latest in a series of reports
suggesting that the economy continues to grow at an unsustainably
fast pace and that the Fed will most likely raise rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rate fears are the big problem,'' said Kenneth Ducey,
director of trading at BT Brokerage, a unit of Bankers Trust.
``People are very nervous'' that the Fed or the fixed-income market
may tighten credit. A key report on the nation's employment
situation is set to be released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, said nothing bearing
on rates in a lunchtime appearance in Boston, and the markets
seemed to take that as a cue to rally.
</P>
<P>
   One exception was brokerage stocks, which continued to reel from
Merrill Lynch's announcement of a new online trading service.
Merrill finished down 4 9/16, to 70 11/16, after two analysts cut
earnings estimates for next year. Nasdaq, which is dominated by
computer and other high-technology issues, finished with a gain of
20.38 points, or 0.8 percent, to 2,432.41. At its low, just after
noon, the loss was more than 47 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, meanwhile, ended 18.37 points
lower, or 0.2 percent, to 10,577.89, after being down nearly 132
points before the comeback. Eighteen of its 30 components lost
ground while 12, mostly cyclical issues, rose.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 0.55 point, to
1,294.81, but advancing stocks barely surpassed declining ones, 243
to 241, with 16 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent wide swings, the Chicago Board Options
Exchange's volatility index has been remarkably subdued, according
to Lawrence D. Cavanagh, an options strategist at Value Line. With
a decline of 1.69 points Wednesday, the index stands at 26.23, far
below this year's high approaching 35 in mid-January. ``Option
premiums have not jumped the way they usually do'' when the
investment tide turns, Cavanagh said. ``A lot of people are not
terribly worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks fell in six of the preceding eight sessions, pulling the
Dow 4.6 percent below its record 11,107.19 on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the market continues to do is unwind the real economic
fear of last year, which motivated investors to own the safest
vehicles in each asset class,'' Greg Smith, chief investment
strategist at Prudential Securities, told clients Wednesday. For
stocks, this was the large-capitalization growth stocks, which are
unlikely to ``return to the growth rates they had previously
shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, inflation fears should ease and June should prove
``pretty good for both stocks and bonds,'' Smith predicted. Some of
Wednesday's biggest gyrations were in Ameritrade, the online
broker, which closed with a gain of 5 7/8, to 85 5/8, after trading
as low as 73 and as high as 91 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   On April 14, the shares were worth more than twice as much,
peaking at 188 3/8. Charles Schwab, the nation's biggest online
broker, slumped as low as 91\ Wednesday before finishing at 96 1/8,
down 3 3/8.
</P>
<P>
   After trading as low as 151{, Ebay rallied to close up 2 5/16,
to 168 13/16, while Amazon.com recovered from a low of 97 1/8 and
finished up 6 5/16, to 112 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   J.P. Morgan lost 2 5/8, to 130 7/8, the biggest drag on the Dow,
while IBM had the most positive impact, rising 1}, to 113}.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products, which tumbled on Tuesday after
announcing an earnings shortfall, recovered 1 13/16, to 53 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
