<HEADER>
A0555 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PLANE-ART-2TAK     06-02 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PLANE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE LONG NIGHT OF DIRECTING NATO CAMPAIGN FROM THE SKY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(rm) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE COMMAND PLANE WAR WIZARD, over Albania _ The War
Wizard lumbered through the night sky over Albania as its battle
staff began another long night of directing air strikes against the
Serbian military.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before, the airmen had ``sanitized'' their flight
suits, stripping off their patches so that their unit could not be
identified if the plane was shot down in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Now they were sitting in an EC-130 that was older than most of
the crew, peering at distant targets on their computer terminals.
</P>
<P>
   Allied strike formations, reconnaissance planes, refueling
tankers and targets in Serbia glowed before them, superimposed on a
computerized map of the Balkans. Red squares traced the Kosovo
Liberation Army penetrations into the disputed province.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, NATO does not support the rebel partisans. But as
the fighting raged along the Albanian-Kosovo border, the War Wizard
was directing NATO warplanes to blast the Serb armor and artillery
in the guerrillas' path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad Dog,'' called out a member of the plane's battle staff,
radioing back for guidance to NATO's command center in Vicenza,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy F-14's had seen Serbian armor near the Kosovo border.
It was an area so close to the KLA guerrillas that it could not be
struck without high-level approval. Mad Dog authorized the strike
and the War Wizard relayed the go-ahead to the F-14's. They blasted
a tank and an armored personnel carrier with laser guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The air war over Kosovo, however, is not always so clear cut. By
the end of its 10-hour mission, the EC-130 had also directed NATO
warplanes on a fruitless search for a dozen other Serb targets near
the border. And it was forced to issue last-minute orders to avert
an unintended air strike against targets in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long night, even for these crews that orbit high above
the war theater for as much as 16 hours at a stretch. And with the
Serbs trying to hide, thousands of ethnic Albanian refugees on the
move and strict rules of engagement to limit civilian casualties,
the crew was prepared for many more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has ever done a mixed battle like this,'' said the
director of the battle staff, who goes by the call sign Rainman, as
he pondered the task he and his men have been handed of sorting out
civilians from partisans from opposing troops from miles above the
earth. ``The desert was a lot easier. If you want to take as many
precautions as we are about hitting third parties and avoiding
fratricide it hard to see how this could be any less painful.''
</P>
<P>
   The EC-130 flying command post is one of the lynchpins in the
allied air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times was allowed to join a combat mission to
observe its operations. Classified details about future targets,
aircraft call signs and rules of engagement were omitted at NATO's
request. But the military made no effort to limit the access of the
reporter to the crew or or censor his account.
</P>
<P>
   The mission began shortly before nightfall with an intelligence
briefing and overview about the upcoming flight at Aviano Air Base
in northern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen airmen _ a 12-person battle staff and a four-man flight
crew _ were zippered up in their green flight suits, with 9 mm
pistols strapped to their sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bloodchits,'' identifying the crew members as downed American
airman in several local languages and offering a handsome reward
for passage to safety, were tucked into the leg pockets of the
flight suits.
</P>
<P>
   Next stop was the squadron's ``life support'' to pick up a small
bag, containing an oxygen mask, head set, ear plugs and flame
retardant gloves. These are old planes and there is reason to worry
about fire in the cabin on take-offs, landing and during mid-air
refuelings.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Life support'' also handed out bulky survival vests,
containing a radio, compass, flares and global positioning system
device, which enables an airman to broadcast his position via a
navigational satellite. The vests felt as if they contained lead
weights; the airmen draped them over the back of their chairs as
soon as the EC-130 was aloft.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one squadron of EC-130 planes in the U.S. Air
Force _ the 42nd Airborne Command and Control Squadron _ and five
of their seven planes are at Aviano.
</P>
<P>
   With NATO stepping up its air war, the crew flies about four
missions a week. New orders can be given once the plane is aloft,
taking advantage of the plane's ability to refuel in mid-flight. So
a mission that is scheduled to last 10 hours can be stretched to
16.
</P>
<P>
   Hauling their gear, the crew drove in a van to the flight line.
The propeller driven EC-130 is hardly the most glamorous plane in
the Air Force. It is more like an old flying bus and was on the
verge of being phased out before the war with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   One of the squadron's planes was involved in the ill-fated 1980
hostage rescue mission President Jimmy Carter ordered in Iran. The
plane hit a sand dune during the operation. It still flies, just a
bit off kilter, pilots said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Built in 1962, the War Wizard has logged more than 34,000 flight
hours, and it takes a vigilant flight crew and dedicated
maintenance team to keep it going day after day.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner did the crew pile into the crowded aircraft than a
faulty fuel indicator forced everybody off again. A swarm of
technicians descended on the plane. By 6:30 p.m., however, War
Wizard was aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Croatian cities glittered in the distance and an F-16 warplane
rocketed by overhead, as the EC-130 headed south for its night of
NATO's air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Much has been made about the altitude restrictions designed to
protect the pilots against Serbian surface-to-air missiles and
anti-aircraft artillery. But NATO planes, in fact, can descend well
below 15,000 feet and the altitude, as it turns out, is not a major
barrier to killing tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the confusion on the battlefield. During the 1991
Persian Gulf War, the allies and Iraqi positions were clearly
separated. More often than not, errant bombs fell harmlessly into
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, Albanian guerrillas fight at close quarters with Serb
troops while homeless civilians roam through the province.
</P>
<P>
   The dilemma was underscored by the classified Air Tasking Order
issued to allied pilots by Gen. Michael Short, the top NATO air war
commander, to guide their actions in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   It said that NATO's air strikes aimed to ``shock'' the Serb
military and deal it a devastating blow. But it also explained that
concern over civilians, the possibility of refugees being used as
human shields and mixed refugee and military convoys required the
alliance to be more cautious about its bombing attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Gulf War, everybody on the other side of the line was a
bad guy,'' said Maj. Gene Roles, the Battle Staff Operations Office
on the War Wizard flight. ``Now we have good and bad mixed in the
same area. That makes it a lot tougher for the guys dropping
bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It has also made it more difficult for the battle staff of the
War Wizard to guide the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   According to standard military doctrine, a U.S. Army officer on
the ground should be picking the targets. The mission of the EC-130
would then be to decide which planes are available and coordinate
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no NATO troops on the ground in Kosovo. So the
EC-130 receives target lists from the command center in Vicenza,
information from observers in F-16s and A-10s planes and
intelligence from other sources.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in front of their computer screens, the battle staff
looks like they are playing the world's biggest video game.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Blue symbols on the screen show the location of allied aircraft
with call signs like ``Magic,'' ``Salt'' and ``Butcher.'' Air
traffic lanes and patrol areas are marked with code names like
``Front Street,'' ``Texaco'' and ``Soccer'' Red symbols depict
targets in Yugoslavia, including the resilient SA-6 mobile
surface-to-air missile batteries.
</P>
<P>
   A laptop computer details maps of Kosovo. Developed by the
National Imagery and Mapping Agency, the maps are used by officers
on the EC-130 to direct pilots to their targets.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the faulty maps that were blamed for the bombing of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade recently, these maps are so accurate
that an EC-130 was able to warn a search and rescue team about
electric power lines when they swooped in to extract the pilot of a
downed F-16.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Over the din of the plane, the crew use microphones and headsets
to squawk coordinates to each other and talk about the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody besides us is helping them out,'' said Brett, one of
the strike controllers. He said he supported NATO's mission to
return the ethnic Albanians to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But David Burns, a senior airman who was pulled out of law
school and activated by the National Guard for this duty,
disagreed: ``I am tired of being the world's policeman,'' he said.
``We have got our own problems at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, some of the people directing the attacks were
skeptical that air power alone would force the Serbs out of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make it very painful for the enemy,'' said Roles, the
operations officer. ``But as well as the Air Force performed in
Desert Storm, it was the Army that rolled across the border. You
can't win wars solely through airpower.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fighting along the Albanian-Kosovo border gave Roles
and the battle staff a chance to try.
</P>
<P>
   As the Serbs pressed their attacks, exposing their armor and
artillery, allied warplanes swooped in. The War Wizard was
preparing to direct the strikes when it encountered one of the many
snafus that can happen in a war. One of its antennas snapped and
began lashing the side of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to stay in the fight, the crew sought a quick fix. They
flew across the Adriatic to the Italian airfield in Brindisi,
chopped off the offending antenna and took off again for Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the EC-130 was back in the fray. Two Navy F-14s radioed
that they had spied Serbian armor in a ``no drop'' zone, meaning it
was so close to the Albanian guerrillas that they could not bomb it
without permission from senior commanders.
</P>
<P>
   The EC-130 battle staff radioed Mad Dog to get permission for
the F-14s, which rolled in and blew up a tank and an armored
personnel carrier.
</P>
<P>
   But as the battle progressed, not even Mad Dog was sure about
how hard to press the fight. The Vicenza command center initially
approved an air strike against Serb units that were only 700 meters
from the Albanian guerrillas but quickly concluded the risk of
hitting of KLA fighters was too great and called off the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Another glitch arose when Mad Dog sent the EC-130 a new list of
targets. After checking its maps, the battle staff radioed Mad Dog
that allied warplanes were about to bomb Albania. Soon a message
flashed across the targeting screens on the EC-130: ``Albania
targets withdrawn.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes prowled over the battlefield, as strike controllers,
intelligence officers and pilots on the EC-130 slipped through the
narrow aisle to raid their stash of sandwiches, pizza and junk
food.
</P>
<P>
   But as dawn approached, the Serbs appeared to have gone back
into hiding and the planes dumped their ordnance on secondary
targets, like border posts and antennas that would be touted in
NATO's press release the next day.
</P>
<P>
   As the War Wizard headed home, the crew looked forward to the 6
a.m. case of beer they would down after the last briefing. They had
been working the night bombing shift so long that daylight seemed
to be a novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some kind of a bright fiery object in the sky,''
Capt. Manuel A. Candelaria, the chipper pilot, quipped as the sun
rose over the Adriatic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2030EDT &QL; 
