<HEADLINE>
CORRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
 (lp) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A picture caption that moved Tuesday about a fire in Florida
left an incorrect impression about the location. The smoke
billowing on the horizon, over a higway in the foreground, was from
a fire near Venice, in west-central Florida on the Gulf of Mexico,
not in the Okefenokee Swamp, which is partly in northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Times News Service. June 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0558 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV0     06-02 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For release Sunday, June 6)  
 UNLIKE McCARTHY, REP. COX REFUSES TO EXPLOIT CHINESE SPY REPORT  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Out of the consternation and confusion over the
House report on Chinese spying in the United States, one undisputed
fact emerges: Rep. Christopher Cox is not Sen. Joseph McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, a thoughtful California conservative, has made no attempt
to exploit for domestic political gain his committee's revelations
that China purloined American technology data to boost the
effectiveness of its own nuclear weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he achieved the unthinkable in today's highly charged
partisan atmosphere when, with the indispensable cooperation of
Rep. Norman Dicks of Washington, the committee's ranking Democrat,
he won bipartisan support for the panel's report on its shocking
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's explanation for that amazing feat: ``Our report was
unanimous because we stuck to the facts. Things about which we
disagreed we simply left on the cutting-room floor because there
was so much that was incontrovertible fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican lawmakers have demanded the resignation of
Attorney General Janet Reno and National Security Adviser Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger, for supposedly failing to realize the gravity of
China's spying and to notify President Clinton of what was
happening. Some Democrats, including Clinton, have adopted a
share-the-blame policy, asserting, quite validly, that Chinese
spying flourished during the presidencies of Republicans Ronald
Reagan and George Bush, although apparently neither was informed.
</P>
<P>
   But so far the outrage expressed by political figures has been
relatively mild. Many lawmakers and some administration officials
have said they want to fire whoever mishandled information about
the Chinese espionage. But no one of any repute has questioned the
patriotism of government leaders.
</P>
<P>
   That undoubtedly is disappointing to those Republicans who hope
to parlay the Cox report findings into votes next year. A half
century ago, when the Cold War dominated world politics,
Republicans scored at the ballot box by accusing the Truman
administration and the Democratic Party of permitting communist
infiltration of the government and allowing the Soviet Union to
steal atomic secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The attack began when a young California congressman named
Richard Nixon began quizzing a respected State Department official
named Alger Hiss before the House Un-American Activities Committee.
Hiss denied that he ever had been a member of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet during the intensive interrogation, Nixon noted
inconsistencies and evasions in Hiss's testimony. Later that year,
Hiss was indicted for perjury and eventually was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue of communists-in-government exploded with nuclear
force on the night of Feb. 9, 1950, when McCarthy, an obscure
first-term Republican senator from Wisconsin, declared in a speech:
``I have here in my hand a list of 205 _ a list of names that were
made known to the secretary of state as being members of the
Communist Party and who nevertheless are still working and shaping
policy in the State Department.''
</P>
<P>
   His charge was pure fiction. He had no names and no numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But he hit the publicity jackpot and overnight became the
nation's premier communist hunter _ although he never sent any
communists to jail.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy, an uncouth man given to brawling and heavy drinking,
exploited for all it was worth the public's concern over the
aggression of the communists, who had been America's allies in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   It did not matter who got tarnished or hurt.
</P>
<P>
   To McCarthy, President Harry Truman, Gen. George C. Marshall,
two-time Democratic presidential nominee Adlai Stevenson, Secretary
of State Dean Acheson and other executive branch officials were
either traitors or what he called ``fellow travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   With his flair for hyperbole, McCarthy labeled America's
leaders, along with Moscow's spies, part of a conspiracy so immense
as to dwarf any previous such venture in history.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of the Hiss case, the fall of China to the
communists in 1949 and the 1952 conviction of Ethel and Julius
Rosenberg for passing atomic secrets to the Soviets further fueled
McCarthy's flaming assault on supposed security risks in
government.
</P>
<P>
   So did Truman's failure to move decisively against spies within
the government, and McCarthy's campaign had a strong following
across the land.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wisconsin firebrand's reign was short-lived. The 1952
election of Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower as president put a Republican
administration, headed by the most admired military leader of World
War, in charge of ending subversion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, McCarthy made the mistake of launching an investigation
of supposed security risks in the Army. The probe led to televised
hearings that demonstrated to the American people that McCarthy was
an unprincipled, undisciplined bully.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, the Senate voted to censure him for bad
conduct, and by 1957 he had drunk himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Cox is cut from far different cloth. The New York
Times described him as ``something of a Renaissance man ... who
speaks Russian, savors Ayn Rand and seeks out the latest
translation of Omar Khayyam.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox and Dicks have established an admirable mode of conduct for
congressional investigators. We can only hope their intensely
partisan colleagues will follow their example.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
