<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0565 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FORTDIX03-COX     06-02 1650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FORTDIX03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refugees expose general's soft side
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT DIX, N.J. _ Imagine a refugee camp, and you probably see a
crowded, dusty place, full of desperation and hunger and surrounded
by razor wire and armed guards. Imagine the Army general in charge
of such a camp, and you see a serious tough guy, a career Army man
who takes no guff.
</P>
<P>
   Now, forget those images. Fort Dix is no prison but instead a
true refuge for 4,000 Kosovars forced to leave their homeland in
Central Europe. And Brig. Gen. Mitchell Zais of Atlanta's Fort
McPherson is a soldier with a heart who calls the refugees
``guests'' and welcomes them with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Dix, a training center for the Army Reserve located between
Philadelphia and New York City, has been a temporary home since May
5 for refugees who will eventually go to cities around the United
States. There is no razor wire, or even a fence, but no one has
tried to escape. The refugees play soccer and chess and make new
friends. They have clean beds, an abundance of food, even a little
American money.
</P>
<P>
   They are not exactly happy: Most came here with only the clothes
on their backs, driven from their homes by Serbian troops bent on
cleansing Kosovo of ethnic Albanians such as themselves. But at
least they have hope, thanks to Fort Dix.
</P>
<P>
   Under Zais, chief of staff of the U.S. Army Reserve Command,
about 400 reservists, National Guardsmen and career soldiers are
running the ``hotel,'' or the accommodations for the refugees. But
the Army is not running the show: The U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services is in charge of Operation Provide Refuge and is
responsible for getting the refugees out of camps in the Balkans,
processing them at Fort Dix and then finding apartments and jobs
for them in other cities. But it is the responsibility of Zais and
his soldiers to ensure their stay at Fort Dix is a pleasant and
safe one.
</P>
<P>
   Lavinia Limon, director of the Office of Refugee Settlement for
HHS and in charge of Operation Provide Refuge, seemed glad to have
Zais commanding the Army's end of things. He's so, well,
un-Armylike, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hates mornings and he hates acronyms,'' she said. ``I
always ask, `Then why are you in this profession?'''
</P>
<P>
   Zais, a tall, graceful man who speaks English, not Army, has
cried often for the plight of his ``guests.'' With a doctorate in
psychology and a master's degree in military arts, he understands
where the refugees are coming from, psychologically and
historically.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we brought 400 soldiers here for this mission, we told
them not to think of chain-link fences and dusty refugee camps, and
not to think of illegal migrants,'' Zais said. ``These people are
here at the invitation of the president, and by extension the
American people. We should welcome them as we would have wanted our
great-grandparents welcomed at Ellis Island. In my mind's eye, I
keep seeing my grandmother coming down the gangplank from the
Ukraine. It's very moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Zais, the son of a four-star general, was born at Fort Bragg,
N.C., and grew up on Army bases around the country. At 52, he is
one of 11 generals from his West Point class of 800. He has been in
Atlanta for about a year with his wife, Susan, and two children,
Ashley, 12, and Bradley, 14.
</P>
<P>
   Zais was a rifle platoon leader during the Vietnam War. He has
served as a social aide to the White House, and he served in Panama
in the 1990s, when 10,000 Cubans were transferred to camps there
from the American base in Guantanamo, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, April 30, Zais was headed home from his office at
Fort McPherson to spend the weekend with his family. His son's
birthday was May 1, his wife's May 2. But instead of celebrating
their birthdays, he boarded a plane just after midnight, headed for
Fort Dix. He was told he had four days to prepare the camp for the
first flight of hundreds of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panic is perhaps too strong a word, but close,'' he said. The
United States is relocating about 20,000 of the hundreds of
thousands of refugees now living in camps in Albania and Macedonia
along the border of Kosovo. Some 4,000 of those have arrived at
Fort Dix to be processed and sent on to cities across the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers at Fort Dix went to work that weekend transforming
barracks into housing, hanging Welcome To America signs in the
gymnasium where the refugees would be processed, and transforming a
broken-down dining hall into a medical center.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the real work: Facing the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have lost all of their worldly possessions, their
language, their culture,'' Zais said. ``Some have lost family
members. They come here with those who have survived, with a bag of
clothes, and their faith. We try to build on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Robert Hagan, a reservist from Oregon, said the assignment
tests the nerves of a soldier in ways no combat could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here two weeks and I feel like it has been a year,''
he said. ``It's emotionally exhausting. You can't imagine this
happening to human beings. Someone back home said, `Well, you're a
soldier. You can handle it.' I said, `B.S., I'm a human being
first.'''
</P>
<P>
   On a steamy afternoon this week, Zais gave a tour of the camp to
the heads of charitable organizations leading the effort to find
more permanent housing for the refugees. They stopped by the area
where refugees, for whom an apartment or a house has been found in
an American city, prepare to leave. They have new, donated luggage
full of clothes. They each clutch a plastic bag containing a snack
for the bus trip to the airport. Many cry _ for their new friends
at the camp whom they might not see again, for Kosovo, which every
day seems further away, and for the future, which is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is scary for them,'' Zais said as he looked at the
refugees sitting in chairs in a large, featureless room, waiting
for their names to be called so they could board the bus. ``Here,
everything is easy, like summer camp. But when you go out, you have
to find a job, you have to learn English, your kids have to go to
school, and you are alone.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple approached Zais and spoke to him through his
interpretor, 2nd Lt. Adem Arslani, an American reservist originally
from Albania. They asked him what it's like in Seattle, where they
are headed. They were worried because it seemed so far away. Zais,
who went to graduate school at the University of Washington, told
them it is beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two directions, you can see mountains covered in snow,''
Zais said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the climate good?'' refugee Shaqir Syla asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it rarely snows,'' Zais said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, because this is difficult for us,'' Syla said. His
wife squeezed a tissue in her fist as her eyes filled with tears.
``Thank you for providing a safe place for us. We especially thank
the American soldiers. They were just incredible to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a nation of immigrants and refugees,'' Zais said. ``All
of our parents and grandparents came from somewhere else. Welcome
to America, and I know you will love Seattle. You will get used to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zais does not think most of the refugees will stay in the United
States if it becomes safe to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ``For these people, a tie to the land is a very strong force _
they will want to go back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Zais says he understands how tensions in Kosovo boiled into the
current conflict and says it is a story being repeated around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People of different ethnic backgrounds want
self-determination,'' he said. ``A lot of these borders were put up
with no regard to religion or enthicities, in Africa, in the
Balkans, in the Middle East. Now those countries are fragmenting.
At the same time, they are growing more economically
interdependent.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an opinion on NATO's bombing campaign against the
Serbs, Zais hesitated, but then said NATO likely will be forced to
send in ground troops, something the alliance is resisting.
``Bombing just strengthens people's resolve to resist,'' he said.
``It's a test of wills. I'm not optimistic this will remain a clean
and casualty-free campaign for NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Zais stood by a path that takes the departing refugees to the
bus. Lining the other side of the path, behind a makeshift fence,
were refugees who will stay, for now, at Fort Dix. They watched as
friends, some new, some old, walked uncertainly toward the bus.
Many cried, some sobbed and reached across the wooden slats of the
fence for a last touch, handshake or hug. As the refugees boarded
the bus, soldiers said goodbye as well; one looked up at the tinted
windows of the bus and located a friend. He reached up and placed
his palm on the glass, then he pantomimed that he would write
letters by scribbling with his finger in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Zais stood with his arms crossed, at first pointing out
portraits of poignant moments to a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that girl there who is saying goodbye to that boy,''
he said. ``And over there, the one with the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he stopped. No tears fell on his cheeks, but he sniffed
occasionally and did not speak again.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in his office, Zais said he often is overcome with
emotion at the camp. He wishes his children could have come to see
the faces of the refugees, so that they could understand more fully
the situation. But they are in school, and Friday, Zais finishes
his assignment here and returns to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to have a heart of stone not to be touched by
this,'' he said. ``But I feel good about this assignment, I really
do. You have such a sense of accomplishment. They have time to do
some healing here, and then they are ready to face a new challenge.
We are here to get them to face the future, and not the past.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
