</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAVINSKY-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONDUCTING STRAVINSKY: HIS OWN READING VS. OTHERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 6) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recordings of Igor Stravinsky conducting his own music date from
as early as 1928, when he was 46 and had few doubts about his own
significance. The composer continued to record his works until
1966, five years before his death.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially active in the studio during the 1950s and
early '60s, when Columbia invited him to record virtually his
complete operatic, orchestral, choral and larger chamber works
under optimal conditions as a lasting legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The strengths and weaknesses of Stravinsky's conducting, and
consequently, the value of these recordings as guides, have been
variously debated. To me, in terms of archival importance, this
discography, especially the Columbia recordings now reissued by
Sony Classical, is the greatest landmark in the history of recorded
music from the classical tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it. A composer who would make many critics' lists,
including mine, of the top five of all time has left us a recorded
document of his own thoughts about his entire output. Imagine if we
had records of Bach, Mozart or Beethoven performing their works:
not just some of them, all of them.
</P>
<P>
   Without being slavish about it, musicians can henceforth turn to
Stravinsky's recordings for rare insights and inspiration. Perhaps
there is no such thing as a definitive performance. Still, whatever
their flaws, Stravinsky's have awesome authority and are impossible
to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   Or so one would think. A new recording on the Philips label (289
446 715-2) offers Valery Gergiev conducting the Kirov Orchestra in
``The Firebird,'' Stravinsky's breakthrough ballet score from 1910.
In its sweep, conception of color, sense of organic drama and,
especially, spacious tempos, Gergiev's performance is notably
different from Stravinsky's.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this enthralling recording conveys its own sense of
authority. Gergiev is the artistic director of the Kirov Opera and
Ballet in St. Petersburg, called the Maryinsky Theater, where
Stravinsky's father, Fyodor, was a leading bass who created roles
in operas by Rimsky-Korsakov, Stravinsky's teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The music of ``The Firebird'' is steeped in Rimsky-Korsakov's
operas, especially ``The Legend of the Invisible City of Kitezh''
from 1907 and ``The Golden Cockerel'' from 1909, which, like ``The
Firebird,'' are fairy tales for adults, replete with a phoenix,
enchanted cities, captive princesses and infernal spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Musically, the Russian repertory of opera and ballet is
Gergiev's daily bread, though he has shown more affinity for
singers and the inner workings of opera than for dancers and the
staging of ballets. In his recording of ``The Firebird'' he stakes
a claim to the score as a Russian work, intent on showing us where
it came from.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize the point he includes Scriabin's ``Prometheus: The
Poem of Fire,'' another mystical Russian work that was most likely
on Stravinsky's mind when he composed ``The Firebird.''
</P>
<P>
   Gergiev's recording is not the only recent one to provoke
thoughts about defensibly different approaches to Stravinsky's
music. RCA Victor has just issued a three-disk Stravinsky set (for
the price of two) from Michael Tilson Thomas and the San Francisco
Symphony that includes ``The Firebird'' (09026-68898-2). And Sony
Classical, in its Masterworks Heritage series, recently released
``Stravinsky Conducts Stravinsky: The Mono Years, 1952-55,'' which
includes several works the composer would later re-record in
stereo, notably, the Neo-Classical Symphony in C. Still, Gergiev's
``Firebird'' is the most provocative performance of the group.
</P>
<P>
   The composer left several recordings of the work, but the best
overall was made in 1961 with the Columbia Symphony Orchestra
(currently available in Sony Classical's Igor Stravinsky Edition:
``Ballets, Vol. I,'' a three-disk set). As a point of comparison, a
1997 recording with Robert Craft conducting the Philharmonia
Orchestra is also revealing.
</P>
<P>
   This Musicmasters disk (01612-67177-2) is part of an invaluable
10-volume series of releases of Stravinsky's works conducted by
Craft, the composer's intimate friend and professional associate,
who assisted Stravinsky in his own recording sessions during the
Columbia project by preparing the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``The Firebird,'' adapted from Russian folklore by
the ballet's original choreographer, Michel Fokine, tells of a
Czarevich who wanders into the garden of the magician Kashchei in
pursuit of an enchanted Firebird, which he captures, then releases
in return for one of her feathers. That feather later enables the
Czarevich to summon the Firebird for help when he is captured by
the monsters who guard Kashchei's castle.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction to the work sets the tone for the story, and
highlights the differences between the recordings in question. The
low strings play a slow, soft motif in steady eighth notes, which
descends four notes (outlining the famously eerie interval of a
tritone) and ascends back, sometimes taking an extra upward turn.
It could be the Russian Impressionistic equivalent of a Baroque
ground bass.
</P>
<P>
   For all the regularity, it's unsettling. After four measures, a
two-note, chantlike figure in low trombones, marked even softer, is
played, then answered by a restless motif for two bassoons. All the
while, the mesmerizing ground bass continues.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky was careful to put precise metronome markings in his
scores to indicate the tempos he desired. The introduction to ``The
Firebird'' indicates that the eighth note is equal to 108 on the
metronome (or 108 beats per minute). Stravinsky's recorded
performance is just under that, and the character of the playing is
restrained, almost cool. Still, the sense of ominous inexorability
is strong.
</P>
<P>
   Craft's performance is actually more faithful to the score. It
is played at the exact metronome marking, and the dynamic level of
the trombone motif is, as requested in the score, even softer than
the pianissimo line for cellos and basses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
