<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PLANS TO COMMIT 7,000 PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite continued denials that NATO is preparing
for a ground war, top US military chiefs are preparing to meet with
Clinton on Thursday to discuss ``whether there should be or could
be a ground option'' among other strategies, Defense Secretary
William S. Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton announced that 7,000 US troops would
be a part of any military peacekeeping mission in the future in
Kosovo. In addition, the prime minister of Macedonia indicated for
the first time that his country would consider allowing NATO to
launch a ground war from Macedonian soil, a suggestion that added
to suspicions that a ground invasion is being prepared in case
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic rejects the peace process
underway in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be following the debate and discussion. And when the
proposal comes, we will have to put the proposal to the Macedonian
Parliament,'' said Macedonian Prime Minister Ljubco Georgievski.
Although it would be illegal under current law to launch a war from
his country, he said the issue would be reconsidered if NATO wanted
to invade Yugoslavia on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart Wednesday downplayed the
issue of ground troops, saying Thursday's meeting would focus on
the success so far of the air campaign. Other administration
officials again applauded the NATO effort and interpreted
Milosevic's willingness to talk to outside envoys as a sign that 10
weeks of airstrikes have started to wear him out.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, too, urged a Colorado Springs audience not to ``grow
weary of this campaign because Mr. Milosevic did not capitulate
when the first bombs fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have the patience and determination to match the courage
and skill of the men and women in uniform, we will achieve our
goals,'' Clinton said at the commencement speech at the Air Force
Academy.
</P>
<P>
   However, Cohen raised the specter of a ground war. Although
``there is no other planning'' underway, Cohen said Thursday's
meeting with Clinton will surely include ``a full range of
discussions, questions about whether or not there would be any kind
of a ground option for a nonpermissive environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, military planning continued for a mission in a
permissive environment _ one in which Milosevic would permit
peacekeeping troops to enter Kosovo to protect ethnic Albanian
refugees returning home.
</P>
<P>
   If a peace agreement is reached, NATO would send 50,000 troops
into the region, with 7,000 from the United States. Pentagon
officials Wednesday outlined the rapid action that would take place
in the event of a deal. Armed Marines would move immediately into
Kosovo, followed by Army tanks and combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   Some Marines, most likely from the 26th Marine Expeditionary
Unit in the Adriatic, ``could be there in a day,'' Pentagon
spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said. A permanent peacekeeping force
would move in later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what right now we see as the type of force that will
be self-contained and be able to provide the engineering
capability, the patrolling capability, the internal force
protection security capability that's necessary,'' Bacon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0352 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0572 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STRAVINSKY-MUSIC-2NDT     06-02 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRAVINSKY-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$ADV06-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and basses.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gergiev conducts the passage at a strikingly slower tempo (about
92 per eighth note). The sounds could be welling up from the center
of the earth. Yet he gives noticeable attention to a telling detail
in the score: two of the string basses are asked to play their
ground motif plucked, or pizzicato, lending a subtle rhythmic nudge
to each note. When the trombones enter, they are almost indistinct,
like some primordial moan. Though not quite what is indicated in
the score, the effect is riveting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what makes the Stravinsky performance ultimately so special
is countless gestures and nuances that are not in the score. For
example, in the introduction, when the trombone motif enters it is,
if anything, louder than the string basses. The trombonists play
the motif with extra, nervous little accents on the offbeat notes
and clipped cutoffs at the ends of phrases.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky's almost balletic way of handling this passage makes
sense, given his background as a child of the Maryinsky Theater. In
body and manner, Stravinsky walked and moved like a dancer, with
vigorous sudden gestures, even in old age, when his body grew
frail. He conducted this way, too, emphasizing biting rhythmic
detail and steady tempos.
</P>
<P>
   Another telling passage comes with the ruminative music of ``The
Firebird's Supplication,'' when the phoenix pleads to be set free.
Her song is conveyed first by a solo oboe and English horn, then by
the soaring violins and finally by the entire opulent orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanying this spiraling, sensual melody is an undulant,
rocking figure in triplets (marked 112 to the eighth note). The
composer must have decided that this was too fast, for his
performance is four metronome notches under that (96). Craft is
almost faithful (108), and the music sounds a bit pressed.
</P>
<P>
   Gergiev is much slower (about 84). Though the performance is
more expansive and impassioned than what Stravinsky may have
conceived, it has irresistible charisma. If this represents
unabashed interpretive freedom, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   The general pattern of contrasts between Stravinsky and Gergiev
continues throughout the work. Where the composer is exacting and
unsentimental, Gergiev is expansive, organic and vividly dramatic.
The Firebird's lullaby is beguilingly played: a slowish tempo, yes,
but one that allows for somber expressivity.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``Awakening Scene,'' when the spell that has been holding
princesses and warriors captive in Kashchei's castle is broken by
the Firebird, Gergiev turns the passage into something totally
coloristic, dramatic and evocative. There seem to be no pitches,
almost no rhythm, just an unearthly emerging growl.
</P>
<P>
   People who love this work and think they know it well may be
astonished by Gergiev's powerfully instinctive performance. Yet the
composer's performance is, by definition, incomparable.
Stravinsky's cooler, more Apollonian approach captures the music's
fancy in a movingly understated way.
</P>
<P>
   You feel that as a composer of 79 revisiting an early score, he
is making a statement about the place of this music in the context
of his life's work, calling attention to the Russian heritage he
came from and the French Impressionists he stole from, and
signaling the future.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas worked with Stravinsky and has been a devoted and
persuasive conductor of his works. His performances of
``Persephone'' and ``The Rite of Spring'' are technically brilliant
and stylistically informed. In ``The Firebird'' he is mostly
faithful to Stravinsky's metronome markings, departing from them
when only when his own ideas compel him to.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his account somehow combines a clearheaded energy, a sheer
excitement in amassing sound and color, and a playfulness about the
music's magical elements into something distinctively American.
There's a bit of Benny Goodman in the way the clarinetist plays the
slinky, teasing melody in the ``Dance of the Firebird,'' a
wonderful and perfectly legitimate touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stravinsky Conducts Stravinsky: The Mono Years'' is offered by
Sony Classical as a chance to hear the composer conducting several
major works when he was younger and less enfeebled than he became
during the 1960s sessions. But he was not that much younger (early
'60s). The 1952 recording of the Symphony in C, for example, is a
bit tauter, shapelier and more organic than that from 1962 with the
CBC Symphony Orchestra. But the later version, a drier, tarter
performance, seems more boldly modern. The tempos are remarkably
consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, like all musicians, Stravinsky reserved the right to
change his mind. The conductor Sir Colin Davis relates a story
about performing Stravinsky's ``Oedipus Rex'' for an audience
including the composer. After the concert, Stravinsky asked Sir
Colin, ``Young man, why did you take Jocasta's aria so slow?'' Sir
Colin answered that he was following the metronome mark. The
composer replied, ``My boy, the metronome mark is just a
beginning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0573 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-1STL     06-02 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRINCIPLES FOR ENDING WAR IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs 7th and 9th graphs to add comments from Rubin; 14th thru
18th graphs to add details of plan) RUSSIA AND THE WEST MOVE CLOSER(See also KOSOVO-PLANE) 
(rm) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Russia and the West on Wednesday narrowed their
differences over the concrete measures required to end the war in
Kosovo, limiting the room for maneuvering by Slobodan Milosevic,
the Yugoslav president, and increasing the pressure on him to reach
a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found a common approach,'' said Viktor S.
Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy to the Balkans, after a marathon
negotiating session in Bonn with American and European officials
that went on through much of Tuesday night and only ended
mid-afternoon Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said ``common approach'' was a
bit of an overstatement. But, the official said, the unity of
purpose was now sufficient to justify a visit to Belgrade late
Wednesday by Chernomyrdin and the Finnish president, Martti
Ahtisaari.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said that Russia had agreed for the first
time that all Yugoslav forces _ army, police and paramilitary _
should withdraw from Kosovo and that the withdrawal be
substantially under way before any pause in NATO bombing. Perhaps a
few hundred Yugoslav soldiers could return, but only after the
deployment of a 50,000-strong international peacekeeping force,
which would include 7,000 American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The West and Russia remain apart, however, on the composition
and the command structure of the peacekeeping forces. Russia is
holding out for a United Nations-controlled force; the West insists
that the force be effectively commanded by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Steiner, the top diplomatic adviser to Gerhard Shroeder,
the German chancellor, said diplomacy would now follow two main
tracks over the coming week: an attempt to secure Milosevic's
agreement to the terms reached by the West and Russia and an effort
to pass a United Nations Security Council resolution that reflects
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The plan that was presented to Milosevic ``preserved and
elaborated'' NATO's demands in their entirety, the State Department
spokesman, James P. Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   But it remained far from clear that Milosevic would agree to
terms that appear closer to NATO demands than to the vague
statement by the Group of Seven richest nations and Russia on May 6
that the Yugoslav government has formally accepted. That gap will
be the subject of Ahtisaari's discussions in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   How Milosevic would accept the plan presented to him was the
``$64,000 question,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made reasonable progress, particularly on the scope and the
timing of the Serbian withdrawal,'' said one U.S. official. ``The
Russians have understood that, for us, all means all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bonn talks were unexpectedly difficult and marked by
brinksmanship that saw Russia threatening to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   European diplomats said that Chernomyrdin argued for a pause in
the 71-day-old NATO bombing as a gesture of goodwill, but was
finally swayed by Western arguments that such a break would not
make Milosevic more pliant or more ready to negotiate in good
faith.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Russia agreed that the Serbian leader must start a
verifiable and substantial withdrawal of his forces before a halt
in the NATO bombardment could be declared.
</P>
<P>
   The plan specifies that Milosevic has to withdraw all his forces
from Kosovo, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also specifies how many days Milosevic has to show that
he is complying with a ``rapid and precise'' timetable of
withdrawal of his 40,000 troops for NATO to stop the air strikes, a
senior administration official said. The official declined to
specify the precise number of days.
</P>
<P>
   Once the withdrawal of Serbian forces had begun in a
``verifiable and demonstrable way'' NATO would be willing to stop
the bombing but reserved the right to resume, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyridin said Wednesday, ``I think at the moment there is a
realistic chance that the war will end.'' Strobe Talbott, the
deputy secretary of state, who has been shuttling between
Washington, Moscow, Helsinki, Bonn and Brussels, said,
``Increasingly the international community is speaking with one
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Russia and the West have shifted their area of
agreement from broad principles that were vague on crucial issues
to the outline of a concrete program to which Milosevic must now
respond.
</P>
<P>
   The principles adopted on May 6 did not stipulate that all
Yugoslav forces must withdraw and alluded only to the deployment of
``effective international civil and security presences'' in Kosovo,
rather than to a NATO-led peacekeeping force on which the Clinton
administration has insisted.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It was on the question of the make-up of the peacekeeping force
that differences with Russia proved most difficult, American
officials said. ``The Russians are still pushing for a United
Nations-controlled operation, but after Bosnia we learned the
lessons of watered-down command structures,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, between 1992 and 1995, a so-called ``dual-key''
system under which both NATO commanders and senior U.N. officials
had to approve any military action proved unwieldy, ineffective and
sometimes disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Belgrade, Chernomyrdin said that, under a
compromise reached in Bonn for the peacekeeping force in Kosovo,
``NATO will command NATO forces, Russia the Russian forces.
Relations between the two contingents will be governed by separate
agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steiner said this statement should not be taken at face
value. ``Obviously, each politician has his constituency that has
to be satisfied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   European and American officials said that a command structure
similar to the one now governing relations between Russian and
Western forces in Bosnia is being considered. This system involves
a NATO chain of command, although it gives the Russian contingent
there considerable latitude.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said a Russian proposal that it take charge of a zone
in the northern part of Kosovo while NATO countries control the
southern part of the province had been rejected because it might
appear to lay the basis for partition.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Steiner said it was now crucial to involve the United Nations.
``If what we have now is the basis for a solution, then we must get
it legalized in the Security Council as quickly as possible,''
Steiner said. ``That in turn will give us the political leverage we
need.''
</P>
<P>
   If a Security Council resolution could now be passed calling for
a complete Serbian withdrawal and the deployment of a large
international force with a central NATO presence, as well as the
return of all ethnic Albanian refugees, then the pressure on
Milosevic would clearly increase still further.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said that with such a resolution, a full and
formal agreement from Belgrade might not be necessary. ``All we
would need is the absence of a rejection from Milosevic and the
withdrawal of his troops from Kosovo,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains unclear whether China, whose relations with the
United States were soured by the bombing last month of its Belgrade
embassy by NATO, would agree to the resolution and whether wording
could be found that would circumvent Russian objections about the
nature of the peackeeping force.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the German foreign minister, said, ``We have
some good news, but I do not want to overrate it. We have to remain
skeptical until the last moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the West have come a long way since the first days of
the NATO bombing, when anger in Moscow was at fever pitch and
rumors were circulating that Russian missiles had been redirected
at European targets.
</P>
<P>
   However the diplomacy now progresses, immense difficulties
appear to remain, not the least being how to convince the divided
Albanian leadership and the Kosovo Liberation Army that any accord
with Milosevic is even remotely credible. The Serbs must also be
convinced that the rebel army can be disarmed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the West would apparently be committing itself to a
massive deployment of forces and huge investment of resources in a
state headed by a man indicted on charges of war crimes last week
by the international criminal tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari was expected to report on the results of his talks
with Milosevic to a summit meeting of European leaders in Cologne
on Thursday and Friday. The Finnish president is the highest-level
Western representative to meet with the Yugoslav leader since the
bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Chirac, the French president, said Wednesday that the
rapprochement between Russia and the West ``undoubtedly opens the
door to a significant chance for a political settlement. In this
situation, I cannot really see how the Serbian authorities could
refuse the solution demanded of them by the whole international
community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
