<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-JOURNALISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAPA URGES FULL INVESTIGATIONS IN UNSOLVED CASES OF SLAIN
JOURNALISTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW DOWNIE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A leading press organization called on the Mexican
government Wednesday to more thoroughly investigate the unsolved
killings of journalists and to clear up inconsistencies in the
slaying of a Texas newspaper reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials of the Inter American Press Association met with
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo and other high-level officials.
They asked Zedillo to step up the investigations. Twenty-six
Mexican journalists have been killed since November of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Between 95 percent and 97 percent of all journalist murder cases
in Latin America go unsolved, according to the IAPA. The
association, which has a membership of more than 1,300 newspapers
and magazines, is dedicated to defending freedom of expression
throughout the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The group's president, Jorge Fascetto, told reporters that
suspects arrested for killing journalists usually turn out to be
the trigger men, not the people who actually planned or ordered the
slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The IAPA delegation visited Mexico as part of a four-nation tour
that also includes stops in Brazil, Colombia and Guatemala, the
Latin American countries where violence against journalists is most
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 journalists have been killed in the region in the
past decade, Fascetto said.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the situation has deteriorated over the last two
years to the point that the country now ranks second only behind
Colombia in the number of journalists slain. Seven journalists were
murdered in Mexico in the last 20 months, IAPA officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These problems are very serious,'' Fascetto said after the
delegation's 50-minute meeting with Zedillo. ``We are very
concerned about them. They are the most serious crimes against
freedom of expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The group, in meetings with Zedillo and Mexico's Attorney
General Jorge Madrazo Cuellar, also raised concerns about the
investigation into the murder last December of Texas reporter
Philip True.
</P>
<P>
   True, 50, the Mexico City bureau chief for the San Antonio
Express-News, was found dead several days after heading alone into
the mountains of central Mexico to take a vacation and research a
story about the region's Huichol Indians.
</P>
<P>
   True, an experienced hiker, was walking through rugged terrain
along the border between Jalisco and Nayarit states when he
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   True's wife raised an alarm after he failed to call home as
scheduled. Mexican soldiers and police as well as True's colleagues
and relatives launched air and ground searches and found his body
at the bottom of a ravine.
</P>
<P>
   Two Huichol men, Miguel Hernandez and Juan Chivarra, were later
arrested and jailed on charges of strangling the reporter.
Investigators said the men attacked True while they all hiked
together near the village of San Miguel Huastita early in the
morning of Dec. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said the men were angry because True had entered
Huichol territory and was taking pictures of people without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez and Chivarra have given authorities at least four
versions of True's killing, and in three of them they admitted
slaying the reporter. Both men are jailed in Jalisco state awaiting
trial.
</P>
<P>
   As in many Mexican court cases, the investigation into True's
death was riddled with contradictions and inconsistencies. Most
worrying for IAPA officials are two separate and conflicting
autopsies performed on True by Mexican state and federal
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The first examination, performed by Jalisco state medical
examiners, concluded that True had been strangled to death. A team
of federal medical examiners ruled in the second autopsy that he
died of injuries to his head.
</P>
<P>
   Both autopsies reported that True, known to friends as a light
social drinker, had large quantities of alcohol in his system at
the time of death.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few days before the Huichol men were charged with True's
murder, a high-ranking official in the Jalisco state prosecutors'
office told Mexican reporters that the correspondent had frozen to
death after falling down drunk and failing to return to his camp
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there are questions remaining,'' Robert Rivard, the
Express-News' editor and an IAPA board member, said after
Wednesday's meeting with Zedillo. ``We don't know why there are
different autopsies, for example. (However), I think there is
overwhelming circumstantial evidence that these two (Hernandez and
Chivarra) are guilty.``
</P>
<P>
   The IAPA delegation was scheduled to meet with the Jalisco
governor, Alberto Cardenas, later Thursday to inquire about the
status of the True investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Rivard and other IAPA board members have already called on
Madrazo, the Mexican attorney general, to form a special unit
dedicated to investigating the murder of journalists. Madrazo has
promised to consider the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo and Zedillo both lent a sympathetic ear to pleas for
better treatment of journalists, Rivard said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle Vice President and Managing Editor Tony
Pederson, who will become president of the IAPA next year, said he
was optimistic that the meeting would help cement the relationship
between the IAPA and the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Zedillo received us very well,'' Pederson said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
