<SLUG> BC-BANKS-NORTHEAST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUNITY BANKS IN MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a surprise merger that forges a new Northeast banking
competitor out of two community institutions, Peoples Heritage
Financial Group Inc. of Portland, Maine, said Wednesday that it
would acquire the smaller Banknorth Group Inc. of Burlington, Vt.,
in a stock-for-stock deal valued at $712 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which boosts Peoples Heritage's size by one-third,
creates a full commercial bank with $17 billion in assets _ just $4
billion less than Citizens Financial Group Inc., the
Providence-based company that will soon be New England's
second-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   The combination also increases Peoples Heritage's attractiveness
to other banks that may seek to expand into New England as the
financial services industry consolidates further. Wall Street has
long viewed Peoples Heritage as a takeover target, especially as
larger national banks seek to acquire sophisticated smaller banks.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, the transaction removes Peoples Heritage,
the region's largest community bank, as a major bidder for branches
and deposits that will be divested when New England's two biggest
banks, Fleet Financial Group and BankBoston Corp., combine later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Heritage, an aggressive institution that has made four
acquisitions in the past two years, previously had said that it
wanted to buy a significant number of the 290 branches that
Fleet/BankBoston will shed to win antitrust approval of their
proposed merger. The combination will create the nation's
eighth-largest bank with $165 billion in assets _ 10 times the size
of Peoples Heritage.
</P>
<P>
   But Peoples Heritage preferred to buy a ready-made bank with a
full array of operations, rather than cast-off deposits and
branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we now have a diminished capacity to look at the
Fleet-BankBoston branches,'' said William J. Ryan, Peoples
Heritage's chairman and chief executive. He said that, at most, the
bank might bid on a few Massachusetts branches.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie H. Hunsicker, a banking analyst at Friedman, Billings,
Ramsay, &AMP; Co., said the company had moved to buy Banknorth, whose
chief executive is retiring, because it knew it could get squeezed
out of bidding for the assets by large, out-of-region banks.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Heritage ``is trying to become the premier community
bank in New England,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Heritage, a holding company that before Wednesday's deal
was New England's fifth-largest bank, has 221 branches, $12.6
billion in assets, and is the leading lender and deposit
institution in Maine and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The company comprises Peoples Heritage in Maine, Bank of New
Hampshire, Family Bank in north central Massachusetts, and SIS
Bancorp, which includes Glastonbury Bank &AMP; Trust in Connecticut, a
savings and loan in Springfield, and insurance operations.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said the bank had reached its goal of bulking up to the $15
billion to $20 billion asset range, though he did not rule out
further acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Banknorth owns eight community banks with 101 branches
throughout Vermont, New York, Massachusetts, and New Hampshire, an
investment management firm overseeing $4 billion, and a mortgage
lending unit. The company, which has grown rapidly through
acquisitions, has total assets of $4.4 billion. Its flagship bank
in this state, First Massachusetts Bank, based in Worcester, has
two dozen branches scattered throughout the central and western
parts of the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   By acquiring Banknorth, Peoples Heritage gains a stronger
presence in northern New England, with toeholds in Vermont _ where
it becomes the number two bank _ and in upstate New York, where it
is still only a minor player. The company also gains a bigger
presence in New Hampshire, where it dominates, and an entrance into
the Worcester area.
</P>
<P>
   Privately owned Citizens, by contrast, is focused on southern
New England, mainly Providence, Boston, and southern Connecticut.
But it will find new competition from Peoples Heritage in New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Heritage will still be only the fourth-largest bank in
Massachusetts, behind Fleet/BankBoston, Citizens, and UST Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to retain its customers, who favor the individualized
approach characteristic of community banks, Peoples Heritage will
not consolidate its branches under one name. But it will change its
holding company name to Banknorth Corp. _ a name reflecting a
broader geography ``that might make us more attractive to a
potential acquirer someday,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most community banks, Peoples Heritage is more than a
deposit-taker, and has a major lending portfolio. With the
Banknorth acquisition, it will have $10 billion in commercial,
consumer, and real estate loans, and home mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, which lost a quarter of its value in the
past 12 months, has long been deemed attractive and undervalued by
analysts. But Wall Street punished Peoples Heritage Wednesday,
sending its shares down 1 3/16 to end the day at 16 13/16 on
Nasdaq. Industry observers said the slide occurred because shares
in acquiring companies usually fall and because the Banknorth
acquisition would slash earnings by 4 cents per share in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Banknorth rose 2 5/8 to close at 29 3/8 on Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   Peoples Heritage declined to detail how it would boost revenues
or cut 30 percent of Banknorth's costs, but said the deal would
produce a one-time charge of $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts think Peoples Heritage overpaid for Banknorth, for
which it will swap 1.825 of its own shares for each Banknorth
share. When the deal was first announced Wednesday, that ratio
valued Banknorth at $32.85 a share _ equivalent to $780 million, a
23 percent premium to Banknorth's closing price on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The slide in Peoples Heritage shares Wednesday pushed the value
of the acquisition down to $30.68 a share by the end of the day.
Still, the decline doesn't make it cheap or easy for either bank to
opt out of the deal, which is scheduled to close later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies signed poison-pill agreements allowing them to
purchase 19.9 percent of each other's stock, a move designed to
thwart hostile bids. The two banks also opted for an unusually
large board of 21 members, six from Banknorth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised Peoples Heritage didn't negotiate the price
down a little bit,'' said Bruce W. Harting, a banking analyst at
Lehman Brothers. ``Ultimately, investors who stay with the company
are betting that it will be taken over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
