<HEADER>
A0584 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MANHEIM-SPI &LR;      06-02 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MANHEIM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH TO DISLIKE THE APPEALING HONESTY OF ACTRESS CAMRYN MANHEIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Camryn Manheim is one of my new favorite people. And
not because of what she says about reporters. OK, maybe a little
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the press,'' Manheim says on page 258 of her
autobiography, which cracked The New York Times best-seller list
last week. ``Niney-nine percent of the reporters I've met have been
really cool people that I'd like to hang out with.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to dislike someone who speaks the truth so
eloquently, so forthrightly.
</P>
<P>
   But for all her appealing honesty, Manheim also can be
confrontational, cynical and antagonistic. Don't take my word for
it. She says so on page 53: ``My behavior can, at times, be
confrontational, cynical, antagonistic.'' This, after already
admitting (on page 46) that she's blunt, nosy, demanding,
intimidating and aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   No biggie. Manheim is a rarity among actors in that she's always
happy to express an opinion. Where most TV stars are loath to weigh
in on anything other than the easy stuff _ motherhood, the
importance of flossing and getting a good time slot _ Manheim is a
walking, talking editorial page. Just don't ask her to ``weigh
in,'' or you'll get an earful of opinion laced with a favorite word
that rhymes with duck.
</P>
<P>
   Manheim's book is titled ``Wake Up, I'm Fat!'' Based on a
cathartic and therapeutic one-woman stage show she created four
years ago, it is a well-written, poignant, profane and enormously
effective treatise on self-acceptance by a woman who has every
right to be bitter and despondent. Though aimed at large people who
have suffered discrimination and low self-esteem all their lives,
it ought to be read by anyone who has ever had an unkind thought
about fat people, or has been party to a joke about fat people, or
has found a reason not to associate with fat people.
</P>
<P>
   As Manheim concludes in her last chapter, ``I have lived my life
in a culture that hates fat people. ... It's a miracle that I laugh
every day and walk through my life with pride and confidence,
because our culture is unrelenting when it comes to large people. I
don't understand it and I doubt I ever will. We hurt nobody. We're
just fat.''
</P>
<P>
   The pride and confidence Manheim speaks of have been abetted by
the Golden Globe and the Emmy she won last year for playing Ellenor
Frutt on ABC's ``The Practice'' (which also won the Emmy as best
drama). But don't assume that a chewy role and some glittering
trophies make her ineligible to address the difficulties faced by
those who carry more weight than society says they should.
</P>
<P>
   We all remember the line at the end of her Emmy acceptance
speech: ``This is for all the fat girls!'' But the words that may
actually resonate longer are: ``I have always felt like such a
misfit, and to get this award from my peers is such a huge
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Acceptance. We all crave it. From our parents, our friends, our
co-workers. Rare is the person who willfully courts derision and
scorn. But fat people get double doses of each. Every day.
Unsolicited. From the media. From well-meaning (and incredibly
insensitive) relatives. Even from complete strangers. At 38,
Manheim has so many stories that ``Wake Up, I'm Fat!'' _ at 289
pages _ is merely a trailer for the full-length feature of her
life, which was a skinny girl's life until she was 11 and living in
Southern California, where people go grocery shopping in bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   She was in Seattle last week to share some of these stories,
doing the obligatory author interviews and a reading at the
University of Washington. And before she could utter a word at the
reading, Manheim was basking in the acceptance of 200 or so wildly
enthusiastic fans who gave her a standing ovation and filled Kane
Hall with shouts and whistles.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Manheim's message of ``fat acceptance'' has found wide
acceptance. This gives her more confidence, more conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really feel my mighty force,'' she said after the reading,
``and that's what I try to infuse my friends with. ... I invite
controversy. I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   True to her words, Manheim inscribes ``Raise hell!'' inside most
of the books she autographs. There are exceptions, though. For
Jacob, a ``nice Jewish boy'' who gave up his place in line to a
woman on crutches, Manheim wrote: ``Jacob, see page 117. Love,
Camryn.''
</P>
<P>
   Page 117 is where readers will find Manheim's official boyfriend
application form. It's part of a chapter in which she tells about
``Doug,'' a capital-L loser she met through an ad in the personals
when she was living in New York, and whose picture should accompany
the dictionary definition of ``cockroach.'' (The night of his date
with Manheim, Doug had a ``backup'' date with another woman later
in the evening, just in case.)
</P>
<P>
   Tall, friendly and confident, the former Debra Manheim _ she
changed to Camryn after being Debi for two decades and hating it _
is even more out there than Frutt, the outspoken defense lawyer she
has played for three seasons on ``The Practice,'' whose growing
acceptance seems to mirror Manheim's story of personal growth.
</P>
<P>
   She already had emerged from years of self-loathing when she met
with the show's creator, David E. Kelley, in January 1996. Her
one-woman show was a hit, her appearance in the ``The Road to
Wellville'' had led to other film work, and she had long ago
stopped taking amphetamines to lose weight, convinced that being a
size 22 was better than being dead.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she considers her ``audition'' to be one of those
defining moments in life, mainly because she seized it and didn't
let go. As Manheim describes it, the meeting wasn't going well and
Kelley seemed more inclined to take a nap than chat. As she got up
to leave, she spied a cribbage board and asked Kelley _ she calls
him Mr. Michelle Pfeiffer _ if he played. He said he played against
the computer, implying that she'd be toast if she tried to take him
on. She suggested they play anyway. If she won, she'd get the part.
If he won, she'd disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley declined, but Manheim got the part. Kelley has since said
he created the role of Frutt specifically with Manheim in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when asked to give counsel to young people, whether it's
about acting or gaining self-esteem, Manheim's answer centers on
seizing the moment and flouting convention, provided no one else
gets hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``My best advice,'' she says, ``is to break the rules, ... raise
a little hell and get what you want. It's the only way you'll ever
get the brass ring.''
</P>
<P>
   On Manheim, the ring fits nicely, but she's not finished yet.
She's waiting for the day when her worth as an actor isn't linked
to her weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason they don't mention that Tom Cruise is 5-foot-8 in
reviews is because it doesn't matter,'' says the 5-foot-10 Manheim.
``I hope that someday my weight will be regarded as equally
irrelevant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
