A0587 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-VOTE-BOS &LR;      06-02 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANC SCORES BIG IN SOUTH AFRICA ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRETORIA _ South Africa swept a new generation of post-apartheid
leaders into power Wednesday in an election that solidified Nelson
Mandela's African National Congress in the closing days of his
rule.
</P>
<P>
   Results early Thursday confirmed the outcome that was widely
expected: Thabo Mbeki, Mandela's carefully groomed deputy
president, will succeed his boss on June 16.
</P>
<P>
   The mood around the country was decidedly less emotional than it
was five years ago, when the majority of South Africans cast
ballots for the first time in their lives _ and many whites,
fearful of black vengeance, added locks to their doors and canned
beans to their cupboards. This time, simple enthusiasm and goodwill
reigned, and voting proceeded with few irregularities or hints of
factional violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel absolutely wonderful. It is an exciting day,'' said
Mandela, the legendary campaigner against apartheid who rose from
decades of imprisonment to become elected president five years ago.
``The feeling is not as intense as in 1994, because then I
exercised my right to vote for the first time. Now I feel
comparatively relaxed. I feel proud. I voted for South Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Mbeki's ascension was never in doubt, two questions
were harder to answer early Thursday: Would the ANC gain a lock on
both parliament and the nine provincial governments? Which minor
party would emerge as the official opposition party?
</P>
<P>
   The road to Wednesday's election was bumpy. The head of the
Independent Electoral Commission, Judge Johan Kriegler, resigned in
a dispute with Mbeki over government encroachment in the process.
Later, two opposition parties appealed to the Constitutional Court,
South Africa's highest tribunal, to annul new identification
requirements for voters.
</P>
<P>
   But when the day for casting ballots arrived, remarkably few
problems arose. Despite months of apparent voter apathy and in
spite of chilly, blustery winter weather on election day, long
lines formed outside polling stations hours before they opened, and
many of the 14,000 locations stayed open past the official closing
time to accommodate thousands of voters who still had not cast
their ballots. More than 18 million South Africans had registered
ahead of the election.
</P>
<P>
   The government deployed more than 100,000 police and military
personnel throughout the country to minimize disruptions.
Opposition leaders made scattered allegations of fraud, but
election officials Thursday night reported no major irregularities
or incidents of violence, unlike the street fighting and bombings
orchestrated five years ago by both right-wing groups and rival
factions of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between 1994 and now is that we have the chance
to vote without intimidation,'' said Mike Maseko, among thousands
standing in a line outside the library in the Johannesburg township
of Vosloorus. ``There is no factional fighting this time. People
are beginning to understand what the vote is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago the masses voted for their liberation from
repressive white minority rule. Wednesday they voted their wallets.
In line after line across the townships on the industrialized
flatlands east of Johannesburg, people said the main factor
determining how they voted was jobs. Unemployment in South Africa
hovers near 40 percent, and the economy is growing at less than 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not feeling good today,'' said Elliott Gxabuza, who voted
in the township of Greenfields. ``I have no work, no money, no
house. I am crying for work.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a polling station in Vosloorus, Dora Siboyana
uttered her protest. ``I voted for the New National Party, because
it is led by a white man,'' said Siboyana, who is black. ``I don't
want the ANC. The black leaders have given us nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same station, Laetia Ndlamla gave the opposite view:
``The ANC is the only way to go. We suffered for 48 years under the
white government. People expect changes overnight, but that is not
possible. No one can do it better than Mandela.''
</P>
<P>
   The ANC sought a two-thirds majority in the legislature to
accelerate the pace of reforms to education, labor, and the
economy. The party shed its broad-based appeal for reconciliation,
the predominant theme of Mandela's presidency, and campaigned on a
platform of aggressive social transformation for the impoverished
black majority.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party also wanted to take control of the two
provincial governments under opposition control, thereby weakening
its rivals in Zulu stronghold of KwaZulu-Natal and the
Afrikaner-based Western Cape. Initial results indicated that the
ANC would take neither province.
</P>
<P>
   Four parties jockeyed ahead of a large pack of inconsequential
rivals. The Democratic Party, appealing to conservative whites,
hoped to knock out the New National Party, a makeover of the group
that led South Africa under apartheid for 48 years and emerged as
the leading opposition to the ANC after the last election. An
upstart, the United Democratic Movement, portrayed itself as the
only party without ties to the past, having been created in 1997.
The early numbers indicated that none of these parties enjoyed more
than regional support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
