<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEE-BAROUH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE STUDENT FALTERS IN 1ST ROUND OF NATIONAL SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: UPDATES pvs story with quotes)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lena Barouh, 13, an eighth-grader at Washington
Middle School in Seattle, failed Wednesday to make it into the
second round of the 72nd National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   A contest judge threw her a killer word: ``erubescent,'' an
adjective meaning blushing or reddening.
</P>
<P>
   She spelled it A-R-E-O-B-E-S-C-E-N-T.
</P>
<P>
   Later she explained the mistake by saying that either the
pronouncer, one of the judges, ``didn't pronounce the word right or
I didn't hear it right.''
</P>
<P>
   But she and her father both said they were proud of her
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who got here is a good speller,'' she said. ``We
wouldn't have gotten here if we weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Barouh, who was sponsored by the Seattle Post-Intelligencer,
will still receive $50 and a commemorative watch for her efforts.
She became eligible for the national contest after winning a
regional spelling bee in April.
</P>
<P>
   She was among 249 contestants whose week-long trip to the
nation's capital was financed by their sponsoring newspapers.
Barouh and 144 other spellers were eliminated during Wednesday's
three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Barouh _ who writes poems, sings and plays the violin _ said she
wants to pursue a career in music. Her mother, Ellen Mohl Barouh,
is a real estate agent, and her father, Aaron Barouh, manages a
shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   The National Spelling Bee's champion, who will be determined
Thursday, will receive $10,000 and a choice of encyclopedias and
other prizes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
