<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0593 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH0603-COX     06-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH0603-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investigators to explore weather's role in plane crash
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Federal investigators will focus today on
what role the weather may have played in the fatal crash of
American Airlines Flight 1420, which slid off the runway late
Tuesday night amid a fierce hailstorm, broke into pieces and caught
on fire. At least nine people, including the pilot, were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators want to know what pilot Richard Buschmann was told
about the violent weather before he attempted to land the plane at
the Little Rock airport.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, which had been delayed for nearly two hours in Dallas
because of severe weather, approached from the southeast. A severe
thunderstorm was headed toward the airport from the northeast about
the same time, producing a ``crosswind,'' said George Wilkin,
science and operations officer for the National Weather Service
office just across the Arkansas River from the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a big crosswind,'' said Richard Klamm, 49, of
Pine Bluff, a passenger in the first-class section. ``I think the
pilot just lost control of the plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 145 passengers and crew on board the Dallas to Little
Rock flight, 83 people were treated at local hospitals, mostly for
cuts and burns. Another 51 uninjured people were reunited with
friends and relatives in a theater at a nearby aerospace museum. At
least two people remained unaccounted for late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary list of 118 survivors released by American
Airlines late Wednesday gave hometowns for about one-third of those
named.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plane was going so fast, when we hit the ground, we went
off the end of the runway,'' said passenger Barrett Baber, who was
returning from a trip to Germany with other members of the Ouachita
Singers from Ouachita Baptist University at Arkadelphia. ``We hit a
huge pole, and it split the plane in half. A fire started at the
front of the plane and spread back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the smoke got too thick,'' Baber said, ``there was
nothing we could do. People were screaming, `God, please save
us!'''
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines Flight 1420 had approached Runway 04 Right as
a severe thunderstorm raged just before midnight Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As the twin-engine, McDonnell Douglas Super 80 touched down,
heavy rain had reduced visibility to about one mile, Wilkin said.
Four-tenths of an inch of rain fell in just three minutes, right
around the time of the accident, Wilkin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an extraordinary amount of rain to have in that period
of time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 minutes before the plane hit the runway, the area had
been placed under a severe thunderstorm warning, Wilkin said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Chicago-based pilot Richard Buschmann, who was killed
in the crash, didn't circle to avoid the violent weather, National
Transportation Safety Board member George W. Black Jr. said that
would be ``assuming he knew it was here.''
</P>
<P>
   A wind gust of 87 mph was recorded at the airport around 11:56
p.m. _ roughly six minutes after the crash. Still, federal
investigators haven't blamed the crash on turbulent weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you can glean from that is that there was
active weather at the time,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, investigators will examine the wreckage again and allow
reporters to see the plane's broken hull, which was sliced open
like an aluminum drink can along its left side. Investigators also
will listen to audio tapes of air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
   The flight data and cockpit voice recorders arrived in
Washington on Wednesday. The instruments captured ``good data'' and
transcripts will be developed in the next several days, Black said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines' chief pilot said he would not have attempted
to land the plane if wind speeds exceeded 57.5 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone told me there were 50-knot gusts at the airport, I
would be leaving town,'' Cecil Ewell said at a news conference at
Fort Worth, Texas. Ewell oversees all of American Airlines' pilots.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service said it warned the tower of the
approaching storm. Bob Baker, the airline's executive vice
president of flight operations, said that weather dispatches were
relayed to the flight crew, but specifics of those conversations
have not been released.
</P>
<P>
   William Shumann, a spokesman with the Federal Aviation
Administration, said there was no distress call from the cockpit
before the landing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It struck a number of structures,'' Black said. The plane
rotated nearly 180 degrees before stopping.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Snowden, a district fire chief, said the 16-year-old plane
split into two after hitting approach lights at the end of the
runway. The left side of the fuselage was ripped open.
Firefighters, who reached the scene in about six minutes, according
to Black, used foam to put out the fire.
</P>
<P>
   FAA records show the plane had been involved in one previous
incident, which was non-fatal. An engine failed in 1987 during a
safe landing in Las Vegas. Worn turbine housing caused that
failure, investigators concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Choir member Baber, seated in row 30, said the flames were
within 15 feet of him by the time he got out 30 seconds after the
landing. Some passengers getting off the plane found themselves in
waist-deep water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was panic, craziness, there were flames,'' Baber said.
``The emergency door was cracked, and people were able to get out
only one at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, President Clinton said he and Hillary Rodham
Clinton were saddened to learn of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We join the American people in extending our deepest
sympathies to the families of those who died or were injured,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The deaths are the first in an U.S. commercial airline accident
since Dec. 28, 1997, when a woman was killed aboard a United
Airlines 747 that encountered severe turbulence over the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. aviation officials celebrated a fatality-free
year aboard scheduled U.S. commercial flights. U.S. airlines also
had one of their safest years ever in 1997, a year after one of the
deadliest on record.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
