<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEE-BAROUH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PILONCILLO' LEAVES BITTER TASTE FOR SPELLING CONTESTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Andrew Shawhan, a seventh-grader from Delmar, N.Y.,
stumbled Wednesday on ``piloncillo'' in the 72nd National Spelling
Bee, but vowed to give the competition another shot next year.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the word, Andrew, 13, concentrated and asked for a
definition. The word refers to a hard candy made of brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting a moment, he asked for the word's origin. The answer:
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew hesitated, then began to spell the world.
</P>
<P>
   P-I-L-O-N-C-I-L-O.
</P>
<P>
   He was one ``l'' short, and in this contest of words and nerves,
the bell sounded, indicating an incorrect answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bethlehem Central Middle School student glanced at the
pronouncer, shook his head and walked off stage to the ``comfort
room'' for the contestants.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew didn't stay in the room long. Emerging after only a few
minutes, he was immediately surrounded by his family, including his
brother, Mark, who competed in the bee two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is luck of the draw and which words you are
given,'' said Andrew, who will take home $50 and a commemorative
watch.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, who still faces final exams later this month, kept the
competition in perspective. ``It's not like we're getting graded up
there or anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew and his older brother, who lost on the French-origin word
``brume,'' which means mist or fog, even managed to joke about the
words that they misspelled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He studies French and was knocked out by a Spanish word; I
study Spanish and was knocked out by a French word,'' Mark, 15,
said. ``Each of us would have easily known the other word.''
</P>
<P>
   Although promising to compete again next year, Andrew said he
was going to take some time off before studying again. ``I need a
break for awhile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew has earned a green belt in Judo and listens to music
ranging from the English composer Gustav Holst to the American
rapper group the Beastie Boys.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's father, Peter B. Shawhan, a lawyer with the New York
Department of Transportation, said he drilled his son on spelling
for weeks before the competition but stopped once they arrived in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, the best part of this is the kids having a chance to
experience the nation's capital and seeing the actual places where
so much history has taken place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's mother, Joanne Parnes Shawhan, a school librarian, said
she was glad the competition was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys learn so much from it and have done so well, but by
the end, we're all pretty tired of it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the National Spelling Bee, sponsored by the E.W.
Scripps Co., will receive $10,000 in cash and other prizes.
</P>
<P>
   Following the first day of competition, 104 of 249 contestants
remained.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
