A0597 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-DAVIS-LB     06-02 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-DAVIS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS AUDITIONS FOR CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Despite the haystack of evidence in his favor,
Baron Davis was obliged to drag the burden of proof into USC's Lyon
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my first time doing this, so I was kind of nervous,''
the ex-UCLA star admitted Wednesday after nearly two hours of
on-court auditioning for the Clippers. ``I just wanted to come in
and no matter what work as hard as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's take a left turn at this concept of ``work.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a 6-foot-2 (legit) point guard with game galore, decided
to enter the workforce last month, forsaking his final two years of
college eligibility to make a living in the NBA. Wednesday was his
first official job interview for teams that will consider Davis for
employment via the NBA Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the roles were transposed: Davis, the Gatorade
National High School Player of the Year while at Crossroads in
Santa Monica, would visit a university whose basketball staff
behaved like skinny car salesmen in a quiet showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a prospective employee expected to be worth millions, it
is incumbent upon Davis to demonstrate that he's worth the pick.
The Clippers have the fourth selection in the June 30 draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big difference,'' Davis said. ``Here, you have to
showcase what you can do, so you basically have to be on top of
your game.''
</P>
<P>
   The specifics of Davis' game are what interest Elgin Baylor, the
Clippers' vice president of basketball operations. At a time when
many severely hyped point guards arrive with high-maintenance egos,
Davis hits the market having played the position since the days
when his Nikes were small enough to swing from the rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a factor,'' Baylor said of Davis' status as a
card-carrying, pass-first point guard. ``He has the point-guard
mentality. There's no question that he has point-guard skills.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the only questions trailing Davis involve his improving
perimeter stroke and that left knee, the wheel he injured in the
last game of his freshman season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee feels great ... one-hundred percent,'' said Davis,
whose post-UCLA regimen of weight lifting and skill building
appears to have put him in fighting trim. Also conspicuous by its
absence was the bulky knee brace that went along for his sophomore
ride. Davis did have to deal with the last hurrahs of a head cold
that compromised his usual on-court energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gamer,'' Baylor said. ``Being in the same city, we know
what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   And being in the same city has allowed Davis to be very aware of
what the Clippers have done. Davis publicly, at least continues to
insist he would embrace the challenge of building another winning
franchise in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love it,'' he said of playing for the Clippers. ``I
think it's a new era. The Clippers have a lot of young talent; I
think I could help in a lot of different ways. Turning it around
here would be an accomplishment I would like to be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, for the record, he also wouldn't mind playing for the other
NBA team that will move into the new Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to play here in my hometown,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona point guard Jason Terry will trot out his stuff for the
Clippers today, with Miami of Ohio forward Wally Szczerbiak due
Friday. Corey Maggette, the high-flying swingman who is leaving
Duke after his freshman season, is expected to visit in about two
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
