<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0599 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-     06-02 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-ABRIDGED-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH BY PRESCRIPTION: AN OVERWHELMED SYSTEM CAN PRODUCE FATAL
ERRORS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.J., R.I., Va., N.C., Wash., Ohio, Colo., Mass.)   (editors: The longer version, about 4,100 words, moved earlier.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic on rise
in prescriptions and decline in pharmacists is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health care experts and federal regulators are
increasingly concerned about the tens of thousands of Americans who
are killed each year not by illness, but by medication intended to
treat it.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1997, Helen McLaughlin, a widow who lived in Elizabeth,
N.J., walked into the pharmacy department of the local ShopRite
supermarket to fill a prescription for chlorpromazine, an
anti-psychotic medication. According to her son Charles and a
lawyer who is suing ShopRite on behalf of her family, she walked
out with a drug that has a nearly identical name, chlorpropamide,
which is used by diabetics to lower their blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   It was a particularly serious mistake, the family said. Mrs.
McLaughlin suffered from diabetes, and was already taking
medication for it. She took the new drug in addition to her regular
pills for three weeks when she was admitted to Elizabeth General
Medical Center with dangerously low blood sugar. That, McLaughlin
said, unleashed a cascade of health problems for his mother,
including stomach ulcers and a drug-resistant bacterial infection.
She died on May 20, 1997. She was 73.
</P>
<P>
   There is no failsafe system to prevent prescription errors, a
fact that is becoming apparent to the Food and Drug Administration
and independent drug safety experts. They say Helen McLaughlin's
death highlights a pervasive and dangerous problem: with more
medications on pharmacy shelves than ever before, and more
prescriptions being written, the nation's health care system is
overwhelmed, creating a growing risk that patients will be killed
or hurt by adverse reactions or mistakes. Regulators, even after
approving a new drug, cannot always predict all potential side
effects, or toxic interactions. Many pharmacists are overworked,
and filling more prescriptions with less help. And with as many as
a dozen medications available for any one ailment, doctors are
having a hard time keeping abreast of FDA warnings about possible
risks.
</P>
<P>
   The true scope of the problem is unknown, in part because
hospitals and doctors are not required to report it.
</P>
<P>
   But recent studies lead scientists to think that prescription
drugs are killing and injuring far more people than previously
believed, and experts estimate two-thirds of the deaths and
injuries could be prevented. Last year, a study in the Journal of
the American Medical Association estimated that 106,000 hospital
patients die and 2.2 million are injured each year by adverse
reactions to prescription drugs, not including cases where errors
are involved. The estimate was the first of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   In a recently released 150-page report, the FDA called upon
pharmacists, doctors, hospitals and drug companies to work together
to create ``a new framework'' for cutting down on the risks from
the drugs the agency approves. On June 1, the FDA implemented a new
rule requiring the manufacturers of some especially risky drugs to
distribute explicit warning pamphlets to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmaceutical manufacturers are discovering new ways to treat
more diseases and conditions, from impotence to diabetes. The FDA,
long criticized as moving too slowly on drug applications, is now
approving products at a record-setting pace. And patients are
living longer with illnesses that could once not be treated.
</P>
<P>
   More prescriptions are being written, not only because there are
more drugs but because the population is aging; the elderly take
more than one third of all drugs that are prescribed. In 1992,
according to the National Association of Chain Drug Stores, 2.03
billion prescriptions were dispensed in retail pharmacies; by last
year, the figure was up to 2.78 billion. By the year 2005, the
association estimates, it will be 4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacies, pressed like other health care providers by the cost
controls of managed care, are struggling to fill the higher volume
of prescriptions in less time, and with less help. ``I worked
12-hour days, and if you get to the bathroom once a day, you're
fortunate,'' said Adle Joseph, a pharmacist at the Leesburg
Pharmacy in Leesburg, Va., who spent 35 years with the Rite Aid
chain before retiring last year to join a slower-paced, independent
store. ``The conditions are just not conducive to good safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, too, are overloaded. Two decades ago, physicians
familiarized themselves with a relatively small pharmacopeia and
prescribed the same drugs again and again. Today, the choice of
medicines rests not only with doctors, but also with managed care
companies, which buy drugs in bulk to reduce costs and list them on
formularies that can change each month.
</P>
<P>
   At the Veterans Administration Medical Center in Providence,
R.I., Dr. Jeannette Chirico-Post, the hospital's chief of staff,
says she is concerned about how complicated prescribing drugs has
become. ``We have more drugs at our fingertips,'' she said, ``and
the potential for drug-drug interaction is far greater than we saw
10 or 15 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   And while computer technology is available to help physicians
avoid mistakes and screen for dangerous combinations of drugs, few
hospitals and even fewer private doctors have it. Those that do say
the systems can produce so many false alarms they are nearly
impossible to work with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are using medications in ways that we never used them
before,'' said Michael Cohen, president of the Institute for Safe
Medication Practices, a nonprofit organization investigates
prescription drug errors. He said the mistake in Mrs. McLaughlin's
case could have been avoided with clearer labeling.
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of ways that people can be killed or injured
by their medicine. Outright mistakes are one; some experts say
these medication errors account for a third to one half of all
cases. Known side effects, including dangerous interactions between
drugs, are another. Unforeseen side effects, which do not turn up
in testing but become apparent after a drug comes into widespread
use, are a third.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Collectively, these are known as ``adverse drug events,'' and in
recent months, the Food and Drug Administration has been troubled
by a string of them:
</P>
<P>
   _ Posicor, a high blood pressure medicine, was withdrawn from
the market last year, but not because the drug was harmful on its
own. Rather, Posicor became lethal in combination with a long list
of other drugs, so many that the FDA felt that doctors and
consumers could not keep abreast of the risks. FDA officials said
that 24 people taking Posicor in the 11 months it was on the market
had died, and that two or three of those deaths were directly tied
to Posicor, although a spokeswoman for Roche Laboratories of
Nutley, N.J., the drug's maker, has said ``no causal link'' was
demonstrated.
</P>
<P>
   _ The diabetes drug Rezulin, approved two years ago, can cause
liver damage, which prompted the FDA to issue repeated warnings to
doctors to closely monitor patients taking it. But an agency
investigation found that doctors were not listening; only 2.7
percent of patients taking Rezulin for three months were being
monitored according to the agency's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   At a hearing in March, the FDA and Rezulin's manufacturer,
Parke-Davis, a division of Warner-Lambert Co. of Morris Plains,
N.J., agreed that 43 people had suffered acute liver failure that
was possibly due to the drug; of these, 28 died. A panel of
independent scientific experts has recommended that the drug be
prescribed only to patients who do not respond to other therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no one in health care is as acutely aware of the
potential harm of prescription drugs than pharmacists. Yet
pharmacists say little attention is paid to the difficulties they
face in today's complex health care environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Leesburg Pharmacy , is a case in point. On a recent
afternoon, half a dozen patients were lined up waiting for their
prescriptions to be filled; others milled about the store. Behind
the counter, 49 prescriptions were in one stage or another of
preparation. ``And this is a slow day,'' said chief pharmacist Greg
Chase.
</P>
<P>
   Leesburg is an independent pharmacy and, like pharmacies around
the nation, its profits are being squeezed by lowered
reimbursements from managed care companies. So it makes up the
difference in volume. The store fills about 300 prescriptions per
day, a 50 percent increase from three years ago, according to its
owner, Bruce Roberts. He said that leaves little time for
pharmacists to talk to patients about how to take their medication,
something experts say is essential if drugs are to be used safely.
Chase came to the Leesburg Pharmacy two years ago from a chain drug
store, CVS, where three pharmacists filled 600 prescriptions per
day and often worked 12 hours straight to do it. ``You've gone four
to five hours without even a chance to go to the restroom,'' he
said. ``Your mind is fried.''
</P>
<P>
   CVS Pharmacy, which owns 4,100 drug stores in the United States,
and Rite Aid Corp., which owns 3,800 stores, said they have no
evidence that more mistakes are being made. But they are concerned
about workplace pressures, and are taking steps to ease the burden.
As members of the National Association of Chain Drug Stores, the
companies are also sponsoring research by a University of
Cincinnati psychology professor who is examining ways to reduce
pharmacy errors.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, Tony Grasha, said in an interview that mistakes
occur when psychosocial factors, such as stress at home, combine
with a higher workload. He said his studies show errors are rare,
about 0.5 percent of all prescriptions filled, and that those that
pose a danger to patients are rarer still. But, he said, with the
number of prescriptions growing, mistakes are serious concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tiny fraction percentage-wise,'' he said, ``but when
you are filling 3 billion prescriptions a year and are anticipating
4 billion by the year 2005, then even a very small percentage is a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Computers are an important part of the pharmacy safety net, but
they have limitations. When Chase typed in the name of a
23-year-old patient who had been prescribed an anti-psychotic
medication, his computer issued a warning that the drug could be
dangerous in combination with another prescription in the patient's
file.
</P>
<P>
   But the system presumes that a patient goes to the same pharmacy
every time. And the computers raise so many red flags, without
distinguishing the serious from the benign, that pharmacists grow
weary of them and start to ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like crying wolf,'' said Susan Winckler, director of
policy and legislation for the American Pharmaceutical Association,
which represents 52,000 pharmacists. ``Some pharmacists call it
`the right hand syndrome.' You just hit the return key when you see
the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lucian Leape, a health policy analyst at the Harvard School
of Public Health, believes that the health care system can be
designed to minimize mistakes and drug dangers. He said, ``Errors
are symptoms of a sick system, not a sick person. Humans make
mistakes. To the extent you can redesign around that, you can get
rid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, the FDA could require pharmaceutical
companies to standardize their drug labels for easy reading.
Medicines could come with bar codes, so that pharmacists could use
scanners to check for the correct name, the same way a grocery
store clerk scans a jar of pickles. Doctors could trade their
prescription pads in for computers.
</P>
<P>
   These ideas are beginning to catch on in some unlikely places.
Two years ago, the Department of Veterans Affairs launched a major
patient safety initiative designed, in part, to minimize
prescription drug errors at the nation's 172 veterans hospitals and
clinics. Over the next two years, the department intends to spend
$40 million on technology that will allow doctors to use computers
to write their prescriptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
