<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGO-PEACE-BOS &LR;      06-02 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVOYS DELIVER PEACE PLAN TO MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ Russian and European envoys Wednesday night handed
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic what they described as a
peace plan and what they hope is a face-saving way to end the war
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The two envoys are expected to resume discussions with Milosevic
on Thursday, and the Serbian parliament is scheduled to debate the
peace plan, which calls for the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from
Kosovo and the creation of a peacekeeping force that will include
troops from NATO nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced Wednesday that he would increase the
US commitment to the peacekeeping force from 4,000 to 7,000 troops
and added 68 US aircraft to NATO's forces.
</P>
<P>
   If accepted by Milosevic, the deal would be formally approved by
the United Nations, allowing the leaders of NATO countries to
sidestep the awkwardness of having to sign an agreement also signed
by an indicted war criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Some sticking points remain: how many Serb forces will be
allowed to stay behind in Kosovo, and what will be the composition
and placement of the international peacekeeping force that is meant
to encourage the return of some 1 million ethnic Albanians who were
expelled by Serb forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russians favor putting their troops in northern
Kosovo, and leaving southern Kosovo to NATO forces, US and British
officials Wednesday said that would amount to a de facto partition
of Kosovo, a prospect which NATO General Secretary Javier Solana
has ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin and the European envoy,
Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, met Wednesday evening with
Milosevic for just two hours, a brief encounter by Milosevic's
usual marathon standards. An aide to Ahtisaari said the meeting was
not a negotiating session, but simply an attempt to explain the
offer to Milosevic. The aide said they would meet again Thursday
with Milosevic to clarify questions raised Wednesday night by
Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari and Chernomyrdin were expected to arrive in the
Yugoslav capital Wednesday morning but did not get here until late
afternoon as the Western allies and Russia tried to hammer out
their differences in Germany. Ahtisaari is scheduled to return to
Germany later Thursday to brief a summit of European Union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting with Milosevic, Ahtisaari said an all-night
bargaining session between Russia and the western allies in Bonn
had been productive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've reached a largely common position,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian officials and those from NATO countries,
particularly the United States and Britain, remain divided on the
placement and composition of the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said, ``There will be two separate presences in
Kosovo, a NATO presence and a Russian presence.''
</P>
<P>
   But US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott, who had held
two days of talks with Ahtisaari and Chernomyrdin, contradicted
Chernomyrdin's assertion.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be unity of command for this to be really
effective, in order for it not to slip down a slippery slope into
partition, ineffectiveness or worse,'' said Talbott.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Talbott suggested the differences with Russia ``are being
narrowed.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Jamie Rubin also said the United
States wouldn't allow any partition of Kosovo. ``The Russians said
they want to participate. We've said we welcome their
participation. The arrangements for that have not been worked out.
But imagining a partition, in which Russians would deploy in a
separate setting . . . that is not acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's talks seemed to indicate major Russian concessions
on what a peace deal would look like. Chernomyrdin previously
opposed several key NATO demands _ including the composition of any
peacekeeping ground troops in Kosovo and the withdrawal of Serb
troops from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But in the two days leading up to the trip to Belgrade,
Chernomyrdin and EU envoy Martti Ahtisaari ``significantly closed
the gaps'' between US and Russian proposals, one senior
administration official said. Rubin said the two reached a point
where they would ``not be saying different things and not be
contradicting each other'' as they presented the NATO plan to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   And yet it was not NATO that made concessions, officials said.
``NATO's conditions remain NATO's conditions . . . and if you see
the details and you see the fine print, you will see it is what we
have been saying all along,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead it was the position of the Russians, who apparently
agreed to some of NATO's central demands in an effort to ``present
a common front and isolate Milosevic'' at the negotiating table,
another official said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the official said, ``All of this is nice. It's helpful.
But what matters is that we're pounding them day and night. And the
longer this continues, the less options Milosevic's going to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   In war-weary Belgrade, there was a palpable sense that Wednesday
night's visit was the beginning of the end. The state-run media
seemed to be preparing people for a deal, praising the ``national
resistance'' to ``NATO aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   Most ordinary people are sick of the nightly bombing, power and
water outages, and the almost daily tales of civilians being killed
by NATO bombs. The government says that more than 1,500 civilians
have been killed, but has not said how many of its soldiers have
died.
</P>
<P>
   Slavica Vesic, 39, a bus driver, said he was tired of driving
his bus amid the wail of air raid sirens and frightening
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are sick of the war,'' he said, adding that he was willing
to accept ``any kind of deal that would bring an end of the
bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Miroslav Papic, a 52-year-old retiree, said he wanted peace, but
trusted Milosevic not to accept a bad deal. Papic, however, said he
did not want Americans in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let them resolve their own problems with black people and
leave us alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While many people said they hoped the war would end soon, both
Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari cautioned against over-optimism.
Chernomyrdin said he did not expect this to be the last visit,
while Ahtisaari said he did not expect an agreement to be signed,
or for the bombing to end with this visit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ahtisaari fed optimism upon his arrival in Belgrade by
saying, ``This is a historic day for Yugoslavia,'' and describing
the plan he and Chernomyrdin brought as ``an offer for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the peace plan, meanwhile, are expected to be opposed
by others. The proposal reportedly would effectively disband the
Kosovo Liberation Army. While not spelled out in the proposal, the
Western allies and Russia have reportedly agreed that the KLA
should be refashioned into a political party and some of its
members made part of the police force in an autonomous Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians will also be upset to learn the peace plan
makes no mention of a referendum to decide whether Kosovo should
become independent. Central to the plan is respecting the
``territorial integrity'' of Yugoslavia by recognizing the current
borders.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the diplomatic maneuvers, NATO showed no letup in the
bombardments it launched March 24, striking Serb military targets
across Kosovo and hitting power lines, fuel depots and TV relay
stations in and around Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav media reported strikes on the central Serbian towns of
Jagodina and Cuprija.
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sounded Wednesday night in Belgrade at about 10
p.m., but for the first time in several weeks there was no routine
bombing in and around the capital. NATO, however, was expected to
continue bombing Yugoslavia until there is a formal capitulation by
Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
