<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNESANDNOBLE-INGRAM     06-02 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNESANDNOBLE-INGRAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARNES &AMP; NOBLE PLANS TO BUILD ITS OWN DISTRIBUTION NETWORK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Nev., Tenn.)   By STEPHEN LABATON and DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Facing a likely challenge from federal antitrust
officials, Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc., the nation's largest retailer of
books, abandoned its plans Wednesday to acquire Ingram Book Group,
the nation's biggest book wholesaler, in a $600 million deal that
had provoked widespread complaints from other book sellers, large
and small.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman of the Federal Trade Commission said Wednesday
that, although the agency had compelling policy reasons for
opposing the deal, it was also concerned that Barnes &AMP; Noble might
prevail in court if the company decided to press the matter. He
said antitrust law on so-called vertical mergers _ those between
companies and their suppliers or distributors _ does not generally
favor the government.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, executives of Barnes &AMP; Noble said they had decided
to scrap the deal and embark on a new course of expanding its
distribution networks in other ways, rather than face the
uncertainty of months or even years of legal wrangling in such a
fast-changing industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any regrets. None. Zero,'' said Leonard Riggio,
the chief executive of Barnes &AMP; Noble. ``I mean, I guess the
emotion here is a combination of a sigh of relief and a feeling of
perhaps frustration that something that should be an open and shut
issue of business and law just gets confounded with emotion and
innuendo.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision was viewed as a major coup for both Amazon.com, a
leading Internet bookseller, and the smaller bookstores that had
waged an aggressive campaign to kill the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Outlining his views about the proposed acquisition for the first
time Wednesday, Robert Pitofsky, the chairman of the Federal Trade
Commission, appeared to sound relieved about the company's decision
to forego a court fight and scuttle the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would not have been a slam dunk case,'' Pitofsky said in
an interview. ``The government and this agency haven't won a
vertical merger case in 20 or 25 years. These are not easy cases.''
</P>
<P>
   While such cases were common more than a generation ago, he
said, none had been pursued in the 1980s, and court decisions have
made it far harder for the government to prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said he and the staff of the agency had concluded the
deal would have been harmful to competition for three reasons. He
said the small bookstores had made a persuasive case that it would
be dangerous for them to rely on Ingram as their wholesaler even as
Ingram was owned by a major competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the smaller bookstores need just-in-time delivery,''
Pitofsky said. ``They were concerned about their ability to get
such delivery in view of this proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the staff continued to analyze the deal, which was
proposed last November, it also began to raise concerns about its
impact on selling books through the Internet, a market which has
been growing rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out that Amazon has shown that it can take care of
itself through its own distribution network,'' Pitofsky said. ``But
what about the next competitor who wants to come along on the
Internet. Where do they find the books to compete with Amazon and
Barnes &AMP; Noble?''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he said there was concern that since Barnes &AMP; Noble has
its own wholesale facility that competes with Ingram, there was
also a ``horizontal component'' to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Pitofsky said the analysis should not be taken as a sign that
the agency had reversed its general policy, which has been lenient
toward vertical mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to start an offensive against all vertical
mergers, but some of them are a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, executives at Barnes &AMP; Noble complained about the
decision made last Friday by the Competition Bureau of the Federal
Trade Commission to recommend that the agency oppose the deal. The
full commission, which rarely disagrees with its staff, was
expected to have voted on the deal later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FTC's staff view of the market appears to be shaped by the
loudest voices instead of the rapidly changing realities of how and
where people buy books,'' said John R. Ingram, chairman of Ingram
Book Group, who called the process a form of torture. ``The events
of the last several days have made it clear that some staff hold an
outdated view of the marketplace, making an objective analysis of
the transaction impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by Barnes &AMP; Noble said that the company now
planned to use the $600 million in cash and stock that was the
purchase price for Ingram for other investments and acquisitions.
Riggio declined to elaborate, although he has said the company was
prepared to expand its New Jersey distribution center into a
network with new warehouses in Reno and Memphis, which will be
designed to serve its online bookstore, Barnesandnoble.com. Those
centers will provide adequate warehouse space for the future, he
said, noting that Barnes &AMP; Noble will continue to be an Ingram
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Barnes and Noble rose $1.25 Wednesday, to $28.625. The
company spun off Barnesandnoble.com on May 25. It hit a high of
$25.625 on May 26 and has fallen since, closing yesterday at
$17.1875.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of Wednesday's developments, Ingram is left in a
more vulnerable position because its top customers _ the Borders
Group, Amazon.com and Barnes &AMP; Noble _ have been expanding their
own distribution networks. A top publishing executive said it was
Ingram that approached Barnes &AMP; Noble to strike the deal because of
projections that the wholesaler could lose millions of dollars in
sales as those shifts took place.
</P>
<P>
   Ingram said there were alliances his company might pursue
although he declined to elaborate. Asked if it would be able to
maintain its 11 distribution centers, Ingram said that ``it is too
early to tell'' and that the future depends on many of the
independent booksellers, who worked vigorously to block the union
of the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those booksellers that were out there making the case that
we were so vital to their survival, I would ask those customers
that they should consider doing business with us, especially now,''
said Ingram.
</P>
<P>
   The American Booksellers Association, a trade group representing
independent booksellers that helped galvanize public opposition to
the deal, actually did seem open Wednesday to some sort of business
rapprochement with Ingram despite existing tensions.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the deal, Avin Mark Domnitz, the
association's chief executive, said it might be willing to use
Ingram in the future as one of its wholesalers for its online
bookstore, Booksense.com, a cooperative effort of independent
booksellers that is scheduled to begin operating in September.
</P>
<P>
   Domnitz said the wholesaler once had close ties with independent
booksellers and ``you don't turn your back on family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the problem is resolved you try to reconstruct,'' he
said. ``Do wounds take time to heal? Do they heal completely
without scars or scabs? Most times they don't. But can you get past
it to a constructive relationship? Certainly we can.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
