A0612 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMBTHREAT-SURVEY03-C     06-02 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMBTHREAT-SURVEY03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parents allowed to choose whether to evacuate kids in bomb
scares
 &HT;    By Diane Loupe
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECATUR, Ga. _ Tired of the disruptions caused by nine recent
telephoned bomb threats at Decatur High School, the city school
superintendent is asking parents to help decide if their children
should be evacuated during threats that appear to be hoaxes.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Ida Love informed Decatur High parents in a
letter this week that the school will not be evacuated solely on
the basis of a threatening call. However, students whose parents
have given their approval will be taken outside under supervision.
Teachers also may opt to leave, and elementary students _
temporarily housed in the building _ will be evacuated. Students
and teachers who remain inside will be in locked classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur school board Chairwoman Sara Turnipseed said the policy
strikes a balance between officials' desire to halt evacuations and
``those parents who cannot live with that risk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My child is not being evacuated, and I love my child,'' said
Turnipseed.
</P>
<P>
   Turnipseed and Love emphasized that school officials will
continue to notify police immediately and search the building after
every telephoned threat and will evacuate everyone if they have
reason to believe any call is more than just a prank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the calls will continue forever if we don't do
something,'' said Turnipseed.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Stephens, executive director of the National School Safety
Center, a Westlake Village, Calif.-based nonprofit group, said he
would advise against creating ``two classes of citizens'' during
evacuations. School officials ought to take seriously every threat
they receive, which doesn't necessarily mean an evacuation,
Stephens said. But ``those decisions should apply to all
students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   How to respond to bomb threats has become a vexing issue because
of hundreds of threats phoned into schools in the wake of the
shootings in Littleton, Colo., and Rockdale County's Heritage High
School. In one attempt to make a stand against threats, the
principal at Tapp Middle School in Cobb County invited parents to
come for a day of celebration at the school on the date when
bathroom graffiti had threatened an explosion.
</P>
<P>
   In the DeKalb School System, principals call in school
detectives and ``depend on their advice on whether or not to
evacuate'' after receiving a threatening call, said school
spokesman Spencer Ragsdale. Last week, police arrested students
from Druid Hills and Columbia High schools, both of whom had used
cell phones to make bomb threats at their respective schools.
</P>
<P>
   Two Decatur High students were arrested last week for making
threats, but at least two bomb threats have come in since then. An
anonymous donor has posted a $500 reward for information leading to
the arrest and conviction of those responsible. BellSouth now has
the ability to trace every telephone call made to the school,
Turnipseed said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Coty, a Decatur High math teacher, said most of his
students said they would evacuate at the next threat. Coty says the
evacuations have ``completely annihilated'' third and fourth
periods, when most threats have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   In all Decatur schools, no students will be allowed to bring
book bags or use their lockers for the rest of the school year,
which ends Wednesday. Off-campus lunch privileges enjoyed by some
seniors have been ended, and more doors are being kept locked.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
