<HEADER>
A0613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUMPING-SENTENCES03-C     06-02 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUMPING-SENTENCES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chemical executives sentenced
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUNSWICK, Ga. _ Two executives at a now-defunct chemical plant
here _ described as one of the nation's most dangerously polluted
sites and the worst ever in Georgia _ were sentenced Wednesday to
some of the stiffest prison terms ever imposed in a case involving
criminal violations of environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   Although more than $55 million has been spent to clean up the
LCP Chemicals-Georgia Inc. site, nearby tidal waterways still are
closed to commercial fishing and crabbing because seafood shows
dangerously high levels of mercury. Pollution was so pervasive that
toxins dissolved subsoil and migrated more than 40 feet down to
bedrock, where ``a blob of poison'' remains because the technology
does not exist to clean it up, federal authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leadership of this corporation set the tone,'' Assistant
U.S. Attorney William McAbee said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Anthony Alaimo sentenced
Christian A. Hansen Jr., 72, the former chief executive officer of
LCP Chemicals-Georgia Inc., to serve nine years in prison and pay a
$20,000 fine. He imposed a 6 1/2-year sentence on LCP's former
plant manager, Alfred Taylor, 59, of Brunswick. Federal sentencing
requires inmates to serve full terms.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Kime, an attorney with the federal Environmental Protection
Agency in Washington, said sentences such as the ones imposed in
Brunswick are as rare as the endangered woodstorks that feed around
the LCP plant, which was shut down five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``A six-year sentence is usually the maximum you see in these
cases,'' said Kime.
</P>
<P>
   Alaimo postponed sentencing Christian Hansen's son, Randall, 39,
of West Virginia, the plant's former chief operations officer and
treasurer. Like his father and Taylor, he was convicted on multiple
counts of polluting the environment and of knowingly endangering
plant workers. The three are appealing their convictions.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth executive, plant environmental manager Brent Hanson of
St. Simons Island, pleaded guilty to similar charges and was
sentenced recently to 18 months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   When the Hansens and Taylor were on trial earlier this year,
workers testified they were told to wade through pools of water so
contaminated with caustic soda that it burned their skin, in order
to repair equipment that could have electrocuted them. The workers
said leaks of poisonous chlorine gas and the threat of explosions
were commonplace before the state Environmental Protection Division
ordered the plant to close in early 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Christian Hansen, of New Jersey, is a former Exxon executive and
corporate powerhouse who founded the Hamlin Group Inc. The chemical
engineer operated plants in New York, West Virginia and other
states before acquiring the LCP plant in Brunswick in 1979. At one
time, Hansen was pulling down a $700,000 annual salary, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
   Described in court as a dictator with his employees, Hansen
turned ''a blind eye'' to problems that grew ever more serious at
LCP after the Hamlin Group went bankrupt in 1991, McAbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's New York plant pleaded guilty in the late 1980s to
dumping mercury and chlorine into a Syracuse lake. ''In New York,
you can see a corporate mentality developing that 'we can run our
plants however we want,''' McAbee said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Lyons, the federal probation officer who prepared
pre-sentence reports on the three, said Christian Hansen ''bled the
Syracuse plant dry,'' then came to Brunswick and repeated his
pattern of corporate pollution. When toxic discharges at LCP got
out of hand, he designed unworkable systems to fix the problem,
Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had his own people telling him a cleanup method he proposed
would not work,'' Lyons said. ''And he told them to do it anyway.''
Taylor, McAbee said, was found guilty of telling workers to dump
tank cars full of wastewater and sent workers into contaminated
water with electrical current running through it. He also
under-reported amounts of wastewater being disposed of by the
plant, McAbee said. ''Almost a million gallons a day of hazardous
waste was not reported for more than a year.'' After LCP closed,
the state exercised a one-time option given to all states: a
so-called ''silver bullet'' that allows authorities to move a toxic
site to the top of the federal Superfund list, clearing the way for
immediate cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   Alaimo noted that Taylor, who stayed on as a $30-an-hour
contract worker after the closure, was lauded by environmental
authorities for his assistance in cleaning up the mess.
</P>
<P>
   In postponing sentencing for Randall Hansen, Alaimo said that if
he knew a way to depart from the stringent mandatory federal
sentencing guidelines, he would. Randall Hansen has two young
children and was described as a devoted father who is involved in
his church and community. Witnesses called him a lover of the
environment who ''picks up every match stick'' on camping trips.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen, an engineer, was called in by his father in what was
styled as a last-ditch effort to save the LCP plant and what was
left of the elder Hansen's empire. ''Randall went to work out of a
sense of responsibility to his dad,'' said his wife, Elizabeth.
''The fact that they have not had the greatest relationship doesn't
mean he didn't feel responsibility.'' During Wednesday's hearing,
Alaimo noted that the Hansens and Taylor all have loving families
and friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of the most difficult days I have ever experienced
after being on the bench for nigh on 30 years,'' he commented.
</P>
<P>
   But Donnie Dixon, the U.S. Attorney for Georgia's Southern
Judicial District, said LCP left a blight on the South Georgia
environment that will last for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''The damage caused by the actions of these defendants will
adversely affect tidal creeks and marshes for at least the next 20
years,'' Dixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
