<SLUG> BC-CRASH-TECHNOLOGY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS, NOT TECHNOLOGY, MAKE THE FINAL DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MITCHELL SCHNURMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Professional pilots have millions of dollars worth of technology
at their fingertips, including radar systems that can track storm
cells 320 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   But just before landing, they depend on air traffic controllers
to tell them a key detail: the wind speed near the runway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the mercy of the information we're given,'' said Drew
Engelke, an American Airlines pilot since 1991 and a first officer
on the MD-80 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are exploring the circumstances that led to
Tuesday's late night crash of American Airlines Flight 1420 in
Little Rock, Ark. Attention has focused on the pilots, and the
thunderstorms and high winds that buffeted the area during the
crash landing.
</P>
<P>
   Engelke declined to discuss the Little Rock crash, saying it is
under investigation. But he offered insight into the
decision-making process that pilots frequently confront when they
face bad weather, along with the limitations of their technology.
</P>
<P>
   Among the key points:
</P>
<P>
   Pilots usually make the ultimate call. The air traffic control
tower may delay a landing because of airplane traffic, low cloud
cover or poor visibility. Otherwise, the pilots decide whether the
conditions are acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they get clearance from the tower and skies are sunny,
pilots can abruptly decide to take a lap around the airport to
check things out again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, they just don't like the way it looks,'' Engelke
said. ``You won't hear any argument from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Commercial planes are not supposed to fly into severe weather.
The MD-80 that crashed Tuesday is certified to land only if
tailwinds do not exceed 10 knots or crosswinds do not top 30 knots,
according to Engelke and others.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the crash, wind gusts hit just under 30 knots at
the Little Rock airport. Five minutes before the crash and six
minutes afterward, the wind gusts were more than twice as strong.
</P>
<P>
   Severe thunderstorm warnings don't ground flights. Engelke said
that pilots regularly fly through areas that are under storm
warnings; the key, he said, is to avoid the storm cells that can
damage planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first rule of thunderstorms is to avoid them,'' he said,
adding that pilots usually fly above or around storms. ``You find a
hole and you get through. But you don't fly into the storms.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots often circle above an airport, waiting for the weather to
clear, he said. Hail, which was falling in Little Rock at the time
of the crash, is very dangerous. Engelke he said he tries to leave
a buffer of up to 10 miles between hailstorms and his plane.
</P>
<P>
   When weather is an issue, pilots list two alternate destinations
before departing. Flight 1420, which had faced a two-hour weather
delay at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, listed Nashville and D/FW as
its alternative sites, Engelke said.
</P>
<P>
   The cockpit radar can detect storm cells but not heavy winds.
Engelke said that pilots learn about wind conditions at the airport
by talking with air controllers or from an automated airport
recording that is updated hourly. The recording can also be faxed
to the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   He said the radar systems that are commonly seen on TV news are
far more sophisticated than the planes' systems.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots decide whether they're too tired to go on. The pilots of
Flight 1420 had been working for more than 13 hours, which is near
the maximum set by federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Safety experts nationwide have focused recently on pilot
fatigue, and Engelke said it is a personal call: If pilots are not
up to the job _ even for a single segment of the trip _ they are
supposed to call in sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``You make the assessment,'' he said. ``You have an obligation
to remove yourself if you're not physically and mentally capable of
flying that aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather advisories vary from one airport to another. Some
control towers provide little information beyond the recorded
weather data that is updated hourly, Engelke said.
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, the pilots can get all the details they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pilots can always ask for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
