<HEADLINE>
NATIONAL EVENT ATTRACTS HIKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Call it ``sole power.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the seventh National Trails Day expect more than a
million volunteers and recreationists Saturday to participate in
the tribute to hiking, biking and equestrian routes. They will lend
a hand in maintaining old tracks or constructing new pathways,
attend educational workshops and ceremonies or just hit the dusty
trail in honor of the annual event.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible to see the amount of interest. It's very
refreshing,'' said Shirley Hearn, National Trails Day coordinator
for the Silver Spring, Md.-based American Hiking Society. The
organization was founded in 1976 to establish, maintain and protect
urban and backcountry corridors. National Trails Day became its
cause _ and the event for which the group is most known.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the largest celebration of America's outdoors, the
first Saturday in June is set aside to help raise awareness of
trail issues _ such as legislative initiatives that raise money to
ensure trails aren't overrun by development or disrepair _ and the
benefits that trails provide. In 1998, more than 3,000 programs in
50 states used National Trails Day as a springboard to promote the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot believe how excited the people get who organize these
events or volunteer for them,'' said Hearn. In her 10th year
working for the American Hiking Society but first year operating
with the National Trail Day, she is surprised by the amount of
interest in the event. ``It's important to me to make people aware
that without volunteers those trails are going to disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the nation during the 1997 event, some 2,500 miles of new
trails were dedicated, opened or built; 10,000 trail miles were
refurbished and 18,000 were hiked, ridden or run. That covers quite
a bit of terrain, and again this year several free Los Angeles-area
programs are slated for Saturday's National Trails Day and need the
help of concerned outdoors lovers: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ A route will be built starting at 7 a.m. from the
Corriganeville Movie Ranch in Simi Valley to the wildlife corridor
tunnel under the Ronald Reagan Freeway (118). Directions: Take the
118 west, exit at Kuehner Drive and turn left. Turn left again at
Smith Road to the dead-end parking lot. Look for sign. Tools, water
and refreshments are provided by the Rancho Simi Trail Blazers.
Ages 13 and older are requested. Information: (805) 520-1470.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work takes place from 8 a.m. to noon along the Pacific Crest
Trail; volunteers should meet at Vasquez Rocks County Natural Area
Park, 10700 W. Escondido Canyon Road in Agua Dulce. Bring a day
pack, gloves, water, sunscreen, long pants, a long-sleeve shirt and
sturdy boots; tools are provided. Directions: Take the Golden State
Freeway (5) north to the Antelope Valley Freeway (14) east, exit at
Agua Dulce Canyon Road and turn left. Turn right at Escondido
Canyon Road and drive to the park entrance, which will be on the
right.
</P>
<P>
   The day will be full of other events in Agua Dulce, as organized
by the Pacific Crest Trail Association and several Agua Dulce
community groups. A barbecue (the only thing that isn't
complimentary), complete with free puppet shows, clowns, balloons,
face painting and merchant booths, is scheduled from noon to 7 p.m.
at the parking lot at 33300 Agua Dulce Canyon Road in Central Agua
Dulce. A slide show and speakers' program is slated from 3 p.m. to
5 p.m. at the Agua Dulce Women's Club, 33201 Agua Dulce Canyon
Road, followed by a cowboy-style campfire, music and story telling
at 7 p.m. at the same locale. Information: (661) 268-1235 or (916)
349-2109.
</P>
<P>
   _ A nature walk, educational workshop and music are planned from
10 a.m. to 4 p.m. along the San Gabriel River bike path. Hosted by
the Vulcan Materials Co. and designed to showcase the San Gabriel
River, it is open to all visitors. Directions: Take the Ventura
Freeway (134) east to the Foothill Freeway (210) east, exit at
Irwindale Avenue and turn left. At Foothill Boulevard, turn left
again. Park at Lario Park at the entrance to the bike path and the
river front. Food and water provided. Information: (323) 474-3203.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nature trails around Crystal Lake above Azusa will be the site
of maintenance work for all ages from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. Directions:
Drive the Ventura Freeway (134) east to the Foothill Freeway (210)
east, exit Azusa Avenue-Highway 39, turn left and travel to Crystal
Lake Recreation Area campground. Meet at the visitors center. Tools
provided; bring lunch, gloves and water. Information: (626)
303-1078. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The day's motto could well be ``Volunteer if you can, but hiking
is the plan.'' If you can't help with trail maintenance, several
hikes unrelated to National Trails Day are planned that present
options for trekkers. Information: California State Parks at (818)
880-0350, the National Parks Service at (805) 370-2301 or the
Angeles chapter of the Sierra Club at (213) 387-4287. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Information on the American Hiking Society and National Trails
Day: (301) 565-6704. Or visit the www.amerincahiking.org Web site,
which includes a state-by-state listing of National Trails Day
programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
