<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-PITCHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTUGAL EXPECTED TO ANNOUNCE RETIREMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime in the next 24 hours, Red Sox pitcher Mark Portugal is
expected to inform the team he intends to follow through on his
desire to retire, which he has expressed to teammates and club
officials.
</P>
<P>
   While offering no details, manager Jimy Williams said he
expected Portugal's situation to be resolved by Friday. Portugal,
36, the divorced father of three children who has been pitching
professionally since he was 18, told teammates he felt it was time
to quit so he could devote more time to his family. Teammates said
issues related to his divorce are involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us that there are things that have been stockpiling on
him for the last two years,'' said one Red Sox player, who was
present Tuesday night when Portugal addressed his teammates in the
Sox clubhouse. ``He wants to be with his kids more, which is tough
for a ballplayer, especially in a divorce situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, who last December signed a one-year contract with the
Red Sox for $2.7 million with a club option of $3.3 million (or a
$300,000 buyout) for the 2000 season, has been plagued with
injuries throughout his career. He has been on the disabled list 10
times in his career, more than any active player. In the last two
years he has had surgery on both his pitching elbow, which caused
him to miss almost all of the 1997 season, and his left knee, and
he wears a brace on his right knee, which was operated on
previously.
</P>
<P>
   While he did not miss a turn in the rotation (he was 3-3 with a
5.33 ERA in 10 starts), Portugal could not avoid more wear and tear
this spring. He was struck in his pitching elbow by a line drive in
the team's last exhibition in Denver, took another ball off the
shin in Oakland, bruised his thigh when he ran into the backstop in
Yankee Stadium, and popped his left shoulder out of its socket
Monday in Fenway Park. His frustration mounted as he won just once
in the last seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan confirmed that Portugal, who cleaned
out his locker following his last pitching appearance on Monday,
said he wants to retire. But Kerrigan would not elaborate on the
pitcher's reasons. ``That's personal stuff,'' he said. ``You don't
have to drag everything else into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's agent, Barry Meister, said he intends to fly from
Chicago to meet with the player Thursday. Asked if he thought
Portugal would retire, Meister said, ``I don't know. I'd rather not
say until I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran teammates such as Mike Stanley and Darren Lewis
expressed empathy for Portugal's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' said Stanley, who turns 36 June 25 and has three
children ranging in age from 9 to 4. ``I go through the same thing
every day. I certainly understand everything he's said. It's been
on my mind the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have three kids at home in Florida, and there's so much you
miss. All my kids were born in September, so I miss their birthdays
every year because we're playing. How easy is that?
</P>
<P>
   ``I made it for the last five minutes when my wife was in labor
with our first child. I missed the birth of our second child
completely, and the only reason I was there for our third child is
because it was the strike year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a nice life, and can afford to take care of our
families, but money can't buy time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, noting that Portugal has been in the major leagues for 13
seasons, said that retiring did not have to be a sad occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that,'' Lewis said. ``There's a time when he
realizes, `My kids are growing up, I've had a great career, it's
time to move on.' That doesn't have to be a sad thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Congratulations, you've had a great career.' If
you survive in this game 10-plus years, you've had a marvelous
career. You've passed every test that's been thrown out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is 31 and the father of a 5-year-old son, Hargett,
was reunited with his family Tuesday night. His son had been in
kindergarten in the Bay Area. ``I've told my wife (Sheri) that we
have to seize this small window of opportunity,'' Lewis said of
their separation. ``But it's a tough situation. She becomes
basically a single parent.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, originally drafted by the Twins in 1980, has played
for the Twins, Astros, Giants, Reds, and Phillies before coming to
Boston. An 18-game winner in 1993, Portugal has won 105 games and
lost 86 in his big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's three children _ Derek, 10, Jacob, 6, and Alexandra,
3 _ live in Rhode Island. At his signing in December, Portugal was
accompanied to Fenway Park by the two oldest children, both of whom
sported Sox caps. He spoke of how thrilled his kids were to go to
school and tell their classmates that their daddy pitched for the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Rapp, another veteran signed in the offseason, is scheduled
to take Portugal's turn on the mound Sunday. After that, Williams
has other options, including restoring rookie Juan Pena to the
rotation. Pena made a rehab assignment for Triple A Pawtucket
Monday and is scheduled to make another Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal could ask the Red Sox to place him on the voluntary
retirement list. He would have to spend a minimum of 60 days on
that list before he could petition to return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
