<HEADLINE>
`TOBOGGAN' CARRIES STUDENT TO SECOND DAY OF SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Natalie DeMaioribus, who just completed the seventh
grade at Holy Spirit School in San Antonio, rode ``toboggan'' to
Thursday's final rounds of the 72nd National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving to Duluth, Minnesota, so toboggan is probably a
word I'm going to need to know,'' a buoyant Natalie said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the first day of competition, Natalie appeared to
have nerves of steel. The 13-year-old confidently spelled each of
her three words without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I knew the words, so I figured why waste time,'' said
Natalie, who was sponsored by the San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   She admitted, however, that she had not been as cool as she
appeared. ``Inside, I was shaking each time.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Natalie spelled ``endogenus,'' meaning developing from
within, and ``bequeathed.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Natalie and the 103 other remaining contestants
will go through progressively tougher rounds to determine the
winner. There were 249 students who made it to the first round of
the bee.
</P>
<P>
   An avid reader who aspires to be a biologist or electrical
engineer, Natalie credited her father, Chris DeMaioribus, with
helping her reach the second day of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each night, we went over some of the words from the practice
list until I knew them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris DeMaioribus, a vascular surgeon, pointed out that while he
was tremendously proud of his daughter, he always believed that the
competition should not be taken too seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole thing is great, but it's not something that
should take over the kid's life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides practicing her spelling, Natalie plays the piano and
violin and rides horses.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the National Spelling Bee, sponsored by the E.W.
Scripps Co., will receive $10,000 in cash and other prizes.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
