<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INSTINCT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INSTINCT' HARD MOVIE TO MAKE BUT DIRECTOR, STAR HAPPY WITH
RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While the rest of Hollywood is still waiting for the
smoke of ``Star Wars: Episode 1'' to clear, the ever-courageous
Disney Company is about to venture into the 1999 Hollywood summer
movie wars with not one but two big-budget movies about African
gorillas.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the studio will unveil ``Instinct,'' with Anthony
Hopkins as a primatologist who turns killer after studying a colony
of mountain gorillas in Rwanda; and June 18 is the release date for
its animated-musical version of ``Tarzan,'' with the emphasis on
the hero's upbringing by great apes.
</P>
<P>
   To get an edge on the competition, Disney has also dispatched
representatives of both films _ including ``Instinct'' director Jon
Turteltaub and co-star Cuba Gooding Jr. _ on a lengthy press tour
of major American cities: a practice that's still common for indie
films but relatively rare these days for big Hollywood movies.
</P>
<P>
   In his recent Seattle stop, I asked Turteltaub straight-off why
he was willing to hit the road on such an exhaustive tour _ more
than 12 cities with back-to-back interviews, on top of a press
junket on each coast _ when most filmmakers in his pay bracket are
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' he answered, ``early summer has become the most
important, and most cut-throat time of the year to release a major
film _ a time when careers are made and broken. So you just want to
give your film every advantage it can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' he added, ``this summer is complicated by the fact that
no one quite knows what effect `Episode 1' will have on the rest of
the movie field. It looms above (the summer movie schedule) like a
dark shadow. So here I am, selling hard.''
</P>
<P>
   A pleasant, bearded man in his early 30s who is the son of a
noted television producer, Turteltaub grew up in Beverly Hills,
graduated from Wesleyan University in Connecticut, and earned a
master's degree from the USC Film School before ``falling into the
family business.''
</P>
<P>
   He's known as something of a boy wonder in the industry, having
turned out no less than four hits in a row in the '90s: ``Cool
Runnings,'' ``Three Ninjas,'' ``While You Were Sleeping'' and
``Phenomenon'' _ all for Disney, where he has a non-exclusive
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the first two films are perceived as children's movies, the
third was snubbed by the critics, and the close association with
Disney _ which is not famous for giving its filmmakers free rein _
has been, he grudgingly admits, something of a stigma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phenomenon'' did get him respect, however, and so did the
episode he directed in the 10-part HBO series ``From the Earth to
the Moon.'' So a success in this most uncertain of movie summers
could be the career boost that would move him right up onto the
A-level director's list.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Instinct' has a reasonably big budget (one report puts it at
$57 million), two Oscar-winning stars, an important (environmental)
theme and special effects,'' Turteltaub said. ``So it's far and
away the most ambitious thing I've ever done.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not an easy film, either. First, there was the problem of
adapting the best-selling source novel, ``Ishmael'' by Daniel
Quinn. ``The book takes the form of a telepathic conversation
between the hero and one of the gorillas _ obviously not a movie.''
It was so drastically altered that the credits now state that the
film was ``suggested by'' the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Then the deteriorating political situation in Central Africa
made it impossible to film there. ``We went to Uganda to scout
locations, and stayed in that same, ill-fated Abercrombie &AMP; Kent
tented camp where all those tourists were horribly massacred a few
months ago.'' Disney choose to substitute Jamaica for Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Working with all those animatronic gorillas was also no picnic,
and Hopkins _ who announced ``Instinct'' might be his movie swan
song _ was reportedly less than a dream actor to work with.
Turteltaub extravagantly praised him as an actor and human being,
but admitted he was often ``impatient.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Turteltaub claims it was a great experience and he's
happy with the results, which Disney's test results say plays well
to all demographic groups, and especially well to women _ despite
the gritty subject matter and lack of a female star.
</P>
<P>
   It's not certain yet, but Turteltaub's next project will
probably be a remake of the 1996 Japanese art-house hit, ``Shall We
Dance?,'' hopefully with Tom Hanks in the lead. ``And I'm hoping to
film it in Seattle, because I need a city where people commute to
work in ferries.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding _ who popped into the joint interview late and left
early _ proved to be likably gregarious and amazingly free of the
guarded caution that most celebrities develop when talking to the
press. When I told him I found his enthusiastic Oscar acceptance
speech refreshing, he acted out the whole scene for me.
</P>
<P>
   He plays an ambitious yuppie psychiatrist who gets his
consciousness raised while treating the Hopkins character in a
Florida prison ward. ``It's my first important lead,'' he admitted,
``the first film in which I carry the audience (point-of-view).''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old actor has been regarded as perhaps the best
serious young black actor in America since 1991's ``Boyz N the
Hood,'' and he won his Oscar for his irresistible turn as Tom
Cruise's client in Cameron Crowe's 1996 comedy, ``Jerry Maguire.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's the first to admit that he's never made the difficult
leap to ``the Denzel Washington status.'' ``They just don't offer
me those kinds of roles.'' And his one effort to secure a solid
lead role for himself by finding the material and producing it
himself ``went straight to cable.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much riding on the film for both of them, were they
unhappy that it was being dropped so soon into the summer of
``Episode 1,'' and almost back-to-back with another Disney movie
about friendly gorillas being exploited by cruel humans?
</P>
<P>
   Turteltaub said, ``Who can say if that's an advantage or a
disadvantage? I'm not at all sure (``Star Wars'') is going to be
the monster everything thought it would be. And, even though it's
about Africa and gorillas, I don't see `Tarzan' as competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Gooding said, ``I just don't allow myself to think about
questions like that. I'd go crazy if I did. I just try to do good
work. Maybe the movie will take off, maybe it won't. But if it's
good, I have to believe that sooner or later, maybe 10 years from
now, it will find its place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
