<HEADER>
A0624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAHAM-ADVANCE03-COX     06-02 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-ADVANCE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Awaiting the Billy Graham Crusade
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was Jesus Christ who saved him, Scott Davis
said, but it was Billy Graham who pointed him in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was only a kid then, tagging along with his grandmother,
but he remembers it like it was yesterday. ``It was a John 3:16
sermon: 'For God so loved the world that he gave his only son ...'
It's a thrilling story... and I finally began to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   He was only 11, but as the choir began to sing ``Just As I Am,''
he left his family and began to walk down the aisle, alone. There
were thousands of people there that night who had come to see
Graham, but Davis never gave a thought to getting lost. ``I didn't
have a choice. There was nothing to stop me. It's a force that
every preacher tries to describe: the supernatural presence of
God's spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Davis, 43, is himself an ``itinerant evangelist,'' in the
style of Graham, whom he calls his role model. He'll travel from
his Beavercreek home to Indianapolis today to be a part of the
Billy Graham Crusade, which rolls into town for four days of
preaching, prayer and song.
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple formula that has served Graham well since his
first crusade in Los Angeles 50 years ago. His old friends, music
director Cliff Barrows and soloist George Beverly Shea, will be on
hand, along with a 4,000-voice choir recruited from the community.
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, crusade planners expect a capacity crowd of
54,000 each evening at the RCA Dome, and hope to fill 5,000 seats
outside with the overflow. The free event begins at 8 p.m. today,
Friday and Sunday and 7:15 p.m. Sunday (7 p.m. and 6:15 p.m.
Indianapolis time).
</P>
<P>
   For Graham, 81 years old and suffering from Parkinson's disease,
this may be among his last crusades, though plans are under way for
an October crusade in St. Louis and an evangelism conference next
summer in Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday in Indianapolis, he had to be
helped to the dais. But his face was deeply tanned and he still
towered over most of his handlers, a cadre of impeccably dressed
men who whispered into cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   His answers to questions were sometimes rambling, but he also
displayed flashes of humor. Asked if he had considered retirement,
he answered that ``the Lord has to make that decision. He called me
to preach; he'll tell me when to step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I had a very vivid dream recently,'' he continued in his
North Carolina drawl. ``I was already in the coffin, and I shook
hands with everyone and preached at them as they walked by.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that Graham has preached in person to more
people than anyone ever has _ from a crowd that numbered 1 million
in Seoul, South Korea, to San Francisco, a city where only 4
percent of the residents regularly attend church.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's staying power may be partly due to the prudence with
which he cultivates his image.
</P>
<P>
   He has placed himself somewhere in the middle ground of the
American political scene for most of this century. A confidante to
10 U.S. presidents, he has been careful to get close _ but not too
close _ to the political heat, although he did spend a lot of time
in the Nixon White House.
</P>
<P>
   He was a friend to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., but largely
stayed away from the civil rights movement, although he did
integrate his ministry in 1957 by inviting a black pastor to
participate, and he proclaimed that there was ``no scriptural
basis'' for segregation.
</P>
<P>
   He has managed to avoid the excesses of televangelists such as
Jim Bakker and Jimmy Swaggart. Financially, he has kept squeaky
clean, having long ago set up the Billy Graham Evangelistic
Association, with a governing board that pays him a salary.
</P>
<P>
   If Graham's message hasn't changed since his first crusade, his
medium has kept up with the times, thanks to a team of media-savvy
young planners who set up shop in a crusade city months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   He has called the 1997 San Francisco crusade the most
challenging he has ever faced, but his ever-clever publicity
machine pitched the event this way on the Internet: ``50,000
sinners in one place, and you don't think you'll have fun?''
</P>
<P>
   In Indianapolis, billboards proclaim, ``The Beginning is Near,''
and an ad placed in the personals section of the city's alternative
newspaper reads, ``Jesus will love you for free.''
</P>
<P>
   But can Graham's message remain relevant in a post-Littleton,
Colo., post-Monica culture, where kids kill each other over a pair
of $100 sneakers?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, says George Robertson, pastor at Dayton's Lawrie
Baptist Chapel, who will attend the Indianapolis crusade with
members of his congregation. Robertson is a black man who
appreciates that Graham's message is nondenominational, and not
``culturally sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's appealing because of it's simple honesty. It's a pure
Bible message, and that's what we need,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Youth outreach is a major part of every crusade. Saturday's
program in Indianapolis will include music by Audio Adrenaline,
Anointed and Michael W. Smith. Athlete Deion Sanders will speak
tonight and NASCAR driver Jeff Gordon will speak Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand their language and they don't understand
mine,'' Graham says of young people. ``Contemporary music helps us
interpret each other. Young people are looking for something to
hold on to. I think we made a terrible mistake when we took God and
prayer out of school, and put sex education in.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a new idea, but even Graham acknowledges his own simplicity,
in his repeated insistence, over the years, that he is a ``simple
farmer from North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectancy here in Indianapolis is high,'' he said
Tuesday. ``But I hope it's not for me. I don't carry a revival
around in my suitcase. This is God's work, not mine.''
</P>
<P>
   It's comes with what Scott Davis calls ``corporate worship'' _
when 50,000 souls come together to pray. ``It gets my blood
going,'' he says. ``I know God's going to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
