A0625 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-02 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HORSE STORY TO GOOD TO BE TRUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELMONT, N.Y. _ I want so badly for the story to be true. How
much? More than I want the mockingly unrepentant Latrell (``The
American Dream'') Sprewell to go 0-for-the-rest-of-June; that's how
much.
</P>
<P>
   This is the tale: 'Tis said that following either a claiming
race at Hollywood Park just before Thanksgiving or at Santa Anita
in February _ the story works quite well either way _ trainer Mike
Mitchell actually filled out the claiming slip for a vastly
disappointing horse named Charismatic. 'Tis further alleged that a
guilt-ridden Mitchell simply could not turn it in because he didn't
want to take something away from Charismatic's kindly owner Bob
Lewis, a Nice Guy's Nice Guy in an oft rough-and-tumble business,
the specific reason being that Lewis was supposed to have more than
once obtained tickets for Mitchell for the Winternational drag race
in Pomona (had someone foisted drag racing tickets on me, I'd be
inclined to hire a hit man, but that's another matter).
</P>
<P>
   How could anyone with any racing knowledge gleaned during the
last four weeks, and in possession of even a dash of romance in his
or her soul, not want that to be true?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but boo. Bob Lewis says it never happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just something you people dreamed up,'' insists the cheery
multi-millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Well, dammit, it could be true, and if I'm not mistaken Mike
Mitchell has even gone on television to say it is true. Bob Lewis
is so modest and lovable he might be incapable of believing the
story, even if confronted with the written evidence. Meanwhile, the
notorious Wayne Lukas slobbers over both Bob and Beverly Lewis, and
the noted trainer has never been confused with Mr. Rogers when it
comes to formulating a viewpoint of the human race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extra special to be representing these people,'' gushes
Lukas, who will be trying to win the first Triple Crown of his
distinguished career when Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner
Charismatic duels 11 rivals in the 131st running of the Belmont
Stakes Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Now if the Mitchell story really is true, the irony would be
that Bob Lewis wouldn't have been wounded at all. The horse in
question was put in that claiming race for a reason. It was
definitely a matter of ``Take my horse _ please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Mitchell knew full well that I was ready to take the
sixty-two-five ($62,500) and move on down the road,'' maintains
Lewis, who had paid $200,000 for the colt at a yearling sale and
who had become convinced that Charismatic would never justify his
monthly upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you run a stable the size of ours,'' continued Lewis,
``you've got to weed them out every once in a while. At $3,000 a
month, exclusive of veterinary fees, you'd better be getting a
return on your money. You can't keep a horse around for sentimental
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, what is going on here? This jilted claimer is now a
mile and a half away from becoming the first Triple Crown winner
since Carl Yast _ oops, wrong crown _ Affirmed 21 years ago. A
two-time claimer conceivably winning the Triple Crown? Think
Harvard winning the NCAA basketball title.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the people seated in this room Thursday, no one is more
surprised than Bob Lewis for Charismatic to be in this position,''
said Bob Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas is somewhat less shocked, although he had easily signed
off on the claiming business a scant three months ago. After
Charismatic ran well at the Lexington Stakes, Lukas had a major
shift of opinion. ``This is a horse I misread a great deal,'' he
said. ``He is a horse that responds well. One thing I've learned
about him is that he has a bounce-back property.''
</P>
<P>
   Had someone placed the proverbial Luger at Lukas's temple on the
morning of the Derby and asked him which Triple Crown race
Charismatic might take to, the answer would have been easy. ``He
told me, `I don't know about the Derby or the Preakness, but this
could be a great Belmont horse,' '' said Lewis. ``Wayne said, `He
can go the distance.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He will start that journey from the number four spot in the
starting gate, not that it makes a whole lot of difference. This
is, after all, a mile-and-a-half race. A horse could start off at
the Montauk Lighthouse and still have a shot when you're talking a
mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   What's really interesting about Charismatic's post position is
the identity of its neighbor to the immediate left. For occupying
the number three spot is none other than Silverbulletday, the filly
trained by Lukas's archrival Bob Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to the ever-cheerful Bob Lewis to deny the obvious. He
knows Bob Baffert as well as he knows Wayne Lukas. He has to know
that these two titans of the industry loathe each other. They are
the Rupert Murdoch and Ted Turner of racing. ``Oh, no,'' coos
Lewis. ``That's another thing you people are making up.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. Two years ago Baffert was in the same spot with
Lewis-owned Silver Charm that Lukas is with Charismatic right now.
Touch Gold ruined Baffert's Triple Crown dream in the Belmont.
Baffert would almost undoubtedly sacrifice a body part if he could
be the 1999 Triple Crown spoiler with, of all things, a filly on
Saturday. And Bob Lewis has to know it. He just won't say it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe all his money has anesthetized him. Take the matter of the
well-publicized $5 million bonus a Triple Crown winner would
collect from Visa. ``I don't know anything about a $5 million Visa
bonus,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   He probably doesn't. Let's see. He doesn't know how close he
came to losing out on a potential Triple Crown winner. He doesn't
know he stands to make $5 million if his horse wins the Belmont. He
doesn't know that Wayne Lukas and Bob Baffert are racing's ultimate
Don't Invites. He doesn't believe the Germans would ever fire at
the Lusitania. I wonder if it's too late to weasel my way into a
spot in Bob Lewis's will.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
