<SLUG> BC-GLF-NICKLAUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS TO PLAY IN THE MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Jack Nicklaus, who designed the golf course at
Muirfield Village on the outskirts of his native Columbus, will
play in The Memorial, which begins Thursday, after overcoming some
considerable odds.
</P>
<P>
   There was much speculation on when Nicklaus would play his first
PGA Tour event after having hip replacement surgery Jan. 27 in
Boston. The surgery was performed by Dr. Benjamin Bierbaum, who
told Nicklaus caution was the watchword following the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has heeded his words, waiting until two weeks ago to
play in a Seniors event and now before testing the PGA waters in a
tournament he started in 1976 and has won twice (1977, 1984).
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no desire to come back any faster than I thought I could
come back,'' Nicklaus said Wednesday. ``It was, `Jack, for the
first six weeks I don't want you to take a step without a crutch.'
I didn't. We actually scheduled my visit at five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``After five weeks, it was off the crutches and onto the cane.
(Bierbaum) said, `I don't want you to walk without the cane until
you can't limp.' After 10 or 11 days, I threw the cane away. I
wasn't limping anymore. He said that when I was stable enough,
`You'll probably want to go chip and putt. After you chip and putt,
you'll want to take the swinging motions and probably pretty soon
you'll want to put the golf ball in front of it. If it gets tired
and it hurts, don't do it.' I started swinging a club at about
eight weeks. Pretty soon, I just got tired of sitting around so I
didn't see any reason why I shouldn't play a tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus returned to Boston recently for an examination and
played 18 holes with Bierbaum at The Country Club, where he shot
71. ``I played 18 holes with him and said, `What do you think?' He
said, `Go play.' I just happened to do the things he told me to do.
If it had taken six months, it would have taken six months. It
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus tuned up for The Memorial in the Bell Atlantic Senior
event at Avondale, Pa., where he finished 18th. ``I felt after that
I needed to take a few days off and I did,'' said Nicklaus. ``I
went to the Keys and fished for three days.''
</P>
<P>
   There was evidence that Nicklaus had lost some distance
following the surgery, but part of that could also be that he is
59. And at that age he says he is uplifted just to be able to play
in his tournament. ``I don't think attacking the golf course has
anything to do with it,'' he said. ``You attack a golf course
mentally, not with your swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have great confidence in your swing and ability to hit
a golf ball, you'll have more confidence to be able to attack a
golf course. I think I'm going to be able to hit the ball up in the
air again. I think my power is going to come back to a certain
degree, but obviously it's not going to come back to the degree the
young kids have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to come back a lot more than it's been in
the last few years, simply because I'll be able to stay behind the
ball. You never saw a baseball player who stood on his left foot
and knocked the ball out of the park.''
</P>
<P>
   The younger players never saw Nicklaus play in his prime, but
they have great respect for him and his accomplishments. ``I think
you just look at the way he approached things when he was playing
and winning,'' said tour earnings leader David Duval. ``I think you
rarely saw him make big mistakes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
