<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SURVIVORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOIR MEMBERS DESCRIBE HORROR OF CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SUSAN GILL VARDON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barrett Baber began to pray when the flight attendant screamed
``brace yourselves.'' The plane shook furiously, and flames shot up
inside and outside the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `God, you're all-knowing and all-powerful. I am going
to go; this is it,''' said Baber, 19, who just completed his
freshman year at Ouachita Baptist University in Arkadelphia, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Baber and several others were pushing panicked
passengers out a small opening at the top of a jammed emergency
door in the back of the American Airlines plane that crashed on
landing Tuesday. Then, he was out himself.
</P>
<P>
   Baber was among 19 members of a university choral group, the
Ouachita Singers, aboard American Airlines Flight 1420. They were
returning to Little Rock from a 10-day tour of Germany and Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Just before midnight Tuesday, the end of their trip became the
start of a nightmare. The aircraft crashed on the runway during a
thunderstorm, cracked apart and caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the group, senior James Harrison, was unaccounted
for Wednesday night, and two members were seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   University spokesman Jeff Root said he has received conflicting
reports about Harrison, a music director at First Baptist Church in
Royal, Ark. American Airlines issued a list midday Wednesday that
listed Harrison as a survivor. A later list from American did not
include Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to some people that saw him and are sure he
survived the crash, but he was helping people off the plane and
that was the last they saw of him,'' Root said about 5 p.m.
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last word I got at least two hours ago was that his
parents were still waiting,'' Root said. ``If he was OK and his
wits were about him, why hasn't he called somebody by now?''
</P>
<P>
   American spokesman Tim Doke would not discuss the discrepancy in
the lists. But he acknowledged that ``mistakes obviously were made.
We regret they were made. But they were honest mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on board the plane were the choir director, Charlie Fuller,
his wife and three daughters, and communications Professor Dave
Ozmun.
</P>
<P>
   One of Fuller's daughters, 14-year-old Rachel, was in critical
condition Wednesday at Arkansas Children's Hospital with burns on
60 percent of her body. And senior Kristin Maddox, 22, the daughter
of Kay County, Okla., District Attorney John Maddox, was in
critical condition at Children's Hospital with burns and smoke
inhalation, a hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Kristen Clark, an Ouachita Baptist senior who was seated in row
25, described Fuller as a hero who helped people out of the plane
as flames shot from the cabin area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Fuller had gotten the side right door open, and he helped
us out,'' Clark said. ``A guy in front of me, an older man, was in
such a hurry he slipped and broke his leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Once out, Clark and the others were pelted with rain and hail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really, really windy,'' she said. ``We were trying to
duck and stay together and keep warm.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozmun, who was sitting about midway on the plane, said he tried
to reach for a handle to the exit door on the left wing when it
popped open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pushed it to one side to get out,'' he said. ``On the wing
there was fire. So in order to jump to the ground I had to jump
through fire. It was hot, but it didn't burn too bad. I singed my
hair a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Baber, who had been seated in row 30, said that as he got
farther from the plane, the ground became wetter and the water
deeper. He said he helped a man whose leg was slashed to the bone
and assisted flight attendant Jenny Gardner across a waist-deep
creek to higher and drier ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I can't swim,' and I said I could,'' said Baber,
who suffered numerous bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Baber's father, the Rev. Mark Baber, pastor of First Baptist
Church of Marion, Ark., was grateful Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``God was good to us; what can I say,'' he said. ``I'm in awe of
the opportunity to have my son alive with me, and in grief for
those who were not so fortunate last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozmun said he has known the choir members only about two weeks
but wasn't surprised when he saw them helping others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had witnessed their maturity and their witness with the
people they had met and shared with in Germany and Austria,'' Ozmun
said. ``I just knew last night that I didn't have to worry about
them too much, because I knew they had the fortitude to take care
of themselves and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Dan Reed and Karen Rouse contributed to this
report.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
