<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FEDERAL JURY DEADLOCKED IN GENENTECH PATENT CASE
</P>
<P>
   A federal jury deadlocked in a lawsuit contending that Genentech
had infringed a University of California patent in developing its
first big product, human growth hormone. The deadlock represented a
narrow escape for Genentech because the panel vote was 8-1 in favor
of the university, according to the jury's foreman. The university
said it would ask for a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY SCRUTINIZED AS EURO SLIDES
</P>
<P>
   Having dropped more than 10 percent against the dollar since its
introduction at the beginning of the year, the euro hit a new low,
dragged down in large part by Germany's languishing economy. The
plunge has ignited a round of finger-pointing between European
political leaders and European central bankers, but it has
especially put the spotlight on Germany, which accounts for
one-third of the euro-zone's total economic output, and its new
left-of-center chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   BANK REVIEWS DEAL WITH ROBERTSON
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Scotland is reviewing its a joint telephone and
Internet banking venture with Pat Robertson, the conservative
American television evangelist, after criticism from depositors.
Responding to Scottish disapproval of him, Robertson once called
Scotland a ``dark place.''
</P>
<P>
   AUTO SALES INCREASED 5.3 PERCENT IN MAY
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives were exuberant about May car and truck sales,
which rose 5.3 percent and continued to propel the industry toward
its best year ever despite weak monthly results from General
Motors. For the first five months of 1999, buyers have snapped up
6.9 million cars, sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickup
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS DROP EARLY, THEN REBOUND
</P>
<P>
   Stocks slumped in early trading but rebounded after bargain
hunters scooped up shares of Internet and other high-technology
issues. The Nasdaq composite index gained 20.38 points, or
eight-tenths of a percent, to 2,432.41. The Dow Jones industrial
average ended 18.37 points lower, or two-tenths of a percent, to
10,577.89. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 0.55 point,
to 1,294.81.
</P>
<P>
   A CONTRACT FOR CAR HAULERS
</P>
<P>
   The teamsters' union and companies that haul new cars to dealers
have reached a tentative agreement, averting a strike that would
have disrupted the Big Three auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   SALES AND PRICES OF NEW HOMES RISE
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new homes unexpectedly surged 9.2 percent in April to
the second-highest level ever, driving prices to a record high.
Sales rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 978,000 units,
exceeding forecasts for a 1.5 percent decline. The median price of
new homes rose 3 percent in April, to a record $159,500 from
$154,800 in March. That is 7.8 percent higher than a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   VERDICT STILL OUT ON WELFARE LAW
</P>
<P>
   Although a Government study shows plunging welfare rolls,
soaring employment rates among former welfare recipients and no
burst of homelessness in the wake of the 1996 welfare-reform law,
critics say it is too early to call the measure an unqualified
success. Michael M. Weinstein: Economic Scene.
</P>
<P>
   A FIERCE HOTEL BIDDING WAR
</P>
<P>
   Bids for the 356-room Regent Hotel in Bangkok, Thailand, will be
received Thursday, ending a battle between Goldman, Sachs and an
American-born Thai citizen.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT OFFERS A REBUTTAL
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft argued in court that it has faced stiff competition,
trying to undermine the monopoly position that lies at the heart of
the Government's antitrust case.
</P>
</TEXT>
