<SLUG> BC-BALKANS-TOURISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CASUALTY OF WAR :  FEWER TRAVEL TO HUNGARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ The pretty, cobblestone streets that wind through the
city's picturesque Castle District are usually almost unnavigable
this time of year, as throngs of tourists line up for a look inside
the Matyas Temple, or the view of the Danube from Fisherman's
Bastion.
</P>
<P>
   But this season, the queues are short and the outdoor cafes are
nearly empty.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a casualty of war, or maybe just the end result of years
of dozing during geography class. Hungary's tourism industry is
suffering from what frustrated Hungarian officials call an unfair
and inaccurate idea that the Central European nation is in a war
zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungary _ and Budapest _ is one of the safest places in the
world,'' says Peter Kraft, the country's newly named state
secretary for Tourism. ``Now that we are in NATO, we are safer than
in anytime during our 1,000-year history.''
</P>
<P>
   True, those countries look close on the map. There's Yugoslavia,
being bombed every day for 71 days by NATO. And there's Hungary,
right on Yugoslavia's northern border.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there haven't been any war-related incidents on the
Hungarian side, although residents who live near the border report
they have sometimes heard the bombing. Still, some tourists have
been afraid to come, and the nervousness could end up costing
Hungary hundreds of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The tourism industry in Hungary has been growing exponentially
since the political changes of 1990, and last year brought in $2.5
billion in revenues. Factor in the ``grey economy'' _ for example,
private homeowners who rent their rooms to travelers _ the number
is closer to $5 billion, Kraft estimates.
</P>
<P>
   That adds up to a startling 10 percent of Hungary's Gross
Domestic Product _ money it can't afford to lose because of some
silly misperceptions by foreigners, Kraft notes.
</P>
<P>
   GKI, a respected Hungarian research firm, estimates that
Hungary's surplus revenues from tourism could drop from $1.3
billion last year to $1 billion this year. The Hungarian Chamber of
Industry and Commerce projects a drop of $250 to $400 million in
revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations in the region are feeling the hit as well.
Croatia, which was just beginning to recover from the drop in
tourism resulting from the Balkans wars of 1995-97, is again being
victimized by the current war.
</P>
<P>
   Greece, too, is being affected _ not just because of its
proximity to Yugoslavia, but because the anti-NATO sentiment among
some of the populace makes Westerners skittish. Flughafen Wien AG,
which runs Vienna's International Airport, reported Wednesday that
air traffic was lower in April and May because of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war has affected us dramatically,'' said Janos Kurucz,
director of Vista, a leading Hungarian tourist agency. Croatia and
Greece _ longtime favorite holiday destinations for Hungarians _
have greatly decreased, he said. Air packages to Greece have
dropped by 20 percent, while bus trips to Greece have sunk by 60
percent, Kurucz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reasons are mainly psychological,'' he said.
``People simply feel uneasy traveling abroad'' when there's a war
on, Kurucz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to go to Greece, but we decided not to do it. Our
parents were against it, because they thought it was dangerous,''
said Shelly Tymkow, 20, a student at New Jersey's Rowan University.
So she decided to come to Budapest.
</P>
<P>
   But if their elders knew they were in Hungary, ``they'd die,''
said Tymkow's traveling companion, 21-year-old Jaime Zazzara, as
she stood near Budapest's St. Stefan's Basilica.
</P>
<P>
   Making a strong offense their best defense, Hungary has been
aggressively pushing itself to tourists. Some $300,000 of the
tourism budget has been redirected to a special marketing campaign
to combat unfounded war hysteria. Kraft has been personally
visiting European capitals to work with the Hungarian tourist
agencies there.
</P>
<P>
   It's mainly the North Americans and Japanese who fear war
spillover, travel agents say, since Western Europeans are more
familiar with their own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are from Germany. We are not so far away,'' said
63-year-old Ingrid Meier, as she sipped a drink at the city's famed
Gerbeaud coffeehouse. ``We are not afraid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
