</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-BELGRADE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC GETS DRAFT OF PEACE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With KOSOVO-DIPLOMACY) 
(rm) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Russian and NATO envoys delivered an
incomplete draft of a peace settlement to President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia on Wednesday, and after a two-hour meeting,
Milosevic said he and his government would study the proposals
overnight and meet the envoys again at 9 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign that Milosevic was taking this approach from the West
and Russia seriously, leading legislators from Serbia's Parliament
were hastily summoned to a late-night meeting to discuss the
proposals. Serbian state television said there would be a special
session of the parliament on Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A politician familiar with the discussions said the government
would urge parliament to approve the proposals. He said government
officials had stressed that a rapid introduction of international
forces into Kosovo under an eventual peace settlement would prevent
the Kosovo Liberation Army from infiltrating rapidly as Yugoslav
security forces withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals require a total withdrawal of Yugoslav security
forces from Kosovo before allowing several hundred to return in a
symbolic manner.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if the ultranationalist Radical Party, led by
Serbia's deputy prime minister, Vojislav Seselj, would vote for the
proposals, but Milosevic's Socialist Party, his wife's political
party and the Serbian Renewal Movement, led by Vuk Dras-kovic,
command a majority in the Serbian legislature.
</P>
<P>
   It was not possible to confirm the politician's account of
Wednesday night's meeting with government officials, or to predict
the outcome of the meeting Milosevic has scheduled early Thursday
with the peace envoys.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Yugoslav minister said that the talks between Milosevic
and the envoys were ``generally positive,'' and that he remained
optimistic that a settlement could be reached. He noted that
Russian and NATO positions were still unclear regarding the command
structure and composition of an international force to patrol
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic was shown on television meeting the Russian envoy,
Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, and the Finnish President, Martti
Ahtisaari, who came to describe NATO's position. Milosevic's top
generals were also in attendance, including the armed forces chief
of staff, Gen. Dragoljub Ojdanic.
</P>
<P>
   Ahtisaari represents the European Union, and although Finland is
not a member of NATO, he is presenting the alliance's position
because Western politicians do not want to be seen negotiating with
Milosevic, now an indicted war criminal. General Ojdanic has also
been indicted by the war crimes tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   The envoys arrived in a capital largely without electric power
because of the air strikes and suffused with war-weariness.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic, who has been signaling his willingness to
consider a settlement for several weeks now, is likely to judge
that an agreement will require more discussion, a senior European
diplomat said. That is because NATO and Russia still disagree on
key points of the plan, the diplomat said, and because Milosevic
will want to portray himself as a negotiator whose forces will not
simply capitulate to the West.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian spokesman, Valentin Sergeyev, described the meeting as
``pretty productive,'' the Interfax news agency said. ``It is
necessary for the Yugoslav leadership to accept this document,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
