<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-AMERICAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 9 DIE IN AMERICAN CRASH AT ARKANSAS AIRPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: Crash-survivor) 
 
By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Violent weather may have forced an American
Airlines jetliner to plow off a runway, where it broke apart,
killing at least eight passengers and a top-ranked pilot, aviation
officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Full to capacity with 139 passengers and six crew members,
Flight 1420 left Dallas more than two hours late because of bad
weather. Touching down at Little Rock National Airport, Adams Field
about 11:50 p.m. CDT Tuesday in hail, high winds and thunderstorms,
the MD-Super 80 aircraft slid off a runway, smashed into a lighting
tower and cracked open in flames about 100 yards from the Arkansas
River.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of passengers fled the smoking fuselage into pounding
hail and waist-deep water. Eighty-three people were sent to local
hospitals, some for cuts and burns and at least seven with critical
injuries. Fifty-one were unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I thought was that I was going to die,'' passenger Bonnie
Montgomery said. ``Everyone was pushing and pulling to get out of
that plane. We were on our hands and knees, and the smoke was so
thick we couldn't breathe. Even I pushed a few people, because your
natural instinct to survive just kicks in.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors included Ray Toler, musical band director at Texas A&AMP;M
University in College Station. He was injured and hospitalized.
About 25 members of a singing group from Ouchita Baptist University
in Arkadelphia, Ark., also were on board, returning from a concert
tour to Germany and Austria, where they performed for Kosovo
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had not released the names of the dead passengers
Wednesday night, pending notification of their relatives. Two
people were not accounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard Buschmann, was an experienced American
Airlines pilot chief in Chicago and spent two months of every year
flying routine routes to maintain proficiency, airline officials
said. His cockpit assistant, First Officer Michael Origel, was a
new employee who finished his training in March. Origel, injured in
the crash, was interviewed by investigators Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The flight crew was about 30 minutes from the 14-hour daily work
limit, having flown from Chicago to Salt Lake City to Dallas first,
according to airline executives.
</P>
<P>
   On all flights, the captain makes the final decision whether to
take off and land after getting information from flight dispatchers
and weather experts, American Airlines Vice President Bob Baker
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Radar images reviewed Wednesday by the National Weather Service
showed the storm arriving at Little Rock's airport about the same
time the jet arrived.
</P>
<P>
   A sudden, powerful shift in weather conditions caused by a
thunderstorm dramatically changed the wind speed and direction
within 30 minutes of the plane's landing and shortly after the
crash, George Black Jr. of the National Transportation Safety Board
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the wind was relatively mild at 9 knots from the south
27 minutes before the accident, but shifted to the northwest and
increased in speed to 76 knots, or more than 80 miles an hour, five
minutes afterward. Heavy rainfall decreased visibility from seven
miles to one mile in that period.
</P>
<P>
   ``That indicates that there was some severe wind in the area,''
Black said. ``We'll have to find out where that was and how it
relates later.''
</P>
<P>
   The weather information was gathered from monitors at the
airport that measure wind speed and direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what (the pilot) knew, we don't know what
information he had. We're still working the radar information, and
we'll get what information was transmitted to him from air traffic
control,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators retrieved the flight recorder and the cockpit
voice recorder, which were sent to Washington. D.C., for analysis,
Black said. He said data from the recorders will determine if the
severe shift in weather played a role in the accident and if the
shift was expected by the flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   A Federal Aviation Administration official confided that the
pilot may have been attempting to take off after the landing and
was unable to generate enough power to lift off the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Black said information from the recorders will determine what
the flight crew was doing at the time of the accident. He said
investigators have no evidence indicating the pilot was attempting
to take off.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA official said the jet struck guided landing system
equipment and then a bridge of lights that span an embankment at
the end of the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Black said the metal lighting structure slowed the plane's speed
and may have prevented it from going nose first into the Arkansas
River.
</P>
<P>
   The plane lay broken in several pieces Wednesday night near the
7,200-foot long, 150-foot wide runway.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers recounted a harrowing landing and frantic escape:
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all kind of looking around basically in disbelief that
he was bringing that plane in with that weather situation. It was
absolutely horrendous,'' passenger Randy Hill told Cable News
Network.
</P>
<P>
   Passenger Tim Benton said the captain used the intercom to tell
passengers the landing would be delayed 15 minutes by a
thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's suicidal to try and land in 80-mile per hour winds. I
hope they get to the bottom of this,'' Benton told the Reuters news
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fire started at the front of the plane and spread back,''
passenger Barrett Baber said. ``Once the smoke got too thick, there
was nothing we could do. People were screaming, `God, please save
us!'''
</P>
<P>
   The jet's maintenance record showed no recent problems, said
American Airlines officials, who quickly expressed their sorrow and
offered to aid passengers and their relatives for as long as help
is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am obviously shocked,'' American Airlines President and
Chief Executive Donald Carty told a news conference at the
airline's headquarters in Fort Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first deadly crash of a commercial airliner at the
Little Rock airport. The last major American Airline accident was
in December 1995 when a Boeing 757 crashed into a mountainside in
Cali, Columbia, killing 163 people.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, the former governor of Arkansas, said he and
Hillary Rodham Clinton were saddened to learn of the crash. ``We
join the American people in extending our deepest sympathies to the
families of those who died or were injured,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Alan Bernstein in Houston contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
