<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-ART-     06-02 1328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-EWING-ART-1000&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING FORCED OUT OF PLAYOFFS BY PARTIAL TEAR OF ACHILLES' TENDON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After enduring excruciating pain to help put the New
York Knicks one step away from the National Basketball Association
championship series, Patrick Ewing's 14-year pursuit of a title
took another cruel turn on Wednesday when tests revealed a partial
tear of his left Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing will miss the rest of the playoffs, and be forced to watch
as the Knicks continue their once improbable playoff push without
him. Tied at 1 game apiece with Indiana in the Eastern Conference
final, the Knicks will play Game 3 on Saturday at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Although the team physician, Dr. Norman Scott, said the injury
will not require surgery, Ewing will wear a cast for six weeks. The
news was another disheartening blow for an aging superstar whose
career has been brilliant but haunted by misguided finger rolls,
ill-fated shots and the looming presence of Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to work so hard and be so close to something
I've dreamed about for so many years,'' Ewing said. ``To not be
able to be on the floor to help my teammates is very frustrating
and disappointing. But if my Achilles ruptures completely, it would
end my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost befitting Ewing's trend of misfortune, his last shot of
this season happened to be a miss at the buzzer of the Knicks' Game
2 loss to the Pacers Tuesday night, leaving the series even at 1-1.
After pivoting in pain to catch a long pass, Ewing's 14-foot jumper
to tie the game banged off the rim as he grimaced. He had been
limping badly all night with what was presumed to be the same
Achilles tendinitis he had been playing with for nearly three
months.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew he was playing on a partial tear that he felt pop
during pre-game warmups. During the game, he mentioned the
sensation to Scott, but he was allowed to play on. Ewing finished
the night with 10 points in 26 minutes, just 48 hours after he
played 40 minutes in the Knicks Game 1 win and calmly delivered the
deciding free throws.
</P>
<P>
   To have his season end with a partial tear was totally
unexpected. Throughout the season, Ewing and the coaching staff
said they were convinced, after conversations with Scott and the
team trainer, Mike Saunders, that there was no likelihood of
further damage if he continued to play with tendinitis in his left
Achilles tendon. There were times when he missed games, 12 in all,
during brief stretches of March and April. But each absence was
because of the pain, not the danger.
</P>
<P>
   `'The risks were extremely low,'' Scott said. `'It's not likely
that tendinitis will go onto a tear. We had no problem with that,
and we don't now.''
</P>
<P>
   Treating Achilles' tendinitis in one of the tougher calls in
sports medicine, according to Dr. Andrew Feldman, who is the
director of sports medicine at St. Vincents Hospital in Manhattan.
Some patients with partial tears never show symptoms leading up to
the injury, he said, while others with pain never develop a tear.
</P>
<P>
   `'Does tendinitis always lead to a partial tear, no,'' said
Feldman, who treats professional and collegiate athletes. `'But in
my patients, if someone has chronic tendinits, if they were to ask
me, `Do I have an increased risk of tearing this as opposed to
someone who has no symptoms,' the answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   An MRI was done as a precaution after Ewing felt the ripping
sensation in his Achilles before Game 2. When Ewing was shown the
results of the MRI on Wednesday morning, he was in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   `'He didn't believe me,'' Scott said. `'He was really depressed.
Here's something that is looking like it's reachable, and now this.
He had learned to cope with the tendinitis and was making his
contributions and now a new event. It was like anyone's normal
reaction: `Why me, why now?'''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy had no answer for Ewing when he sat in his
office with the team's star center for about an hour on Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years as a Knick assistant and head coach, Van Gundy
has been a witness to every disappointment Ewing has had in his
effort to win a title. He has been by his side as an avid defender
when Ewing has been dogged for coming up short in big games,
criticized for seeming as selfish and booed by a public that has
never fully embraced the private star.
</P>
<P>
   He was there when Ewing crashed down on his wrist on Dec. 22,
1997, and within 24-hours had season-ending surgery. Ewing missed
the final 56 games of the regular season last year and made a
futile but gallant return in the playoffs. This year, he proved he
could recover his shooting touch, which many thought would never
return. Somehow, this latest setback seems even more troublesome
considering how much pain Ewing played in, how much adversity the
team has been through with Van Gundy's coaching status uncertain
and Ewing's own future as a Knick unclear, and how close the team
is to a title chance.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   `'The reason he plays today is to win a championship,'' Van
Gundy said. `'All the personal achievements and team achievements,
with the exception of a championship, have been done. He fought
through a lot of pain to try to help us even though he knew he
couldn't be the Patrick Ewing everyone knew. But as we told him
many times, it's not about what you can't do, do what you can to
help us. And he did.
</P>
<P>
   `'To talk to him and to see him, I just felt very bad for him
because it's like he's being cheated out of another opportunity. I
feel for him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy understands the team cannot use Ewing's injury as
an excuse to fail now. They have proven in the past that they can
win without Ewing. This season, with the additions of the slashing
Latrell Sprewell and lively Marcus Camby, the Knicks have unveiled
a team capable of running opponents ragged. Even the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, the Knicks scored 22 fastbreak points, though it took
Ewing's four free throws in the closing seconds to win it. In Game
2, with Chris Dudley at center next to Camby, Sprewell, Allan
Houston and Chris Childs, the Knicks went on a 17-4 run without
Ewing and nearly won the game. But nearly was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   `'Obviously, when you lose a great player it doesn't help you,''
Van Gundy said. `'He was the one guy who had the respect of the
officials to get a call when bumped. There are a lot of things he
does for us, like rebounding and low-post presence. We're going to
have to find some answers.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At times this season Ewing was the one who kept the once
disjointed Knicks alive for a playoff berth they were on the verge
of missing the postseason for the first time in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks clinched the final seed after Ewing scored 27 points
and grabbed 19 rebounds against Boston, in the regular season's
next to last game. And in a display of just how high his pain
threshold can be, Ewing played through tendinitis and a strained
muscle in his ribcage to make game-deciding stops on defense and
shots on offense to give the Knicks a series-deciding Game 5 of
their dramatic first-round triumph over Miami.
</P>
<P>
   With three days until Game 3 of their series with Indiana, it
seemed Ewing would be able to catch a break and rest his aching
body.
</P>
<P>
   `'It's going to definitely help me,'' Ewing said after Game 2,
just hours before tests would reveal the partial tear. `'But
remember, Larry says I'm faking it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was his poke at Pacer Coach Larry Bird, who jokingly
questioned whether Ewing could be really hurt after the Knicks
center played 40 minutes in Game 1. The answer as to how hurt he
was came on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
