<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0647 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RUNWAYS-BOS &LR;      06-02 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RUNWAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER AIRPORTS AND HAZARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a perfect world, there would be an extra 1,000 feet at the
end of every runway _ as federal regulation mandate for new runways
_ just in case the plane doesn't stop fast enough, or the pilot
touches down too far along the airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond that, there would be an additional safety area to
cradle any runaway jet.
</P>
<P>
   But in the real world, there are older airports like Little
Rock's National Airport and at Logan Airport in Boston, which have
hazards that would not be permitted if they were built today. And
when pilots have to deal with bad weather, poor traction, and
obstructions looming just past the end of runways, the results can
be catastrophic.
</P>
<P>
   In Little Rock late Tuesday, American Airlines Flight 1420, with
145 people on board, tried to land in violent weather and
apparently hydroplaned on the wet runway, overshot the end, crossed
an access road, hit a steel light structure, and broke apart before
coming to rest on the bank of the Arkansas River.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wasn't there an overrun area at the end of that runway?''
asked Norman Komich, a commercial airline pilot who works with
Damos Research, a Los Angeles-based aviation consulting firm. ``Why
was there a steel light tower at the end that wasn't frangible.''
</P>
<P>
   The light system did not break away, but instead turned the
sleek MD-80 fuselage into three chunks of scrap. Jet fuel leaked,
fire erupted. At least nine people died, including Captain Richard
Buschmann, the airline's chief pilot in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are likely to scrutinize what the flight crew knew
about weather conditions before deciding to land.
</P>
<P>
   The crash not only highlights the difficulties pilots face in
operating in a less-than-perfect world, it also raises questions
about the quality of equipment and personnel at smaller airports,
such as Little Rock's.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in Little Rock, which opened in 1917, and Logan, which
opened in 1924, pilots and controllers must work in conditions that
existed long before federal regulations requiring overrun areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Logan, being an older airport, does not have the luxury of
having those standards'' of 1,000-foot-long overruns with no
obstructions, said Thomas Kinton Jr., Massport's director of
aviation. ``Absent shortening runways, we cannot achieve those.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it is built into Boston Harbor, only two of the 10 major
runways at Logan have overrun areas of any significant length.
</P>
<P>
   New York's John F. Kennedy International Airport recently
installed a prototype ``arresting system'' that last month stopped
an American Eagle commuter plane with 27 people on board from going
into the water. The foam bed acts like an adhesive tape to stop
planes quickly and safely. Federal Aviation Administration
officials think it saved lives.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators will spend much of their efforts trying
to determine what caused Flight 1420 from Dallas Forth Worth to go
off the end of the 7,200-foot-long runway in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   One area certain to gain considerable attention is what
Buschmann and the copilot, First Officer Michael Origel, who was
hired by the airline this year, knew about weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A violent storm with torrential rain and hail, and winds gusting
above 70 miles per hour was reported across the river from the
airport around the time the airplane touched down.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Logan, Little Rock does not have sophisticated Doppler
radar that helps controllers analyze the severity of local weather.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of Doppler radar played a role in the 1994 crash of
USAir Flight 1016 in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board found such a radar
system ``would have provided controllers with information about
severity of weather, and the information would have been beneficial
to the flight crew.''
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking federal safety official said that the FAA can be
slow in keeping pilots updated about weather. ``They pay attention
to it in the big cities, it's just when you get down to the next
level,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The national air traffic control system is hectic place to work,
and the busiest facilities attract the most confident controllers.
It is reflected in salaries _ the busier the airport or airspace,
the bigger the paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-paid controllers work at so-called Level Five
facilities, such as Logan. Little Rock is a Level Three facility,
according to the National Air Traffic Controllers Association.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials would not release tapes of air traffic controllers
talking to the American Airlines flight crew.
</P>
<P>
   As pilots approach an airport, they listen to a recorded tape
with updated field and weather information. The tape, known as an
ATIS, contains a barometric pressure reading used to set
altimeters. An FAA spokesman in Washington did not know when the
ATIS was last updated for Flight 1420.
</P>
<P>
   An outdated ATIS recording contributed to the near catastrophe
of an American Airlines MD-80 landing after midnight on Nov. 12,
1995, at Bradley International Airport in Windsor Locks, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A low-pressure system was moving through the area, and with an
outdated ATIS tape, the altimeter reading was artificially high.
The plane cut a 100-yard swath through oak trees as it crossed a
ridge near the airport, lost power, and barely made it to the
runway.
</P>
<P>
   Komich and other pilots are angry that billions of dollars are
sitting unused in the FAA's Aviation Trust Fund. ``There is money
to make the system safer,'' he said. ``But it has flaws in it, and
the public needs to know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
