r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-WATERSKI-LADN     06-02 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-WATERSKI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER-SKIING OPENS DOORS FOR DISABLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASTAIC _ Some water-skiers see Matt Tracey as a mentor. He just
wants to offer encouragement to the uninitiated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It thrills me. That's why I'm here, to give any support I
can,'' said the 76-year-old retired painting contractor from West
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled to see that disabled people today have a chance,
because I came along in an era where if you were disabled the word
was `unabled,''' said Tracey, who lost his right leg at age 9 after
being hit on his bike by a drunken driver. ``As in, `Your unable to
participate in what we're doing, so go over and sit on the bench
where you won't be in the way because we don't want you to get
hurt.'
</P>
<P>
   ``For people like us, we've already gotten hurt; now we want to
do something.''
</P>
<P>
   That something, in this case, is water-skiing at Castaic Lagoon
through the Disabled Water Sports Program at the Cal State
Northridge Aquatics Center. With the assistance of volunteers, paid
staff and specially designed equipment that allows one to sit atop
the board, participants can get out of their wheelchairs and on the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're free. You're feeling as normal as possible,'' said
Anthony Orefice, 24, of Canyon Country, who lost the use of his
legs in 1993 following a motorcycle accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're on that ski, you're flying around again, cutting
up the water,'' he explained, shivering back dockside after his
first and only ride of the day. ``You're not doing 2 mph an hour in
this chair; you're out there doing like 20. I like speed.''
</P>
<P>
   The whitecaps on this unseasonably chilly and breezy afternoon
did little to dissuade the medical supply sales rep, but they did
impact his water-skiing. ``I crashed a lot more,'' Orefice said
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Since it was inaugurated in September thanks to grants and
private donations, the program has offered a certain emotion, a
certain energy on the water that everyone involved seems to feed
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a good feeling,'' said Paul Jorgensen, 27, of
Newhall, a CSUN student employee who at various times prepares
skiers for their rides, operates the ski boat and serves as a
rescue diver aboard an accompanying Jet Ski, reaching fallen skiers
moments after a spill. ``It's fun working with them, and they get
excited and that gets you excited.''
</P>
<P>
   Even John Van Arsdale, a CSUN professor of leisure studies and
recreation, still gets caught up in the contagious emotion of the
day's activities after 23 years of calling the Aquatics Center his
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love seeing people achieve something that they
haven't been able to do before,'' said Van Arsdale, 54, of
Valencia, director of the renowned center.
</P>
<P>
   Recognized by the National Recreation and Park Association as
tops among such university facilities, the center is thought to be
the country's second-largest aquatics education facility of any
kind that teaches water and boating safety. Van Arsdale and his
crew see some 8,500 students and community members partake in
sailing, kayaking, canoeing, windsurfing, wakeboarding,
water-skiing and, occasionally, fishing.
</P>
<P>
   But no one lets the fun fog the issue of safety, he said.
Despite being fitted with life jackets, quadriplegics, for example,
have difficulties holding their heads above water during takeoff,
after falling and upon returning to the dock. ``They tell us they
can hold (their breath) for 40 seconds under (the water), `Then
come and pull me out after that,''' said Jorgensen. ``We get there
within like 10 to 15 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteer Gina Arnold helps coordinate the disabled water-skiing
project and drums up interest through word of mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `I've never done this before and always wanted to,
but I didn't know there was any service that would provide this,'''
said Arnold, 30, of Van Nuys, a participant herself who has been in
a wheelchair since contracting polio at age 3 while growing up in
Vietnam. ``I just like helping people. And I get to meet new people
and I get to know about other activities that are provided for the
disabled community.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the water-skiing, Arnold said, ``It's just exhilarating
and fun, and I haven't fallen yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Schechter wasn't supposed to live after falling 65 feet
when his rock climbing support rope was severed by broken beer
bottles at Chatsworth's Stoney Point Park. Eighteen surgeries
later, he still wasn't supposed to walk. Now the Northridge
plumbing contractor walks with crutches and throws a ``life party''
each Aug. 5 _ the date of his 1990 accident _ to celebrate his
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   There he was Tuesday, perched on his Air Chair _ an unusual ski
that elevates above the water by way of a hydrofoil underneath it _
saying, ``Hit it.'' When the boat reached 12 mph, Schechter began
bouncing up and down on the device and zigzagging between the
wakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of an adrenaline junkie and I've always looked for
certain things, and because of the accident I can't do the things
that I used to do,'' Schechter said. ``And so for me it's
absolutely incredible to find those types of things again that
allow me to really have some freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Turned on to the disabled water-skiing project by Tracey during
their therapy sessions at CSUN's Kinesiology Department, Schechter
admires his old friend's perseverance in a time when he was told he
was ``unable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they tell you, `No,' the more you try,'' Schechter
said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
