<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0653 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT     06-02 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON DEPLORES CONDITION OF NEW YORK CITY SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Signaling a likely theme for her potential Senate
campaign, Hillary Rodham Clinton Wednesday decried the condition of
New York City's public schools, asserting that they had been
undermined by political infighting and underfinancing by City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In two speeches on the subject, the first lady never mentioned
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the Republican who has also expressed
interest in running for the Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   But her remarks _ at a spirited outdoor graduation at City
College in Harlem and at a $500-a-plate Democratic fund-raising
luncheon at Tavern on the Green _ clearly invoked the public
battling between Giuliani and Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew and
suggested that it was ruinous for the school system. Mrs. Clinton
left little doubt that if she runs, she would attempt to make
Giuliani's stewardship over the city's schools a central issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can never lift up our public schools _ or the students they
serve _ by tearing them down,'' Mrs. Clinton said as students rose
out of their seats in applause. ``We can never ensure the economic
future of this city or state or our nation by undermining the
public education system that is at the very foundation of the
American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who has been trying to use her recent travels to
New York as a way of establishing some connection to the state
where she has never lived, cited what she said was the motto for
Public School 1 in Manhattan: ``All children can learn _ no
exceptions, no excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do this if we will stop pointing fingers and instead
use our hands to roll up our sleeves and get to work together,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's aides have been expecting his line of attack, and
some Democrats believe that the mayor's recent criticism of Crew,
whose appointment he had strongly supported, was a calculated
effort to distance himself from problems in the schools. And
Giuliani lingered at the lectern at City Hall when the topic came
up Wednesday, brushing away Mrs. Clinton's criticism as he sought
to turn the discussion back to what his aides want to be the
central subject of the campaign: her residency.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he viewed the speech as an attack on his education
policies, Giuliani responded: ``Well, I'm glad she found her way
there. Next question.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter pressed him on the subject, he said: ``I think
that it's nice to see that she's finding her way around New York.
Maybe I'll travel to Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   The crosstown exchange offered an early glimpse of the intensity
that might accompany a contest between the two. The election to
succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring, is not until
November 2000. But the rows of television cameras recording Mrs.
Clinton's speech suggested the fierce interest that the hint of
such a race has stirred, even though neither Giuliani nor Mrs.
Clinton has announced that they are actually running.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's remarks appeared sharper in tone that most of her
recent speeches in New York, which have tended to offer broader
discussions about the problems facing the nation. Her commencement
speech contained passages that sounded very much like a political
stump speech, complete with the kind of sharp, pungent sentences
that are likely to find themselves onto the evening news programs.
</P>
<P>
   The speech came one day after she spent 90 minutes meeting with
Hank Morris, the Democratic consultant who helped run the
successful campaign of Sen. Charles Schumer last year. Mrs.
Clinton's criticisms of the public school system Wednesday were
evocative of Schumer's attacks on Sen. Alfonse D'Amato last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wins, especially our children, if our schools are
plagued by poor test scores and performance, by low expectations
and social promotions,'' Mrs. Clinton declared, not mentioning that
Giuliani is, in fact, a strong opponent of social promotion, the
practice of allowing even failing students to go on to the next
grade. ``No one wins, especially our children, if politics takes up
much needed seats in the classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said she would support more money for early
education and teacher training, as well as spending to improve
run-down schools and to reduce class size.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
