<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, JUNE 3
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NEWMEDIA-IPOS-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 30,
about the flurry of initial public offerings among new-media
companies based in New York misstated the reason senior executives
are often unable to sell their stock for several months after the
start of trading. The practice is dictated by contracts between the
companies and their underwriters, not by Federal regulations. The
article also misidentified the headquarters of Lycos Inc., an
Internet company. Although it has a sales and marketing office in
Manhattan, it is based in Waltham, Mass. The article also
misspelled the name of a strategic-communications firm. It is
Siegel &AMP; Gale, not Siegal.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PRESIDENT-SALARY-NYT (moved on Saturday, May 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, May 29,
about the opinions of Presidential candidates on whether the next
President of the United States should get a pay increase misstated
the attitude of Elizabeth Dole. Rather than being one of five
Republican candidates declining to comment on the President's
salary, Mrs. Dole told Speaker J. Dennis Hastert in a letter last
week that Congress should reject a proposal to raise it to
$400,000. She said the current figure of $200,000 was ``fair and
appropriate,'' considering the many perquisites of the office.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MEDIA-MARKETPLACE-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 30)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 30,
about companies that own small newspapers misstated the ownership
of Media General. It is independent, not part of Cox
Communications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
