   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 6-2 -- First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton greets graduates during commencement
exercises for City College on Wednesday. Though her address was
greeted by roars and cheers by the graduates, she stopped far short
of saying the magic words that her supporters have been waiting to
hear -- that she is running for U.S. Senate. (Don Hogan Charles/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- June 2, 1999 -- OBIT-SPENCER-B&AMP;W, 6-2 -- Dr.
Frank Spencer, shown here in 1990, suspected an anatomist was
behind the 1912 hoax. Spencer, an anthropologist who rummaged
through the bones of controversy to theorize about the identity of
the mastermind behind the Piltdown Man hoax of 1912, died on
Sunday. He was 58 and lived in Bayside, Queens. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) INDIANAPOLIS -- June 2, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-EWING, 6-2 --
New York Knicks center Patrick Ewing holds his foot as he sits on
the bench during game two of the Eastern Conference Finals against
the Indiana Pacers on Tuesday night. Ewing will miss the rest of
the playoffs with a partially torn left Achilles tendon. ``It's
frustrating to work so hard and to be so close to something I've
dreamed about for so many years,'' says Ewing, 36, whose only trip
to the championship series came in 1994 when New York lost to the
Houston Rockets in seven games. (Barton Silverman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- June 2, 1999 -- CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE-2, 6-2 --
Not so long ago, parents were encouraged to hang black-and-white
mobiles above cribs to stimulate newborns and to press headphones
to their pregnant bellies to expose the unborn to Mozart. These
days, many parents view the computer as a symbol of a
technology-laden tomorrow and want even the tiniest citizens of the
future to be prepared. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- June 2, 1999 -- MEDICARE-CONGRESS, 6-2 --
Gail Wilensky, chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory
Commission, in her office at Project Hope on Wednesday. Wilensky
suggested on Wednesday that budget cuts in the Medicare program
were harming the quality of patient care and said Congress should
increase payments for certain nursing home and hospital services.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) REFUGIO, Texas -- June 2, 1999 -- EXTINCT-INDIANS-HNS-2,
6-2 -- A car drives past Our Lady of Refuge Roman Catholic Church
where archeologists are unearthing the remains of Karankawa
Indians. Last week, in the middle of a major highway construction
zone, a team of archaeologists started digging up the graves of
what are believed to be the last of the Karankawa. (E. Joseph
Deering/Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) REFUGIO, Texas -- June 2, 1999 -- EXTINCT-INDIANS-HNS,
6-2 -- Archaeologist Diane Dismukes uncovers the remains of what is
believed to be Spanish missionaries and Karankawa Indians. Last
week, in the middle of a major highway construction zone, a team of
archaeologists started digging up the graves of what are believed
to be the last of the Karankawa. The 200-year-old remains, first
uncovered by Texas Department of Transportation workers in early
March, are among those of at least 127 Europeans and Indians buried
in a cemetery on the grounds of Nuestra Senora del Refugio, the
last Spanish mission built in Texas. (E. Joseph Deering/Houston
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- LOFT-LIVING-2, 6-2 -- The
back of the bookshelves is a fiberglass panel, which acts as a
headboard while letting light pass through. A sliding door divides
bedroom and office. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- LOFT-LIVING-1, 6-2 -- A
curved sculptural wall - called the box - encloses a home office
and divides the living room from a bedroom in the rear. Three
decades into the loft age, the box, a floor-to-near-ceiling
structure, became an important design element - an architectural
treasure chest that made loft living open and airy, yet intimate.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
