<P>
   (NYT8) ALBANY, N.Y. -- June 2, 1999 -- PHONE-ETIQUETTE-HNS, 6-2
-- Anne Trimble, owner of La Serre restaurant, speaks on a cell
phone in her restaurant last month. The number of wireless-phone
users in the United States has grown from 1.6 million in 1988 to
more than 69 million today, according to Cellular One, an equipment
and service provider. More than half of all Americans are expected
to have wireless phones by 2003. (James Goolsby/Albany Times Union)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-2, 6-2
-- A customer signs for her prescription at a Manhattan pharmacy
last month. Food and Drug Administration officials, as well as
independent drug safety experts, say a flood of new and ever more
complicated medications are overwhelming the nation's health care
system, making it increasingly difficult for pharmacists, doctors
and hospitals to protect patients from being killed or harmed by
adverse reactions or mistakes. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-1, 6-2
-- A prescription is filled at a Manhattan pharmacy last month.
Food and Drug Administration officials, as well as independent drug
safety experts, say a flood of new and ever more complicated
medications are overwhelming the nation's health care system,
making it increasingly difficult for pharmacists, doctors and
hospitals to protect patients from being killed or harmed by
adverse reactions or mistakes. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
