<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-SURVIVOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH SURVIVOR: `I KNEW WE WERE IN TROUBLE WHEN WE LANDED'  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ Moments before American Airlines Flight 1420
skidded off a runway in a torrential rain storm at Little Rock
National Airport, Adams Field, killing nine and injuring dozens,
Jamie Goss had been reading.
</P>
<P>
   The last scene she read in ``Their Eyes Were Watching God'' told
a bracing tale of people surviving a hurricane. The book
foreshadowed what would happen to Goss in the last minutes of her
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   About 11:50 p.m. CDT Tuesday, the McDonnell-Douglas Super 80
lost control after touching down on the runway at the airport in
gusting winds and hail. The plane slammed into a light standard at
the end of runway, broke into several pieces and burst into flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kept remembering what I had read,'' Goss said Wednesday
from her home in Little Rock. ``The scene was about a storm and the
people couldn't see in the dark but ``their eyes were watching
God.'''
</P>
<P>
   Goss, a junior at Georgetown University in Washington, D.C., who
celebrated her 21st birthday Tuesday, was flying home for a
two-week summer break. After the crash she managed to grab hold of
a woman sitting next to her. The pair found their way off the plane
safely only to be stranded in a marshy field near the Arkansas
River as the storm raged around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we left Dallas there were no problems with the weather,''
Goss said. ``But about 20 minutes before we landed we were warned
by the pilot that we were getting into some bad weather and the
ride would be bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a little bit unnerving. But I knew we were in trouble
when we landed.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss described the landing as shaky and fast. She said she could
tell Capt. Richard Buschmann was trying to slow down but was losing
control. Three times the plane swerved off the runway and each time
the pilot seemed to gain control momentarily, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking at the ground, and we were drifting off the
runway. We were going so fast and he never slowed down. Then we hit
the lights.''
</P>
<P>
   During the landing, Goss said, only a low murmur could be heard
among the 139 passengers. ``I didn't see a stewardess again.''
</P>
<P>
   Panic broke out as the plane crashed, broke apart and caught
fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone went nuts,'' Goss said. ``They were screaming because
of the fire and the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting in row 13 by the window and there was a small
crack in the side of the plane in front of us.'' Goss said. ``We
didn't even worry about where an exit was. We climbed over the
seats and out the first hole. I was holding on to the lady, pushing
her from behind and she was navigating us. We helped each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss said she briefly spoke to the woman during the flight from
Dallas but never asked her name and hasn't seen her since they were
rescued.
</P>
<P>
   As others around her screamed ``Oh God'' and ``We're going to
die,'' Goss said all she could think about was getting off the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you think about things like dying. But I just told
myself ``Well I can't die. I have to get myself out,''' she said.
``And you just struggle to do it. I just kept thinking about my
parents and friends and a thousand different things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sort of in a daze. It's like you're lost and you're
trying not to be lost anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Goss said everyone in her group of survivors helped each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody just grabbed a hand,'' Goss said. ``That part amazed
me the most.''
</P>
<P>
   After escaping the burning plane, Goss and about 20 others waded
across a waist-deep marsh and lay in a field because their was no
cover from the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were worried that a tornado was going to get us, so we just
got on the ground,'' she said. ``People were yelling ``God save
us,' and in the field that's when some started reciting Bible
verses.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Goss said she began to pray, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other thing to do,'' she said. ``You just pray and
hope your parents know you're OK. And you hope we can last out here
(in the field during the storm).''
</P>
<P>
   Goss recounted her experience with remarkable calmness, saying
that is how she ``deals with things.'' She was even planning to go
to a movie theater later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But she said her true test of courage will come in two weeks
when she has to return to school for a summer session to continue
her degree in American Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get on another plane, and that's when we'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other college students, members of the Ouachita Baptist
University choir of Arkadelphia, Ark., also were on the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant professor of communications, Dave Ozmun, accompanied
the group of 30 on a tour of Germany and Austria, where they sang
at churches and schools and performed a concert for Kosovo
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have great admiration for what the pilot had to go through
before the crash and afterward for our students,'' Ozmun said. He
said all in the group of mostly juniors and seniors were accounted
for, though some were seriously injured. Those who were not wounded
remained calm and helped other passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were quite impressive,'' he said. ``They handled
themselves very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozmun, who was working in his office Wednesday in Arkadelphia,
said he was lucky because he was sitting near an emergency exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got it open easily and climbed out,'' Ozmun said. ``The
wing had fire on it and we had to jump through that. But we just
needed to get away from the plane as fast as we could because the
smoke was very stifling.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the weather was almost as bad as the smoke-filled plane,
Ozmun said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in knee-deep water. People were yelling for their
family and friends,'' he said. ``And the hail was coming down very
hard, hard enough to hurt. It was hard to see and breathe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozmun said surviving such a crash was hard to describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like you're suspended at that point,'' he said. ``You
just brace yourself and prepare for you don't know what. But that
part only lasted for about 10 to 12 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very, very fortunate. The emergency exit opened quickly
and I got to the ground quickly.'' Ozmun said. ``I guess it's just
a sense of self-preservation. I just didn't have time to worry.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
