</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINAL ARGUMENTS BEGIN IN POLICE TORTURE TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the first day of closing arguments in an explosive
case of police brutality in New York City, a federal prosecutor
declared Wednesday that four police officers had brutalized Abner
Louima in a night of violence and terror that ended in a vicious
assault in a police station restroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe that something so depraved and so cruel
could actually happen, let alone that it could be two New York
police officers in uniform who did it,'' the prosecutor, Alan
Vinegrad, told the jury, saying that one officer rammed a stick
into Louima's rectum while another held him down in a restroom at a
Brooklyn police station two years ago. Two other officers are
charged with beating Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The officer who wielded the stick, Justin Volpe, interrupted the
trial last week in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn to plead guilty
to six federal crimes in the case and was no longer at the defense
table when Vinegrad spoke Wednesday. But Officer Charles Schwarz,
who is charged with restraining Louima during the attack, listened
intently at the defense table.
</P>
<P>
   Also listening closely were the three other defendants who
remain on trial after Volpe's unexpected exit from the case, which
came after he decided that the testimony against him had become
insurmountable and that his best course was to plead guilty and
throw himself on the mercy of the court.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution portrayed Volpe Wednesday as the ``driving
force'' of the crimes against Louima, but said that the other
officers were his willing accomplices. The two defense lawyers who
presented their closing arguments Wednesday sought to use Volpe's
plea to suggest to the jury that the only guilty party had already
been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Two officers, Thomas Wiese and Thomas Bruder, are charged with
joining Volpe and Schwarz in beating Louima in a police car between
the time he was arrested in a street melee outside a Flatbush
nightclub and the attack with the stick in the station house
restroom. Doctors said the attack tore Louima's rectum and bladder,
causing injuries that required three operations. And the final
defendant, Sgt. Michael Bellomo, is accused of trying to cover up
the beating in the police car and a second assault by Volpe on a
second man, Patrick Antoine, in the area of the street brawl.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Schwarz and Bellomo are to give their closing
arguments Thursday _ both men have insisted the charges against
them are untrue _ while the lawyers for Wiese and Bruder told the
jury in their summations Wednesday that while Louima might have
been tortured by Volpe in the restroom, he had not been beaten in
the patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they maintained, Louima had fabricated that incident
both because he was enraged at every police officer involved in his
arrest, which had ended with the restroom attack, and because he
and his family believed that he had to embellish his encounter with
the police to make his account of the attack in the restroom more
credible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that he was violently assaulted in the bathroom and
Justin Volpe was part of that,'' Bruder's lawyer, Stuart London,
told the jurors in a courtroom whose gallery was packed for the
closing arguments. ``But he has to exaggerate what happened on the
street,'' London continued, because Louima and his family ``needed
to create more on the street so people would believe the bathroom''
attack.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Wiese, Joseph Tacopina, said that another reason
for Louima to make up the story about being beaten in the police
car was that he was so angry over the torture that ``he wanted
everyone or anyone who had anything to do with his arrest that
night to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another lawyer for Wiese, Russell Gioiella, touched on a theme
that was laced through Wednesday's defense arguments: that while
one sympathized with . Louima for having been ``violated in the
bathroom,'' that ``doesn't give him the right to blame innocent
people for things they didn't do.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another theme in the defense arguments by the lawyers for Bruder
and Wiese was that their clients had been charged because of what
Volpe had done in the restroom to Louima, a 32-year-old immigrant
from Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Wiese sits here because of what that monster Justin
Volpe did to Abner Louima in that bathroom,'' Tacopina asserted.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor, Vinegrad, an assistant United States
attorney in Brooklyn, apparently anticipated that argument and
repeatedly insisted that the four remaining defendants had each
committed crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In his summation, Vinegrad returned to the prosecution's
contention that the four officers who were charged with assaulting
Louima had mistakenly believed that he had punched Volpe in the
face and knocked him down during the melee. Vinegrad called Louima
``a man who Justin Volpe, Charles Schwarz, Thomas Bruder and Thomas
Wiese decided to violently punish for a crime that, as it turns
out, he did not even commit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And while Volpe ``was angry and wanted revenge'' and was the
``driving force behind what happened to Abner Louima in that
bathroom,'' Vinegrad said, ``he had help,'' and ``it was Charles
Schwarz who was all too willing to give it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In entering his guilty plea last week, after three weeks of
testimony in the case, Volpe said another officer was present
during the attack on Louima in the restroom, but he did not
identify that officer. Until the guilty plea, the prosecution had
focused much of its efforts on Volpe, and wrapped up its case
against the other defendants in two days. The defense lawyers also
quickly rested their cases, saying they had refuted the prosecution
case during cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Vinegrad said, Louima was ``living proof of the
horror of police brutality,'' and he urged the jury _ which is
expected to get the case after summations end Thursday _ to declare
through its verdict that ``the rule of law must prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the back of a patrol car,'' he said. ``This is not
a station house bathroom. This is a court of law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
