<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 06/02/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTION:
</P>
<P>
   The captions for photos NYT16 and NYT17, which moved on Tuesday,
left an incorrect impression about the location of a fire in
Florida. The smoke billowing on the horizon, over a higway in the
foreground, was from a different fire near Venice, in west-central
Florida on the Gulf of Mexico, not in the Okefenokee Swamp, which
is partly in northern Florida. The photos were slugged:
FL-WILDFIRES-FLOATER
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-STAKES-3, 6-2 --
D. Wayne Lukas, trainer of the horse Charismatic, stands in the
doorway of a private aircraft which was used to transport his horse
from Kentucky on Wednesday at John F. Kennedy Airport. Kentucky
Derby and Preakness Stakes winner Charismatic will compete for the
last jewel in the Triple Crown and a $5 Million Dollar bonus in the
VISA Triple Crown Challange Saturday in the Belmont Stakes. (Skip
Dickstein/Albany Times Union)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) ELMONT, N.Y. -- June 2, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-STAKES-2,
6-2 -- Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes winner Charismatic is
lead to his stable at Belmont after arriving on Wednesday.
Charismatic will compete for the last jewel in the Triple Crown and
a $5 Million Dollar bonus in the VISA Triple Crown Challange
Saturday in the Belmont Stakes. (Skip Dickstein/Albany Times Union)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- RAC-BELMONT-STAKES, 6-2 --
Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes winner Charismatic is lead from
an airplane at John F. Kennedy Airport after a trip from
Louisville, Ky., Wednesday morning. Charismatic will compete for
the last jewel in the Triple Crown and a $5 Million Dollar bonus in
the VISA Triple Crown Challange Saturday in the Belmont Stakes.
(Skip Dickstein/Albany Times Union)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 6-2 -- First
Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton greets graduates during commencement
exercises for City College on Wednesday. Though her address was
greeted by roars and cheers by the graduates, she stopped far short
of saying the magic words that her supporters have been waiting to
hear -- that she is running for U.S. Senate. (Don Hogan Charles/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- June 2, 1999 -- OBIT-SPENCER-B&AMP;W, 6-2 -- Dr.
Frank Spencer, shown here in 1990, suspected an anatomist was
behind the 1912 hoax. Spencer, an anthropologist who rummaged
through the bones of controversy to theorize about the identity of
the mastermind behind the Piltdown Man hoax of 1912, died on
Sunday. He was 58 and lived in Bayside, Queens. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) INDIANAPOLIS -- June 2, 1999 -- BKN-KNICKS-EWING, 6-2 --
New York Knicks center Patrick Ewing holds his foot as he sits on
the bench during game two of the Eastern Conference Finals against
the Indiana Pacers on Tuesday night. Ewing will miss the rest of
the playoffs with a partially torn left Achilles tendon. ``It's
frustrating to work so hard and to be so close to something I've
dreamed about for so many years,'' says Ewing, 36, whose only trip
to the championship series came in 1994 when New York lost to the
Houston Rockets in seven games. (Barton Silverman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) UNDATED -- June 2, 1999 -- CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE-2, 6-2 --
Not so long ago, parents were encouraged to hang black-and-white
mobiles above cribs to stimulate newborns and to press headphones
to their pregnant bellies to expose the unborn to Mozart. These
days, many parents view the computer as a symbol of a
technology-laden tomorrow and want even the tiniest citizens of the
future to be prepared. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- June 2, 1999 -- MEDICARE-CONGRESS, 6-2 --
Gail Wilensky, chairwoman of the Medicare Payment Advisory
Commission, in her office at Project Hope on Wednesday. Wilensky
suggested on Wednesday that budget cuts in the Medicare program
were harming the quality of patient care and said Congress should
increase payments for certain nursing home and hospital services.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) REFUGIO, Texas -- June 2, 1999 -- EXTINCT-INDIANS-HNS-2,
6-2 -- A car drives past Our Lady of Refuge Roman Catholic Church
where archeologists are unearthing the remains of Karankawa
Indians. Last week, in the middle of a major highway construction
zone, a team of archaeologists started digging up the graves of
what are believed to be the last of the Karankawa. (E. Joseph
Deering/Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) REFUGIO, Texas -- June 2, 1999 -- EXTINCT-INDIANS-HNS,
6-2 -- Archaeologist Diane Dismukes uncovers the remains of what is
believed to be Spanish missionaries and Karankawa Indians. Last
week, in the middle of a major highway construction zone, a team of
archaeologists started digging up the graves of what are believed
to be the last of the Karankawa. The 200-year-old remains, first
uncovered by Texas Department of Transportation workers in early
March, are among those of at least 127 Europeans and Indians buried
in a cemetery on the grounds of Nuestra Senora del Refugio, the
last Spanish mission built in Texas. (E. Joseph Deering/Houston
Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- LOFT-LIVING-2, 6-2 -- The
back of the bookshelves is a fiberglass panel, which acts as a
headboard while letting light pass through. A sliding door divides
bedroom and office. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- LOFT-LIVING-1, 6-2 -- A
curved sculptural wall - called the box - encloses a home office
and divides the living room from a bedroom in the rear. Three
decades into the loft age, the box, a floor-to-near-ceiling
structure, became an important design element - an architectural
treasure chest that made loft living open and airy, yet intimate.
(Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. -- June 2, 1999 --
CRANBROOK-RENOVATION-3, 6-2 -- Eliel Saarinen's house in Bloomfield
Hills. More than $100 million worth of construction and renovation
has been completed or is now contemplated at the ensemble of
museums, schools and design academy now known as the Cranbrook
Educational Community. (David Dunlap/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. -- June 2, 1999 --
CRANBROOK-RENOVATION-2, 6-2 -- Ceiling detail at the Albert Kahn
house at Cranbrook. More than $100 million worth of construction
and renovation has been completed or is now contemplated at the
ensemble of museums, schools and design academy now known as the
Cranbrook Educational Community. (David Dunlap/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. -- June 2, 1999 --
CRANBROOK-RENOVATION-1, 6-2 -- A Cranbrook School dining chair by
Eero Saarinen. Cranbrook offers a vibrant reminder that modernism
is not exclusively the realm of sharp right angles and cold, flat
surfaces, of glass and steel. In other words, that there is a place
for the tactile, the colorful and the irregular, for the handiwork
and sensuousness of rough masonry and glazed tile, even - dare one
say it? - for the picturesque. (David Dunlap/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) JEZZIN, Lebanon -- June 2, 1999 -- ISRAEL-LEBANON, 6-2
-- A soldier with the South Lebanese Army stands near an armored
personnel carrier while withdrawing from the town in southern
Lebanon. The withdrawal from Jezzine by the Israeli backed army is
being seen by many people in Lebanon and Israel as a possible
test-run for the full-scale withdrawaDl from southern Lebanon that
has been promised by Israel's Prime Minister-elect, Ehud Barak.
(Courtney Kealy/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- CROSSROADS-THEATER-2, 6-2 --
Gretha Boston and Ron Taylor in Crossroads' ``It Ain't Nothin' But
the Blues,'' on Broadway. The production received four Tony
nominations, including one for best musical. (Sara Krulwich/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. -- June 2, 1999 --
CROSSROADS-THEATER-1, 6-2 -- Ricardo Kahn, founder of the
Crossroads Theater Company, a showcase for black talent in New
Brunswick. Kahn's mission is one that, he admits, has had its share
of financial pitfalls and has had him spending more than a few
afternoons sweeping floors, tiling bathrooms and ``wondering why I
got into this.'' Perhaps the answer is in the four Tony nominations
Crossroads' ``It Ain't Nothin' But the Blues'' recently received.
(Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) SAVANNAH, Ga. -- June 2, 1999 --
SAVANNAH-MERCER-HOUSE-2, 6-2 --Dr. Dorothy Williams Kingery in the
hallway at the Mercer House, an Italianate mansion that overlooks
Monterey Square in Savannah. Dr. Kingery has just put the house,
which her mother gave her, on the market for $8.95 million. If it
fetches anywhere near that price, the mansion, known as Mercer
House, would become the top-price residence in Savannah. (Jonas
Jordan/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SAVANNAH, Ga. -- June 2, 1999 --
SAVANNAH-MERCER-HOUSE-1, 6-2 --Dr. Dorothy Williams Kingery in the
pipe organ room at the Mercer House, an Italianate mansion that
overlooks Monterey Square in Savannah. Dr. Kingery has just put the
house, which her mother gave her, on the market for $8.95 million.
If it fetches anywhere near that price, the mansion, known as
Mercer House, would become the top-price residence in Savannah.
(Jonas Jordan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) AVIANO, Italy -- June 2, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PLANE-1, 6-2 --
Members of the crew prepare their EC-130 before a mission.
Officially, NATO does not have a military alliance with Kosovo
Liberation Army partisans. But as the fighting rages along the
Albanian-Kosovo border, the EC-130, known as the War Wizard, has
directed NATO warplanes towards blasting Serb armor and artillery
in the KLA's path. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) AVIANO, Italy -- June 2, 1999 -- KOSOVO-PLANE-1, 6-2 --
Maintenence personnel look at an EC-130 on the tarmac at the U.S.
base. Officially, NATO does not have a military alliance with
Kosovo Liberation Army partisans. But as the fighting rages along
the Albanian-Kosovo border, the EC-130, known as the War Wizard,
has directed NATO warplanes towards blasting Serb armor and
artillery in the KLA's path. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- June 2, 1999 -- PANDA-FLOATER, 6-2 -- The
National Zoo's giant male panda Hsing-Hsing, a gift from Beijing in
1972, lies in her pen on Wednesday. A spokesman said tHsing-Hsing
perked up a bit Wednesday but remained gravely ill with age-related
kidney disease. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- June 2, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 6-2 --
During the spring and summer months, homeowners keep their windows
open to allow fresh air to circulate through the house. It is
important to make sure the screens are clean before opening the
windows; otherwise, dirt on the screens will blow into the house.
Screens with extensive damage should be replaced. If the frame is
solid and in good shape, you only need a roll of new screening
material. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Illustration) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LONDON -- June 2, 1999 -- SOUTHBANK-RENEWAL, 6-2 -- Rick
Mather, left, who will revamp London's forbidding South Bank
Center, with its chairman, Elliott Bernerd. ``This needs to feel
part of the city again, to be busy and full of life all day,'' says
Mather, 61. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PEEKSKILL, N.Y. -- June 2, 1999 -- COPLAND-2000-B&AMP;W, 6-2
-- Aaron Copland in 1980. Plans for ``Copland 2000,'' a worldwide
celebration of theAaron Copland's music and contributions to
American culture were announced this week. Copland, who was born in
Brooklyn, would have turned 100 on Nov 14, 2000. He died in 1990.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) ATLANTA -- June 2, 1999 -- FOOD-FANNIEFARMER-COX, 06-02
-- Marion Cunningham is the former personal assistant to father of
American food writing James Beard, a cookbook author and cooking
teacher. Ms. Cunningham, 77, the author of the famous ``Fannie
Farmer Cookbook'' has a new cookbook titled ``Learning to Cook.''
(Joey Ivansco/Atlanta Journal-Constitution Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) JOHNSON CITY -- June 2, 1999 -- -TRAVEL-LBJ-HNS, 6-2 --
The grave of President Lyndon B. Johnson in the Johnson Family
Cemetery, situated in the Lyndon B. Johnson National Historical
Park which is among many Texas Hill Country sites associated with
the 36th U.S. president. LBJ's career thrived on Capitol Hill, but
the 36th president of the United States often returned to his ranch
near Johnson City and Stonewall.(Joseph Deering/Houston Chronicle)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ALBANY, N.Y. -- June 2, 1999 -- PHONE-ETIQUETTE-HNS, 6-2
-- Anne Trimble, owner of La Serre restaurant, speaks on a cell
phone in her restaurant last month. The number of wireless-phone
users in the United States has grown from 1.6 million in 1988 to
more than 69 million today, according to Cellular One, an equipment
and service provider. More than half of all Americans are expected
to have wireless phones by 2003. (James Goolsby/Albany Times Union)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-2, 6-2
-- A customer signs for her prescription at a Manhattan pharmacy
last month. Food and Drug Administration officials, as well as
independent drug safety experts, say a flood of new and ever more
complicated medications are overwhelming the nation's health care
system, making it increasingly difficult for pharmacists, doctors
and hospitals to protect patients from being killed or harmed by
adverse reactions or mistakes. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- DEADLY-PRESCRIPTIONS-1, 6-2
-- A prescription is filled at a Manhattan pharmacy last month.
Food and Drug Administration officials, as well as independent drug
safety experts, say a flood of new and ever more complicated
medications are overwhelming the nation's health care system,
making it increasingly difficult for pharmacists, doctors and
hospitals to protect patients from being killed or harmed by
adverse reactions or mistakes. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- June 2, 1999 -- FLA-CONNERLY, 6-2
-- Attorney Ward Connerly outside his office in 1997. Connerly, the
man who campaigned successfully to end affirmative action in
government hiring and school admissions in California and
Washington state, has now aimed his crusade at Florida, to the
sound of slamming doors. (Don Preisler/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SEATTLE -- June 2, 1999 -- CIR-STEPHENSON, 6-2 -- Neal
Stephenson a during a recent interview. Stephenson, who is known
for his best- selling science fiction novels ``Snow Crash'' and
``The Diamond Age,'' has a new novel, ``Cryptonomicon,'' that has
reached No.15 on the New York Times best-seller list despite being
918 pages long and having cryptography as its central subject.
(Robert Sorbo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) LOS ANGELES -- June 2, 1999 -- CIR-LATIN-INTERNET, 6-2 --
Luis Hernandez, 18, an 11th grader at Hollywood High School, using
his school's library computer to keep in touch with friends in
Mexico and check for releases of his favorite music. As they rush
to sign up Spanish-language consumers, Internet giants in the U.S.
face stiff competition from both Latin American media companies and
existing United States-based Spanish-language portals. (Chris
Pizzello/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 2, 1999 -- CIR-BABY-SOFTWARE, 6-2 --
Aliza Borish, 6, plays on her computer as her siblings, Isabel, 4,
and Harley, 8, watch television in their Manhattan apartment. Not
so long ago, parents were encouraged to hang black-and-white
mobiles above cribs to stimulate newborns and to press headphones
to their pregnant bellies to expose the unborn to Mozart. These
days, many parents view the computer as a symbol of a
technology-laden tomorrow and want even the tiniest citizens of the
future to be prepared. (Craig Wallace Dale/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DORCHESTER, Mass. -- June 2, 1999 -- MA-WETLANDS-BOS, 6-2
-- Rich Kleiman, working for the Neponset River Watershed
restoration project, checks out the height of phragmites, or common
reeds, that has taken over parts of the Neponset salt marsh, the
oldest protected marsh in the country. After centuries of watching
much of nature's most valuable real estate disappear beneath
cities, farms and other human constructions, Massachusetts is
taking a national lead in fighting back. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
