</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0410 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN-HNS &LR;      06-02 2163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-DUNCAN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SAN ANTONIO _ Desperately, foolishly, the NBA searched for another
savior, building false idols and false hopes. Michael Jordan's time
was running out, then gone. And the best of times seemed certain to
go with him until a successor could be found.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually, we admitted there would not be another Michael
Jordan and that it was unfair to expect every Grant Hill, Penny
Hardaway or Kobe Bryant to fill his airspace.
</P>
<P>
   We did not, however, realize another truth until now. Basketball
doesn't need another Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   It needs Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   You can make copies of the Mona Lisa, but they will never offer
the genius of the original. So it seems such a no-brainer now, like
finding your glasses on the top of your head. If basketball needs a
signature superstar, it doesn't need a copy. It needs someone
different enough to stand alone.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan fashioned his perfect exit, securing a sixth world title
with his final shot. Hold the pose. Roll the credits. Fade to
black. There is no need for a sequel. He was perfect for his time,
just as Bill Russell was for his, Julius Erving for his and Magic
Johnson and Larry Bird for theirs. But this is no longer Jordan's
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be the next Michael,'' said Spurs center
Will Perdue, who as a former Bull was present for Jordan's
ascension. ``There's going to be a Tim Duncan.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems so obvious, now that he has taken apart the Lakers and
all their eye-catching pyrotechnics with the most basic layups,
hooks and dunks that, rather than stress-test rims, barely seem to
touch them.
</P>
<P>
   The Stuart Scotts of television can shout all they want about
Bryant's stunning double-pumps. Duncan slipped in a simple jump
hook to win Game 2 of the Western Conference semifinals, then laid
70 points on the Lakers in the next two games, all without ever
wagging his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   Two games and two Spurs wins into the Western Conference finals,
the Trail Blazers have sent an army of defenders at Duncan. He
still has averaged 22 points and seems on the brink of another
LA-type eruption.
</P>
<P>
   But while Duncan has brought the Spurs within two games of
advancing further than they have ever been, this is all just a
start. Players around the league rush to declare Duncan the NBA's
best, but they immediately add that he is just 23, in his second
season and about to become much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players knew right off the bat with Tim,'' said Spurs center
David Robinson, a former Most Valuable Player once celebrated as
Duncan is now. ``You've got to let the fans pick who they want,
who's going to be Mr. Exciting and the attention-getter. It's not
always the most solid players that get all the attention. But
players see the stuff that's on the floor. Around the league, the
players knew. We saw how good he is and how great he's going to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson knew and willingly passed the focus of the Spurs'
offense to Duncan, who this season was the only NBA player to rank
among the league's top 10 in each of the big man's measures of
statistical success: scoring, rebounding, blocked shots and
field-goal percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Tim's talent, you'd be stupid not to really let him go,''
Robinson said. ``The boy can really play. He can put the ball in
the hole. He gives our team just a great, solid scorer. I can use
some of the other abilities I have.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems little question Duncan is the difference in a team
that has gone from Western Conference contender to, with the
league's best record, championship favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seems to have raised his game to a different level in the
playoffs,'' said Perdue. ``That's what players of that caliber
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Spurs guard Steve Kerr, another former Bull who saw
Jordan's magnificence regularly: ``Tim's been blessed with the
opportunity to play with Dave and right away be on a good team. But
he's put this team over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan is indeed helped by playing next to Robinson, especially
on defense, where the Admiral can take on Hakeem Olajuwon or
Shaquille O'Neal and allow Duncan to avoid the wear and tear of
dealing with the moves of the Dream or the brute strength of the
Diesel. But by assuming the first-option responsibilities on
offense, Duncan has taken the bulk of the pressure from Robinson
with a game that seems built for just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared to last year, my role has changed,'' Duncan said.
``People accept their roles, and I accept mine.''
</P>
<P>
   A better indication about what Duncan expects of himself might
be his attitude regarding his play in the Western Conference
finals. Despite 44 points (on 16-of-26 shooting), 23 rebounds, 10
blocked shots and two wins in two games, he seems dissatisfied with
his performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really frustrated with his play,'' Spurs guard Mario Elie
said. ``He's put up terrific numbers, and he's still mad at
himself. That makes him a terrific player.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's genius might lie in being so straight-faced that Duke
fans called him ``Spock'' when he was starring for Wake Forest. But
for all the Capt. Kirk overacting in the NBA, the stoic 7-footer
might be as confident as any rim-bender or fist-pumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just who I am,'' said Duncan, who shares little about
himself. ``I've never been someone who gets up and down. You have
to control your emotions out there so you never get too high or too
low. It's worked for me so far, so I'm not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining that even keel has helped Duncan handle the load
that has been given him. So has honing his simple moves to the
point where the Spurs can rely on them every night.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan starts everything with unfailing loyalty to the basics,
from drop steps and short jump shots off the backboard to keeping
the ball high and out of the reach of quick-handed guards.
</P>
<P>
   His moves can be uncovered in the drills junior high coaches
teach their big-men-to-be, even in grainy George Mikan films. But
when perfected with obvious athletic talent, soft, sure hands and
surprising strength, they remain unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of those guys like Michael. Even though you know what
he's going to do, you can't stop him,'' Perdue said. ``As hard as
you try, and you know it's coming, it's just impossible. Sometimes
that's the most frustrating thing. You watch the tape, and you
think, `Drop step, dunk, jump shot off the backboard. I think I can
get him.' Thirty points later, they're shaking their heads.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, all the greats built their games from that
foundation, then soared where their talent would take them. And by
the end of Jordan's career, when he removed some of the flash to
become more efficient, there was a growing sense that there was
more to him than boundless ability. Duncan merely came in with the
style stripped away, building his game solely on substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's something that's tough for the average fan or even
the media to understand,'' says Kerr. ``You have to really, really
understand the game to understand how fundamentally sound a player
is, especially a guy like Michael. All you see is his dunking over
everybody, but you don't see how he got open to catch the ball, his
footwork, his hands, his shooting ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Tim has. Tim is as fundamentally sound as any big
man I've ever seen. He has unbelievable footwork. If you think of
the best players of all time, they all had a strong fundamental
base. Bird. Magic. Michael. Footwork. Passing. Shooting. Those are
the basics of the game. Then you add to that phenomenal talent.
Forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for the game. We need a lot more players like Tim.
He still might not get the recognition from the average fan. If you
polled the average fan out there, `Who would you start a franchise
with?' it would be Shaq. If you polled 29 GMs around the league, it
would be Tim, maybe unanimously. Those guys understand the
importance of great hands, great footwork, knocking down the free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Understanding the game, as great as Shaq is, Tim's better. He
may not be as physically gifted. But he's a better basketball
player. And I love Shaq. I'm a big Shaq fan. But Tim is the best in
the game. And he's in his second year.''
</P>
<P>
   The time is right for a player with no visible ego, no
entourage, no assistants around to answer the cell phone. In the
first post-lockout season of the NBA, where excess now seems almost
offensive, the time is right for a star whose approach to his sport
seems unchanged from when he was a swimmer and his stage was St.
Croix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ironic,'' Kerr said. ``Everybody is saying athletes want
to be stars. Tim is the most down-to-earth NBA superstar I've ever
seen. If anybody knocks him for not being Mr. Accessible, catering
to the media, it's a pretty big contradiction. Everybody knocks
guys for being Mr. Hollywood. He's a great player, a great guy,
down to earth. He just does his own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He does at least have a passing interest in his reputation. Told
of his first Sports Illustrated cover, which labeled his triumph
over the Lakers ``Substance over Style,'' Duncan said: ``Sweet.''
He almost smiled.
</P>
<P>
   But just as he might now be celebrated for his unadorned
professionalism, for his lack of ego and selflessness, if Duncan is
to become the league's top young celebrity, a backlash might
follow. Aloof and relatively inaccessible to the media, he would
seem able to carry the league's flag only so far.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, Bryant and the Lakers, the antithesis of Duncan's
no-frills flight, could still click and catch Duncan and the Spurs.
And the more spectacular styles of Allen Iverson, Kevin Garnett or
Bryant will surely give them rooters, especially if they are to be
compared to a straight-faced 7-footer.
</P>
<P>
   Wilt Chamberlain said no one roots for Goliath. And Duncan shows
little interest in making it easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a time when they build you up and a time when they
tear you down,'' Robinson said. ``He's going to be a great player.
But you have to know it's all going to be temporary. He has to
enjoy doing what he's doing. That's the key. You enjoy that by
winning and playing together. Fortunately, we have a team that can
do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to get wrapped up in yourself too much. It will
get to him some when it happens. He has a great personality for it.
He handles things well. But it will happen. If you can get the
success and win and do the things he needs to do, it (the backlash)
will be less.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Duncan seems perfectly suited for whatever comments
come. He has shown so little interest in winning praise, it seems
difficult to imagine him caring about deflecting criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great head on his shoulders,'' said Spurs guard Avery
Johnson. ``He'll stay focused. He's not a guy that grew up wanting
to be in Nike tennis shoes. He keeps everything in perspective. He
could care less if he does commercials. It's nice; financially,
it's rewarding. He won't think twice about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether the media tears him down or builds him up, it really
doesn't faze him. He could care less. He's a pretty levelheaded
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the NBA could probably use such a leading man in the
post-Jordan era, assuming that role is won on the court. The game
has suffered when Jordan pretenders ignored the fundamentals to
practice the frills. If a star emerges whose highlights are basics,
he could do as much for the game in his time as his predecessors
did in theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talked about ambassadors of the league, they
talked about guys who had flash, style,'' Perdue said. ``I was
reading about Vince Carter and his rookie season, but he was known
more for his spectacular dunks than his skill level. Tim is known
for his skill level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about driving by playgrounds and kids are
practicing up-and-unders and dunks and fancy layups, and nobody is
practicing their jump shot. Jump shooting is almost a lost art. You
talk about somebody being old school, he is definitely old school.
He may not dress like it, but he plays like it. Someday, we'll
drive by a playground and kids will be practicing Tim Duncan
moves.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncan hasn't had that kind of impact yet. But if his rise is
made complete, the NBA might just get what it needed most, if not
exactly what it originally had in mind when Jordan departed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a disciplined guy, a guy who stands for
something,'' says Johnson. ``A professional. You need a guy like
that. He's not about the hype and glitz. He's not trying to sing.
He's not trying to have his own corporation. He's just trying to
play basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He entertains in his own way. He's not going to entertain with
hollering and hanging on the rim. You'll be able to appreciate his
Tim Duncanness. A good dose of more Tim Duncan is going to be good
for the league. We need guys like Tim Duncan.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
