<HEADER>
A0675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTON-EARNINGS-LADN     06-02 0312
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLID LITTON EARNINGS FORECAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODLAND HILLS, Calif. -- Litton Industries Inc., which has been
on the acquisition trail, is expected to report a 12 percent gain
in quarterly earnings today on strong performance from its
information systems and shipbuilding units.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of eight analysts by First Call Corp. puts Woodland
Hills-based Litton's earnings at $1.10 a share for its third
quarter ended April 30. The company earned 98 cents a share in the
1998 third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts pegged Litton to turn in a strong performance early on
and stuck to that prediction throughout the quarter, said Chuck
Hall, First Call's research director. The range is from $1.06 to
$1.11 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like it's been real steady throughout the quarter.
There has not been any changes in the last two months,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Litton signed a contract to build at least
two 1,500-passenger cruise ships for American Classic Voyages Co.
The deal potentially could be worth $1.4 billion to the company.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Patriquin, an analyst with Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. in Boston,
said most of Litton's quarterly growth will be driven by gains in
the information systems unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm expecting about an 8 percent revenue growth, about 11
percent in operating profit and 12 percent eps (earnings per share)
growth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1998 third quarter, Litton earned $46.8 million on
sales of $1.143 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Litton announced this week that its $528 million bid for
Avondale Industries Inc., a military shipbuilder, has been approved
by that company's board. Litton also is trying to buy Newport News
Shipbuilding Inc. for $1.9 billion, a combination opposed by the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
