<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTOMAKERS-EXPANSION-     06-02 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOMAKERS-EXPANSION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALES OF LIGHT TRUCKS DRIVE AUTO INDUSTRY'S EXPANSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Ala., S.C., Md., Mich., Ohio, Japan, Germany, Canada)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig J. Thomas stands near the end of DaimlerChrysler Corp.'s
assembly line in Fenton, Mo., and waits for a spindly orange robot
to lower a pickup bed to meet the rest of a Dodge Ram truck. Then,
37 times an hour, 300 times a day, he bolts the bed to the truck
and waits for the next pickup to reach him.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-May, he got a break from the rhythm of the robots to
celebrate with other workers: The company said it would spend $435
million to expand the Ram factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this industry, the first thing they teach us is it is feast
or famine,'' said Thomas, 25, who has been feasting on overtime for
two years. ``A truck always sells.''
</P>
<P>
   The auto industry is feasting, too. Flush with profits from five
fat years and scrambling to keep up with red-hot demand for pickup
trucks and sport utility vehicles, automakers are on an expansion
binge.
</P>
<P>
   In just the past month, DaimlerChrysler, General Motors,
American Honda Motor and Ford Motor have announced plans for
outlays of a stunning $1.54 billion to upgrade factories or build
new ones. Thursday, GM is expected to say it will spend another $1
billion to build a nine-story headquarters for its car engineers in
Warren, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole lot of new capacity,'' said Christopher J.
Benko, managing director of the Autofacts Group, a unit of
PricewaterhouseCoopers. ``There are probably more plants coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe trouble, too. In effect, the industry is gambling that the
economy will keep growing. If it is wrong _ if the economy stumbles
and America's love affair with new cars and trucks cools _ the
industry could be stuck with huge excess capacity, leading almost
inevitably to price wars, skidding profits and labor unrest.
</P>
<P>
   A production glut could also spell trouble for American
automakers, giving a competitive edge to Japanese and European
rivals that are less beholden to labor and thus more able to ride
out a recession by laying off workers.
</P>
<P>
   A recession seems a remote possibility right now, with auto
sales hitting a record 6.9 million in the first five months of this
year, up from a robust 6.4 million for the same period last year.
Still, some analysts say a slump in demand isn't a question of if,
but when.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the market starts to tail off, then you'll start to hear
about some of the more negative aspects and the plant closings,''
said Michael E. Robinet, director of forecast services at CSM
Worldwide, an auto research firm in Northville, Mich. ``There will
be some consolidation that will have to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   While automakers don't know when the economy will head south,
they do know that their rivals are breathing down their necks right
now. So they are focusing on giving customers what they want.
</P>
<P>
   What they want are trucks. In 1990, cars accounted for slightly
more than 67 percent of new-vehicle sales, while light trucks _
which include sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickups _
totaled the rest. Last year, the two categories were almost neck
and neck; cars made up 52.4 percent of sales and light trucks 47.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign automakers, which have historically specialized in cars,
are now counting heavily on America's truck fever, partly in
response to the success of Mercedes-Benz's M-class sport utility
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Honda, best known for its dependable sedans, plans to invest
$400 million to build a factory near tiny Lincoln, Ala., capable of
producing 120,000 sport utility vehicles or minivans annually
beginning in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will enable us to offer a full range of vehicles in the
U.S., from small cars to light trucks,'' said Koichi Amemiya,
American Honda's president and chief executive. ``This demand has
stretched our production to the limits.''
</P>
<P>
   Honda has said it plans to invest $30 million to increase
engine-production capacity at its factory in Anna, Ohio, and
another $30 million to add the capacity to build sport utility
vehicles to its factory in Alliston, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota, meantime, is spending $500 million to expand its new
$700 million Tundra pickup factory in Princeton, Ind., to enable it
to build large sport utility vehicles there starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, BMW will start building its X5 ``sports activity
vehicle'' at the Spartanburg, S.C., factory where its Z3 roadsters
are now built. BMW spent $600 million to expand the factory, and
plans to hire 1,000 more workers to build the X5.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and GM are hustling to meet demand, too _ or in GM's case,
to create it. GM has seen its United States market share of
passenger vehicles decline from 35.7 percent in 1990 to less than
30 percent last year; in a bid to reverse that slide, the company
said last month that it would pay $450 million to build an assembly
plant in Lansing, Mich., and $250 million for a plant producing
transmissions for commercial trucks in White Marsh, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Those projects come in addition to a $500 million commitment the
company made last year to replace its V8-engine factory in Flint,
Mich., with a V6-engine factory. GM spent $21 billion to upgrade
facilities in the United States between 1994 and 1998, and plans to
invest $28 billion more between now and 2004.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why the expansion drive if sales are flagging?
</P>
<P>
   GM makes no secret that it wants to close inefficient factories
and replace most of them with modern plants that can produce the
same number of cars and trucks using half or a third as many
workers.
</P>
<P>
   To placate its unions, GM has pledged to reduce its work force
through retirements, not layoffs. It has tried to locate new plants
near old ones so current employees can take the new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In total, we will not increase our overall capacity,'' said
Ronald L. Zarrella, president of GM North America. ``While the
Lansing plant is a car plant, the general direction of those
footprint decisions will be to shift more of our mix from cars to
trucks, crossover vehicles and other truck derivatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the big automakers, Ford has avoided building new
factories. Instead, it has managed to squeeze more production from
existing plants, notably by increasing their capacity to switch
from one model to another. Just last week, for example, Ford said
it would assemble a new luxury pickup truck, the Lincoln Blackwood,
at the factory in Claycomo, Mo., where it makes its F-series
pickups.
</P>
<P>
   These expansion announcements come as GM, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler prepare for negotiations this month for a new
three-year labor contract, and the United Auto Workers is certain
to demand the renewal of clauses that protect employees against
layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the UAW has failed to organize workers at foreign-owned
plants, and the discrepancy creates an uneven playing field. It
mean lower labor costs for Japanese and European automakers in good
times and bad. While UAW workers are guaranteed 95 percent of their
pay even if they are laid off, companies with nonunion workers
wouldn't face those high costs in the event of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The UAW is fighting the teamsters union for the right to
organize workers at Honda's Ohio factories. Hoping to exploit
Daimler-Benz's acquisition of Chrysler last year, it is also
campaigning to add Mercedes-Benz's American workers to its roster,
as well as those at Freightliner, a DaimlerChrysler unit that
builds heavy trucks.
</P>
<P>
   In top-level meetings in Germany, the union has reportedly
accused the company of antilabor activities and pressed it to
remain neutral as the union continues its drive to represent the
workers.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the UAW seeks to expand its influence, labor experts
warn that it must cast aside its old militancy for the sake of its
members' job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real challenge here for labor,'' said David L.
Gregory, a law professor at St. John's University in New York. ``To
be competitive in an international economy, the unions are going to
have to cooperate with management.''
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's expansion of its Jeep factory in Toledo, Ohio,
is a good example of the pressures the union faces. After Chrysler
said it might close the aging factory and build a replacement
elsewhere, workers _ and the city _ engaged in an extensive ``keep
Jeep'' campaign. In the end, the company decided to spend $600
million refurbishing the old factory and another $600 million to
build a new one next door. But together, the two modern factories
will employ just 4,900 workers, down from 5,600 in the existing
factory, because they will be more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio taxpayers will pay a big piece of the tab: The company won
concessions from the city and state worth $232 million, or about
$47,000 for each job retained. This combination has drawn fire from
Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate, as an egregious example of
``corporate welfare'' because the company won concessions in
exchange for downsizing. Nader also questioned whether residents
whose homes are to be demolished to make room for the factory were
fairly compensated.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler makes no apologies. ``The city has worked with
the neighbors and I think everybody is happy now,'' said Gary L.
Henson, senior vice president of manufacturing for DaimlerChrysler.
``We're going to continue to reduce our costs as we modernize.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the company's trucks have proved so popular, its
Chrysler unit has added 15,000 workers during the 1990's. At its
Dodge Ram Quad Cab factory in Fenton, DaimlerChrysler will receive
$10 million to $20 million in aid from the State of Missouri for
worker training, but no tax breaks in exchange for its expansion.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an understatement to say that DaimlerChrysler's
investment has cheered the workers in Fenton. ``We've been through
a plant closing, the old-timers have, and we know what that
means,'' said Randy Glover, president of UAW local 136. ``Thank God
people can't get enough of this Dodge truck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
