<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-WEATHER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER IS PRIME SUSPECT IN CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE LEE and ANITA BAKER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   American Airlines Flight 1420 left Dallas/Fort Worth Airport at
10:40 p.m. Tuesday, about a half-hour after weather watchers
learned about a line of powerful thunderstorms 40 miles southwest
of Little Rock and moving east.
</P>
<P>
   The plane and the storms were headed for Little Rock. When they
met, the results were disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   As investigators piece together what caused Flight 1420 to crash
just before midnight Tuesday, a key question may be what the crew
knew about the storms that were pelting .MDNM/the runway at Little
Rock National Airport with hail, rain and high winds.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:25 p.m., about 25 minutes before the plane touched down,
the National Weather Service issued a severe thunderstorm warning
for the area around Little Rock, meaning that hail and winds of 57
mph, or 50 knots, were possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone told me there were 50-knot gusts at the airport, I
would be leaving town,'' American's chief pilot, Cecil Ewell, said
at a news conference. ``I don't know what the (wind) maximums are
on the MD-80. On the airplane I fly, the 767, it's 32 knots.''
</P>
<P>
   A McDonnell-Douglas spokesman said the MD-80 that crashed was
rated to land in 10 knots of tail wind, 25 knots of head wind and
30 knots of cross wind, or about 34.5 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Wednesday night what wind speeds Flight 1420
encountered as it approached the runway. A 75-mph gust was recorded
about five minutes before the plane touched down, but the weather
service said winds may have been around 32 mph about the time of
landing.
</P>
<P>
   George Black, a spokesman for the National Transportation Safety
Board, said investigators want to know what the pilot, Richard
Buschmann, was told about the approaching storm and the
deteriorating conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ultimately a pilot's decision to land or not, but they
have to base that on the information they have,'' he told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Selfen, marketing director for the International Airline
Passenger Association, said that air traffic controllers generally
do a good job of passing weather information to pilots, but that
the system could have broken down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, if the weather was as bad as we're hearing ... the
controllers at the airport should have made the pilots aware,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous systems warn pilots about impending weather, said Tim
Forte, a former federal investigator who teaches aviation at
Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   At D/FW Airport, American's dispatchers would have given the
pilot an update on the weather in Little Rock before the plane took
off, then updated the pilots along the way. The crew also had a
cockpit weather radar capable of detecting thunderstorms, Forte
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Little Rock airport is equipped with a low-level wind shear
alert system that uses sensors to detect wind gusts and wind shear,
FAA spokeswoman Alison Duquett said. It notifies air traffic
controllers visually and audibly of potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Wednesday whether the system alerted the
controllers to the wind gusts.
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/The air traffic controllers in Little Rock should have
given the pilots the latest conditions on the runway as the plane
approached the airport, Forte said. Officials haven't said publicly
what the air traffic controllers told the crew, except that the
plane was cleared to land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There shouldn't be a lack of information at all,'' Forte said.
``Clearly, in the investigation, they're going to look at the
decision-making model and try to determine what else was going on
on that flight deck that we might not be aware of yet that would
allow him to make a decision to land in what appears to be pretty
severe meteorological conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's no doubt that the weather was bad.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderstorms stretched from 45 miles north of the airport
to the Oklahoma boarder in southwest Arkansas, National Weather
Service meteorologist George Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   About 10:15 p.m., a 60 mph gust hit Hot Springs, 40 miles
southwest of Little Rock, Wilken said. That was followed by the
severe thunderstorm warning at 11:25 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The information was passed on to the air traffic controllers via
computer, Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have had the severe thunderstorm warning in hand,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm bore down on Little Rock, the weather service
tracked it on two Doppler radar systems: one in Little Rock and one
in Fort Smith, about 110 miles northwest of the airport. A third
weather service staffer passed the updates to the Federal Aviation
Administration, Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:32, the weather service recorded a 65-mph gust at its
office seven miles north of the airport. At 11:45, a 75-mph gust
was recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, when the plane crash-landed, the peak winds
were about 32 mph, hail was falling and it was raining so hard that
the weather service recorded four-tenths of an inch in three
minutes, Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes after the plane landed, the strongest winds were
recorded, an 87-mph gust, Wilken said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board and
the airline will review the data from the airport radar and the
weather service radar, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to have access and listen to the tower recordings, the
cockpit recordings,'' American Vice President Bob Baker said.
``Until we get a full picture of the weather, we can't speculate as
to whether it (weather) was a part of this, to what degree, or even
what the weather really was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the best anyone could do was ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   American's pilots ``to a man'' would not try to land in 57-mph
winds, said Drew Engelke, a spokesman for the Allied Pilots
Association, who flies an MD-80.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to know that that particular wind is out of the
capability of the aircraft,'' he said. ``Ideally, you would expect
that information to be relayed to the pilot. That's a question
that's going to have to be found out.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Dan Reed contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
