<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seeking offense, Klesko's in left
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves keep searching for an answer in left field,
and Ryan Klesko might be it again.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko, who moved from left field to first base in spring
training because of Andres Galarraga's illness, moved back to left
field Wednesday as the Braves continued to try to fill an offensive
void.
</P>
<P>
   Otis Nixon never got untracked as an everyday left fielder _
he's hitting .194 _ and his replacement, Gerald Williams, hit .194
(14-for-72) in May, .182 (12-for-66) as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox said he made the move to get Randall Simon
some at-bats. He also indicated he plans to use Williams in left
field and Klesko as the designated hitter this weekend against
Boston. If Klesko stays in left field, Simon and Brian Hunter would
platoon at first base. The Braves were 6-3 with Simon and Hunter
sharing first base while Klesko was hurt in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever's best for the team,'' Klesko said of returning to
the position he played his first five full seasons in the majors.
``As long as they don't make me catch. I'll play anywhere.''
Simon's turn
</P>
<P>
   Simon welcomes some at-bats. In May, he went 0-for-8 with no
RBIs, all as a pinch hitter. That followed his .379 batting average
in April, when his pinch hit at-bats were scarce but he made seven
starts at first when Klesko had the sore hamstring. Smoltz update
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz got a good report from team orthopedist Joe Chandler
the morning after his first start since coming off the disabled
list with an inflamed elbow. Smoltz picked up his sixth win with
six scoreless innings. Said Chandler: ``Today we looked to see if
there was fluid, and it looked good. There was no fluid and no
soreness.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss hopes to return this weekend from the strained
quadriceps that has kept him out of the lineup since last Thursday.
``There's still a little something there,'' Weiss said. ``But it's
certainly better (than a similar injury last year).'' ... In the
first release of the All-Star balloting, Chipper Jones is the
closest Brave to winning a starting spot. He has received 46,527
votes, which trails only Arizona's Matt Williams (51,865) among
third basemen. Other Braves figuring in are Javy Lopez (33,218), a
distant third behind Mike Piazza (122,392) at catcher; and Weiss,
who is third at shortstop with 30,823 votes behind Rey Ordonez
(60,779) and Barry Larkin (60,161). Andruw Jones (27,777) is
seventh and Brian Jordan (23,847) 11th among outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
