<SLUG> BC-BBN-DRAFT03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stahl, Faison selected 18th, 20th
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The baseball draft started 25 minutes late because of
a problem with the conference call. But once it began, Richard
Stahl and Vince Faison didn't have to wait long Wednesday to find
out where they had been selected.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl, a 6-foot-7 left-hander from Newton High School in
Covington, was taken by the Baltimore Orioles with the 18th pick in
the first round. Faison, a two-sport standout from Toombs County
who has signed a football scholarship with Georgia, was selected by
the San Diego Padres at No. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Redan High School shortstop Brandon Phillips was the next
Georgian taken, going to the Montreal Expos in the second round
with the 57th overall pick. He hit .630 with 14 homers as a senior.
</P>
<P>
   Once the draft started, it took less than 15 minutes to complete
the first round. Stahl got a call shortly after 1:30 p.m., then
returned to school for his British literature class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 24 hours have seemed like a week,'' said Stahl, who
was 11-0 as a senior. ``I've been very nervous. The Orioles were
one of the teams that I was hoping would draft me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second year in a row that two high school players
from Georgia were picked in the first round. Last year, Corey
Patterson of Harrison was taken No. 3 by the Chicago Cubs and
received a record draft bonus of $3.7 million. Sprayberry's Rick
Elder, also an outfielder, was taken by Baltimore with the 26th
pick and received $950,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stahl and Faison are expected to receive bonus offers of more
than $1 million each. Last year, the No. 18 pick got $1,075,000 and
the No. 20 selection $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Faison told the Padres and others teams that he would forsake
college football if taken in the first round. His father, Vincent
Sr., is waiting for a second kidney transplant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to turn down first-round money,'' said Faison, an
outfielder who hit .531 as a senior. ``My family will be
financially secure, and my dad will get some of the best medical
attention that's offered.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
