</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NOTEBOOK03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money, schedule hot topics
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ While the 1999 U.S. Women's Open
Championship will get its fair share of media attention this week,
the golfers will earn half what their male counterparts will at
Pinehurst, N.C., June 17-20.
</P>
<P>
   The total purse is $1.75 million and the champion will take home
$315,000. Compare that with $3.5 million and $625,000 for the men.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the women probably won't even get the same level of
press coverage that they're enjoying this week. The 2000 Women's
Open at Merit Club in Libertyville, Ill., a suburb of Chicago, will
bump up against the British Open at historic St. Andrews June
20-23.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Capouch, chairwoman of the U.S. Golf Association Women's
Committee, said the USGA isn't concerned about the scheduling
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is going to have that much of a bearing on
the Women's Open,'' she said, ``because we are in a great market
area, and we are standing on our own now.''
</P>
<P>
   However, there has been criticism that the women play their
biggest event in relatively isolated areas. Capouch announced that
the 2002 Women's Open will be held in Hutchinson, Kan., at Prairie
Dunes, another small venue in the same vein as Old Waverly and last
year's site, Kohler, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding prize money, Capouch said the USGA is ``working as
hard as it possibly can to do everything we can to make the purse
higher,'' but she doesn't see equal prize money happening soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Equal treatment to the USGA,'' she said, ``is conducting a
national championship of high quality, and we do the same treatment
for the women at the Women's Open as we do for the men at the Men's
Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain, rain, go away
</P>
<P>
   A torrential storm Wednesday afternoon terrified people who had
parked their cars in nearby fields, but didn't faze officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course drains really well,'' said Capouch, no doubt
relieved to field a question unrelated to prize money and
scheduling. ``The course is in perfect condition, and they did not
have a lot of rain prior to last weekend, so I think the course can
stand water.''
</P>
<P>
   The early forecast for today is warm and humid with a chance of
afternoon thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Park and drive
</P>
<P>
   Grace Park, the 1998 U.S. Women's Amateur Champion, is a long
hitter whose game suits the Old Waverly Course, which is 6,431
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recently at the NCAA, I hit a 342-yard (drive),'' said Park,
who won the individual title for Arizona State. ``The wind was
really strong with me, but still that was an official yardage. I've
hit a couple of times over 300, 280, somewhere around there. I
don't really account on how I hit it that long. I guess I've just
been fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, a native of South Korea who moved to Hawaii when she was
12, gained entry to the Open based on her amateur title. She'll
turn pro after this week.
</P>
<P>
   Button up
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, her first year as a pro, Nancy Lopez finished second to
Hollis Stacy in the Women's Open. She doesn't blame her driving or
her putting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was because my zipper was busted on my pants that
final day,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
