u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WEBB03-COX     06-02 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WEBB03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Karrie Webb: Getting a new grip on putting, LPGA Tour
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ Switching to a cross-handed putting grip has
made Karrie Webb a winner in four tournaments this year and the
favorite in the 1999 U.S. Women's Open that starts here today.
</P>
<P>
   But persistent questions about whether she can win her first
major have made the Australian just a little cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I answered these sort of questions at Dinah Shore this year,''
said Webb, who has won 13 tournaments since bursting onto the LPGA
scene in 1996 with a record $1 million rookie season. ``Coming into
the Dinah Shore (where she placed third), I only played 12 majors.
This is my 14th major that I have ever played in. I have a long
career ahead of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Old Waverly be the Webb site? This year, she has finished
in the top 10 in all 11 of her tournaments and leads the LPGA with
$738,066.
</P>
<P>
   She has won from the front and from behind, after trailing by as
many as five strokes. Her 26-under par at the 1999 Australian
Ladies Masters in February set an LPGA record.
</P>
<P>
   Webb leads the LPGA in scoring average at 68.49, a full stroke
better than Annika Sorenstam of Sweden. She also leads the tour in
rounds under par (33 of 39), top 10 finishes (11 of 11), birdies
(192) and greens in regulation (.789).
</P>
<P>
   In the Open, she will be challenged by 149 other players,
including fellow Aussie Rachel Hetherington, Juli Inkster and Meg
Mallon, each of whom has won twice this year; veteran Nancy Lopez,
who has been the runner-up at the U.S. Open four times; Sorenstam;
and defending champion Se Ri Pak of South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play another 15 years, I have 60 more chances at winning
a major,'' said Webb, 24, who shares her hometown with Greg Norman.
``I'm not in a hurry to win a major. If I win one, that is going to
be great. I think it goes along with winning your first tournament
ever: I think sometimes you don't really know what you are doing,
and everything falls into place and you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Webb has all of the tools to help that happen. Laura
Davies has called her the world's best ball-striker. After she won
the Mercury Titleholders on May 10, Mallon said, ``It looks so easy
that you forget how awesome it is.''
</P>
<P>
   But winning a major has never looked easy. Dottie Pepper, who is
paired with Webb in the first two rounds, said she thinks there is
undue emphasis on winning majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have often said I thought (Jack) Nicklaus started this whole
major rah-rah, because he built his schedule around majors and
evaluated his career on majors,'' said Pepper, who won the Dinah
Shore to end a three-year winless streak. ``Majors do not make a
career. Ask Andy North. He has won two Opens and that was about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pepper said she focuses more on getting into the Hall of Fame.
``I've got to believe that that is one of Karrie's goals as well,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, who is not one of the most charismatic or talkative
players on the Tour, is characteristically understated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think my overall game has been pretty consistent,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   But her putting has improved markedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you make a 10-, 15-footer in the first couple of holes,''
Webb said, ``it takes the pressure off trying to hit it close for
the rest of the day, because you sort of have the feeling that you
are going to make them anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't really put a lot of pressure on myself to hit the
ball close because my putting has been so good.''
</P>
<P>
   In her three U.S. Opens, Webb has not played well in the first
two rounds. Her best finish was fourth in 1997. She tied for 31st
last year. ``I definitely lost my patience with nine holes to go,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was a season that would be stellar by most players'
standards, but it was sub-par for her. She won twice and was fourth
on the money list, but she was overshadowed by Sorenstam and Pak.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my first two years, it was pretty hard to accept
anything less,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   So, she went home to Australia and changed her putting grip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not think I had much to lose,'' she said. ``Years back,
in the mid-1980s, if a player went cross-handed, you thought it was
the end of her career because of the yips.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb's career is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
