<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S. African anti-bias group got $25,000 from Atlanta Olympic
group
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Among the gifts made by Atlantans in their effort to
land the Summer Olympics, one stands out in documents released
Wednesday: $25,000 to the South African Non-Racial Olympic
Committee in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, founded in 1963, was dedicated to creating an
integrated South African Olympic team at a time when blacks were
barred from participating, its former president said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the country's team remained segregated, the committee,
known by the acronym SAN-ROC, worked to have it barred from
participating in the Olympics _ an effort which succeeded in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   But SAN-ROC was not a political organization, said poet Dennis
Brutus, its first president until the late 1980s, in a telephone
interview from London.
</P>
<P>
   ``SAN-ROC was not formed to challenge the government,'' he said.
``Our concern was strictly with sport and the observance of the
Olympic charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Brutus said he did not know how the Georgia Amateur Athletics
Foundation money was used.
</P>
<P>
   The president of SAN-ROC in 1990 was Sam Ramsamy. In the 1990s,
as apartheid ended and an integrated South African Olympic team was
created, SAN-ROC merged with other groups to become the National
Olympic Committee of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Young, co-chairman of the Georgia Amateur Athletics
Foundation, said the donation to SAN-ROC was important because
South Africa was preparing to rejoin the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many leaders of Atlanta's bid group were passionate about what
South Africa meant to the Olympic Games,'' he said, ``and our
financial support for its efforts was a small means by which we
could share our passion.''
</P>
<P>
   In its report to the U.S. House Commerce Committee, the GAAF
said the grant was meant ``to help speed the destruction of
apartheid in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
