<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GIFTSQ&AMP;A03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Line between gift, bribe not crossed, leaders say
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Olympic leaders Billy Payne and Andrew Young,
co-chairmen of the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation, met with
Olympics beat reporter Melissa Turner on Wednesday in the World
Trade Club at the downtown Sun Trust building for a
question-and-answer session on the GAAF's report to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have steadfastly denied that the Atlanta bid committee
did anything that violated the International Olympic Committee
rules on gift-giving and visits by IOC members. Does this report
mean you are changing your tune?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: The $200 rule was a guideline established to protect bid
cities from spending too much money. And the few times we exceeded
it, they were all personalized, specialized gifts _ 50 percent of
the time glass blown by Hans Frabel here to depict the sport that
was important to the IOC members. We were proud to give those
gifts. We believe they do not fit the category whatsoever of trying
to influence voters.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where, then, do you draw the line between a gift and a bribe?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: The relativity of how we bid vs. others would certainly
be a beginning point. But we'll let others make those judgements.
</P>
<P>
   Young: You are also assuming influencing a five-step secret
ballot process can be done monetarily.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You characterize these expensive items as simply gifts for
friends. Were these IOC members really close friends?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: These people became in every respect our close personal
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Young: The gifts are seen as kind of mementoes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is a $1,000 carburetor kit a memento?
</P>
<P>
   Young: It is a memento if you come from a country where you
can't get a carburetor kit. Q: Why would GAAF pick up the cost for
tuition and accommodations for three young African athletes to
train in Atlanta if not to influence the IOC voters in those
countries?
</P>
<P>
   Young: Same reason we had an Olympic training camp in LaGrange.
Same reason we hosted the Angolan basketball team at Clark Atlanta
University. We are sports-loving people that see sports as
important in world development.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Aren't there deserving, talented athletes with Olympic
potential all over? Why select these three?
</P>
<P>
   Young: If we could have gotten half a dozen kids with Olympic
potential, we would have found the money for them.
</P>
<P>
   Payn: A more appropriate answer would be, you do what you can do
and help where you can help. And while it may be small in the
context of the whole world of opportunity, it is demonstrative of
the way Andy has lived his life and been involved in sports.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you not consider paying for the two tennis players from
the Republic of Congo as a favor to (expelled IOC member)
Jean-Claude Ganga?
</P>
<P>
   Young: Yeah. We were in the business of doing favors. But these
were not bribes. Q: Did you ever step back and ask why you were
spending $14,000 for two plane tickets?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: Because that's what the bill was. We were reimbursing
them for the cost of the tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you ever feel you were taken advantage of by these IOC
members?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: We were so in love with the prospect of introducing the
world to the people of Atlanta and we were working within the
bounds of our own sense of fairness and honor and integrity.... and
(we) believe we did so successfully, that the sinister side of the
process never entered our minds for the whole three years. Q: Why
did you not provide this documentation to the IOC when they asked
for it months ago during their investigation of bid cities? Payne:
The IOC didn't ask for details. This asks the big questions and
wants all the details, which is precisely the forum we've been
wanting and have been asking for _ an official inquiry which we are
delighted to cooperate with.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you believe the IOC would act on this information if they
had it?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: There are no gifts on there I believe would be
unfavorably or surprisingly or disgustingly received by the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   Young: The context we ought to frame this in is, we spent $6.5
million up to the bid. Toronto spent $15 million. Greece spent up
to $30 million. Melbourne spent $25 million. Given the amount of
money spent on the bid, to reach the conclusion that we bought the
Games with the smallest amount of money just doesn't compute.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Salt Lake City spent a great deal of money on gifts. Would
you consider them bribes?
</P>
<P>
   Young: When you (missed out on a previous bid), you become
friends with people, and their circumstances become desperate and
you try to figure out ways to help them. Part of what happened to
Salt Lake is friendships and people taking advantage of
friendships.... I think Salt Lake got a very bad rap. I don't know
what Salt Lake did and what they didn't do. I defend the
scholarships, but I don't defend any financial payments. But the
technical assistance to athletes, the scholarship opportunities
that help to improve the condition of athletics in those countries
(is fine). Q: Wasn't (ousted Salt Lake Olympic Chief) Tom Welch
also just in the business of doing favors for the IOC members?
</P>
<P>
   Young: He was. The difference is Salt Lake turned on people who
won them the Games. Tom Welch beat up his wife and they got angry
with him and wanted to get rid of him. He did some bad things _ bad
things in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you create the ``Atlanta model'' of wooing IOC members,
and then other cities took it to excess?
</P>
<P>
   Payne: Yes, I believe we made wonderfully sincere friendships
and I know we did it with the expenditure of a minimum amount of
dollars for gifts that we have established with this report.
Whether others since us have tried to develop the next iteration of
``let's be their friends'' and also give lavish gifts or the next
version of the Atlanta model, I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
