<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    (Almost) a United-free environment
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ We promise. From this date on _ at least during the
offseason _ this column will try to be Manchester United-free. But
a few loose odds and ends from the scintillating European Cup final
last Wednesday need to be tied up before embarking on a summer
without even mentioning the upcoming wedding of David Beckham and
Posh Spice or any other activity involving the Red Devils.
</P>
<P>
   The day after they shocked Bayern Munich 2-1 with two
injury-time goals, United's value on the London stock exchange rose
by about 30 pence a share, to roughly $797 million. And corporate
beancounters are frothing about United's further merchandising
potential, which surely will solidify its position as the
wealthiest club in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in football, it's all about brand development, not just
in Britain, but around the globe,'' said Nick Batram, London soccer
business analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Hating United, of course, is an equally lucrative pursuit in the
U.K., with ``Manchester United Ruined My Life'' currently high on
the sports best-seller lists. For all the wondrous soccer talents
of Beckham, Ryan Giggs and company, what they represent to the men
in monkey suits also has earned them plenty of derision from
self-proclaimed purists.
</P>
<P>
   On the pitch, United's success is dovetailing into optimism for
England's endangered Euro 2000 hopes. Saturday's Wembley qualifier
with Sweden, the first for new full-time manager Kevin Keegan,
could feature United striker Teddy Sheringham, who along with Ole
Gunnar Solsjkaer came off the bench to get the goals against Bayern
Munich.
</P>
<P>
   They also provided The Sun with perfect fodder for tabloid
headlines:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Subs Sink Germans.''
</P>
<P>
   Only in England.
</P>
<P>
   Euro 2000: Yugoslavs denied visas
</P>
<P>
   The Irish government announced Wednesday it would deny travel
visas to members of the Yugoslavia national team, which is
scheduled to play Ireland Saturday in a Euro 2000 qualifier in
Dublin. UEFA, the European soccer federation, has ignored pleas
from Ireland and the sports ministers of other European nations to
call off the game because of the Balkan nation's actions in Kosovo
that have led to NATO bombings. Yugoslavia was banned from the 1992
European championships and the 1994 World Cup because its war
against Bosnia-Herzegovina ... A full weekend of qualifiers
starting Friday features Moldova at Germany, Belarus at Denmark,
Russia at France, Bulgaria at Poland, San Marino at Spain, Slovakia
at Portugal, Hungary at Romania, Croatia at Macedonia, Italy at
Wales, Czech Republic at Estonia and Scotland at the Faroe Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Atlas-Toluca final
</P>
<P>
   After shocking Cruz Azul 6-0 on aggregate in the Mexican Torneo
de Verano semifinals, Atlas has a chance to do something it hasn't
done in 48 years _ win a league championship. The Guadalajara club
will play host to Toluca tonight in the first leg of the finals,
providing a high-scoring possibility against the favorites. Juan
Pablo Rodriguez and Hugo Castillo scored two goals apiece in the
semifinals for Atlas. Toluca had a tougher time putting Santos
Laguna away 4-3 on aggregate. Enrique Alfaro got the winner in the
75th minute Sunday in a 3-2 triumph. The second leg of the finals
will be shown live at 2 p.m. Sunday on Univision.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Morientes' value rises
</P>
<P>
   If anybody wants to pry midfielder Fernando Morientes from Real
Madrid before his contract expires in 2003, they're going to have
to shell out a minimum of $94.2 million. His buyout clause was
raised from $21.9 million on Tuesday after Morientes scored twice
to give Madrid a 2-1 victory over Mallorca and second place in the
Primera Division.
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Mazzone raps ex-boss
</P>
<P>
   Carlo Mazzone walked out Monday as head coach of Bologna, livid
over comments from owner Giuseppe Gazzoni before the Serie A season
wound to a close that he wanted to make a change at the top.
Mazzone made it for him, jumping to Perugia, his 10th Italian club.
... AS Roma finished fourth and fifth in the Serie A the last two
seasons under coach Zdenek Zeman, but that apparently wasn't enough
for him to keep the job. Club management is eyeing former AC Milan
head man Fabio Capello to succeed Zeman.
</P>
<P>
   Germany: 'Fairy tale' comes true
</P>
<P>
   With a stadium seating fewer than 10,000 and a budget thin even
by American A-League standards, SpVgg Unterhaching has been
promoted to the Bundesliga. The suburban Munich club sells Guinness
on tap at home games and is flexible with starting times to
accommodate its largely yuppie fan base. ``It's a modern fairy
tale,'' club president Engelbert Kupka exclaimed. England: Watford
gains promotion
</P>
<P>
   Although his club spends far less on salaries than he probably
did on wardrobe during his ``Goodbye Yellow Brick Road'' tour 25
years ago, Watford chairman Sir Elton John said he intends to toe
the line on wages despite moving up to the Premier League. Watford,
which beat Bolton Wanderers 2-0 Monday in a first-division playoff,
is ensured of at least $15 million in Premier League television
revenues. But John and manager Graham Taylor, the former England
coach, say they won't spend it all on player acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
