A0705 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      06-02 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS RULING COSTS BUREAU $1.7 BILLION, OFFICIALS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has asked Congress for
an additional $1.7 billion that it said would be needed to conduct
the 2000 census as a result of a Supreme Court decision sharply
restricting the Census Bureau's ability to use statistical
sampling.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent Tuesday to the Republican and Democratic
leaders of the House and Senate appropriations committees, Jacob
Lew, director of the Office of Management and Budget, said the $2.9
billion that the administration had already requested to conduct
the census next year would not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have already said they will spend whatever is
necessary to conduct the census without sampling, which political
analysts estimated would have added to the population counts in
urban areas that tend to vote Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   The additional $1.7 billion would push total spending for the
2000 census to $6.99 billion, dwarfing the $2.6 billion spent on
the 1990 census.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is evidence that in the absence of using modern
statistical methods, it is simply going to cost a lot more to do
the census,'' said Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the spending request, the cost of the census was
expected to be double that of 1990. Increases in the number of
women working outside the home, in immigrants with a limited
command of English and in people alienated from government have
made the American population more difficult and therefore more
expensive to count.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said that even with the additional spending, he could
not guarantee that the 2000 census would improve on the 1990
census, which missed 8.4 million people and double-counted 4.4
million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not more than cautiously optimistic that the 2000 census
might be better than we had in 1990,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials said the additional money would mainly be
needed to pay the salaries and provide office space for 860,000
additional census takers. These field workers, or enumerators, will
go door-to-door to count people in households that did not return
mail-in census forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just in paying the enumerators and giving them infrastructure
support, you're already over $1.2 billion,'' Prewitt said. ``Then
it's bits and pieces: more telephone lines, more technology
support.''
</P>
<P>
   Under its original plan, the bureau had hoped to keep down the
cost of the census by counting everyone in 90 percent of the
households in each census tract _ an area of about 1,700
households. Field workers would then count everyone in 1 out of 10
households in the remaining 10 percent of dwellings and use that
sample to estimate the number and characteristics of those missed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans objected to the plan, declaring that it was illegal
and would give Democrats a political advantage in the drawing of
boundaries for congressional districts, since many of those who are
missed tend to be minorities who live in overwhelmingly Democratic
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican politicians and advocates, including
then-House Speaker Newt Gingrich, sued the administration, and on
Jan. 25 the Supreme Court ruled that the bureau's proposed
statistical sampling could not be used to determine the population
counts for purposes of allocating seats in the House of
Representatives among the states.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court left open whether sampling could be used to
determine population counts used to distribute federal money or to
draw boundaries for congressional or other legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders could not be reached Wednesday for comment on
the administration's figures.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats in Congress, meanwhile, are gloating over the
Republicans' predicament of now having to finance an increasingly
expensive census as Congress and the administration are struggling
to stay under legally mandated budgetary targets for domestic
spending.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
