<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0708 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINUX-LINUX_SFCHRON &LR;      06-02 1505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINUX-LINUX </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Linux Wrestling Microsoft for the Desktop  
 By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Linux already has won the hearts of techies the world over, and
lately, the free operating system has carved out a place on
corporate servers. Could the typical office worker's desktop be the
next stop?
<P>
   Some signs are pointing in that direction, as a growing army of
Linux developers races to overcome obstacles that have kept
mainstream users at a distance. But most analysts say that although
the upstart OS will continue to spread rapidly, it's not likely to
put much of a dent in Microsoft's domination of the desktop, at
least not any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   Linux, known by its penguin logo, is an operating system _ the
basic software that controls a computer. Cooperatively developed by
volunteer programmers, it's available free on the Internet though
some companies sell enhanced versions on CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
   And Linux sales have been booming. Last year, they reached 2.6
million worldwide, up 47 percent from 1997, according to
International Data Corp. And there's no way to track how many more
people are downloading free copies.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers are big enough to make Microsoft take notice: An
internal memo leaked last year from the Redmond, Wash., giant
described Linux and other ``open-source'' software as ``a direct
threat.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Linux has shown up in business and government mainly on
servers _ the big computers that manage networks of PCs _ but now
it's starting to appear on some ordinary computers.
</P>
<P>
   In Medina, Wash., the Seattle suburb where Bill Gates built his
palatial estate, City Hall recently installed a Linux system to
handle storage and retrieval of correspondence and other documents.
``We knew what we needed _ mostly ease of use and reliability _ and
what we could pay, and Linux was the clear choice,'' said Craig
Fischer, deputy city clerk. ''It's working out fine.''
</P>
<P>
   While most Linux supporters still see servers and workstations
as their biggest opportunity, some vendors have their eye on the
broader business market. Consider these recent developments:
</P>
<P>
   _Dell, which in April began offering servers and workstations
with Linux instead of Windows, last week extended the program to
its OptiPlex line of mainstream business PCs. The Round Rock,
Texas, company also eliminated a $20 premium it previously had
charged for systems with Linux preinstalled, and it made Linux
software and information easier to find on its heavily traveled Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Dell apparently is the only major PC vendor offering
Linux preinstalled, but other heavyweights such as IBM and
Hewlett-Packard recently have pledged various kinds of support for
the alternative OS.
</P>
<P>
   _More than 1 million people have downloaded the Linux version of
Corel Corp.'s WordPerfect 8 word-processing program since the
company made it available free on the Web in December. Clearly
hoping that the Linux wave will help Corel regain ground it lost to
Microsoft in the Windows application market, the Ottawa software
publisher plans to deliver its entire next-generation suite,
WordPerfect Office 2000, for Linux this fall. Its popular graphics
titles are slated to follow early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Two other productivity suites, called StarOffice and Applixware,
already are available for Linux. Like WordPerfect, both can open
and save files in Microsoft Office formats, the standard in most of
corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   _The selection of software for Linux is growing steadily.
Netscape offers a version of its Communicator browser and e-mail
software, and IBM announced plans last month to bring its ViaVoice
speech-recognition technology to the platform. An open-source
project called WINE, with support from Corel and others, is
providing tools to help others ``port'' still more Windows programs
to Linux.
</P>
<P>
   And users who require Windows applications not yet available for
Linux now can run both operating systems at the same time with
VMware, a $199 ``virtual platform'' utility ($75 for noncommercial
use) released two weeks ago by VMware Inc. of Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   _To help nontechnical users switch to the new OS, Linux
distributors and developers are simplifying their installation
programs, which previously required users to enter numerous
technical details, and polishing up point-and-click interfaces that
make the system easier to use.
</P>
<P>
   Among nearly half a dozen companies now selling Linux on CD-ROM,
the current leader in user-friendliness is Caldera Systems of Orem,
Utah. Its version, called OpenLinux 2.2, comes with an intelligent
installer that all but eliminates the need for users to understand
much about their hardware. Also included is KDE 1.1, a graphical
user-interface package that lets users choose the look and feel
they like best from among several elegant alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Other Linux distributors are concentrating mainly on server and
technical markets, but they, too, are putting increasing emphasis
on ease of use. Red Hat Linux 6.0, the latest release of the
best-seller among Linux distributions, includes both KDE and GNOME,
a new open-source user-interface alternative created, like Linux
itself, by a far-flung international team of volunteer programmers.
</P>
<P>
   And next fall, Corel plans to put its own name on yet another
``distribution'' _ a bundle of software built around the free OS _
featuring a specially enhanced, Windows-like version of KDE.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  _Linux distributors have been beefing up their support
programs, and they've been joined by startup companies specializing
in tech support, training, compatibility testing and consulting for
the free OS. Previously, cautious corporate technology managers
often refused even to consider Linux because such services weren't
available.
</P>
<P>
   LinuxCare Inc. of San Francisco hasn't yet reached its first
birthday, but it already has won a contract to provide support for
Dell's Linux systems. Just last month, it secured financing from
Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers _ the well-known Menlo Park
venture capital firm's first Linux investment.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of these trends has convinced some business
customers that Linux is ready for mainstream desktops.
</P>
<P>
   The Burlington Coat Factory chain, for example, is installing
1,250 Dell systems with Red Hat Linux in some 250 stores in 42
states. They'll be used to run Web-based store-management
applications, including Burlington's Baby Registry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deploying in Windows boxes in 250 stores would be pretty
daunting,'' said Mike Prince, chief information officer of the
Burlington, N.J., company. ``We put Linux out there, and the boxes
run for six to 12 months without rebooting. It just seemed to us a
more stable, scalable and economical environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Caldera's OpenLinux soon will appear on desktop PCs in the
office of the Kern County Superintendent of Schools in Bakersfield.
``We've had it on servers and some of the engineers' desktops for
nearly three years,'' said David Cates, network systems engineer,
``but now with Caldera's 2.2 release, it's finally become a viable
solution for the masses.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the office's current PCs will ``go the way of the dodo''
this year because of Year 2000 problems, he said, and up to 100 of
them will be replaced with low-cost hardware running OpenLinux,
WordPerfect and, to fill any software gaps, VMware.
</P>
<P>
   Several local school districts, according to Cates, also are
planning to switch to Linux on classroom machines; some of them
even plan to install the free OS on their Apple Macs.
</P>
<P>
   While watching such developments with interest, analysts said
they don't expect Linux to sweep the business world, at least in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to be proven wrong,'' said Bill Peterson, Linux
market analyst at IDC in Framingham, Mass. ``But I still think the
real opportunity for Linux is the server and will be for several
years to come.'' He noted that Microsoft's domination of the
desktop market is still increasing, while sales of Linux for server
deployment rose 212 percent from 1997 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   George Weiss, an analyst at the Gartner Group in Stamford,
Conn., put the point more forcefully: ``Linux just isn't a
significant part of the desktop market,'' he said. ``It doesn't
offer compatibility with the wide variety of applications written
for Windows nor does it offer any compelling advantage over what we
have already.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some Linux partisans agree up to a point, but they argue
that the situation is changing fast. ``The general view is that
Linux is pretty slick on the server but still needs another six to
eight months in the oven before it's ready for the desktop,'' said
Arthur Tyde III, founder and executive vice president of LinuxCare.
``But there are already plenty of good office applications, and if
you prebuild the desktop for people, they have no trouble using
it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the next year,'' Tyde said, ``I think you're going to see
explosive growth in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
