<SLUG> BC-SCOTLAND-ROBERTSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER CRITICISM, BANK OF SCOTLAND REASSESSES ROBERTSON DEAL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ After squirming under public criticism of a banking
venture with Pat Robertson, the conservative American television
evangelist, Bank of Scotland said Wednesday that it was reviewing
its relationship with him .
</P>
<P>
   It was the first indication by the bank that the project, which
was once described as something of a coup, might be foundering.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism from depositors began almost immediately after the
bank agreed in March to establish a joint telephone and Internet
banking venture with Robertson, hoping to harness its expertise in
telephone-banking to Robertson's vast data base of followers.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Scotland has a similar deal with the retailer J.
Sainsbury PLC and saw the venture with Robertson as a smart way to
tunnel into the rich U.S. banking market. The bank's executives
vouched for Robertson's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But the depositors, and some Scottish institutions, did not
quite see it that way. About 500 depositors _ none of them big
accounts, according to the bank _ switched their money elsewhere.
Gay rights groups and churches protested the bank's association
with a figure who is depicted as a right-wing fundamentalist. The
local West Lothian district council said it might close a $400
million account with Bank of Scotland in protest.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few days, matters came to a head.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Scottish disapproval of him, Robertson used an
episode of his television show, ``The 700 Club,'' to call Scotland
a ``dark place'' where ``you can't believe how strong the
homosexuals are.'' The remarks made the front page of The Scotsman,
one of the country's main newspapers, on Monday and were seen as
putting the bank in an untenable position with its heartland
Scottish clientele.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, after the bank announced that Robertson would be
the chairman of the new venture, the Trades Union Congress,
Britain's biggest labor organization, threatened a boycott by
100,000 members using the bank's credit card.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Iain Fiddes, director of public relations for Bank
of Scotland, said the contentious ``700 Club'' program had ``now
been received and reviewed.'' ``The Bank is considering its
position, and a statement will be made in due course,'' Fiddes said
in a statement that was issued shortly after Bank of Scotland stock
fell 3.7 percent to close at 850 pence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank will meet with the other shareholders, Robertson
included, in the next few days,'' Fiddes said. Bank executives are
expected to meet with Robertson in Boston on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is a potentially lucrative venture that would offer
telephone banking to as many as 50 million television viewers, with
the possibility later of credit cards, loans and mortgages. But
analysts said financial damage to the Bank of Scotland would be
limited if it pulled out of the deal, because it involves no
capital investment or jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Robertson's Christian Broadcasting Network in
Virginia Beach, Va., did not immediately respond to telephoned
requests for comment. Its vehicle for the project with Bank of
Scotland is called Robertson Financial Services.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Scotland is not Robertson's only British business
partner. Last January, he became a non-executive director of Laura
Ashley PLC, the ailing clothing and home furnishing retailer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
