<HEADER>
A0710 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINUXSIDE-LINUXSIDE_S     06-02 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINUXSIDE-LINUX </SLUG>
 SIDE _ SF CHRON  
 REVIEW/HENRY NORR  &HT;     Replacing Windows With Linux Is Tricky 
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
To see just what would be involved in replacing Windows with Linux
as a desktop operating system, I recently tried out two of the
latest releases of the open-source OS, Caldera Systems' OpenLinux
2.2 and Red Hat Software's Red Hat Linux 6.0. I also checked out a
word-processing application, Corel's WordPerfect 8 for Linux. It
was my first experience with Linux or any form of Unix.
<P>
   On the whole, it wasn't encouraging: Trying to install the new
OS on a machine already set up for Windows 98 brought me up against
a long list of frustrations, and I still don't have Red Hat
running. But I did finally manage to get Caldera's OpenLinux
installed, together with WordPerfect 8.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with installing Linux alongside Windows is that
the two systems require different hard drive formats, so they have
to be installed on separate drives or partitions (portions of a
hard disk set up to operate like a separate drive). Caldera's
installer incorporates a special Linux-compatible version of
PowerQuest's PartitionMagic, a popular Windows partitioning
utility. My problem was that I'd already partitioned my hard drives
with the regular Windows version. As a result I already had more
than four partitions, which turns out to be as many as the Caldera
version of the program can handle _ a limitation not mentioned in
OpenLinux's otherwise-excellent manual.
</P>
<P>
   Once a Caldera tech-support rep had explained the problem, I
disconnected one of those drives and tried instead to install
OpenLinux on an unpartitioned 18-gigabyte SCSI drive. The manual
told me I had to defragment it _ a long slow task on a drive that
big. Once that was done, the actual installation went smoothly,
until I got to a screen that asked me to specify whether my
hardware clock runs in local time or Greenwich Mean Time _ a
question I couldn't answer without studying the manual. The
installer also guessed wrong about the specs of my video card,
until I told it to check again.
</P>
<P>
   I did finally get the OS installed on the SCSI drive, but
BootMagic, a utility that was supposed to let me choose between
Linux and Windows 98, apparently couldn't find Linux there. Neither
could the utility that's supposed to uninstall Linux partitions.
</P>
<P>
   So I tried again on a different drive, this one a Castlewood
Orb, a new device that uses 2-gigabyte removable platters. Again
the installation went pretty smoothly, and this time BootMagic saw
the new OS. But when I selected it, OpenLinux reported a ``file
system failure'' leaving me no choice but to reset the machine.
</P>
<P>
   My adventures with Red Hat 6.0 were even more unpleasant. This
distribution includes not one but two partition utilities. But both
turned out to be beyond me _ they kept asking me to do things like
``enter a mount point'' _ a concept the manual acknowledges is
likely to be unfamiliar, but never effectively explains. Suffice it
to say that my many attempts to figure out what they're after have
so far been in vain.
</P>
<P>
   I finally decided to back up and reformat one of my standard
drives so I could dedicate it to OpenLinux. Now it's working pretty
well. The point-and-click interface it comes with is attractive,
fairly easy to figure out, and very customizable. WordPerfect 8 is
a polished and powerful word processor, with all the features of
its Windows sibling. When I went online, Netscape Communicator 4.5
was noticeably faster on Linux than on Windows 98 on the same
400-MHz Pentium II system, or on my 400-MHz Power Mac. But I still
can't figure out how to get the system to recognize my CD-ROM
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: Once it's completely installed, Linux may be
easy enough for just about anyone to use. The trick is getting it
on your machine. If you try it, I recommend that you use a freshly
formatted internal IDE drive. And if possible, arrange to have a
Unix geek on hand to help.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
