<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-GENENTECH </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Genentech Wins UC Lawsuit  &HT;     By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Genentech Corp. eked out an important legal victory yesterday when
a federal jury in San Francisco failed to find that the biotech
giant had infringed on a University of California patent for human
growth hormone.
<P>
   Although eight of nine jurors concluded that the South San
Francisco firm had copied UC's work, a lone juror sided with
Genentech, sparing the company as much as $1.2 billion in actual
and punitive damages that the university was planning to seek. But
the deadlock also allows UC to seek a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won,'' said Genentech attorney Sean Johnston. ``The
University didn't prove its case.''
</P>
<P>
   UC lawyer Gerald Dodson said he was ``disappointed we didn't get
a unanimous verdict'' but said he was ``heartened'' that all but
one juror sided with the university.
</P>
<P>
   UC spent nine years and $20 million trying to prove that, 20
years ago, two former Genentech researchers used DNA purloined from
a UC lab in San Francisco as the starting point for Genentech's
growth hormone drug, called Protropin.
</P>
<P>
   Dodson said UC lawyers now must decide whether to press their
patent-infringement claim in a new trial, which could cost an
additional $2 million. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors prescribe Protropin for children who are abnormally
small and need help to grow. Protropin and a second growth hormone,
Nutropin, generated $214 million, or almost 20 percent of
Genentech's total sales last year.
</P>
<P>
   The case attracted media attention because the two former
Genentech scientists who worked on the growth hormone project took
opposite sides during the six-week trial.
</P>
<P>
   German-born researcher Peter Seeburg, testifying for UC, alleged
that he and David Goeddel conspired to use UC's DNA and concealed
that fact for the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg said he returned to a UC lab one month after he had quit
working there, removed a DNA sample and put it in a refrigerator at
Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   Goeddel denied he ever used the DNA that Seeburg took, and
offered his 20-year-old lab notebook as proof that he had grown a
separate DNA sample in his lab at Genentech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight of nine of us believed Mr. Seeburg took it (the UC DNA)
and used it,'' said juror Don Ladue, a Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric
supervisor. ``He had it (the DNA) sitting there in an icebox. He
was under pressure. Sure he used it.''
</P>
<P>
   S. Mau, a juror from the East Bay, said the panel was bothered
by inconsistencies in Goeddel's notebook. ``In the beginning, he
recorded everything, hour by hour,'' Mau said. ``We felt it was
strange how his notes got so vague just where the switch supposedly
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Goeddel, who now is chief executive of another South San
Francisco biotech firm, Tularik Inc., defended his work in a brief
telephone interview with The Chronicle. He said Genentech has
posted his notebooks on its Web site so that scientists can
scrutinize his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as solid a notebook as any scientist has ever kept,''
Goeddel said, adding, ``Hopefully, my scientific reputation won't
be tarnished by one person's unsubstantiated claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeburg, now a scientist with the Max-Planck Institute in
Heidelberg, Germany, could not be reached for comment. But in a
letter published this week in the scientific journal Nature,
Seeburg repeated his contention that under ``increasing pressure''
to finish the growth hormone project in 1979, ``my colleague
(Goeddel) and I agreed to use the University of California's DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this conflicting scientific testimony generated
headlines, jury foreman Ronald Losch said jurors didn't dwell on
their different version of events. The issue that finally hung the
jury was technical, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's lawyers claimed that their growth hormone DNA had
subtle but important differences from UC's version. Losch said the
lone juror agreed with Genentech and refused to go along with the
eight jurors who decided that the two DNAs were identical enough to
support the university's claim.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech stock fell 31 cents to close at $86.50 per share as
the verdict broke just before the close of trading.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
