<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0714 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON_SFCHR     06-02 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-CHEVRON </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Texaco Board Ends Talks With Chevron  &HT;     By Rebecca Smith 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Texaco's board of directors terminated merger talks with Chevron
yesterday, saying a combination was ``unacceptable for several
reasons, including complexity, feasibility, risk and price.''
<P>
   Until yesterday, neither company had admitted that talks were
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts said Texaco slammed the door because differences
between the oil giants proved intractable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both sides realized that getting FTC approval would
have been too big a hurdle,'' said Keith Petersen, analyst for
Salomon Smith Barney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also appears Chevron wasn't being overly generous
financially and Texaco executives may simply have decided they'd
rather keep their company and their jobs,'' Petersen concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse press release, Chevron Chairman Kenneth Derr said he
was ``surprised that the Texaco board turned down a very
competitive offer that included a significant price premium to
Texaco shareholders and an opportunity to receive Chevron stock
with its acknowledged strong growth prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they think both Chevron and Texaco will continue
to seek merger partners. The logical suitor for Texaco now is Royal
Dutch Shell, with which it already operates service stations and
refineries in the United States under joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron is expected to woo independent oil companies, mostly
because other ``majors'' already have gone to the altar with
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that could be prospects for Chevron include Conoco,
Phillips Petroleum, USX Marathon, Burlington Resources, Anadarko
Petroleum, Kerr McGee or Enron, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Chevron nor Texaco was viewed as needing to merge. Both
are well-managed companies with strong balance sheets. But a merger
would have enabled the combined firm to cut costs by an estimated
$1.5 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron reportedly offered $80 a share or a total of $42 billion
for New York's Texaco, although that price was never confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   But Texaco continued to trade at a $15 discount to the rumored
price, indicating Wall Street speculators didn't believe the deal
would come off.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts late yesterday theorized that the issue of corporate
succession was a problem. Derr was believed to have insisted on
retaining chairmanship of any combined company until he retires in
two to four years. The hitch concerned who would succeed him _
Texaco Chairman Peter Bijur or Chevron Vice Chairman David
O'Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   In general, analysts speak more admiringly of Bijur but O'Reilly
was presumed to have held the stronger hand as a key executive of
the acquiring firm.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the talks marks the second time this year that
San Francisco's Chevron has failed in a merger attempt.
</P>
<P>
   It tried to buy Atlantic Richfield Co. of Los Angeles, but lost
out to BP Amoco in March in a $26.8 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Chevron-Texaco deal gone forward, antitrust officials
would have &UR;  &LR; probed the combined company's control of the refining
and fuel retailing marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, a merger of Chevron and Texaco (with its Shell
connections) would have put 43 percent of all branded gasoline
stations in the hands of related companies, far ahead of
Mobil-Exxon's 12-percent market share and Arco's 11-percent market
share.
</P>
<P>
   Most industry watchers said they believed the FTC would have
ordered divestitures to prevent unacceptable market power.
</P>
<P>
   News of the talks' collapse came after the close of trading.
Texaco's stock closed up 31 cents, at $64.50, on the New York Stock
Exchange. Chevron's stock closed up $1.56, at $92, also on the Big
Board.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
