A0717 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC-PUC_SFCHRON &LR;      06-02 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-PUC </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Pricing for Calls to Internet Still in Limbo  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; A frenzy has erupted in California over a proposal that could have
increased what consumers pay to surf the Internet.
<P>
   But the proposed plan, which would have reclassified calls to
the Internet as long-distance instead of local, has been modified
and won't impact what consumers pay to get online _ at least for
now.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, state regulators will vote today on two proposals _ one
that largely would keep the status quo and another that would
reopen the issue to examination by state regulators at a later
date.
</P>
<P>
   It all stems from a dispute between Pacific Bell and Pac-West
Telecomm, a competing local phone company that provides phone
service to many Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   The two are fighting over whether Pac-West should be compensated
for handling calls made from Pac Bell's customers to various ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1996 Telecommunications Act, local phone companies are
obligated to pay one another for completing each other's local
calls. The industry term for this is ``reciprocal compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a Pac Bell customer calls a business that uses
Pac-West Telecomm for local phone service, Pac Bell pays Pac-West
for ``terminating'' the call. Phone companies have to maintain
networks capable of receiving calls from other phone providers, and
the termination fee helps defray that cost.
</P>
<P>
   The same rules apply for calls made to Internet service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, much of the phone traffic is one-sided. Residential
callers, who are predominantly Pac Bell customers, dial their ISPs,
which use competing phone companies because they have lower rates.
Pac Bell, in turn, is forced to pay its startup rivals to complete
the calls.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell argues that even though a computer user dials a local
phone number to hook into an ISP, the call actually is
long-distance because the Internet is a global network and the call
can wind up anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the state Public Utilities Commission
disagreed, ruling that calls to the Internet were local and that
reciprocal compensation should apply. But several weeks later, the
Federal Communications Commission said calls to the Internet were
long-distance. However, the FCC gave states the right to decide
whether companies should pay one another for completing calls.
</P>
<P>
   An administrative law judge with the PUC has recommended that
calls to the Internet still be considered local and that Pac Bell
should pay Pac-West _ or any competing phone company _ for
completing those calls. Pac-West says it is owed $50 million by Pac
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   But PUC Commissioner Josiah Neeper originally proposed
reclassifying Internet calls as long-distance and ending reciprocal
compensation, stirring up longtime fears that higher charges soon
would apply.
</P>
<P>
   ISPs and phone companies have suggested that if reciprocal
compensation is ended, the phone companies would have to raise the
rates they charge ISPs. The ISPs, in turn, would have to charge
consumers more to access the Internet. Some have even floated the
idea of per-minute charges.
</P>
<P>
   During the past week, the PUC has fielded dozens of e-mails,
phone calls and faxes from consumers who were upset or concerned,
said Rob Feraru, the PUC's public adviser. Some state senators also
sent the PUC a letter, asking it to postpone voting until a later
date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are calling in a lather,'' Feraru said. ``Some are
just unclear on the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Neeper changed his proposal, recommending
that the issue be re-examined by the full commission sometime in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   But the new proposal still isn't sitting well with some in the
industry and consumer groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This commission has already decided that these calls are local
calls. This is just an attempt &UR;  &LR; to rewrite the rules,'' said Regina
Costa, telecommunications analyst with The Utility Reform Network.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Griffin, president of Pac-West, said the new Neeper plan
is better than the first one but that it still could lead to the
reclassification of Internet calls as long-distance down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't decide anything, it just delays a decision even
longer,'' Griffin said. His company is supporting the judge's
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Other competing phone companies also support the judge's
proposal and say Neeper's new plan doesn't resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Neeper's ``plan doesn't do what we'd like it to do and it isn't
terrible either, but it largely leaves the issue unresolved,'' said
Eric Artman, MCI WorldCom vice president for industry relations.
``It could have numerous adverse impacts down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell had been pushing to reclassify the calls as
long-distance, but officials say they are content with Neeper's
idea of reopening the issue to debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest in this issue, and it should be
fully developed and discussed,'' said Bill Mashek, a spokesman for
Pac Bell. ``But we believe we will prevail based on the weight of
evidence from the FCC and the simple logic that a call to the World
Wide Web is not local, but goes around the world so it's
interstate.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
