<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GATES-FOUNDATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATESES GIVE RECORD $5 BILLION GIFT TO FOUNDATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In what is considered the largest gift ever by a
living person to a foundation, Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill Gates
and his wife, Melinda French Gates, on Wednesday announced a gift
of $5 billion to the William H. Gates Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's philanthropies now rank third among U.S.
foundations, if the $1.3 billion assets of the Gates Learning
Foundation are added. Only the David and Lucile Packard Foundation
at $12.2 billion and the Lily Endowment at $12 billion are larger,
according to June figures from the Chronicle of Philanthropy, a
newspaper based in Washington. The combined endowment of the Gates
foundations is now $11.3 billion, larger than that of the Ford
Foundation, which has $11.1 billion in assets, said Stacy Palmer,
editor of the Chronicle. By itself, the William H. Gates Foundation
ranks fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just huge, $5 billion in one fell swoop,'' Ms. Palmer
said. ``It sets the sights of various philanthropists that much
higher, that someone is putting that much money into
philanthropy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Palmer recalled how the media magnate Ted Turner, the
founder of CNN, had asked in 1997 if the nation's wealthiest people
were giving enough to charity, when he announced a gift of $100
million a year for 10 years, equaling $1 billion, to establish the
United Nations Foundation. That gift was considered the largest
donation by a living person at the time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Gates donation came from Microsoft stock the couple
sold, a foundation spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The William H. Gates Foundation focuses on child and maternal
health in developing countries, and education and community
assistance in the Pacific Northwest. The Gates Learning Foundation
is designed to address the ``digital divide'' between people who
have access to technology and those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the Gates Foundation has given more than $200
million to health-related causes, including $25 million for the
International AIDS Vaccine Initiative, $50 million to prevent
maternal and child mortality, $20 million for international family
planning efforts, and $100 million toward children's vaccines.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reflection of Bill and Melinda's growing enthusiasm
for what their giving can do in these areas,'' said the foundation
spokesman, Trevor Neilson. ``People's lives around the world can be
improved and in some cases saved by giving them access to services
that in the United States we take for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   The William H. Gates Foundation also announced Wednesday a $50
million grant to the Program for Appropriate Technology in Health,
an international organization based in Seattle, to promote the
development of a new vaccine to prevent malaria, which infects 300
million to 500 million people a year, said Dr. Gordon Perkin, head
of the group. As many as two million people, mostly children, die
of malaria, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' worth is estimated at $75 billion, making him the richest
individual in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
