</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-MEDIABYTES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIABYTES/DAN FOST 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Button-Down Magazines Getting a Little Hot Under the Collar 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
It's spring, and high-tech and business magazines have discovered
the selling powers of sex.
<P>
   In an increasingly crowded and competitive marketplace,
button-down magazines like Fortune, Forbes and Upside are trying to
grab readers by splashing sizzling headlines and sexy pictures on
their covers.
</P>
<P>
   Fortune has led the way, with a provocative May 10 cover,
``Addicted to Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   That cover followed Fortune's April 12 issue, which showed a
close-up of a woman's derriere, wrapped snugly in a pair of jeans
with the headline, ``How Levi's Trashed a Great American Brand.''
That cover ran on the East and West coasts and in Chicago, while a
cover featuring race car driver Jeff Gordon ran in the South and
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   At least Fortune's Levi's cover story was about blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   There's less of an excuse for the skin and leather paraded on
the cover of the June issue of Upside. To illustrate a June cover
story called ``100 Hot Companies,'' this San Francisco technology
mag shows the bare midriff of model Sandra ``Angelica'' Sage
squeezed into a tight pair of black leather pants.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Ms. Sage has nothing to do with Upside's list of top privately
held technology companies. Instead, the list is full of companies
in fields such as communications equipment, enterprise software and
Internet infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Upside chief executive David Bunnell defended the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we convey something that is hot, sexy and alluring?''
he said. ``We chose the best image to convey that.''
</P>
<P>
   He disses as ``bland and boring'' his competitor Red Herring's
June cover of its own top 100 companies. That cover features a
large number 100 against a red background, with squiggly lines
indicating something dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The goal isn't merely to sell the magazine. ``Covers are not
just for newsstands,'' said Bunnell, a veteran publisher. ``Where
our magazines go, people get lots of magazines. You have to grab
their attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ziff-Davis' wholesome monthly Yahoo Internet Life features
the thighs and cleavage of ``Austin Powers'' sidekick Heather
Graham on its June cover.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Wired magazine was whacked by Brill's Content, a
monthly that tracks the media, for going ``from nerdy to naughty''
with January cover lines such as ``Salon's Web Dream,'' ``The Truth
About Vibrators,'' ``William Gibson Reveals His Secret eBay
Obsession'' and ``Phone Sects: What Happened When the Amish Went
Wireless.''
</P>
<P>
   Brill's blamed Wired's new parent, New York magazine giant Conde
Nast. (Of course, the latest issue of Brill's features a caricature
of the New York Times' Maureen Dowd, clutching a lollipop and a
blazing machine gun, with the cover line ``Op-Ed Vixen.'')
</P>
<P>
   Using sex is an age-old technique and one stolen from
advertising. Indeed, New Media _ a monthly trade magazine for
multimedia and Web designers _ has a raging debate in its letters
section over a Macromedia ad featuring what one reader called a
``leather-clad dominatrix.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of dominatrices, check out the photo of CrossWorlds
Software's CEO Katrina Garnett gracing the May 31 cover of Forbes.
Last month, Forbes sent out press releases to hype the story.
</P>
<P>
   You may remember Garnett for her low-cut dress in her ads last
June; apparently, she's had another makeover, as the Forbes cover
shows her with hair slicked back, glossy lips pursed, wearing a
high-collared black vinyl jacket and clutching a red arrow, snapped
in two.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, the journalism behind these photos is all solid,
which is to say: Don't judge a magazine by its cover.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ALMOST HOME &QL; 
The long-delayed sale of Wired Digital appears about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, announced last October, calls for Internet portal
Lycos to buy the San Francisco Web pioneer for $83 million. It's
been tripped up several times: Lycos tried its own merger with USA
Networks, the Securities and Exchange Commission repeatedly sought
clarification in the Lycos-Wired filing papers, and the Wired
Digital shareholders bickered among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Lycos-USA merger was killed, and last week, the SEC
gave the green light to the Lycos-Wired Digital deal. All that's
left is for shareholders to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The big sticking point was an odd provision that gave the
original shareholders _ including Wired founders Louis Rossetto and
Jane Metcalfe _ a lower value than who  &LR; for their stake in the
company. That's been hammered out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's been resolved,'' Metcalfe said this week. ``It
looks like it will close sometime around the end of June.''
</P>
<P>
   FREE SPEECH FUND-RAISER &QL; 
The Electronic Frontier Foundation is going offline to raise money
to support its fight for free-expression rights online. The
Grateful Dead spin-off band Ratdog and The Flying Other Brothers, a
band comprised of Silicon Valley executives, will perform June 18
at the Fillmore Auditorium. Tickets are $35 and are available at
all BASS Tickets outlets; $250 VIP tickets, which get you into a
preshow private party, backstage passes and preferred parking, are
available online at  &LR; www.eff.org/fillmore &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
