<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-PACIFIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   Pacific Exchange Picks New CEO 
 &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a surprise move, the Pacific Exchange named former mutual fund
executive Philip DeFeo as chief executive, succeeding Robert
Greber, who will remain chairman.
<P>
   Until February, DeFeo, 53, was president and chief executive of
Van Eck Associates Group, a New York fund company with $1.5 billion
in assets that specializes in commodities and international stocks.
</P>
<P>
   DeFeo's appointment comes amid wholesale changes among the
exchange's top officers. In the last few months, President Warren
Langley and Chief Financial Officer Kim Williams resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The new CEO arrives at a critical juncture for the Pacific
Exchange, the nation's third-largest stock-options market. Earlier
this year, its pending merger with the Chicago Board Options
Exchange collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the exchange has been scrambling to update its
technology to permit computer-based trading of options. Currently
it uses a traditional trading-floor system, where brokers shout out
orders to buy and sell options.
</P>
<P>
   Floor-based exchanges, such as Pacific, face a growing challenge
from electronic rivals that claim they can match buyers and sellers
of securities more cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, DeFeo said he plans to study all options open
to the exchange. ``Everything will be under review,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, DeFeo said he will re-examine negotiations under
way with New York brokerage Cantor Fitzgerald to start a
computer-based stock options trading system.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed deal, Cantor would provide its proprietary
electronic trading technology and the Pacific Exchange would move a
portion of the 800 options it handles from its Montgomery Street
trading floor to the joint venture.
</P>
<P>
   DeFeo said he didn't know enough about the exchange's stock
trading operations to comment on plans for that business, which has
been losing money and market share in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Greber, 61, a securities industry veteran, joined the Pacific
Exchange in 1990 as chief of marketing and became chairman and CEO
six years later. In an interview, he said he told the exchange's
board after the CBOE merger fell apart in January that he intended
to step down as CEO before year-end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, I put myself first,'' said Greber, who noted
that he doesn't plan to look for another job.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate move, the exchange said its members approved a
plan to reduce its board of governors from 22 to 21 seats and
require that 11 be public representatives. Seven seats currently
are set aside for the public, while others are held by brokers and
exchange officials.
</P>
<P>
   The move follows an appeal to U.S. exchanges by Securities and
Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt to reserve half of board
seats for the public.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
