<HEADLINE>
QUEST TO SAVE MONEY KEPT FLIERS OFF DOOMED PLANE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROL LEWIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Claudia Seay's quest for a cheaper air fare from Little Rock to
Dallas/Fort Worth Airport might have saved her life.
</P>
<P>
   Seay and her boss regularly travel to Dallas on business, taking
a flight in the morning to D/FW and returning at night. They had
planned to travel Tuesday, but at the last minute decided to wait a
day to get cheaper fares.
</P>
<P>
   She heard about the crash late that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boss said we really dodged the bullet on that one,'' said
Seay, an international sales manager with Day Runner of North
Little Rock, Ark. Seay arrived Wednesday morning on the first
flight of the day from Little Rock with co-worker Carla Davenport.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airport was really calm,'' Davenport said. ``Sitting in
the lounge area, you could tell it was on everybody's mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were police around the Little Rock airport, Seay said.
And the flight to Dallas was full, Seay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared to death,'' Seay said shortly after arriving in
Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The two talked about changing their plans but decided they
wouldn't let the crash interrupt their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to keep going,'' Davenport said. ``You can't arrange
your whole lifestyle every time something happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The co-workers planned to return to Little Rock on Wednesday
night, Seay said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
