<SLUG> BC-CRASH-CREW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTAIN WAS 20-YEAR VETERAN WITH OVER 5,000 HOURS OF MD-80
EXPERIENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pilot who died while landing American Airlines Flight 1420
during a thunderstorm in Little Rock, Ark., was a 20-year veteran
of the airline who had flown 5,500 hours on MD-80s, the airline
said.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Richard Warren Buschmann, 48, of Illinois was trying to
land the Super MD-80 when it skidded off the runway, crashed into a
light tower and burst into flames, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Buschmann's first officer, Michael Origel, and four flight
attendants survived.
</P>
<P>
   Origel, 36, based in Chicago, sustained a broken leg. Flight
attendant Nancy Luna of Irving suffered a fractured pelvis and
Jennifer Chapman sustained a compound leg fracture, airline
officials said. Flight attendants Tammy Gardner and Laurie Nelson
were not seriously injured, the airline said. All four are based at
Dallas/Fort Worth Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Their hometowns were not immediately available. Efforts to reach
family members last night were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Origel is a recent arrival to the world of commercial flying,
the airline said. He completed his training in March and joined
American Airlines. He had accumulated 186 flight hours with
American and his first assignment was as the first officer on the
Super MD-80, airline officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In bad weather, the first officer's responsibility would have
been manning the radios to get weather reports from the airport
control tower.
</P>
<P>
   Buschmann lived in Naperville, Ill. An experienced pilot, he had
accumulated 9,600 hours of flying time, including 5,500 on the type
of plane that crashed. He was one of four chief pilots based in
Chicago and his experience qualified him to check other American
pilots on their handling of that aircraft, American spokeswoman
Andrea Rader said.
</P>
<P>
   Buschmann and Origel, who had both been on duty for nearly 14
hours, started their day in Chicago, flew to Salt Lake City and
then on to Dallas-Fort Worth. Thunderstorms in Texas delayed their
departure to Little Rock, where they had expected to spend the
night.
</P>
<P>
   (Star-Telegram staff writers Dan Reed and Rebeca Rodriguez
contributed to this report, which contains material from The
Associated Press. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
