<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0731 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ADOBE-ADOBE_SFCHRON &LR;      06-02 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADOBE-ADOBE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Adobe to Cut 250 Jobs, Beef Up on E-Commerce  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Adobe Systems Inc. yesterday announced it will slash 250 jobs by
the end of the year, the second round of layoffs to hit the San
Jose graphics software maker in the past nine months.
<P>
   Adobe officials said savings from the layoffs, which will cut
about 9 percent of Adobe's workforce, will be used to beef up the
company's Internet commerce services. Adobe, criticized in the past
for being slow to take advantage of the Web, plans to turn its
popular Internet site into a portal for Internet graphics services.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the same breath, Adobe executives said revenues for its
second quarter, which ends tomorrow, should be better than
expected. Adobe expects as much as $246 million in revenues for the
quarter, which would touch the high end of analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business is doing well and we are certainly excited by
that,'' said Bruce Chizen, Adobe executive vice president for
worldwide products.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have an obligation to all of our constituents, our
stockholders, our customers and certainly our employees to grow
this company aggressively,'' he said. ``This is geared toward
making sure we have enough resources to invest in things that will
fuel our long-term growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Adobe dominates the market for graphics and document software
used by publishers with programs like Illustrator, Photoshop and
PageMaker.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe, which has about 2,700 employees worldwide, said 40
percent of the job cuts will come from the closure of its European
corporate headquarters in Edinburgh, Scotland, by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The office has about 100 finance, technology, human resources,
legal and sales employees whose jobs will be consolidated in
Adobe's main headquarters in downtown San Jose. The firm will keep
sales and support offices open in Munich, London, Paris and
Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   Another 125 workers in San Jose will lose their jobs, including
about 90 people who work in Adobe's printing engineering research
and development department.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe revolutionized the publishing industry with printing
software like PostScript, but growth in that part of the business
has been flat for several years, Chizen said.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining job cuts will occur as Adobe centralizes other
operations like sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Last August, Adobe announced a restructuring that eventually
pared 350 positions, or 12 percent, of its workforce. Those
cutbacks included some senior executives as Adobe streamlined its
management.
</P>
<P>
   For the latest round, Adobe will take a onetime $15 million
restructuring charge. Chizen said the company's goal is to save
about $25 million to $30 million in administrative costs annually.
</P>
<P>
   Although plans are still sketchy, Adobe plans to use the savings
to become more aggressive with electronic commerce and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   Chizen said the company is considering ideas like selling a Web
version of its professional graphics software to people who may
only have occasional need for the program. Or Adobe could use the
site to license clip art.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the site could become a broker for other Web design and
digital imaging services, much like financial sites offer mortgage
services.
</P>
<P>
   The twin announcements were made before the market opened
yesterday. Adobe stock closed at $75.06, up $2.56 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Adobe halted trading after the market closed Tuesday to avoid
after-hours trading in anticipation of yesterday's announcements,
but that action fueled speculation by analysts that Adobe was going
to acquire another company or announce poor earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Although the actual news wasn't as dramatic, analysts endorsed
Adobe's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good overall strategy,'' said Hana Nada of U.S. Bancorp
Piper Jaffray, which has a ``buy'' rating on Adobe. ``They've been
getting bloated of late, but now they can focus their energy on the
Web site to try to turn it into a publisher's portal.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fagin of Bear, Stearns said Adobe ``was doing the smart
thing looking at where they can trim some fat.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
