<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETCO-PETCO </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 EEOC Accuses PETCO of Gender Bias  &HT;     By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
The federal Equal Employment Opportunity Commission sued PETCO
Animal Supplies for sex discrimination yesterday, claiming the
giant pet food chain paid female managers in its East Bay stores
substantially less than their male counterparts.
<P>
   EEOC officials said they have so far identified five women who
were paid less than similarly skilled men doing the same job _ in
one case $10,000 a year less.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is very clear that men and woman have to be equally
paid when they have similar qualifications and experience,'' said
EEOC regional attorney William Tamayo. ``This lawsuit serves to ...
address what appears to be a systemic problem within the company.''
</P>
<P>
   PETCO, which is based in San Diego and is the country's No.2 pet
food retailer, denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managers' salaries are based on breadth and scope of
management experience and other business considerations,'' said
Janet Mitchell, senior vice president of human resources. ``The
company has a strong commitment to equal employment opportunity and
does not discriminate against employees on any basis, including
sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The EEOC lawsuit, which was filed in U.S. District Court in San
Francisco, focused on PETCO's treatment of five women managers in
1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Among the charges in the lawsuit:
</P>
<P>
   _PETCO allegedly told its Walnut Creek manager Sherri Savage
that a $22,000 salary was ``the best that we can do,'' even though
her male predecessor had been paid $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   _The company allegedly told Savage it could not pay her more
than $26,500 when she later took over as manager of its Martinez
store, even though her male predecessor had been paid $36,000.
</P>
<P>
   _PETCO allegedly told its Dublin manager Katherine Bloom that
there was ``no money in the budget'' to increase her salary above
$27,300. Seven months later when Bloom transferred to another
store, the firm paid $36,000 to her male replacement, who had no
prior experience at PETCO or any other pet food stores.
</P>
<P>
   EEOC officials said they expected news of the lawsuit to bring
forward similar complaints from other women. The suit sought
compensation including back pay and benefits for the women,
possible reinstatement if they had left the company, and punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the lawsuit was part of a heightened agency
emphasis on combating sex discrimination in workers' pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has said that
Equal Pay Act cases ... should be a priority,'' Tamayo said. ``This
is a big issue for our chairwoman, Ida Castro, who used to be head
of the women's division of the U.S. Department of Labor.''
</P>
<P>
   PETCO operates 482 stores nationally.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
