<HEADER>
A0735 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      06-02 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WIND HELPS BLOW AWAY TWO MORE FAVORITES AT FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The summer sizzle, the museums, and the subway system
were all out of commission and on strike in Paris Wednesday, and so
were the seeded stars who took to the clay for their quarterfinal
assignments at the French Open.
</P>
<P>
   Gustavo Kuerten and Alex Corretja did a disappearing act that
left a bizarre men's semifinal round with by three unseeded gate
crashers and one very veteran master of ceremonies in 13th-seeded
Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Kuerten, who won his first title at Roland Garros in 1997 and
expected to re-assume that post this year, and Corretja, the
sixth-seeded Spaniard, went crashing from contention in straight
sets. Under aggravating conditions on center court, where an
unrelenting wind whipped the clay into sirocco-strength whorls,
Kuerten was reduced to a crestfallen bystander by the brute
strength, and brutal drop shots, of 100th-ranked Andrei Medvedev,
7-5, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Medvedev, whose career went into steep recession
after he reached the semifinals here six years ago, blithely
attributed his resurgence to a head-over-heels reunion with his
on-again, off-again girlfriend, Anke Huber of Germany. Kuerten
linked his own dispassionate performance to the pressure of being
the tournament favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to do all the things just by myself, but I
couldn't do,'' the eighth-seeded Kuerten said. ``I just didn't play
good today; it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Corretja, weakened by a recent bout with mononucleosis and a
mid-event brush with food poisoning, bowed to 54th-ranked Fernando
Meligeni, Kuerten's Brazilian understudy, 6-2, 6-2, 6-0. The match
was remarkable only for the progressive absence of any
counterpunching from Corretja, who allowed the 28-year-old Meligeni
to play the final set virtually uncontested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't move my legs at all, so if you cannot move your
legs in tennis, you better stay home, no?'' said Corretja, normally
a human backboard.
</P>
<P>
   With his balding pate, wrinkled shirt and plaid shorts, Medvedev
looked more like he was ready to to go bowling after mowing his
lawn rather than taking on the tournament darling in the
quarterfinals of the Grand Slam played in the world's most stylish
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are practice shorts,'' said Medvedev, who finds them as
comfortable to play in as they are to practice and sleep in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took all the labels off,'' he added, aware that his
contractual responsibilities lie elsewhere. ``I'm not going to
change now.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Medvedev's casual attire, his game was tailored to the
clay like high fashion. He kept his ground strokes deep, the better
to force Kuerten backward and taunt him with drop shots; he
threaded his down-the-line backhands; his returns were cannons, and
he served with such steady placement that Kuerten waited 1 hour 41
minutes before taking a peek at a break point. After Medvedev broke
him in the first game of the final set, Kuerten could do nothing
but applaud the Ukrainian's brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev rose to fourth in the world back in 1993, the year he
went to the semifinals here, but an array of injuries, including a
wrist he fractured when his 6-foot-4-inch frame landed on it during
a match against Michael Chang at the 1995 Australian Open,
conspired against him. As did his misery whenever he and Huber,
with whom he is unofficially engaged, were on the outs.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev said he had not felt like a serious Grand Slam
contender since 1994, and by last year he was ``maybe half dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't really care that my ranking was dropping faster than
the ball from the high building,'' he said. ``But six weeks ago I
started to think that I'm 105 in the world and perhaps that it is
not a position where I would like to see myself.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Medvedev, who barely qualified for the main draw and
admitted he had not won two matches in a row since last October,
will see himself in the semifinals against Meligeni, whom he has
beaten in both previous meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Medvedev had inspired himself here by toppling Pete Sampras in
the second round. ``Beating Pete, doesn't matter if it's on clay or
mud or water, it doesn't matter,'' he said. ``You beat him in
backgammon, you feel good. Is like a second birth in tennis, in
life. It's fantastic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
