A0736 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MACQA-MACQ&AMP;A_SFCHRON &LR;      06-02 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACQA-MAC </SLUG>
 Q&AMP;A _ SF CHRON  
 MAC Q&AMP;A/HENRY NORR  &HT;     Office 98 Simplifies Mac-PC Exchanges 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; EDITOR'S NOTE: &LR;  This new question-and-answer column for Mac users
will run the first Thursday of each month. David Einstein's
Computing Q&AMP;A will continue to run the other Thursdays.
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Q: I have Microsoft Office 4.2.1 on a Power Mac 7500. I can't open
Microsoft Excel or PowerPoint files that come from Windows
machines; by the same token, Windows users can't open Excel or
PowerPoint files I send. And when I send a Word document to a
Windows user, it typically loses formatting. Is this a function of
my machine or my version of Microsoft Office? If I got a G3, will
all my conversion issues go away ... or should I just give in and
get a Dell?!
</P>
<P>
   A: No need for new hardware, Mac or PC. The problem is just that
your version of Microsoft Office saves files in formats different
from those that Office for Windows uses.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that there's now a solution: Upgrade to Office
98 for the Mac, which saves files in the same formats as the
current Office for Windows, and even the upcoming Office 2000 for
Windows. Once you upgrade, you shouldn't have any problem reading
files PC users send.
</P>
<P>
   In the other direction there's one small complication: When you
e-mail a Mac Office file to a Windows user, she might get two
attachments with your message, one for each of the two ``forks''
into which most Mac files are divided. The smaller one will
probably be unreadable, but just tell your correspondents not to
worry _ the larger attachment should open just fine.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that the upgrade will cost you $250 to $300. It
also requires at least 90 megabytes of free disk space and 16
megabytes of RAM (32 recommended).
</P>
<P>
   One warning: Retail upgrade packages might not include
Microsoft's latest bug fixes, which include solutions for some
serious privacy issues and compatibility problems with Mac OS 8.5
and 8.6. You can find the updates at &LR;  http://www.microsoft.com &LR; 
 &LR; /macoffice/users/issues.htmcomb.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If you don't wish to make another contribution to Bill Gates'
fortune right now _ even on the occasion of the birth of his new
baby, Rory John Gates _ an alternative is DataViz' MacLinkPlus, a
$99 utility that includes translators for many Windows formats,
including Word 97 and Excel 97  &LR; (http://www.dataviz.com/products &LR; 
 &LR; /MLP/MLPHome.html).  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Year 29,941 Problem
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a Mac II that uses Mac OS 7 and wonder whether there
will be any trouble if the clock turns over to 2000. I have
Visa/MasterCard processing software and when I tried it with a card
that has a 2000 expiration date, it worked, but will it still work
next January?
</P>
<P>
   A: One advantage of being a Mac user is that you don't have to
worry about whether your computer and operating system will still
work come next January. (As ``Hitchhiker's Guide'' author and Mac
devotee Douglas Adams put it, ``We may not have got everything
right, but at least we knew the century was going to end.'') The
very first release of the Mac OS, way back in 1984, could handle
dates up 2040, and all recent versions are good up to 29,940 A.D.,
although you'll need to update the Date &AMP; CQ  &LR; Time control panel
before 2019 (see &LR;  http:// &LR;   &LR; www.apple.com/about/ &LR;   &LR; year2000/) &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Applications like your credit-card software, however, are a
different story. Some programmers rely on their own code, instead
of the Mac OS, to handle dates, and in these cases there's no
guarantee they did the right thing. Try contacting the publishers
of the programs you depend on _ most have a page on their Web sites
about ``Y2K compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   But in your case, especially if your software goes back as far
as your hardware (10 or 12 years), that might not work, because
most publishers test only recent versions of their products. If you
can't get a straight story, you'll need to test for yourself. Apple
provides advice about how to do that at the same site mentioned
above.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Staying Connected
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last year I bought a new Mac G3 PowerBook with a 56K internal
modem and switched Internet service providers at the same time (to
Mindspring). The problem is that I get disconnected often when I'm
on the Internet. My ISP blames the phone lines, the phone company
blames the modem and the ISP, and Apple blames everyone but
themselves. How can I find out what the problem is and what can I
do to fix it?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: The first thing I'd do is download and install something
called Apple Modem Updater 1.3.5, which you can find at &LR;  http:/ &LR; 
 &LR; /asu.info.apple.com &LR;   &LR; /swupdates.nsf/artnum/n11315.  &LR; It will
update the modem's firmware (its built-in instructions) and put
some new software into your System Folder.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't work, try some controlled experiments to zero in
on the problem. Take your PowerBook someplace where a friend has a
reliable Internet connection, and try going online from there. If
you don't get disconnected there, your phone line at home is
probably at fault. If you get dropped no matter where you are, grab
one of those promotional CD-ROMs from America Online or some other
Internet provider and sign up for a free trial. If that works where
Mindspring doesn't, time to change ISPs.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Send questions to Henry Norr at mac &LR; sfgate.com. Please specify
what Mac model and what version of the Mac OS you're using.
</P>
</TEXT>
