<SLUG> BC-BEE-CONLEY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY-AREA STUDENT BREEZES INTO SECOND ROUND OF SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBs attribution in 8thgraf, ``I wish _ Mike Conley sted
Chris.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sean Conley, one of 13 children from home schools
competing in the 72nd National Spelling Bee, spelled his way into
Thursday's final rounds of the contest.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year-old, who attends Tri-City Homeschoolers in Newark,
Calif., coolly worked his way through ``nonuble'' in the third
round of competition Wednesday. It is an adjective denoting the
number nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the word right away, but I worked through it
because of the definition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, who was sponsored by the San Francisco Examiner, said he
was never nervous on stage in a contest that opened with 249 top
spellers. ``I've been studying the practice list on and off for
two-and-a-half years ... so I didn't worry.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean's parents, Mike Conley, a software engineer for Apple
Computer Inc., and Bryanne Conley, a teacher at Tri-City, weren't
as composed as their son. ``People always say it's worse for the
parents, and they're right,'' Bryanne Conley said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Sean spelled ``Talmudic,'' referring to the writings
constituting Jewish religious and civil law, and ``lexicon,'' a
rather appropriate word for a spelling contest.
</P>
<P>
   For each word, Sean calmly asked for the definition and for any
alternate pronunciations. Then, with a concentrated gaze, he
spelled each without haste or hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish my mind worked as well as his,'' Mike Conley said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, who by the age of 2 already had begun to read and to spell
words such as ``Albuquerque'' using refrigerator magnets, and the
103 remaining contestants will go through progressively tougher
rounds to determine the winner. There were 249 students who made it
to the first round of the bee.
</P>
<P>
   An avid reader, Sean loves to compete, participating in math
contests and chess tournaments as well as spelling bees. He also
enjoys learning the martial art of karate and playing the piano.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the National Spelling Bee, sponsored by the E.W.
Scripps Co., will receive $10,000 in cash and other prizes.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
