u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANE-CRASH-1STLD-WRI     06-02 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-CRASH-1STLD-WRITETHRU-780&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE KILLED AS JET CRASHES IN STORM IN LITTLE ROCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Subs 5th graph to add wind speed; subs penultimate graph to
clarify two aboard are unaccounted for.) (rm) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ An American Airlines jet carrying 145 people
touched down in a furious thunderstorm late Tuesday, slid off the
runway and was sliced open as it hit a lighting tower. Nine people,
including the captain, were killed in the fiery crash, and more
than 80 people were injured, some with severe burns.
</P>
<P>
   Terrified passengers on what had been an uneventful, though
delayed, flight from Dallas scrambled out of the hole in the
burning fuselage and huddled in a low-lying field a few feet from
the Arkansas River while being pelted by dime-size hail. Others
squeezed through an emergency exit, and some jumped from a wing
that was ablaze with burning jet fuel. Several of the victims were
apparently seated near the wings of the twin-engine McDonnell
Douglas Super 80, where a fast-growing fire prompted the panicked
exits.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we came to a stop I looked over my shoulder and saw a
fireball coming down the aisle,'' said Phyllis V. Caruth, a
statistics teacher at Little Rock Central High School. ``I thought,
`Forget the purse, woman, get out of the plane.'''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said it was too soon to blame the weather
as a primary culprit, but made it clear that the landing conditions
were severe.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Black, a member of the National Transportation Safety
Board, said winds had picked up from 10 miles per hour a few
minutes before the crash to 30 m.p.h. near the moment of impact,
which occurred at 11:51 P.M. A few minutes after the crash, radar
equipment picked up enormous gusts of up to 88 m.p.h., Black said.
</P>
<P>
   George R. Wilkins, operations officer at the National Weather
Service station in North Little Rock, said a line of thunderstorms
was approaching the airport from the northwest at the time the
plane was landing from the south. He said the peak gust at the
moment of landing may have been as high as 40 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The airport had equipment to detect windshears, but
investigators said they did not yet know whether the gusts
registered on the equipment or whether the crew had been informed
of the severe weather.
</P>
<P>
   Robert W. Baker, American's executive vice president for
operations, said the crew had been informed by the Dallas
dispatcher that there was bad weather in the Little Rock area, but
said it was not known whether the Little Rock tower advised the
crew of its severity. Officials of the National Transportation
Safety Board said the plane's voice and data recorders were
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of the crash, the airport lost electrical power,
Black said, although he did not know if that was caused by the
collision with the light tower or by the weather.
</P>
<P>
   The two-man crew of Flight 1420 had been on duty for 13.5 hours,
a half-hour short of the American Airlines limit for flying duty.
They had begun their day in Chicago, making stops at Salt Lake City
and Dallas, where the flight was delayed two hours because of bad
weather, before departing for Little Rock. American Airlines denied
that the crew was fatigued, but other pilots said the long day may
have pushed the crew to the limit.
</P>
<P>
   The flight captain, Richard Buschmann, who died in the crash,
had flown for American Airlines for 20 years and was the company's
chief pilot in Chicago. The co-pilot, Michael Origel, had just
finished his training in March; he suffered a broken leg in the
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1420, scheduled to leave Dallas at 8:30 p.m., had been
delayed for more than two hours because the scheduled plane had not
arrived due to bad weather in north Texas, several passengers said.
Around 10:30 p.m., American brought over an MD-80 which had been
stationed in a hangar, and the flight left around 10:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Goss, a Georgetown University senior who was returning
home to Little Rock, said there was no turbulence or noticeable bad
weather until about 15 minutes before landing, when she saw
thunderclouds and lightning not far away. The descent seemed
ordinary until touchdown, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like he was trying to brake, but couldn't,'' Ms. Goss
said. ``Then all of a sudden, I said, `Oh my God, we're on the
grass,' and we had veered off the runway to the left. We were going
way too fast. Then there was this boom, and then a really loud
boom, and all the lights went out.''
</P>
<P>
   Black, the Transportation Board investigator, confirmed that the
plane had left the runway to the left, heading down an embankment
to the river, until it hit the lighting tower and several other
pieces of heavy airport equipment. The crash stopped the plane from
dropping into the water, he said, but in doing so it ripped the
plane's skin apart and caused the fire.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In terror, passengers in the back rows managed to escape through
the rear hatch, while those in the front got out through the
torn-open fuselage. The fire was in the middle of the plane, and it
spread swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see there was flame from the middle of the plane to
the back and it was getting worse,'' said Richard M. Klamm, a
chemical salesman from Pine Bluff, Ark. ``You look at it and then
you wonder how anyone came out of it. It was like a dream: you
think you'll roll over and it'll be a dream. It wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goss said there was no warning from the crew that a crash
was imminent, and said she saw no flight attendants helping people
out of the plane. Firefighters had to use chisels to pull some
passengers through openings in the plane's side.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Goss' father, Patrick J. Goss, is a partner at Wright,
Lindsey &AMP; Jennings, which is President Bill Clinton's old law firm.
Mayor Jim Dailey of Little Rock said the president had several
friends on the plane, all of whom survived.
</P>
<P>
   Area hospitals treated 83 people for injuries, mainly abrasions,
cuts and burns, while 51 people escaped without injuries. The
authorities said two people were unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The nine fatalities confirmed by the county coroner were the
first in the 82-year history of Little Rock's airport, and the
first on an American commercial plane since December 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
