<SLUG> BC-CKE-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES OF CKE DECLINE ON BAD NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares in CKE Restaurants Inc. fell sharply
Wednesday as the parent of the Carl's Jr. and Hardee's food chains
said it would widely miss analysts' first quarter earnings
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-food restaurant operator lost $4.3125, or 23.88
percent, to close at $13.75 after the company issued a statement
Wednesday morning stating it would earn closer to 35 cents per
share than the 45-cent consensus estimate of analysts surveyed by
First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the drubbing was justified. ``They missed
estimates by 22 percent, so the stock's down in line with that,''
said Doug Christopher at Los Angeles-based Crowell Weedon &AMP; Co.
``When you disappoint in this market you're going to get hit
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim, Calif.-based CKE said same store sales at its Carl's
Jr. and Hardee's restaurants would be down 4.7 percent and 4.8
percent, respectively, for the quarter ended May 17, accounting for
the bulk of the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to be hitting a plateau for a while,'' William Foley,
CKE's chief executive said in a statement. Foley also said
conversion of some Hardee's restaurants into Carl's Jr. outlets
hurt sales.
</P>
<P>
   Following the announcement, SunTrust Equitable Securities
analyst Robert Derrington downgraded the company to ``long-term
attractive'' from ``buy.''
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, CKE said its Taco Bueno restaurants will show
a 10.7 percent increase in same-store sales and $27 million in
total sales for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   CKE operates 874 Carl's Jr. restaurants in the western United
States and Mexico, 2,785 Hardee's restaurants throughout the
country and abroad, and 111 Taco Bueno restaurants in Texas and
Oklahoma. CKE expects to report earnings June 14.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
