<SLUG> BC-BEARS-RELEASE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST GROUP OF REHABILITATED BEARS WILL BE RELEASED INTO WILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Five black bears, scrubbed and nourished after a
winter in a Lynnwood, Wash., rehabilitation facility, will be sent
out into the world to fend for themselves on Thursday in Eastern
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   They're the last five to be released of 16 that were taken in by
the PAWS Wildlife Center between March and December last year.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen bears is well over the usual two or three the center
gets each year, said Deb Dyson, PAWS rehabilitation manager.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife experts told PAWS the reason for so many distressed
bears last year was likely the poor berry crop in Eastern
Washington caused by drought.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson also said that housing and business developments are
encroaching on traditional bear habitat, creating problems for
bears that use those areas.
</P>
<P>
   The five bears all came from the same area in Wenatchee, Wash.,
Dyson said. A couple of the cubs were orphaned when their mother
was shot as a nuisance bear, she said. Several of the other cubs
were found thin and with coats in poor condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what happened to the mother. They wouldn't have
survived the winter if we hadn't rehabilitated them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those bears had to be sedated so they could be bathed to get rid
of mange and they were also given medicine to fight ringworm. They
were nourished back to health with fruits, mostly vegetables and
some dry dog food.
</P>
<P>
   Keepers were careful to avoid habituating the bears to humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't go in with the bears,'' Dyson said. ``They don't see
us giving them food. We try not to stand there and stare at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, photographers are allowed to shoot pictures, but
otherwise there is normally no visual contact, Dyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Bears that become too used to being around humans or, especially
bears that associate food with humans, are considered more likely
to become dangerous bears.
</P>
<P>
   Things got crowded at times at the PAWS center this winter,
Dyson said, with close to 14 bears there at one time.
</P>
<P>
   One of the 16 bears that came in during the year died under
anaesthesia and another had to be killed because its leg was too
mangled to be repaired after it was hit by a car.
</P>
<P>
   One, which came from California early last year, was released
last summer. Two bears were released into the North Cascades two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Six were released during the winter. The center first induced
hibernation by cutting back on their food, laying out straw for
denning material, and creating dark, quiet conditions. The bears
were then sedated and moved to suitable denning locations that had
been found by the state Department of Fish and Wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   The five bears to be released on Thursday will travel across the
mountains towards Wenatchee in a convoy to Pateros. Three will go
to one area, and two will go to another area.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the bears released during the winter wear radio collars
and are being tracked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all seem to be doing fine,'' Dyson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
