<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-SETTLEMENT-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS REACH ACCORD WITH HAULERS OF NEW CARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also AUTOMAKERS-EXPANSION, AUTO-SALES) 
(mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Averting a strike that would have disrupted the Big Three
automakers, the Teamsters' union and trucking companies that haul
new cars to dealers reached a tentative contract agreement
Wednesday in negotiations that were the first big test for James P.
Hoffa, the union's new president.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa trumpeted the four-year contract as a major triumph for
12,800 car-haul workers, increasing their pay and pensions and
providing health insurance to those who retire before the age of
65. In addition, the agreement for the first time provides coverage
of prescription drugs, supplementing Medicare, for retirees 65 and
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contract serves notice the Teamsters are back,'' Hoffa
said in a news conference Wednesday morning at a hotel in
Arlington, Va., where at 1 a.m. the two sides had reached
agreement. ``This contract sets a new standard for working people
across the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa's backers hope that the accord, struck 25 hours after the
expiration of the old contract, is only one of many that will yield
impressive wage and benefit gains like those his father, James
Hoffa, achieved when he headed the International Brotherhood of
Teamsters four decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the new contract provided enough of a nod to management,
inc,uding the lack of a raise in the first year, that the
president's critics within the union were able to argue that it was
in no way a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Like a politician trying to put the best gloss on developments,
Hoffa boasted that the union had persuaded the car haulers to
surrender on two of their major demands: a lower starting pay for
new car-haul workers and increased use of part-timers.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the negotiations, industry officials had argued that
they needed to reduce labor costs and gain more flexibility to keep
railroads and nonunion companies from increasing their share of the
car-haul market. But Ian Hunter, the chief negotiator for National
Automobile Transporters Labor Division, which represents 17
car-hauling companies, acknowledged that he had made numerous
concessions to prevent a walkout. ``We were very eager to avoid a
strike,'' Hunter said. ``And we have succeeded in one of our
acknowledged obligations, to improve the financial status of our
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Several industry analysts said a number of factors had given
Hoffa the upper hand at the bargaining table. With Detroit churning
out cars at record levels, even a short strike could have greatly
disrupted dealer sales, especially those of hot-selling cars.
Further, the nation's low unemployment rate would have made it
harder for car-hauling companies to find replacements for striking
workers. And the Wall Street boom has made it easier for the
industry and itr benefits fund to afford more generous pensions and
healdh coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously has won some important things in this
agreement,'' Harley Shaiken, a professor of industrial relations at
the University of California at Berkeley, said of Hoffa. ``He went
into it with important leverage. The automakers didn't want a
strike, and they leaned on their transporters.''
</P>
<P>
   The current average pay of the car-haul employees _ drivers and
the garage workers who maintain the trucks _ is about $20 an hour.
Under the agreement, which faces a ratification vote over the next
few weeks, they are to receive a $1,500 lump-sum payment, rather
than a raise, in the first year and then 50-cent-an-hour wage
increases in years 2, 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   Further, those with 25 years' experience will be able to retire
at 55 with a $2,500 monthly pension; under the old contract, they
could not receive a $2,500 pension until 57.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, the industry's chief negotiator, said the contract would
increase labor costs 3 percent to 4 percent each year.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Terry Hewer, who as a business agent with Local 299 in Detroit
represents 850 car-haul workers, said: ``From what we've seen, it's
an excellent contract. The negotiating committee did a good job
meeting one of our biggest concerns, which was better pension
benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa declared that he had forced the industry to drop plans to
use Mexican truckers to transport new cars to the United States
from Mexican factories. But Hunter maintained that management had
not put forward such a proposal. ``We never asked to use Mexican
drivers,'' he said, ``not once.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Paff, a longtime Hoffa critic who is national coordinator of
Teamsters for a Democratic Union, said the contract provided for
too many concessions. In particular, he cited a provision
eliminating much of the overtime pay that car-haul workers now
receive by working on weekends: In the Midwest and the South, the
new agreement will allow companies to hire new mechanics and pay
them straight time when they work on weekends, rather than time and
a half or double time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoffa's brought back concessions to the Teamsters,'' Paff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Big Three welcomed the agreement. A strike of much
duration at all could have cost the automakers hundreds of millions
of dollars in lost sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy about it,'' said James Holden,
DaimlerChrysler's executive vice president for sales and marketing.
``You'd hate to have anything like a transportation interruption
interrupt this market.''
</P>
<P>
   David Healy, an automobile analyst with Burnham Securities,
said, ``Generally car plants don't have enough space to store more
than a couple days' output, so a strike would have clearly involved
some plant shutdowns and some layoffs and would have whacked
profits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
