<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TODD-SALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODD-AO HIRES CONSULTANTS FOR POTENTIAL SALE OR MERGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Post-production specialist Todd-AO Corp.,
generating little enthusiasm on Wall Street in the past year, has
hired investment bankers to explore putting the company up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement, made Wednesday, had little effect on shares of
the Los Angeles-based company, which edged up 12.5 cents to
$8.6975, leaving the issue down 33 percent since it touched $13 a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the current market valuation does not reflect
Todd-AO's unique position and growing global reach in providing the
most technologically advanced post-production techniques to the
industry,'' says a printed statement from Salah Hassanein,
president and chief executive officer of the company created in
1952 from a partnership between late film producer Michael Todd and
American Optical.
</P>
<P>
   Hassanein said Todd-AO has retained Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. to
advise the company on options including a sale, merger or joint
venture. Company officials noted there has been no decision on a
specific option and said there is no assurance a transaction will
result.
</P>
<P>
   Todd-AO, which has won 19 Academy Awards including this year's
sound-mixing award for ``Saving Private Ryan,'' has been
aggressively buying smaller rivals to become a one-stop provider of
sound and video-editing services for Hollywood producers.
Burbank-based Four Media Co. has employed a similar strategy in
recent years, and its stock has also remained depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say many of Hollywood's service providers have been
hurt in the past year by intense competition and by major studios'
decisions to keep closer watch on spending and to give the green
light to fewer big-budget projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Post-production is a tough business to make Wall Street
notice,'' said entertainment industry analyst Arthur Rockwell.
``The street's not patient, and there are a lot of costs in
upgrading equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd-AO, which has facilities scattered throughout Los Angeles,
previously reported a 9 percent gain in profits to $3.4 million, or
35 cents a share, in the six months that ended Feb. 28, with
revenues up 31 percent to $62.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
