<HEADLINE>
D/FW AIRPORT CENSORS TV COVERAGE OF CRASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON DICKSON and CAROL LEWIS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS/FORT WORTH AIRPORT _ Overhead televisions usually
dominate the passenger waiting areas at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport
with nonstop news and e entertainment, but their screens were blank
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   There were no TV reports of the deadly crash of American
Airlines Flight 1420 in Little Rock, Ark., hours after it had taken
off from D/FW.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, many passengers who had been traveling all
morning were unaware of the crash. Several heard the news from
passers-by after inquiring about the large number of reporters in
the terminals.
</P>
<P>
   In Terminal A, grief counselors turned their backs on media
cameras and quietly boarded a flight to Little Rock, where they
were to console and comfort survivors and victims' relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Chaplains were on duty in the three chapels at D/FW to talk to
anyone who wanted to talk.
</P>
<P>
   But keeping some of the harsher realities out of the terminals
by limiting TV coverage is routine after an accident, airport
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Weller, a D/FW spokesman, said airport policy allows an
airport manager or an airlines official to cut off the TV monitors
if they believe the content will upset travelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to show people that when they are getting onto
a plane,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When the televisions came on about 10:30 a.m., the programs were
mostly feature stories on fashion and business. The programming is
provided by CNN Airport Network, which features coverage that is
different from CNN's main newscast.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wanted to get the news could find televisions in
restaurants and bars tuned to the networks.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Batiste, 28, a Little Rock attorney who flew to D/FW
Wednesday morning, noticed there was no news coverage of the crash
on the airport TVs and no talk of it among airline and airport
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell they were a lot more attentive to us today,''
she said. ``But when you walked into the airport, it was like
nothing had happened. Nobody was talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman who lives in Mountain Home, Ark., began trembling and
seemed to fight back tears when told of the accident as she boarded
a 12:42 p.m. flight to Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I am nervous. I am terrified,'' said the woman, who
identified herself as A. Davis. ``I don't usually fly.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew of the crash had questions.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Allman of Dallas, returning Wednesday from Little Rock
after his daughter's graduation, said many passengers on his flight
wanted to know why Flight 1420 tried to land in bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have got a lot of questions,'' he said. ``It was a pretty
bad storm last night. It started raining pretty tough about 11
o'clock last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock residents Del Medlin and his wife were relieved to
be on the ground after they arrived to visit their son at Baylor
University in Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's original flight out of Arkansas Wednesday morning
was canceled, and they speculated that the aircraft for that flight
was the one that crashed Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we took off, I could see the wreckage. It was almost in the
Arkansas River at the end of the runway. There were big sections of
it,'' Medlin said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
