<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING'S DEPARTURE LEAVES BOTH TEAMS UNCERTAIN AS TO ITS EFFECT ON
THE SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In 1994, his Game 7 tip-in against Indiana sent
the New York Knicks to the finals. A year later, his finger roll
off the back iron allowed the Pacers to advance.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing's presence in the Eastern Conference's enduring
rivalry has been almost as luminous as Reggie Miller's the past
seven years.
</P>
<P>
   That fact was not lost on the Pacers Wednesday after they
learned that Ewing would miss the remainder of the playoffs because
of a partial tear in his left Achilles' tendon, suffered in Game 2
here on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see he was hurting,'' said Mark Jackson, the Pacer
point guard and Ewing's former teammate. ``I'm proud of him. He's a
warrior. A lot of guys wouldn't have even suited up.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson added: ``This is still going to be a difficult series.
The proof is there that the Knicks are a team that can deal with
adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with Coach Larry Bird, Jackson and Miller were among
several Pacers who implied after Game 1 that Ewing was not as
injured as he or the Knicks claimed. The comments came after Ewing
played 40 minutes and scored 6 points down the stretch of a victory
at Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Miller went so far as to end his post-game news conference on
Tuesday night by getting a dig in at Ewing for missing the game's
last shot.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the game often comes down to such situations, Miller
looked over at Ewing waiting in the wings and said, ``Isn't that
right, Pat?''
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, Miller and the Pacers were subdued by the news of
Ewing missing the rest of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing often dominated his counterpart at center, Rik Smits, in
the early 1990s before Smits began maturing and developing as a
pivot player. Yet over the past two seasons, Smits began exploiting
Ewing's defensive liabilities when the Knick center returned from
wrist surgery last season and limped noticeably this season.
</P>
<P>
   While Miller's heroics are most remembered in the playoff series
between the two teams, Ewing hit his share of crucial shots against
Indiana in the post-season _ including a putback in the 1994
conference finals that vaulted the Knicks into the league finals.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, he made four consecutive free throws in the final
30.6 seconds to help insure the upset and give the Knicks
home-court advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame because Patrick is such a great competitor and
has been a huge part of this great rivalry and the great games the
two teams have played,'' Miller said. ``The Knicks are still going
to be dangerous. It doesn't make our job any easier. It probably
makes it tougher because they will step it up even more.''
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Walsh, the Pacers' team president, said he noticed a
marked difference in Ewing between Games 1 and 2. ``He played 40
minutes in Game 1, and I saw him in the second game and was
surprised to see him limping,'' Walsh said. ``Maybe that took more
out of him than most people thought. I'm sorry to hear that. I
really do respect him as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said he expected the Knicks to alter slightly their
offensive philosophy and try to force an up-tempo game when the
conference finals resume Saturday night in Game 3 at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Patrick is the go-to guy and all that,'' Walsh
said. ``But the rest of their team, we don't expect things to
change that much. We still think they're going to be a very
formidable team. For the most part, the other guys were the ones
playing huge roles along with Patrick.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh added: ``They'll get more defensive oriented, look for
transition baskets and look for mismatches on the floor and exploit
them. In some ways, because we're a big team, they could put a
bigger team out there with Patrick. Now they'll try to create more
mismatches.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
