<DOCNO> NYT19990602.0467 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     06-02 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR EWING, MUCH AGONY, NO ECSTASY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Patrick Ewing missed another critical shot Tuesday
night, but this time you felt there would be redemption. The
Knicks' younger, faster legs seemed to have the Eastern Conference
finals in control: they stole the opener in Indiana and Games 3 and
4 were at home. You knew the Big Fella would have one more chance.
But there will be no redemption. Not this season. Dr. Norman Scott,
the team physician, says the partial tear of Ewing's left Achilles'
tendon will mend without surgery; Coach Jeff Van Gundy, who rode
his warrior center hard, like a workhorse, referred to Ewing's
being in uniform for ``a few'' more seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is clear now; not the series, Ewing's future, the
organization's future. The Knicks' foundation has unexpectedly
changed.
</P>
<P>
   The lingering image from the Knicks' 88-86 loss in Game 2 came
when Ewing walked off the Market Square Arena court seconds after
his 14-foot jumper bounced long off the back of the rim. Ewing's
face tightened, and suddenly he let out a bellowing ``Aaaagggghhh''
that momentarily stunned Pacers fans in the midst of their
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   That roar encapsulated not simply one night of frustration but
many seasons of bitter disappointments. Now the season-ending
frustration had greeted him once again. This time it seemed a bit
too much to bear. That was the final shot at a championship this
season, perhaps ever.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has watched Ewing evolve from the bashful teen-ager
to the ferocious college player to the rugged pro knows that there
is so much agony and irony to his 14-year career. Even this latest
injury has a sorrowful symmetry: when he returned from a fractured
wrist last season, Indiana was the post-season opponent and the
Pacers won the series.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is leaving the post-season with a partly torn tendon,
Indiana is the opponent. Last year, Ewing was lauded for his
courage but criticized for upsetting the chemistry of the team.
This year, critics say he was the wagon wheel on the Knicks'
Ferrari. Critics agree that he is a presence that opponents must
contend with, but can't always agree whether that presence is
imposing or suffocating.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, without a championship Ewing's legacy is
unclear. Perhaps this accounts for the sense of urgency that
repeatedly has led Ewing to push his body seemingly beyond its
limits. John Thompson, Ewing's coach at Georgetown, watched Game 2
and spoke to Ewing Wednesday morning. For several months he had
tried to tell his former player to take it easy, that his pursuit
of a championship was becoming obsessive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a thin line between desire and bad judgment,''
Thompson said ``Patrick crossed that line a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Patrick and I respectfully disagree with the fact
that he made himself get out there and play,'' Thompson said. ``But
I know why, I know what he wants and I know how he is.'' Thompson
said he never told Ewing not to play. ``I told him that it was
bordering on being dangerous, and every time the final buzzer would
go off, I'd breathe a sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the Knicks are better off without Ewing, better when
he's not in the game. Now we'll see. Ewing's season-ending injury
completely takes the training wheels off the new Knicks and all but
forces Van Gundy to rely consistently on a running game.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's loss may be a bigger nightmare for Indiana than the
Pacers realize, for it means that Marcus Camby will get more
minutes; the last person Indiana wants to see get more minutes is
Camby. The Pacers simply have no answer for the Knicks in
transition. If there could be a game with 1,000 fouls, Indiana
would take it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, you can say this about Ewing: in an era of so much
fans anger directed at millionaires who play games for a living,
and don't always put forth the effort, not a season, not a game has
gone by in Patrick Ewing's career _ college and professional _ that
he has not put forth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   In a way this led to a breakdown of his body: he could not say
no. These are his Hall of Fame qualities: the ability to endure
pain, play with pain, play through pain. He inspired the team, even
as his presence sometimes helped hurt the team. Ewing wanted so
desperately to be part of a championship season. Now he'll watch
with an odd sense of ambivalence. If they lose, he can look back at
that missed 14-footer as the signature of his season. If they win?
If they win, in some ways that might be even more excruciating for
a player who prided himself on carrying the team on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he can only hope that his missed shot on Tuesday night
in Market Square Arena wasn't his final shot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
