<SLUG> BC-NYS-ANTISMOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANY CHIEFS WANT TO SPEND MORE TO FIGHT TOBACCO USE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The leaders of both houses of the Legislature
have called for a major increase in state spending on anti-tobacco
advertising and education, and Gov. George said Wednesday that he
would not be averse to such an increase.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver proposed a $90 million a year
program, compared with the $6.5 million that the state now spends.
He said the effort should be financed in part by a state-mandated
price increase on tobacco products, to be included in the
long-delayed budget for the fiscal year that began April 1.
</P>
<P>
   That way, the state would not have to wait until the
disbursement of its $25 billion share of the $206 billion national
settlement with the tobacco industry begins, which could be a year
away.
</P>
<P>
   New York's anti-tobacco campaigns, which total $8.2 million a
year when federal grants are included, are far smaller, when
adjusted for population, than those of the eight other states that
have such programs. The biggest spenders are California, at $120.1
million a year, and Florida, at $70.4 million. Eleven other states
expect to begin anti-tobacco efforts in the next year; at least 10
of them plan to spend much more per capita than New York.
</P>
<P>
   In his proposed budget, Pataki called for financing the program
at the $6.5 million level over the next year. Several studies have
shown that advertising, in particular, can be effective in cutting
smoking rates, but anti-smoking advocates contend that New York
spends too little to make a dent.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Pataki's response to such criticism was, ``If you
look at anything, the state could be spending more.'' He then
changed the subject.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the governor, a Republican, said he would not
oppose a major increase in anti-smoking efforts as long as it was
in the context of a sound budget.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Democrats who control the Assembly nor the
Republicans who control the Senate included an increase for
anti-tobacco spending in the budget proposals they passed earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Silver has been preparing a $90-million-a-year anti-tobacco
package for several weeks, and in an interview Tuesday he disclosed
its basic elements, saying they would become part of the Assembly's
position in budget negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Silver proposed a increase of five cents per pack in the
state-mandated minimum price for cigarettes _ effectively a tax
increase under a different name _ with two cents a pack going to
anti-tobacco programs like advertising and education.
</P>
<P>
   The programs would also get 10 percent of the state's share of
the national tobacco lawsuit settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno said he, too, wanted to see
some portion of the settlement money used for ``anything having to
do with education on the pitfalls of smoking.'' He said it should
be much more than the state now spends.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno was wary, however, about the prospect of including an
increase in anti-tobacco spending in the next budget before the
settlement money is in hand.
</P>
</TEXT>
