<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-STARTREK-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `STAR TREK' SERIES GOES GENTLY INTO DEEP SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``Star Trek: Deep Space Nine'' series finale bristles with
bang-up battle scenes and then takes its fans through a gentle rite
of separation.
</P>
<P>
   Seven seasons, nearly 200 episodes, and after this week it was
all one fine toss in a holosuite.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that's so bad _ beats the Bajor out of earthbound
drudgery. As the Ferengi barkeep Quark says, Earth is ``nothing
more than a rotating ball of boredom.''
</P>
<P>
   The concluding episode is called ``What You Leave Behind.'' It
begins where all creatures, earthling and alien, take pleasure: the
sack. Ezri Dax (Nicole DeBoer) and Julian Bashir (Alexander Siddig)
are cuddling and promising each other that they'll survive the
impending battle.
</P>
<P>
   If you dropped out a while back, the Federation Alliance is
tussling with the Dominion from off in the Gamma Quadrant. It's bad
enough that the Jem'Hadar are fighting our heroes, but they're
joined on the Dominion side by the dreaded Breen and the
Cardassians.
</P>
<P>
   Put it this way: There's trouble in River City. Also, the
notorious Gul Dukat (Marc Alaimo) is making mischief. Maybe he'll
be joined by his loathsome brother Cul de Sac. Kidding about the
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the audio and visual effects were missing from the
review tape sent to critics, but clearly this is an episode that
fills the screen with lots of pop _ battling starships firing
salvos, spinning out of control, burning and exploding
spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   Can ships burn in space, without oxygen? Just wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Prisoners are taken. Executions are ordered. Backs are stabbed.
A few characters bite the dust or traipse into that big wormhole in
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the series finale seems to lurch to its conclusion
in fits and starts. It seems to end, and then exhales a few more
story threads. It's as if ``DS9'' doesn't really want to find the
exit.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of those endings involve Capt. Benjamin Sisko (Avery
Brooks), who must have a confrontation with his nemesis Gul Dukat.
</P>
<P>
   ``DS9'' also brakes for a final tribute to its principal
characters _ brief clips from previous episodes _ as they prepare
to disperse to destinations across the galaxy.
</P>
<P>
   The parting emphasis is on comradeship and the wonder of space,
with affection but a blessed minimum of sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   And what a lot of characters there are. Thirty years ago, the
original ``Star Trek'' made do with three characters _ Kirk, Spock,
McCoy _ at the center of the show. ``Star Trek: The Next
Generation'' tripled that, and ``DS9'' added still more characters
and deliberately accentuated their complex ties to one another on
the space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``DS9'' became so complicated that, truth be told, it barely
resembled its two predecessors, even though sometimes, in tribute,
it recycled story fragments from ``Star Trek'' and ``Star Trek:
TNG.''
</P>
<P>
   There are adversaries in any ``Star Trek'' _ Q, the Borg, Gul
Dukat, the shape-shifting Changelings of the Dominion. But ``DS9''
seemed to hit its highest notes with story lines among crewmates,
not with invading monsters.
</P>
<P>
   That ``DS9'' leaves its crew so widely scattered at its
conclusion might say something about a lack of future plans.
</P>
<P>
   Paramount says it isn't mapping a ``DS9'' theatrical movie,
which would involve reassembling the crew. (After last year's
``Insurrection'' disappointment, ``Star Trek'' is taking a rest
from the movies, period.)
</P>
<P>
   Nor are there plans, Paramount says, for a new TV series anytime
soon. The fourth ``Star Trek'' prime-time franchise, UPN's ``Star
Trek: Voyager,'' will have next season to itself in the Delta
Quadrant.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, though, you've got to believe that there will be
another TV startup. How about a series based at Starfleet Academy?
One of the ``DS9'' regulars, viewers learn this week, happens to be
headed in that direction.
</P>
<P>
   In a night of series resolution, the character left most in
limbo is none other than the station commander, Sisko.
</P>
<P>
   The way I had it figured, he would resign his commission, find
his bliss as a movie critic, team up with another critic and,
voila, ``Sisko &AMP; Ebert.''
</P>
<P>
   It would truly be a match made in the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
