<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: THE CODE OF SILENCE AS A CO-CONSPIRATOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (with NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Narrowly speaking, Alan Vinegrad's job Wednesday was
simply to convince a jury of the guilt of four New York police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   But as Vinegrad, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, crisply
proceeded through his summation, and as he recounted the intricate
sequence of events that culminated with an officer's jamming a
stick into Abner Louima's rectum, he also poured steaming buckets
of condemnation on a far larger target: the New York Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   He told jurors of a sergeant _ not one of the defendants _ who
turned away from the sight of the filthy stick because he wanted to
``see no evil, hear no evil.'' He told them of one of the
defendants' mentors, a captain _ also not a defendant _ who
literally counted the days until he was reassigned out of the
despised Internal Affairs Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   He told of officer after officer _ none of them defendants _ who
did not raise one word of protest as Louima was marched through the
lobby of the 70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn, his pants
down around his ankles.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the four defendants. They are not as well
known as Justin Volpe, the former police officer who confessed last
week to tearing a hole in Louima's rectum and bladder. But as
Vinegrad argued the evidence Wednesday, he repeatedly sought to
connect their actions with the department's much-examined culture
of silence.
</P>
<P>
   It is a culture, he said, where officers felt free to inflict
``street justice'' against anyone who dared to raise a hand against
them. It is a culture, he said, where officers felt free to write
false arrest reports to cover up acts of brutality on innocent men.
It is a world, he said, where officers felt free to plot and lie
and evade when confronted by questions from Internal Affairs, or
even the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Vinegrad described a culture in which those who were
sworn to uphold the rule of law instead casually subverted it in
ways large and small.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trial is about justice,'' he said in his summation. ``It
is about holding these defendants responsible for breaking the rule
of law and for taking the law into their own hands in a violent and
brutal way.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the streets of Brooklyn. This is not the back of a
patrol car. This is not a station house bathroom. This is a court
of law. In this courtroom, the rule of law must prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have only begun their summations, but they, too,
had harsh criticism for the Police Department. They described their
clients as scapegoats for politically cowed police commanders.
</P>
<P>
   In their view of the evidence, the Police Department is a place
where officers rat out innocent comrades for the sake of a
promotion. It is a place, they said, where internal affairs
investigators lay treacherous traps during interrogations, hoping
to trick their brethren into saying something incriminating.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad dwelt at length on how police treated Patrick Antoine,
another Haitian immigrant who was arrested that night. At the time,
Antoine, 36, was walking home from a friend's house. He was minding
his own business; he had had nothing to do with the melee outside
the nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Then Volpe _ searching for a man who had hit him in the face
outside the nightclub _ ran up behind Antoine. He screamed at him
to stop, and then he began beating him with his fists and
flashlight. It took seven stitches to close a cut in Antoine's
head.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad said that both Volpe and his supervisor, Sgt. Michael
Bellomo, soon realized that Antoine was utterly innocent, that he
was in the wrong place at the wrong time. But rather than admit
error, Vinegrad said, the two settled on an easier solution: ``Lock
him up on a trumped-up, phony charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad read to jurors reports Volpe and Bellomo wrote in which
they gave identical accounts of how Antoine attacked Volpe without
provocation, causing Volpe to suffer ``substantial'' pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds great, doesn't it?'' Vinegrad asked jurors. ``Very
official sounding. Good enough to lock Patrick Antoine up for all
sorts of different crimes: felony assault, obstructing government
administration in the second degree, disorderly conduct. Only one
problem. It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpe and Bellomo deny they conspired to falsify charges against
Antoine. Even so, the trial testimony has shown that nearly every
single word in their reports about Antoine was factually incorrect,
and Vinegrad suggested that the notion of owning up to error was
never really an option in the culture of the 70th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do about a guy who's been assaulted unjustifiably
by a cop?'' Vinegrad said. ``I mean, do you go up to him and say:
`I'm sorry, sir. I'm sorry Police Officer Volpe punched you in the
head and hit you with a flashlight and started a fight with you.
Would you like to file an excessive- force complaint?''
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad did, however, take note of one instance in which a
supervisor in the 70th Precinct seemed less concerned about
protecting his own than in seeing justice done.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the testimony of Officer Mark Schofield, one of the
first officers who came forward with incriminating evidence against
Volpe. Days after the bathroom assault, Schofield testified, he
sought the advice of a sergeant in the 70th Precinct, Jeff Fallon.
</P>
<P>
   Vinegrad said Fallon told the officer: ``If you know something
about what happened that night, if somebody actually did this to
Louima, then they are animals. They are not your friends. Don't go
protecting anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
