<HEADER>
A0768 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIG-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-02 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIG-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KWAN MAKES TOUGH DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The aspiring collegian stared at the essay question that was
part of her UCLA application:
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you looking forward to in life?''
</P>
<P>
   This was a compulsory exercise, a secondary component in the
overall judging. No one would have forgiven Michelle Kwan for
skating. With minimal exertion, she could have strung together
words that would have earned her high technical marks.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan could have written by rote the story of her disappointing
second-place finish to Tara Lipinski in the 1998 Olympic ladies
figure-skating competition and how she looked forward to competing
for the gold medal that had eluded her when the Winter Olympics
convene again, in Salt Lake City three years hence.
</P>
<P>
   No one would have been the wiser, save for Kwan. Only she would
have known that answer was no less a cop-out than turning a triple
toe loop into a double toe loop in the waning seconds of a free
skate. The truth is, if Kwan weren't looking forward to more in
life than skating, she wouldn't have bothered with a college
application.
</P>
<P>
   So that's where Kwan started her essay, with an admission:
</P>
<P>
   Whereas she once figured she'd just glide through life as a
skater, she'd now rather go to college and strive to be something
more, maybe even something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to fall into that rut and go the same old
route,'' said Kwan, a featured performer in Tom Collins' Champions
on Ice troupe, which will perform at the Arrowhead Pond of Anaheim
on Friday and at the Sports Arena on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen people involved with skating and that's all they do.
I don't think life is about sticking to one thing. It's about
developing an all-around presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwan has spent more than half her life wowing judges with her
jumps and her  &UR; !ital! &LR; joie de vivre &UR; !off! &LR; . But that's not the only
group on whom she has made an indelible impression. You can add to
the list the college admissions officers at UCLA, who green-lighted
the 18-year-old's entrance into the university. She will enroll as
a freshman in the fall, much to the consternation of the more
myopic members of the figure-skating community.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Dick Button was a freshman at Harvard in 1948
when he won his first Olympic men's singles title and that he
successfully defended his Olympic crown as a senior while balancing
the then-revolutionary triple toe loop with his thesis,
``International Socialism and the Schumann Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget that two-time U.S. Olympian Tenley Albright entered
Harvard Medical School after capturing the gold medal in 1956 and
that Debi Thomas was a premed student at Stanford when she took
home the ladies' silver medal from Calgary in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   It sends some people into a camel spin just thinking about Kwan
pulling all-nighters or possibly putting on the dreaded ``freshman
15.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a college degree to recognize hypocrisy in its
various hybrid forms. How is it that basketball player Baron Davis
is criticized for not bothering to finish his schooling at UCLA and
Kwan is criticized for bothering to start hers?
</P>
<P>
   Kwan scoffs at some of the feedback she has gotten. People have
told her she's making a mistake. ``Don't go to college,'' their
reasoning goes. ``You'll miss out on a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Kwan sees it, she can't afford not to go. Ten years down
the road she doesn't want to be like NASCAR superstar Jeff Gordon.
The driver who seemingly has everything expressed regrets in a
recently published interview about not having any college
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying that right now about going to high school,'' said
Kwan, who had private tutors for five years beginning in the eighth
grade, one of many concessions she made to her skating career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had the social life of regular school,'' said Kwan,
who made the 1994 Olympic team as an alternate at the age of 13.
``Most of all, I followed my dreams. Now I have a chance to catch
up in that experience. Now I have a chance to do something pretty
normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't ask Kwan how she'll fit ice time and ballet classes and
choreography sessions and cardiovascular work and a full class load
into a typical weekday. Her dorm room might be the only thing more
crammed than her schedule. She hasn't sat down yet with Frank
Carroll, her longtime coach in Lake Arrowhead, to devise a master
plan. The Champions on Ice summer tour concludes on June 19,
affording her the rest of the summer to figure things out.
</P>
<P>
   All she can say for sure is she's doing the right thing. The big
picture is clear in her mind, even if the details are a little
sketchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is best for my skating and what is better for Michelle?
That's sort of the dilemma I faced when I was making this
decision,'' said Kwan, who delayed college for a year to try life
as a full-time skater on for size.
</P>
<P>
   The fit was OK, but it was like a skating outfit that hugs the
skin. There wasn't a whole lot of room for growth. School, Kwan
decided at length, was just the accessory she needed to complete
herself and her skating.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just skate, you're putting everything on hold,'' Kwan
said. ``You're not really living your life. You can end up dwelling
on skating all the time. It's like, hmmm, I better work on that
triple lutz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be good in a way to have to juggle everything.
College is going to be a great diversion.''
</P>
<P>
   A great decision, too, no matter what happens in 2002. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
