<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES-METS _ WHAT 6 GAMES MIGHT MEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul O'Neill didn't want to talk about the Mets'
three-game visit to Yankee Stadium that begins Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't that big a deal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' right fielder didn't even want to talk about his
home run off Mel Rojas at Shea Stadium in the Yankees' 8-4 victory
in the opener of last year's Subway Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a lot of other games more than that one,'' he said.
``It didn't mean that much. They didn't lose by one game, did
they?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, come to think of it, the Mets did lose by one game.
In the National League wild-card race, they finished one game
behind both the Cubs and the Giants; the Cubs won the playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Mets were 9-7 against the American League East
in interleague games last year, losing two of three to the Yankees
kept them out of what would have been a three-way wild-card
playoff. And this season the Mets and the Yankees, along with most
of the other natural geographic rivals in both leagues, will be
playing each other six times, including the July 9-10-11 dates at
Shea.
</P>
<P>
   For the Yankees, those six could mean the difference between
first place and second place. For the Mets, the difference in a
wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   On form, those six games figure to be more of a burden for the
Mets than for the Yankees. And the Mets don't think they got a fair
shake.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Mets' rivals has to play the reigning World Series
champions six times, although the Braves, the perennial NL East
champions, will be playing six games with the Red Sox, currently
the AL East leaders. If you're wondering what the Atlanta-Boston
connection is, Boston was the Braves' ancestral home before the
franchise moved to Milwaukee in 1953, then to Atlanta in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an equitable schedule,'' said Mets manager Bobby
Valentine, alluding to six Mets-Yankees games, ``but it's great for
the fans, and the fans make up the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But with half of their 18 interleague games in AL ball parks
this season, the Mets will be able to use the designated hitter in
nine games. Three potential wild-card rivals _ the Cubs, the
Cardinals and the Giants _ play only 6 of their 15 interleague
games in AL ball parks.
</P>
<P>
   The DH is the silliest rule in sports; one league uses it, the
other doesn't. But it gives the Mets a wild-card edge.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Yankees were 4-2 against the Mets over the first
two interleague seasons, Joe Torre isn't enthralled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nightmare for us,'' Torre said recently. ``The fans
love it, the whole city is charged and that part is great, but the
outcome of the game is torture. There's so much made out of winning
and losing. I've got to pick up my dry cleaning. Those are the guys
that torture you.''
</P>
<P>
   But interleague games were adopted in 1997 for those guys who
work in the dry cleaners, those fans everywhere _ not for the
managers and the players who would surely prefer a peaceful weekend
series in Detroit or Florida to the cauldron that will be Yankee
Stadium this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, interleague competition should involve the Yankees
going against all of the NL teams each season, not just those in
the NL East. Or the Mets going against all of the AL teams.
</P>
<P>
   Mix and match the schedules, as the National Basketball
Association and the National Hockey League do when not constrained
by a labor dispute, so that each team visits every other city.
Think of the fun if the Dodgers, the Giants and, yes, the Arizona
Diamondbacks played in Yankee Stadium every season; if the Mets
played in Cleveland and Seattle. Yes, some interleague matchups
might not mean much. Tampa Bay in Milwaukee, or Kansas City in
Montreal. But every matchup would provide a new stage for the best
players and pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza, for example, will be playing baseball in Yankee
Stadium on Friday night for the first time. Now in his seventh
season, all in the National League, the Mets' catcher sounded like
a little kid going there for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history,'' he said. ``The whole idea of you're playing
where Babe Ruth played. How can you not have more adrenaline?''
</P>
<P>
   And no matter what Paul O'Neill thinks about the first of two
Subway Series this season, how can you not think it's a big deal? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
