<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARISMATIC LIVES UP TO HIS NAME  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Md.)   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He favors his great-grandfather. It is amazing how the genes
come through.
</P>
<P>
   He poked his great chestnut head through the open portal of a
727 Wednesday, the same stately way presidents and popes do when
they are visiting foreign soil.
</P>
<P>
   His owner named him before ever laying eyes on him. He was just
a yearling with some Secretariat heritage on a slip of paper, and
Beverly Lewis named him Charismatic because, well, ``because
Charisma was a beautiful name, but Charismatic had a more masculine
sound to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Did she ever have it right. He flew up from Kentucky Wednesday
morning, outlasting the thunder and the lightning the way he had
outlasted all the contenders in the Derby and the Preakness. Now he
was coming North to race on Saturday in the Belmont, where his
great-grandfather once ran, ran like a Kentucky spring tornado with
a purpose.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The creamy-white plane had no markings on it, no logos to tip
off anybody about the precious cargo inside. Tethered a few spaces
away was a filly named Silverbulletday, one of the threats to keep
Charismatic from winning the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The plane taxied over to the tarmac at an air-cargo terminal on
the north end of Kennedy Airport, and was met by a portable ramp
from the H.E. (Tex) Sutton First Class Equine Air Travel company.
</P>
<P>
   Down came the trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, in jeans and boots, a
green jacket and white cowboy hat. Then came Lukas' favorite stable
pony.
</P>
<P>
   Then came royalty. The first part out the doorway was the nose
with the white marking, not quite as elongated as that of his
great-grandfather, but starting in the same spot, right between the
forceful eyes. Seeing Charismatic for the first time, I got the
chills.
</P>
<P>
   (For reference, I later went home and stared at the only sports
memento in my house, a photograph of me petting Secretariat in May
1989 at Claiborne Farm, courtesy of a sugar cube. They look alike.
And I am not the only one who thinks so.)
</P>
<P>
   The colt strode comfortably down the steep ramp, when he sensed
a couple of dozen photographers greeting the great chestnut hope.
They did not call out the way they would to a rock star or a
politician, but somehow Charismatic knew this was all about him,
and he turned that massive neck and chest to the right, as if to
say, ``All right, boys and girls, you've got 10 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great horse, great horse,'' I heard a photographer say, while
looking through his lens. Then the horse was in the Sallee
transport van, en route to Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   When he emerged outside Barn 10, Charismatic was frisky and
composed, and his handlers washed him down, let him move his legs
in a modest field. He will do no serious training in New York
because Lukas did all the work back at Churchill Downs, seeing no
problem in shipping Charismatic 80 hours before the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my formula,'' Lukas explained later. ``After the
Preakness, we've always come in here on Wednesday. We went back to
Kentucky because our staff lives there, and it's always good to
sleep in your own beds, and keep costs down, but also these horses
don't handle change very well, and you want to keep them in their
own environment.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas said he never second-guessed himself Wednesday in
Kentucky, even when a brutal storm postponed the flight by several
hours, but he conceded, ``I might really wish I hadn't, come Sunday
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he was feeling pretty good after arriving at the
track just in time for the draw and discovering that Charismatic
had lucked out with the No. 4 post position. He said his colt got
off the plane in a good mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knows he's getting a lot of attention,'' Lukas
said, ``but I don't think he knows he's going to be a star on
Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   The former basketball coach tried to muster up his most
pessimistic version of the trip to New York. ``It's just like the
NCAA and the NBA,'' he said. ``It's tough to win on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to say this is the road. Charismatic once nearly
slipped away in a claiming race, but his bloodlines are very good,
including a great-grandfather who won the Belmont by 31 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic never knew his great-grandfather. Secretariat passed
from this world on Oct. 4, 1989, and Charismatic was foaled on
March 13, 1996, a few miles away in Bluegrass country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same expression, the same ears, the same little crest in
the neck, the same muscles,'' Lukas said later.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Lukas received a call from Ron Turcotte, who rode
Secretariat to the Triple Crown, and they talked for 40 minutes,
finishing each other's sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we make Charismatic finish his gallop, he gets mad
because he wants to run more,'' Lukas said. ``He kicks at the
ground. Or he runs an extra eighth. Turcotte said Secretariat was
exactly like that.''
</P>
<P>
   They all know there can never be another Secretariat (another
Babe Ruth, another Ali), but they do know that racing is waiting
for a Triple Crown champion. Some of these genes have been this way
before. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
