<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-TAKEOVER-FIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT FOR JAPAN PHONE CARRIER BECOMES TEST ON OPEN MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ One of the largest shareholders in International Digital
Communications, the target of a takeover fight between Nippon
Telegraph and Telephone Corp. and Cable and Wireless PLC, said
Wednesday that price would not be the sole determinant of its
allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Hiroshi Okuda, chairman of Toyota Motor Corp., which holds a
17.7 percent stake in International Digital, a struggling Japanese
phone carrier, said that his company had made no decision yet but
that such matters as the preservation of jobs and the potential
impact on Japan's reputation for resistance to foreign investment
would be weighed alongside the price.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over International Digital, the first takeover
fight pitting a Japanese company against a foreign one, has been
cast as a test case of Japan's willingness to open one of the few
relatively strong areas of its economy to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   International Digital's board has said that the decision whether
to accept one of the offers is up to shareholders. Toyota, as one
of the largest shareholders, has a pivotal role, as does Itochu
Corp., which holds a stake of the same size. Naoki Kitajima, a
spokesman, said Itochu had made no decision.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cable and Wireless, which also owns 17.7 percent of
International Digital, raised its all-cash offer to 69 billion yen,
or $570 million at current exchange rates, plus the assumption of
International Digital's debt. The improved offer came in response
to a sweetened offer from Nippon Telegraph. Details were not
disclosed, but NTT's offer is believed to be worth 68 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless contends that NTT has not made a firm bid
under Japanese law because of restrictions on it as a
government-controlled company. The offer is dependent on changes in
the law that would not take effect until October at the earliest,
while the new Cable and Wireless offer is good until June 15.
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Okuda, who is considered one of the most
progressive Japanese executives, suggest that the barriers to entry
may be cultural as much as regulatory and that the standard rules
of the takeover game will have to change to accommodate elements of
Japanese corporate culture, with its dedication to preserving
employment.
</P>
<P>
   From a business standpoint, it is unclear exactly why Nippon
Telegraph and Cable and Wireless are so eager to acquire
International Digital. The company is about one-fifth the size of
KDD, Japan's largest international carrier, but shoulders roughly
five times the debt, according to Nikko Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Telegraph could use International Digital to start an
international business, but it could just as easily do so on its
own, analysts say. Cable and Wireless could use International
Digital to gain a bigger presence in the Japanese market but at
some expense to its balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   As the new chairman of the Japan Federation of Employers
Associations, Okuda finds himself in this case torn between that
organization's pledge to help ease the record unemployment in Japan
and the interests of Toyota's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he found himself having to address the subject of
Toyota's plans for its International Digital stake Wednesday at the
employers federation's regular news conference, where his main
agenda was to have been to urge the government to move quickly to
devote as much as 8 trillion yen, or $66 billion, to combating
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors have long complained that Toyota places other
interests ahead of their own. Its investment in noncore businesses,
which range from telecommunications to financial services and real
estate development, have not mirrored the success of its auto
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   It is becoming harder for Toyota to ignore those voices now that
it wants to trade its shares on the New York Stock Exchange, in
part because it hopes to attract more foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   Nippon Telegraph and Cable and Wireless have tussled before. A
few years ago, analysts said, they disagreed over the disposition
of an NTT subsidiary called NTT Personal, in which Cable and
Wireless had a stake. Ultimately, Nippon Telegraph had its way and
the business was handed over to NTT Docomo, the company's former
mobile-phone business that was partly spun off earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But not without some hard feelings. ``Cable and Wireless has
made an enemy of NTT one time already,'' said Makio Inui, a senior
telecommunications analyst at Nikko Salomon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2314EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
