<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 23:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0911 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WATER-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-02 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATER-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: RFK JR. PUSHES BOTTLED WATER TO AID ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is a seemingly incongruous image: Robert F.
Kennedy Jr. _ crusading environmental lawyer, member of the famous
Kennedy dynasty and potential political candidate _ in a meeting
with local supermarket executives to persuade them to distribute a
new product.
</P>
<P>
   But the product has a catch that helps the picture make sense.
Keeper Springs' Mountain Spring Water is being introduced to
finance efforts to preserve and protect local waterways nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just about selling a bottled water, it's about
getting out a message,'' Kennedy said during an interview at Pace
University Law School's Environmental Litigation Clinic Inc., where
he runs a team that has successfully won more than 150 legal
actions totaling more than $1 billion in judgments against
polluters of the Hudson River over the last decade. The cleanup of
the Hudson River is now a national environmental model.
</P>
<P>
   Using seed loans from friends and family, Kennedy and other
environmentalists formed Tear of the Clouds LLC to introduce Keeper
Springs, which is named after the 35 ``keeper'' groups across the
country that protect and improve local waterways.
</P>
<P>
   To get out its message in the crowded field, Keeper Springs is
introducing a print and outdoor campaign in the New York area, with
a budget estimated at $2 million to $3 million that zeros in on the
clean waterways cause.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is being created by DeVito/Verdi in New York, which
was selected in April after a review involving 10 shops. The
initial ad is boldly political. The headline asserts, ``After just
one sip, you've done more for the environment than most
politicians.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that the ad reflected his years of frustration
fighting the rollback in national environmental regulations, which
he said was backed by big money polluters with political clout.
Besides his work at Pace, Kennedy is also the chief counsel for the
national Water Keeper Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Smooth sailing for Keeper Springs is by no means assured. The
product is coming to market against some 500 other bottled waters
and the industry is starting to consolidate among powerhouses such
as Nestle's Poland Spring, Danone Group's Evian and waters marketed
by the beverage giants Pepsico and Coca-Cola, said Michael Bellas,
chairman of Beverage Marketing Corp., the consulting concern that
provides annual reports for the International Bottled Water
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Bellas also questioned whether consumers were moved enough by a
cause to make a purchase, noting that other good causes have tried
to bottle water without much success, including some municipalities
in Texas and an Indian tribe in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough go,'' Bellas said. ``Ten years ago, it was like a
field of dreams _ you bottled water and they came. Now it's far
more complicated.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy who bears a striking resemblance to his late father,
said he and John Hoving of the Hudson Riverkeeper environmental
group came up with the idea while skiing in New York State and saw
that the ski area was marketing its own water. With financing an
issue, the Hudson Riverkeeper was seeking new income sources, and
had signed a licensing agreement with Sony Signatures to use its
name on sunglasses, hats and outdoor apparel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, hey we could do this,'' Kennedy recalled. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like much political advertising, Keeper Springs' campaign is
direct and to the point. One ad shows New York's East River in the
year 2026: with New York's skyline serving as a panoramic backdrop,
a beautiful woman swims in azure water amid the fish. Other ads
feature such headlines as ``All our profits go to cleaning up the
environment. Bottled Water doesn't get purer than that'' and ``To
532 endangered species, it's holy water.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we have a very clear point of difference, and we
should push that difference,'' said DeVito/Verdi president Ellis
Verdi.
</P>
<P>
   For the bottle itself, a Tiffany's designer created the
product's blue, red and white label with an oval disk of a colorful
mountain lake scene and the message ``All our profits to the
environment,'' set off by stars. The label also gives a brief
history of the Hudson Riverkeeper, which spawned a national
movement, and urges people that ``if you want clean water, fight
for it!''
</P>
<P>
   Working in Keeper Springs' favor is a booming bottled water
market. Bottled water accounted for $4.3 billion in sales last
year, with premium brands showing the fastest growth, up 30 percent
last year to about $1 billion, according to Beverage Marketing.
Today, about half of all adults drink bottled water, said Tear of
the Clouds general manager Gil Solnin . &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Solnin said research by Newman's Own, which was founded by actor
Paul Newman to help charities, showed that some 70 percent of
consumers would try a product if it benefited a cause they cared
about.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's name has been mentioned often as a possible candidate
for political office in New York state. But Kennedy, the third
child of Robert F. and Ethel Kennedy, dismissed the notion that the
bottled water would help him put his name and record in the public
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's name does not appear on the product, but as company
founder he will help publicize the product and he also might be
able to draw some celebrity support. The annual Hudson Riverkeeper
dinner, for instance, is usually a celebrity draw and has welcomed
guests like actors Harrison Ford and Billy Crystal, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Keeper Springs is being introduced first in the New York
metropolitan area and will move then throughout the Northeast
before eventually going national.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heavy competition, distribution in the New York area
has been excellent, Solnin said, and he credited Kennedy's efforts
with helping the product get shelf space in a crowded market.
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy said it was the environmental cause that had
resonated with the supermarket executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases, I didn't have to show up; they loved the
idea,'' Kennedy said. ``They've been very supportive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
