<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SECESSION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. AGENCY SETS SCHEDULE FOR SAN FERNANDO VALLEY CITYHOOD
HEARINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: With budgeted story BC-INFORMATION-GAG-LADN) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Public hearings into San Fernando Valley cityhood
should begin by late July, officials for the agency overseeing the
breakup study decided Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A day after receiving Valley VOTE's proposal for what the
unprecedented study should include, a Local Agency Formation
Commission committee set an ambitious work schedule that counts on
the city to cooperate fully in providing data for the comprehensive
financial analysis.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule could be further complicated by the San
Pedro-Wilmington secession drive, as community leaders turned in
Wednesday what they said are more than enough petition signatures
to gain a cityhood study of their own.
</P>
<P>
   LAFCO is sending the Valley VOTE proposal to all City Council
members, Mayor Richard Riordan and all city departments. LAFCO
leaders want the city to respond by June 30 so the agency can
decide what the study will include and approve a request for
information for the city at a public hearing July 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to begin to move on this,'' said Los Angeles County
Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, chairman of the LAFCO committee
assigned to the cityhood issue.
</P>
<P>
   While LAFCO must hold the July meeting as required under state
law, its committee will do most of the work culminating with a
possible citywide vote in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The committee set its hearing schedule for the third Thursday of
every month beginning in August. They will be scheduled in the
evening to encourage attendance and will be held across the San
Fernando Valley and the San Pedro-Wilmington area.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders were encouraged with the committee's
decision to reach out to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a Valley VOTE process, this is a public process.
LAFCO by law has to make the decisions, but they have to hear from
the public,'' said Richard Close, chairman of Valley Voters
Organized Toward Empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   If the study finds secession would be financially neutral for
both the Valley and the remaining city of Los Angeles, LAFCO would
put the secession plan on the ballot. It would have to be approved
by a majority of voters in the Valley and in the city as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders said the group's proposal seeks a
comprehensive and fair study.
</P>
<P>
   The secession group's plan would divide the city's assets and
liabilities, revenues and expenditures equitably between the Valley
and the remainder of the city. Buildings, land, libraries, parks,
facilities, infrastructure, equipment and vehicles already within
the Valley would become the property of the new proposed city.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE also proposes that regional facilities, notably Los
Angeles International Airport, the Port of Los Angeles, and the
Department of Water and Power, be managed through joint operating
agreements. They would be negotiated for as long as three years
after a favorable public vote.
</P>
<P>
   The LAFCO committee did not comment on Valley VOTE's proposal.
Members sought to set a tone that plays no favorites in the
possible municipal divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to caution against getting too cozy,'' Yaroslavsky
said. ``I think from this point forward we have to have a public
disclosure role.''
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky was responding to a suggestion from Valley VOTE
leaders that the LAFCO committee work closely with city and Valley
VOTE leaders to deal with any disagreements during the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps the integrity of the process a lot to have
everyone lay out their cards as early as possible,'' said Bob
Scott, who chaired the Valley VOTE committee that prepared the
study proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Yaroslavsky said the full LAFCO commission will decide any
disagreements based on recommendations from his committee.
</P>
<P>
   Valley VOTE leaders told the committee they appreciate the
agency's position as the study's arbiter. Yet they fear that city
officials will resist or oppose what they contend should be a
smooth study process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (this month's) deadline creates the need for the city
to have a unified response vs. a bureaucratic response. Will it be
cooperative or a stone wall, we will have to wait and see,'' Close
said.
</P>
<P>
   How to pay for the study remains a potential hurdle. The cost is
pegged at between $1.8 million and $2.6 million and primarily would
pay for economic and legal consultants.
</P>
<P>
   While state lawmakers, and city and county officials wrestle
with the funding issue, LAFCO is compiling a list of consultants so
they can be interviewed and ready to work when funding is
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than that, we're just looking at a good divorce
lawyer,'' joked City Councilman Hal Bernson.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
