<SLUG> BC-EURO-ART-690&AMP;ADDNYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE EURO FALLS, SOME IN EUROPE FAULT GERMAN GROWTH AND
LEADERSHIP
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ During his campaign a year or so ago to
reassure anxious Germans about adopting a new European currency,
then-Chancellor Helmut Kohl insisted at almost every opportunity
that the euro would be ``as strong as the deutsche mark.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, five months after the euro's well-publicized debut, the
original fear has proved almost exactly wrong. It is not the euro
that is dragging down Germany, but German issues that are dragging
down the euro.
</P>
<P>
   Having dropped nearly 12 percent against the dollar since its
introduction on Jan. 4, the European single currency reached a new
low here Wednesday of $1.0327, settling later in New York at
1.0355, and is inching ever closer to the economically
insignificant but politically mortifying level of 1-to-1.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's plunge has ignited a round of finger-pointing between
European political leaders and European central bankers, who met
Wednesday and refused to intervene on behalf of the currency.
</P>
<P>
   But it has also put the spotlight on Germany, which accounts for
one third of the 11-nation euro zone's total output, and on its
Social Democratic chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   Otmar Issing, the European Central Bank's chief economist and a
former top official at the German central bank, said this week that
Germany is in danger of becoming ``the sick man of Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth is running well below 2 percent, slower than any
other euro zone country but Italy. Its exports are languishing,
investment capital is heading overseas and unemployment remains
stuck above 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And at the center of all that is a continued paralysis over
reducing Germany's high tax rates and making its rigid work rules
more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the Portuguese, the Spanish, the Irish or the French
that are pulling down the value of the common currency,'' wrote
Oliver Schumacher on the front page of Wednesday's issue of Die
Zeit, the influential German weekly. ``No, it is above all the
Germans.''
</P>
<P>
   The political implications are profound. Schroeder, who is
playing host at a meeting of European heads of government on
Thursday in Cologne, had hoped to produce a common declaration on
plans to fight unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   But he was unable to reach agreement with France, and the
meeting will in any case be overshadowed by the euro's decline and
by deliberations over the war in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to the Yugoslav war, which has given Schroeder
the image of a refreshingly tough leader on foreign policy, the
chancellor's popularity has climbed in recent polls.
</P>
<P>
   But the economic problems have ignited a new wave of criticism
about what his detractors call a rudderless leadership.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the euro has other problems. Investors were rattled
last week when European finance ministers agreed to let Italy run a
slightly higher budget deficit than it had originally promised. The
war for Kosovo underpins such pessimism.
</P>
<P>
   But most economists agree that German stagnation is the biggest
problem. More than anything else, they say, the euro's decline
stems from a glaring contrast between slow growth in Europe and the
continuing surge of the U. S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   And that disparity stems primarily from Germany as well as
Italy, which together account for about half of the euro zone's
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   France's output is growing at an annual rate of more than 2
percent. Many smaller European countries _ Finland, the
Netherlands, Spain, Portugal and Ireland _ are growing well above 3
percent annually, overcoming problems caused by the Asian financial
crisis and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States, with its high degree of flexibility, has
managed to get through the problems fairly well and so did some of
the smaller countries'' in Europe, said Thomas Mayer, a senior
economist at Goldman, Sachs here. ``But Germany has not.''
</P>
<P>
   German government officials dismissed such criticism Wednesday,
arguing that the euro's decline was not a problem in itself and
that German growth would accelerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident of a pickup in the second half of the year,''
Economics Minister Werner Mueller, said in an Italian newspaper
interview.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A weak euro does give Europe a lift because exports become
cheaper and therefore more competitive in the American and other
foreign markets. But the euro's decline also undermines its
credibility and puts the European Central Bank in an increasingly
difficult position.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely because European growth has slowed so sharply, the
central bank cut its base-line interest rate to 2.5 percent from 3
percent early in April. If the bank now tried to defend the
currency by raising rates, it would very likely slow European
economies further. Bank officials also argue that attempts to
intervene in world money markets would almost certainly be futile.
</P>
<P>
   Wim Duisenberg, the president of the European Central Bank,
appeared tired and impatient with reporters' questions about the
euro's decline after a board meeting here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``These very short-term volatile movements in exchange rates _
I'm inclined to play them down,'' Duisenberg said. But other board
members, notably the outgoing president of the Bundesbank, Hans
Tietmeyer, have said in the last few days that they are unhappy
about the euro's fall.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Duisenberg tried to dampen expectations about
intervening in world markets, but he left himself room for
maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will comment on intervention when it is necessary to do
so,'' he said, adding that ``the issue of intervention was
discussed only to the extent that we spoke about what I should say
when a question comes on the issue of intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   The key question, though, comes back to Germany and Schroeder.
Gerhard Grebe, an economist here with Bank Julius Baer, said
investors were closely watching what his new finance minister, Hans
Eichel, would propose in its next round of tax reforms, due on June
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new government created a lot of uncertainty that damaged
the relationship with the corporate sector,'' Grebe said. ``If
Eichel comes up with really substantive cuts in corporate rates and
real relief, then everybody will realize there is a change in
public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, Schroeder has shown little willingness to challenge
the orthodox socialist wing of his Social Democratic Party on some
major policy issues. Indeed, he has ignited a new round of protests
from industry groups by pushing through laws that remove the
tax-free status of people in low-paying part-time jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a complete failure to act on structural
reforms,'' said Stephen Bell, an economist at Deutsche Bank
Securities. ``Indeed, they've been marching in the other
direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
