<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Polk un-retires to coach Georgia Bulldogs
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ Ron Polk, one of the most celebrated baseball
coaches in NCAA history, has decided to come out of retirement and
take over the struggling program at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The official announcement could come as early as today with a
news conference in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Polk, 55, has been an assistant athletics director at
Mississippi State for the past two years after serving 22 years as
the Bulldogs' coach. In that span he won 888 games and took
Mississippi State to the College World Series five times. He is one
of three coaches to take three different schools to the CWS. He
went with Arizona as an assistant in 1966 and with Georgia Southern
in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual SEC spring meeting here, Georgia athletics
director Vince Dooley would neither confirm nor deny that Polk
would be replacing Robert Sapp, who recently was reassigned in the
athletics department.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted at his home in Starkville, Miss., Polk would say only:
``I can't say yea or nay. There's a lot going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Polk returns to the state where he broke in as a head coach.
After serving as an assistant at Arizona (1966), New Mexico (1967)
and Miami-Dade South Community College (1968-71), Polk was hired as
head coach at Georgia Southern in 1972. A year later he had the
Eagles in the CWS.
</P>
<P>
   After four years in Statesboro, Polk was hired at Mississippi
State, where he won four SEC championships and took the Bulldogs to
the CWS in 1979, 1981, 1985, 1990 and 1997. At Mississippi State,
he coached 27 All-Americans and 12 future major-leaguers, including
Will Clark and Rafael Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 years as a head coach, Polk has a record of 1,043-486. He
has taken teams to the NCAA Tournament 17 times, winning six
regional championships. His 888 wins at Mississippi State are the
most in SEC history.
</P>
<P>
   Polk stepped down after the 1997 season in order to turn the
program over to Pat McMahon, one of his proteges. But after two
years of administrative work, Polk informed friends earlier this
year that his batteries had been recharged and that he was ready to
coach again.
</P>
<P>
   He has coached amateur baseball all over the world and was a
coach on U.S. Olympic teams in 1988 and 1996. He is a member of the
athletics hall of fame at both Georgia Southern and Mississippi
State.
</P>
<P>
   Polk was the national coach of the year in 1973 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-02-99 2322EDT &QL; 
