</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENT ABOUNDS AND ISSUES EMERGE FOR WOMEN'S OPEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Kan., Ill.)  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, Miss. _ On the course, it has been another
interesting year for women's professional golf. Karrie Webb leads
the LPGA money list and has won four times this year. Kelli Kuehne,
a two-time U.S. Amateur Champion, won her first professional
tournament last month.
</P>
<P>
   Two other young players with star potential recently decided to
turn professional: Jenny Chuasiriporn, a runner-up at least year's
U.S. Open, and Grace Park, who recently won the National Collegiate
Athletic Association individual women's championship.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the U.S. Women's Open begins Thursday at the Old Waverly
Golf Club, a picturesque course in northeastern Mississippi some
150 miles from Memphis, women's golf is still facing challenges.
</P>
<P>
   For example, why has next year's Women's Open been scheduled for
the same week as the 2000 British Open at St. Andrews, a conflict
that could diminish the attention given the women's event?
</P>
<P>
   Would the Women's Open attract more attention and publicity at
more heavily populated sites, rather than in more rural areas, such
as this year's site and the 2002 site, Hutchinson, Kan.?
</P>
<P>
   Those questions were answered by Mary Capouch, chairman of the
U.S. Golf Association's women's committee, at a pretournament news
conference Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, the conference was called to announce that the 2002
Women's Open would be held at Prairie Dunes Country Club in
Hutchinson. But with women's golf heading toward the next century
blessed with new talent but facing some of the same old issues, the
subject quickly changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have grown so much in just the last five years; we feel we
can take the Women's Open anywhere and be successful,' Capouch said
talking about taking the tournament to non-major market areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the easiest marketing area, but we had somebody
who really wanted us, and a $900,000 commitment from the state of
Mississippi to help market the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Capouch was also asked about the discrepancy in prize money
between the men's and women's U.S. Open champions _ $625,000 for
the men's winner this year, and $315,000 for the women's winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on that,'' Capouch said. ``We're proving our
worth as a USGA championship and our attendance is growing. We hope
our prize money will grow, and we're working on it each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about next year's Women's Open at the Merit Club in
Libertyville, Ill., going head-to-head against the British Open,
Capouch remained optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is going to have that much bearing on the
Women's Open,'' Capouch said. ``Libertyville is a northern suburb
of Chicago. We expect to get good crowds.''
</P>
<P>
   If this year's Women's Open can match the excitement of the
previous two, the tournament will be terrific. Se Ri Pak won in
memorable fashion last year over Chuasiriporn, prevailing in an
18-hole Monday playoff that went two extra holes. In 1998, Nancy
Lopez thrilled the gallery and almost fulfilled her career-long
quest to win an Open, before losing by one stroke to Alison
Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   This year's course, although particularly challenging on the
back nine, has wider fairways and lower roughs than other recent
Open cites, meaning there will be more birdie opportunities, and
probably more players with a realistic chance to win. Wednesday's
weather was not unbearably hot, with highs in the upper 80s but the
humidity could rise this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Among those to watch in the 150-player field:
</P>
<P>
   _Webb, who has been the Ladies Professional Golf Association's
most-dominant player this year, but who is still looking for her
first major.
</P>
<P>
   _Dottie Pepper, who won the year's first major, the Nabisco
Dinah Shore.
</P>
<P>
   _Park, playing her last tournament as an amateur, is one of the
longest hitters in the field and confident she can do what
Chuasiriporn did last year.
</P>
<P>
   _Lopez, who will once again be the sentimental favorite, but who
is bothered by a sore left knee.
</P>
<P>
   _Juli Inkster, who has won three majors, but never the Open,
although she finished second in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '92 Open was really tough; I still think about it a lot,''
said Inkster, who has won two tournaments this year. ``When you
grow up as a little kid you want to win the U.S. Open. That's what
you practice for. That's what you watch. That's what you see. To
get your name engraved on that trophy is the ultimate''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
