u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-590&AMP;AD     06-02 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-SALES-ART-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 5 STRONG MONTHS, AUTO INDUSTRY IS ON TRACK TO SET ANNUAL
SALES RECORD
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Auto executives were exuberant Wednesday as May's car
and truck sales propelled the industry toward its best year ever.
</P>
<P>
   Despite weak results from General Motors Corp., the industry's
sales rose 5.3 percent in May compared with results in the period a
year earlier, when sales were also stellar.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's seasonally adjusted annual sales rate of 17.3
million was surpassed only by a rate of 17.8 million set in
December 1986. Anything more than an annual rate of 15 million is
considered strong.
</P>
<P>
   For the first five months of 1999, buyers have snapped up 6.9
million cars, sport utility vehicles, minivans and pickup trucks,
well ahead of the 6.4 million they bought in the first five months
of 1986 _ the industry's best sales year.
</P>
<P>
   ``May was a blockbuster sales month for Ford and the industry _
stronger than we expected,'' said Robert Rewey, Ford Motor Co.'s
group vice president for marketing, sales and service. ``A record
year is within reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford sales rose 8.1 percent, to 379,153 vehicles. Light-truck
sales climbed 5.8 percent, while car sales rose 11.5 percent. The
results exclude Volvo, which Ford bought earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers are responding to strong economic fundamentals _
growth in jobs and income, low inflation and interest rates, as
well as innovative products,'' &UR;  &LR; Rewey said. ``We believe those
fundamentals will keep U.S. auto sales healthy for the rest of
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler, the American unit of DaimlerChrysler AG, had its best
month ever. ``We're thrilled with the performance for the month,''
said James P. Holden, executive vice president for sales and
marketing at DaimlerChrysler. ``It's been a great five months.'' He
predicted the industry would exceed the record of 16.1 million
vehicles sold in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler's sales rose 5.9 percent, to 264,732, with car
sales up 1.5 percent and sales of sport utility vehicles, minivans
and pickup trucks up 7.7 percent. The company's Mercedes-Benz unit
saw its sales rise 6.8 percent, to 16,732.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's sales gains came despite a 4.4 percent sales
decline last month at GM, compared with its sales in May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market this month once again was really hot,'' said Roy S.
Roberts, vice president and group executive for North America
vehicle sales, service and marketing at GM, which sells more cars
and trucks in the United States than any other company. So far this
year, GM's sales are running 1.3 percent higher than they were in
the first five months of last year.
</P>
<P>
   GM's car sales dropped 6.7 percent, while its sales of sport
utility vehicles, minivans and pickup trucks fell 1.9 percent. Most
of the declines came from Chevrolet, GM's largest division, where
sales fell 11.4 percent. Sales of full-size sport utility vehicles
like the Suburban, the Chevy Tahoe and GMC Yukon were so weak that
GM executives are considering whether to offer rebates on them to
bolster sales.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota Motor Corp. said its sales rose 4.7 percent, to 142,625,
in May compared with results in the period a year earlier, and an
executive there said the industry's sales pace seemed to have
climbed to a new level. ``There seems to be a developing consensus
that this is a new plateau, not merely a surge,'' said Yale Gieszl,
executive vice president at Toyota Motor Sales.
</P>
<P>
   Honda Motor Co.'s sales rose 6 percent, to 98,158, last month,
with sales of pickup trucks, minivans and sport utility vehicles
jumping 42.6 percent because the Odyssey minivan is proving so
popular. Car sales inched up 0.4 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Five years of strong sales, which seem to be only getting
stronger, have prompted Honda and many other automakers to announce
plans to build new factories or expand existing factories.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly because sales have been so strong this year,
automakers were relieved to learn Wednesday that the teamsters'
union and the vehicle-transport companies that deliver new cars to
showrooms had averted a strike by agreeing to a new four-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the threat of a car-transporter strike behind us, we are
looking forward to a strong summer selling season,'' said Dick
Colliver, executive vice president of American Honda.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
