A0925 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRASH-RESPONSE-TEX     06-02 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRASH-RESPONSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH RESPONSE TEAM ANTICIPATES CATASTROPHE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN REED and SEAN WOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ In a demonstration of one the grim realities
of the airline business, American Airlines was able to launch a
huge, well-planned response to the crash of Flight 1420 late
Tuesday night in Little Rock in a matter of hours _ precisely
because it had a anticipated such an event.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 a.m. Wednesday, every key executive in the company's
crisis response management team was in place at the airline's
high-tech System Operations Control Center near Dallas/Fort Worth
Airport, at American's headquarters a half-mile away, or tied into
the crisis response team by phone.
</P>
<P>
   By 7 a.m., two jets filled with members of the airline's
Customer Assistance Relief Efforts, or CARE Team, and the technical
experts who make up its emergency response ``Go Team'' were
airborne and headed for Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   By 9:30, the cafeteria in the company's headquarters had been
turned into a fully equipped media conference center with cable
connections for live TV hookups, risers and platforms for
photographers, broadcast-quality audio hookups for radio reporters
and a buffet table for the horde of reporters and other news media
members who descended on the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``As terrible as all of this is, we recognize that it is part of
the industry,'' said American spokesman Al Becker, who has been
involved in crisis response efforts after six fatal American or
American Eagle crashes in his nearly 30 years with the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we have a plan in place _ and hope we never to put
it into effect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the crash about 11:50 p.m. Tuesday, Art
Pappas, managing director of American's Systems Operations Control
Center, was phoned and told of the crash. Pappas called Robert
Baker, American's executive vice president of operations.
</P>
<P>
   By 1:30 a.m. Wednesday, the two men were in position at the head
of huge, U-shaped conference table in the ``bridge'' room
overlooking the main control room at the SOC, a room the size of
two football fields that looks much like NASA's Mission Control,
only about 10 times larger. Gathered around them were senior
representatives of nearly every effected department: flight
operations, ground operations, safety, scheduling, cabin service,
meteorology, reservations, corporate communications, legal and
others.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission, Becker said, was to ``immediately regain control
of the situation to whatever degree we can and to begin responding
in the most effective, and most humane way we can to the tragedy
that had just occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   That response includes subtle efforts to protect the airline's
image. American made sure its news media briefing room had no
American signs or insignia visible. Two speakers' lecterns with
American Airlines logos used for happier events sat in the corner
of an adjacent room, while American executives stood behind a plain
brown lectern.
</P>
<P>
   But Becker downplayed the efforts at image damage control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue of protecting the image flows from how well you
perform under great adversity,'' he said. ``And it evolves into how
you take care of the passengers and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first steps in activating American's plan was to call
in some of its 1,200 CARE team members _ American employees
systemwide who have volunteered to respond to the scene of an
accident to aid survivors and victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   (American was criticized early Wednesday because families who
awaited the flight at Little Rock's airport were initially confused
about what had happened.)
</P>
<P>
   While the airline has long had a practice of assigning employees
to the families of passengers involved in a crash, six years ago it
instituted a formal and thorough training process for its CARE Team
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are authorized to do whatever is necessary to make sure
that families are comfortable,'' Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon Wednesday, American had activated 213 CARE Team
members, Becker said. Of those, 121 were either in Little Rock or
en route there. Each of those team members will be assigned to a
family affected by the accident.
</P>
<P>
   CARE Team members are given carte blanche to pay for funerals,
hotel accommodations, meals, transportation and whatever else
victims or their families need.
</P>
<P>
   Most survivors, for example, needed new clothes because the ones
they were wearing when they escaped the crash were ruined by jet
fuel, mud and rain. Whatever remains of their luggage was still on
board the stricken plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our responsibility,'' American Airlines spokesman Mark
Slitt said.
</P>
<P>
   But David Stempler, president of the Airline Travelers
Association in Washington, D.C., said Wednesday that that sense of
responsibility has been a relatively recent development for the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone full circle from the less-than-caring, barely
responsible agencies and airlines to those who find this policy to
be more effective,'' Stempler said. ``It's a good business
practice.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also federal law. In 1996, President Clinton signed the
Aviation Disaster Family Assistance Act, which gives survivors
someone to turn to for information after an aviation accident.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was written after the 1996 crashes of TWA Flight
800 off Long Island, N.Y., and a ValuJet plane in the Florida
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Stempler said bending over backward for the families of victims
and survivors serves the airlines in several ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airlines that pride themselves on service, like American, want
to be there in bad times as well as good,'' he said. ``Airlines get
criticized if they do a bad job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
