<HEADLINE>
UNMANNED PLANES FLY LOW AND GET THE PICTURE OVER KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRESEVO VALLEY, Macedonia _ As the NATO air campaign grows into
nearly nonstop bombing, the light unmanned aerial vehicles known as
drones are crisscrossing the skies over Kosovo, acting as
electronic scouts, finding and filming elusive targets, especially
Serbian troops hidden in bunkers or woods, and sending those images
immediately to fighter jets overhead.
</P>
<P>
   At least 21 drones, the only aircraft that the allies let fly at
such low altitudes, have been lost to gunfire or mechanical
problems, said NATO and Pentagon officials.
</P>
<P>
   The drones are part of the electronic warfare that is being
waged from border posts like this one and from bases here, in
Albania and even Bosnia. At Observation Post 380, on a plateau that
overlooks villages and summer fields sprinkled with poppies, French
and British soldiers aim their Doppler radar, infrared telescopes
and communications towers toward the border two miles away,
watching and listening to the Serbs and in Kosovo directly to the
west.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal now is to overwhelm the Serbs with technology,'' said
Maj. Arnaud Bellynck, a French paratrooper and a commander in the
French brigade that is assigned to the eastern sector of northern
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   To operate effectively, the drones have to be near the
battlefield, which required the deployments here and in Macedonia
to be carried out quietly. France, Germany and the United States
have based unmanned surveillance planes here despite the Macedonian
government's insistence that NATO has a headquarters here just to
carry out a peace accord, and not to fight an air war.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Hunter surveillance plane flies from the Skopje
airfield. The more sophisticated unmanned Air Force Predator is
based in Bosnia, at Tuzla, according to NATO and Pentagon officials
who are equally wary of acknowledging the role of the Bosnian
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no choice, given the short range of these planes'' a
NATO officer said. ``But it's worth it. We're getting fabulous
imagery of Serb forces, refugee movements and battle-damage
assessments. So we know how well we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   No NATO official said the intelligence matched the quality that
they could obtain from pilots who would fly at low levels or ground
troops. ``It's very good, but it is limited,'' said Bellynck.
</P>
<P>
   The videos, as well as photographs from the drones, have become
critical as NATO concentrates on Serbian troops and equipment. To
avoid detection, the troops are in small units hidden under trees,
in camouflaged bunkers and near villages.
</P>
<P>
   Programmed to fly as low as 1,000 feet, the surveillance planes
capture on camera what they see on the ground and immediately relay
the pictures to forward aircraft like A-10 and F-16s, whose pilots
call in strikers to bomb the targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the biggest thing now, to get those pictures in real
time for tactical information so we can move on the targets as soon
as we find them,'' said an allied official.
</P>
<P>
   The information and photographs are generally sent first to
controllers here and then to NATO headquarters here, in Italy or
Belgium. The information relayed through the Hunter planes is
processed through the Apache task force in Albania, according to a
Pentagon official, and much of the video from the Hunters and
Predators is sent to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Bellynck said allied soldiers conducted electronic eavesdropping
along the border and were becoming adept at ``distinguishing the
sound of cows from the Serbs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
