<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPS-Y2K-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REGULATIONS WILL REQUIRE Y2K COMPLIANCE ON SHIPS ENTERING PUGET
SOUND PORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Commercial vessels entering the Strait of Juan de Fuca
and Puget Sound will have to prove their on-board computers won't
pose a safety hazard when the new year clicks over to 2000 under
new Coast Guard procedures expected to be put into effect later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Vessels from big cargo haulers to commercial fishing boats will
have to respond to a series of questions about ``equipment critical
to the operational safety of the vessel,'' said Capt. John
Veentjer, chief of the Marine Safety Division for the Coast Guard's
13th District, which includes such major ports as Seattle, Tacoma
and Portland.
</P>
<P>
   The questions about so-called ``Y2K'' problems will be included
with those asked when vessels routinely provide their 24-hour
advanced notice of intent to enter a port, Veentjer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will also ask if the company owning the vessel has a
documented Y2K policy in place, yes or no,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard also will ask information about navigation,
steering, propulsion and power generation systems and cargo
handling equipment and other safety equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will ask if they had inventory checks for the ship to
identify and categorize potential non-compliant equipment,''
Veentjer said.
</P>
<P>
   Failure of critical on-board systems could result in container
ships, some weighing as much as 50,000 to 75,000 deadweight tons
and carrying as many as 5,000 shipping container units, rampaging
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Failure of computerized cargo handling equipment could result in
hazardous material being spilled.
</P>
<P>
   Veentjer and other officials are meeting on Thursday with
Canadian coast guard representatives at Coast Guard facilities at
the Port of Seattle to hash out wording on the requirements, which
will be published in the Federal Register and on the Coast Guard's
Internet site when ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the same procedures in place for vessels that enter
the Strait of Juan de Fuca regardless of whether they are going to
turn left and head to Vancouver, B.C., or turn starboard and head
to the Port of Seattle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The extended requirements will be in effect for 24 hours before
and 24 hours after Sept. 9, 1999, Jan. 1, 2000, and Feb. 29, 2000,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The September date is included because old computer programs
might read the abbreviation ``9/9/99'' as a code to shut down. The
Feb. 29 ``Leap Year Day'' might not be included in some programs.
</P>
<P>
   Decisions on what to do with vessels that might pose risks to
navigation or the environment because computers on-board or ashore
fail will be left to the captain of the port.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Cmdr. Mike Moore, currently executive officer to
Capt. Miles Booth, captain of the port in Seattle, will succeed
Booth on June 28 and is now heading local efforts at bringing
vessels here into compliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be ready in advance as much as possible and to
minimize the number of vessels we know little about showing up just
before midnight on Dec. 31 and expecting to enter a port here,''
Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Most container ships entering the Port of Seattle and Port of
Tacoma are liners owned by steamship companies that regularly bring
the same vessels into Puget Sound, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have information on those vessels in hand ahead of
time, so that we will know in advance if they have been checked out
as much as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While questions about Y2K compliance will be globally imposed at
ports throughout the United States, providing consistency for
shipping lines, each of the 40 or so captains of the port will have
authority to make judgments because each port has different
currents, weather and other local conditions to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tug availability is another factor that varies from port to
port and a captain of the port might require a vessel to have a tug
escort, depending on his evaluation of the vessels response to the
questions,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could ask a vessel to remain at sea or merely not to use
autopilot as it enters our navigable waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some steamship operators and their associations independently
are taking precautions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The petroleum tanker industry, for example, has decided all of
its vessels will be at sea or tied up at dock at the critical
dates,'' Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are at dock, they are not going to transfer oil until
they are sure they don't have unexpected computer problems. We
didn't go to them with this. They just came to us and said, `That's
just how we're going to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard's own Vessel Traffic Service, which operates
radar and video systems on its shipping lanes much like the air
traffic control systems oversee plane traffic, is bringing its
systems into Y2K compliance and will have backup systems in place.
Rescue boats also are being checked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
