<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES </SLUG>
 COLUMN-TEX 
STARS OWN ADVANTAGE IN DELICIOUS DECIDER (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Now'' we can talk about Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for your patience and your understanding about tabling
this subject until other, more important items on the agenda _ like
the Dallas Stars winning Game 6 Tuesday night _ were checked off.
</P>
<P>
   But now we've come down to it, and did you ever, really expect
anything less?
</P>
<P>
   In Denver, those who get paid to have an opinion are saying this
heart-stopping, incredibly delicious Western Conference finals
series is ``too close to call.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's too close not to call.
</P>
<P>
   Stars win Friday night. Mark it down. Stars win.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, that's just an opinion, too, but there are too many
portents that say the pendulum in this anything-goes series has
finally swung toward the Stars for good.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the Stars must do to keep it there and advance to
the Stanley Cup Finals against Buffalo:
</P>
<P>
   Refuse to panic or get caught up in the first-period blitzkrieg
that the Avalanche will come with, because that's the only chance
the visitors have.
</P>
<P>
   Play the same game that they put on the ice in the second and
third periods Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Use the uplifting spiritual ``force'' that a sellout crowd of
17,001 psyched-up fans will provide.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure Eddie Belfour is wearing extra-dark shades and that he
understands that just because the sun's still out in Texas at 6:30
in the evening, that doesn't mean it's not a night game.
</P>
<P>
   Even the hockey gods seem to be smiling on the Stars now. The
same NHL playoff schedule makers that hurt the leg-weary Stars with
a quick turnaround between Games 4 and 5 have now granted them an
extra day to rest for Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   That helps the Stars, with their older, slower defensemen, far
more than it does the younger, always ready-to-skate Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Game 7 to see who goes to the finals ... it's probably what
everybody in the world of hockey wanted,'' Mike Modano said after
the Stars' 4-1 victory tied the series at three games apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Well, everybody but the world of Denver, which has grown weary
of seeing the Avs lose at home during these playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. It won't happen again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Avs, a remarkable 8-1 on the road during their playoff
run, must accomplish something no other team has been able to do
this entire season: beat the Stars three times in their own
building.
</P>
<P>
   Hell will have its own hockey rink before that happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to take that home-ice advantage,'' vowed Jamie
Langenbrunner, who scored two opportunistic goals to lead the Stars
to Tuesday night's victory.
</P>
<P>
   A bad sign for the Avalanche is that the Stars were able to put
Sunday's glimpse of NASCAR-on-Ice behind them and rediscover that
delicate balance between strong, positional defensive hockey and
offensive pressure on Colorado goalie Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars played tentatively in the first period, searching for
that balance. They were waiting and reacting, however, instead of
being aggressive. When Claude Lemieux tipped in Adam Foote's
blazing slap shot from just inside the blue line with less than 35
seconds remaining in the period, things looked ominous for Dallas.
Goals scored in the final minute of a period are particularly
devastating and the Stars have been allowing that to happen far too
often.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of deflating the Stars, it worked to their
advantage. They came out for the second period with a new sense of
urgency while the Avalanche, smelling blood on the ice, turned
careless. Jere Lehtinen's chip shot over Roy's left shoulder tied
the score and turned the momentum in the Stars' favor.
</P>
<P>
   Game 7 will cap a tremendously entertaining series between two
desperate and dissimilar teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche, without question, has a collection of immensely
talented players. The Stars have a great team, playing a great
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs are Van Cliburn on ice. The Stars are Jerry Lee Lewis,
hot licks and great balls of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't get by on just pure talent, not against Dallas,''
Avalanche defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh said.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like frustration, you're right.
</P>
<P>
   Resignation?
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these teams has come this far to quit now. This ain't
for show anymore. This is a war and the casualties are mounting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only sad thing is that one of these teams will be finished
playing Friday night,'' Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said.
</P>
<P>
   Sad, but true. Remind me to drop him a postcard from Niagara
Falls. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
