<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE FAMILIAR WITH SLIPPERY SLOPE
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Claude Lemieux's face mirrored the 19 other Avalanche
players around him as the horn sounded ending Game 6 on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   There was the distinct look of ``What now?''
</P>
<P>
   The ``what now'' was gone less than 24 hours later, replaced by
the knowing looks of players who had been down before only to
bounce back. Colorado coach Bob Hartley said his players only have
to reflect on this season to do so again in Game 7 of this Western
Conference finals series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that if we look at Game 7, we have to open up the book
that we started writing since training camp,'' Hartley said. ``We
jump like so many hurdles. We trip on a couple of occasions. But
every time that we went down, we found ways to get back up. That's
called facing adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing adversity has become a Colorado specialty this season.
</P>
<P>
   From Patrick Roy tearing up Hartley's office after a
regular-season game, to a season littered with inconsistency, to
falling behind Detroit 2-0 in the West semifinals, to blowing a
chance to wrap up a Stanley Cup berth because of an uninspired loss
in Game 6, adversity has been an Avalanche linemate.
</P>
<P>
   So what exactly does the book say about how to bounce back?
</P>
<P>
   ``The same way we bounced back from every setback,'' Lemieux
explained. ``It's by going into the game and not thinking and not
looking past that first shift, not looking past that first period
and not making too much of it, but just going out and playing the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche players failed to follow that plan in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Joe Sakic called Game 6 a must-win game, and player
after player had talked of dreading going back to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   So when a once DOA-looking Stars bunch took a 2-1 lead,
Avalanche players admitted to panicking, pressing and then folding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 6, as of right now, doesn't mean a thing,'' Avalanche
winger Shjon Podein said. ``It's a one-game deal now. You are going
to hear it from so many people. It's 60 minutes for the series.
It's 60 minutes to go to the Stanley Cup, and that's all that
matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartley said if a single lesson needs to be learned from Game 6,
Colorado needs to play a fearless, risk-taking style that has
helped them to advance this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't play cautious,'' Hartley said. ``We're all out. We
have a great-skilled hockey club, and we have to use those skills
to our advantage.'' Home on the road Why? The Avalanche can't say.
</P>
<P>
   But they do agree it is lucky that Game 7 is being played in
Dallas. They are 8-1 on the road this playoffs, compared with 3-6
at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we try to do too much at home, if we get too
fancy if we try to put on a show,'' Shjon Podein said. ``I know
that on the road we seem to keep things a lot more simple, cut down
on the turnovers, play a more basic game and we wait for our
chances. When we get our chances, we take advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche has won two of the three games at Reunion Arena so
far, but their only road loss this playoffs came against the Stars
in Game 2. Series to remember The Detroit-Colorado series may have
been bloodier, but Claude Lemieux said the Dallas-Colorado series
is better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely one of the best that I've been a part of,''
Lemieux said. ``It's one of the most unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it's good for the NHL, because it generates interest as
fans try to figure out a series that has become a constant
cliffhanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, let's start rubbing our crystal balls, and
hopefully, we can see the future before Friday,'' coach Bob Hartley
said. ``And if not, there is going to be two great hockey clubs
going at it and it should be a great battle.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
