<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NEW-SCHOOLS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL DISTRICT MAY RAZE HOMES FOR NEW SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The Los Angeles school district may seize 48
North Hollywood homes and apartments under eminent domain to make
room for a new elementary campus.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed school is one of 13 citywide that members of the
Board of Education will discuss today, all planned to ease
overcrowding at existing campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Construction would remain a long way off even if the board makes
the selections today. First, an exhaustive environmental study of
each location must be prepared, and all homes that would be taken
would be appraised. Then the full school board would have to vote
on whether to acquire each site and buy out the property owners.
</P>
<P>
   For most sites, such a vote would be at least a year away, said
LAUSD real estate director Robert Niccum.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the district's preferred location for a new school in
suburban North Hollywood, in the city's San Fernando Valley
northwest of downtown, already has alarmed some residents who could
be forced to sell their homes to the district at market rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my memories are here from all my life,'' said Lorraine M.
Crews, who has lived in the area since 1942. ``I'm 77. I don't want
to be uprooted.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other proposed schools of the 13 to be discussed today would
be located in the San Fernando Valley. The district might be able
to build both without taking any homes, possibly locating them atop
an old gravel pit in nearby Sun Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the district planning to build 100 schools in the
next 10 years, the school board increasingly will face the choice
of taking the homes of people like Crews or picking sites that
might not work as well.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion comes at a time when district officials are
considering changing the way they select sites.
</P>
<P>
   School board member David Tokofsky, who serves on the facilities
committee, said he wants more community input in the way sites are
selected. He said today's discussion might be premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we be going ahead with site selection if we don't have
a selection process?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the facilities committee, for example, will look at
nine possible sites today for the proposed North Hollywood
elementary school. They will then tell district staffers which site
deserves further study.
</P>
<P>
   Some choices would require seizing few homes, if any. But those
relatively painless options are located too far away from the
overcrowded schools the district wants to relieve, said Niccum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trade-off is you don't help one of those schools that
needs help, and that's exactly the kind of policy question that the
board has to decide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another location a block away from the North Hollywood site
contains an abandoned police station, but Niccum said the city's
parks department already owns the property and wants to use it for
a senior center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to get the vacant police station,'' he said.
``It is already spoken for.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sun Valley, the district needs a new high school and middle
school. At first, the district identified several sites that would
have involved bulldozing houses or apartments. But during a meeting
in January to seek community input, residents suggested that the
district consider instead building both schools on a local gravel
pit.
</P>
<P>
   Niccum said he didn't know what kinds of environmental
contamination the district would have to look for before picking
such a site. But he has recommended that the committee choose the
62-acre site for further study.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it works, there's a lot we could do with that site,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
