<HEADLINE>
DAY OFF `GREAT FOR' OLDER STARS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Stars took Wednesday off, with most
players not even coming to the rink.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he expects his team to skate
about 30 minutes today and then make the morning skate an optional
tomorrow. Hitchcock said he's hoping to use the extra day off
between games to get his team healthy and energized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great for us,'' Hitchcock said. ``Any time with an
older team that you can get extra time off, it can't do anything
but help.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the Stars are used to performing without practice
because they have used that format throughout the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't been doing this, it might be a problem. If we
were a younger team, it might be a problem,'' Hitchcock said. ``But
we've prepared for this all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Mike Modano said players from both teams will
benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice having two days off,'' he said. ``There should be
great energy in that building for Game 7.'' NO PRESSURE
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano has two assists in the past three games and is
minus-2 in that span. Meanwhile, Colorado Avalanche center Peter
Forsberg has a goal and three assists and is a plus-2 in those
three games.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken Hitchcock said that doesn't mean Modano and linemates
Jere Lehtinen and Brett Hull are playing poorly against Forsberg,
Valeri Kamensky and Claude Lemieux. Instead, he said the Stars' top
offensive line has the toughest checking job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line is playing against three world-class players,''
Hitchcock said. ``They broke even \Rin Game 6\S and that gave us a
chance to win. In Game 5, we didn't break even, and we didn't win
because of it. I think that's a big responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said he still looks at his role as checking, even though
he, Modano and Lehtinen have combined for 16 playoff goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a checking line all year, and that's been a hard
thing to get used to,'' Hull said. ``But I think we look at
ourselves that way right now. We look at ourselves as a checking
line that can score goals.'' QUICK CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have been particularly cautious about avoiding bad
line changes and almost got caught in two in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a conscious effort of leaving two people on the ice
in every (shift change),'' Hitchcock said. ``With (goalie Patrick)
Roy and their defensemen, they really took advantage and caught
Detroit six or seven times a game. We try to have certain people on
the ice until the shift is cleared, and sometimes that's hard
because you can get caught up for some extra seconds.'' TWO DRAFT
PICKS SIGNED
</P>
<P>
   The Stars announced the signing of 1997 draft picks Brenden
Morrow and Ryan McKercher to standard three-year rookie contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Morrow, a burly winger who was the Stars' first-round pick (25th
overall) that year, will join the Stars at training camp in
September and is a lock to make the Michigan K-Wings. McKercher, a
defenseman who was taken 189th, will also be on hand at training
camp, but could return for one final year of junior play if the
Stars deem he is not ready for the K-Wings. HRKAC CLOSE
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Tony Hrkac, who has been out a month with cracked
ribs, has been practicing at full speed for a week and likely is
available if Ken Hitchcock needs him for Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, who has not changed his lineup for the past three
games, likely will leave his forward group intact. CONSISTENCY
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have not lost three games in a row with Ed Belfour in
goal since he joined the Stars before the 1997-98 season. Belfour
has played 155 games (regular season and playoffs combined) and has
not lost more than two in a row. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
