<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THAILAND-HOTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIERCE BIDDING WAR FOR A FIVE-STAR HOTEL IN BANGKOK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Have a drink in the tranquil lobby of the
Regent Hotel here, beneath palm fronds and the hand-painted silk
ceiling, and you would scarcely guess that this five-star refuge is
the object of one of the most lively and improbable bidding wars in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The combatants are Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and an American-born
Thai citizen, William E. Heinecke. Goldman owns 34 percent of the
Regent and wants to buy control of the hotel. Heinecke's company,
Royal Garden Resort, owns about a one-quarter stake and is
determined to fend off the investment bank.
</P>
<P>
   The battle, which began after Goldman bought its holding in the
Regent two months ago, reaches an important junction on Thursday,
when both sides are required to submit final tender offers for the
356-room hotel. Neither will disclose its next move, but Heinecke
maintains that cash alone will not guarantee victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot more than just money involved,'' he said in his
office here, cluttered with model airplanes and photographs of him
at the wheel of a 1966 Ferrari racing car. ``This property has a
bit of emotion attached to it.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the outcome of the bidding war is less significant
than the fact that it is taking place at all. Bangkok is glutted
with half-empty hotels. And while it has been nearly two years
since the devaluation of the Thai currency set off the Asian
crisis, most investors still give this country a wide berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first takeover battle in Thailand since the
crash,'' said Anil Thadani, chairman of Schroder Capital Partners,
a private investment firm in Singapore that owns a stake in Royal
Garden Resort. ``Hopefully, it marks the reawakening of investor
interest in Thailand.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle for the Regent also demonstrates that some assets in
Thailand remain valuable, even amid the economic wreckage. Although
the Regent's bookings and profits swooned in 1997, rooms began
filling up again last year as Goldman and other foreign investment
houses sent battalions of bankers to help Thailand sort out its
debt-ridden banks and companies.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, which through its real estate funds owns stakes in the
Essex House in New York and the Ritz-Carlton in Laguna Niguel,
Calif., first became interested in the Regent last year, when a
troubled Thai investor put a 24 percent stake up for sale. That
deal was snatched by Heinecke.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman returned the favor in April, when Heinecke thought he
had completed a deal to buy an additional 33 percent from a
Japanese investor. Instead, Goldman walked away with that stake and
promptly made a tender offer for the rest of the Regent's parent,
the Rajadamri Hotel Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get an opportunity, anywhere in the world really, to
buy a five-star existing property because people tend to hold them
for dear life,'' said Henry Cornell, who supervises Goldman, Sachs'
equity investments in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell said Goldman's offer was superior because it is offering
to buy the entire hotel at a value of $45 million. Heinecke is only
willing to buy 10 percent, just enough to keep Goldman from gaining
effective control.
</P>
<P>
   But Heinecke has been a wily opponent. The 49-year-old
entrepreneur was born in the United States, but spent the last 36
years in Thailand. He has become a tycoon here with interests from
hotels and restaurants to toiletries and golf accessories. In 1991,
he became a Thai citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Heinecke is turning his local standing into a weapon. He is
casting the battle as one between a scrappy local outfit and a
giant foreign interloper. The argument resonates in a country where
fears of foreign colonization have risen as much of corporate
Thailand has tumbled into insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who feel that some foreigners have tried to
take advantage of Thailand when it was down,'' Heinecke said.
</P>
<P>
   Pravit Rojanaphruk, an editor and columnist at The Nation, an
English-language newspaper here, said: ``Of course, there are fears
of foreigners overrunning Thai society. But whether it is bad for
Thailand is debatable. The Thais who owned the assets before didn't
do such a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell is careful not to criticize the Regent's managers, who
he insists he would retain. But he noted that the company could do
more. He said Goldman would use the Regent as a base to build or
buy other hotels. For starters, he envisions a new Regent on the
resort island of Phuket, in Thailand's south.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a spectacular company with great assets,'' he said.
``You need someone to imbue it with strategic purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Heinecke said the Regent's shareholders do not want Goldman to
turn the hotel into a vehicle for speculative ventures. Among the
minority shareholders are the Thai Farmers Bank, the Crown Property
Bureau, the business arm of Thailand's royal family, and the king
himself.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Heinecke seems to be holding his own. Barely 2 percent
of the shares have been tendered to Goldman. Unless it offers more
money or a stronger sales pitch, it is unlikely to gain control.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell does not seem ready to give up, but he complains that a
simple real estate deal has become a political football. ``We're
not the big, bad foreign bogeyman,'' he said. ``It's not like we're
going to pick the hotel up, put it on a boat, and move it to New
York City.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
