<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      06-02 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS GO INTO BRONX IN A FUNK 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A sweaty and satisfied Bobby Valentine finished
throwing batting practice to some Mets pitchers Wednesday and
playfully chirped about how effective he had been. He returned to
the dugout for a drink and continued gabbing about the most routine
baseball exercise. It was typical Valentine. He likes to talk and
embraces the attention.
</P>
<P>
   Based on those attributes, this is a poor time to be Valentine.
The Mets are limping along and will begin a three-game series
against the Yankees Friday night at Yankee Stadium. The appealing
interleague matchup will be scrutinized and will receive an
abundance of news media attention, even with the Knicks still
breathing.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Valentine and his Mets are mired in an unenviable
position. The Mets have been perennially overshadowed by the
Yankees, who have won two of the last three World Series titles.
Now, when the Mets have the perfect chance to slap the Yankees and
steal some space on New York's baseball marquee, even if only
temporarily, they are traipsing into the Bronx in a funk.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets lost their sixth straight game Wednesday night against
the Reds. They have too many outfielders, they do not have
consistent starting pitching, they have some players who have
groused anonymously about Valentine's penchant for changing
lineups, and they even resorted to a team meeting on Tuesday. Those
are obvious signs of a wayward club. Could there be a worse time
for the Mets to be playing the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't predict how I would rather go into the series,''
Valentine said. ``I'll let you know afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   It is all Valentine can say. The manager says that the best way
for the Mets to challenge the Yankees is by being healthy, and that
means that Edgardo Alfonzo's sprained left foot must heal. But
Valentine would surely be elated if the Mets were in first place
and were taking a winning streak into this intriguing series. He
just would not admit that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's on the schedule,'' Valentine said. ``The next time we
play them, that'll be the next time we play them. Whether or not
that's a good time or a bad time, it's the time we play them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Piazza and Bobby Bonilla were two players who were critical
of the Mets' having to face the Yankees six times this season.
Piazza argued that three games are enough because they would be
less likely to detract from a meeting in the World Series. Bonilla
smartly said that the Mets are the only team in the National League
East who are saddled with six games against the Yankees, instead of
three. Even Valentine grudgingly agreed that opposing the Yankees
six times is a drawback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they feel it's an advantage to play us six times instead of
the Braves six times? Probably,'' Valentine conceded. ``If they
think it's to their advantage, it's probably to our disadvantage.
It is what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Mets are what they are, a struggling 27-26 team that
could plummet further against the Yankees. The Yankees will start
David Cone, Orlando Hernandez and Roger Clemens _ a former Cy Young
Award winner, a poised Cuban who can be especially arduous on teams
who rarely see him, and a five-time Cy Young Award winner. The Mets
will counter with Rick Reed, Masato Yoshii and Al Leiter. No one
from this trio would be working this weekend if he pitched for the
Yankees, even if it was a four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter reminded Valentine that Hernandez had pitched a
no-hitter for five and two-thirds innings and allowed one run and
two hits over eight innings in the only contest the Mets actually
won, 2-1, against the Yankees last season. Valentine nodded and
said: ``He was tough on us. I won't say he's tougher than Cone or
Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   While Piazza theorized that the Mets could be helped by the
``playoff atmosphere'' of the series, Valentine tried to lessen its
importance and acted shocked when he was told George Steinbrenner
would be outraged if the Yankees were swept. In the end, the series
will count as three more games. But, this weekend, it will be
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need to do is win games and win our division,''
Valentine said. ``They're not in our division. They're in our town.
There's nothing that three or six games can do to tarnish or take
away from what they've done and it's not going to stand by itself
for whatever we do. It won't stand alone. It's going to be mixed in
with 162 games in our record. That's what's going to matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
